<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUMPKIN-PIE-PANIC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THANKSGIVING HOLIDAY CREATES PUMPKIN PIE PANIC FOR NON-BAKERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 &HT;    By GREGORY J. WILCOX  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Wait until Thanksgiving Day to snag a freshly
baked pumpkin pie and you may end up cooling your heels in line
while the pie is in the oven or, even worse, be forced to eat pound
cake from a convenience store.
</P>
<P>
   Credit that great holiday refrain -- ``leave room for some pie''
-- for turning a brown fruit dessert into a Thanksgiving must-have.
(Ever eat a pumpkin pie at a Fourth of July picnic or after Easter
dinner?)
</P>
<P>
   You can credit the pumpkin pie with spawning another tradition:
putting down a deposit on a pie and then waiting in a long line to
pick it up.
</P>
<P>
   That's right. Pumpkin pies are so popular, yet apparently too
much work for home bakers, that people will gladly line up to pick
up pies beginning this morning that they ordered and paid for
several days ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have lots of orders for (today) already,'' said Judy Brown,
who with her husband, Sheldon, owns Brown's Victory Bake Shop in
suburban North Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   The neighborhood shop, redolent with the aroma of pumpkin and
other baked goods this week, was busy Tuesday filling orders for
200 pies, most of them pumpkin.
</P>
<P>
   Brown recommends placing an advance order so a pie can be had
before the store closes tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``It might be a good idea,'' she said. ``There is a possibility
we could run out of pies, but we keep them coming out of the oven
all day long, so we try to have them in stock.''
</P>
<P>
   Her husband was just one of the bakers across the city's San
Fernando Valley area up to their elbows in flour as they scrambled
to keep up with the pumpkin pie demand.
</P>
<P>
   Danny Klein, owner of Gelson's Pastry Shop, said he reached his
limit Tuesday. He can't take any more pie orders.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trouble is I don't have any place to put them,'' Klein
said. ``I'd love to take more orders, but I don't have any more
room for the pies.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, he's too busy to think about how many pies he has
baked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no idea,'' Klein said. ``Call me after the holiday and
I'll tell you.''
</P>
<P>
   Pam Dinkowitz, who with her husband, Steven, owns Classic Cakes
bakeries in suburban Porter Valley and Valencia, has been in the
business for 35 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of people who reserve the pies, and then again
we have a lot of them on hand so people can walk in and pick up a
pumpkin pie,'' said Dinkowitz, who also has six other varieties on
hand.
</P>
<P>
   The store will go through about 800 pies, about half of which
have been pre-ordered. A baking crew came into work at 1 o'clock
this morning, and the ovens will stay hot until about 5 p.m. to
meet demand.
</P>
<P>
   For those who procrastinate until Thursday, Marie Callender's is
one of the few options. The restaurant chain, which has nine
eateries in the San Fernando Valley, will be winding down a pumpkin
pie baking marathon.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the company produces more pumpkin pies this time of
year than almost everyone.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Locke, senior vice president of food and beverages for the
company, said Marie Callender's ovens across Southern California
were turned on Tuesday night so bakers could work around the clock
to keep up with the Thanksgiving pie demand.
</P>
<P>
   About 750,000 pumpkin pies will be sold during the holiday, and
reservations are recommended.
</P>
<P>
   Pie pickup lines will probably spring up as early as this
afternoon. The lines are especially long between 8 and 11 a.m.
Thanksgiving Day, but walk-in customers will most likely be able to
get a pie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because we are serving Thanksgiving dinner, we are using pies
for the restaurant, so we are baking them all through the day,''
Locke said. ``But the volume is so huge they could have to wait a
little bit, which no one wants to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The demand is so heavy that some former employees even show up
at various stores every Thanksgiving to help pass out the pies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of them are guys that the wife just wants out of the
house for the morning so she can cook, and this is a good place for
them to go,'' Locke said.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
