<HEADLINE>
JOHNSON OFFERED 4-YEAR DODGERS DEAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Los Angeles Dodgers added a fourth year
Tuesday to their contract offer for Randy Johnson, but the total
package of more than $52 million might not be enough to bring the
free-agent left-hander to Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels and Arizona Diamondbacks have made similar offers and
enjoy the advantage of ties to Johnson's home outside Phoenix. The
Angels hold spring training in nearby Mesa and the Diamondbacks
play less than 30 minutes away.
</P>
<P>
   But Dodgers general manager Kevin Malone, who spent Tuesday in
Arizona examining potential spring-training sites, said if his team
is out of the running, he hasn't been told.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to (Johnson's agent Alan Nero) this morning and if we
are no longer players, I haven't heard that,'' said Malone, who did
not meet with Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who has said he wants a deal in place by the
Thanksgiving weekend, could make his decision today or Friday.
Despite a four-year, $50 million offer from Texas, Johnson has
hinted he does not want to play for the Rangers, who also train in
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson went 10-1 with Houston after being acquired from Seattle
at the July 31 trading deadline. The Astros pulled out Tuesday
after refusing to budge on their three-year, $33 million proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to clearly take a fourth year to remain in this
competition,'' Astros general manager Gerry Hunsicker said. ``We
were not prepared to do so at this time.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's other agent, Barry Meister, said Tuesday from his
office in Chicago that the stakes have been raised.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to make it clear Randy is trying to sign with a club
where he is going to finish his career and we honestly believe
he'll play four more years,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the Dodgers' pitch to Johnson, 35, is the proposed
spring-training move to Arizona in 2000. Malone and club president
Bob Graziano flew to the Phoenix area Tuesday to examine a site in
Ft. McDowell, 15 miles north.
</P>
<P>
   Graziano has not decided where the club will hold spring
training after the 1999 season. He said Monday that all renovations
on Dodger Stadium have been postponed until after the club gets a
better grasp of its 1999 payroll, which is expected to pass $70
million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
