<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLIDAY-HELP-HASSLE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALL SANTAS MAY BE IN SHORT SUPPLY AS SEASONAL JOBS GO UNFILLED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ENRIQUE RIVERO  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Southern California's healthy economy is giving
retailers the holiday blues.
</P>
<P>
   With the economy in high gear and unemployment rates at
generational lows, retailers say their pool of job applicants for
temporary holiday retail jobs is as dry as Death Valley.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, hundreds -- maybe thousands -- of temp jobs are
going unfilled across the region, despite the ubiquitous ``Help
Wanted'' signs on storefronts along area boulevards and indoor
malls alike.
</P>
<P>
   All this has retailers afraid that they won't be able to find
enough qualified help to get them through the typically busy
holiday shopping season that will start Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Just how fearful are they?
</P>
<P>
   ``It even gets down to people being afraid there will be a
shortage of people to play Santa in the malls,'' said Jack Kyser,
chief economist for Los Angeles Economic Development Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Giss, a partner with the retail services group of the
accounting firm Deloitte &AMP; Touche LLP in Los Angeles, said the temp
jobs just aren't appealing to the vast majority of people who now
have good-paying, full-time jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got very low unemployment and these are temporary jobs
and they're relatively low-paying jobs,'' Giss said. ``With the
economy in good shape, they're less attractive and appealing than
they otherwise might be.''
</P>
<P>
   Retailers of every size are feeling the crunch, from small
independent operations to big chains like Target stores, a division
of Minneapolis-based Dayton Hudson Corp.
</P>
<P>
   For the past few years, the chain has started beefing up its
temporary holiday staff a little earlier in the year, said Target
spokeswoman Denise Workcuff. Each store typically hires between 50
and 150 employees for the holidays, most of them part time.
</P>
<P>
   This year the holiday hiring started in August.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always a challenge. This year it's going to be more of a
challenge than in years past,'' Workcuff said.
</P>
<P>
   Target has started offering a number of incentives to reel in
the applicants. For example, besides offering ``very flexible
hours,'' Target pays 50 cents to $1 an hour more for tough-to-staff
evening and weekend shifts, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's no more challenging for Target than it is for any other
retailer,'' Workcuff said. ``We're just trying to meet the
challenge by starting (hiring) earlier and trying to be more
creative.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past, it's taken Denise Williams only until about
mid-October to find all the holiday help she needed to work at her
Lavender's Hallmark store in the Sherman Oaks Fashion Square in
suburban Sherman Oaks.
</P>
<P>
   But here it is well into November and Williams has filled only
half of her six temporary slots -- which means she and her managers
have to come in to work up to two hours early each morning to get
things ready in time to open the doors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a little more difficult; that's basically it,''
Williams said. ``There are no applicants, very few qualified
applicants.''
</P>
<P>
   She's not alone. Many of the 125 stores in the Sherman Oaks
Fashion Square are having a difficult time filling their temporary
holiday positions, said mall general manager Ruth Tewalt, who has
heard repeated complaints from store owners and managers about the
shortage of qualified help.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just walking through (the mall) you see the `Help Wanted'
signs,'' Tewalt said. ``That's the biggest indication that folks
are looking.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Target store in suburban Woodland Hills, about half of
the 60 or so temporary positions have been filled so far, said
store manager Joyce Atkinson. Many of them have been filled by high
school-age employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's more of an influx this year than in years past,'' she
said. ``They've worked out quite well for me.''
</P>
<P>
   The robust economy might not be entirely to blame. According to
Kyser, the holiday season typically generates 12,000 to 13,000
temporary jobs. But there are some 300,000 people in Los Angeles
County who are officially classified as unemployed.
</P>
<P>
   ``That means there should be a pretty decent labor pool,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   So why aren't more people diving in?
</P>
<P>
   ``In a lot of cases people are saying, If I do this, will this
take me away from my goal of finding a real full-time job?'' he
said. ``Whenever the economy is good, it makes it difficult for the
retailers.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all area retailers are finding themselves high and dry.
</P>
<P>
   One of the lucky ones is Dave Dutton, owner of Dutton's Books in
suburban Valley Village, Burbank and downtown Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Dutton gets plenty of people who've worked past holidays who are
eager to come back. And people who clerked in his stores as high
school students are returning during their holidays from college.
</P>
<P>
   He said he always tries to hold positions open for the veterans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just seem to have a pretty good pool of college returnees
to draw from, and I haven't made any plans to take on any new
people,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   XXX &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
