<SLUG> BC-TERMINATOR-UNIVERSAL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TERMINATOR HEADS FOR THEME PARK UNDER DEAL WITH UNIVERSAL STUDIOS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE McNARY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Universal Studios Hollywood announced that it has
joined forces with director James Cameron to open a ``Terminator 2
3-D'' attraction at the theme park this spring.
</P>
<P>
   The project, a 12-minute sequel to Cameron's
robots-from-the-future blockbuster with live-action motorcycle
stunts and three 50-foot-wide screens, will be similar to the
highly successful Terminator 2 attraction that opened two years ago
at Universal's theme park in Orlando, Fla. Construction recently
started on the park's western side on the site of the Family
Challenge theater.
</P>
<P>
   Universal, which faces the task of distinguishing itself from
family-friendly Disney parks, noted that a recent Fodor's travel
guide called the Florida ``T2'' the world's best theme-park
attraction.
</P>
<P>
   ``The T2 in Florida is a fabulous convergence of digital film,
robotics and live action,'' said Tim O'Brien, Southeast editor at
Amusement Business magazine. ``It's the first time these elements
have been put together and it works very well. They even have a
character saying, I told you I'd be back.''
</P>
<P>
   ``T2 3-D,'' using technology developed at Cameron's Digital
Domain effects studio, will be the 18th attraction at the
California park and will seat 700 people at once. Cameron shot the
footage over two weeks at a deserted steel mill in Desert Center in
neighboring Riverside County.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien said the attraction has helped boost attendance at the
Florida theme park, which hit 8.9 million last year, an impressive
tally but still lagging each of the three Disney theme parks in
Florida and Disneyland. Universal Studios Hollywood followed with
5.9 million, the magazine estimated.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
