<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-UNION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: TIME FOR A UNION TAKEOVER 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Wednesday, Nov. 25:
</P>
<P>
   New York City's largest union, District Council 37, is in a
colossal mess. The Manhattan district attorney, Robert Morgenthau,
is investigating charges against union officials ranging from
embezzlement to falsifying records to kickbacks for Thanksgiving
turkeys. Now comes an even more serious charge, of vote fraud in
the crucial 1996 ratification of an unpopular city contract. The
contract, which became the linchpin of Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's
budgetary and labor policy, imposed a two-year pay freeze on most
municipal workers.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley Hill, executive director of District Council 37,
announced that he had dismissed two top aides who knew about the
fraud. He also assured the 120,000 members of the council's local
unions that ``we will clean our own house and weather this storm.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, Hill's promises are too late and too weak for a
union that now needs some real industrial-strength cleaning from
the District Council 37's parent union, the American Federation of
State, County and Municipal Employees. Although none of these
charges have touched Hill directly, the parent union's trusteeship
of District Council 37 is necessary to revamp the union's feeble
governing structures and to find a stronger, reform-minded leader.
</P>
<P>
   The vote fraud on this 1996 contract is the final straw. Ever
since the results of that election were announced, union reformers
have been protesting that the numbers smelled wrong. Hill dismissed
these complaints until a news article about the vote fraud last
week. The contract's pay pattern affected other workers like
policemen, whose union was forced to accept the wage freeze after
arbitration.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's lawyers argue that despite the vote fraud, the
contracts are valid and will remain in force. Hill and a number of
prominent labor lawyers agree. The larger question is what happens
to the work performance of employees who feel bamboozled by their
own representatives. To insure more openness and fairness, the
council and its unions should allow greater access by members to
financial records and encourage outside supervision of elections.
</P>
<P>
   Hill, who has ignored excesses among union leaders until these
recent allegations, said he had agreed to stricter financial rules
and some outside monitoring of local union votes. The parent union
has also sent in an investigative firm to determine whether the
strange 1996 contract vote was really tainted. These responses are
reactive at best. Hill has proved he cannot control his union. It
is time for the parent union to take charge.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
