<HEADLINE>
CULTURE NOTES: GENIUS REVISITED; THEIR HERO; TRIED AND TRUE;
NORTHERN INVASION
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: L.A., Mass., Canada)  (nk) 
 By KATHRYN SHATTUCK 
  c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It was music's mean season when Bob Dylan abandoned
folk music to embrace rock-and-roll in the summer of 1966. The
ensuing hostility can be witnessed in the film ``Eat the
Document,'' on view at the Museum of Television and Radio in
Manhattan and its Los Angeles branch through Dec. 20. Made for
ABC's ``Stage 67,'' the documentary was shelved when the network
became confused by its stream-of-consciousness flow. Bootleg copies
have been in circulation for years, but the museum's version
presents the work as it was intended. The screenings coincide with
the release by Columbia Records of Dylan's ``Live 1966'' CD's.
Information: (212) 621-6800 or (310) 786-1042.
</P>
<P>
   Their Hero
</P>
<P>
   Over the last 18 years, the National Yiddish Book Center in
Amherst, Mass., has recovered nearly 1.5 million volumes that serve
as a record of Jewish life before the Holocaust. Brittle with age,
many of the works are now threatened with extinction. Steven
Spielberg hopes to remedy the situation. His Righteous Persons
Foundation has made a grant of $500,000 to create ``The Steven
Spielberg Digital Yiddish Library.'' Using digital technology, the
library intends to preserve works permanently by reprinting them on
demand, issuing them as CD-ROM's and making them available on the
Internet. The project, whose first volumes will be out early next
year, insures access to a ``lost Atlantis of cultural treasure,''
said Aaron Lansky, the center's founder.
</P>
<P>
   Tried and True
</P>
<P>
   He champions the Baroque and the contemporary. But when Julius
Rudel takes the podium at the Metropolitan Opera on Wednesday
night, it's Puccini's war horse ``La Boheme'' that will commemorate
his 20th season at the Met. Rudel made his debut there with
Massenet's ``Werther'' in October 1978; since then he has conducted
18 different operas with the company, ranging from Handel's
``Samson'' to Mozart's ``Magic Flute.'' The maestro will lead ``La
Boheme'' and Mozart's ``Nozze di Figaro'' this month and next.
</P>
<P>
   Northern Invasion
</P>
<P>
   People in the United States prefer Canadians, if the nominees
for the 26th annual American Music Awards are any indication. Some
20,000 listeners were bowled over by the Canadian country siren
Shania Twain, who led with five nominations, including best female
artist and best album in both the pop-rock and country categories.
Celine Dion was nominated for top female artist and album in the
pop-rock category and favorite artist in the adult contemporary
genre. But Americans weren't shut out. Will Smith, who began his
career as the rapper Fresh Prince and went on to television and
movies, earned four nominations. The awards will be handed out on
Jan. 11 in Los Angeles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
