r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CATHOLIC-JEWISH-SUMMI     11-25 0531
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CATHOLIC-JEWISH-SUMMIT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. CARDINAL MEETS WITH REGION'S JEWISH LEADERS TO HEAL RIFTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DEBORAH SULLIVAN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- L.A. leads the world in Catholic-Jewish
relations, but more cooperation is needed to fight social ills and
heal historic rifts between the two faiths, Cardinal Roger Mahony
told the Southern California Board of Rabbis.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Catholic-Jewish dialogue in the United States is the
oldest and most advanced in the world,'' Mahony said Tuesday, ``and
much of this dialogue was pioneered here in Los Angeles.''
</P>
<P>
   But Catholic-Jewish cooperation has slowed in recent years, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Mahony's speech, at the invitation of Board of Rabbis President
Lawrence Goldmark, marked the first time the leader of the Los
Angeles Archdiocese has addressed the Jewish body.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having the leader of the Roman Catholic Church speak to the
rabbis of Los Angeles' Jewish community is incredibly important,
because it is the continual building of bridges between communities
that will dispel ignorance and ill will that have existed for
thousands of years,'' Goldmark said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Jewish people have to realize that the Catholic Church has
changed.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, the Vatican apologized for Catholic silence
during the Holocaust, and Mahony noted that a Los Angeles
Jewish-Catholic group produced a similar statement on the
atrocities in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Mahony stressed that the church in recent decades ``turned its
face toward, rather than away from the Jewish people'' and adopted
an understanding of Judaism ``in which there is not the slightest
hint of contempt, and not an iota of a conversionist agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather than praying for Jews to convert to Catholicism, he said,
the church now calls for Catholics to pray that Jews remain
faithful to their own religion.
</P>
<P>
   The growing understanding and cooperation between the two faiths
must be harnessed to serve the city's immigrant poor, Mahony said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The archdiocese of Los Angeles has labored long and hard in
the inner city, remaining in many cases the primary focus of hope
and stability,'' he said. ``Now, more than ever before, we need you
to join us.''
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi Steven Jacobs of the Kol Tikvah synagogue in suburban
Woodland Hills urged Mahony and other leaders to remember the San
Fernando Valley's poorer neighborhoods as well.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs said a once-thriving Jewish-Catholic dialogue in the
Valley has diminished from its peak 25 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Mahony attributed that decline to turnover and deaths among the
Valley's clergy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have had an almost total transformation of priests in the
Valley,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs said the Valley religious leaders from both faiths have
become overwhelmed by the area's surging population and changing
demographics.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, he said, they have focused on immediate needs of
their own congregations at the expense of social action and
interfaith collaboration.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a great influx of poorer people in the Valley, and
more than ever we need to cooperate to preserve the dignity of the
human being,'' Jacobs said.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
