<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-25 00:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8325 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOLIDAY-HORROR-TRAVEL     11-25 0780
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLIDAY-HORROR-TRAVEL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLIDAY TRAVELERS CAN HELP THEMSELVES TO AN EXTRA SERVING OF
TRAFFIC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL COIT  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- This is traditionally the busiest day of L.A.'s
travel year, and it's likely to be busier than ever thanks to the
strong economy and low fares that have more people on the move this
Thanksgiving holiday weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that's why the Flyaway parking lot in suburban Van Nuys
was already full Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had some spots open, and then by 10 or 11 o'clock the lot
was filled up.'' said Pat Freudenburg, a spokeswoman for the
airport service.
</P>
<P>
   The Flyaway bus remains an inexpensive option for suburban San
Fernando Valley residents flying in and out of Los Angeles
International Airport. But you need a ride to the bus terminal
because the 2,020-space lot likely will remain full through the
holiday weekend, Freudenburg said.
</P>
<P>
   The rush already was on Tuesday at LAX and suburban
Burbank-Glendale-Pasadena Airport. Even worse, crowds are expected
to increase 30 percent to 50 percent today. By tonight, motorists
-- some driven by gas prices 25 cents a gallon lower than a year
ago -- will clog Southern California freeways.
</P>
<P>
   There will be long waits even if you're flying. Airport
officials suggest arriving two to three hours early. And if you're
driving, make sure the vehicle is ready for the road and get some
rest before the drive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thanksgiving is a traditional go-see-the-family kind of
holiday,'' said Jeff Spring, spokesman for the Auto Club of
Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   ``Based on what we've seen the last five years, the number of
people traveling on this holiday is increasing. There's a better
economy and people are more comfortable with taking trips.''
</P>
<P>
   The swell of travelers began surging into the area's two main
airports Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're seeing a slightly higher volume coming through the
airport today,'' Sean McCarthy, a Burbank Airport spokesman, said
Tuesday. ``We will see it probably peak tomorrow afternoon and
evening, and then there will be another spike Thursday morning. We
can expect a similar rush of return passengers on Sunday and Monday
morning.''
</P>
<P>
   Burbank Airport's daily crowd count will increase from 12,000 to
some 16,000 on those days, McCarthy said. The normal daily load of
nearly 200,000 travelers at LAX will grow by 100,000 today and
again Sunday, said Cora Fossett, airport spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   ``The majority of people are pretty busy in life in general and
are just rushing around at the last minute. So many people during
the holiday period are once-a-year travelers. They're in a state of
heightened anxiety and excitement,'' she said. ``That's why we
advise people to arrive earlier.''
</P>
<P>
   Driving will be the preferred mode of transportation during the
holiday weekend, according to a national Auto Club survey. Of the
nearly 34 million Americans expected to travel over the period,
27.7 million will drive, Spring said.
</P>
<P>
   So expect congestion on the Ventura Freeway north as far as
Santa Barbara, on Interstate 10 through San Bernardino, on
Interstate 15 to Las Vegas, and on Interstate 5 through the
Grapevine and into the Central Valley, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   If you're heading north on I-5, beware of road repairs from
rural Castaic to Gorman. The California Highway Patrol and state
Department of Transportation predict 20-mile backups from the
combination of road work and traffic.
</P>
<P>
   The first project involves work on the bridge at the I-5/Highway
138 interchange that requires the closure of the two right-hand
lanes. For the second project, crews have been repairing a
half-mile section of road south of Templin Highway near Castaic.
The open lanes there are rough and bumpy, and traffic will be
reduced to 45 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Given that one in six highway deaths are caused by drivers who
fall asleep at the wheel or are drowsy and not alert, the Auto Club
has launched a public awareness campaign providing free Solution to
Drowsy Driving tip cards at AAA offices across the region.
</P>
<P>
   ``Expect the roads to be busier,'' Spring said. ``They don't
have to be more dangerous; just use common sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Weather conditions should be favorable. Mostly clear skies with
daytime highs in the mid-70s are forecast for Los Angeles County
and neighboring Ventura County today and Thursday, said Stuart
Seto, a National Weather Service specialist in Oxnard, in Ventura
County.
</P>
<P>
   Travelers going into the Central Coast and Northern California
should expect rain tonight with snow above 6,000 feet, and a second
storm late Friday and into Saturday, Seto said.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
