<SLUG> BC-FBN-COLUMN-THIEL-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEAHAWKS YET TO ROPE `STUDHOSS' QB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Local fans of football irony, this is your week.
</P>
<P>
   The week that the Seahawks pick a no-pedigree mutt from Central
Washington as their starting quarterback, they play a team that has
a no-pedigree mutt from Milton College who was, and is, the best
quarterback in Seahawk history.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Krieg is a backup for the Tennessee Oilers and might not
play Sunday in the Kingdome. But he's still in the NFL at 40, just
two years younger than Warren Moon and with a Seahawk resume that
is superior to his more heralded counterpart.
</P>
<P>
   Krieg's return combined with the Seahawk move to Jon Kitna makes
a thunderous point about the Seahawks as their 23rd season dwindles
down in the same ignominious fashion as so many others:
</P>
<P>
   Never have the Seahawks had a prime-time quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Among the 15 who have thrown passes for the Seahawks, there have
been good QBs, fun QBs, winning QBs and in Moon, a Hall of Fame QB.
</P>
<P>
   But never in their nearly quarter century in the NFL have they
had a studhoss at his peak.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, they've tried. My goodness, they have tried.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, the Seahawks squandered a first- and fifth-round pick
on Kelly Stouffer. In '91, they squandered a first-round pick on
Dan McGwire. In '93, they squandered a first-round pick, second
overall in the draft, on Rick Mirer.
</P>
<P>
   What all those franchise resources _ plus more that have been
wasted on lesser luminaries _ add up to is a grand total of three
wins in the playoffs and a soon-to-be-10-year absence from the
postseason.
</P>
<P>
   Krieg, a stumpy, undrafted free agent from a college that
expired, was the QB for all three playoff wins.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, the long-term Seahawk woes are attributable to far
more than a wretched few decades at one position. For example,
having an owner's right-hand man indicted for murder (you haven't
forgotten Mike Blatt, have you?) is just one of many signals that
this franchise must have been born upon a violated burial ground.
</P>
<P>
   More to the football point is that the Seahawks also never have
had a Pro Bowl offensive lineman. That's five positions times 23
years, and not once have they possessed a big ugly in his
pancake-making prime. In the NFL, that is almost a mathematical and
strategic impossibility.
</P>
<P>
   But when, year after year, the Seahawk observer sees team after
team advance to the playoffs in large part because of a stable,
solid signal caller, the Seattle void screams.
</P>
<P>
   A good QB is not a guarantee of success, of course. But not
having one is virtually a guarantee of failure.
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say that Kitna won't be the answer. He has offered
up enough intrigue in his limited playing time to suggest there are
decent possibilities here.
</P>
<P>
   Except the Seahawk fan has been down that road before.
</P>
<P>
   The sheer weight of franchise history conspires against his
success.
</P>
<P>
   If we confine this gridiron anthropology dig to the past 10
years, the record shows that in 1988, when Krieg took the Seahawks
to an AFC West championship with a 9-7 record, he had a quarterback
rating of 94.6, second best in the NFL that year and just shy of
his 1983 club record of 95.
</P>
<P>
   None since, including Krieg in his final three Seahawk seasons,
have approached that number. Even Moon last year, when he set club
records for passing yards and completions, had only an 83.7 rating,
largely because of his propensity for the interception.
</P>
<P>
   The rating system is hardly an absolute measure of quarterback
contribution. But it is one consistent device through the seasons
that measures the key virtue of passing efficiency. It doesn't take
into consideration all the other variables in the offense, but hey,
I have only 20 newspaper inches to make a point. Indulge me.
</P>
<P>
   Krieg probably will find this comparison amusing, since during
his time here he often was criticized for all the things he
couldn't do instead of praised for the things he could do. Hey,
he's still the NFL's career leader in fumbles (official) and
soap-dish passes (unofficial).
</P>
<P>
   But Mudbone had a grittiness and resolve about him that overcame
his mistakes and physical limits and pushed him, and his team, as
far as anyone could have expected.
</P>
<P>
   It's just that few have expected a lot from the Seahawks.
</P>
<P>
   Except for now, under Paul Allen.
</P>
<P>
   As Seahawk followers know, the owner's investment in payroll has
created a team far more talented than the 5-6 record, which is why
coach Dennis Erickson couldn't be more finished here than if he
were sanded, varnished and buffed.
</P>
<P>
   Much has been expected. Unfortunately for him, four years of
middling results will be remembered ironically for the period's
offensive desperation: The franchise had to rely on a
fortysomething trigger man who had the audacity to hold out of
training camp for more money. And he got at least some of it.
</P>
<P>
   Revered as he is in Seattle and the NFL, and as untouchable as
his longevity records will be, Moon should not have been in
position to leverage the franchise as he has.
</P>
<P>
   Don't blame him for being a smart businessman. Blame almost a
quarter century of bad judgment and bad luck that made the Seahawks
so vulnerable at the game's most important spot.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-25-98 0101EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
