<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OCEAN-ENERGY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OCEAN ENERGY AND SEAGULL SET TO CREATE MAJOR OIL CONCERN 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By AGIS SALPUKAS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ocean Energy Inc. and the Seagull Energy Corp. have agreed to
merge in a stock swap creating the nation's 10th-largest
independent oil company, executives said on Tuesday night. The deal
is expected to be announced on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   James Flores, the president and chief executive of Ocean Energy,
said in an interview that the companies, which will have a combined
market capitalization of $1.9 billion, decided to merge to cut
costs and increase efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   He said about $45 million in yearly savings would come mostly
from cutting duplicate staff. Flores said about one-third of the
1,200 employees of the combined companies would lose their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are striving to be more efficient and drive our costs
down,'' said Flores, who is 38 and will become the chairman of the
combined company, which will be called Ocean Energy Inc. It will be
based in Houston. James Hackett, who left Duke Energy to take over
as president of Seagull just a few months ago, will become
president and chief executive officer of the combined company.
</P>
<P>
   Hackett told analysts this month that he was seeking to merge
with another independent oil company.
</P>
<P>
   Low crude oil prices are forcing many oil companies to seek ways
to cut costs or to find merger partners to share the expense of
exploring and producing.
</P>
<P>
   Independent oil companies, most dependent on the revenue they
get from selling crude oil and natural gas, have been particularly
hard hit. They do not have refineries and retail outlets to sell
gasoline to help them get through long periods when crude oil
prices remain depressed.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the deal, each Ocean Energy shareholder will
get one newly issued share of Seagull common stock for each share
of Ocean Energy. There will be 165 million shares outstanding, with
61.5 percent owned by Ocean Energy shareholders and the rest owned
by Seagull shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Seagull fell 56.25 cents, to $10.8125 on Tuesday.
Shares of Ocean Energy rose $1.6875, to $10.25. Both are traded on
the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Flores said the combined company would concentrate on increasing
production from its domestic fields and in the Gulf of Mexico. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
