<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-PEPP-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONGING FOR FAST LANE, PEPPERDINE CRAWLS TO WIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MALIBU, Calif. _ Tie an anvil to Carl Lewis' track shoes, strap
Linda Tripp on his back and place him in a broom closet, then tell
him to sprint. That roughly approximates the boiling, bottled-up
frustration felt by Pepperdine right about now.
</P>
<P>
   As the Waves play through a stretch of walk/don't-run opponents,
their up-tempo style slowed to a maddening crawl, the games are
losing some aesthetic value. But the Waves continue to compensate
with victories, the latest a 60-50 decision over Wichita State on
Tuesday at Firestone Fieldhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Pepperdine endured a painfully slow and physical opening half to
take an eight-point lead by halftime, then held off a handful of
surges from the Shockers to close out the win. The Waves are 5-0
for the first time since the Carter administration, and it only
seems like it's been that long since an opponent let them run full
speed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would like to get loose. We feel like we're locked up right
now,'' guard Jelani Gardner groused.
</P>
<P>
   For perspective, consider that Wichita held the Waves to just 41
field-goal attempts, about 12 fewer shots than their season
average. The slowdown produced rushed shots, turnovers and minimal
electricity. It was the second straight game, following a victory
at Long Beach State, in which Pepperdine has had to win at half
speed.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of teams want to slow us down, because they know that's
our strength. . . . We've proven that we can play either way and
win,'' Gardner said.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, he must admit, ``I think guys get bored with this
style.''
</P>
<P>
   He isn't kidding. But the Shockers' strategy was effective to
the extent it kept them in the game. After trailing continuously
since early in the first half, and by as many as 13 in the second
half, Wichita chipped the lead down to five, 55-50, when Jason
Perez hit a 3-pointer with 1:18 left in the game.
</P>
<P>
   The shot capped a 5-0 run over a three-minute span in which the
Waves missed a pair of free throws and turned the ball over on
mishaps such as Gardner stepping on the baseline.
</P>
<P>
   ``We became a little impatient at that point,'' Waves coach
Lorenzo Romar said. ``We are at our worst when we begin to hurry.''
</P>
<P>
   But the threat from Wichita, which had pulled no closer than six
points in the half, was short-lived. Gardner fed Marc McDowell for
an easy layup to make it 57-50, and at the other end, Kelvin Gibbs
blocked Maurice Evans' 3-point attempt with about 30 seconds
remaining to seal the win.
</P>
<P>
   Not that it would have even been that close if the Waves could
shoot free throws. They hit 14 of 25 (56 percent). Gibbs missed
four of his 10 foul shots but led Pepperdine with 13 points and
eight rebounds. Gardner and McDowell scored 10 each.
</P>
<P>
   They'll be itching to crank up those numbers soon and might get
their wish against Cal State Fullerton on Saturday and certainly
against Kansas on Dec. 5. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
