A8358 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-SCHOOP-LADN     11-25 0569
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-SCHOOP-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLOW START, LATE ROUT FOR USC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ There was the upset of Nevada-Las Vegas. There was
the handful of votes in this week's Top 25 poll. There was Tuesday
night's opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Is it any wonder USC got off to a slow start against Long Beach
State?
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans, basking in the good fortune of the past few days,
were ahead by just six points at halftime against the 49ers. But
perhaps in a demonstration of how differently this year's team is
developing, USC quickly regrouped and routed the 49ers 74-48 before
2,836 at the Sports Arena.
</P>
<P>
   USC (3-0) is off to its best start in 10 years, and handed the
49ers their second-worst loss in the two-plus seasons of coach
Wayne Morgan.
</P>
<P>
   But early in the game it didn't look like it would be that way.
The Trojans were nip and tuck with the 49ers for the entire first
half, fortunate to scratch out a 33-27 advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were very sluggish. Our practices the last two days were
the same way,'' USC coach Henry Bibby said. ``You kind of expect
that coming off a big win over UNLV, a nationally known game. It
takes time for guys to get in sync.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Bibby dropped a bombshell. He said he feared the 49ers
(1-3) more than UNLV, whom the Trojans defeated last Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really scared of Long Beach State,'' Bibby said. ``They
have athletes. They rebound. I really feared this team, probably
more than Vegas, from a standpoint of a letdown.''
</P>
<P>
   Bibby snapped USC out its first-half funk by giving the team an
earful at halftime. Among those who listened was guard Jeff
Trepagnier, who had 12 points and three blocked shots, after
scoring just one point in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess it was the halftime speech. Coach said if I wanted to
play, I would have to do something,'' Trepagnier said. ``Everybody
says I play hard and they feed off my energy.''
</P>
<P>
   Trepagnier energized the Trojans by making two impressive
blocks, then followed up with a spectacular dunk that resulted in a
three-point play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jeff's dunks (make a difference),'' forward Brian Scalabrine
said. ``The whole crowd goes nuts. We say to ourselves, `OK, it's
fun. Let's play basketball.' He's the key to our team.''
</P>
<P>
   So is Scalabrine. He had 19 points, four rebounds and four
assists and is already USC's best player, despite sitting out last
season at Highline Community College in Des Moines, Wash. There's
been no trace of rust on 6-foot-9 redhead, who hadn't played a real
basketball game in nearly two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I redshirted, but I worked out before practice, during
practice and after practice,'' Scalabrine said.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Trepagnier, the Trojans' other spark came from forward
Greg Lakey, who was motivated by being limited to five minutes in
the victory over UNLV. Lakey had nine points and nine rebounds in
16 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really wanted to come in and show (Bibby) I could do what I
needed to do,'' Lakey said. ``I felt kind of angry and put it in a
positive mode to get the job done. I was trying to be everywhere,
so next time he'll think of me.''
</P>
<P>
   !arrow!Note:!off! With minutes in short supply, forward Shannon
Swillis found himself the odd man out and did not play. After going
16 minutes in the opener against San Diego State, Swillis has
played just five minutes in the previous two games.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
