</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-RANDY-JOHNSON-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANDY JOHNSON LOOKING WEST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Rangers are in danger of losing out in the high-stakes race
to sign free-agent pitcher Randy Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Major-league officials close to the negotiations said yesterday
Johnson is leaning toward signing with either the Arizona
Diamondbacks or the Anaheim Angels. However, Alan Nero, his agent,
said the Rangers and the Los Angeles Dodgers haven't been
eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Rangers are clearly being considered,'' Nero said. ``They
have made a very competitive offer, a very formidable offer. Randy
has a lot of respect for that organization. They're a contender,
and he's made it clear that he wants to play for a contender.''
</P>
<P>
   All four teams have offered Johnson a four-year contract. The
Rangers offered four years at $50 million on Monday. But a source
said the Dodgers have made the highest offer at $52 million, and
the Diamondbacks have offered somewhere between $48 million and $50
million.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers general manager Kevin Malone said, ``If we're out of it,
we haven't been notified.''
</P>
<P>
   Rangers president Tom Schieffer said yesterday he had not talked
with Nero or agent Barry Meister since their face-to-face meetings
at The Ballpark in Arlington on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a real quiet day, but we expected that,'' Schieffer
said. ``We gave them a lot of information to digest, I think
they're in the process of doing that. I think something will happen
in the next few days. When, I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Nero said Johnson could make a decision today or would wait
until after Thanksgiving.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels fit Johnson's desire to play for an American League
team that has a chance to win and is close to his home in Arizona.
The Diamondbacks are getting strong consideration because Johnson
lives in a Phoenix suburb and wants to stay close to his family.
</P>
<P>
   All indications are Johnson's decision will come down to either
staying home to pitch with the Diamondbacks or with one of the
three other teams who are considered legitimate contenders.
</P>
<P>
   But the second-year Diamondbacks, who finished 65-97 last year,
are also making a strong bid to become competitive quickly. They
have already signed pitcher Todd Stottlemyre and have talked with
the agents of free-agent outfielders Bernie Williams and Steve
Finley.
</P>
<P>
   The Disney-owned Angels are close to signing first baseman Mo
Vaughn to a deal potentially worth $80 million, and general manager
Bill Bavasi spent much of yesterday meeting with ownership
officials, discussing if the club could afford both Vaughn and
Johnson. A source said they could.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' offer did serve to eliminate the Houston Astros and
New York Yankees from contention. Houston Astros general manager
Gerry Hunsicker, who traded for Johnson on July 31, said yesterday
his club is no longer pursuing him. Sources said the New York
Yankees have also declined to match the Rangers' offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a discussion with Randy Johnson's representatives
yesterday, and he officially notified us that to stay competitive,
we would have to commit to a four-year contract,'' Hunsicker said.
``We're not prepared to do that. It just came down to economics,
that's not a level where we can participate financially.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros had offered Johnson a three-year deal worth
approximately $33 million. The Rangers trumped that with a
three-year, $39 million offer earlier this month, then went even
higher on Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
