<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-25 09:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8641 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUGSLIFE-REVIEW26-COX     11-25 0602
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUGSLIFE-REVIEW26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Movie review of 'Bug's Life'
 &HT;    By Chris Garcia
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ An annoying little film that strives to
entertain with a bullhorn, ``A Bug's Life'' will mollify the Happy
Meal lot as surely as it will chafe anyone who no longer finds the
noun ``butt'' a sufficient punchline. It's buggy, all right _ like
a caffeinated gnat buzzing in your ear. You want to squish it.
Hard.
</P>
<P>
   Brought to us by twin mavens of manipulation Disney and
computer-animator Pixar _ the same team that conspired on the
richer, wittier ``Toy Story'' _ ``A Bug's Life'' pales under the
long and fruitful shadow of last month's crawly cartoon comedy
``Antz.'' That movie boasts more quality laughs in its first 10
minutes than its paltry brethren summons in 90.
</P>
<P>
   Both films center around computer-drawn, anthropomorphic ant
colonies, but while ``Antz's'' comic sophistication crackles with
knowing satire, ``A Bug's Life'' lacks a whit of originality. The
characters don't budge beyond hackneyed types that could be plucked
from any animated Disney feature, and the story is nothing more
than a caramel-dunked ``Seven Samurai.''
</P>
<P>
   Needless to say, Pixar is no schlump in the art department. The
gleaming, often striking computer images move wonderfully and emit
a kind of waxed car sheen, a plasticky perfection. But the script
is steadfast in its pursuit of common denominator yuks, vanilla
gags aimed at suburban TV sensibilities.
</P>
<P>
   A scene that gets some of the biggest laughs shows a fly who is
drawn into a bug-zapper, hypnotized by the contraption's purple
radiance. (``Look away from the light!'' his pal cries.) A
typically lame one-liner comes when a female spider says her
husband is dead and chirps, ``I'm a black widow widow.'' ``A Bug's
Life'' fairly chokes on cutesies like these.
</P>
<P>
   A bland Dave Foley (from TV's ``NewsRadio'') provides the voice
of Flik, an earnest young ant who departs his teeming colony to
enlist help against a marauding band of grasshoppers. The
grasshoppers, led by ruthless Hopper (Kevin Spacey), invade the ant
colony by the seasonal clock in order to pillage their crunchy
harvest. Why, we never know. The movie needs a villain, so why not
rapacious grasshoppers?
</P>
<P>
   When Flik stumbles across a feckless flea circus, he thinks he's
found a worthy crew of mercenaries, unaware the motley troupe is
literally a bunch of clowns. Drama mounts as Flik's expectations
are frustrated and the ant colony appears doomed, and the
floodgates of predictability gleefully swing open.
</P>
<P>
   Three-alarm slapstick reigns in ``A Bug's Life,'' and the shrill
vivacity could be mistaken for wit if its contrivances weren't so
graceless. Pinging and clanging in a tireless clamor Spike Jones
would find obnoxious, the story finally winds down with a deflating
why-didn't-they-think-of-that-before? resolution.
</P>
<P>
   The too-tidy ending is steeped in Disney's didactic fondness for
order and conformity, inoculating us with sweet incantations about
self-esteem and perseverance. It's nice stuff for the children, but
it's also conventional to the bone.
</P>
<P>
   My adult star rating for ``A Bug's Life'' is two stars. If I
were 5 years old, it would be a giggle-laced three. Sorry, kids.
Starring: the voices of Dave Foley, Kevin Spacey, Julia
Louis-Dreyfus, Phyllis Diller Director: John Lasseter
Screenwriters: Andrew Stanton, Donald McEnery, Bob Shaw MPAA
rating: G
</P>
<P>
   Chris Garcia is the film critic for the Austin
American-Statesman, Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-25-98 0932EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
