</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-CHAMP-BAILEY26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Either way, Bailey's best
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ Georgia's Champ Bailey won't win the Heisman
Trophy. In fact, the Bulldogs' two-way star probably won't be
invited to New York's Downtown Athletic Club for the Heisman
presentation on Dec. 12.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, the Heisman rarely goes to college football's best
player, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't make any difference what spot it is _ cornerback,
wide receiver or return man _ Bailey does it all better than
anyone, including former Michigan star Charles Woodson, who
parlayed his versatility and knack for making big plays in big
games into winning last year's Heisman.
</P>
<P>
   Bailey, a 6-foot-1, 186-pound junior from Folkston, first
displayed his penchant of making big plays on both sides of the
ball in Georgia's 27-24 win over Georgia Tech in last year's
regular-season finale. On Saturday, he'll get another shot at the
Yellow Jackets in what could be his final game in Sanford Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Bailey, who starts at both left cornerback and wideout for the
No. 12 Bulldogs, is projected to be a top-10 pick in next year's
NFL draft if he leaves Georgia after this season. Bailey says he
won't announce a decision regarding his future until after the
Dogs' bowl game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hear people say stuff about it (turning pro), but I still
don't know what the facts really are (on his possible draft
position),'' Bailey said. ``I'll just have to wait and see. I don't
know what's going to make me decide.''
</P>
<P>
   What others are saying is that Bailey, a finalist for the Thorpe
Award, which goes annually to the nation's top defensive back,
could be among the first five players drafted. If he leaves Athens
a year early, he could be the first defensive back taken, ahead of
Arizona's Chris McAlister and Ohio State's Antoine Winfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's somewhere in the top 10 players, depending on what
juniors come out,'' ESPN draft analyst Mel Kiper Jr. said. ``He's
certainly in the top five to 10. I've heard that he's probably
coming out. When you look at the corners, it's Bailey and McAlister
with Winfield right behind them. They'll all probably go very
high.''
</P>
<P>
   Bailey's versatility has some NFL scouts pondering what position
he'll play at the next level. Last year, Bailey was only a novelty
on offense. He had only 12 catches for 234 yards and five rushes
for 15 yards. But his big-play capabilities proved very fruitful
against Georgia Tech.
</P>
<P>
   With only 48 seconds left in Bobby Dodd Stadium, Georgia trailed
Tech 24-21. The Bulldogs started their final drive at their 35-yard
line. On first down, quarterback Mike Bobo hit Bailey with a short
screen pass, which he turned into a 28-yard gain to the Tech 37. On
the next play, Bobo hit Bailey on a slant pattern for a seven-yard
gain to the 30.
</P>
<P>
   After a nine-yard pass to tailback Robert Edwards and a
controversial pass interference call against the Yellow Jackets,
Bobo found Corey Allen in the end zone, giving the Bulldogs a 27-24
win.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got confidence in Champ to make the plays,'' said Bobo,
now a graduate assistant at Georgia. ``Coach (Jim) Donnan wanted to
get the ball to the fastest guy on our team and let him make
something happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Bailey has made things happen on offense ever since. This
season, he's Georgia's biggest weapon on offense. Bailey has seen
action in 855 plays and made an impact on offense, defense and
special teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see myself as a defensive back and wide receiver,'' Bailey
said. ``I think I've probably got better potential as a defensive
back in the NFL. I'd like to play both on the next level, though.''
</P>
<P>
   As a defensive back, Bailey has three interceptions this year,
despite opposing quarterbacks' reluctance to throw to his side of
the field. His workload _ Bailey has been involved in 49.9 percent
of Georgia's plays this season _ has somewhat diminished his skills
in the secondary.
</P>
<P>
   Bailey, who spends halftime taking fluids intravenously, has
surrendered two touchdowns this season. He got beat on a couple of
crossing patterns in last week's 24-17 win over Mississippi, but
Bailey played in that game with a bruised left thumb, which remains
in a soft cast.
</P>
<P>
   On offense, Bailey leads the Bulldogs with 43 catches for 706
yards, an average of 16.4 yards per catch, with five touchdowns. On
special teams, he's a threat to break a big return at any time _
against Kentucky he returned three kickoffs for 90 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to get the ball to Champ on offense more,'' Donnan
said. ``Every time we've thrown him a deep ball, he seems to catch
it.''
</P>
<P>
   While Georgia stands to lose a Bailey for the second year in a
row _ his older brother, Ronald, graduated last year after starting
at right cornerback for two seasons _ the Dogs will gain another
one.
</P>
<P>
   Bailey's cousin, Kenny Bailey, verbally committed to Georgia on
Saturday. Bailey, an all-purpose player from Charlton County High,
enrolled at Hargrave Military Academy in Virginia after originally
signing with Wake Forest in February. He'll join Boss Bailey,
Champ's brother and a freshman linebacker for the Bulldogs.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Schlaback writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
