<HEADER>
A8643 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-LASTPLAY26-COX     11-25 0797
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-LASTPLAY26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Still feeling burn from '97
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The touchdown that gave Georgia the victory over
Georgia Tech last year went from quarterback Mike Bobo to receiver
Corey Allen on a pass route called a fade.
</P>
<P>
   For Georgia Tech cornerback Kofi Smith, that play has done
anything but fade.
</P>
<P>
   Smith's Georgia-Georgia Tech experience _ and for a while, all
of his Georgia Tech career _ was whittled from 60 minutes to 48
seconds to one single moment. Since then, he has seen it dozens of
times on videotape. He has stared at it frozen in time in a framed
newspaper photograph, which captured Allen clutching the ball at
his chest a foot away from Smith's outstretched left arm. Both of
them were airborne at the edge of the end zone in Bobby Dodd
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was me and the receiver and the quarterback and the
clock,'' said Smith, who started that game in place of injured
Jason Bostic. ``I held the guilt on me, the loss on me.''
</P>
<P>
   The touchdown to end the 27-24 loss _ Tech's seventh in a row in
the series _ came with eight seconds left in the game, but to Smith
it felt like eight seconds had been left in his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought that was it for me as a player,'' Smith said. ``I
had all intentions of giving up my football career after that play.
That was the hardest thing I have ever faced. I took it pretty bad.
I was walking around saying I lost the game. . . . I didn't feel I
could attend Georgia Tech anymore and look into the other students'
eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   After a couple of weeks, Smith started to bounce back, taking
comfort in some words from a friend, who reminded him that
``sometimes God closes a door to open up a new window.''
</P>
<P>
   By his door, Smith hung a framed copy of the newspaper picture
of the play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever I went out the door, it made me think about it, to
make sure it would never happen again,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Heading into his final game against Georgia on Saturday, Smith,
who is a reserve cornerback used mainly on special teams, has taken
the picture down. He doesn't want to focus on the negative. But the
play is still fresh in his mind, as is the last drive, and he still
uses it as a motivating force.
</P>
<P>
   The same goes for every Tech player on the field and on the
sideline during the final drive. For the Yellow Jackets, that drive
did more than break their hearts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your rib cage is ripped out,'' Tech coach George O'Leary said.
``From kickoff to score, we didn't do very much right. It's a
60-minute game. I think our team has learned from that. . . . They
made plays, and we didn't make a play. It's a simple fact.''
</P>
<P>
   Five plays, 65 yards, 40 seconds, six points.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia's winning drive was set up by a kickoff out of bounds by
Tech's David Frakes, jumpstarted by a 28-yard screen pass from Bobo
to Champ Bailey and pumped with new life following a pass
interference call against Donte Booker, which negated a Travares
Tillman interception and gave Georgia first and goal at the 8.
</P>
<P>
   The call went against Booker, then a reserve sophomore outside
linebacker from Pittsburgh whom Tech coaches decided to use for his
cover skills on Georgia's big-play receiver Hines Ward across the
middle.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I turned in, I was in good position,'' Booker said. ``I
was trying to 'wall' him in, keep him from beating me on the
inside. He dove and I dove after him. I landed on top of him. Three
and a half yards away Travares Tillman had intercepted the pass. I
got up to celebrate, (and) then I saw the flag.''
</P>
<P>
   Booker and his teammates still doubt the call. Georgia players
said afterward they thought it was good call.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a big-time NFL prospect; I'm playing against him looking
for my first big break,'' Booker said. ``I have a chance to make
the winning stop. . . . I was the one who gave them another chance
to score on us. I had to live with it.''
</P>
<P>
   It brought Booker to tears. It disturbed his sleep. It put him
on his knees to pray.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the next month and a half, I dreamed about it a lot,''
Booker said. ``It's been on my mind ever since. I still have a bad
taste in my mouth every time I think about Georgia. I'm looking for
a chance Saturday to redeem myself.''
</P>
<P>
   The year-old memories aren't anywhere close to fading, but for
the Yellow Jackets, maybe that's not just a bad thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``You always want to remember where you came from,'' senior
defensive end Jesse Tarplin said. ``Every long drive we have is a
reminder of the Georgia game. We feel like if we ever get in a
situation like that again, we can come up with a big play.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll Rogers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
