<HEADER>
A8644 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-UT-RENFRO26-COX     11-25 1379
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UT-RENFRO26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dusty Renfro shows determination, good attitude
 &HT;    By Mark Wangrin
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Normally, Dusty Renfro would deal with this
problem like he did anything else, just bludgeon it into submission
with sheer determination. Kind of like he did with the speech
impediment, or in winning district in the shot and discus with a
broken hand, or in becoming the driving force of the Longhorn
defense with the song of too-small, too-slow, ringing in his ears.
</P>
<P>
   Sleep is a different animal, though. The more you try to drift
off, the more your mind races with possibilities, and Sunday night
the senior linebacker's head was ground zero of cranial activity.
</P>
<P>
   He crawled into bed at 11 p.m. with visions of Friday's game
against Texas A&AMP;M, his final home game as a Texas Longhorn. He
picked off a pass. Made a sack. Stood up the running back at the
goal line. The clock ran, but the game must have gone into
quintuple overtime, because it was 4:30 a.m. and he was still
tackling, blitzing and sacking.
</P>
<P>
   Once was a time when Renfro had a sure-fire cure for anxiety
induced insomnia, courtesy of his mom, Mary. One night long ago,
after visions of a horror movie melded with the imagination of a
4-year-old, dust bunnies became monsters, fears became tears and
sleep became out of the question. Thinking quickly, Mary filled a
spray bottle with water and slapped on a hand-written label that
read, ``Monster Spray.'' Spritz a little under the bed before you
go to sleep, mom said, and monsters stay away. Every night at
bedtime. Spritz. Spritz. Spritz.
</P>
<P>
   This time was different. Monster spray wasn't needed, because
monsters weren't what Renfro feared. If anything, in his dreams he
was the monster and the Aggies were the petrified 4-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to have the game of my life,'' Renfro says.
</P>
<P>
   To do that, Renfro would have to outshine his more illustrious
counterpart, Aggie inside linebacker Dat Nguyen, a Butkus Award
finalist. ``I definitely want to outplay Dat,'' Renfro says. ``That
means I'd be doing more for my team than he is for his. Really,
I've got to.''
</P>
<P>
   Renfro finally drifted off in the pre-dawn hours Monday,
presumably dreaming of just how he was going to do that. It's a
tall order, but Renfro is used to standing taller than his listed
6-feet, hitting harder than his 239-pounds and running faster than
his 4.8 speed in the 40 yard dash.
</P>
<P>
   ``His desire to be good is his No. 1 asset,'' says Texas
linebacker coach and defensive coordinator Carl Reese. ``If you
drew up the prototype linebacker, that would be the No. 1 asset.
Then you'd want him to be 6-4, run a 4.4 _ but he's got the thing
I'd pick first in a linebacker.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've gained more appreciation for him from the first day than
any player I've ever coached,'' head coach Mack Brown says. ``He's
a great role model for us in recruiting. I told our coaches, go
find players with the heart, desire and academics of Dusty Renfro.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a fun year of coaching, and he's one of the
reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   Renfro, who over the years has been a regular at the weekly
press luncheons despite having to stomach a steady diet of
questions about the defense's shortcomings along with the brisket
and sausage, doesn't shy away from the criticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``They always forget that I'm one of the strongest players (450
bench press, 585 squat) on the team,'' Renfro says of his
detractors. ``Also, I'm about to become the fifth-leading tackler
in school history. That's got to count for something.''
</P>
<P>
   Fact is, Renfro was cut out to play linebacker from the moment
he was born to Mary and her husband Terry, who had aspired to play
college football at UT-Arlington before learning Mary was pregnant
with their first child, Chad, after which he took two jobs to make
ends meet while going to college. ``My dad tells me all the time
I'm living out his dream,'' Dusty says.
</P>
<P>
   The first word out of the infant Dusty's mouth was ``ball.'' His
parents bought him a ``little bitty'' football uniform and he
worked on his tackling technique in the front yard. ``If it wasn't
his brother, it was the trees,'' Mary recalls. ``I don't think he
won too many of those battles _ the trees are still standing.''
</P>
<P>
   Dusty started playing football for real in second grade, moving
in immediately at middle linebacker on the Alvarado Chiefs of the
Brazos Valley Pee Wee Football Association, a team that included
third and fourth graders. When the team went into one-on-one
tackling drills, the other players suddenly grew interested in
math. ``They were always back there counting positions, to see who
was going to face him,'' says Terry, who coached that team. ``They
were always playing musical chairs, trying not to face him.''
</P>
<P>
   He was always strong. As the family was preparing to go to the
funeral of a cousin died of Rocky Mountain Spotted Fever, Dusty
developed a high fever, too, and Mary noticed a tick bite on his
neck. They took Dusty to the hospital, and it took three adults to
hold down the 7-year-old to take his blood. (Turns out he hates
needles. Also turns out he did have Rocky Mountain Spotted Fever,
and only a quick dose of tetracycline saved his life, Mary says.)
</P>
<P>
   At 12, he tried the bench press for the first time and promptly
lifted 200 pounds. His strength earned him the requisite nicknames
_ Bam Bam and Tank _ and it also attracted the attention of
Alvarado High School football coach and athletic director Jim
Skinner, who wanted Renfro to throw the shot put and discus for the
track team. Renfro made him a deal: I'll win the shot and disc at
district for you; you get me a powerlifting team. Agreed.
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of both competitions, Renfro got something else _ a
broken hand from a fist fight with, as Renfro put it, ``a couple of
Harley-Davidson guys.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought he shouldn't life with a broken hand,'' Terry says,
``but he was bigger than we were.''
</P>
<P>
   So he lifted, finishing second in the 242-pound class at the
state meet, held at A&AMP;M (''I strutted around in my Texas hat, shirt
off, staring everyone down,'' he recalls warmly). He also made good
on his promise, winning the shot and discus at the district track
meet.
</P>
<P>
   Though he nearly committed to Spike Dykes on his recruiting
visit to Texas Tech, he wound up becoming a Longhorn, something
he'd always dreamed about. He backed up Tyson King at inside
linebacker as a freshman and became a full-time starter as a
sophomore, missing two games with a thumb injury. Last year he
began the season at strongside linebacker in the new 4-3 set, but
moved back to the middle after Aaron Humphrey's trial there didn't
pan out.
</P>
<P>
   This year he hasn't made as many tackles as his career-high 116
last fall _ a function of the defensive improvement _ but he
already has more sacks (6) and as many pressures (3) as he had in
his three previous seasons combined.
</P>
<P>
   What Renfro lacks in speed, he has to make up for in smarts.
Before each game, he watches each of the take-home videotapes of
the opponent's three previous games twice. ``I'm trying to find
something that will tell me the play before the snap,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Against Oklahoma State, Renfro noticed that when the right
tackle was in a two-point, pass-blocking stance while all the other
linemen were in three-point stances, it meant a weakside lead run
was coming. Every time OSU lined up that way, Renfro shouted the
call to his teammates (''It was Fat Boy,' in honor of the tackle,''
Renfro grins) and the play was shut down.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt he's dreaming of similar feats against the Aggies, and
he isn't about to let someone tell him it isn't possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the last time,'' Renfro says. ``There are things I
want to get done.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked for his favorite Dusty story, Terry pauses and says,
``Really, every time he plays the game. We expect the best and he
delivers it. All the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard Mack Brown say that he used to think Dusty was an
overachiever, because he didn't run a 4.5 40, but that he realized
that after you keep doing it for a while, you become an achiever.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Wangrin writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
