<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMEFRIES-REVIEW26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Movie review of 'Home Fries'
 &HT;    By Chris Garcia
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ When a movie has to graft on a Cobra attack
helicopter as a major comic device, you can be sure the script is
wanting just a wee bit.
</P>
<P>
   In the hopelessly dumb ``Home Fries,'' the airborne conveyance
pops up twice, out of nowhere and for no apparent reason. Um, it
looks cool? It creates the illusion of a big-budget movie?
</P>
<P>
   My theory is that director Dean Parisot has a friend or uncle
who owns a Cobra chopper and he just couldn't resist using it in
his movie. He should have, for the result is one of the most
awkward and unnatural visual gags I've ever seen. And I'm just
pointing out the most blatant example of forced ``wacky humor''
that makes ``Home Fries'' such a queasy dud.
</P>
<P>
   Filmed in Bastrop two years ago this month (the finished movie
moldered in limbo for well over a year), the dark Southern farce
stars Drew Barrymore as a drive-thru clerk at the local
Burger-Matic. She's burstingly pregnant, but the sad-sack father is
not only married, he just died of a heart attack caused by, guess
what, that infernal helicopter. (The scene is astonishingly
preposterous.)
</P>
<P>
   The copter pilots are dim-bulb brothers (Luke Wilson and toothy
Jake Busey) and the guy they snuffed is their stepfather. Their
mother (Catherine O'Hara), mortified by his adultery, nudged the
boys to do it. Now she wants the guilty mistress deleted as well.
Thing is, one of the boys has fallen for the mistress (Barrymore)
and ... well, the story plummets to embarrassing depths of inanity
from there.
</P>
<P>
   Lacking an authentic moment, a smart joke or persuasive acting
(even the doleful Shelly Duvall just kind of lies there), ``Home
Fries'' tries desperately to work off its white-trash quirks and
hillbilly cutes, from the drunk, scrappy redneck to the big-haired
bimbo who lives in a trailer. We're supposed to laugh. I winced.
</P>
<P>
   Starring: Drew Barrymore, Luke Wilson, Catherine O'Hara, Jake
Busey Director: Dean Parisot Screenwriter: Vince Gilligan MPAA
rating: PG-13 for language, cartoonish violence
</P>
<P>
   Chris Garcia is the film critic for the Austin
American-Statesman, Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
