<HEADER>
A8646 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-UT-RECORD26-COX     11-25 0517
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UT-RECORD26-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Hoopla for Williams won't include stopping game
</P>
<P>
   By Suzanne Halliburton
</P>
<P>
   C. 1998 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The 81,000 fans expected at Royal-Memorial
Stadium Friday morning will be in for huge dose of Ricky Williams
if the star Texas running back breaks the Division I-A rushing
record against Texas A&AMP;M.
</P>
<P>
   But the huge dose won't come until after the game.
</P>
<P>
   UT officials planned Monday for a Williams celebration, figuring
that he likely will rush for the 63 yards he needs to break Tony
Dorsett's career rushing record of 6,082.
</P>
<P>
   Don't expect the game to be stopped when Williams gets the
record. The football, if the game officials allow it, will be
secured and taken safely to the sideline. It will be sent, along
with Williams' jersey, to the National Football Foundation Hall of
Fame in South Bend, Ind.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't intrude on the integrity of the game,'' said UT
associate athletic director Chris Plonsky. ``If he breaks it, you
announce, and the game keeps going.''
</P>
<P>
   After the game, there will be about a two-minute video tribute
to Williams on the JumboTron scoreboard. Coach Mack Brown also
plans to address the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Williams said Monday he wants no fuss.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it were up to me, there would be no big deal,'' Williams
said. ``We'd keep playing the game, then I'd go into the locker
room, no big deal.''
</P>
<P>
   But it's obviously not up to Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ABC will broadcast the game to a national audience. The network
has been hyping Williams and the game since last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   And Dorsett plans to fly to Austin on Friday morning. His plane
lands 25 minutes before kickoff, and he will be given a police
escort to the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Dorsett has been issued a sideline pass. He will be accompanied
by former UT great and Heisman winner Earl Campbell, who saw his UT
career rushing record broken by Williams earlier this season.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, there have been more than 500 media passes issued.
Along with the state newspapers, representatives of Sports
Illustrated, the New York Times, the San Diego Times-Union and the
Chicago Tribune will be on hand to chronicle Williams' assault on
college football history. Even the Columbia Missourian has
requested a credential. Officials with the Walter Camp Football
Foundation also have been given press passes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The in-state papers are doubling and tripling their
coverage,'' said Bill Little, UT assistant athletic director. He
said the media throng rivals the number of journalists who covered
the UT-Notre Dame game in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   However, a number of the credentials were issued to reporters
and photographers from small weekly papers around the state. The
px is full, and the overflow will be given sideline passes.
No more credentials will be issued.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every weekly paper got a pass because of Mack Brown's feeling
that this game is so important to the state of Texas,'' Little
said.
</P>
<P>
   Suzanne Halliburton writes for the Austin American-Statesman,
Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
