<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-25 09:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8647 &Cx1f; tad-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-AGENT-CUTS26-C     11-25 0876
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-AGENT-CUTS26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Travel agents face cut in pay, online booking
 &HT;    By Jerry Mahoney
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Just as she did three years ago, Austin travel
agent Beth Barnes is once again looking around her office for ways
to cut costs.
</P>
<P>
   If it isn't needed, it faces elimination. Expenses for
conferences, new equipment, even magazine subscriptions are
scrutinized.
</P>
<P>
   Like Barnes, travel agency owners across Central Texas and
throughout the country are trying to figure out how to absorb what
amounts to another pay cut from several major airlines.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, American Airlines and Delta Air Lines announced they
would match United Airlines in capping commissions on all
international flights at $100 round-trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been very devastating for our business,'' said
Barnes, owner of B. Barnes Travel on Shoal Creek Boulevard in
Austin.
</P>
<P>
   The average international fare is $2,420 for a round-trip
ticket, according to the American Society of Travel Agents.
</P>
<P>
   With an 8 percent commission, travel agents would make $193.60
when they sold a ticket at that price. Now they get $100.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a long-range blow to our income,'' said Nancy Linares,
co-owner of Holidays 'N Travel of Austin. The agency, which employs
10 agents, gets 80 percent of its revenue from international
travel, she said.
</P>
<P>
   It's not just airlines putting the squeeze on travel agents
these days. Increasing sales of airline tickets over the Internet,
at sites like Microsoft's Expedia Travel, Travelocity and at
airlines' proprietary Web sites also are cutting into some
agencies' profits.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, travel agents still arrange an estimated 80 percent of
all airline flights, according to Linares.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't the first time that airlines, looking for ways to cut
their own costs, have cut commissions for travel agents.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, most major U.S. airlines capped commissions on domestic
flights at $50 for a round-trip fare. Commissions on international
bookings stayed at 10 percent until September 1997, when they were
cut to 8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Following 1995's cuts, employees of Round Rock Travel &AMP; Tours
thought they could make up the lower commissions by booking more
flights.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were just all getting frazzled and we were making
mistakes,'' said owner Bill Peckham.
</P>
<P>
   The agency stopped booking travel for some of its biggest
customers, including Southwestern University in Georgetown. Like
many agencies, Round Rock Travel &AMP; Tours now focuses on companies
that specialize in cruises or tours, which still pay 10 percent
commissions, Peckham said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tour companies and the cruise companies still love us,''
Peckham said.
</P>
<P>
   Delta said it paid more than $1 billion in travel agency
commissions last year, and expects the new cap to save $40 million
to $45 million annually.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers may soon be asked to make up for the lost revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Holidays 'N Travel's Linares, who also is on the board of the
American Retail Travel Agents Association trade group, said
agencies will be forced to charge travelers fees _ or if they
already charge fees, raise them _ to make up for lost commissions.
</P>
<P>
   The ASTA is quick to blame it on the airlines.
</P>
<P>
   ``The airlines know perfectly well that since they're reducing
the level of compensation below what it costs agents to process
tickets that the agents will have to turn to the consumers with
service fees,'' said Steve Loucks, a spokesman for the travel
agents society.
</P>
<P>
   According to an ASTA survey taken in June, 64 percent of member
agencies are charging some type of fee for doing services such as
issuing refunds, canceling trips and sending faxes to customers.
The average fee for a service is about $10.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent announcement has travel agents wondering what to
do next.
</P>
<P>
   The travel agent society said it is considering whether to try
and make an antitrust case, claiming the airlines are trying to
monopolize all ticketing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Independent studies have shown travel agents provide lower
fares than when the consumer contacts the airline directly,''
Loucks said. ``We believe that United's move is part of a
far-reaching strategy on the part of all the carriers to move
consumers to book directly with the carriers, so they'll pay more
for their tickets.''
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Transportation is already looking into whether
airlines discriminate against online travel services and travel
agents who use the Internet to obtain tickets.
</P>
<P>
   In his small offices across town from Dell Computer Corp., whose
online sales average more than $10 million a day, Peckham of Round
Rock Tour &AMP; Travel said he believes the Internet is overrated as a
means to buy airline tickets.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, there is no assurance the Internet sites display
the most current or lowest information, Peckham and other agents
say.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet is estimated to account for only about 1 percent of
airline ticket sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, there are too many of us old people who want to
come in and talk to somebody who has been on that ship,'' said
Peckham, who is 70.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Mahoney writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
