<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BOHLS-COLUMN26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    UT should to retire Williams' No. 34
 &HT;    By Kirk Bohls
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Friday's war will be the final time that we'll
see Ricky Williams running wild at Royal-Memorial Stadium. Other
than the bowl game next month, it should also mark the last time
we'll see his jersey number anywhere in college football.
</P>
<P>
   In what should be the biggest no-brainer since Playboy chose to
feature Katarina Witt over Dick Button, the University of Texas
should announce this week that it is retiring Williams' No. 34.
</P>
<P>
   No Longhorns player could duplicate or exceed the
accomplishments on or off the field that this guy with the funny
hairdo and the genteel manner has compiled over the last four
glorious seasons. Consequently, Texas should extend him the
ultimate honor and take his jersey number out of circulation for
all-time.
</P>
<P>
   ``That'd be nice,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   Few, if any, would argue the impact that Williams has had on any
number of levels, be it recruiting, exposure _ even fund-raising,
since he has helped raise $18,000 for the general scholarship fund
through the Doak Walker Award and ABC Player of the Game
decorations and should bring in another $10,000 with another Doak
Walker trophy. Williams has certainly been one of the top five
players in the history of this school.
</P>
<P>
   Come Saturday morning, he will awaken as the greatest running
back in college football history. Actually, he can wake up today as
the same, but the official coronation won't come until yard No. 63
against Texas A&AMP;M on Friday gives him the all-time Division I-A
rushing mark that currently belongs to Tony Dorsett.
</P>
<P>
   A decision to retire Ricky's garment might not be the slam-dunk
most would think. Remember, this is a school that has retired only
one jersey of the 64 All-America football players who have put on
the burnt orange and white, 31 of them consensus choices. Texas
didn't even remove Earl Campbell's No. 20 from use until 1979, two
years after he won his Heisman Trophy in his senior season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a precedent of retiring Heisman winner jerseys,''
Texas Athletic Director DeLoss Dodds said. ``There are a couple of
other people we've got to look at.''
</P>
<P>
   That would be linebacker Tommy Nobis (No. 60), considered the
greatest defensive player ever at the school, and quarterback Bobby
Layne (Nos. 41, 22), probably the school's greatest offensive
player preceding Campbell and Williams. Here's a vote for both of
theirs to be retired soon as well.
</P>
<P>
   Former Texas baseball coach Cliff Gustafson set off a firestorm
years ago when he publicly announced the school was retiring jersey
No. 21, which belonged to now-five-time Cy Young winner Roger
Clemens. The men's athletic council simmered privately after
Gustafson's presumption but eventually approved the move. The
backlash was considerable, because in the the next year the council
rebuffed Gus' plans to retire three-time All-American Burt Hooton's
jersey, which is why the lonely No. 21 sits on the right
center-field wall of Disch-Falk Field.
</P>
<P>
   Remember also that, while deserving now, Clemens never so much
as won All-Southwest Conference acclaim, a stinging rebuke that
irritates him to this day. Greg Swindell, who also wore No. 21, was
three times the UT pitcher Clemens was, but he has not been so
honored to this day. But then, Texas put Denton Cooley in its
Longhorn Hall of Honor more for replacing hearts than being the
heart and soul of the 1939-41 basketball teams.
</P>
<P>
   At North Carolina, Mack Brown said the Tar Heels have 15
``honored jerseys,'' as opposed to retired ones, for consensus
All-Americans, but running back Amos Lawrence doesn't fit in, even
though he and Dorsett are the only two backs to rush for 1,000
yards in four consecutive seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good thing is we have too many (potential honorees)
here,'' says Brown, now the Texas coach. ``But it's something I'd
like to see discussed.''
</P>
<P>
   Every school handles this delicate dilemma in its own way.
Alabama hasn't retired a single number despite 36 consensus
All-Americans. Neither has Notre Dame, despite having more than 30
players in the College Football Hall of Fame. As Irish football
spokesman John Heisler said Monday, ``There'd not be enough numbers
left to play a game. It's a difficult thing politically.''
</P>
<P>
   Illinois has retired Dick Butkus' No. 50 (he wore 51 for the
Bears) and Red Grange's No. 77. Ricky's wouldn't even be the first
No. 34 to be set aside nationally because Georgia has retired
Herschel Walker's, along with three other jerseys.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan has retired five numbers representing seven players.
Surely you recall the three Wistert brothers, ``Whitey,'' ``Ox''
and ``Moose'' _ all All-America linemen with All-American
nicknames. Even Gerald Ford's No. 48 was taken out of circulation.
He was a center on two national championship teams and a team
captain, but ``being president helps,'' Michigan's Jim Schneider
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Wolverines haven't retired his helmet because, of course, he
didn't wear one.
</P>
<P>
   Kirk Bohls writes writes for the Austin American-Statesman,
Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
