<HEADER>
A8654 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DREAM-FRIDGE26-COX     11-25 0975
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DREAM-FRIDGE26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pondering the dream refrigerator
 &HT;    (EDS: Embargoed for Nov. 26)
 &HT;    By Kitty Crider
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Oh, for the ultimate fridge today. A walk-in
cooler with limitless room to stash turkey and dressing, molds and
bowls of salads and vegetables, relish trays, pies of pecan,
pumpkin and sweet potato, all without having to rearrange three
shelves to make things fit.
</P>
<P>
   And it would not have to be a one-day wonder. Come summer such a
haven of refrigeration could be a secret hideout. Pull in a
La-Z-Boy, stock the shelves with beverages and books, shut the door
and chill out July and August's mind-frying heat.
</P>
<P>
   That would be so cool. But definite overkill.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, maybe I should go with a Traulsen, that commercial
refrigerator loved by chefs and food pros who even sneak it into
their homes despite the fact that it lacks door shelves and an ice
maker and doesn't meet energy codes for residences. It has great
space and refrigeration. But if I slip one into the neighborhood,
I'm going to feel really bad if I take out everyone's power during
the holidays.
</P>
<P>
   So maybe there's time to have a Sub-Zero delivered today before
noon. Basic appliances in upscale homes, Sub-Zero fridges are so
popular that the manufacturer can hardly make them fast enough,
even at prices more expensive than some new cars my husband and I
purchased in our early married days.
</P>
<P>
   With two compressors, one for the fridge and one for the
freezer, Sub-Zeros last forever. I opened a friend's the other day;
it has been humming happily for more than 20 years. That's more
than I can say for mine.
</P>
<P>
   But other friends are frustrated because large deli platters and
baking sheets won't fit on the Sub-Zero's trademark shallower
shelves. Probably wouldn't be very energy-efficient to leave the
door cracked to accommodate that oversize turkey platter, now would
it?
</P>
<P>
   Besides, such open-door actions would spoil the looks of these
fridges, known for their beauty. We're talking wood-paneled doors _
extra charge of course _ that cleverly conceal the unit. I can just
visualize my relatives and good friends rummaging through the
cabinets looking for the Dr Pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, if I go with this elegant paneled or trendy stainless
steel look, I'm going to have to give up the photo album on my
fridge. Sure, some might consider it a cluttered look, but I call
it a fridge with personality. No matter what mood I'm in, I always
smile as I approach the refrigerator door and look at the snapshot
of our sons cutting up, view the photo from a friend's wedding,
admire the new baby of a former baby sitter. My fridge is not just
an appliance to hold good food, but a reminder of good times, too.
</P>
<P>
   Gee, I thought my ultimate fridge search would be simple: a unit
that is at least 20 cubic feet but no wider than 36 inches. It must
keep my celery and lettuce crisp for more than 30 minutes. I want
spill-proof shelves, adjustable to accommodate big birds and tall
bottles of oils and condiments. Give me a deli/cheese drawer, big
produce bins, shelves on the door and some freezer space that does
not turn the ice cream to crystals. Is that asking too much?
</P>
<P>
   ``Have you checked out the new 25-cubic-foot side-by-side
fridges?'' asks a veteran home economist in the appliance industry.
They have pull-out freezer shelves, adjustable door bins that hold
gallons of milk or soda, humidity controls on the crispers, and
those optional ice-maker and water dispensers Is that ultimate
enough?
</P>
<P>
   If not, these fridges also have a quick freeze shelf in the
freezer, extra cold bins for meats and drinks, wine racks and
filtered water systems, all for under $2,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Get real!'' admonishes my nephew, the television sportscaster,
touting the finer points of a dorm fridge. It's big enough to hold
a jar of salsa, a six-pack, a leftover turkey leg and a piece of
pie. It can sit by your chair where you can open the door with one
hand and hold the remote with the other. It's even the right height
to serve as a TV stand.
</P>
<P>
   All in the eyes of the remote beholder. Refrigerator Buyer's
Guide Ranges from 1.7 cubic feet in a small dorm refrigerator to 24
cubic feet or more for a large kitchen model. About 20 cubic feet
is good for a family of four.
</P>
<P>
   Buying guide
</P>
<P>
   Brands
</P>
<P>
   Amana, Fridigaire, GE, Kenmore, Maytag, Whirlpool, Sub-Zero,
White-Westinghouse, Kelvinator, Gibson, Tappan, Hotpoint, RCA,
Magic Chef, Admiral, Jenn-Air, KitchenAid, Roper and more.
</P>
<P>
   Basic forms
</P>
<P>
   _ Side-by-side: More freezer space than other models. More of
the refrigerator is at eye level.
</P>
<P>
   _ Top-freezer: less costly than side-by-side, but with a smaller
freezer. More energy-efficient than side-by-side.
</P>
<P>
   _ Bottom-freezer: relatively uncommon now.
</P>
<P>
   Built-in refrigerators: Fit flush, or nearly flush, with kitchen
cabinets. Customized so that they blend in.
</P>
<P>
   Compact refrigerators: For dorm rooms, offices or family rooms.
Usually for snacks and drinks.
</P>
<P>
   Possible features
</P>
<P>
   _ Shelves with spill guard
</P>
<P>
   _ Adjustable door bins
</P>
<P>
   _ Temperature-controlled chiller _ keeps meat or fish a few
degrees cooler than the rest of the refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ice-maker and water dispenser _ mounted on the door in some
side-by-sides.
</P>
<P>
   _ Shelf snuggers _ keep bottles from moving around when you open
the door.
</P>
<P>
   _ Water filter _ improves taste of ice and water.
</P>
<P>
   Cost
</P>
<P>
   Begins at $70 for a small dorm refrigerator, goes to $6,000 and
up for large, luxury kitchen models. Most standard kitchen
refrigerators run from $500 to $2,000.
</P>
<P>
   Where to buy them
</P>
<P>
   Discount, appliance, department and specialty stores.
</P>
<P>
   Kitty Crider is the food editor for the Austin
American-Statesman.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
