</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DREAM-TV26-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Pondering the dream TV
</P>
<P>
   (EDS: Embargoed for Nov. 26)
</P>
<P>
   By Diane Holloway
</P>
<P>
   C. 1998 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Size counts. Anybody who thinks otherwise is
probably humming the national anthem of Monaco.
</P>
<P>
   Big is good, but huge isn't necessarily better _ or realistic _
when it comes to the ultimate home entertainment center.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on the size and configuration of your viewing area,
super-huge TV screens, like the appalling 100-inch,
front-projection home theaters that are lurking out there, look
grainy and distorted at relatively close range.
</P>
<P>
   So, with a belly full of turkey and a heart full of thanks, I'll
settle in front of my ``dream wall'' to gobble up a football game
or two and wind up the day with a sappy Frank Capra movie or a
blood-chilling Alfred Hitchcock thriller. That swell little
picture-in-a-picture feature allows me to keep track of the news on
CNN.
</P>
<P>
   The picture on my fantasy TV is clear as a bell, thanks to that
home satellite dish. Experts say big-screen TV sets, like my brand
new 53-inch Sony rear-projection model, aren't nearly as impressive
on cable or antennae. You've gotta do the dish for maximum visual
pleasure. But you've also gotta keep cable or buy an outside
antenna to keep the local stations.
</P>
<P>
   Most people with ultimate entertainment on their minds ignore
the built-in sound systems in big-screen TVs and install a
``surround sound'' system, like the one that shakes your drink cup
in a movie theater. This requires a pre-amplifier, an amplifier, a
sub-woofer and five. You can turn up the volume sky high and not
get a single scratch, pop or distortion. Your ears may bleed, but
it's a joyful bleeding.
</P>
<P>
   I've chosen this fantasy home entertainment center with a
modicum of restraint. My den is a modest size, so I've opted for
the 53-inch set rather than one of those monstrous 60-, 65- or
80-inch rear projection models or one of those wall-sized, 100-inch
front projection models. (I've also ignored those petite 36-inch
models. Fine for real life, but, hey, this is a fantasy.) Since the
sole purpose of our living room is to shelter the Christmas tree
every year, the den is the only place I'll put a TV _ except for
the tiny TV/VCR hidden in our bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   It's not just a matter of wall space. You've got to be able to
get far enough away from the screen that you're not looking at
lines and dots. A guide from the Consumer Electronics Manufacturing
Association says your viewing range for a TV larger than 46 inches
should be between 13 and 15 feet. Our den can accommodate
pleasurable viewing of a 53-incher without anyone going blind.
</P>
<P>
   With this fabulous (and fabulously large) picture, Troy Aikman
appears to be throwing the old pigskin right into my turkey-greased
hands. And I hear every awful crunch and crackle on the field. This
is not necessarily good, hearing bones break, so I might switch off
the surround sound and return to the TV sound for the duration of
football.
</P>
<P>
   Next up on the dream wall is movie time. Slip a video disc into
the shiny new DVD player and up comes the real reason people
mortgage their houses to buy big-screen TV sets. Watching a movie
on disc on the dream wall is almost as good as watching one in a
top-notch stadium seat theater. And this is where super digital
stereo surround sound can take your breath (and eyelashes) away.
</P>
<P>
   You may be wondering where I've put all this ultimate home
entertainment stuff, and the answer is this: in the ultimate home
entertainment center cabinet. Mine is wood, to match the other
furniture in the room, and it's remarkably tasteful. Some of these
things look like altars, which can make couch potatoes feel a tad
guilty.
</P>
<P>
   But this one has two columns of shelves on each side (to hold
sound equipment, VCR, DVD and other necessary accessories) with an
adjustable hole for the TV in the middle. It's adjustable so that I
can accommodate up to an 80-inch high-definition TV when the
digital age fully arrives. Of course, I'll also have to win the
lottery and trade up to a much larger house at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   Home Entertainment Center Buyer's Guide
</P>
<P>
   TV sets
</P>
<P>
   Size: 36- to 65-inch screens
</P>
<P>
   Brands: Sony, Panasonic, RCA, Hitachi, Mitsubishi, Pro-Scan,
Toshiba
</P>
<P>
   Features: digital-quality sound, picture-in-a-picture
</P>
<P>
   Cost: $900-$7,000
</P>
<P>
   Stores: discount electronics, specialty electronics, some
appliance, furniture stores and department stores
</P>
<P>
   Sound systems
</P>
<P>
   Brands: JBL, Sony, RCA, Hitachi, Toshiba
</P>
<P>
   Features: 5 speakers, pre-amps, amps, subwoofer
</P>
<P>
   Cost: $600-$5,000+
</P>
<P>
   Stores: discount electronics, specialty electronics, some
appliance, furniture and department stores
</P>
<P>
   DVD players
</P>
<P>
   Brands: same as TVs
</P>
<P>
   Features: play video and audio discs and some computer games
</P>
<P>
   Cost: $300-$1,000
</P>
<P>
   Stores: same as TVs
</P>
<P>
   Cabinets
</P>
<P>
   Brands: Great American Oak, Bush, custom designs
</P>
<P>
   Features: adjustable TV hole, two shelf columns to hold all
audio and video equipment, wood or metal.
</P>
<P>
   Cost: $400-$5,000+
</P>
<P>
   Stores: department, electronics and furniture stores
</P>
<P>
   Diane Holloway writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
