<HEADER>
A8657 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLA-FIELDHOCKEY26-COX     11-25 0466
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-FIELDHOCKEY26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Get ready, Florida: Here comes Field Hockey!
 &HT;    By Ron Hayes
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WELLINGTON, Fla. _ You know what field hockey is _ right?
</P>
<P>
   It's kind of like polo, but without the horse.
</P>
<P>
   A little like soccer, but they play it with sticks.
</P>
<P>
   A bit like football, but the ball is round.
</P>
<P>
   The sport, which has never been very popular outside the
Northeast, and largely limited to Ivy League schools, is about to
become very good for Palm Beach County.
</P>
<P>
   About 4,500 field hockey players and family members arrive today
for four days of games at Palm Beach Polo Club.
</P>
<P>
   Along with their passion for the little-known sport, they also
will bring about $2 million into the local economy, according to
Pam Gerig, executive director of the Palm Beach County Sports
Commission, which has lured the U.S. Field Hockey Association back
for another National Hockey Festival.
</P>
<P>
   The athletes will stay in 13 different hotels, eat Thanksgiving
dinner at eight local restaurants and rent 100 vehicles from local
agencies during their stay. And they'll be back next year, for
sure, and have an option for the 2000 games.
</P>
<P>
   This year's festival is a return visit for the association,
which held its 1996 games here after the sports commission hosted a
``familiarization day,'' driving representatives of various sports
associations to local venues.
</P>
<P>
   That first visit was sweetened by a $15,000 grant from the
commission, and another $20,000 this year and next, Gerig said. The
money comes from the county bed-tax.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never thought we could host field hockey because it's not
really known or played in South Florida,'' Gerig conceded, ``but
when we showed them the polo grounds, they said, `Wow!''
</P>
<P>
   Field hockey is played by two teams of 11 players each, with
each team scoring points by knocking the ball into the goal. It
requires a playing area 100 yards long by 60 yards wide. With 165
teams participating in the association's largest event ever,
festival organizers figured they'd need about 22 fields.
</P>
<P>
   Palm Beach Polo Club, with 14 polo fields 300-by-160 yards each,
has more than enough space, and sunny days in November, too.
</P>
<P>
   Now all they need is more local fans.
</P>
<P>
   The event will bring players from 30 states, Canada, Germany,
The Netherlands and the Cayman Islands. But none from Palm Beach
County.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this country it suffers from the same problems as soccer,''
says Howard Thomas, an association spokesman. ``It's not on TV, and
it's not a professional sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're working to change some of that, and we hope this
festival helps the exposure.''
</P>
<P>
   Ron Hayes writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
