<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-25 09:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8658 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LA-Z-BOY26-COX     11-25 0881
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LA-Z-BOY26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The recline of Western civilization
 &HT;    (EDS: Embargoed for Nov. 26)
 &HT;    By Patrick Beach
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ To have a La-Z-Boy recliner, preferably one of
those with the side pocket for magazines and the remote, is to have
a beach house in the middle of your living room _ to have, within
walking distance, a retreat. You don't sit in a La-Z-Boy _ that
most American piece of furniture _ so much as succumb to it. You
accept what the La-Z-Boy offers: peace, torpor, a chance to say I
am not available at this time. I was working, and now I am not.
Open a cold one, grab the remote and take your brain off-line for
routine maintenance.
</P>
<P>
   To sit in a La-Z-Boy (practice saying it with me, boys and girls
_ don't utter a rushing headlong ``lazyboy'' rather but ``Lay''
(pause) ``Zee'' (pause) ``Boy'' _ is to sit with your eyebrows,
elbows, navel. It is to sit with your essence.
</P>
<P>
   To sit in a La-Z-Boy is to recline, to be at an angle _ not
horizontal, because that would imply being sickly, sleepy, dead or
comatose. To be in a La-Z-Boy at an angle is a paradox of
relaxation: to be in a state of deep rest, to be sure, but also
catlike, ready to shoot out of the chair in an instant if, for
instance, a person needs to be forcibly shooed away from blocking
your view of the football game.
</P>
<P>
   To sit in a La-Z-Boy is to be perfectly average, middle America
incarnate, fat, happy, full of turkey and smack dab in the great
American mean. You are middle class. Not upper middle, not lower
middle. You are in the exact middle of the middle class in your
La-Z-Boy. You are so middle-of-the-road, if you were on Interstate
35, you'd get run over. You embrace this knowledge. Say it again,
slowly: Lay. Zee. Boy. Exhale slowly as you say that last word,
feeling the worry empty out of you through toes perched atop the
foot rest.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, you could easily spend more on a reclining chair. You could
spend more on a reclining chair than you probably spent on your
car, but who can relax in an expensive reclining chair? At what
point would you stop hearing the little voice saying, You spent
FOUR THOUSAND DOLLARS on this thing? Never, that's when. You'd sit
in your expensive chair waiting for your first heart attack, and
when you'd had it you'd have the privilege of worrying about how
much that was going to cost you.
</P>
<P>
   No. Instead you investigated La-Z-Boy (Lay. Zee. Boyyyyyyy.).
You discovered La-Z-Boy sold not just recliners, not just sleeper
sofas, not just modular units (the mind reels _ astronomical
possibilities) but entire sets of furniture. They sell a way of
life. A philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   You read about the Dreamtime Reclina-Rocker, described in
pornographic detail: ``The sleek, eye-catching detail of Dreamtime
is sure to capture the attention of the contemporary consumer.''
(That's me! The contemporary consumer!) ``The bold, radiused front
posts are padded and skirted. The overstuffed back area offers
unique lines that are positioned to offer the utmost comfort.
Dreamtime _ a bold, new direction in the contemporary reclining
chairs.''
</P>
<P>
   You considered the Avenger, $879 in top grain leather, easy to
clean up those salsa stains, yessir. Not quite as voluptuous and
accommodating as the Dreamtime, maybe, but then the Dreamtime is
sort of the Monica Lewinsky of La-Z-Boy reclining chairs. But
terribly manly, the Avenger. If only it had an afterburner.
</P>
<P>
   You read more about this all-American company. You read about
two cousins named Ed who started making chairs shortly before the
crash of '29, how they accepted payments of livestock, how people _
even in the height of the Depression, or perhaps more then than at
any other time _ needed the life the La-Z-Boy offered. How that
same company posted $1 billion in sales last year.
</P>
<P>
   And then you drifted off, the La-Z-Boy way, folded into a dream
of bold, radiused, padded and skirted front posts, dreaming of a
place where everything was as good and pure as the La-Z-Boy, where
all you had to do was run the remote control and all it took to get
a refreshment was barking, ``Marge! Beer me!'' The La-Z-Boy
recliner: better than life itself.
</P>
<P>
   LA-Z-BOY recliners buyer's guide
</P>
<P>
   Styles
</P>
<P>
   There is a wide variety, including:
</P>
<P>
   _ The familiar chaise-style recliner
</P>
<P>
   _ High-leg, wing-back loungers with cabriole or ball-and-claw
legs
</P>
<P>
   _ The ``Grand Snuggler,'' a large padded chaise recliner for big
and tall men
</P>
<P>
   _ The rocker recliner
</P>
<P>
   _ A recliner designed for small spaces, which can operate close
to walls and corners
</P>
<P>
   _ The massage recliner, with different speed, heat and intensity
levels
</P>
<P>
   Colors
</P>
<P>
   Include burgundy, green, brown, blue, beige, black, white,
green, rose Special features
</P>
<P>
   _ Available in some models: A 360-degree swivel base Power lift.
Touch a button and the chair changes its angle
</P>
<P>
   _ Built-in drink holders
</P>
<P>
   _ Storage space to stash remote controls
</P>
<P>
   _ Speakerphones, computer modem hookups
</P>
<P>
   Cost
</P>
<P>
   Ranges from $225 to $600 and up for a non-leather recliner; $500
to $1,350 and up for a leather recliner.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Beach is a staff writer for the Austin
American-Statesman, Austin, Texas
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
