<HEADER>
A8669 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EZZARD-COLUMN29-COX     11-25 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EZZARD-COLUMN29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Family lore connects holidays past
 &HT;    (For release Sunday, Nov. 29.)
 &HT;    By Martha Ezzard
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TIGER, Ga. _ ``Ma'' Clyde remembers holidays in Tiger when the
wind was so fierce that the rug on the living room floor rippled
along the cracks in the wood. My husband's 90-year-old aunt is my
favorite source of Rabun County farm lore. Clyde Arrendale
Pleasants, now Clyde English, knows what has changed and what
hasn't.
</P>
<P>
   I took her some cranberry relish a few days ago and lingered, as
always. Her white frame farmhouse, built in 1828, is just down the
road from our new home at the foot of Tiger Mountain. It has rifle
slots in the side of the staircase, for aiming guns at Indians. (If
I had to choose, I'd aim at developers clear-cutting mountainsides
before I'd be rid of the Cherokee. At least they were good stewards
of the land.)
</P>
<P>
   Old timers take back the moutains in late November when the last
reds and yellows fade from the sourwood, maple, hickory and wild
dogwood trees. When the seasonal lake-people leave, the natives get
out the water-ground meal for corn bread dressing and start the
home-made fruit cakes swimming in rum.
</P>
<P>
   Clyde says turkey wasn't always the main feature of mountain
Thanksgivings. Sometimes there was pork roast, dove or quail. Her
daughter recalls folks who considered fried squirrel a delicacy,
boiling it first over an open fire. We're lucky wild turkeys have
reappeared, Clyde says. In her day, hunting was unlimited and they
were scarce.
</P>
<P>
   As the firelight flickered over the hand-hewn beams, I wondered
if a city girl like me could ever qualify as a Rabun native. No
question about my husband, though. His ancestors on his mother's
side date to Thomas Arrendale, a hunter who got what became the
Arrendale farm in the 1820 land lottery. In estate recordings of
the time, it was valued at a dollar an acre _ a wonder to John and
me, having just bought acreage from his siblings in today's market.
</P>
<P>
   I love Clyde's memories of holidays past, but I didn't always
love the ``wimen folk'' roles of mountain culture. On visits to the
farm when I was younger, I detested a day of chopping and cooking
when a hike or a good book beckoned. Now, though, I relish holiday
times in the kitchen. I gloat over my first jars of grape jelly
tucked away from summer. The old Concord grape vineyard John's dad
planted three decades ago was bountiful and irresistible in August.
Now, with the leaves gone, its twisted locust posts are a stark
contrast to the new metal trellises supporting the wine grapes.
John and I love the symbolic vineyard link with the past. Our
decision a few years ago to leave Denver after 25 years and bring
our lives full circle to the South, where we both grew up, was
risky. Changing careers in our 50s was even riskier. Now we have no
regrets.
</P>
<P>
   Clyde looks out her bedroom window toward our house and talks
about changes the land's been through. First it was apple orchards,
wiped out in successive spring freezes. Then her father, John V.
Arrendale, tried celery and cauliflower, a sweet potato kiln,
making hickory ax handles and wood products. John V., as John's
granddad was known, was the county surveyor, too. Rabun County
history books credit him with starting Black Rock State Park and
with bringing blueberry farming to the county _ a tradition carried
on by John's dad, Col. W.T. Ezzard. The colonel had a successful
dairy business until he got called back into the army for the
Korean War.
</P>
<P>
   As John lays out rows of posts for another new vineyard, the red
clay of a Rabun farmer is surely in his veins. I hope our children
won't some day say to their children, ``Remember when Dad planted
those silly European wine grapes?'' I hope they talk instead about
the joy of growing something on the Ezzard farm.
</P>
<P>
   Martha Ezzard is a columnist for The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution. E-mail: mezzard(at)ajc.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
