<HEADER>
A8701 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-WELTY-1000&AMP;AD     11-25 1924
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-WELTY-1000&AMP;ADD-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EUDORA WELTY
</HEADLINE>
  Complete Novels 
 By Eudora Welty 
 1,009 pp. New York: The Library of America. $35 
 EUDORA WELTY 
 Stories, Essays, &AMP; Memoir 
 By Eudora Welty 
 Illustrated. 976 pp. New York: The Library of America. $35 
 EUDORA 
 A Writer's Life 
 By Ann Waldron 
 Illustrated. 398 pp. New York: Doubleday. $25.95
 ------ 
 WHERE THE VOICE CAME FROM 
 By JAMES OLNEY 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``It was the strangest experience,'' Eudora Welty told Anne
Tyler after reading back over her short stories in preparation for
their collected publication in 1980. ``It was like watching a
negative develop, slowly coming clear before your eyes. It was like
recovering a memory.
</P>
<P>
   With the appearance of the two Welty volumes in the Library of
America series -- comprising not only the short fiction but also a
handful of acute essays, the superb ``One Writer's Beginnings'' and
five books designated ``novels'' (``The Robber Bridegroom,''
``Delta Wedding,'' ``The Ponder Heart,'' ``Losing Battles'' and
``The Optimist's Daughter'') -- Welty's admirers have the
opportunity to watch with her as the body of her work gradually
emerges, indeed like a developing photographic image, a richly
varied yet single living entity, something always there, always
coming into being but wholly perceptible only now, when it can be
viewed through the lens of memory. I specify admirers (and who is
not one? her popularity no doubt accounts in part for Welty being
the first living author included in the Library of America) for, as
she describes the process, it requires a previous knowledge of the
work and a double doubling back. Memory is a first-stage recovery
of the past; recovering a memory is akin to remembering
remembering. Welty has always been prodigious in her remarks on
memory: ``Of course the greatest confluence of all is that which
makes up the individual human memory,'' she says in ``One Writer's
Beginnings.'' ``My own is the treasure most dearly regarded by me,
in my life and in my work as a writer. Here time, also, is subject
to confluence. The memory is a living thing -- it too is in
transit. But during its moment, all that is remembered joins, and
lives -- the old and the young, the past and the present, the
living and the dead.'' Joined and living, too, one might add, in
our reading are Welty's past achievement and our present
recollection, savoring, reconstruction and re-creation of it.
</P>
<P>
   What is at issue both for Welty and for the reader of ``Eudora
Welty: Complete Novels'' and ``Eudora Welty: Stories, Essays, &AMP;
Memoir,'' edited and annotated unobtrusively but meticulously by
Richard Ford and Michael Kreyling, is a memory of things written,
of things made, which locates the life of greatest interest firmly
and first and last in the writing. Focusing there, one shares
Welty's sense of wonder yet of inevitability at how it's all come
about: no one could have predicted it would be so, but in
retrospect it could not have been otherwise. Asked in 1989 how she
would describe the vision that has sustained and impelled her
throughout a career of more than 50 years, Welty responded that
such a vision ``lies only in the work. . . . It's what the work
shows, comprises altogether.'' What she desires, she continued, is
for ``the work to exist as the thing that answers every question
about its doing.''
</P>
<P>
   If the body of her work, in its parts and its entirety, contains
the story of its writing, then this renders a biography of the
``writer's life'' (in the phrase that supplies the subtitle to Ann
Waldron's biography, ``Eudora'') not only nugatory but an
impertinence. The word impertinence is intended in the double sense
of irrelevance and of rudeness (which one can find most tellingly
in Waldron's aggrieved tone at not being allowed every confidence
of Welty's private life and in her frantic search for explanations
of the fiction in what Waldron takes to be Welty's sexual
frustration and her despair at having had no dates -- no dates at
all! -- in high school).
</P>
<P>
   To ``explain'' the fiction, as Waldron does, as compensation or
sublimation, with unfounded speculation and reckless surmise as her
principal tools -- Welty seems to have been depressed at this time,
which was likely caused by (what else?) an unhappy love attachment,
and the depression (which Waldron takes for an established fact) is
the cause of such and such a scene in ``The Robber Bridegroom'' or
a character in ``June Recital'' -- consigns Welty's work to a
presumed starting point in the ``foul rag-and-bone shop of the
heart.'' It shackles her imagination to the detritus of a life when
the desire of that life has been to create a new world not on the
basis of day-to-day grievances but in the likeness of the visible
and audible phantasmagoria surrounding her and her readers.
Everything one needs to know biographically about Welty can be
gleaned from the Library of America chronology. Her autobiography
-- the story of a writer -- is written across the whole body of her
work.
</P>
<P>
   That story, as against the one retailed in Waldron's book, is of
a pervasive and inexplicable mystery at the heart of human
existence and relationships. It is also an account, by way of the
writing, of techniques for rendering that mystery a living presence
in fiction. The tale begins with the imaginative explosion of ``A
Curtain of Green,'' a collection of 17 stories that seem
individually like so many experiments in voice, perspective,
texture.
</P>
<P>
   The volume's tonal variety is astonishing: from the somber
``Death of a Traveling Salesman'' to the hallucinatory ``Flowers
for Marjorie,'' from the wonderment at the variety of human faces
of ``Clytie'' to the foreboding near-violence of the title piece,
from the jazzy ``Powerhouse'' to the satiric ``Petrified Man,''
from the wildly comic ``Why I Live at the P.O.'' to the dignified
``A Worn Path'' (the ``grave, persistent, meditative'' sound of old
Phoenix Jackson's cane tapping the frozen earth establishes the
tone at the outset).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-NYTBOOK-WELTY-2NDTAKE-NYTSF &QL; 
 &UR; UNDATED: the outset).) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In ``A Curtain of Green,'' with marvelous success, Welty tests
voice after voice, as if the lesson learned in one story were to be
put aside, perhaps for future use, while another lesson is worked
through. ``The source of the short story is usually lyrical,'' she
says in ``Writing and Analyzing a Story.'' But she immediately goes
on to assert that, however much the lyrical impetus, and therefore
the tone and mood, may change from story to story, each story
carries the author's ``signature because of the one impulse
characteristic of his own gift -- to praise, to love, to call up
into view.'' Welty seems to offer these impulses as separate, but I
should say that to call up into view, to praise, to love -- taken
in whatever order -- are ultimately a single desire driving her
work from the first published story (``Death of a Traveling
Salesman'') right through ``One Writer's Beginnings.''
</P>
<P>
   The short story is the medium in which Welty has always shown to
greatest advantage, and this is true both of the relatively brief
pieces of ``A Curtain of Green'' (1941) and of the more expansive,
slower-paced stories of ``The Wide Net and Other Stories'' (1943),
``The Golden Apples'' (1949) and ``The Bride of Innisfallen and
Other Stories'' (1955). When she moved on to the novel, as she was
urged -- against her instincts -- to do by publishers, Welty
recognized that she was taking on a form markedly different in its
demands and capabilities. Few enough writers have been brilliantly
successful at both modes, and though Welty's novels have much to
recommend them, the truth is that she never quite divested herself
of the ways of seeing and saying most appropriate to the writing of
short fiction. The novel can be and has been many things, but one
doubts it has ever been quite what we get in ``The Robber
Bridegroom'' (1942): a gallimaufry thrown together out of frontier
brags, Yeatsian folk fantasy and shape-changers, fairy-tale love
and adventure, the mock heroic and heroic mockery and high spirits,
blended with comic undercutting at every turn. There are a thousand
events in the book, but of plot hardly a hint. Much the same could
be said of plot in ``Delta Wedding'' (1946) and ``Losing Battles''
(1970) -- that there is not much more of it in those novels than in
``A Visit of Charity'' or ``Keela, the Outcast Indian Maiden'' or
``The Wide Net,'' wonderful stories all.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Optimist's Daughter'' (1972) shows a fairly conventional
plot, but this is unique in Welty and achieved at the cost of being
drawn in large measure from details of her biography. And then
there is ``The Ponder Heart'' (1954), really a short story spun out
to something between novella and novel length, a pure exercise in
voice, nothing more, but a virtuoso performance and great triumph
as such (and very funny). Welty opens ``One Writer's Beginnings''
with a chapter called ``Listening'' and concludes with ``Finding a
Voice''; ``The Ponder Heart'' could be a textbook illustration --
but full of life and humor -- of how to listen to Edna Earl's voice
and reproduce it on the page.
</P>
<P>
   Edna Earl's is but one of Welty's hundreds of voices, all
different but all issuing from the artistry of one listener. In
this regard they are like the faces Clytie studies in the story
that bears her name. There were not more than 150 people in Farr's
Ginn, but ``the number of faces seemed to Clytie almost infinite. .
. . When she began to look at people's actual countenances there
was no more familiarity in the world for her. The most profound,
the most moving sight in the whole world must be a face. Was it
possible to comprehend the eyes and the mouths of other people,
which concealed she knew not what, and secretly asked for still
another unknown thing?'' That Clytie's maker shares an abiding
fascination with the infinite variety of nature, human and other,
is clear on every page of her work.
</P>
<P>
   The need to capture the otherness and the sameness in a voice,
in a face, is what accounts for the proliferation of similes and
metaphors in Welty. Such figures of speech are a reaching out to
bring that which is not us, yet is also us, within the ambit of our
emotional capacities. They are a way of bringing home the world's
mysteries without depriving them of any jot of their strangeness.
The words mystery and mysterious echo like mantras in Welty's
fiction, essays and memoir, referring to the endless oddity of the
world and of relationship (``relationship is a pervading and
changing mystery''). When, in ``Place in Fiction,'' Welty declares:
``Life is strange. Stories hardly make it more so; with all they
are able to tell and surmise, they make it more believably, more
inevitably so,'' we are reminded that there is an archaic meaning
for mystery, which is craft or trade. There has been in our time no
more assiduous practitioner of fiction than Eudora Welty, and for
the mystery that pervades her work and is her artistry there can be
no explanation (a la Waldron), only gratitude.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   James Olney is co-editor of The Southern Review. His ``Memory &AMP;
Narrative: The Weave of Life Writing'' will be published in
January.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
