<DOCNO> NYT19981125.0048 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-25 10:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8703 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-FICTION-BRIEF     11-25 1505
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-FICTION-BRIEFS-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 BOOKS IN BRIEF: FICTION
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; TOWARD THE SUN
</P>
<P>
   By Kent Nelson.
</P>
<P>
   Breakaway, $20. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   When Kent Nelson writes about sports, that's really the last
thing on his mind. In this collection of stories, each pegged to a
particular sport, Nelson is writing about struggles that take place
not so much on courts, playing fields, ice rinks or ski trails as
in the mind. And he makes us recall that even team sports can be
lonely endeavors, with each participant competing against himself
as well as opponents -- and occasionally taking time out to clarify
just who and what that self is. This is a central concern in the
story called ``The Actress,'' when Andrea Sykes, a paralegal on a
ski vacation, is introduced by her mysterious host to fellow guests
as an actress. A similar exercise in reinvention takes place in ``A
False Encounter,'' in which a son, taught how to box by his father
(himself a collegiate pugilist), seeks to solve the mystery of why
his father committed suicide -- and, along the way, is able to
discover principles that will give his own life direction. These
stories are also about the obstacles inherent in relationships
between men and women. In ``Every Day a Promise,'' Nelson describes
the warm-up routine of a high jumper who is finding it difficult to
commit himself to a deeper relationship with the young single
mother he's been dating: ``He stayed apart from the others, checked
and rechecked his steps. He felt loose, as strong as he had ever
felt. But he knew he was in his own world, the fate of everyone who
tried to realize dreams.'' And these words by Renner, an unorthodox
college professor, to Solomon, the star quarterback who's been
having problems not only on the field but in class, sum up the
dominant theme that runs through all these stories: ``What we seek
is our true selves, uncorrupted by images, unmeasured by numbers.
We seek the invisible within us. That's what we've been trying to
get at.'' _ CHARLES SALZBERG
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MARY MCGREEVY
</P>
<P>
   By Walter Keady.
</P>
<P>
   MacMurry &AMP; Beck, $24. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   You have to love the title character of Walter Keady's second
novel, who suffuses the whole book with her graceful charm and
feisty humor. It is 1950 and Sister Mary Thomas' father has died;
after leaving the convent to settle his affairs, she decides not to
return -- and in the remote Irish village of Kildawree such an
abandonment of her vows creates a scandal. But that's not the half
of it: very soon, Mary becomes pregnant and refuses to reveal the
name of the man who is responsible. Of course, the nosier villagers
pay careful attention to Mary's most regular visitors, creating a
kind of paternal whodunit. Is the father an old pre-convent flame,
rakish Kevin Kelly? Or the solid schoolmaster, Tom Tarragh, newly
married to troublesome Kitty Malone? Shy Jack Banaghan is a
possibility, and then there's Mick Burke, off to England -- a sure
sign of trouble. Some parishioners are even suspicious of their
good and gentle priest, John Mulroe. Keady, who grew up on a farm
in the west of Ireland, clearly knows the territory. Both his plot
and his prose are as down-to-earth as the parish he creates. _
PETER BRICKLEBANK
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PURPLE DOTS
</P>
<P>
   By Jim Lehrer.
</P>
<P>
   Random House, $23.95. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Jim Lehrer's 11th novel, ``Purple Dots,'' is less a gripping
thriller than a high-spirited Washington Beltway romp, kept light
by insider gossip, very fine dinners and a good deal of picturesque
rural scenery. Whether this novel does for the West Virginia
panhandle what, say, Peter Mayle's equally frothy suspense novels
have done for Provence remains to be seen, but ``Purple Dots''
certainly provides comic relief in a turbulent political season. It
also probes deftly, if not too deeply, into such abiding issues of
governance as the corruption of idealists and the triumph of
hypocrisy. At the same time, Lehrer lets his wily heroes -- a band
of semi-retired CIA spooks scheming to outwit some shady
Congressional attempts to derail a friend's nomination as the
agency's new director -- have a very merry time. In fact, the old
goats dance rings around the self-important young lawyer who serves
as chief minority counsel of the Senate Intelligence Committee.
Part of the fun is wondering whether Lehrer, the veteran PBS
journalist, is telling tales out of school. Do wounded CIA agents
actually receive ``blue hearts''? Do the anecdotes about missions
gone horribly wrong lie somewhere near historical truth? Presumably
our spymasters do not manufacture a truth serum from fish oil, but
who knows? In the end, we learn that a flawed human being will be
confirmed in his post. We also learn how to behave on C-Span and
how to get unexpected political mileage out of a tuxedo. But the
title may be Lehrer's wittiest gibe -- suggesting that the supreme
perk of power in Washington is a purple dot that permits the owner
unlimited free parking. _ CHARLES FLOWERS
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CEREUS BLOOMS AT NIGHT
</P>
<P>
   By Shani Mootoo.
</P>
<P>
   Grove, $23. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Shani Mootoo's impressive first novel mixes elements of magic
realism and Gothic horror in a style that is by turns lyrical and
lurid. The town of Paradise, on the imaginary Caribbean island of
Lantanacamara, provides a lushly landscaped backdrop for the
troubled and finally tragic history of Mala Ramchandin and her
family. As a boy, Mala's impoverished father, Chandin, was
considered fortunate when he was adopted by a white Christian
missionary, Mr. Thoroughly. It becomes apparent that his luck is
also his misfortune when Mr. Thoroughly rejects him as a suitor for
his daughter, Lavinia, leading Chandin to the bitter realization
that he is valued only for his usefulness in converting other
islanders. In reaction, Chandin impetuously marries Lavinia's best
friend, Sarah, an islander who feels as displaced as Chandin by her
education at the missionary school. The marriage results in two
daughters, Mala and Asha, and sparks an explosive chain of events,
ranging from adultery and incest to madness and murder. Mala's sad
tale is gradually revealed to Tyler, the only male nurse in the
Paradise poorhouse and the sole employee willing to minister to a
patient the others fear as a violent old loon. Their kinship is
based on the shared knowledge of what it means to live as someone
stigmatized for being different: Tyler by virtue of his sexual
orientation and his penchant for cross-dressing, and Mala as a
result of her history of abandonment, abuse and madness.
Ultimately, these two outcasts are shown to be truer to themselves
-- and more accepting of nature's seeming misfits -- than
conformists who, in their eagerness to appear normal, deny the
individual characteristics that define each of us as human. Mootoo,
who grew up in Trinidad and now lives in Canada and New York City,
has an impeccable ear and gives Tyler, the novel's narrator, a
mellifluous voice. At times her writing tends to be overly
elaborate, and the plot takes a few too many twists and turns. But
the plea for tolerance that lies at the heart of this novel is both
authentic and powerful. _ DIANE COLE
</P>
<P>
   &UR; RUBY
</P>
<P>
   By Ann Hood
</P>
<P>
   Picador USA, $22 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Over the course of a few giddy months, Olivia Bertolucci, a
stylish 37-year-old milliner living in Manhattan's East Village,
falls in love with and marries a charming industrial designer,
David Henderson. ``A person doesn't have a right to so much
happiness,'' Olivia tells herself one day while they're talking
about buying a beachfront vacation cottage in Rhode Island.
Naturally, soon after they take up residence, David goes out
jogging and is killed by a reckless driver. At first, ``Ruby''
resembles one of those stories in which a tragedy-beset heroine is
portrayed as bravely picking up the pieces. But Ann Hood's sly,
incisive novel soon breaks free from this familiar ground, deftly
exploring the strange rhythms of mourning, the unpredictable and
unavoidable demands of sorrow. Months after David's funeral, a
grief-numbed Olivia returns to the beach house, intending to tidy
the place up before selling it -- only to discover that a pregnant
teen-age runaway has taken up residence. Clever and voluble, Ruby
quickly explains that she has been shunned both by her mother and
stepfather and by the baby's frat-boy father. Olivia formulates a
plan that feels to her like fate: She will take Ruby in, care for
her and pay her medical bills -- if Ruby will let Olivia adopt the
baby. While lies, betrayals and manipulations give the plot its
undeniable page-turning pull, Hood's caustic wit, brightly detailed
prose and thoughtful delineations of two women struggling with
private, powerful regrets supply ``Ruby'' with rich and surprising
emotional depths. _ MEGAN HARLAN
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
