<DOCNO> NYT19981125.0052 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-25 10:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8707 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-CRIME-NYTSF     11-25 1071
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-CRIME-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRIME
</HEADLINE>
 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)   By MARILYN STASIO 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Martha Grimes doesn't write them fast enough for me, so you'll
excuse me while I savor for a minute the quirky charms of her new
Richard Jury mystery, THE STARGAZEY (Holt, $25). There's the
authentic English pub, of course, that gives the novel its title
and a hint of its mood. This time, it's a spiffy neighborhood
hangout in Fulham, a once seedy area newly gentrified by ``the
chattering classes'' where Jury first catches sight of an elegant
blond woman in a sable coat who disappears (perhaps to be murdered)
on the grounds of Fulham Palace. Then there are the wondrously
eccentric characters, including one grand old dame (the former
owner of the sable coat) and a supremely self-centered little girl
named Pansy. Finally, there are all the witty particulars that
surface at the oddest times. ``Most people don't notice little
things like this,'' a barmaid says to Jury about a curious postcard
of a fish pie. ``You miss a lot in life if you don't notice little
things.''
</P>
<P>
   Given all this, you want a plot, too? This one is strange beyond
belief, strained in the telling (Assassins! Aristocrats!
Doppelgangers! Nonsense!) and garbled in its conclusion. But if the
big picture is absurd, the details are divine.
</P>
<P>
   Haunted since childhood by his eyewitness memory of his sister's
murder, Paul Graves has the kind of nightmares that would send most
of us screaming to a shrink. But instead of exorcising his demons,
the protagonist of Thomas H. Cook's eerie suspense story
INSTRUMENTS OF NIGHT (Bantam, $23.95) endlessly recycles the trauma
in the bleak stories he writes about a police detective and a
sadistic master criminal who battle it out in turn-of-the-century
New York. Although his novels earn Graves a living, they don't do
much for his mental health, and after 15 books, the author is no
better off than his hero, whose ``view of life had turned so
intensely grim that his character seemed poised on the brink of an
absolute despair.'' Salvation (or is it damnation?) presents itself
when the wealthy patron of a writers' colony in New York's Hudson
Valley asks Graves to train his morbid imagination on the
50-year-old mystery of her best friend's murder. He doesn't have to
solve the case, she tells him -- just dream up something credible
enough to soften the pain and banish the ghosts.
</P>
<P>
   Cook does a lot better than that in this psychological horror
story. With his fondness for a twisted narrative line and his
appreciation of the nuances of terror, he devises a plot that
harnesses Graves's gloomy fantasies to a greater evil that should
shock him out of his obsessive brooding -- or shove him off his
mental cliff. Although it's easy to miss the very real clues that
Cook drops so artfully into the story, there's no ignoring his
savage imagery, or escaping the airless chambers of his disturbing
imagination.
</P>
<P>
   You're not a real New Yorker if you don't want to kill somebody,
sometime: the umpire who blows a call; the crazy guy at the deli;
your swine of a husband; even the mayor when he's on some dumb
rant. Mike McAlary, who regularly sounds off in a column for The
Daily News, gives raucous voice to that invigorating rage in his
first novel, SORE LOSER (Morrow, $24), which he aims and points
like a loaded gun at some of our favorite public targets.
</P>
<P>
   A ladylike tennis pro named Ginny Glade gets to go first, when
she takes a tire iron to the umpire whose lousy line call costs her
a shot at being seeded at the United States Open. ``Murder was
empowering,'' Ginny discovers. ``Murder, like winning, was
thrilling stuff.'' And when that thrill wears off, there's more
excitement to be had running around with Mickey Donovan, an
attractive, if preposterously idealized, supercop who travels in
the highest (and lowest) circles of power -- although always within
bellowing range of the egomaniacal mayor, a hilarious caricature of
Rudy Giuliani in all his volatile glory.
</P>
<P>
   In manic overdrive, the hyperkinetic style eventually sends the
story swerving off into total fantasy. But even then, McAlary is
fun to read. The cops are cute, everybody is a screamer and the
energy is pure New York.
</P>
<P>
   Crime marches on, even in wartime, and in the series of
melancholy police procedurals that J. Robert Janes sets in occupied
France, it falls to Inspector Jean-Louis St.-Cyr of the Surete
Nationale and Hermann Kohler, his softhearted Gestapo colleague, to
protect ordinary citizens from themselves. But, ``as always these
days,'' Janes reminds us in MANNEQUIN (Soho, $22), ``crime had to
be viewed through the occupation's prism, warped though that was.''
In the disjointed Parisian society of 1942, every local crime --
from a daring robbery of the Credit Lyonnais bank to the grisly
murders of a dozen or more would-be fashion models -- seems rooted
in the deeper moral chaos of these convulsive times. For all their
efforts to focus the search for a missing girl from St.-Cyr's
neighborhood, the detectives keep turning up sad or sinister
associations between the army of occupation and a conquered people
desperate to survive. Janes devises a shocking solution to the
brutal crimes at hand, but his larger point about the complexities
of human guilt isn't so easy to close the book on.
</P>
<P>
   Life in Toronto in 1895 was no glide across the ice, according
to Maureen Jennings in her horridly graphic period mystery UNDER
THE DRAGON'S TAIL (Thomas Dunne/St. Martin's, $21.95). Even the
high and mighty were plagued by syphilis, birth defects and
loathsome skin conditions, and the lower classes were also
malnourished and crawling with worms, while any woman, rich or
poor, who needed an abortion or had to give up a child for adoption
was at the mercy of her midwife. When Dolly Merishaw, an unsavory
specimen of the profession, is smothered on her own hearth, the
police dispatch William Murdoch to determine which of Dolly's
shameful deeds drove one of her clients to murder. Despite certain
plot transparencies, the grim story is told in forthright detail
and put in a social context that elicits real sympathy for
characters bound by class and biology.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
