<HEADER>
A8713 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-CAPITALISM-NY     11-25 1156
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-CAPITALISM-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 THE CRISIS OF GLOBAL CAPITALISM
<TEXT>
<P>
   Open Society Endangered.
</P>
<P>
   By George Soros.
</P>
<P>
   245 pp. New York: Public Affairs. $26.
 &UR; ------- &QL; 
 &UR; BE AFRAID! &QL; 
 &UR; By FLOYD NORRIS &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The world's economy has seldom seemed as imperiled -- at least
in the past half-century -- as it did this summer in the aftermath
of Russia's default on its debt. ``The Crisis of Global
Capitalism'' was rushed into print by one of the best money
managers, and most generous philanthropists, to come along this
half-century. Its financial analysis is brilliant and persuasive,
its remedies less so. And its extraordinary pessimism may prove to
be overdone.
</P>
<P>
   George Soros has been known on Wall Street for decades, but it
was not until 1992 that he became an international celebrity. That
was when the hedge funds he managed bet huge amounts that Britain
would not be able to maintain the value of the pound against other
European currencies. His funds made billions, and he felt a little
guilty. ``The Bank of England was on the other side of my
transactions and I was taking money out of the pockets of British
taxpayers,'' he writes. He doesn't think that should have deterred
him -- somebody else would have made the money anyway, he figures
-- but it does provide an argument for better international
regulation of markets.
</P>
<P>
   Soros thinks that argument is more valid today than ever. He
traces the way Thailand's financial collapse in 1997 led to
problems in other Asian countries, and then to Russia, and finally
to Latin America. It is a process he thinks will continue, arguing
that we are in the early stages of a global bear market.
``Eventually the markets should go much lower, leading to a global
recession,'' he forecasts. ``The disintegration of the global
capitalist system will prevent a recovery, turning the recession
into a depression.''
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of his argument are two beliefs: First, that the
financial markets have grown so large and powerful that they can
destroy countries, and second, that those same markets have now
become so frightened that they will withdraw capital from most
countries in the world.
</P>
<P>
   It is certainly true that some players in the markets, Soros
among them, have amassed huge amounts of money for investment, and
that those resources can, at times, overwhelm the forces against
them. That is particularly true when countries are seeking to
defend overvalued currencies. Soros's funds were among the first
speculators to bet against Asian currencies last year, although he
denies that he caused the meltdown of those currencies.
</P>
<P>
   One reason those currencies grew to be overvalued was a huge,
and in retrospect irrational, flood of capital into emerging Asian
economies. Asia was seen as a region of extraordinary growth, and,
as Soros notes, experiences like the Mexican bailout had dulled
investor fears about risk. Indeed, the Asian bailouts of 1997
tended to do a better job of protecting international investors
than they did of aiding the economies involved.
</P>
<P>
   It was in that atmosphere that the Russian economic collapse
came as such a shock. The Russian Government was in desperate shape
last spring, and everyone knew it. It was running a huge budget
deficit, not because it was spending so much money but because so
little was coming in. Few paid taxes, and some of the taxes that
were paid stayed with regional authorities. The Government was
determined to protect the international value of the ruble, since
stabilizing it had brought down inflation and was one of the few
economic successes to which the Government could point. So it was
unwilling simply to print rubles, and had to borrow money to pay
its bills.
</P>
<P>
   But who would lend money to such a basket case of a government?
Russians who owned rubles were reluctant to do so, demanding
interest rates of more than 50 percent. Even at those rates, the
Government could not borrow enough rubles. So it borrowed dollars
instead. In June, Goldman Sachs managed to sell $1.25 billion of
bonds denominated in dollars. Russia was to pay more than 12
percent interest, or more than double what the United States
Treasury was then paying, and many investors thought they had a
sure thing. After all, the Western world would surely not let
Russia, with all those nuclear weapons, default.
</P>
<P>
   But it did. Soros was a player in that crisis, talking to
Russian and American officials and, when the Aug. 17 collapse was
near, proposing his own solution, which would have involved further
international aid and a fairly modest devaluation of the ruble. The
major Western nations were unwilling, and international investors
lost billions. Soros's funds were among the losers.
</P>
<P>
   That collapse shocked international investors, and in the
aftermath many of them fled from risky investments. It was not only
doubtful foreign countries that were affected, but also European
and American companies whose credit was less than top notch. Soros
is furious that more was not done to salvage Russia. He thinks the
continued decline of financial markets is inevitable, albeit with a
rally or two along the way, and is harshly critical of the lack of
effective international action to ease the financial problems.
</P>
<P>
   Since this book went to press, however, there have been efforts
to arrange coordinated international action to fight financial
decay, and Congress has at long last provided the $18 billion in
American money needed to expand the International Monetary Fund.
Markets have rebounded, reflecting optimism that the fixes will
work.
</P>
<P>
   Soros wants more international regulation of markets. He would
love to see an international central bank, or at least an agency to
guarantee some international loans. It is unfair to dismiss those
ideas, as some have, as being ill-disguised plans to bail out
investors like Soros, since he wants to force investors to take
hits when things go wrong. But he is not persuasive in arguing that
such changes could be made to work.
</P>
<P>
   This book is sometimes hard sledding, particularly in the first
section, where Soros explains his theory of reflexivity, which
essentially argues that reality affects perceptions and in turn is
affected by those perceptions. It is an idea that seems obvious,
and readers may be tempted to skip over much of that. But when
Soros gets down to financial market business, and explains how we
got to where we are now, he does an excellent job. ``The Crisis of
Global Capitalism'' will be worth reading even if its dire
forecasts prove to be wrong.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Floyd Norris writes editorials for The Times. He is a former
financial columnist for the paper.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
