<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981125.0066 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-25 10:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8753 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LIVINGWITHDEATH26-COX     11-25 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIVINGWITHDEATH26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: I still spend holidays in kitchen with Mom
 &HT;    By Richard L. Eldredge
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thanksgiving morning 1997. As the Barney balloon terrorized
bundled-up small fry in Manhattan during the Macy's parade on
television, my father and I were having an equally ... animated
chat on the phone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know she wrote it down, Pop, it's in her cookbook,'' I said
impatiently as my father shifted papers on the other end. ``I'm not
seeing it in any of the pockets of her recipe book,'' he said. Then
I remembered my mother's filing system. ``You know all those loose
recipes tossed inside the front cover of the church cookbook? Check
there.'' Mission accomplished.
</P>
<P>
   The ``mission,'' in particular, was to locate and to accurately
re-create my mother's famed Thanksgiving coleslaw dressing recipe
originated by my great-grandmother. It had become the final
culinary hurdle to clear before the end of the first-year grieving
cycle for our family. Or as I began referring to it: the coleslaw
coup de grace.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after delivering my mother's eulogy in early December
1996 (in which I noted her 25-plus years spent teaching Sunday
school to 3- and 4-year-olds, her genetic predisposition toward
marriage and motherhood and her impressive, seemingly effortless
repertoire of recipes for special _ and ordinary _ occasions), I
felt a nagging need to continue her work. Preserving family rituals
had always been a priority: The week before her death, she put out
a lavish Thanksgiving spread for 14.
</P>
<P>
   And since I haven't acquired her patience for skillfully
separating Play-Doh from the knees of Toughskins while spinning
yarns detailing Noah's savvy flood insurance provisions, I chose to
throw down the gauntlet and pick up her whisk.
</P>
<P>
   I'd logged a lot of holiday hours in the kitchen with Mom over
the years and had already achieved ``two spoons up!'' approval on
her Christmas cookie recipes, her baked macaroni and cheese dish
(my sister's favorite food, not counting mayonnaise) and her potato
salad recipe (the secret weapon, published here for the first time
_ a splash of apple cider vinegar!).
</P>
<P>
   During the year after her death, as I prepared her dishes for
family gatherings, conversations with my mother went something like
this: ``Ma, it's 2 a.m. What do you mean sift all ingredients and
mix in the four eggs one at a time?!''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, as the first anniversary of her passing loomed, I
invited family and friends to a remembrance dinner. It featured,
among other things, Mom's Missouri casserole and Jewish apple cakes
(one particular fan of this recipe would anxiously wait every year,
checkbook in hand, for Mom to arrive at the church bazaar with an
armload of these).
</P>
<P>
   Dad had boxed up my mother's entire recipe drawer and asked me
to organize it. It was a year before I was ready.
</P>
<P>
   Rooting through the contents was like an archaeological dig
through 40 years of American life. There's an incredible comfort in
seeing index card after food-splotched index card of my mother's
neat penmanship in blue ballpoint ink. (Family favorites from her
many cookbooks also carry remnants of flour, sugar and chocolate.)
</P>
<P>
   A particular treasure is her 1956 edition of ``Betty Crocker's
Revised and Enlarged Picture Cook Book,'' a wedding gift from my
grandmother. One of my favorite ``helpful hints'' features an
aproned wife serving a tray of appetizers and drinks to a suited
husband, lounging in an easy chair. The caption: ``The clever wife
has a simple appetizing cocktail (cold in summer, hot in winter)
ready for her weary husband when he comes home at night.'' Not
surprisingly, there are no splotches of food on that page.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Reader's Digest Guide to Healthful Eating'' (published
sometime in the 1970s), which contained a recipe for Swedish
meatballs with sour cream sauce, was equally entertaining. I was
even able to locate an age-old molasses cookie recipe presumed lost
at sea after a family flood.
</P>
<P>
   This year, as I prepare holiday favorites a la Mom, I'm sure my
thoughts will drift back to last Christmas, when I decided to
continue my mother's culinary legacy into the foreseeable future.
That day, it meant bringing the requested pineapple cheesecake to
dinner at my cousin's home.
</P>
<P>
   And just for a moment, as I lingered with my mug of coffee,
staring into the nearly empty cheesecake dish after dessert, I
could have sworn I felt my mother sitting across the room in her
favorite chair.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
