<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-25 10:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8757 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DRJOY-COLUMN-NYTSF     11-25 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRJOY-COLUMN-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WISH YOUR DAUGHTER A BON VOYAGE
</HEADLINE>
  By DR. JOY BROWNE 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   QUESTION: My daughter is a college freshman and wants to go to
Europe this summer. She's saved her own money, but it's so
dangerous these days. Is there any way to convince her terrorists
are dangerous, not romantic? _ Portland, Ore.
</P>
<P>
   DR. JOY: My dear, I doubt very much that your daughter thinks
terrorists are romantic. More likely she's having a difficult time
dealing with your fears. Isn't there a tiny part of you that is
proud of her gumption, independence and sense of adventure? How
'bout setting up a collect-call schedule _ and make it weekly, not
daily _ or ask her to write every week.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds like you've got a cool, self-sufficient, responsible,
independent kid here. You've done a good job. Stock her up on lots
of wash-and-wear undies, wish her a lovely summer and a bon voyage,
dry her tears and swallow your fears. Mom, you're growing up.
</P>
<P>
   QUESTION: I dated a 33-year-old woman for 10 months before she
moved in with me two months ago. I'm 44 and neither of us has been
married before. She agreed to pay $350 a month as her share of the
rent, but I haven't seen any of it. And when we go out, it's always
me who pays for everything. She never offered to pay for anything
when we were dating either. I'm getting the idea she doesn't want
to part with her money. What do I say to her? _ Los Angeles
</P>
<P>
   DR. JOY: Try saying, ``How about some money for the rent?'' Your
job is not to collect what you think she owes you, but to be honest
in communicating your understanding of your ``contract'' with each
other. Maybe she thought you were kidding about the money, maybe
she's a little short this month, or testing you or working on some
sort of old-fashioned idea of how men and women SHOULD be. Or maybe
she is signaling she isn't sure she wants to be in this
relationship.
</P>
<P>
   QUESTION: At the college I attend, I had a boyfriend for a year
and a best friend for three years. My friend knew I was still
suffering six months after the breakup, but then she had casual sex
with him, not once but twice in one week.
</P>
<P>
   I suspected something because she was avoiding me that week, but
then she came right out and told me. She said she wanted to be
honest. She doesn't care about him; he doesn't care about her. But
they both hurt me.
</P>
<P>
   It's a small campus, so I can't avoid her. She swears she's
still my friend, but even if I can forgive her, how can I ever
trust her again? _ Buffalo, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   DR. JOY: In a small college if everyone is expected not to date
people their friends have dated, you're all going to be sitting at
home a lot on Saturday night. Her mistake was not in having casual
sex with him _ although I'm not a fan of casual sex _ but in
telling you about it. That's really the question: Why did she tell
you? She's going to say she's just being honest, but don't buy it.
She knew that it wasn't a nice thing to do or she wouldn't have
confessed it to you. At this moment I'd back off the friendship a
bit, but I'd rethink your rules on your friends dating your
ex-boyfriends or you're going to be more miserable than absolutely
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   QUESTION: I'm seeing a woman who is divorced with a 9-year-old
son who is learning-disabled. I adore this woman, and am strongly
considering proposing to her. I get on very well with her boy, but
I'm a bit concerned about my ability to cope with his problem over
the long term. What would you do in this situation?
</P>
<P>
   DR. JOY: All God's children got problems. The real challenge
won't be his learning disability but his adolescence! If you decide
to marry his mother, you don't have to be this boy's dad. As a
potential stepparent, your role is to be a good friend and a good
host _ a relatively pleasurable combination of roles.
</P>
<P>
   -0-
</P>
<P>
   Questions may be sent to Dr. Joy Browne, c/o The New York Times
Syndication Sales Corp., 122 E. 42nd St., New York, NY 10168, or to
drjoy &LR; nytsyn.com. Questions of general interest will be answered in
this weekly column. Dr. Joy regrets that unpublished letters cannot
be answered individually.
</P>
<P>
   Copyright 1998 by Dr. Joy Browne Distributed by New York Times
Special Features
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
