 EDITORS: Dr. Joy Browne, a licensed psychologist, has joined the
New York Times Syndicate to give your readers the warm, friendly _
and professional _ advice that she supplies to 9 million listeners
in the United States and Canada through the WOR Radio Network and
soon will be sharing on CBS television.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Her weekly Q&AMP;A column, ``Dr.Joy,'' will answer readers'
questions about personal relationships that are key in having happy
and productive lives.
</P>
<P>
   For a sample of Dr. Joy's column, see BC-DRJOY-COLUMN-NYTSF, on
the wire now under catetory ``l.''
</P>
<P>
   A New Orleans lady with a New York edge, Dr. Joy specializes in
straightforward professional advice mixed with common sense and a
sense of humor. She earned her doctorate in psychology from
Northeastern University, graduating Phi Beta Phi. This year she
received the President's Award from the American Psychological
Association for service to the profession.
</P>
<P>
   Regularly short-listed as one of the top talk show hosts in
America, she is also the author of six books including ``Dating for
Dummies'' (IDG, 1998) and the just-released ``The Nine Fantasies
That Will Ruin Your Life and the Eight Realities That Will Save
You'' (Crown).
</P>
<P>
   For information on subscribing to Dr. Joy, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
