<TEXT>
<P>
   EDITORS, attention features, technology page editors:
</P>
<P>
   Here is a list of selected computer-related stories from the
past week from  &UR; The N.Y. Times News Service &LR;  and its partners.
</P>
<P>
   These stories are being repeated with a distinguishing ``CPT''
in the slugline and an ``a'' general news category code.
</P>
<P>
   Similar stories planned for Thursday's New York Times will be
listed on  &UR; BC-CIRCUITS-BUDGET-NYT &LR; , moving later this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   LIBRARY-NET-FILTER-NYT (Undated) _ A ruling by a federal judge
Monday that barred public libraries in Loudoun County from limiting
how patrons use the Internet is binding only in southern Virginia,
but it seemed sure to have national implications as librarians
across the country began to review their own Internet policies in
the wake of the decision in the closely watched case. By Amy
Harmon.
</P>
<P>
   AOL-E-COMMERCE-NYT (Undated) _ America Online built itself into
the most potent force in cyberspace largely by appealing to
families with chatty teen-agers who want to flirt online and adults
looking for an easy way to send electronic mail while checking the
weather and sports scores. Now, the company has to get serious if
it is to win the hearts and minds of corporate executives in
pin-stripe suits. By Saul Haskell.
</P>
<P>
   TECHTOOLS-COX (Undated) _ The new editions of electronic
encyclopedias range from excellence to garbage.
</P>
<P>
   CYBERSCENE-COX (Atlanta) _ With the help of a map, most of us
can get very confused. But there are times when a map actually
helps. You'll find maps on the Web that will plot your route across
town or across the country. But the many sites on the Net that
offer maps offer a lot more than that. By Bill Husted.
</P>
<P>
   TECHNOBUDDY-COX (Atlanta) _ Getting back to the good old days of
building things as a kid. By Bill Husted.
</P>
<P>
   TECH-MEDIA-COX (Atlanta) _ A preview of the holiday season's
offerings on CD-ROM, and online outlets.
</P>
<P>
   NETWATCH-COX (Undated) _ Discussing Internet communities.
</P>
<P>
   TECH-REPORT-COX (Atlanta) _ So far, most computer games have
been devoted to digitizing what we do, paying taxes, playing
football, flying planes and hunting deer. Now, companies are coming
out with games for your PC that make fun of what we do.
</P>
<P>
   KTEL-INVESTOR-INTEREST-NYT (Undated ) _ Even for
Internet-related stocks, the tale of K-Tel is an extreme one. Until
April, K-Tel was an obscure company selling music compilations like
``Heart Throbs of the '70s.'' But when the company announced that
month that it would open an Internet record store, its shares
jumped to nearly $40 from about $4, adjusted for a subsequent
split. By Andrew Pollack.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-COLUMN-HNS (Las Vegas) _ The hot new product at the
Comdex computer trade show is ``home networking,'' allowing a
family with multiple computers to link them. Officials are calling
home networking the next big trend in personal computing. By Dwight
Silverman.
</P>
<P>
   AOL-NETSCAPE-CLASH-NYT (Undated) _ When Marc Andreessen and his
fellow whiz kids from the University of Illinois arrived in Silicon
Valley in 1994 to found Netscape Communications Corp., the brash
new darling of the digerati was the antithesis of America Online,
which was widely perceived as a shelter for technical ``newbies''
unprepared for the brave new world of the Net. That the two are now
on the brink of merging is a measure of how much the divide between
Internet sophisticates and mere computer-using mortals has
narrowed. By Amy Harmon.
</P>
<P>
   AOL-BROWSERWAR-COX (Atlanta) _ The proposed America
Online/Netscape deal has the potential to permanently change the
face of the Internet industry and create a company uniquely suited
to compete against Microsoft. By Frances Katz.
</P>
<P>
   AOL-HUSTED-COX (Atlanta) _ America Online was way too simple for
me, right from the start. If you're a longtime reader of my column,
maybe you remember my predicting the demise of AOL about four years
ago. Predicting the future has always been easy for me because I'm
almost never right. By Bill Husted.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTINGQ&AMP;A-SFCHRON (Undated) _ A Low-Tech Use for Free CDs. By
David Einstein.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTERS-BOMBAY-COLUMN-TEX (Undated) _ Talk to me, baby, with a
microphone.
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE-COUNTRY-NYT (Cambridge) _ Last week, 100 youngsters from
10 to 16 years old from around the world attended a global forum at
the Media Laboratory at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
The forum, called the Junior Summit, is to the quaint old Mock
United Nations what a personal computer is to an abacus. Connected
online for months before they arrived for the summit, equipped with
pagers with e-mail functions and Power Point presentation skills,
the participants in the summit did not jabber about treaties and
points of order. They simply plotted to change the world, using
technology.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-BRIEFS-NYT (Undated) _ Computer notes and news.
</P>
<P>
   OOD-CYBERSPICE-COX (Undated) _ Got turkey trauma? Help's just a
click away. By Betty Parham.
</P>
<P>
   WEB-HATE-2 TAKES-BOS (Undated) _ The battle over civil rights
has spread from the political arena to the new frontiers of
cyberspace. As it rages, it is spinning off perplexing and
intriguing questions about freedom of speech. By Patti Hartigan.
</P>
</TEXT>
