<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Wednesday, Nov. 25, 1998      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Thursday. If you have questions, call Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   HOLIDAY-SHARING (Troy, N.Y.) _ On Thursday, Carl and Kath
Siebels and two graduate student from India will spend their second
Thanksgiving together. Itty Matthew and Anurag Jain have quickly
absorbed the uniquely American holiday. The straightforward
concepts, of spending time with family, and of thankfulness, are
not lost on either. By MICHAEL LOPEZ.
</P>
<P>
   IMMIGRANT-FEAST (San Francisco) _ The first day of school is
hard enough for anybody, but Kenneth Mo, 8, had to deal with his
very first pumpkin pie, too. Kenneth and some 100 other immigrant
students at the Chinese Education Center in San Francisco's
Chinatown partook of an American rite of passage Tuesday _ their
first Thanksgiving feast. By ANNIE NAKAO.
</P>
<P>
   HOLIDAY-DIET (Undated) _ It's easier to put the weight on than
take it off during the busy holiday season. But food experts agree
that now is the wrong time to start a diet. Instead, they suggest
trying to keep ahead of those extra pounds with some healthy tips _
exercise and moderation _ that work year-round. By SYLVIA WOOD.
</P>
<P>
   WILD-TURKEYS (San Francisco) _ While the carcasses of their
dimwitted domestic cousins repose on millions of American tables as
the centerpiece of Thanksgiving dinner, wily and wary wild turkeys
are flourishing throughout the California foothills. Theirs is one
of the great environmental success stories of the 20th century _ a
species rescued from the brink of extinction. By ERIC BRAZIL.
</P>
<P>
   HISPANIC-LITERATURE (Houston) _ Arte Publico, a Houston-based
small press specializing in Hispanic literature, is discovering and
nuturing Hispanic writers. Arte Publico first made a name for
itself with books used in university classes, but its works are
catching on with the general public, including a number of
non-Hispanics. By JEANNIE KEAVER. (Art available on NYT service.)
</P>
<P>
   SKY-SLEUTH (San Marcos, Texas) _ Professor Donald Olson of
Southwest Texas State University uses astronomy to solve puzzles
involving historical events and artistic works, to fix dates and
locations, to explain why the inexplicable happened. From a
supernova in ``Hamlet'' to astronomical references in ``The
Canterbury Tales,'' Olson is always working. His latest project:
the Battle of Quebec. By TODD ACKERMAN. (Art available on NYT photo
service.)
</P>
<P>
   CHRISTMAS-TREES (Altamont, N.Y.) _ The product development cycle
is long and the profit margins are slim, but the finished products
sure smell good. Consumers can start catching a whiff this weekend,
when Christmas tree growers ship trees to retailers. Yes, tree
farmers say, a fresh tree you buy this weekend will easily last
through Christmas if properly cared for. By JO-ANN JOHNSTON
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS-FINANCE (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   AOL-NETSCAPE-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ While Wall Street analysts chewed
over the $4.2 billion AOL-Netscape-Sun Microsystems merger,
computer users were asking what was in it for them. The San
Francisco Examiner posed some user questions to AOL's chief
executive officer, Steve Case, at AOL headquarters in Dulles, Va.
Following is a Q&AMP;A with Case. By MATT BEER.
</P>
<P>
   CAREER-SUCCESS (San Francisco) _ Paul DiGiammarino thought he
was doing a great job, until he received a negative performance
review _ from his teen-age son. The successful business executive
had to learn how to juggle his successful career and family life,
something he now encourages others to do. By DAVE MURPHY.
</P>
<P>
   HOLIDAY-RETAIL (San Francisco) _ Predicting holiday retail sales
blends a curious mix of pessimistic analysts and relentlessly
optimistic retailers. But this year, both sides expect a
year-over-year sales gain of about 4 to 6 percent, an increase
strong enough to make the season merry and lucrative for retailers.
By VICTORIA COLLIVER.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-BABE-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Babe: Pig in the City,'' which is
quite impressive and often fun, is also a downer for about half its
length because of the constant threat of death to the animals. The
sequel has our little pink hero in a surrealistic nightmare fantasy
that is fascinating but also disturbing. By LOUIS B. PARKS.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-SONGWRITERS (San Antonio) _ The fodder for Texas
songwriters is pretty straightforward: Somebody's going get shot.
Failing that, they're going to get shot at; or hold up a
convenience store; or steal a car; or fall in love with the wrong
person, the wrong train, or, God forbid, the wrong pickup truck. A
new album takes a look the writing talent in the Lone Star state.
By JIM BEAL Jr.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-THRILLERS (Undated) _ ``The Pied Piper,'' Ridley Pearson's
fifth thriller featuring Seattle Police Lt. Lou Boldt and forensic
pathologist Daphne Matthews, is fast-paced, hair-raising and
mesmerizing. This is a terrific thriller by one of the best in the
field. By BOBBIE HESS.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL (``t'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-DEVILS-ISLANDS (Devil's Islands, French Guiana) _ This
former penal colony has shed its deadly reputation to become a
tourist haunt. By JOHN OTIS.
</P>
<P>
   With: TRAVEL-DEVILS-SIDE
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FBN-49ERS (Santa Clara, Calif.) _ San Francisco 49ers coach
Steve Mariucci will give his players Thanksgiving off. For what?
Certainly not for stalwart play. This is a team that needs work,
not more down time on the old La-Z-Boy. By JOHN CRUMPACKER.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   LYNCH-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ Carol Van Ginkel died recently at
age 82. His last years had been arduous because his wife was gone
and his body was betraying him. But on Thanksgiving, his daughter
will reflect on his life and her own gratitude for two little dogs
who'd loved her father so deeply and made his last years worth
living. By DAN LYNCH.
</P>
<P>
   WONG-COLUMN (Oakland, Calif.) _ Foo Tooey Moo was one of the
last, if not the last, old Chinese women of pre-World War II
Oakland Chinatown. She died earlier this month at age 92 and her
passing punctuates the passing of an era, almost ineffably. It was
just this past summer that another Oakland Chinatown icon, George
Catambay, a barber of Filipino descent, died at the age of 93. By
WILLIAM WONG.
</P>
</TEXT>
