<HEADLINE>
A WAR OF WORDS IN CYBERSPACE 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATTI HARTIGAN   c.1998 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The battle over civil rights has spread from the political arena
to the new frontiers of cyberspace. As it rages, it is spinning off
perplexing and intriguing questions about freedom of speech.
</P>
<P>
   For several years, groups that advocate intolerance _ hate
groups, as they are known _ have used the Internet to spread their
message. For the most part, their cyber-efforts have received less
attention than, say, pornography sites _ although that changed
briefly with the recent murder of a New York state doctor who had
been targeted on line by abortion foes.
</P>
<P>
   But as hate groups' cyber-campaigns have heated up, so have the
efforts to counter them, resulting in a full-scale _ and
increasingly sophisticated _ war of words on the Net.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, for instance, the Anti-Defamation League
introduced HateFilter, a noncommercial software package that blocks
specific hate sites and redirects browsers to the ADL's education
site.
</P>
<P>
   Filtering tools have been controversial since they first came on
the market a few years ago; one of the first packages was so
primitive it unintentionally blocked the site for the National
Organization for Women, alarming First Amendment activists. But ADL
officials contend they are not advocating outright censorship of
certain sites but simply providing parents with a choice on how
their children receive information.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, civil rights groups are getting increasingly
savvy in cyberspace. A typical search for the Ku Klux Klan will
direct users to a site where it's possible to purchase a Klan robe,
complete with blood-drop shoulder patch, for a mere $85, but the
search results will also lead browsers to Klanwatch, a civil rights
site operated by the Southern Poverty Law Center.
</P>
<P>
   The implication is clear: The same technology that provides a
forum for extremists enables civil rights groups and individuals to
mobilize a response in unprecedented ways.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC;  Hate on the Net is only a mouse click away. Some examples:
</P>
<P>
   _A Web site called Aryan Female Homestead lambastes
intermarriage and preaches racial purity.
</P>
<P>
   _The Web page for the World Church of the Creator declares a
``racial holy war'' against its ``mortal racial enemies.''
</P>
<P>
   _Another site known for its vicious attacks against gays and
lesbians features a letter condemning the parents of Matthew
Shepard, the young gay man who was tortured and murdered in Wyoming
last month.
</P>
<P>
   _And an infamous Web page called the Nuremberg Files declares
that ``legalized abortion is war'' and lists the names, addresses,
and telephone numbers of doctors who provide abortion services.
</P>
<P>
   Lining up in opposition are such people as David Goldman, a
35-year-old law librarian who runs a site called HateWatch.org out
of a modest office in Cambridge, Mass. With a small budget and a
tiny staff augmented by volunteers all over the world, Goldman
offers the most extensive on-line resource available to monitor
hate on the Internet. It ferrets outsites that advocate violence or
``unreasonable hostility'' toward groups or individuals based on
race, religion, national origin, sexual orientation, gender, or
disability.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you give a fool enough rope, he'll hang himself,'' said
Goldman, who started the site a few years ago when he was a
reference assistant at the Harvard University Law Library. ``I have
no fear that a rational, thinking person is going to be swept up by
these hate sites. I always say, `Don't believe me. Don't believe
HateWatch. Don't believe the ADL. Go in, take a look at the
information and judge for yourself.' I don't fear bigots. I fear
apathy.''
</P>
<P>
   Sites similar to HateWatch are emerging all the time:
Anti-Semitic sites are countered by the Nizkor Project, an
exhaustive on-line resource center that challenges Holocaust
denial. And while users can easily download white power computer
games for free, they can also play an on-line interactive game
about hate on the Internet sponsored by the Canadian Human Rights
Organization.
</P>
<P>
   While some groups are lobbying Congress to pass blanket
legislation that would censor the Internet (primarily to block out
pornography), other groups are urging Internet service providers to
subscribe to a voluntary code of conduct that prohibits hate sites.
</P>
<P>
   Some providers, including America Online and Bell Atlantic,
include such provisions in their service agreements. But Rick
Eaton, senior researcher at the Simon Weisenthal Center in Los
Angeles, said that when his organization sent out a voluntary code
of ethics to hundreds of service providers two years ago, he
received only a handful of responses.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet, after all, is in its infancy, both in terms of
ethics codes and criminal justice. There is almost no legal
precedent that specifically addresses free speech on the Internet,
and existing First Amendment statutes concerning other media have
yet to be tested in cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   There are two principles that distinguish protected speech from
speech that incites violence, according to Nadine Strossen,
president of the American Civil Liberties Union. First, the speech
must be proved to be a ``true threat'' that goes beyond political
rhetoric and hyperbole. Second, it must be deemed to constitute an
intentional incitement to imminent violence.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of the Nuremberg Files, legal experts and FBI
officials alike contend that it is impossible to prove that its
founder, Neal Horsley, actually incited the killer of Dr. Barnett
Slepian, who performed abortions, to pull the trigger.
</P>
<P>
   Horsley, a self-taught computer consultant and a graduate of the
Westminister Theological Seminary in Pennsylvania who runs the site
out of Carrollton, Ga., is unrepentant. ``Until the babies stop
getting killed, more and more people are going to get shot or
bombed,'' Horsley warned in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   The recent publicity resulting from Slepian's murder in his home
near Buffalo, N.Y., has only increased the Nuremberg Files site's
notoriety: In October, it received more than 400,000 hits, double
its usual count.
</P>
<P>
   Horsley said he has been visited by officials from the FBI and
the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco, and Firearms. Bill Carter, an FBI
spokesman in Washington, would not comment on whether Horsley had
been investigated. But he said, ``No matter how abhorrent a
particular person's beliefs might be, we still live in a free
country, and free speech is a constitutional right.''
</P>
<P>
   To date, the Justice Department has only prosecuted two cases
concerning threatening speech on line. A few years ago, a Federal
District Court judge in Michigan dismissed charges against a
student indicted for threatening other students by violent,
pornographic fantasies via e-mail. In February, a former college
student in California was convicted of a felony for e-mailing
racist death threats to 59 Asian students and staffers at the
University of California at Irvine.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Pennsylvania attorney general Michael Fisher sued a
Web site operator named Ryan Wilson, along with his service
providers, for allegedly threatening two civil rights activists who
are members of the Reading-Berks Human Relations Council and the
Pennsylvania Human Relations Commission. The site, which was called
ALPHA HQ and has since been shut down, included a photograph of one
of the employees and a message saying, ``Traitors like this ...
will be hung from the nearest tree or lamp post.'' The site also
featured an image of an office building blowing up.
</P>
<P>
   That suit is being watched closely in on-line circles,
particularly since it also names the primary service provider and
the secondary service provider, a man named Don Black who operates
a white supremacist site called Stormfront out of West Palm Beach,
Fla. ``It's a precedent-setting case for sites such as mine, but
also for all ISPs (Internet service providers),'' Black said of the
Pennsylvania case. ``It makes them liable for content of sites that
they don't even host.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Internet service providers would blanch at that connection,
for it was Black who posted the first white supremacist site back
in March 1995. At the time, the World Wide Web was just emerging,
and Black, an ex-Grand Dragon of the Alabama KKK who learned
computer science while he was incarcerated for conspiring to
overthrow the government of a Caribbean island, inaugurated the use
of the Internet as a tool for extremist groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are able to reach millions of people that we never had
access to in the past,'' he said in a telephone interview. ``The
Internet is becoming an alternative news media for those who have
an alternative point of view.''
</P>
<P>
   Black defines what he calls white nationalism as ``the idea that
whites may need to create a separate nation as a means of defending
themselves.'' In addition to providing links to the Aryan Nation,
KKK groups, and Holocaust denial sites, Stormfront includes a
library, an on-line chat room, and a white-singles dating service.
His site has inspired many others like it, including a site
operated by David Duke, the former KKK leader and occasional
political candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people who have ruled the information media have been
people with fantastic amounts of power and money, and finally, the
Internet makes it possible for different points of view to be
heard,'' said Duke, whose slick, multimedia site features the
manifesto ``The Coming White Revolution _ Born on the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   But while many lament that such views are available on the Net,
activists like Goldman contend that bringing hate into the on-line
mainstream may actually defuse its potential power. ``They can spew
all the filth they want, but as long as they're spewing it, someone
like HateWatch is going to be out there watching what they do and
educating the public about what they can do about it,'' Goldman
said. ``We'll be there, shining the light on the cockroaches.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-11-23-98 1330EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-25-98 1104EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981125.0075 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-25 11:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8825 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-COMPUTER-BRIEFS-N     11-25 0796
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTER-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARTUP'S SHAREHOLDERS HOLD MEETING ONLINE  
 FOR YEAR 2000 GNATS, A SCENTED `BUG' SPRAY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (Eds: Bylines follow individual items.) 
(lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the age of the Internet, the proxies and mahogany-lined
boardrooms typical of important company meetings might give way to
quirkier variations. Such was the case with Travelzoo.com, a budget
travel company that held its first company meeting online on
Friday. No jacket was required; shareholders just logged on,
entered their passwords and cast their electronic ballots for the
board.
</P>
<P>
   A month ago, the start-up company's 700,000 ``owners'' _ each of
whom qualified for three shares of stock simply by showing up at
Travelzoo's site on the World Wide Web this spring _ were asked by
e-mail who among them cared to run for the seven nonpaying
directors' seats.
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Bartel, the founder of Travelzoo.com, said he was
surprised at how many shareholders submitted their biographies for
consideration _ 400 in all.
</P>
<P>
   They ranged from the author of a book on Maryland wines to an
executive with McDonald's to a second-year medical student in
Ponce, Puerto Rico, named Greg Kohanski, whose biography sounded
like a campaign promise for student office: ``I am extremely
organized, very responsible and will take my position very
seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   Jason Jennings, a financial manager from Gaithersburg, Md.,
bolstered his candidacy by proclaiming, ``I am interested in
Travelzoo.com because I like to travel, especially to places with
tennis courts.''
</P>
<P>
   And Barbara Crane, a 28-year-old social worker who did not list
her residency, defied the notion that a board member has to be
steely and impersonal: ``My personal interests include my husband,
baby (German shepherd), family, friends, church, theater, hiking
and movies. I love to travel. I feel for mental health it is
important to vacation and explore other cultures and lifestyles.''
</P>
<P>
   The results of the election will be posted on the company's site
by Tuesday, said Bartel _ who, as founder, retained 30 percent of
the company stock, no doubt ensuring his election to one of the
seats.
</P>
<P>
   He was quick to note the company's third-quarter profit of
$34,749, on revenues of $103,282, which he attributed to
advertising sales and commissions on sales of plane tickets from a
new booking feature on the site.
</P>
<P>
   His big-name competitors, he said, are not profitable, because
they pay millions of dollars ``to become exclusive travel agents or
spend millions on advertising.''
</P>
<P>
   Bartel started the business with no capital and no corporate
alliances, hoping to rely on word of mouth and what he called a
``power of the people'' business strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Naysayers laughed at his strategy at first, saying the chance of
the company's paying dividends was nil, but on the Internet,
suspension of disbelief appears to be part of the business plan.
</P>
<P>
   _ LISA NAPOLI
</P>
<P>
   For Year 2000 Gnats, a Scented `Bug' Spray
</P>
<P>
   It was only a matter of time. With all the anxiety among those
trying to head off computer chaos when the year 2000 arrives, some
computer-savvy entrepreneur was bound to come up with a less solemn
approach. And now, sure enough, a ``Y2K Bug Spray'' has appeared.
</P>
<P>
   The spray bottle is the brainchild of Dan Dyce, a claims
adjuster and Web-page builder from El Dorado Hills, Calif., who
teamed up with a buddy, Dale Miller, to create this ``Solution for
Your Year 2000 Problems.''
</P>
<P>
   The ingredients are almost entirely (99.746 percent, to be
exact) either ``Y2KBS'' or water, depending on which part of the
label you believe. And Dyce hopes it becomes the stocking stuffer
of choice for overstressed Cobol programmers everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   The two got their gag into distribution via www.isgnet.com/y2k
for less than $1,000. Their local Mail Boxes Etc. store receives
the orders and handles the shipping.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did the trademark work, found our raw materials, found a
manufacturer, all via the Internet, all during evening hours, all
without ever leaving our home,'' Dyce said.
</P>
<P>
   At $4.95 a bottle, plus shipping, Y2K Bug Spray is being used as
an icebreaker at technical meetings and as a humorous advertising
tool by Steven Schroeder, an accountant in Rancho Cordova, Calif.,
whose clients include insurance adjusters likely to run into year
2000 claims.
</P>
<P>
   What if the red and yellow spray bottle fails to stop irate
calls from chief executives or deliver the other suggested
benefits? Never fear. This pine-scented liquid comes with a
guarantee _ an ironclad promise that it will still be a
``solution'' if used by Jan. 1, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   _ BARNABY J. FEDER
</P>
<P>
