<HEADLINE>
FANNING FLAMES IN HEATED POLL DEBATE
</HEADLINE>
 
(Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News   To really take
this Bowl Championship Series formula to the next level, someone
back at mission control should factor in the results from the
Internet's top two weekly fan polls on ESPN.com and CBS SportsLine.
<TEXT>
<P>
   They've got to be as legit as anything else.
</P>
<P>
   In order to preserve the integrity of its poll by using software
that eliminates duplicate votes _ thus preventing ballot-stuffing _
voting on the ESPN.com poll
(http://ESPN.SportsZone.com/interact/chat/fanpollrank.html) runs
Sunday night to Tuesday morning, and the results are posted by
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Going into last Saturday's games,Kansas State had replaced
Tennessee as the new No. 1 in this cyber survey with 4,602
first-place votes
(http://ESPN.SportsZone.com/interact/polls/ncffanpoll.html). UCLA
checked in at No. 3.
</P>
<P>
   The CBS SportsLine poll accepts Shockwave, Java or HTML ballots
between Saturday night and Thursday morning (http://
ww1.sportsline.com/u/football/ college/polls/fanpoll.htm), with the
results available Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Last week's poll (http:// ww3.sportsline.com/u/contests/
entries/fanpoll.htm) closer resembled the BCA poll, as Tennessee
had a 447-point lead at No. 1 over UCLA, with Kansas State third.
</P>
<P>
   For a comparative chuckle, check out the poll at the USA Today
site (http://survey.usatoday.com/survey/fanvot.html), which permits
just one vote for No. 1 (instead of the full 25 slots) plus
requires giving up an e-mail address (no doubt for future spam)
before the ballot counts. Updated every minute, the poll had UCLA
10th as of Sunday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, gussied-up versions of the Associated Press' writers'
poll (http://www.aptop25.com) and the USA Today/ESPN coaches' poll
(http://www.usatoday.com/sports/football/sfc/sfcpusa.htm) are
around for reference. Or debate.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's Mike DeSimone of Clarksboro, N.J., who uses
mathematical algorithms to figure out his No. 1-to-112 poll at his
site (http://www.algorithms.com/users/desimone/top25.htm). His top
pick?
</P>
<P>
   Hey, you do the math.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-11-22-98 2106EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
