</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
TALK TO ME, BABY _ WITH A MICROPHONE
</HEADLINE>
 CPT- COMPUTERS-BOMBAY-COLUMN-TEX 
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
(RESENDING to fix slug) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DR. EMILIO BOMBAY c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dear Dr. Bombay: Is it possible to use your telephone receiver
as a microphone, since it's connected to the modem? _ Just Curious
</P>
<P>
   Dear Just: Just drive by the nearest fire station and see if you
can borrow the Jaws of Life for a few minutes. Then maybe you can
pry your wallet open long enough to extract five lousy bucks for a
stinking microphone.
</P>
<P>
   Haven't you ever picked up the phone while you were online? You
get knocked off immediately, right? That's because only one device
can be using the line at a time, unless you have some fancy digital
doodads. You can't just pick up the phone, murmur ``What are you
wearing, baby?'' into it and have it broadcast all over the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The modem has nothing to do with transmitting your voice. All
that stuff is handled by your sound card, which records what you
mumble into the mike, then funnels it into your video- or
audio-conferencing software. From there, it gets turned into tiny
little bundles of data and passed on to the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Your modem takes all those digital signals _ all those little
ones and zeroes _ and translates them into a horrid screeching
sound that can be sent over a regular phone line. Modems on the
other end reverse the process.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Dr. Bombay: On a CD-ROM drive, the tray slides out, and you
just place the CD on it. Once the CD is inside, what makes it spin?
On a CD player with a flip-up lid, the CD goes on a spindle, but on
the slide-out kind? No spindle, just a little hole. _ The Hole
Truth
</P>
<P>
   Dear Truth: It's been a closely guarded industry secret until
now, but there are thousands of tiny little invisible fairies who
live in your computer. It takes a specially trained army of about
70,000 of them to surround the CD, lift it ever so gently from the
tray, then run around in a circle as fast as they can until they
get so dizzy they throw up. That dust you see collecting in the CD
tray? Fairy puke.
</P>
<P>
   Look, there really is a spindle, and it's inside the drive with
the rest of the guts. When the tray retracts, the spindle grabs the
CD. No fairies are injured in the process.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Dr. Bombay: Bruce Williams has his picture in our paper.
Jane Bryant Quinn has her picture in our paper. Even The Motley
Fool has a picture in our paper. Why not you? _ A Real Fan
</P>
<P>
   Dear A: The statute of limitations hasn't run out in your state.
Anyway, that whole unfortunate incident at the liquor store was a
simple misunderstanding. It was all Bruce's idea.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Dr. Bombay: An objectionable picture has lodged itself on
my wallpaper as well as the wallpaper menu. How do I delete it so
my kids will not see it? _ Whoops
</P>
<P>
   Dear Whoops: Well, I guess that'll teach you to get twitchy with
your mouse hand. Most browsers let you capture Web images as
Windows wallpaper with a click or two. Of course, that means you
have to have been looking at the image in the first place. Nice
example for the kids.
</P>
<P>
   Wallpaper images usually can be found in the Windows folder with
a .BMP extension. If it's not there, use Find (on the Start menu)
to locate it, then go delete it. Or better yet, send it to me for
safekeeping.
</P>
<P>
   (Wondering if your wallpaper is naughty? Noted computerologist
Dr. Emilio Bombay will guard your morals, too. He can be reached at
drbombay\Nstar-telegram.com or via snail-mail at Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, TX 76101. Fax: 390-7257. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-11-19-98 1855EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
