<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Wallets full, consciences clear
 &HT;    (EDS: This is the column that normally moves on Thursdays,
moving today because of the holiday.)
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   I have very good news for you. All those companies and trade
associations and cats fat beyond measure who have been off-loading
multimillions in ``soft money'' to the Democratic and Republican
parties don't want a darn thing back and can't buy a penny's worth
of influence no matter how much they shell out.
</P>
<P>
   We have no less than officials of the GOP to thank for this
welcome reassurance, uttered in recent testimony to the Federal
Elections Commission.
</P>
<P>
   With campaign-funding reform left in a bloody heap on the
barroom floor after the recent Congress quit town, the FEC
commissioners are considering whether they should _ in fact,
whether lawfully they can _ adopt reforms on their own. The answers
are almost surely that they won't and couldn't anyway, but the
exercise is not without its merits even so.
</P>
<P>
   There is not otherwise much mirth in Washington these days, but
there was Craig Engle, general counsel for the National Republican
Senatorial Committee, explaining that in the unlikely event any of
the big political sugar daddies should be found trying to cop a
grope for his diamonds and flowers, ``There are bribery statutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed there are, but there's the niggling problem of trying to
prove a cause-and-effect connection when everybody involved in the
transaction is tutored in the etiquette of silence and shocked
denial.
</P>
<P>
   So we are left to conclude that in the last Congress, it was
just coincidence that Wall Street contributors, who shelled out
$23.2 million, wound up getting a delay in regulations for swaps
and derivatives and won helpful new standards for securities
class-action lawsuits. The Center for Responsive Politics noticed
that and dozens more such coincidences.
</P>
<P>
   Telephone and TV companies got between $12 billion and $70
billion in free broadcast frequencies, a boon in which, happily,
their $14.4 million in political contributions had absolutely no
role. Tobacco's $6.1 million had nothing to do with the defeat of
legislation to limit tobacco advertising and cut youth smoking.
</P>
<P>
   It was just a pesky accident, and no doubt embarrassing as such
to the parties, that $6.9 million in contributions from accountants
coincided with the Treasury Department backing away from rules to
close a tax loophole that lets some multinationals cut tax payments
abroad and duck payments to the U.S. government on overseas
operations.
</P>
<P>
   Soft money is the money contributors give to the parties to get
around limits on how much can be contributed directly to
candidates. The parties then broadcast ``issue'' ads that, as
chance would have it, boost, say, Sen. Hy Faluten (it's almost
always an incumbent) by helpfully pointing out his opponent
strangles small, cuddly animals for fun.
</P>
<P>
   By mid-October this year, Democrats had pocketed $78.8 million
in soft money, an 84 percent increase over the last
non-presidential cycle (1993-94). Republicans had hauled in $94.7
million, a 144 percent increase.
</P>
<P>
   I can almost feel your relief that all those givers brought to
the table only a pristine commitment to the electoral process. Can
you feel my relief?
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers. He is
based in Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
