A8843 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HISPANIC-LITERATURE-A     11-25 1439
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HISPANIC-LITERATURE-ART-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMALL PRESS, GRANDE INFLUENCE: ARTE PUBLICO A LEADING FORCE IN
HISPANIC LITERATURE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Accent mark needed over o in Limon, second e in ``Bernabe,''
u in Publico, a in Nicholas; and a tilde is needed over n in
Villasenor) 
 
(Photo available on NYT service) 
 
By JEANNIE KEVER 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Graciela Limon believed in her first book, ``In Search
of Bernabe,'' but it seemed no one else did.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many, many, numerous rejections, without explanation,'' she
says to sum up her experiences with the publishing world.
</P>
<P>
   Unwilling to give up, she entered a literary competition at the
University of California-Irvine. The first-place winner was
guaranteed a publishing contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Search of Bernabe'' placed third.
</P>
<P>
   Discouraged, Limon nonetheless agreed to read from her work at a
reception for the award winners. And there she found another true
believer.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in the audience was a representative of Arte Publico
Press.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Search of Bernabe'' was published in 1993, going on to win
an American Book Award, among other accolades.
</P>
<P>
   When Limon's fourth novel is published next spring, Arte Publico
will again be at the helm, evidence of the author's faith that a
Houston-based small press specializing in Hispanic literature can
treat her work more carefully than a more-prestigious New York
publishing company.
</P>
<P>
   Discovering and nurturing Hispanic writers _ knowing how to
market their works, from advertising on Spanish-language radio to
selling in Hispanic neighborhood supermarkets _ is a cornerstone of
the way Arte Publico has grown since its founding 19 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The press originally flourished in educational publishing,
providing materials for the then-new fields of Hispanic studies and
women's studies. When public schools, increasingly filled with
Hispanic students, began looking for more relevant books, Arte
Publico bolstered its children's line by starting a separate
children's division in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   As Hispanic and other ethnic literature has edged into the
mainstream, Arte Publico has ridden the wave; it now estimates that
about 40 percent of its business comes from the general book-buying
public, and about 30 percent of its readers are non-Hispanic.
</P>
<P>
   It also is guiding an ambitious academic project to recover
Hispanic works _ from newspapers to novels _ that were published
and then vanished between 1808 and 1960. A conference on that
project will be Dec. 4-5 at Rice University.
</P>
<P>
   Arte Publico has published about 350 books since its founding,
now averaging between 30 and 35 books a year, most of them in
English.
</P>
<P>
   It all grew from one man's sense that something was wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Nicholas Kanellos had been active in the Chicano movement of the
1960s and '70s, teaching Hispanic literature at Indiana University
Northwest and, surrounded by many of the important Chicano writers
of the day, troubled by the paucity of places that would publish
their work.
</P>
<P>
   He started a small literary magazine in 1973 and, six years
later, expanded it into a full publishing company, which he named
Arte Publico Press.
</P>
<P>
   When the University of Houston offered him a teaching job the
following year, Kanellos and his fledgling venture moved south.
Timing worked in their favor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were involved from the ground up in (helping to develop
curriculums for) ethnic studies, bilingual education, women's
education,'' said Kanellos, who teaches a graduate course in
Hispanic literature at UH in addition to running Arte Publico.
``That was where the strength of Hispanic literature was, and still
is.
</P>
<P>
   ``It lives at the university (level).''
</P>
<P>
   Changing demographics also played a role in the company's growth
_ it now is the largest nonprofit publisher of literature in the
United States _ as public schools and libraries began looking for
books to better reflect the lives of their increasingly Hispanic
student populations.
</P>
<P>
   That's especially true in Texas, California and other areas of
the Southwest with large Hispanic populations, said Christine Lind
Hage, a librarian from suburban Detroit who is president of the
national Public Library Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is growing support in public libraries for providing
literature and services to the entire community,'' she said. ``It
certainly is a collection that many libraries are developing.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't always that way. Kanellos still remembers the sting of
growing up Puerto Rican in New York, dismissively lumped together
with all other Hispanics as ``Spanish,'' finding nothing in his
school books that resembled his life at home.
</P>
<P>
   Limon, chair of the Chicano studies department at Loyola
Marymount University in Los Angeles, credits Kanellos with helping
to change that for today's Hispanic students.
</P>
<P>
   ``Up to 10 years ago, to teach a decent course in Hispanic
literature, you couldn't find good publications,'' she said. ``Arte
Publico jumped in to come up with fine publications in fiction and
nonfiction. ... In the world of U.S. Hispanic literature, I think
Dr. Kanellos has been an absolute pioneer.''
</P>
<P>
   Arte Publico was the first, but other small presses followed.
Marilyn Ross, executive director of the Small Publishers
Association of North America, said the movement gained momentum
several years ago, well after Arte Publico entered the field.
``They really were the trend-setters,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   As demand grows, Ross predicts that mainstream publishing
companies will increasingly go after Hispanic authors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything small presses do and do early and do well,
eventually the big presses say, `This is a bandwagon we need to
climb on,''' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Kanellos is more skeptical. Large publishing houses do publish
more Hispanic writing, he admitted, including Sandra Cisneros and
Ana Castillo, both of whom got their start at Arte Publico.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's only infinitesimally more,'' Kanellos said. ``You'd
be hard-pressed to count more than 10.''
</P>
<P>
   Competing with publishing's heavyweights _ companies including
Random House, Dutton and Putnam _ is difficult, especially as
mega-bookstores overtake the independent retailers who once made up
most of the nation's booksellers. The big publishing companies have
money to promote their books; Arte Publico doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Arte Publico has had its moments. Its big break came with
``Rain of Gold,'' the 1991 best-selling family saga by Victor
Villasenor.
</P>
<P>
   Villasenor had a contract and a $75,000 advance from a New York
publishing company, an enviable position by most standards. But the
publisher wanted changes that he couldn't accept, including
renaming the book and marketing it as fiction.
</P>
<P>
   Villasenor said no, and he bought back his contract. The book
became the first hardback published by Arte Publico, which had
previously worked exclusively in paperback because of the lower
production costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rain of Gold'' was a hit, and Arte Publico suddenly gained
notice.
</P>
<P>
   ``It meant we had a national presence in the national book
industry,'' Kanellos said, as well as giving them experience in
publishing a hardback book, marketing paperback rights and other
spin-off benefits.
</P>
<P>
   But writers also leave for larger publishers.
</P>
<P>
   Kanellos isn't worried about finding other talented writers, but
losing writers whom he has nurtured isn't easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that's the way it goes,'' he said. ``We really can't
compete with the commercial houses. They can afford a very large
advance, which we can't.''
</P>
<P>
   Limon insists that, despite her success _ awards, favorable
reviews, respectable sales _ she isn't tempted to leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``What attracts some writers to the larger houses is a big fat
advance,'' she said. ``But that's all it is, an advance. ... If the
books don't sell, a larger publishing house will just yank your
book and say, `See you later.'''
</P>
<P>
   Careful promotion can result in higher sales, allowing writers
to make more money in the long run, she said.
</P>
<P>
   She prefers to think long-term.
</P>
<P>
   So does Kanellos, who predicts that Hispanic literature will
gain readership in coming years. The trend actually started in the
1980s, as colleges began shifting Hispanic and other ethnic
literature into the core curriculum, making it required reading for
all students. Many books are also widely reviewed in general
readership newspapers, giving them broader exposure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect we're going to have our Toni Morrisons,'' Kanellos
said, ``and Hispanic literature will be a staple, just like Jewish
literature became after the Second World War.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
