<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-25 11:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8844 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN29-CO     11-25 0647
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Who's burning out whom?
 &HT;    For release Nov. 29, 1998.
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   News item: The University of Michigan's Institute for Social
Research has come to the conclusion that we are burning out our
children well before their time. The heavy schedules we impose upon
them, the study of 3,586 children under the age of 12 says, has
taken the fun out of being a kid.
</P>
<P>
   I'll go along with that. I'd also go along with a study that
showed the demands placed by those same kids on their parents are
burning out Mommy and Daddy well before their time as well. It
takes the fun out of being an adult.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line: I think we're all to blame, Mom, Dad and Junior
alike.
</P>
<P>
   When I was an under-12 child (World War II era) there wasn't
much of a schedule. Go to school, come home. On Friday nights, go
over to Grandma's for one of those rubber chicken dinners. On
Saturdays, I played baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Not for any of the above engagements did either parent have to
escort me. Everything, of course, was in walking distance. No, I
didn't live in the country; yes, I did live in the city. So I
walked.
</P>
<P>
   As with the chicken and the egg, I do not know what started the
contemporary marathon-like lifestyles of kids and their parents.
Likely it was the post-war exodus to suburbia for so many of us.
Things got too far away.
</P>
<P>
   It is a fact that the nation's highways now are clogged with
minivans and SUVs driven mostly by weary mothers taking kids to and
from school, to and from dancing lessons, to and from baseball
practice, to and from Sunday school, to karate lessons and from
karate lessons, to and from Cub Scout meetings, to and from Brownie
meetings, to the store, from the store, and on and on.
</P>
<P>
   Seemingly, my fortyish daughter spends her entire weekday life
in that red minivan schlepping two young sons to appointments, many
of which the kids want to meet, some of which they do not.
</P>
<P>
   We did it all to ourselves. We did it to our kids, insisting
they do this and that. Our kids did it to us, insisting that they
want to do other this and that.
</P>
<P>
   For many of the kids of today, a game of baseball no longer is a
bunch of kids drifting together, choosing up sides and playing
until it gets dark. Now, it's an organized endeavor that requires
you to have to be at a specific park, on a specific team, at a
specific time (usually dinner time) and at a specific distance from
your house _ like a couple of miles. You can't walk it; mom usually
drives, plops down on a lawn chair, and waits out all the hits and
errors until such time as she has to commute again back to the
house, or perhaps the Scout meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, beginning with my generation, we did put pressure on our
kids to play ball, dance, stick with religious school, and even
take on dozens of other tasks that we did not have to do as a
child.
</P>
<P>
   But to say that we're burning them out before they are 12? What
about all those stories of the generations before, of kids having
to walk five miles in the snow to get to school, to walk down to
the grocer each and every day to pick up fresh butter and milk for
Mom, of working after school in the candy store, or getting up at 5
a.m. to deliver the morning paper _ not to mention those child
sweat shops?
</P>
<P>
   Didn't that burn out those kids? Well, apparently not. Our
parents survived, so did we.
</P>
<P>
   The pressures of 1990s lifestyles on children and adults alike
are rigorous, but so, in other ways, were those of our parents and
grandparents. The main difference between today and yesterday is
that today people are making studies of it.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
