<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKY-SLEUTH-ART-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SKY SLEUTH: PROFESSOR RELIES ON CELESTIAL CLUES TO SOLVE MYSTERIES
OF ART, HISTORY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Photo available on NYT service) 
 
By TODD ACKERMAN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN MARCOS, Texas _ In astronomy professor Donald Olson's
office, reproductions of van Gogh paintings and portraits of
military battles occupy more wall space than observatory posters or
solar system charts.
</P>
<P>
   The bookshelves are filled with collections of Ansel Adams
photographs, histories of the Civil War and World War II,
biographies of Abraham Lincoln, and the works of Shakespeare,
Chaucer and Dante.
</P>
<P>
   ``The contents of my office inspire me,'' says Olson, of
Southwest Texas State University. ``They put me in a mood conducive
to the kind of creative thinking I need for the research I do.''
</P>
<P>
   Olson is an academic sleuth, a Renaissance man who uses
astronomy to solve puzzles involving historical events and artistic
works, to fix dates and locations, to explain why the inexplicable
happened or how a genius operated.
</P>
<P>
   He determined that Lincoln did not fabricate evidence in a
celebrated murder trial, that Spanish explorer Cabeza de Vaca took
a route through Mexico rather than Central Texas, and where and
when Adams took his famous ``Moon and Half Dome'' photograph.
</P>
<P>
   Most recently, Olson was in the news for his theory that a
particular star mentioned in the opening scene of ``Hamlet'' was a
supernova that appeared in the constellation Cassiopeia in 1572.
</P>
<P>
   The supernova, a dramatic exploding star that burned for 16
months before fading from sight, was a source of profound
uneasiness among the general populace, which saw it as a sign of
things going wrong, a recurring theme of ``Hamlet.''
</P>
<P>
   Olson is working on research involving the Battle of Quebec,
regarded by some historians as Canada's Gettysburg. He and a few
students recently returned from a trip to the St. Lawrence River,
where they showed what little understanding historians have had of
the use that British Gen. James Wolfe made of moonlight and tides
in defeating the French.
</P>
<P>
   Olson's student assistance comes from undergraduates in his
``Astronomy in Art, History and Literature'' class, an honors
course usually composed of mostly liberal-arts and fine-arts
majors, not science majors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the experience those students get is invaluable,''
says Ron Brown, a Southwest Texas State dean, who suggested that
Olson teach the course. ``Where else can nonscientists conduct
on-site research and employ the scientific method?''
</P>
<P>
   Olson's interest in historical and artistic research dates back
to liberal-arts parties he attended in the late 1980s with his
wife, an English professor. At one, an expert on Chaucer questioned
Olson about some of the astronomical references in ``The Canterbury
Tales.'' At another, a history professor suggested he look into the
mysterious tide that led to the U.S. Marines' disastrous WWII
invasion of the Japanese-held Pacific atoll of Tarawa.
</P>
<P>
   Olson says at the time he ``had not a clue'' how to investigate
such matters. But through extensive historical research and
state-of-the-art astronomical computer programs that can re-create
constellations from before the time of Christ, he became good at
it.
</P>
<P>
   And Olson, always an eclectic, became particularly sensitive to
potential astronomical matters in photos, paintings, literature and
history. A decade later, he has published more than 60 academic
papers using astronomy to unearth new information about history and
art.
</P>
<P>
   The papers have made an impact. National newspapers, magazines
and television shows have carried stories on them. Recently,
authoritative books on Tarawa, Lincoln, Paul Revere and Ansel Adams
have referred to them. When Olson and his students pinpointed a
time when the moon would be in the same place above Yosemite's Half
Dome as it was in Adams' photo, Adams' daughter-in-law and more
than 40 photographers showed up.
</P>
<P>
   Olson says the research is also valuable because it shows
students that astronomy isn't just an ivory-tower pursuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shows the interconnectedness of knowledge,'' Olson says.
``And it helps me teach them that the universe contains beautiful
things, that it's comprehensible and that you can have a great time
studying it.''
</P>
<P>
   Olson considers Tarawa his most significant discovery. Olson
found that the reason the tide didn't rise as expected, causing the
landing craft to not clear a barrier reef and 1,000 Marines to be
killed as they waded ashore in chest-deep water, was an unforeseen
and rare lunar phase that stops tides from rising or falling
significantly. Such phases occurred only twice that year, and the
Marine landing had the misfortune to be staged on one of them.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the students' assignments have been tackled by Olson and
his research partner, Russell Doescher, a Southwest Texas State
physics professor. The students don't read the professors' results
until after they have reached their own conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   One such assignment involves Lincoln's defense of a man accused
of murder, a defense made famous by a Norman Rockwell painting of
Lincoln holding an almanac. The almanac showed that the moon was
setting and near the horizon at the time of the crime, discrediting
a witness who said he saw the murder by the light of a bright, full
moon high in the sky.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, questions have been raised about the
authenticity of the almanac because townspeople testified they
recalled seeing the moon high in the sky shortly before the murder.
But as Olson discovered _ and his students learn _ because of a
phenomenon that happens once every 19 years, the moon rose and set
much quicker than normal that night, making the townspeople's
recollections consistent with the almanac's notation and clearing
Lincoln of charges of dishonesty.
</P>
<P>
   Other assignments involved Vincent van Gogh's painting ``Moon
with Cypress and Star,'' in which students figure out that the
``stars'' were actually Mercury and Venus; and Paul Revere's ride,
which was preceded by Revere sneaking past a British warship in a
rowboat thanks to an unusually low, full moon that didn't
illuminate him.
</P>
<P>
   Each class, some students take part in one original research
project. In 1996, for instance, Olson and four students traveled to
northern Mexico and found pion nut trees that Cabeza de Vaca
described in his diary. Previous histories said the trees didn't
exist in Mexico and as a result accepted an alternate route through
Central Texas that the explorer's descriptions of the moon also
indicated.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Olson and students floated down the St. Lawrence
River to test their theories about the successful British attack on
French forces located on steep cliffs above the river. The
research, conducted in the middle of a night in conditions that
were exactly the same as the battle's June 1759 night, showed Wolfe
picked a date and time when the direction of the moonlight and the
turning of the tide allowed him to sneak past the French
undetected.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, historians disagreed on whether there was even a
moon that night.
</P>
<P>
   The students who made the trips say they won't forget them. They
also say Olson's class achieved its goal: It gave them a new
appreciation of the beauty of nature, of the power of the universe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you take the class, you stop seeing references to the
moon or stars in the same way,'' says Sandra Smith, who made the
trip to Mexico. ``You see them as part of a larger story.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
