<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-TECH-TOYS25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   &HT;    Toys that play back
 &HT;    By Shelia M. Poole
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Forget G.I. Joe.
</P>
<P>
   If it doesn't send cars roaring down the streets of Los Angeles
at speeds exceeding 200 miles an hour or help Crash Bandicoot
collect crystals to save the world, then it probably won't make
Alexander Diaz's Christmas list.
</P>
<P>
   ``He probably has 20 CD-ROMs at home for his computer,'' said
Alexander's dad, Rene Diaz, owner of Atlanta-based Diaz Wholesale &AMP;
Manufacturing Co. ``He's very in tune with what's cool. Nowadays,
almost everything is high tech, and he likes interactive toys.''
</P>
<P>
   For many kids like 6-year-old Alexander, what's cool is whatever
is hot in the latest video games and high-tech toys, which include
everything from Mattel's $99.99 My Interactive Pooh that can be
programmed to say a child's name and ``remember'' her birthday, to
Playmates' Amazing Amy, a wonder doll that can tell which clothes
she should have on based on the time of day and the foods she wants
to eat. (Please don't try to feed her a banana when she said she
was thirsty, and don't try to give her breakfast at dinner time.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's kids live in a time when Dad has a beeper and Mom has
a cellular phone,'' said Christopher Byrne, a toy industry expert
and contributing editor of Playthings Marketwatch. ``Technology is
part of their universe. Technology represents the first major
innovation in the toy industry since World War II.''
</P>
<P>
   The demand for technologically advanced toys is sweeping the
$22.6 billion toy industry _ so much so that once-popular offerings
like board games are experiencing a downturn. For the first six
months of 1998, sales of board games were down 15 percent from the
same period a year earlier, according to NPD Group, a research
firm. The pressure not to be defeated by a microchip is so intense
that toy makers even have CD-ROM versions of ``Candy Land,'' ``The
Game of Life'' and ``Monopoly,'' which also has a hand-held
version.
</P>
<P>
   Amazing Amy, for instance, has touch and resistance sensors and
a microprocessor that tells her when to use more than 10,000
phrases. She also has about 500k of computer memory.
</P>
<P>
   One of the hottest toys this season is the gremlin-like Furby, a
$29.99 virtual pet that responds to touch, light, other Furbies
and, best of all, has a regular sleep pattern.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Hampton, Furby's inventor, said he got the idea after
viewing digital versions of virtual pets.
</P>
<P>
   His virtual pet, created for Tiger Electronics, is soft, furry,
and speaks ``Furbish'' and English.
</P>
<P>
   Furby interacts with his environment through some simple rules
of programming Hampton calls ``emergent behavior.'' Furby's toy
technology is possible because the creature features internal
processing power just a bit above the old Apple II, Hampton said.
``Compared to a Pentium 333 it isn't very fast, but for a toy
selling for about $30 that's not bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Even that old staple Legos has gone high tech.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the company expects its $200 Mindstorms robotics
building system, which is sold in toy and electronic stores, to be
among the season's most popular offerings.
</P>
<P>
   Mindstorms (which has its own Web site at http://www
</P>
<P>
   .legomindstorms.com) was developed with cooperation from the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology and targets kids ages 11 and
up. Youngsters build robots using a microcomputer and Lego pieces.
The creations can move and carry objects.
</P>
<P>
   Other high-tech offerings this season include:
</P>
<P>
   _ Barbie Photo Designer Digital Camera (Mattel, $69.99). Girls
can use a digital camera to take photos and see them instantly on
their computers. Away from the computer, the camera stores up to
six photos at a time.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Totally Twister'' (Hasbro, $24.99). A new take on the old
``Twister'' game. Players can use this hand-held electronic game
that has a ``cool'' voice and soundtrack to twist, turn and touch
colored buttons.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Rugrats Movie Game'' (Nintendo
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-11-24-98 1031EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
