u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-BABE-REVIEW-HNS &LR;      11-25 0864
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-BABE-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BABE' SEQUEL DARK BUT IMPRESSIVE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LOUIS B. PARKS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Halfway through the new sequel to ``Babe,'' our little pink hero
is being pursued through city streets by a vicious bull terrier
with murder in its eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Gathering all his will, the sheepherding pig suddenly turns on
his pursuer and asks a question: ``Why?''
</P>
<P>
   The question should be aimed at the makers of ``Babe: Pig in the
City.''
</P>
<P>
   Why? What were you thinking when you put so much love and
imagination and care into such a dark movie?
</P>
<P>
   The original ``Babe: The Gallant Pig'' left viewers charmed,
amused and delighted. ``Babe: Pig in the City'' may leave many
bedazzled but also depressed and befuddled.
</P>
<P>
   For grown-ups and older kids, this movie is quite impressive and
often fun, but it's also a downer for about half its length because
of the constant threat of death to the animals.
</P>
<P>
   Technically, ``Pig in the City'' far surpasses the original
``Babe.'' It is a breathtaking visual-effects triumph. The effects
are so good at making the absurdly impossible look casually natural
that most viewers may not even be impressed.
</P>
<P>
   In sheer imagination, ``Pig in the City'' is also good,
constantly surprising us with wonderful images and unexpected
events.
</P>
<P>
   But what starts out as charming and bright soon turns into a
surrealistic nightmare fantasy that is fascinating but also
disturbing.
</P>
<P>
   How this movie ever got a G rating is a mystery to me. There is
no sex, serious violence, bad language or drugs, but the atmosphere
and tone, something that should count with the ratings board, is
sometimes too oppressive for sensitive young children.
</P>
<P>
   The movie is like a Grimm's fairy tale before Disney took out
the grim. Such impressions are highly subjective of course, and you
_ or your children _ may not feel that way at all.
</P>
<P>
   The film may be a miscalculation, but it is beautifully done. It
begins with a storybook opening in which we learn that Babe, after
coming home a hero (from the first movie) accidentally causes great
injury to Farmer Hoggett (again played by James Cromwell, though
the role is much smaller this time).
</P>
<P>
   Bills begin to pile up, and in order to save the farm, Esme
Hoggett (Magda Szubanski), the farmer's wife, decides she must take
Babe to a big city where he can earn money performing at a fair.
Babe does not want to go, but the other animals tell him he must.
</P>
<P>
   Babe and Esme arrive in the big city (no country or city is
designated, though it looks a lot like Manhattan from the air.)
They immediately run into a series of mishaps, some of them
amusing. Broke and without a job, they finally end up in a
European-looking midcity hotel that secretly caters to animals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is he house-trained,'' the proprietor asks about Babe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, just like you and me,'' Esme says.
</P>
<P>
   Babe looks out the hotel window on the magnificent city and sees
the Eiffel Tower, the Sydney Opera House, the Statue of Liberty,
the Hollywood sign and other familiar landmarks. It's truly a
cosmopolitan metropolis.
</P>
<P>
   Babe and Esme are soon separated _ she's thrown in jail _ and
Babe finds himself and all the other animals of the house,
including different types of apes, dogs, cats and fish _ chased and
then captured by animal control. It is up to Babe to rescue one and
all from danger, which, be assured, he does.
</P>
<P>
   It is necessary to say that there ``is'' a happy ending, because
at times in this film we begin to doubt it, so borderline grim does
the movie become.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the following.
</P>
<P>
   A dog falls off a bridge and is left hanging by his back paw,
head in the water. He struggles and struggles. As the other animals
watch him drowning, one says ``don't look'' and turns away.
Finally, Babe comes to the rescue, but only after a long, painful
scene in which it seems the dog has drowned.
</P>
<P>
   In another scene, a handicapped dog with a wheelchair under his
hind legs is pulled by a truck through dangerous traffic, then
flies off and crashes, lying crumpled in a heap. He goes off into a
near-death experience _ a clever idea _ in which he has four
working legs. He survives, but only after we have been dragged
through an intensely sad moment.
</P>
<P>
   In yet another, a goldfish must struggle out of water, gasping
for life. Babe is stolen by a scary clown. And so on.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, ``Pig in the City's'' imaginative settings
and special effects aren't to be missed. There are times when the
images bring to mind such dark fantasies as Terry Gilliam's
``Brazil'' or the French ``The City of Lost Children,'' both
brilliantly designed films.
</P>
<P>
   What the animals say and do is sometimes wonderfully comic and
endearing. The Hoggett farm, seen all too briefly, is even more of
a pastoral fantasy than before.
</P>
<P>
   While many kids will have no problem with the movie, parents may
need to reassure small, sensitive children that everything will
work out fine, eventually. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Babe: Pig in the City &QL; 
Starring: Magda Szubanski, James Cromwell, Mickey Rooney &QL; 
Rated: G (but the film may be scary to young children)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
