<HEADLINE>
TIPS ON BUYING A COMPUTER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID HOYE   c.1998 The Arizona Republic   UNDATED - Ready or
not, here come the holidays!
<TEXT>
<P>
   For many people, this year's holiday season will involve buying
a new desktop computer for home use.
</P>
<P>
   If you ask me, there's never been a better time to take the
computing plunge. Today's models offer an exciting array of
features, whether you're in the market for a sub-$1,000 machine or
a top-of-the-line, bleeding-edge technology screamer!
</P>
<P>
   Trouble is, buying a new home computer can be tricky. And nobody
wants to mess up when $1,000 or more is on the line.
</P>
<P>
   So, here are some tips, suggestions and rules of thumb you might
want to review before heading out to spend your hard-earned money:
</P>
<P>
   - Think about how you would use a computer. Surfing the Internet
doesn't require a powerful machine, but graphics work or playing
the latest 3D games need all the power you can afford. Talk with
friends who have computers. Check software stores for titles you
might want to use, and look for the ``minimum requirements'' listed
on the box.
</P>
<P>
   - PC or Macintosh? This is something you'll need to decide for
yourself. Most of the world uses PCs running Windows 95 or Windows
98. But many students, artists and others swear by the ease of use
offered by the Macintosh. Go with your gut on this one.
</P>
<P>
   - Set yourself a budget. This will help keep you from being
talked into buying something you don't need. A good beginning
system shouldn't cost more than $1,250, including monitor. In fact,
many decent systems cost hundreds of dollars less. (See the
following tip.) Midrange systems cost between $1,250 and $2,000.
The best systems run from $2,000 to $3,000.
</P>
<P>
   - Looking to buy the cheapest computer you can find? OK, but
make sure you know what you're getting. I've seen some systems
advertised for less than $400, but they don't come with monitors,
CD-ROMs, modems or even operating systems! Here's something to look
for: IBM has just announced the Aptiva D1N, a system with a
suggested retail price of $599. It doesn't come with a monitor, but
it sounds like a decent beginning computer. Learn more at
www.pc.ibm.com/us/aptiva /aptivad1n.html (that's an underscore in
front of `d1n').
</P>
<P>
   - Educate yourself. I'm not suggesting you take a college
course. But you'd be surprised how much you can pick up by spending
a couple weeks reading through some computer magazines or talking
with people who use computers.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, start scanning computer ads. Soon, the lingo won't
sound so weird, and you'll get an idea of the things most computers
contain and how much similar systems cost.
</P>
<P>
   Ask friends, relatives and co-workers what kinds of computers
they have at home. Ask them where they bought their machines, what
brand they own and whether they'd do anything differently the next
time.
</P>
<P>
   Visit a couple of computer stores just to try out their
computers on display. This will give you an idea of how the models
vary, what different keyboards feel like and whether you can do
without that expensive 17-inch monitor.
</P>
<P>
   Don't expect to get your education from the salesman on duty.
They won't have the time to answer your questions, and, if they do,
they probably won't give you the best answers.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, if you don't have time to educate yourself, at least
find a computer-savvy friend who can help you choose the right
computer.
</P>
<P>
   - Be brave. No matter where you end up buying, chances are you
will encounter at least one condescending salesman. I don't know
why. But you should expect it.
</P>
<P>
   This person will try hard to make you feel stupid and probably
will act as though he or she doesn't have time for you unless
you're ready to plunk down your Visa card, buy a computer and
quickly leave the store.
</P>
<P>
   Remain calm. Know that this happens to everybody, regardless of
how much _ or how little _ they know about computers. Be prepared
to turn around and walk out (or hang up the phone) if a salesman
refuses to treat you properly.
</P>
<P>
   - Use common sense. Don't expect a department store that sells
sofas and washing machines to offer a wide variety of computers or
have a sales staff that knows much about them. The best sources of
computers and software are always those places that do nothing else
but sell computers and software.
</P>
<P>
   - Computers are like houses _ you should buy the biggest you can
afford. Believe me, you will grow into every nook and cranny your
computer offers. It's better to have a little extra to begin with
than to wish you had a better computer just six months down the
road.
</P>
<P>
   - If you ask me, beginners do best buying a name-brand computer
from a major retail store, such as CompUSA, or from a major
mail-order outlet, such as Gateway or Dell.
</P>
<P>
   - Technical support, service and reliability are everything,
because chances are something will go wrong. Make sure you can get
help seven days a week, 24-hours a day. The November issue of ``PC
World'' magazine rated Dell, IBM, Micron, Quantex, CyberMax and
Sony as tops. Compaq, Gateway, Hewlett-Packard and NEC were
average. AST and Packard Bell were rated poor. Acer was dubbed
`unacceptable.'
</P>
<P>
   - Call me short-sighted, but I don't think DVD drives and
television tuner cards are worth the money. I just don't see a big
need for such capability _ at least not yet. If you buy a $3,000
computer to watch DVD movies, you have way too much disposable
income. Most buyers would be better off putting the money into a
bigger monitor or a good printer or scanner.
</P>
<P>
   - Speaking of which: No home system is worth much without a good
printer. And if you have kids or you plan any kind of graphics
work, you should invest in a good flatbed scanner. These days, you
should be able to find a quality color inkjet printer for $300 or
less. A decent scanner will cost about $125.
</P>
<P>
   - Make sure that computer you are buying is NEW! This sounds
obvious, but some retail outlets have been known to repackage used
equipment and resell it as new. They are very good with the
shrink-wrap machine, so it's not always easy to spot used stuff. If
it's refurbished, it should be marked as such, and should not cost
as much as new.
</P>
<P>
   - Fourteen-inch monitors are long gone, leaving 15-inchers the
standard size with preconfigured systems. But if you can afford it,
get yourself a 17-inch monitor. You will enjoy computing more,
because you'll be able to see more at once, use larger fonts (if
you need to) and many other things. The 17-inchers are everywhere
these days, and for good reason.
</P>
<P>
   - Do what you want, but if it was up to me, you'd never buy one
of those extended warranties. They are pure profit for the
retailer. Most brand-name machines come with their own warranties,
which last from one to three years. Some even come with on-site
repair service. If it ain't broke after three years, it'll be
outdated. So tell the salesman ``NO'' when the subject of an
extended warranty comes up.
</P>
<P>
   - Be polite, but refuse when your brother or his friend or the
guy down the street offers to build you a new system ``real
cheap.'' So he saves you money? Will he be around every time you
have a question? Will he guarantee his work? What software will he
provide? And if serious problems arise you'll want to demand
immediate service, not worry that you'll offend some relative or
damage a friendship.
</P>
<P>
   - If you buy a new computer and it goes south within the first
30 days, TAKE IT BACK. Demand a full refund or a new system. If you
let them start fiddling with bits and pieces of a faulty system,
you are asking for trouble. And some companies will even force you
to accept refurbished equipment to complete the repairs. Don't even
go there!
</P>
<P>
   That's about it. Have fun!
</P>
<P>
   Oh, one more thing: Last week I promised to print some of your
feelings about Microsoft's new Internet Explorer 5.0 and the
Microsoft antitrust trial going on in Washington, D.C. As you can
see, I ran out of room this week. So look for the comments next
week! &QL; 
David Hoye can be reached at dhoye(at)pni.com by e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-11-23-98 1634EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-25-98 1115EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
