<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-25 11:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8862 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-DEVILS-ISLAND-     11-25 1458
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-DEVILS-ISLAND-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER PENAL COLONY SHEDS DEADLY REPUTATION TO BECOME TOURIST
HAUNT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN OTIS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEVIL'S ISLANDS, French Guiana _ Henri Charriere, better-known
as Papillon, spent many of his days at the notorious penal colony
here pacing back and forth in his solitary-confinement cell,
swallowing cockroaches to survive and dreaming of escape.
</P>
<P>
   The way Charriere tells it, he eventually floated to freedom
through shark-infested waters on a raft made of coconut shells.
</P>
<P>
   Today, visitors to the Devil's Islands _ three palm-lined
volcanic keys seven miles off the Atlantic coast of French Guiana
in South America _ have it a lot easier.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, forced labor is out. Tourists can wander freely
through the guard quarters, solitary-confinement cells and
graveyards of the old prison camp. The only permanent inhabitants
are pigs, roosters, squirrel monkeys and palm rats that wander
among the mango and guava trees.
</P>
<P>
   Meager prisoner's rations have given way to fine French cuisine
served in the former warden's hall. The bar, once decorated with
frescoes painted by inmates, serves ``convict's punch'' at happy
hour. Accommodations are in the remodeled guards' bungalows.
</P>
<P>
   And escape no longer requires a homemade raft, just a ticket for
the passenger ferry back to the mainland.
</P>
<P>
   A sort of tropical Alcatraz, the Devil's Islands are both
fascinating and horrifying. The penal colony inspired such
Hollywood films as ``Papillon, Passage to Marseille'' and
``Condemned to Devil's Island.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The objective was not to exterminate the prisoners, but many
of them died from neglect or due to the incompetence (of prison
officials),'' said Alexander Miles, who has written a book about
the Devil's Islands. ``It was nothing to be proud of.''
</P>
<P>
   From the mainland of French Guiana, getting to the islands
requires a 90-minute ferry ride from the coastal town of Kourou.
Royal Island, larger and better maintained than St. Joseph's Island
and Devil's Island, is the first stop. A small, whitewashed museum
with an array of enlarged black-and-white photographs and drawings
outlines the islands' history.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their sinister reputation, the Devil's Islands were a
lifeline for newly arrived settlers in French Guiana in the 1700s.
Cooled by trade winds, they provided safe haven and a healthier
climate at a time when malaria and other tropical diseases were
spreading on the mainland. Their original name was Les les du Salut
_ the Salvation Islands. (Some guidebooks, including Lonely
Planet's comprehensive ``South America'' reference, still use this
designation.)
</P>
<P>
   When the colonial economy collapsed after the abolition of
slavery in 1848, France opted to develop and people French Guiana
with convicts ready to pay their debt to society through work. The
inspiration came from England, which had colonized Australia with
prisoners at the end of the 18th century.
</P>
<P>
   Thus a series of work camps were built on the Devil's Islands
and on the mainland. But as a development project, the penal colony
failed miserably.
</P>
<P>
   During one 20-year stretch, for example, convict road-building
crews managed to construct just 15 miles of highway.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't all their fault. Prisoners were ravaged by epidemics
and weakened by the workload, the equatorial heat, malnutrition and
poor hygiene. Of the 8,000 prisoners sent to French Guiana between
1852 and 1856, just 3,600 survived.
</P>
<P>
   The worst conditions were on St. Joseph's Island, site of the
solitary-confinement cells. Although the iron bars are rusty and
the cells are infested with vines and moss, they remain a chilling
sight. Barred ceilings allowed guards to keep a constant watch on
the prisoners, who were forbidden to make the slightest sound.
</P>
<P>
   Anthelme Girier, ringleader of an inmate uprising in 1894, began
a hunger strike to protest.
</P>
<P>
   ``To escape from your torture, I resolved to starve to death,''
Girier wrote. ``This will give you an idea of how much we have had
to suffer. ... I beg you to remove my chains and let me die in
peace next to my bread rations.''
</P>
<P>
   Those with sentences of more than eight years were required to
live in exile in French Guiana for a period equal to their
sentences, a cruel system known as ``doublage.'' The policy kept
such unwanteds from returning to the mother country and helped to
maintain the population of French Guiana, which is now an overseas
department of France.
</P>
<P>
   More than anything, the islands were a convenient, far-off place
for France to stash troublesome political prisoners, people
suffering from leprosy and other undesirables.
</P>
<P>
   The most famous was Alfred Dreyfus, a French Army colonel who
was accused of selling military secrets to the Germans and sent to
Devil's Island, the smallest of the three keys, in 1895.
</P>
<P>
   His deportation ignited a polemic debate in Paris. French
authorities were so concerned about a possible escape or rescue
attempt that they built a watchtower and a 9-foot-high wall around
his hut. Dreyfus was released in 1899 after the publication of a
Emile Zola's ``J'accuse,'' a lengthy essay defending Dreyfus.
</P>
<P>
   Dreyfus' bench, a rock formation where he meditated, still sits
on the north end of the island. But because of treacherous ocean
currents and the lack of a suitable landing site for boats, the
French government has banned travel to this island.
</P>
<P>
   From all three islands, escape was nearly impossible. Those who
tried are thought to have drowned or been eaten by sharks. And
despite Charriere's dramatic getaway story in ``Papillon,'' some
historians claim that he actually fled from a prison camp in the
capital city of Cayenne on the mainland _ a much easier task.
</P>
<P>
   The only documented escape was pulled off by Charles de Rudio,
who was dispatched to the islands for his part in an assassination
attempt against Emperor Napoleon III. De Rudio eventually made his
way to the United States, where he enlisted in the Army and was one
of the few survivors of the Battle of the Little Bighorn.
</P>
<P>
   More than 67,000 prisoners were sent to the penal colony before
it was closed in 1946 in response to international protests over
the harsh conditions. But its legacy lives on. Many freed
prisoners, with nowhere to go, found jobs on the mainland as
servants, carpenters, gardeners and bricklayers.
</P>
<P>
   They weren't always welcome. Pierre Servini, a historian who
lives in Cayenne, says that as a boy he used to shoot his slingshot
at vagabond ex-cons sleeping in the streets. ``They were like
dogs,'' Servini said.
</P>
<P>
   Gradually the freed prisoners blended into society. Today a
number of residents are relatives of ex-cons, including the mayor
of St.-Laurent-du-Maroni, a colonial town on the border with
Suriname where prisoners just off the boat from France were
registered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Times have changed,'' said Robert Rivial, who runs a hotel in
St.-Laurent-du-Maroni. ``Now people are proud of their heritage.
They boast about it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Many were employed as farm help or else they got married,''
said Lithaw Flore, a retired accountant and town council member.
</P>
<P>
   The penal-colony ruins are especially well-preserved in
St.-Laurent-du-Maroni, and visitors can lie down on the cement bed
in Cell 47, Charriere's initial way station before he was sent to
the islands. In an abandoned shed under a plastic tarp lies a
disassembled guillotine that was used to execute prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   The town also is home to the last survivor of the penal colony,
98-year-old Mauhamed Bachir.
</P>
<P>
   A Moroccan who served a 20-year sentence resulting from a
``family dispute'' that he doesn't want to explain, Bachir did his
time, then opened a small grocery store. He is partially deaf,
nearly blind, wears thick glasses and has just one tooth, making
conversation nearly impossible.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mauhamed was a very generous person. He had his corner store.
If you ever needed something, he would give you four or five
cigarettes. He was a good man,'' says one of Bachir's relatives,
who wouldn't give his name.
</P>
<P>
   For all the horrors of the penal colony, many people in French
Guiana look back with fondness. ``During the time of the penal
colony, St.-Laurent was alive. But when it closed, everyone shut
their shops and left,'' Flore said. ``It was the end.''
</P>
<P>
   But on the Devil's Islands, the penal colony has given way to
tourism and technology.
</P>
<P>
   Royal Island houses a cinetheodolite for infrared tracking of
satellite-laden rockets that are launched every month from the
European Space Agency complex near Kourou. And every day, hundreds
of visitors descend on the islands to explore the old prison and
pay homage to Papillon.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
