</HEADLINE>
 
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   &HT;    It's that time of year for `best of' lists
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ You can always tell the holiday season is around the
corner when computer magazines start running the ``best of'' lists.
The first out of the gate this year is PC World, which features the
best computer CDs and DVDs in its December issue. The magazine's
top 10 titles include Microsoft's Encarta Reference Suite 99, an
electronic encyclopedia that retails for $100. Other picks include
Access Software's golf game ``Links LS 1999,'' Blizzard
Entertainment's ``StarCraft'' and National Geographic Maps from
Mindscape.
</P>
<P>
   In the same issue of PC World, the magazine's editors decided to
test a boast by Apple's Steve Jobs that his new iMac was faster
than the quickest Pentium II PC. They pitted the iMac against the
most expensive Pentium and a system that was $300 less than the
iMac, which retails for $1,299. The iMac finished last in every
test against both of these PCs. The magazine concluded Jobs' boast
was ``pure hype.'' It did find, though, the iMac is indeed the
easiest computer to set up and get going on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   On CD-ROM
</P>
<P>
   If rock musicians can do it, how about the star of a 1980s video
game? Hasbro Interactive is hoping so in its re-release of
``Centipede'' in the form of a computer CD. ``Centipede'' made its
debut as an Atari video game. Now Hasbro has souped it up with 3-D
graphics and new game play. Now you don't just blow away the evil
Centipedes but must also rescue the Wee People threatened by them.
Available only for PCs with operating systems Windows 95 or newer,
``Centipede'' retails for about $40.
</P>
<P>
   These days, it seems you're never too young for your first
computer game. For the holiday season, Fisher-Price has released a
new game for children as young as three. It's called the ``Little
People Christmas Activity Center.'' The game is a two-computer CD
set that lets kids make holiday cards, gift tags and wrapping
paper. There also are printing activities and other games. The game
works with both PCs and Macs and retails for $9.99 if you buy
another Fisher-Price title.
</P>
<P>
   Online
</P>
<P>
   It's the dawn of the holiday season but not everyone is happy.
Just check out the Web. Sadly, it has become a breeding ground for
hate groups. Now you can keep up with what sites to avoid and steer
your children clear of. The site is called Hatewatch. You'll find
it at http://www.hatewatch.org.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-11-23-98 1040EST &QL;
</P>
