<HEADER>
A8876 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARRIED-CATHOLIC-CLER     11-25 0885
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARRIED-CATHOLIC-CLERGY-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CATHOLIC BISHOP COURAGEOUSLY CALLS FOR 'MARRIED CLERGY' 
</HEADLINE>
   (Commentary)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (Mike McManus is a syndicated columnist whose ``Ethics &AMP;
Religion'' appears in almost 100 newspapers)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative NIRDI
RELIS in New York at (800) 972-3550 or (212) 499-3333, or fax her
at (212) 499-3382.)  
 &HT;    
 By MIKE McMANUS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    In a thoughtful pastoral letter published by his diocesan
newspaper, Catholic Bishop Raymond Lucker of New Ulm, Minn., has
called for a change in the church law of priestly celibacy, which
would create ''the option of married clergy.''
 &HT;    ''Nothing causes me greater concern than the shortage of
priests,'' he writes. In his largely rural diocese, there were 71
priests in 1988. That number fell to 53 by 1997 to serve 83
parishes. Some priests were asked to serve two or three parishes.
 &HT;    Bishop Lucker pioneered another answer by appointing 20 pastoral
administrators, mostly nuns. But they can not celebrate Mass, hear
confessions, etc.
 &HT;    Many lay people have asked Lucker, ''Why can't we have married
priests?'' His response: ''The law of celibacy is a church law
which can be changed. It is not something that came to us from the
revelation of God or from the command of Jesus.
 &HT;    ``Celibacy has been a universal rule in the Western church only
since the 11th century,'' Lucker points out. ``As we all know,
Peter, the head of the Apostles and leader of the Church of Rome,
was married. The Catholic Church has married priests in the Eastern
Rite,'' such as the Ukrainian Catholic Church.
 &HT;    Also, 200 former Episcopalian priests have converted to
Catholicism, and brought their wives and children.
 &HT;    ''In view of the pressing shortage of the clergy ... would it
not be better to change the law of celibacy? I believe that we
ought to change the law and have the option of married clergy,''
Lucker wrote. ''But no individual bishop can change the law. There
would have to be a modification of the law of the universal
church.''
 &HT;    Under Pope John Paul II, that will not happen. He has made it
clear that the subject is closed, and he has told bishops they are
not to speak about the possibility of change, though a few have
done so, such as Milwaukee Archbishop Rembert Weakland.
 &HT;    However, the pressure for change is growing. In Austria last
month, a national assembly of lay leaders appointed by the bishops
debated church policies and then put them to a vote -- the first
such assembly in the world.
 &HT;    More than 75 percent of delegates endorsed ordination for
married men, freedom for couples to choose which method of birth
control to use, allowing divorced and remarried Catholics the right
to receive the sacraments, the right of parish councils to make
decisions without the priest's blessing, and a greater local role
in selecting bishops.
 &HT;    The Austrian bishops were pressured to take this step by a lay
movement called ''We Are Church,'' which garnered a half million
signatures demanding such reforms.
 &HT;    The closest parallel in America is a group, ''Call to Action,''
19,000 lay Catholic who have called for similar reforms. Its
president, Linda Pieczynski, said, ''We are very supportive of
Bishop Lucker's call for an end to mandatory celibacy, which we
have called for since 1991.'' However, Call to Action has not even
considered organizing something like Austria's national assembly.
 &HT;    Lucker's courageous stand has received some press coverage. Last
week, when he attended the National Catholic Conference of Bishops,
he had dinner with 15 bishops, all of whom were in favor of
allowing priests to marry. Every bishop who spoke to him was
supportive, he said.
 &HT;    But when I asked some bishops for their reactions, they were
either noncommittal or were supportive, but did not want me to use
their name. The pope has intimidated them.
 &HT;    There is a darker side of this picture. A careful study of 1,500
priests by A.W. Richard Sipe, who was ordained as a Catholic priest
but later left to marry and to become a psychotherapist, came to a
shocking conclusion: ''At any one time no better than 50 percent of
priests are practicing celibacy. About 25 percent are
heterosexually active, 20 percent are homosexually active and 6
percent are sexually involved with minors.''
 &HT;    Details of his study can be found in Sipe's books, such as
''Sex, Priests and Power: Anatomy of a Crisis.''
 &HT;    Those numbers may seem impossibly high. But 23,000 priests have
left the priesthood to marry. And more than 1,000 priests have
confessed that they have molested children, including at least one
sitting bishop. The church has had to pay hundreds of millions of
dollars in damages.
 &HT;    The scandal of priests who are not practicing celibacy combined
with the acute shortage of priests and their exhaustion in trying
to serve 10 times as many parishioners as an average Protestant
pastor demands an end to mandatory celibacy.
 &HT;    When will the National Conference of Catholic Bishops put this
issue on its agenda?
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ----
 &HT;    c.1998 Mike McManus
<TEXT>
<P>
</P>
