<SLUG> BC-CPT-NETWATCH24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   &HT;    Some communities are more orderly than others
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ ``Community'' is a word that gets tossed around on the
Web almost as much as ``portal,'' ``commerce'' and ``IPO.''
However, if you ask three Web pundits what community is, you're
likely to get three different answers.
</P>
<P>
   TheGlobe.com (http://www.theglobe.com), GeoCities
(http://www.geocities.com), Tripod (http://www.tripod
</P>
<P>
   .com) and local sites such as AccessAtlanta
(http://www.accessatlanta.com) each invite users to build
special-interest home pages, add chat rooms and build a presence on
the Web. But while community has become the buzzword du jour, even
the folks at the Mining Company (http://www.miningco
</P>
<P>
   .com), which pioneered the notion of a networked collection of
special-interest Web sites, have trouble defining community.
</P>
<P>
   ``Community is a much misunderstood concept,'' says Amanda Hass,
who works on program and community development for the Mining
Company. ``There's a lot of buzz about community, but if there
isn't a responsible guide in charge, that's not community, that's
anarchy.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mining Company aims for a more professional look and feel to
its sites and encourages its guides to build out their sites with
incentives. So far, the results have been good: Media Metrix ranks
the Mining Company the eighth most popular site on the Web in the
information/entertainment/news category.
</P>
<P>
   The Mining Company believes hiring experienced guides to develop
and maintain special-interest sites is the answer to the anarchy of
random personal pages with no clear voice directing the information
on the site. The company recruits guides expert in areas ranging
from pregnancy and politics to rock music and rodeos, puts them
through a three-week online training period, then helps them set up
sites that provide users with chat, links, articles and even an
e-mailed newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   At last count, there were 642 guides with sites on the Mining
Company site. A recent peek at a site devoted to the impeachment
hearings assembled by guide Tim Hosfeldt is one of the most
complete collections of information and background on the Starr
investigation on the Web. Sites devoted to Canadian news and the
Beatles are equally comprehensive. If you need information, you'll
probably be able to find something you can use from a Mining
Company site.
</P>
<P>
   The people who run the Mining Company's sites do it because they
love their subject matter, but there's also monetary compensation.
Guides get 40 percent of advertising revenue and transactions made
via partnerships with companies like online bookseller Amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   If you define online community as a group of people who may or
may not know each other drawn together by an interest in a
particular subject, then the Mining Company is certainly a
community. However, as Hass points out, ``We were revolutionary
when we launched, but now more and more people are moving toward
our model.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, she says she sees no immediate threats from any community
sites or wannabes. ``We pioneered the model that made (the other
sites) possible. The problem is getting users to find you and love
you.''
</P>
<P>
   What's New
</P>
<P>
   NASA: The agency that takes us into space has also given us Tang
and freeze-dried ice cream. Discover the myriad other things it
does _ from studying meteors to helping to preserve the original
``Star-Spangled Banner'' _ at this slick, professional site.
</P>
<P>
   http://www.nasa.gov/
</P>
<P>
   Parenthood Web: Packed with polls, news, features and bulletin
boards, this is a well-rounded site for new parents and
parents-to-be. Most of the resources focus on babies and young
children, but a few of the articles are addressed to parents of
older kids.
</P>
<P>
   http://www.parenthoodweb.com/
</P>
<P>
   Surfing the Net With Kids: This site offers weekly selections of
the best kid sites in a variety of topics, reviewed and rated by
Barbara Feldman. Each week's collection serves up the best sites in
a particular topic, from dinosaurs to ghost stories to Beanie
Babies.
</P>
<P>
   http://www.surfnetkids.com/
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
