<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-25 11:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8881 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-CYBERSCENE24-COX &LR;      11-25 0640
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-CYBERSCENE24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   &HT;    Map sites on Web make charting your life easier
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ With the help of a map, most of us can get very
confused.
</P>
<P>
   But there are times when a map actually helps. You'll find maps
on the Web that will plot your route across town or across the
country. But the many sites on the Net that offer maps offer a lot
more than that. Many of the maps can be copied and then pasted into
homework assignments for geography and others offer you a chance to
better understand news stories that happen half a world away.
</P>
<P>
   Let's start our trip through the maps of the Web at a couple of
sites that offer help driving to a new location. One of the best is
MapQuest at http://www.mapquest.com. You can use the site without
joining, but you'll get additional services once you're a member.
Since membership is free, go ahead and enroll.
</P>
<P>
   One of the best features of the page is its ability to plot a
turn-by-turn course to a destination anywhere in the country.
Besides the map, you'll get a text description of the turns to
take. In fact, since the maps are relatively small and don't show
much detail (you can zoom in for more detail but sometimes end up
with a map that doesn't cover a large enough area to be helpful),
you'll find that the text is the best way to use the navigational
information.
</P>
<P>
   The routes plotted seem to be accurate and do a good job of
following a logical route. However, if you are familiar with an
area, you probably know a better way. However, if you're familiar
with an area, you probably don't need the map in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   Another service that offers much the same service is AltaVista
Maps, run by the search engine company of the same name, at
http://maps.altavista.com/cgi-bin/mapcgi. Even though you probably
won't find much difference between the routes provided by these two
sites, it's handy to bookmark both. These are high traffic sites
and you may want an option if one site is particularly slow because
of online traffic.
</P>
<P>
   The next site _ called Create A Map at http://www.aquarius
</P>
<P>
   .geomar.de/omc/ _ may not be as useful in day-to-day life but is
enormous fun. You can build your own maps using this excellent
German site (most of the text here is in English as well as German
so you shouldn't have any trouble using the site) and manipulate
the way the map is displayed.
</P>
<P>
   You can, for instance, enter coordinates in latitude and
longitude and then select the map you want, including a
topographical map that shows ridges and features of the Earth. You
can also tell the site to include city names or to leave them out.
It's my guess that you'll spend a lot of time practicing map-making
here. And if you have children, this is a great way to teach them
geography.
</P>
<P>
   If you've ever searched the Web for online maps, you know that
the place is the world's greatest repository of maps. So the ones
we've mentioned just scratch the surface of what's available.
That's why the next Web site is an enormous help for anyone
interested in maps.
</P>
<P>
   It's called Online Map Resources, and it is located at
http://www.geog.ukans.edu/map.htm. You'll find a plain-vanilla page
here that is filled with links to various places on the Web where
you'll find maps. You can, for instance, at the click of a mouse go
to the excellent University of Texas map site at
http://www.lib.utexas.edu/Libs/PCL/Mapcollection/Map
</P>
<P>
   collection.html. There also are links to the Harvard University
map site at http://icg.harvard.edu/(tilde)maps/ and dozens of
others.
</P>
<P>
   Maps, you'll find, are a pleasant way to lose yourself for
hours.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
