decreed her unfit to hold her job as executive director of Temple
Beth David in Palm Beach Gardens. She is, after all, a committed
Jew. She has dedicated her professional life to the Jewish
community and her personal life raising two observant children. But
she married a Catholic. And as far as the highest rabbinical
assembly in the Conservative movement is concerned, that means she
cannot be a positive role model. By Belkin
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-COLUMN-NYT (Undated) _ When leaders of major religious
organizations believe their flocks to be facing a matter of
overarching importance, they may decide guidance is best given
through a formal pastoral statement, a nuanced and reflective
document sent to all congregations under their care. At least two
such messages were published this week, one by the nation's Roman
Catholic bishops, the other by the president of a Protestant
denomination. Each, in its own quite separate way, addressed the
question of how Christians should act in the larger society. By
Gustav Niebuhr.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   STARR-PEPPERDINE (Malibu, Calif.) _ Pepperdine University's
public courtship of Kenneth Starr as dean has brought unusual
attention to a law school that says it is one of the most committed
of perhaps a dozen in America that say their mission is to
incorporate the values of Jesus Christ into the law. A visit to the
law school provided a glimpse of the origins of Starr's attitudes
about morality and the law. By William Glaberson. Photo.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
