<HEADLINE>
FOREIGN STUDENTS DISCOVER AN AMERICAN THANKSGIVING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL LOPEZ  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TROY, N.Y. _ It is easy to see why the Siebels family and
Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute graduate students Itty Matthew and
Anurag Jain have become friends.
</P>
<P>
   Carl and Kath Siebels relate to the two students, both from
India, in an easygoing yet somewhat parental way, and invite them
to their rural Rensselaer County home for casual spur-of-the-moment
pizza, for instance, and, now, for Thanksgiving.
</P>
<P>
   Matthew and Jain are excellent cooks, and the Siebels look
forward to Indian cuisine every couple of months.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the Siebels family and the two students will spend
their second Thanksgiving together, sitting down for a dinner of
turkey, dressing, and pumpkin and apple pies.
</P>
<P>
   Matthew, 25, from Madras, and Jain, 23, from Delhi, have quickly
absorbed the uniquely American holiday of Thanksgiving. The
straightforward concepts, of spending time with family, and of
thankfulness, are not lost on either.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very unique, because, in my opinion, almost all of the
U.S. comes to a stop, to spend time with family. You don't see that
happen very often,'' Matthew said.
</P>
<P>
   The Indian holiday most likely similar to Thanksgiving is Onam,
an August harvest festival, but not one celebrated universally.
</P>
<P>
   The two are part of a year-round volunteer program that seeks to
broaden the American experience of international students. While
these American hosts and students may go camping or cross-country
skiing throughout the year, Thanksgiving is one of the more popular
and natural holidays for their get-togethers.
</P>
<P>
   The Siebels' Thanksgiving could not sound more typical or
comforting: attending the Turkey Trot road race with their three
daughters, Erika, 20, Talia, 19 and Elke, 15, then catching part of
the televised Macy's parade. Dinner is always at 1 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   For Jain, studying chemical engineering and electronics at
Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute for more than two years, this is
the only traditional Thanksgiving he has known.
</P>
<P>
   Matthew has been in the United States longer, studying at the
University of Delaware before transferring to Rensselaer about two
years ago. He is earning a doctorate in material science, a field
that explores how, in the computer age, materials are tailored to
different uses.
</P>
<P>
   In his four years in the United States, Matthew has had a chance
to taste Thanksgiving alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the Thanksgivings, I remember being the lone person,
working in a building that normally houses 500 people,'' Matthew
said of his time attending the University of Delaware. That day, he
wrote a term paper, and visited the soda machine a couple of times.
``I think even the 7-Eleven was closed that day.''
</P>
<P>
   He was determined not to spend another Thanksgiving that way, so
he visited a cousin in Connecticut one year, and, last year, hosted
an out-of-town friend for Thanksgiving, Indian style, with lots of
spicy lamb.
</P>
<P>
   Horizons International, the volunteer effort that introduced the
Siebels and the doctoral students, is designed to ward off the
isolation Matthew experienced on that early Thanksgiving.
</P>
<P>
   Matthew and Jain are among about 120 students at Rensselaer
Polytechnic Institute and the nearby state University of New York
at Albany who are matched with American families through the
volunteer group. Horizons aims to cultivate friendships between
Americans and adult international students, from dozens of
different countries.
</P>
<P>
   Although Horizons has grown from the involvement of 20 or 30
churches, the program is secular.
</P>
<P>
   ``International students come here and they're relatively
isolated within the campus community,'' said Mark Harkness, a
graduate of Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute and a General Electric
Co. engineer who helped expand the program a decade ago. Typically,
these students may return home after several years without ever
having an American's name in their address book, Harkness said.
</P>
<P>
   Both Matthew and Jain guess that their contact with everyday
Americans would be rare, if they had not purposely done something
about it. To reinforce the point, Matthew mimics the ``forced
smile.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People are very polite and friendly as long as it's within the
small domain of 8 a.m. to 4:30 p.m. at work,'' said Matthew, a
teaching assistant. ``After that, it's like everybody goes back to
their own black hole.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kath Siebels calls her friendship with Jain and Matthew ``a real
relationship.'' It wouldn't be unusual to sometimes find the young
men flopped in the living room, rested and full, after dinner. The
two were the first to send flowers last year when the Siebels
celebrated their 25th wedding anniversary. And, Matthew makes a
small but telling point when he mentions how much he looks forward
to Kath's cheesecake, served on Thanksgiving.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, they'll sit down to Thanksgiving dinner, and won't
lack for conversation.
</P>
<P>
   ``All human beings go through the same struggles and have the
same wants and needs, across civilization, across time,'' Matthew
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
