<SLUG> BC-HOLIDAY-DIET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DECK THE HALLS BUT HOLD THE CALORIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SYLVIA WOOD  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   'Tis the season for overindulgence.
</P>
<P>
   The average American gains five to 10 pounds at this time of
year, according to Tammy Baker, a spokeswoman for the American
Dietetic Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot more high-calorie food around,'' she said.
``It's difficult to resist.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, as most of us know, it's easier to put the weight
on than take it off. The goal shouldn't be to lose weight. Food
experts agree that now is the wrong time to start a diet. Instead,
they suggest trying to keep ahead of those extra pounds with some
healthy tips that work year-round.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of pressure to eat this time of year,'' said
Nancie Segel of Food Management, a service near Albany, N.Y., that
uses a behavior-modification approach to eating less. ``Some people
don't even realize they're doing it. They'll be at a cocktail party
and shoving food in their mouth and not even notice it.''
</P>
<P>
   Here are some helpful hints for managing weight during the
holiday season:
</P>
<P>
   _ Enjoy the conversation, not the food.
</P>
<P>
   That's one low-calorie suggestion to make it through the
numerous social engagements and family reunions this time of year
without regrets next year.
</P>
<P>
   Another is to be especially careful to cut down on high-fat
appetizers and snacks.
</P>
<P>
   Sandra McNeil, the clinical nutrition manager at Glens Falls
Hospital in Glenn Falls, N.Y., also suggests eating a healthful
snack, like high-fiber crackers or fruit, and drinking plenty of
water, before heading out to a party.
</P>
<P>
   With something already in your stomach, you're less likely to
overeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Typically it takes 20 minutes for your stomach to signal that
it's full,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   _ Scale down on alcoholic beverages and watch your portions.
</P>
<P>
   That's easier said than done, especially when generous hostesses
are more than happy to fill up dinner plates with seconds. Resist
the pressure, tell your hostess you want to save room for dessert
and then insist on only a sliver of pie or cake. If you're
confronted with a buffet, be selective and choose only the foods
you really want to eat.
</P>
<P>
   _ Forget the all-or-nothing mindset.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the holidays only come once a year and it's no fun to feel
guilty about enjoying special foods.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tradition is a big part of it,'' Segel said. ``We've been
socialized to socialize with food.''
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, Segel tells her clients to set some rules,
like a three-cookie limit at a party. The key is moderation. Don't
skip a meal with the hope of making it up with sweets. That
strategy rarely works because cake and cookies are never as filling
and satisfying as other foods.
</P>
<P>
   ``They end up taking in many more calories to fill their tummy
up,'' Segel said.
</P>
<P>
   _ Exercise.
</P>
<P>
   This time of year, many people tend to scale back on their
workouts to make extra time for shopping and socializing. There are
ways to do both. If you're at the mall, Segel suggests parking as
far as possible from the entrance or doing a lap or two inside
before hitting the stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is we're allowed to eat a certain number of
calories a day,'' she said. Here's how those calories can add up:
Eat 500 extra calories a day and you'll gain a pound in a week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
