<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-SONGWRITERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS TEMPO IS ALL ABOUT TALK, GUNS AND LOVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM BEAL Jr.  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ The fodder for Texas songwriters is pretty
straightforward: Somebody's going get shot. Failing that, they're
going to get shot at; or hold up a convenience store; or steal a
car; or fall in love with the wrong person, the wrong train, or,
God forbid, the wrong pickup truck.
</P>
<P>
   When a songwriter from elsewhere _ say, Connecticut _ writes
about love gone wrong, listeners are apt to have to sit through a
litany of soul-searching and self-flagellation.
</P>
<P>
   When a songwriter from Texas writes about love gone wrong, blood
isn't always shed, but welts are often raised. And it usually takes
a while for the writer to explain exactly how wrong that love went.
</P>
<P>
   For proof, listen to Lyle Lovett's ``Step Inside This House,'' a
double-album tribute to some of the Texas-bred or, in some cases,
Texas-tempered, wordsmiths whose works influenced his career.
</P>
<P>
   The writers Lovett covers include Steve Fromholz, Townes Van
Zandt, Guy Clark, Eric Taylor, David Rodriguez, Walter Hyatt,
Michael Murphey, Vince Bell, Willis Alan Ramsey and Robert Earl
Keen.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Earle is one of Texas' highest-profile singing
songwriters. At the moment, he's ensconced near Galway Bay in
Ireland, where he is working on a book.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Earle, whose work also bears the mark of some of Lovett's
influences, notably Clark and Van Zandt, will readily take time out
to communicate about what sets songwriters from Texas apart from
songwriters in other parts of the universe.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the first place, Texans in general speak in analogies. If a
Texan begins with `It's like ...,' you're going to be there for a
while,'' he wrote. ``If a Texan becomes a songwriter he is
proportionately long-winded, so `moon/June/spoon' are simply out of
the question.''
</P>
<P>
   Fromholz, a generation ahead of Earle, tends to agree. His
``Bears'' opens ``Step Inside this House,'' and his opus ``Texas
Trilogy'' sets the pace for the second disc of the album.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't shut us up. You can't get my guitar away from me and
you can't shut me up. I've been doing this for 33 years,'' he said.
``No one has gotten me to quit yet. I don't think they could.
Texans are definitely storytellers, raconteurs. And most of the
songs we write we write for ourselves, for our wives, for our
girlfriends and for our friends. We're all proud of being Texans.''
</P>
<P>
   The storytelling aspect of Texas songwriters knows no
boundaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's the corrida tradition in our neck of the woods,''
Earle said. ``When Fred Gomez Carrasco made his break from the
Walls Unit in Huntsville, Spanish-speaking radio in San Antonio was
playing three different corridas about his death before the body
was released to the family.''
</P>
<P>
   Fromholz has his own take on the gunfire quotient in Texas
music.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we're afraid of contention,'' he said with a
laugh. ``It doesn't frighten me to play in a joint that has chicken
wire in front of the stage, as long as I'm inside the chicken
wire.''
</P>
<P>
   And what does a songwriter from Connecticut think?
</P>
<P>
   Eric Von Schmidt didn't invent the East Coast school of folk
music, but he certainly helped a number of singing songwriters hone
their craft.
</P>
<P>
   Von Schmidt was influenced by people such as Huddie
``Leadbelly'' Ledbetter. In turn, the singing songwriter and noted
painter influenced Bob Dylan, Joan Baez, Chris Smither, Tom Rush
and others.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a more expansive, a tougher and more illustrative
line, almost like painting pictures instead of writing songs, that
Texas songwriters are so good at,'' Von Schmidt said in a telephone
interview. ``There's also more humor and less introspection in the
songs of a lot of Texas writers. The introspective thing has really
gotten out of hand in the East. There's so much political
correctness. The Texas school of writing has always been a breath
of fresh air.''
</P>
<P>
   Fromholz figures Texas history has rubbed off on its
songwriters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it all goes back to being Texan, which means being
independent,'' he said. ``Texas was once an independent nation and
we believe in that. It's like if you don't like what we're doing,
to hell with you. And we all care about each other. We learn from
each other.''
</P>
<P>
   A lot of what Texas writers do is go out and work the road. More
than a few Lone Star songwriters might prefer playing songs to
attentive audiences in listening clubs, but most won't shy away
from fronting a band in a honky-tonk.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody from the Northeast or from Canada came up to me at
one of the festivals and said she could dance to every song,'' said
Rod Kennedy, the founder and director of the Kerrville Folk
Festival and a man who has probably listened to more varied
songwriters than anyone else on the planet.
</P>
<P>
   ``So much of our tradition here in Texas has been inspired by
Western swing, Mexican music and country music, all of which is
dance music.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the subject matter that Texas songwriters deal with
is a holdover from the frontier spirit. They have it in Canada,
too,'' Kennedy added. ``Part of it is the romantic myth of the Old
West. Our guys have a mixture of rural and urban in their songs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
