<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAREER-SUCCESS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXECUTIVE FINDS CAREER SUCCESS BEGINS AT HOME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAVE MURPHY  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Paul DiGiammarino thought he was doing a great
job, until he received a negative performance review _ from his
son.
</P>
<P>
   After all, DiGiammarino had founded the financial services unit
of American Management Systems and was the co-leader of the $100
million unit. He loved his job, but it was demanding too much.
</P>
<P>
   He remembers what his son, then 12 or 13, told him: ``You always
say that things are going to change and you're going to be able to
spend more time with us. But it never happens.''
</P>
<P>
   It finally did.
</P>
<P>
   In a keynote speech at the American Management Association
conference in San Francisco this month, DiGiammarino cited a story
from Stephen R. Covey, author of ``The 7 Habits of Highly Effective
People'': A man on his deathbed described how he always analyzed
decisions before he made them, and generally made good decisions,
but he still didn't end up accomplishing what he wanted to in his
life.
</P>
<P>
   That's what can happen when your life is out of balance,
DiGiammarino said. His job was taking up most of his time and he
was making the right decisions in it, but he was ignoring his
family, his friends and his favorite recreational activity, golf.
</P>
<P>
   So he took a step back to sort things out. ``During this period,
I played a lot of golf and I didn't work very hard,'' DiGiammarino
recalled. ``But I wasn't happy, either.''
</P>
<P>
   So he listed the things that were important in his life, and
what he wanted to accomplish in each of those areas. ``Defining
what my goal was in each one was extremely important.''
</P>
<P>
   DiGiammarino ended up drawing what looked like a spider web,
with six spokes _ one each for work, family, community, health,
spirituality and golf. The spokes weren't symmetrical; the length
of each depended on how important he felt that aspect of his life
should be.
</P>
<P>
   Then he drew a second web, this time making each spoke represent
how much time he actually spent on each of his six important
aspects.
</P>
<P>
   The two webs weren't exactly a close match.
</P>
<P>
   In the course of aligning his webs, DiGiammarino downshifted to
a role as vice president with American Management Systems, a
company that was eventually named as one of the best places to work
in America by Working Mother, Fortune and Computer World magazines.
Then he changed companies, becoming senior vice president for
global financial services at Sapient Corp. in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   He also took two steps that he urges all workers to consider: He
developed a personal mission statement and determined how well his
goals aligned themselves with the company's mission. DiGiammarino
also urged companies to do the same thing in reverse, considering
whether they can attract top employees if they expect people to
devote too much of their lives to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can no longer just blindly go out there and say, `This is
our corporate mission statement and people have to get in line with
it.'''
</P>
<P>
   If you decide that your life is out of balance, DiGiammarino
suggests that you think about which things you want to start doing
and which things you will have to stop to make room for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's extremely difficult to move anything off the plate,'' he
warned.
</P>
<P>
   To help simplify his work life, DiGiammarino followed another of
Covey's suggestions and divided his work tasks into four
categories: urgent and important, the most crucial aspects of the
job; not urgent but important, such as developing people's skills
and recharging your batteries; urgent but not important, such as
answering e-mail and voicemail messages; and neither urgent nor
important.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe we spend way too much time in the `urgent, not
important,''' DiGiammarino said, adding that he often felt
compelled to respond to messages, even though it took a lot of
time. ``I was letting other people tell me what to do with my
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Once he stepped back, though, he found that his family members
weren't the only ones who benefited. Other people he worked with
also gained because they took on more responsibilities, giving them
chances for career growth that weren't there before.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt bad when I didn't respond to somebody's e-mail,''
DiGiammarino recalled. ``But you know what? I felt worse when my
kid told me I wasn't spending enough time with him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
