<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-25 12:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8989 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RELIGION-CAPITALIST-B     11-25 0912
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-CAPITALIST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAPITALIST CASTS BREAD ON THE WATERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Chuck Stetson seems an unlikely figure to lead a
national religious movement. He lives on the stiff upper lip of
Manhattan's East Side, and runs an equity fund that manages over
$100 million for venture capitalists _ none of which quite fits the
image of someone shouting the gospel from rooftops.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Stetson, 53, is the main organizing force behind the
National Bible Association, a group that sponsors National Bible
Week, which started Saturday, and promotes reading the Bible as a
path to personal and social salvation.
</P>
<P>
   This is not your typical bunch of evangelists, though. ``There
are no thumpers on our board,'' Stetson emphasized, sitting in the
townhouse where he works and lives with his wife and three
daughters. ``I was attracted to it by the fact that it is not a
fundamentalist organization. What attracted me was that this is a
group of business people in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   He is well aware of the biblical passage that declares it easier
for a camel to pass through the eye of a needle than for a rich man
to pass into heaven. And Stetson is a rich man who makes his money
by making others even richer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think about that,'' he said of the apparent contradiction.
``But I think Andrew Carnegie answered that in an essay he wrote. I
was just looking at it again the other day. In his day, he made
$350 million, which is the equivalent of $40 or $50 billion today.
... And he gave it away in his lifetime. That's his message.''
</P>
<P>
   Carnegie gave a lot of his money to libraries. Stetson gives a
lot of his to pushing the Bible. ``I wouldn't be successful doing
straight venture capital without balancing it here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The National Bible Association was founded in 1940 by business
leaders who saw war on the horizon, felt the nation needed moral
strengthening to survive it, and concluded the Bible could be a
source.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in a similar period today,'' Stetson reflected. ``People
are searching for spiritual reality. They've gone through New Age,
it's been hollow, they're looking for the real thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite its nearly 60 years of operations, the Bible association
has not exactly penetrated popular culture. This is where Stetson
feels he can make his mark.
</P>
<P>
   ``My challenge as a venture capitalist is to find where capital
can be really effective,'' he said. He sees Bible promotion the
same way. ``I treat this as a venture-capital investment, and the
potential return is infinite. The number of lives you touch, you
never know.''
</P>
<P>
   He started a Web site, which receives 20,000 hits a day. He
negotiated with America Online Inc. to make the association its
official Bible contact group. Although the group stays away from
particular denominations, he worked a deal with the Episcopal and
United Methodist churches _ ``because they have TV downlinks'' _ to
produce national Bible-reading teleconferences.
</P>
<P>
   On a low-tech level, he put together a ``starter kit,''
suggesting how to organize Bible-reading groups. He outlined, then
hired an author to write, a pocket Bible guide, now published by
Doubleday.
</P>
<P>
   Stetson has been doing this sort of thing on a smaller scale for
17 years. He holds a Bible-reading group with fellow businessmen.
At St. Bartholomew's, one of the city's blue-blood Episcopal
churches, he heads the Alpha Program, teaching a course on
Christianity.
</P>
<P>
   His came into this realm from a spiritual crisis. ``In
1979-80,'' he recalled, ``I was a little bit lost. There was
something lacking in my life. I was in investment banking, moving
from one job to the next. Things that had once come easy to me were
all of a sudden difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   His mother gave him a book on Corinthians I 13, a biblical
chapter about love or charity. ``It got me so intrigued, I wanted
to read more,'' he said. ``I was ready for it.'' Soon, he figured
others were ready for it, too, and wanted to make them realize it.
</P>
<P>
   Some are leery of his campaign. Last week, the American Civil
Liberties Union sued the mayor of Gilbert, Ariz., and the state's
governor, who had been selected this year by the association to
issue the official proclamation of Bible Week. The ACLU argued the
act violated the First Amendment's separation of church and state.
A judge filed an injunction against the proclamation, pending a
hearing next month.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas May, the National Bible Association's president, is
puzzled. ``The proclamation just encourages people to read the
Bible as a source of wisdom and ethics,'' he said. ``It doesn't
encourage you to do some religious activity.''
</P>
<P>
   Laurence Tribe, professor at Harvard University Law School, who
had the proclamation read to him over the phone, agreed most of it
was ``unobjectionable, like celebrating a tradition.'' However, he
said its first paragraph _ which mentions ``the Judeo-Christian
principles upon which our nation was conceived'' _ does cross the
line.
</P>
<P>
   Stetson, a graduate of Yale University and Columbia Business
School, takes the constitutional issues seriously, and plans to
consult specialists on how to alter the language.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, Stetson wants to turn Bible Week into a ceremony as
grand as the Fourth of July. ``I was in Philadelphia around
Independence Day,'' he recalled, ``and they had 196 events going
on. I'd like to see something like that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
