u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-VERY-BAD-BOS &LR;      11-25 0680
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-VERY-BAD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIAZ IS A BRIGHT SPOT IN `BAD THINGS' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
VERY BAD THINGS 
Written and directed by: Peter Berg 
Starring: Christian Slater, Cameron Diaz, Daniel Stern, Jon
Favreau, Jeremy Piven, Jeanne Tripplehorn, Leland Orser 
Running time: 100 minutes 
Rated: R (a graphic sex scene, profanity, oodles of bloody
violence) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Very Bad Things'' is not a very bad movie, just a relentlessly
tiring one. It's a ``Road Runner'' cartoon filtered through Quentin
Tarantino's kill-'em-with-a-weapon then kill-'em-with-laughter
approach to filmmaking. It's a brutal, pitch-black comedy that
never lets silly little things like plot and believable characters
get in the way of another senseless murder.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Berg, best known as Dr. Billy Kronk on the CBS medical
drama, ``Chicago Hope,'' makes his feature writing and directing
debut with this film about a bachelor party gone horribly awry.
Like most first-time filmmakers, he dearly wants to make a lasting
impression and fatally overshoots his target. As the film begins,
with a painfully off-key piano rendition of ``The Wedding March,''
Kyle (Jon Favreau) and Laura (Cameron Diaz) are just few days away
from tying the knot. But things seem doomed from the get-go.
</P>
<P>
   Laura is one of those women who has spent her entire life
planning her wedding, and she jumped into the project with
terrifying military precision. She is Bride-zilla, an unstoppable
force of nature who will not allow anyone or anything to screw up
her perfect day. So she's particularly ticked that Kyle plans to
head off to Las Vegas for a bachelor party with his best pals.
Laura, of course, hates his friends (she does have a point there),
and she is especially concerned that Kyle will enjoy one last love
dance with the obligatory party prostitute. She doesn't want him
saying his vows reeking from the ``stench of cheap-hotel-whore
sex.''
</P>
<P>
   But a man gotta do what a man's gotta do. Kyle hops into a
minivan with sleazebag Boyd (Christian Slater), creepy Moore
(Leland Orser), horny Mike (Jeremy Piven), and mild-mannered Adam
(Daniel Stern) for what will turn out to be a killer of a bachelor
party.
</P>
<P>
   Once they arrive in Vegas, there's booze, bongs, and blows
galore. The boys trash their room, trash each other, and quite by
accident, a stripper Boyd hired for the festivities. Adam wants to
call the cops, but Boyd has far less noble intentions. No one knew
the stripper was in the room, hence, he reasons, she's just a
``105-pound problem that has to be moved from point A to point B.''
They agree to sneak her body out of the hotel and bury her in the
Nevada desert. Cruel, but simple and clean _ that is, until a hotel
security guard investigating a report of a commotion in their suite
finds the body. Next thing, you know, he's just as dead with a
corkscrew in his heart.
</P>
<P>
   Each murder becomes an effort to conceal the original sin, and
the body count climbs until Berg starts to run out of cast members
to kill. Of course, most of the folks are so grating you wouldn't
mind someone taking a chainsaw to the whole bloody lot. Slater does
the smooth psycho thing he's been working since ``Heathers,'' a far
superior black comedy that also has murder on its mind. Stern plays
yet another nebbish, and there isn't much to distinguish the other
revelers. Berg doesn't spend nearly as much time on character
development as he spends trying to shock us with callow violence,
and more than a few jokes about handicapped children. He tosses in
some interesting camera angles, but those most often occur when
dialogue or a logical narrative fails him.
</P>
<P>
   The one true bright spot is Diaz, who just oozes screen presence
even when she's screeching like a banshee about having enough
chairs at her wedding. It's the frightening flip side of her perky
bride-to-be in 1997's ``My Best Friend's Wedding.'' She gives a
marvelously manic performance, and although it's basically a
one-note character, Diaz turns it into a symphony.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-25-98 1226EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
