<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-$ADV29-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAX CONSIDERATIONS ON SELLING SHARES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, November 29, 1998; this is the column that
normally moves Friday)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I have been purchasing stocks and mutual funds shares for
several years, but I am experienced in selling them. I bought
$7,500 worth of shares of CGM Mutual fund between September of 1995
and July of 1997. During this time, I received long-term capital
gain distributions of $1,484 and short-term capital gain
distributions of $1,816. These distributions have been
automatically reinvested and I have paid income taxes each year
resulting from these distributions. I anticipate needing funds in
the spring for a different investment and am considering selling
all my shares. I prefer to complete my income tax forms myself, and
my question is how do I handle the sale? I invested a total of
$7,500 to purchase 234 shares, and these shares are worth about
$5,600 today. Through reinvestment of $3,300 in distributions, I
acquired an additional 121 shares, which would be worth $2,900 if
sold today. Thus if I sold the entire position, I would receive
about $8,500. This would appear as a $1,000 gain, but I already
have paid taxes on the $3,300 in distributions. If the
distributions are included, is my basis $10,800? If this is the
case, I would consider selling now and claiming a capital loss of
$2,300 -- thus avoiding the tax liability of distributions at the
end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; M.R. &LR; ,  &UR; Vancouver, Wash &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. The base cost for the CGM Mutual shares you own is indeed
$10,800 -- the total cost of all of your purchases, whether they
were made through direct purchases or through the reinvestment of
distributions. Thus if you sold the entire position for $8,500, you
could claim a capital loss of $2,300. (Fortunately for you, the
shares of this volatile fund have recovered strongly since you
wrote, and you would realize more than $9,000 if you sold at the
price prevailing as this is written. But in the discussion that
follows, I'll stick with the values cited in your letter.) I
understand your confusion:: How can you claim a capital loss when
you only paid $7,500 for the shares, and then you sell them for
$8,500? The answer is that reinvested distributions are no
different than direct purchases, and so you have actually paid
$10,800 for your 355 CGM Mutual shares, and thus you are entitled
to claim the capital loss.
</P>
<P>
   Effectively, what has happened is that the taxes you paid on the
distributions each year represented, from a long-term point of
view, an overpayment, and when you sell you will be able to reclaim
that overpayment through the capital loss.
</P>
<P>
   In fairness to CGM Mutual, which has been having a tough time
for the past 18 months or so, you apparently have been taking the
income distributions in cash; had you reinvested all distributions,
you would have a larger position and realize more from a sale. But
it's also fair to note that the fund's aggressive investment style
is sufficient for Morningstar Mutual Funds to note ``horrendous tax
inefficiency'' for the fund and to suggest it is best used as an
investment for a long-term tax-deferred account.
</P>
<P>
   There's one more wrinkle that you might want to consider. If you
sell only a part of your CGM Mutual holding, the tax rules allow
you a choice of two methods of allocating your base cost. The
default, which is the method used if you do not specify in writing
which shares you are selling, is to average the price paid for all
shares you hold, and then to multiply that average price times the
number of shares sold. But if you specify in writing which shares
you are selling -- carefully indicating the date of purchase -- you
can use the actual cost of the price of the shares you have sold,
and in a case such as yours, you would probably realize a larger
capital loss than you would achieve through averaging the costs.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, is it best to sell now rather than in the spring, so as
to avoid taxable distributions? My guess is that for 1998 this
won't be a big factor. As this is written, the fund has a 3.6
percent year-to-date total return. Although it's not impossible for
a fund with a modest total return to make a substantial capital
gains distribution, it's not particularly likely. The last time
this fund had a really bad year, losing 9.73 percent in 1994, there
were no capital gains distributions at all. And at the time of the
last Morningstar Mutual Funds report on the fund, dated Sept. 30,
the potential capital gains exposure for the funs was only 7
percent of assets.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, if you're pretty sure you're going to sell
early in 1999, why not indeed push the transaction forward to 1998,
thus allowing you to claim the capital loss on your 1998 tax return
rather than the 1999 return?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have learned from you that my husband and I have too many
stock mutual funds and not enough with other types of investments.
My husband has retired from corporate life but not from work. At
age 66, he works part time counseling at a local junior college,
earning $1,200 a month, and has a consulting business which brings
in $20,000 to $30,000 annual before taxes. He also receives a $500
monthly pension. He does not see retirement in the future -- his
choice -- but I think we need to plan for the time when he may
change his mind. In that case, we would need $20,000 to $30,000 a
year to supplement our Social Security and his pension. Our
financial advisor has steered us away from GNMA and bond funds, but
I am questioning this. We have already lost money in the latest
correction and I think we need a more conservative portfolio. I
enclose a list of our investments. You will note that 23 percent of
the assets are in a trust, and I use the money there for art
expenses, since I am a semi-professional artist. I would like to
keep this money separate and pass it along to my children if it is
possible.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; M.B. &LR; ,  &UR; Brookings, Ore &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Given your particular situation, I don't necessarily agree
that you need more fixed- income funds. To begin with, I set the
conservatively-invested trust to one side, since it's your
intention to keep that separate to whatever degree is possible.
</P>
<P>
   Looking at the remaining assets, I tallied about 33 percent on
the fixed income side -- counting here your money market funds and
the 36 percent of the Vanguard Wellington fund positions which
represent fixed-income investments. A 33 percent fixed-income
holding is fairly typical for a couple of your age -- but it might
be viewed as fully adequate and even conservative since at this
stage you are not drawing upon your retirement savings, and indeed
don't expect to be drawing upon them for the foreseeable future.
</P>
<P>
   Let's suppose that you will be able to leave the non-trust
investments alone for five years. If the portfolio average return
during that period is 7 percent, you will see a gain of roughly
$100,000 during that time. (This presumes you use other funds to
pay any taxes generated from your taxable accounts.) In any event,
at that poit let's presume you begin to withdraw from the
portfolio at the rate of $25,000 a year. The funds would be
sufficient to last 41 years from that time. (But note that if you
raise withdrawals at the $30,000 annual rate, the pool would last
only a little more than 22 years, which is too close to a possible
life expectancy for most people.) Even though your portfolio seems
a little complicated at first, with 18 different holdings, I think
it's working well. For one thing, there's a good deal of
duplication of funds from category to category. I'd look at it this
way: 24 percent of the money is in Vanguard Wellington, 11 percent
in Fidelity Equity-Income II, 25 percent in money market funds, 9
percent in Fidelity Low-Priced Stock fund, and 31 percent in an
assortment of growth - oriented stock funds, with Vanguard's Index
500 fund dominating that category. They're all solid funds, and so
long as my assumption that your husband will continue to work for
at least five years, I think I agree with your financial advisor --
things are in good shape as they are.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Please comment on including Warren Buffett's Berkshire
Hathaway as part of an investment portfolio. The class A shares are
rather pricey. Do the class B shares offer the same potential?
Should these shares be viewed much like a mutual fund?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A.S. &LR; ,  &UR; Andover, Mass. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Well, Berkshire Hathaway certainly operates much like a
mutual fund with a very long- term outlook, and with the advantage
that since it isn't one, it can be more tax efficient than a fund
is likely to be. But if it were a mutual fund, it would be an
closed end fund, where share prices move as much as a function of
sentiment as the underlying value. If CEO Warren Buffett were not
at an age when most people are retired, I'd consider it an
attractive long-term holding. But he is, so I don't. I know that
it's broadly considered heresy to view a corporation as a one-man
show. Okay -- in this case, I'm a heretic.
</P>
<P>
   The class B shares of Berkshire Hathaway, which entered this
week trading at $2,244 each, have 1/30th of the value of a Class A
share, which were quoted at $67,400. But the Class B shares carry
limited voting rights, equivalent only to 1/200th of that of a
Class A share. That's the only substantive difference.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Send letters, including your name, address and telephone
number, to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass. 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
