<DOCNO> NYT19981125.0128 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-25 12:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9010 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      11-25 0885
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S POLITICAL FOOTBALL IN CHAMPIONS LEAGUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Galatasaray-Juventus match in the Champions League has been
postponed from Nov. 25 to Dec. 2 because of capital punishment.
Sort of.
</P>
<P>
   The official reason, according to UEFA headquarters, is ``the
deterioration of relations between Turkey and Italy,'' stemming
from the Italians' refusal to extradite Abdullah Ocalan. Italy's
constitution outlaws the death penalty, and its justice system is
obligated to not extradite to countries that allow capital
punishment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am profoundly sorry,'' said Italy's president, Massimo
D'Alema, ``but we cannot violate the Constitution, even if an ally
asks us to.''
</P>
<P>
   Such a concept is not easily accepted these days in Turkey,
where Ocalan is wanted for terrorist activities in the name of the
PKK Kurdistan Workers Party.
</P>
<P>
   Italian flags are being burned, products boycotted, and a
television commercial shows images of dead children, Ocalan, and a
plate of spaghetti with blood, with the message to Italy: ``You
should clean your pasta.''
</P>
<P>
   Near one of the dozens of Istanbul's Benetton stores, which have
covered their windows in black, Juventus shirts are being sold ``so
you can burn them,'' according to the proprietor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm afraid, I admit it,'' Juventus' French midfielder Zinedine
Zidane told La Gazzetta dello Sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Juventus cannot play in Istanbul, it could be the end of
soccer,'' Galatasaray coach Fatih Terim said. ``Why? Only
Galatasaray can calm all this tension.''
</P>
<P>
   When the teams finally do play, the match could become a symbol
for peaceful co-existence and understanding. Unfortunately,
Juventus' players are feeling threatened, and many of them are not
even Italian.
</P>
<P>
   ``Juventus made a mistake cancelling our welcome banquet and
seeking a neutral field,'' Galatasaray director of sport Mete
Razlikli said. ``Why? For a peaceful demonstration of 100,000
people in a city of 13 million. What do they want _ Ireland?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Whither Ronaldo?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The failure of Brazil's national team and the virtual
disappearance of Ronaldo has not been adequately explained more
than four months after the World Cup final in Saint-Denis.
</P>
<P>
   But whether Ronaldo was drugged, spell-bound, or a combination
of factors sabotaged the Brazilians, Ronaldo should not have been
on the field for 90 minutes. Since that game, Ronaldo seldom has
performed.
</P>
<P>
   Ronaldo was burned out, mentally and physically. Roberto Baggio
was in a similar position in 1994. And after Italy lost to Brazil
in the final in Pasadena, Baggio required nearly a full season to
recover.
</P>
<P>
   Inter allowed Ronaldo to report late to training camp. In fact,
Ronaldo was absent when the team was playing its opening Champions
League matches in late August. He has been so out of form that his
orthopedist from Brazil was called in last week to consider knee
surgery.
</P>
<P>
   The surgery was ruled out, but Ronaldo was absent as Inter lost,
3-1, to first-place Fiorentina Sunday. But Ronaldo is expected to
return against Real Madrid in the Champions League Wednesday in
Milan.
</P>
<P>
   This could be an opportune moment. Real Madrid has been
struggling. In the last seven games, it has earned 8 points and
surrendered 13 goals. Fernando Hierro, the captain, has been
injured and the central defense appears slow. Much of the blame has
fallen on Sanchis, who nearly came to blows with Dutchman Clarence
Seedorf during a 3-1 loss to Valencia, and Fernando Sanz, son of
club president Lorenzo Sanz. The Valencia victory was considered a
positive sign for Inter because Valencia's tactics were designed by
Italian coach Claudio Ranieri.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Multiple choice
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Major League Soccer is among the few leagues that allows
multiple ownership of teams. Revenue sharing has been formalized on
all fronts under the single-entity structure of the league, so the
teams all belong to one ownership group.
</P>
<P>
   The Lamar Hunt family owns the Columbus Crew and Kansas City
Wizards; Philip Anschutz' Sports Enterprises controls Chicago,
Colorado, and Los Angeles; and now the Kraft Sports Group has added
the San Jose Clash to its ownership of the Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   Hunt invested in two franchises when the MLS began in 1996.
Other original investors were allowed to purchase the rights to
expansion teams under their initial investment terms, and Anschutz
paid $5 million for the Chicago Fire. Anschutz was so encouraged by
the success of the Fire that he offered to buy out Marc Rappaport,
whose group had purchased the Los Angeles Galaxy. But the
``original investor'' clause did not apply this time, and Anschutz
paid $26 million for the Galaxy.
</P>
<P>
   The Krafts stepped in after Dentsu Inc. financing failed in San
Jose, but the ``original investor'' clause did not apply since this
was not an expansion team.
</P>
<P>
   ``They paid about the same price as Anschutz paid for the
Galaxy,'' a Kraft spokesman said. ``They would love to be able to
buy a soccer team for $5 million, but that's just not possible.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Krafts received significant concessions. They paid a
comparatively low up-front amount of cash, and received credit for
capital investments in the league itself.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-25-98 1230EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
