<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHN KERRY AND A WRITER'S BIG MISTAKE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I spent $50 of my publisher's money Monday night to attend a
John Kerry fund-raiser. It was a pleasant affair, with singers
Shawn Colvin and James Taylor, and comedian Robin Williams arguing,
with varying degrees of conviction, that John Forbes Kerry was a
great gift to mankind. As the evening drew to a close, Kerry
delivered a brief comedy routine of his own, ogling the assembled
$1,000-a-head fat cats and Big Labor grandees, while blathering
about the ``grass-roots'' politics that have buoyed his successive
candidacies.
</P>
<P>
   What is it about John Kerry that makes people cringe? Is it the
plastic surgery to his lantern jaw, which he claims was medically
necessary? The Super-8 movies he filmed of himself in action in
Vietnam? The ``JFK'' monogram he wore on his oxford shirts at St.
Paul's prep school? His shallow, manipulative demagoguery over the
``missing'' POWs? Or his belated admission that the medals he
jettisoned in a famous 1971 antiwar protest were not his own?
</P>
<P>
   Kerry has said that he will decide whether to run for president
within a few weeks. There is plenty of logic to a Kerry campaign.
He stood on the sidelines six years ago, and watched a little-known
governor from a rural state buck the odds and capture the White
House. Nominal front-runner Al Gore has all the charisma of ... of
a John Kerry! And our junior senator, who whinges constantly about
money, has a bank in the back room: His second wife,
heiress/philanthropist Teresa Heinz, is worth an estimated $800
million.
</P>
<P>
   Curiously, the Kerry 2000 bandwagon seems to be stuck in first
gear. Approached by a Boston Herald reporter at a Kerry function
last month, Heinz called her husband's presidential ambitions
``ridiculous.'' In the key primary state of New Hampshire, Kerry is
about as popular as the income tax. Queried about backing a Kerry
presidential run, esteemed colleagues like Ted Kennedy and Barney
Frank have adopted a wait-and-see posture.
</P>
<P>
   With friends like these, who needs hostile columnists?
</P>
<P>
   Kerry is someone who seems to make a vice of his virtues. As a
Yale undergraduate, he was a star athlete and a member of the elite
secret society Skull and Bones. ``But,'' according to Globe
reporter Charles Sennott's definitive 1996 profile of the senator,
``despite his achievements, Kerry generally was not well liked.''
(That reminds me of the phrase that dogged Texas senator Phil Gramm
during his 1996 presidential run: ``Even his friends can't stand
him.'')
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, the Globe ran an amusing account of the just-divorced
Kerry's numerous liaisons, dubbing him ``The Senate's New Romeo.''
Not for the first time, we reported that Kerry had been keeping
company with actresses Morgan Fairchild and his fellow St. Paul's
alum, Catherine Oxenberg, described by the late Globe columnist
John Robinson as ``virtually without talent in her chosen field.''
Kerry said his characterization as a rake was ``unfair,'' and then
told an editor here we should feel ``ashamed'' to have printed the
article. And we did, we did.
</P>
<P>
   Several years ago, I committed the Columnist's Big Mistake. I
flew down to Washington and had dinner with John Kerry. At the time
he was mired in his principled but quixotic pursuit of the shadowy
Bank of Credit and Commerce (remember Robert Altman, Mr. Wonder
Woman?). Guess what? He's intelligent, well mannered, whiny _ yes _
but all in all a thoughtful, decent guy. This is why writers should
never confront the targets of their scorn; we are all Will Rogers
at heart. I never met a man I thought I didn't like, whom I didn't
end up liking, a little.
</P>
<P>
   One detail of our meeting stands out clearly. George Bush's Gulf
War was still fresh in people's memories, and Bill Clinton was
suffering the quadrennial media mauling in the run-up to the New
Hampshire primary. But John Kerry bet me that the Democrats would
win the White House in 1992, which of course they did. Is it
possible that the tall, arrogant elitist John Kerry knows more
about running for president than the average-statured, arrogant
elitist Alex Beam?
</P>
<P>
   My, that would be a revelation.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Alex Beam's e-mail address is beam(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
