<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-ASSASSINATE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICAL KILLINGS LEAVE RUSSIA CHILLED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ It was a rare public outpouring of grief for a country
all too familiar with gangland-style slayings of its political and
business leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of mourners paid their last respects Tuesday to Galina
Starovoitova, a prominent liberal legislator gunned down outside
her St. Petersburg apartment Friday night in an apparent contract
murder.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands more lined the streets outside the hall where
Starovoitova's body lay in state, their numbers forcing a
three-hour delay of the funeral. Many mourners carried banners
expressing shock and outrage, which the country's leaders, many of
them longtime allies of the slain lawmaker, for once seemed to
share sincerely.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are killing our comrades, our friends,'' said Anatoly
Chubais, a former deputy prime minister who now heads Russia's
electricity monopoly. ``Do they want to stop us? Do they want to
scare us? They will not succeed.''
</P>
<P>
   But as the sun set on St. Petersburg, and Starovoitova was laid
to rest in the Alexander Nevsky monastery, their indignation was
subsumed by a deeper sense of helplessness about a crime wave that
no one in Russia appears able to stop.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole system of power in Russia is rotten,'' said Andrei
Piontkowski, a well-known Moscow political analyst. ``What we are
seeing is systemic chaos, not a conspiracy.''
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of leading Russian businessmen, journalists, politicians,
and political aides have been killed in recent years. No major
murder case has been solved. Many of the killings have involved
business dealings gone bad, an ugly side effect of a lawless
society in which contract disputes often end in contract murders.
</P>
<P>
   The 52-year-old Starovoitova (pronounced stah-rah-VOY-tah-vah)
was the sixth member of the Russian parliament assassinated since
1993. Her spokesman, Ruslan Linkov, 27, barely survived the same
attack. At least 15 legislative aides have been killed in the past
two years.
</P>
<P>
   She was also the sixth prominent figure to be attacked _ and the
third killed _ in recent weeks in St. Petersburg, which is
preparing for local elections on December 6. The newspaper Segodnya
Tuesday called the fight for seats ``the dirtiest election campaign
in the history of Russia.''
</P>
<P>
   While Starovoitova was not believed to have business interests,
she was one of the leaders of an electoral bloc that hopes to win a
majority of the city's 50 districts. Control of the Baltic port's
lucrative trade and customs business is at stake. Boris Nemtsov, a
former deputy prime minister, said the city reminded him of
``Chicago in the 1920s.'' Many observers think Starovoitova was
getting in the way of powerful criminal clans who hoped to place
their candidates in the legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's leading political forces have come up with other
theories to explain the shooting. Chubais and other liberals have
blamed ``Communists'' on the grounds that Starovoitova frequently
criticized them. Severnaya Stolitsa, a St. Petersburg newspaper
that she published, recently accused the Communist speaker of the
lower house of parliament, Gennady Seleznyov, of extorting the
city's businesses for campaign contributions.
</P>
<P>
   Seleznyov countered that ``democrats'' allied with Starovoitova
could have had her killed to attract public attention and sympathy.
He also said he planned to sue the paper.
</P>
<P>
   Other observers think the problem goes deeper than political
affiliations and power struggles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Evil fears no one in today's Russia. It is convinced of its
invulnerability,'' commented the newspaper Izvestia in an
editorial. ``This means that Russia is no longer a state. It is
dead.''
</P>
<P>
   President Boris Yeltsin appears powerless to do anything about
the situation. He came to power with the support of the democratic
movement Starovoitova helped form and later employed her as his
adviser on ethnic issues. Yeltsin was hospitalized on Sunday with
pneumonia, which his spokesman said was brought on by
Starovoitova's death. While Yeltsin found the strength to host
President Jiang Zemin of China in his hospital room, he has not
addressed the nation on television about Starovoitova's slaying.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Kremlin issued a statement saying Yeltsin was
taking personal control of the investigation. Yeltsin said the same
thing after the 1995 murder of popular television host Vladislav
Litsyev, who was shot outside his Moscow home, and the 1995 killing
of reporter Dmitry Kholodov, who was blown in half by a suitcase
bomb. Neither murder has been solved.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Security Service, the successor of the once dreaded
KGB, has been put in charge of the investigation of Starovoitova's
murder. That order came just days after a group of former agents
accused leaders of the FSB, as the service is known in Russia, of
ordering contract murders for profit for crime gangs.
</P>
<P>
   For the past week, the agents have appeared in press conferences
and on Russia's main national television network, sometimes wearing
dark glasses and ski masks to protect their identities, to provide
details of assassination orders they claim to have received from
former FSB director Nikolai Kovalyov and others.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin has promised to look into these allegations as well. But
so far, the only threat of legal action has come from Kovalyov, who
has said he will sue the television station's owner, prominent
financier Boris Berezovsky.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the chief of Russia's police force, Interior Minister
Sergei Stepashin, has promised to spare no effort to find
Starovoitova's killers, and he dispatched a small army of
investigators and forensic experts to the scene.
</P>
<P>
   Police lost valuable time in the hours after the shooting,
almost guaranteeing the killers' escape. They ordered a dragnet to
catch the gunmen, but officers were not told whom they were looking
for, the newspaper Nezavisimaya Gazeta reported. The paper and
other sources said the investigation of the crime scene only began
eight hours after the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Communist leader Gennady Zyuganov called for ``extreme
measures'' to deal with crime. The term has a scary ring to it,
given Russia's history of purges, and critics charged that the
Communists missed a chance to show their commitment to law and
order when they failed to censure one of their members of
parliament, retired General Albert Makashov, for a string of
anti-Semitic public comments.
</P>
<P>
   Starovoitova's allies noted that she had sharply criticized
Makashov in parliament.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every unsolved contract murder is a straight path to the next
one,'' Chubais mused Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But Chubais, too, has critics who say he himself has concealed
knowledge of contract murders for murky political goals. One of
them, investigative journalist Alexander Minkin, on Monday
published a transcript of what he said was a 1996 conversation
between Chubais and other top officials about murders carried out
by Kremlin security chiefs. In the transcript, which Minkin said
was obtained by security officials, Chubais allegedly hints he is
keeping documents proving the murders secret to protect himself
from retribution. Chubais denied the allegations when they first
appeared two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But Minkin's conclusion, one probably shared by most Russians,
is that there are no white knights among Russia's current leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``In (parliament), in the government, in the Kremlin, they are
only concerned with themselves, their successes, their
well-being,'' Minkin observed.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday in St. Petersburg, an unknown gunman fired several
rounds into the apartment of Konstantin Serov, a member of the city
legislature and a candidate for the Dec. 6 elections. He was
unhurt.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
