u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-TESTS-BOS &LR;      11-25 0864
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-TESTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDUCATORS SPLIT ON MAKING STATE TESTS A CLASS SUBJECT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JORDANA HART  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Although Massachusetts teachers are divided on whether
to ``teach to the test'' to boost scores on the statewide exams for
fourth-, eighth-, and 10th-graders, many educators say the test is
so broad that teaching to it could benefit many classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   The release next month of MCAS scores showing how each student,
school, and district performed is expected to pressure teachers to
boost their pupils' scores by teaching as specifically to the test
as they can.
</P>
<P>
   In statewide results released on Monday, a majority of students
scored in the ``failing'' or ``needs improvement'' categories in
English, math, and science, with one exception: Most eighth-graders
did well in English.
</P>
<P>
   In recent interviews, several educators said that if the
Massachusetts Comprehensive Assessment System effectively tests
critical thinking, analysis, and writing, then teaching to it could
only improve education.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the MCAS, it is not teaching to the test. It is teaching
kids to think and take risks,'' said Althea Brown, who teaches
ninth- and 10th-grade science at Medford High School.
</P>
<P>
   Said Boston School Superintendent Thomas W. Payzant, ``If you
are teaching them to write a decent essay or helping them learn to
answer key questions in a lesson ... then they should be able to
transfer those skills to any unknown question on the test.''
</P>
<P>
   But not all parents and educators are ready to see classes and
teaching methods altered especially for the MCAS, given that the
test was just taken for the first time in May.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is everybody performing for the right reasons?'' said Joyce
Knippenberg, a parent, former high school teacher, and president of
the Massachusetts Parent-Teacher Organization. ``I disagree with
teaching to the test because you are giving the wrong motivation,
and students pick that up.''
</P>
<P>
   This week, a cadre of education luminaries on an ad hoc
committee on MCAS dismissed the test as ``poorly written, filled
with trivia and ambiguities, excessively long, and (lacking) a
recognizable educational purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, committee member Vito Perrone, director of teacher
education at Harvard Graduate School of Education, said the test
``looks very much like other standardized tests I have reviewed. It
is eminently coachable. It is possible to teach to this test
without teaching very much.''
</P>
<P>
   Perrone said that if states continue to depend on the
``multiple-choice, single right-answer, and limited choice test
format, it will be difficult to get at higher-level thinking,
understanding, and those things we most want.''
</P>
<P>
   The state's interim education commissioner, David Driscoll,
praised the test, but noted that it is not _ and should not be _
the only assessment of children. Assessment ``goes on every day,
every minute. This test is part of that,'' Driscoll said.
</P>
<P>
   But many educators who ardently oppose teaching to most
standardized tests say the MCAS may be an exception: a welcome
change from the ``drill and grill'' that has long dominated
American education.
</P>
<P>
   The MCAS exams, which take 12 to 17 hours over three weeks, use
many open-ended and essay questions, even in math. For the first
time in Massachusetts on a standardized test, students have had to
explain their answer to a math or science problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world of MCAS has changed a lot of people's minds about
teaching to the test,'' said Wayne Sylvester, chairman of the
social studies department at Pentucket Regional High School in West
Newbury. ``Private schools for years have stopped what they are
doing and prepped for SATs, but public schools never did that. MCAS
has changed everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Recent studies show that nationally, the practice of drilling
children for standardized tests is widespread, particularly in
preparing students for tests tied to high school graduation, as the
MCAS will be for 10th-graders beginning in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   But these studies indicate that coaching, while it can boost
test scores, rarely improves a student's genuine knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   A 1997 National Science Foundation test-taking study found that
such preparation goes on more often in districts with high
proportions of poor and minority pupils. About 60 percent of
teachers with many black and Latino students in class reported more
use of drilling and rote learning to prepare, and most said they
began preparing students as much as a month in advance.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a fair amount of evidence that you can boost scores
on high-stakes tests without really teaching students the
underlying skills,'' said Walter Haney, a Boston College professor.
``But because the MCAS uses three different formats to test kids'
knowledge, there's less danger of ill effects.''
</P>
<P>
   Perrone and others say the MCAS is still unproven as a measure
of student ability. Further, educators say it makes no sense to
change classroom practices now because districts are still matching
curriculums to the new state requirements.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Beth Daley of the Globe staff contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
