<HEADLINE>
IN BRITAIN, BUSH BROTHERS' ADVICE IS IN DEMAND 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Trailing badly in opinion polls, and desperate for an
effective message against one of the most popular British
governments in memory, Britain's Conservative Party is turning to
the sons of former US President George Bush for advice on how to
sell ``compassionate conservatism.''
</P>
<P>
   Conservative Party leader William Hague plans to visit Texas
Governor George W. Bush in Austin early next year to learn how Bush
and his brother, Jeb, who was recently elected governor of Florida,
fared so well in elections earlier this month while hard-line
Republicans did so poorly.
</P>
<P>
   Hague's aides confirm that he spoke with George W. Bush after
the latter's landslide reelection and that the Conservatives indeed
can glean much from how both Bush brothers distanced themselves
from the more extreme elements of the Republican Party bent on
making the congressional elections a referendum on the impeachment
of President Clinton over his sexual conduct.
</P>
<P>
   While George W. Bush has presided over more executions than any
other American governor, Conservative strategists consider him to
be the embodiment of ``compassionate conservatism'' and are
intrigued by his ``inclusive politics.'' Like Bush, Hague is wary
of the religious right wing of his party and has sought to portray
himself as more tolerant of homosexual and abortion rights than
previous Conservative leaders.
</P>
<P>
   In appealing to successful American conservatives for help,
however, Hague may only arm critics who charge that he has no new
ideas of his own. But then Blair and his advisers consulted
extensively with the Clinton administration while preparing their
1997 campaign for Parliament, which resulted in the Tories'
humiliation and the biggest parliamentary Labor majority in nearly
two centuries.
</P>
<P>
   There exists a prior relationship between the Bush political
machine and the Tories. In 1992, advisers to Prime Minister John
Major made no secret of their preference for George Bush over
Clinton as president, and they helped the Republican campaign. As a
result, Clinton's advisers harbored a grudge, which occasionally
surfaced when Clinton and Major talked about Northern Ireland and
other matters of mutual interest.
</P>
<P>
   The significance of Hague turning to the Bush brothers for
advice merited front-page coverage Tuesday in The Daily Telegraph,
the newspaper most closely associated with Tory thinking. Questions
about the trip were referred to Hague's press secretary, Gregor
Mackay, who did not return telephone calls seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   Like Clinton, Blair moved a dogmatically liberal Labor Party
toward the center to seize victory. After 18 years in power, the
Tories have been slow to remount an effective opposition to Labor.
Major resigned after the electoral drubbing, and Hague, who is
described as youthful by supporters and boyish by detractors, has
tried to be statesmanlike while his party continues to mutiny over
Britain's role in the European Union.
</P>
<P>
   Euro-skeptics are now firmly in control of the Conservative
Party. They vow to frustrate Blair's attempts to integrate Britain
more deeply in Europe and get rid of the 759 members of the
1,164-member House of Lords who inherit their seats. Only 17 of
those so-called hereditary peers are Labor supporters, while the
overwhelming majority have traditional ties to the Conservative
Party.
</P>
<P>
   Hague's plans to consult with successful American conservatives
underscores the plight of European conservatives, who are in
opposition in every major European country except Spain. While the
British parliamentary system is far closer to those in Europe, the
Tories apparently believe the only worthwhile advice to be had is
in the United States.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
