A9031 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RELIGION-DOMESTIC-BOS     11-25 1069
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-DOMESTIC-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROGRAM SEEKS TO EDUCATE CLERGY ON DOMESTIC ABUSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIEGO RIBADENEIRA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Victims of domestic violence sit in their pastors'
pews, listen to their sermons, have them baptize their children.
</P>
<P>
   But when those same women go to their pastors after being abused
by their husbands or boyfriends, they have sometimes been told to,
`turn the other cheek.'
</P>
<P>
   For many clergy members there has long been tension between a
religious desire to maintain the sanctity of a marriage, and
personal concern for the safety of battered women.
</P>
<P>
   Today, after years of trying to grapple with the issue, an
increasing number of clergy members are conceding they have done a
poor job of shielding victims abusive partners. Simply put, many
clergy members say they do not know how to deal with domestic
abuse.
</P>
<P>
   With this in mind, Boston Justice Ministries, a nonprofit
domestic violence prevention group, this month launched a
groundbreaking project involving 10 Jewish and Christian
congregations.
</P>
<P>
   The Safe Havens Project will train clergy members on how to talk
to victims as well as abusers; require clergy members to write
sermons on the issue; and help congregations host workshops and
distribute literature on the issue, among other things. It is
believed to be the first program in the nation to provide extensive
and ongoing domestic violence training to religious congregations,
according to local victim advocates.
</P>
<P>
   As the Rev. Charles Virga, an Episcopal priest in Chelsea, put
it: ``We have to take a long hard look in the mirror and realize
that we as communities of faith have been far too negligent on a
fundamental issue of human justice.''
</P>
<P>
   Clergy members in the Justice Ministries say the training is
vital both because clergy members are often the first persons
abused women confide in, and because their moral authority makes
their advice so powerful with many women.
</P>
<P>
   ``Victims may be more at ease going to a clergy person because
that's someone they know and because churches are typically
considered places of refuge,'' said Debra Robbin, director of
education and training at Casa Myrna Vasquez, a battered women's
shelter in the Boston area.
</P>
<P>
   One Methodist minister says she will never forget the reaction
of her own minister several years ago when he found out that she
had walked out on her abusive husband.
</P>
<P>
   ``My husband had gone to him to try and get the minister to get
me to go back home,'' said the minister, who asked not to be
identified, although she does tell her story to those she counsels.
</P>
<P>
   ``He called me in and told me that I needed to forgive my
husband. He said I must not be a true Christian because I didn't
have any faith in the power of the Holy Spirit to change people. It
felt like God had turned his back on me,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  The Rev. Anne Marie Hunter, executive director of Boston
Justice Ministries, said she felt compelled to try to sensitize
religious congregations after years hearing disturbing stories from
some women about how they were treated by their clergy.
</P>
<P>
   ``One woman told me that that her minister encouraged her to
turn the other cheek,'' Hunter recalls. ``She did _ until she ran
out of faces. These are awful stories _ and there are stories where
congregations were wonderful in their response to abuse _ but there
is certainly room for improvement.''
</P>
<P>
   Some leaders of religious congregations say their thinking about
families and marriage has evolved as they have learned more about
the dynamics of domestic violence and how difficult it is for
victims to admit they have been abused or for abusers to admit they
are batterers.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, what has historically been a religious tilt in
favor of maintaining a marriage is shifting more to the view that
the Bible in no way condones a violent partnership.
</P>
<P>
   While years ago they might have been more inclined to try and
repair an abusive relationship, clergy members say, their first
priority now is to protect the victim.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marriage is a covenant, but that covenant is broken ... the
moment there is violence,'' said Rabbi William Hamilton, spiritual
leader of Congregation Kehillath Israel in Brookline &UR;  &LR; and a Safe
Havens participant. Hamilton has set up a private hot line in his
office for abuse victims.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a clergy person, I am not all ambivalent about that. I will
not send a victim back to her abuser.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past, he said, ``The truth is that for too long we, as
religious institutions, have wrongly believed that holding families
together was more important than the well being of individuals in
those families.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to bring this issue into the light and not relegate it
to hidden cracks of religiosity because it makes us comfortable or
causes conflict with our beliefs about marriage,'' said the Rev.
Jeffrey L. Brown, pastor of Union Baptist Church in Cambridge, one
of the congregations involved in the Safe Havens program.
</P>
<P>
   Debbie Brown, a deacon at New Covenant Christian Center in
Mattapan, said her church decided to enroll in Safe Havens because
for years New Covenant has resisted owning up to the reality that
``there are victims right inside our walls.''
</P>
<P>
   Too often, added Brown, who works at Finex House, a shelter for
battered women, her church ``took the attitude that it was shameful
to talk about it or that we were in church to talk about our
relationship with God and nothing else. But we have to make
churches realize that God doesn't have in his plan for a wife to
lay down and be beaten like a doormat.''
</P>
<P>
   For the next year, Smith said, Safe Havens will provide several
educational sessions as well as individual training to the 10
congregations, financed through private donations and foundations.
Since 1991 Boston Justice Ministries has run seminars, provided
speakers and organized candlelight vigils around the issue of
domestic violence. With additional funding, Smith hopes to add 10
congregations to the program annually.
</P>
<P>
   ``From our perspective this is a wonderful intervention
program,'' said Diane Coffey, deputy chief of the victim witness
assistance program in the Suffolk County district attorney's
domestic violence unit. ``It's not about breaking up families or
interfering with people's religious beliefs. It's about keeping
families healthy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
