<HEADER>
A9034 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-THRILLERS-HNS &LR;      11-25 0911
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-THRILLERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEARSON'S NEWEST THRILLER IS A MESMERIZING TALE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BOBBIE HESS  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Pied Piper.'' By Ridley Pearson. Hyperion. $23.95. 497
pages.
</P>
<P>
   Ridley Pearson's fifth thriller featuring Seattle Police Lt. Lou
Boldt and forensic pathologist Daphne Matthews is fast-paced,
hair-raising and mesmerizing.
</P>
<P>
   It is not the best of times for Boldt. Newly promoted, he's been
moved out of homicide into intelligence. His wife, Liz, has cancer
and suddenly decides to stop treatment. And the serial kidnapper
who has been taking babies in San Diego and Portland has now struck
in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Dubbed the Pied Piper by the media because the kidnapper always
leaves a penny flute in the child's crib, the Piper always calls
when the parents are out, hits the baby-sitter with a stun gun and
takes the child. Boldt is assigned to a joint task force made up of
Seattle police officers and FBI agents.
</P>
<P>
   A second Seattle kidnapping goes from bad to worse when the
baby's grandmother suffers a fatal heart attack following the stun
gun attack. As Boldt tries to piece together clues, he finds that
much of the FBI's ongoing investigation evidence collected from
past kidnappings is off limits and he begins to suspect that
someone inside the task force is aiding the kidnapper.
</P>
<P>
   Then Boldt's 2-year-old daughter, Sarah, is taken and Boldt is
told to derail the investigation if he wants to see Sarah again.
Boldt enlists the aid of Matthews to get his son to his sister's
home outside Seattle. Once his son is safe, Boldt finds that in
past kidnappings, witnesses who should have been questioned weren't
and key paperwork has disappeared. When he talks to a Portland cop
tied to the kidnapping investigations there, he eventually learns
that the Portland cop's child was also grabbed but eventually
returned unharmed.
</P>
<P>
   As he tries to work on his own, his wife, Liz, enlists police
help for a second, secret investigation to find Sarah and the rest
of the missing children. They discover that in each instance, the
child had received a gift bearing a picture of them as a newborn.
Once the manufacturer is found, the investigation really takes off.
</P>
<P>
   Pearson's attention to detail is amazing. Nothing rings false as
inevitably Boldt pieces together the clues that will lead to the
identity of the Pied Piper. A terrific thriller by one of the best
in the field.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Cat Chaser.'' By Elmore Leonard. William Morrow. $9.95. 283
pages.
</P>
<P>
   First published in 1982, ``Cat Chaser'' is just what one would
expect from Elmore Leonard _ quirky, peopled with oddball
characters, a scatter-shot plot, and more twists and turns than a
roller coaster.
</P>
<P>
   George Moran married rich and lived the good life in Coral
Gables. When his wife divorced him, he got the Coconut Palms, a
12-unit resort motel in Pompano Beach, Fla. One day, Nolen Tyner
walks in, rents a room and proceeds to sit by the pool and drink
beer all day. Moran figures Tyner has to be a private eye and sure
enough, Tyner is checking out a Latin couple who meet at the motel
each day. The woman is the sister of Andres DeBoya, a drug dealing,
mob-connected former top Dominican cop. Some toughs show up hunting
for the couple, then DeBoya arrives and makes an offer to buy the
Coconut Palms, which Moran rejects.
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen years ago when the United States invaded the Dominican
Republic, Moran was an 18-year-old Marine who ``was a First Squad
fire-team leader, shot a sniper, was wounded, taken prisoner by the
rebels, got a Purple Heart and met a Dominican girl he would never
forget.'' Now Moran wants to ``walk those streets again without
sniper fire coming in and see what he remembered.''
</P>
<P>
   Moran flies to Santo Domingo and places an ad in a newspaper:
``CAT CHASER is looking for the girl who once ran over rooftops and
tried to kill him.'' He doesn't find the girl, but he does find
DeBoya's wife, Mary, and they begin an affair. When they return to
Florida, the affair continues and the danger of discovery
escalates. A Dominican con artist shows up with a girl he says is
the one Moran was searching for. Tyner comes up with a plan to rip
off DeBoya.
</P>
<P>
   Vintage Elmore Leonard _ you'll never guess the ending. Leonard
would be great just for his characters. But throw in snappy
dialogue, twisted plots and over-the-top atmosphere and you find
yourself in the hands of a master.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Where the Bodies Are Buried.'' By Janet Dawson. Fawcett
Columbine. $23.50. 279 pages.
</P>
<P>
   If you have a couple of free hours, check out Janet Dawson's
seventh mystery featuring feisty private investigator Jeri Howard.
</P>
<P>
   This time out, Jeri gets a middle-of-the-night phone call from
her ex-husband asking if she has a client named Rob Lawter. Then he
tells her that Lawter ``took a header'' out of his fifth-floor
window.
</P>
<P>
   Lawter was a paralegal at Bates Inc., a food-processing company.
About to blow the whistle on a corporate coverup, he hired Jeri
after receiving a threatening note. Jeri has already cashed his
retainer, and she wants to find out if he was murdered and if so,
by whom.
</P>
<P>
   A former paralegal, Jeri gets a temp job in Bates' legal
department and slowly learns that some products are causing health
problems and company officials are trying to cover it up.
</P>
<P>
   Dawson's plot, characters and dialogue are believable. A nice
little read for a rainy afternoon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
