<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-25 12:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9036 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      11-25 0862
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REGARDING HENRY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DERRICK Z. JACKSON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The one thing he did right was the day he started to fight. With
cameras and lights. Producers and editors. Historians and history's
forgotten soldiers. ``It was a civilized war,'' Henry Hampton once
said of the civil rights movement. He could have said that about
himself, with interviews, recordings and footage that destroyed the
shallow, patronizing history America had been telling itself about
the movement.
</P>
<P>
   ``A hundred civil rights stories had been told, but it was
always black people being saved by whites,'' Hampton said. He said
the stories ``have always been told by whites who depicted black
folks as poor, downtrodden and brutalized primitives ... it was the
strength of blacks that made the civil rights movement happen, with
support from some whites.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Hampton who unveiled black people as civilized warriors.
For six episodes in 1987, and then for eight more in 1990, America
was graced with ``Eyes on the Prize,'' Hampton's Emmy-award-winning
TV series on the civil rights years.
</P>
<P>
   The series was named after the freedom song that opened and
closed every episode with, ``But the one thing we did right / Was
the day we started to fight/ Keep your eyes on the prize/ Hold on,
hold on.'' Easily forgotten is that Hampton had to hold on
desperately to get the series on the air.
</P>
<P>
   One deal in 1979 with Capital Cities died as Hampton, who had
never taken on a series of this magnitude, became overwhelmed by
the task of putting the material together.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Hampton's production company Blackside, which
made government films, nearly went bankrupt as a hostile Ronald
Reagan became president.
</P>
<P>
   With the help of producer Michael Ambrosino, and with the
urgings of best friend, civil rights activist and television
investor Ruth Batson, Hampton began peddling an eight-minute
sampler of ``Eyes on the Prize.'' But commercial television and
many potential corporate sponsors were still too afraid of the
truth about the civil rights movement, the truth that black people
could speak for themselves, to be interested.
</P>
<P>
   His struggle mirrored his comments on one of the subjects ``in
Eyes'' _ the Black Panthers. ``What was really being called for
more widely was black empowerment, but white America was hearing it
as black power, and that was like pouring gasoline on the
situation,'' Hampton said. ``Black empowerment is saying, `We have
to take control of our community.' And you have to say it in soft
words, because it scares the horsefeathers out of the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Hampton found the money. The Public Broadcasting Service aired
the series. What makes it special are the faces of the unfamiliar.
No work of TV has captured the power of African-American women as
did the episode on the Montgomery bus boycott.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had won self-respect,'' said Jo Ann Robinson, who in one
night ran off 35,000 copies of boycott instructions. ``We had
forced the white man to give us what we knew was a part of our own
citizenship ... it is a hilarious feeling that goes all over you,
that makes you feel that America is a great country and we're going
to do more to make it greater.''
</P>
<P>
   No television seriess has so captured the depth of commitment of
freedom marchers who went to jail with none of the notoriety given
to movement leaders. In recalling his time in a Mississippi
penitentiary, Frederick Leonard recalled how the guards took away
the prisoners' mattresses for singing freedom songs.
</P>
<P>
   When the prisoners kept singing the next day and guards
threatened to again take the mattresses, Leonard, remembering how
uncomfortable it was to sleep in shorts and T-shirt on cold steel,
vowed not to let his mattress go. He was dragged out into the cell
block. The guards sent a muscular black inmate to beat the mattress
out of Leonard.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said, `Peewee, get him,''' Leonard said. Peewee came down
on my head. Whomp! Whomp! He was crying. Peewee was crying. And I
still had my mattress. Do you remember when you parents used to
whup you and say, ``It's going to hurt me more than it hurts you?
It hurt Peewee more than it hurt me. I still wouldn't turn my
mattress loose.''
</P>
<P>
   We have these stories because Hampton would not turn his vision
loose to either despair or commercialism. ``If you have the power
to believe in yourself, then you can confront these things,''
Hampton said. ``But if you give up on your country, or yourself,
then the answer's right there _ you won't change anything.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Eyes on the Prize'' changed America because Hampton showed how
civilized the war was for basic freedoms and human rights, from the
highly educated Martin Luther King, Jr., to the illiterate Mose
Wright, the elderly man who had the courage to stand up in a racist
Mississippi courtroom and point out the killers of Emmett Till. Now
that Henry Hampton has passed from us, his eyes and spirit are cast
down toward us. He is watching to see how we protect the prize. He
is watching to see how well we hold on.
</P>
<P>
   (Derrick Z. Jackson is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-25-98 1238EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
