<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-25 12:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9037 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NOLAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      11-25 0690
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOLAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW BIOGRAPHY OF ACHESON FLIRTS WITH PERFECTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARTIN F. NOLAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO -- The Cold War, which convulsed the world with
unknown fears, ended almost 10 years ago, the Berlin Wall having
weakened in 1988 before collapsing in 1989. Just when the Cold War
may be fading from memory, a new literature happily illuminates its
dangerously anxious decades for those who might not recall the
Inchon landing or civil defense.
</P>
<P>
   In writing ``Acheson: The Secretary of State Who Created the
American World,'' James Chace flirts with perfection in the art of
biography. Other works and Dean Acheson's own memoirs have detailed
his ``often impatient'' stubbornness and his reluctance to suffer
fools. Chace carefully documents Acheson's role and his stature
among the giants of that era, including Franklin D. Roosevelt,
Harry S Truman, and George C. Marshall, as they dealt with The
Bomb, the Soviet Union, Red China and other gargoyles that
terrified millions.
</P>
<P>
   He was tough yet elegant, blunt but diplomatic. Acheson would
not be bullied by Winston Churchill, Joe Stalin or Joe McCarthy,
who called him ``this pompous diplomat in striped pants with the
phony British accent.'' Acheson compared McCarthy to Shakespeare's
Caliban, inflicting ``a vicious madness'' on American society.
</P>
<P>
   The future secretary of state was not born wealthy. His father
was an Episcopalian cleric. (In his notorious defense of Alger
Hiss, the secretary of state cited Chapter 25 of St. Matthew.) He
went to Yale, where he met Averell Harriman, and Harvard Law
School, where his roommate was Cole Porter. Acheson regarded public
service as ``not only a powerful stimulant, but a habit-forming
one,'' which private law practice interrupted briefly.
</P>
<P>
   In the book's opening, Acheson arrives in singular loyalty to
greet Truman at Union Station after the disastrous 1946 elections.
The scene is from David McCullough's ``Truman,'' an essential
volume on a Cold War bookshelf, along with ``The Fifties'' by David
Halberstam; ``The Wise Men'' by Walter Isaacson and Evan Thomas;
and anything by Herblock, the Washington Post cartoonist. G. Pascal
Zachary's biography of Vannevar Bush, ``Endless Frontier,'' also
belongs there, as does ``Forged Consensus'' by David M. Hart, which
traces science and technology policies (or lack thereof) from 1921
to 1953.
</P>
<P>
   Chace answers the puzzlement of Scotty Reston of The New York
Times: ``I liked the guy and occasionally wondered why.'' At Groton
School, the rector, Endicott Peabody, called the teen-ager ``a very
unexpected sort of person. Irresponsible ... disagreeable to teach
at times.''
</P>
<P>
   I got to know Acheson during the Vietnam War, when his patrician
bearing gave way to an impish disposition and a gift for uncanny
analysis. Washington was a smaller town then and he was interested
in conversation, not drumming up clients for his firm, Covington
and Burling. One winter's day outside St. John's Church, he arrived
with no topcoat, but sported leather gloves and a homburg as we
attended the funeral of Christian A. Herter. ``Your former governor
was an extremely able diplomat, far superior to his predecessor,''
he told me. Herter had succeded John Foster Dulles as secretary of
state.
</P>
<P>
   He expressed his disdain for the self-promoting advisers to
presidents Johnson and Nixon with this truism: ``In Washington, the
purpose of a memo is not to inform the reader, but to protect the
writer.''
</P>
<P>
   At his Georgetown home, where he loved to talk about politics, I
never mentioned how I had once defended him against a teacher whose
heroes were Rev. Charles E. Coughlin, Generalissimo Francisco
Franco, and General Douglas MacArthur. Timothy Crouse wrote of my
youthful defense of Acheson in ``Boys on the Bus,'' published after
Acheson died in 1971. It's just as well he didn't read it. Although
he admired loyalty, sentimentality was a trait that would have
aroused the mustache-twitching, utterly charming wrath of Dean
Gooderham Acheson.
</P>
<P>
   (Martin F. Nolan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
