</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOOD OF COMPROMISE MAY AID SOCIAL SECURITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was only by chance that my appointment to interview the boss
at State Street Bank and Trust in Boston began a half-hour after
the Dow-Jones Industrial Average, the world's box-score for how
goes the economy, set its new record Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Reversing a 20 percent drop that began in July and culminated on
Oct. 8, the index of 30 Blue Chips took off again like a dose of
Viagra. But that was merely prelude to my seminar with Marshall N.
Carter. State Street, a bank holding company, employs 17,000 people
in eastern Massachusetts alone.
</P>
<P>
   What do they do all day (and all night)? They keep track of $4.3
trillion in global assets over which they exercise record-keeping
chores, and oversee what happens to $422 billion in assets under
management. And Marsh Clark, who learned to watch his step during
28 months of combat duty in the field in Vietnam, keeps his eye on
the people who follow the money.
</P>
<P>
   So who better to jaw with about saving Social Security, which is
the number one priority next year of both the Republicans and the
Democrats, if you can believe what they say publicly?
</P>
<P>
   State Street is one of many financial institutions that want to
be in the mix if Congress and the White House agree to open up
Social Security to private investments. But the stakes are so high,
the numbers so vast, the politics so intense, the opinions so
divided, and the risks so Draconian, that the process has been
stuck for some time.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 8-9, President Clinton convenes a government summit
meeting, bringing in the Congressional factions and the
bureaucratic experts, to begin to talk about how to solve the
problem we'll face in a few short years, i.e., too many Baby
Boomers retiring and too few people working to pay the taxes that
support Social Security pensions.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are 148 million taxpayers in the U.S., began Carter.
``That is five times the number of people who have 401-K plans,''
and already have learned the rudiments of deducting some of their
weekly pay at work, and funneling the pre-tax deduction into an
account that grows tax-free in an investment vehicle that may give
them six or eight or ten options, ranging from conservative to
risky.
</P>
<P>
   Carter and William Shipman co-authored a 1996 book, ``Promises
To Keep: Saving Social Security's Dream,'' exploring some of the
options. He is used to dealing in numbers with lots of zeroes
behind them, and he is well aware of the political complexities of
adjusting such a complex and important life-support system for so
many millions of Americans.
</P>
<P>
   But his banker's DNA tells him that the private sector is a
better wealth-generator than the public sector, and he is one of
thousands of experts surveying the terrain for ways to increase the
investment potential of Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   ``My bottom line,'' he sums up, is, 1. ``We should clearly have
the dialogue in the Senate and House,'' 2. it needs to be
emphasized that ``individual accounts create real wealth,'' and 3.
the eventual changes should be subjected to ``a study for two or
three years.''
</P>
<P>
   He is not a pure capitalist
damn-the-government-private-enterprise-will-save-us-all type.
``There is a very strong social responsibility ethic in the
American people, that there should be some balance in spreading the
wealth around.''
</P>
<P>
   And when it comes to the tax money paid into Social Security via
payroll taxes, he said, ``No one is talking about 100 percent
privitization.''
</P>
<P>
   The debate in Washington is about whether to invest some of that
payroll tax in some kind of government-supervised private sector
investment, or perhaps whether to change the rules regarding
Individual Retirement Accounts, or the new Roth IRAs.
</P>
<P>
   So vehement are some of the players _ the AFL-CIO and the
American Association of Retired Persons on one side, and the
privitize crowd on the other _ that touching ``the third rail''
issue of Social Security could lead to political electrocution of a
political candidate who mishandles the issue.
</P>
<P>
   It is only by chance that the Social Security summit comes to a
head as the Republican-dominated Congress tries to wriggle off the
impeachment hook by which it sought to bring down President
Clinton. Following upon the House Judiciary Committee's hearing
featuring 12 hours of Kenneth Starr's testimony, it is clear that
this Starr is not burning so brightly.
</P>
<P>
   A compromise falling short of impeachment, centering on some
kind of censure and political wrist-slap on the president's roving
hands, seems to be in the cards. That being the case, and with the
Republican leadership either changed (the let's-make-a-deal
Speaker-elect Bob Livingston of Louisiana supplanting the ousted
Newt Gingrich of Georgia) or chastened (Senate Majority Leader
Trent Lott choking on the notion of a go-nowhere impeachment
trial), there may be a compromise in store for Social Security as
well.
</P>
<P>
   No one in Washington wants to make the first concrete offer of
Social Security changes, for fear of getting torched in a political
ambush. But what about a backstage deal? In exchange for
censure-instead-of-impeachment, why can't Clinton promise the firm
of Livingston &AMP; Lott that he'll hold fire on denouncing them for
being soft on Social Security? Then some real work could get done.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine. Real work being done in D.C. Wow.
</P>
<P>
   (David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
