<HEADLINE>
HARTFORD'S RANK; CELLULOID AND ASTEROID HEROES  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Paging Bob Kraft: Are you really sure you want to move the
Patriots to Hartford?
</P>
<P>
   Shangri-La it emphatically ain't, as we are reminded yet again
by a survey in the December issue of  &UR; P.O.V. &LR;  of the best cities
for entrepreneurs. Poor Hartford is ranked 75th on a list of 75 and
dissed by the magazine _ which caters to young men, a primary
audience for football teams _ as ``the lemon of all US cities.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A sleepy pessimism permeates the place,'' reports coauthor
Bryan Dawson. ``We could have discharged a howitzer down Main
Street without causing too much disruption. ... No one seems at all
psyched to be here _ a surefire business killer.'' Ouch! In a
tongue-in-cheek effort to gauge the prospects for start-ups, Dawson
set up a lemonade stand in downtown Hartford. He sold three cups.
</P>
<P>
   In case you were wondering, Boston is No.11 on the P.O.V. list,
up from 31st place last year. Burlington, Vt., ranks fifth. Now
there's nothing wrong with the magazine's gimmick of ranking
boomtowns, but the staffers at P.O.V. need to get the stars out of
their eyes. The magazine is utterly besotted with first-ranked
Seattle and its chief employer, Microsoft, a regular Camelot of a
company that is home, we are told, to ``14,000 forward-thinking
employees. ... If you are a computer-related startup owner, these
people are your friends.'' (The Justice Department might beg to
differ, no?) And there are too many insipid, boosterish quotes like
this one from a Denver entrepreneur: ``We have active, happy people
here. There's a lot of sunshine. People work hard, but they play
hard, too.'' Ah, shaddup.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Too often,  &UR; Premiere &LR;  settles for routine puff pieces on movie
stars. Once in a while, though, the magazine goes deeper and peels
a layer of tinsel off Hollywood, showing us an aspect the movie
capital might not want us to see.
</P>
<P>
   An example is Holly Millea's superb, well-reported piece on
actor Rodney Harvey (``My Own Private Idaho,'' the TV version of
``The Outsiders''), who succumbed to a heroin overdose earlier this
year at the age of 30. Harvey was a fundamentally good-hearted kid
from the streets of South Philly whose looks quickly landed him
gigs as a model and actor. Apparently believing it's better to burn
out than to rust out, he eagerly enlisted in the fast-lane life,
but his drug addictions derailed what could have been a decent
career. A series of harrowing police mug shots is testament to the
cycle of drug busts and rehab stints and more drug busts he fell
into.
</P>
<P>
   Millea chronicles Harvey's rise and fall with a sympathetic but
unsparing eye. She describes how he was drawn into a heroin
subculture that captivated many young actors in the early 1990s
(``It was just a movie all the time,'' one actress gushes about an
altercation with a gun-wielding drug dealer), while some older
members of the Hollywood establishment looked the other way. This
would make a pretty good movie _ ``The Smack Pack''? _ but somehow
I doubt it's one Hollywood would want to make.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------ &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you believe in both God and science and sometimes have
difficulty reconciling the two, the December  &UR; Astronomy &LR;  contains
some reassuring news.
</P>
<P>
   Author Tony Ortega journeys to an Arizona mountaintop to visit a
Vatican-run observatory containing a telescope known as ``the Pope
scope,'' where a Jesuit priest supervises the study of stars and
asteroids. It's part of the evidence for Ortega's assertion that
``science and religion have become compatible ways of understanding
the universe.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Pope's affinity with science ... has been matched by a
growing interest in religion from scientists,'' writes Ortega.
``The continued acceptance of the big bang theory and the
strangeness of quantum physics apparently prompt the coziness.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Planetary scientist David Grinspoon, who writes an
accompanying essay, points out that science, no less than religion,
often relies on knowl-edge handed down by authorities. And
Grinspoon suggests that scientists, the self-proclaimed ``masters
of reality,'' ought not to get too big for their britches.
``Remember, description is not explanation and when it comes to
primary causes science explains nothing,'' he writes.
</P>
<P>
   In  &UR; Life &LR; , Frank McCourt offers a somewhat superficial account
of his journey from the dogmatism of his Irish-Catholic upbringing
to the ``spiritual smorgasbord'' of America. More absorbing than
McCourt's words are the pictures that accompany them, photos of the
faithful of every imaginable denomination.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jim Carrey has enjoyed a much bigger career than any of his
black costars _ Keenen Ivory Wayans, his brother Damon, and David
Alan Grier among them _ who made Fox's ``In Living Color'' such a
distinctive show.
</P>
<P>
   In  &UR; Icon &LR; , David Kushner asks why a show that seemed to have
``opened doors for primetime diversity'' has not had a lasting
impact. One reason, he suggests, is that networks like Fox and WB
emphasize ``urban'' programming when they are starting out, in an
effort to forge an identity and a niche in the marketplace, but as
they become more established, they succumb to a play-it-safe
mentality that leads to shows like WB's ``Felicity.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-25-98 1243EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981125.0141 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-25 12:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9045 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-BABE-BOS &LR;      11-25 0724
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-BABE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BABE' LEAVES A STY IN THE STICKS FOR THE SLIME OF THE CITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
BABE: PIG IN THE CITY 
Directed by: George Miller 
Screenplay by: Miller, Judy Morris, Mark Lamprell 
Starring: Magda Szubanski, James Cromwell, Mary Stein, Mickey
Rooney, with the voices of E.G. Daily (Babe), Danny Mann, Glenne
Headly, Steven Wright, James Cosmo, Nathan Kress, Myles Jeffrey,
Stanley Ralph Ross, Russi Taylor, Adam Goldberg, Eddie Barth 
Running time: 95 minutes 
Rated: G 
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   How are you going to keep ``Babe'' down on the farm? George
Miller, faced with putting together a sequel, realized he couldn't.
Besides, it's a little difficult to accustom ourselves to accepting
James Cromwell as the farmer again after seeing him play the
corrupt cop in ``L.A. Confidential.'' So the talking pig is off to
the big bad city in ``Babe: Pig in the City,'' which is another way
of saying that the new film takes place in a nastier world.
Although chaotic, it's an interesting try, mostly because of the
way the menacing city has been conceived. Parents, however, may
find it too dark for younger children. Even the ending, while
happy, is not altogether so.
</P>
<P>
   ``Babe: Pig in the City'' is the darkest children's film since
``City of Lost Children.'' I liked the scary city, a sort of Red
Grooms pop sculpture composite that incorporates San Francisco's
Golden Gate Bridge, Los Angeles's Hollywood sign, the Statue of
Liberty, and the Eiffel Tower, but concentrates a lot on a
neighborhood that mashes together Venice, Italy, and Venice, Calif.
Actually, there's more city than story. It's a nice nightmarish
environment, with a hotel full of animals and sufficient action for
Babe, who quickly must develop fleeing skills to supplant the
sheepherding skills that are of no use in this new situation.
</P>
<P>
   The emblematic difference between the two films is that Babe,
impressionable adolescent that he is, exchanges his homey old brown
leather neck strap for a black spiked goth collar given to him by a
killer pit bull who turns friendly. The city and its dangers, in
short, are portrayed as grimly as in any of Grimm's Fairy Tales,
starting with an injury to Cromwell's farmer, necessitating Babe's
departure with Magda Szubanski's plump Esme, his wife, to raise
money to save the farm. When they fail to make an airplane
connection at a stopover in the States, their misadventures begin.
</P>
<P>
   Before it's over, Esme is mostly diverted out of the picture,
and another human dies, leaving Babe and his new friends _ a tribe
of dogs and a family consisting of an orangutan, chimps, and
monkeys _ to shift for themselves. One of the dogs uses a wheeled
apparatus to get around, having lost the use of his hind legs. Babe
almost becomes a late-night snack for a pair of junkyard dogs the
chimps feed him to. A merciless team from the pound crashes into
the hotel and rounds up the animals, setting the stage for a heroic
rescue effort from Babe, the little pig that could.
</P>
<P>
   In a couple of cases, the motives of the kind humans are
explained by the fact that they're pig-faced. And the sometimes
Venetian city holds at least as much menace as whimsy. Ferdinand
the Duck is back, and so is the trio of singing mice. Last time,
they were sensational in ``Blue Moon.'' Here their big number _
when they're not fronting the film's chapter headings _ is ``Are
You Lonely Tonight?'' The music _ different pop periods punctuated
by operatic excerpts _ is imaginatively chosen, including the big
theme _ a rescored version of the bombastic organ solo from
Saint-Saens's Symphony No.3 that makes it sound balletic.
</P>
<P>
   Miller is going to take some heat for making this new film
inhabit a cruel world. But better that than sugarcoating the story.
He's found a way to recycle a popular film _ choppily perhaps,
episodically perhaps, but provocatively. The setting at times
upstages the characters, and Babe seems at more of a loss here than
he was in his rural setting. The pig (pigs, actually, considering
that more than one was used) isn't quite given the chance to be the
charmer he was the first time around. But at least this sequel
isn't bland. It reminds us that the ``Babe'' films and Miller's
``Mad Max'' films aren't as far apart as people assumed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
