<HEADLINE>
`A BUG'S LIFE' A VISUALLY INGENIOUS TALE FOR YOUNGSTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
A BUG'S LIFE 
Directed by: John Lasseter 
Screenplay by: Andrew Stanton, Donald McEnery, and Bob Shaw 
With the voices of: Dave Foley, Kevin Spacey, Julia Lewis-Dreyfus,
Hayden Panettiere, Phyllis Diller, Richard Kind, David Hyde Pierce,
Joe Ranft, Denis Leary, Jonathan Harris, Madeline Kahn, Bonnie
Hunt, Michael McShane, John Ratzenberger, Brad Garrett, Roddy
McDowall, Edie McClurg, Alex Rocco, David Ossman 
Running itme: 94 minutes 
Rated: G 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pixar's ``Toy Story'' team has another winner in ``A Bug's
Life.'' Its writing isn't as witty as that of ``Antz,'' but it's
much more beautifully drawn, from the slight iridescent sheen on
the ants' hard bodies to the sunlight shining through the canopy of
green leaves towering over them like redwoods. After you've seen
the spruced-up new ``Wizard of Oz,'' go see ``A Bug's Life'' to
catch the real Emerald City. Just as DreamWorks's killer comet
movie, ``Deep Impact,'' didn't keep Disney's rival ``Armageddon''
from being the summer's big hit, so DreamWorks's ``Antz'' hardly
seems likely to leave ``A Bug's Life'' in the dust. It's that rich
and dazzling.
</P>
<P>
   While both have almost identical stories _ a misfit ant leaves
the colony in disgrace, yearning for the princess, then returns to
lead it against aggressors _ ``A Bug's Life'' is better suited to
younger audiences than ``Antz.'' The latter, headlined by Allen's
trademark kvetching, seems more skewed to adults or older kids.
Flik, the loser-turned-hero ant of ``A Bug's Life,'' hasn't as much
personality, and ``A Bug's Life'' hasn't the novelty value of ``Toy
Story,'' but more than makes up for it in detail, as the flat
indoor geometrics of ``Toy Story'' are succeeded by the much more
elaborate outside world here.
</P>
<P>
   If ``Toy Story'' rep-re-sent-ed a breakthrough, ``A Bug's Life''
rep-re-sents a snazzy step forward by John Lasseter's team. ``A
Bug's Life'' has lots of showbiz pizazz to go with its visual
delights, made even more eye-catching in CinemaScope. The film
reverses the ant and grasshopper fable. Here, the ants spend the
summer industriously piling up food, but instead of turning the
grasshoppers away when autumn comes and food gets scarce, the
grasshoppers are presented as a gang of extortionist thugs that
forces the ants to give them the food, leaving only enough to allow
the ants to live through the winter so they can gather a new bunch
of food for the grasshoppers each succeeding year.
</P>
<P>
   As one resigned ant says, ``They come, they eat, they leave.''
Formidable enough when they're flying in formation to Ant Island,
they're even scarier after they land, advancing on their long,
spindly legs, recalling the dreaded Imperial Walkers from ``Star
Wars.'' The trouble begins when Flik inadvertently loses the stored
food. Hopper, the grasshoppers' leader, voiced in film-dominating
fashion by Kevin Spacey with an entertaining sneer built into his
deliveries, tells them they've got to cough up twice as much by the
end of the season, or face the loss of their little ones.
</P>
<P>
   The hapless Flik, slinking out of the colony and into a
multispecies saloon (again suggesting the varied clientele of the
``Star Wars'' watering hole) rounds up a troupe of what he thinks
are tough mercenaries, but are unemployed circus insects. Bad for
the colony, but good for the film, since it provides a variety of
colorful turns from a moth, a caterpillar, a dung beetle, a male
ladybug, a black widow spider, and other multilegged diversions.
</P>
<P>
   Denis Leary is fun as the ladybug determined to proclaim his
virility, Bonnie Hunt hits some original notes as the spider, and
Jonathan Harris is amusing as the hammy old mantis. Unsuited as
they are to suiting up for battle, they throw themselves spiritedly
at the grasshoppers, who come swarming in, buzz-bomber style. But
the eye-catching array of characters is only part of what's so
engaging here, and perhaps a lesser part at that, like the
arrestingly rendered litter of food cartons and containers which,
to the ants, are skyscrapers.
</P>
<P>
   The difference between the indoor ``Toy Story'' and the outdoor
``A Bug's Life'' is not simply the difference between floors and
grass. Some of the most captivating moments in ``A Bug's Life''
come when rain and wind and water arrive, changing the ants' world
in a blink. We know what's going to happen when the brave little
bugs take on the bad big bugs. What we don't know is precisely what
this excursion into their microcosm is going to look like.
</P>
<P>
   But no fear. The Pixar wizards fill the wide screen with
knockout colors, visual dazzle, and magnified grandeur. They'll
soon have lots of company in the computer-generated animation
sweepstakes. But they're still the front-runners, not least because
of their knack of subtly exploiting the airless space of
computer-generated graphics, playing up its artificiality in ways
that turn what we would ordinarily overlook as a mundane patch of
country turf or stream bed into something captivatingly
otherworldly. There's more to ``A Bug's Life'' than meets the
camera's eye.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-25-98 1245EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
