<DOCNO> NYT19981125.0143 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-25 12:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9047 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MERGER-CONSULTANTS-BO     11-25 1569
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MERGER-CONSULTANTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPERTS HELP MERGED COMPANIES PRESERVE THE MARRIAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was one of the most talked about marriage proposals in the
high-tech world: Compaq Computer Corp., a hard-charging Texas
behemoth known for its meteoric rise in the personal computer
industry, had offered to buy Maynard-based Digital Equipment Corp.,
the staid, over 40-year-old struggling computer giant, for a
whopping $9 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Digital accepted, but, like most marriages, this one wasn't
going to be easy: Compaq was young and valued speed. Digital was
older, hierarchical, and slower-paced.
</P>
<P>
   So Digital found a merger ``marriage counselor:'' 43-year-old
Nancy Yahanda of Yahanda Inc. in Boston, a self-described executive
coach who, in recent years, has transformed herself into a
mergers-and-acquisitions guru for top executives seeking to thrive
in a reshaped workplace.
</P>
<P>
   First, Yahanda helped top Digital executives decide which
managers should make the transition to the new Compaq, then she
advised the executives on how to prepare their managers and staffs
for anticipated changes, recalled Ilene Jacobs, former senior vice
president of human resources at Digital.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq hired counselors, too: Among them, Price Pritchett, 56,
of Dallas-based Pritchett &AMP; Associates. He helped Compaq executives
abroad, and middle managers and staffers in the United States, make
the leap to a corporate culture requiring faster-paced development,
tighter security, and more teamwork.
</P>
<P>
   As the merger frenzy in corporate America continues, US firms
are finding that once the honeymoon is over, serious glitches over
corporate culture can derail even the best planned mergers. Often,
it's not the melding of product lines or marketing strategies that
can trip up a merger, but problems on the human side. Increases in
corporate marriages have created a booming industry for so-called
integration consultants.
</P>
<P>
   Take Wells Fargo's takeover of First Interstate Bank in Los
Angeles two years ago. Touted as one of the most lucrative
proposals in the banking industry, the huge $11 billion deal was
considered an ideal marriage. Indeed, Wall Street was less
concerned with the ramifications of a hostile takeover on employee
morale and customer loyalty than on the profits the two
institutions were expected to reap.
</P>
<P>
   Then, things went wrong. According to a recent report in the Los
Angeles Times, the new company started hemorrhaging jobs, more than
12,000 in all, thousands more than expected, and clients started
bailing out. Consumers got angry when a computer glitch caused
their deposits to be credited to the wrong accounts, workers were
mad about their new employer's &UR;  &LR; seemingly heavy-handed approach,
and some longtime customers didn't like the new company's sales
approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big companies usually have trouble with trying to integrate
cultures,'' said Chuck McVinney, cofounder of Michaels McVinney, a
Charlestown integration strategy firm. ``They don't get forums
started; they don't bring people in to discuss the transition,
which is why we are called in to do what we do. It is also why we
now have the Dilbert phenomenon: employees feeling as if they are
being jacked around.''
</P>
<P>
   The number of corporate mergers and acquisitions in the United
States rose from 1,570 in 1993 to 2,857 in 1997. Over the same time
period, the dollar value of those transactions soared, increasing
from an annual total of $118 billion five years ago to $462 billion
in 1997, according to New York-based Mergers &AMP; Acquisitions
magazine.
</P>
<P>
   No one knows exactly how many integration strategists have
cropped up over the last few years, but experts say big consulting
and accounting firms, workplace psychologists, and executive
coaches are all providing such services. Some offer classes,
seminars, and one-on-one sessions to senior executives. Others
provide group counseling to employees fearful of layoffs and
change.
</P>
<P>
   ``Failure to pay a lot of attention to and put a lot of thought
into how you are going to integrate two corporate cultures is a big
reason why a lot of acquisitions and mergers do not work,'' said
Kenyon Hodge, vice president of Mercer Management Consulting, a
general strategy firm in Lexington.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1998 study of 400 North American acquisitions and mergers
with a minimum value of $500 million each, Hodge found that 50
percent did not meet average industry shareholder returns within
the first year. An earlier study by Hodge revealed that nearly 50
percent of all mergers and acquisitions fail within the first few
years _ because either they lose money or the companies decide to
split up.
</P>
<P>
   The reason? They forgot they had to work together, according to
Hodge.
</P>
<P>
   When Yahanda meets with top executives, her top priority is
easing their fears. ``I tell people that this is a defining
moment,'' she said. ``You can either live in fear or be paralyzed.
You either sit back and watch what is happening, or decide to be a
leader during the transition. That really demonstrates who the true
leaders are.''
</P>
<P>
   Will it save an executive's job? ``Not necessarily,'' Yahanda
said, ``but you will have a better chance and it builds resume
value to be able to say, `I was on the transition team,' or `I
looked at cost-savings between the two entities.' It is better to
help than stand by and worry only about your own job.''
</P>
<P>
   But consultants sometimes meet with resistance from employees,
often demonstrated by work slowdowns and less productivity.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a certain amount of resistance to the acquisition or
takeover, and sometimes there is resistance to what we do,'' said
McVinney. ``Sometimes staff think we're just management's henchmen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had people say, `This is a waste of time. I'd be better
off in my cube, working on a resume.' It's expected. The further
down you go in the company, the more powerless and suspicious of
management people tend to be.''
</P>
<P>
   McVinney said &UR;  &LR; their morale slips, as they worry about the
future of their jobs and that everything they're used to will
change. They develop a kind of lethargy _ often, they get depressed
and stop putting in the extra effort.
</P>
<P>
   The solution? ``Leaders have to give people the feeling they are
connected to something that cares about them and will last,'' said
McVinney. ``That means giving them good compensation packages,
giving them career direction, building solid teams so they are in
it together and not competing for a single job.''
</P>
<P>
   Among those leaders who have been able to calm concerns: Peter
Hussey, president of CyberTrust Solutions in Needham. CyberTrust
was established as a division of GTE Internetworking, which in turn
was created by the 1996 merger of Bolt Beranek &AMP; Newman and GTE
Corp. &UR;  &LR;  The company hosted retreats for staffers, at which they
were encouraged to air and discuss their concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Said McVinney, ``Talking can make a huge difference. It calms
people and, if done well and followed up with real solutions, it
can let people know they are being heard. That's better than
leaving them stranded.''
</P>
<P>
   McVinney, Yahanda, and Hodge agree that the human side has to be
considered amid the financial frenzy of the merger process. They
point to logistical problems that may seem insignificant, but can
add up to serious morale and productivity problems for employees
being swallowed by a new entity. Some examples:
</P>
<P>
   _A week after a large company acquired a smaller one, movers
showed up to relocate the new employees downtown. ``There was no
warning,'' said Hodge. ``The employees were never prepared for the
move.''
</P>
<P>
   _Another firm moved everyone from a smaller company it had
purchased to its headquarters, but forgot to order ID and key cards
for its new staff.
</P>
<P>
   _Employees of a newly acquired company reported to work but
could not use the computers because their employer had forgotten to
assign passwords.
</P>
<P>
   _The sales staff of two merged companies were unable to combine
duties and services because personnel from the bigger firm refused
to listen to their new peers' ideas. The result? A stalemate that
cost the firm valuable time and money.
</P>
<P>
   _New employees from a tiny computer firm known for its flexible
hours kept to their regular schedules after a merger, showing up at
8:30 a.m., instead of 8 a.m. as the new corporate parent required,
and nearly lost their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   To prevent these kinds of bad feelings and snafus, Compaq and
Digital executives participated in a management course taught by
J.B. Pratt, a strategist with Texas-based Pritchett. ``Executives
from both firms were asked to put together a new mission statement
based on already established goals and values,'' said Pratt.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, some Digital managers experienced a bit of
culture shock when they visited Compaq headquarters for the first
time, coming from their open environment at Digital. ``What they
found was that once you get into the lobby, you can't go any
further _ not even to the bathroom _ without someone else or a
passkey or key card,'' Pratt said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Digital line staff were offended by a screen saver on
their computers warning against game-playing or downloading dirty
pictures during work. ``They said, `We know we can't download those
kinds of pictures, but now we are seeing this message every single
day.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
