<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYDER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RYDER CAPTAINS CONVENE AT TCC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 BY JOE CONCANNON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ The 33d Ryder Cup matches will be contested
next September at The Country Club, and it has become a competition
of highs and lows. Ever since it became Europe against the US in
1979 at The Greenbrier, the event has been lively. They held a
gathering Tuesday, and the respective captains were in attendance.
Mark James of England for the European side, Ben Crenshaw of Texas
for the US.
</P>
<P>
   Each has known a few low moments as competitors. At the 1979
competition, James was fined, along with Ken Brown, by the European
Tour for balking at appearing at team functions. It's something he
didn't want to talk about at the time, nor will he talk about it
now.
</P>
<P>
   The European captain was John Jacobs, but James said, ``I'm not
saying the captain was the problem. I felt he was a perfect
captain. There was someone else involved who didn't take a showing
to me at that particular time. I have no intention of going into
the details. What I said at the time is, what happened was about
personalities and not misdemeanors. It's as simple as that.''
</P>
<P>
   Now he's captain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess there's a sense of irony in there,'' said James.
</P>
<P>
   In 1987, Crenshaw broke his putter on the sixth hole after
taking three putts in his match against Ireland's Eamonn Darcy. He
subsequently had to putt with his sand wedge and 1-iron before
losing, 1 up, in the deciding match of the competition _ the first
time the US lost on its own soil.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know why I had the head of the putter in my hand,''
said Crenshaw. ``I tapped the putter on the ground. It was a little
disgust, but I'd hit it much harder in much more of an anger
before. The shaft was rusted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did the best I could, but he played very well. We have a
laugh to this day about it, but it was very painful at the time.''
</P>
<P>
   The Europeans won the Cup again three years ago at Oak Hill, and
defended it successfully a year ago at Valderrama GC in Spain. They
are 4-2-1 in the last seven competitions.
</P>
<P>
   There have been questions raised about the composition of the
European team, since several of their top players compete on the US
PGA Tour instead of in Europe, where the Ryder Cup points are
accumulated.
</P>
<P>
   The previous captain, Seve Ballesteros, had campaigned for more
wild-card selections, and he even cut Spanish countryman Miguel
Angel Martin in a controversial move that allowed him to get both
Nick Faldo and Jesper Parnevik on the 1997 team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it will be a little easier this time,'' offered James.
``They've both rejoined our tour on a full-time basis. They'll be
competing for points. I've got a pretty good deal. I think the two
wild cards will be truly wild.''
</P>
<P>
   Crenshaw first saw The Country Club 30 years ago when he played
in the US Juniors at the age of 16, and the experience kindled his
interest in the game's tradition and the older courses. He is
excited about the matches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't imagine a better place to have the matches than here
at The Country Club,'' said Crenshaw. ``It's a place that means
quite a lot to our golf history. Some wonderful things have taken
place here, and it will be a marvelous place for both teams to
enjoy.''
</P>
<P>
   He is hoping that players who compete in next year's $5 million
NEC Invitational, part of the World Golf Championships, will travel
from Akron, Ohio, to Boston and play some rounds at The Country
Club. That event ends Aug. 29, and the Ryder Cup is Sept. 24-26.
Course familiarity, it has been argued, was a major factor in the
US defeat at Valderrama.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some particular problems inherent to this course,''
said Crenshaw, who also competed here in the 1988 US Open. ``We can
go through all the gyrations of how you prepare your team, but it's
eventually left up to your players.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------ &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There was a meeting at The Country Club earlier this month
regarding the formation of the Massachusetts Golf Alliance, whose
mission will be to bring together the various golf groups in the
state to work toward common goals in the best interests of the
game. The meeting included representatives of the Massachusetts
Golf Association, The Women's Golf Association of Massachusetts,
the New England PGA, the Golf Course Superintendents of New
England, the New England Golf Course Owners Association, and the
Ouimet Scholarship Fund.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that novel an idea,'' said MGA executive director Tom
Landry. ``The premise is working collectively, and having all the
various bodies working together on an agenda that will be a lot
more beneficial to the game rather than have all of us working
alone on our particular agendas. We sort of orchestrated the
initial meeting, and people seem to be pretty excited about it.''
</P>
<P>
   The first step will be an economic-impact study.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will help us quantify what golf means to the Massachusetts
economy,'' said Landry. ``We have two of the largest manufacturers
in the state (Acushnet, Spaulding), and tourism plays a great part,
and I believe it's got to be in excess of $1 billion. We want to
engage somebody to make a comprehensive study.''
</P>
<P>
   There will be a subcommittee made up of Landry, Ed Carbone of
the NEPGA, Suzanne Nelson of the WGAM, James Fitzroy of the GCSANE,
Bob Donovan of the Ouimet Fund, and Leigh Bader of the NEGCOA.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to try to come up with a mission statement,'' said
Landry. ``There are legislative issues we should weigh in on and
keep an eye on.''
</P>
<P>
   These include the Americans With Disabilities Act, which drew
national attention in the case of Casey Martin, environmental
concerns, tax issues, and equal access legislation, which was
passed in Connecticut. The subcommittee will meet in early
December.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The MBTA has said there will be no vacations granted during the
week of the Ryder Cup, since extra buses will be running from
Cleveland Circle. ``I can't recall it happening before, and I've
worked for the MBTA for 27 years,'' says Brighton's major golf nut,
Tommy McCarthy. But an MBTA representative said, ``We do it for
First Night. We plan on even extra buses.'' ... Those holding Ryder
Cup tickets will ride free on the MBTA ... The NEPGA will have a
volunteer presence on site, and will coordinate golf outings for
visitors in the Greater Boston area. ``We'll line up golf for
corporations who have tickets and individuals who have tickets at
private and daily-fee facilities,'' said Carbone. ``They can give
us a call at 508-869-0000 to find out more information.'' ... There
were approximately 41,000 requests for the 10,000 tickets available
to the public, and they have been allocated to 5,000 lottery
winners.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
