<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOU'LL MISS DREW BLEDSOE THIS SUNDAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Drew Bledsoe will eventually visit Canton. Not the Canton of
Massachusetts Route 128. We're talking about the Canton of
immortals, the one tucked in the righthand corner of Ohio. It is
the one where pro football legends give acceptance speeches, walk
away, and then let the plaques and busts do their speaking for
them.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe will be in Canton five years after he throws the final
pass of his career. He is a Hall of Famer. That's right. The
quarterback of the New England Patriots will forever be known as
one of the best passers of all time. I hold these truths to be
self-evident: The designated hitter is a good thing; ``The
Godfather'' was a great thing; and Bledsoe being elevated as one of
the game's finest is a sure thing.
</P>
<P>
   It is 1998, the sixth season of Bledsoe's career. We should all
know the facts by now, right? Bledsoe reached 20,000 career passing
yards faster than every quarterback in history except one, Dan
Marino. Bledsoe has thrown 26 more touchdown passes than
interceptions in his career; Hall of Famer Dan Fouts ended his
career with 12 more touchdown passes than interceptions. Some
self-loving players exaggerate their abilities, calling themselves
Big Money and Mack Daddy; Bledsoe is a mellow man with a daddy
named Mac.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday night, for the fourth time in the last five meetings,
Bledsoe's team handled Marino's team. The Patriots came back to win
after trailing in the fourth quarter. They have done that at least
a dozen times in Bledsoe's career. Many of us are surprised when it
happens. Many of us are goofy.
</P>
<P>
   But I am not a preacher man. I am not here to point out the
goodness of having Bledsoe in the Patriots backfield. I am here to
point out the sadness of his likely absence from it. On his most
recent comeback escapade, Bledsoe broke his right index finger on
the last drive of game, the one that ended with a touchdown pass to
Shawn Jefferson. He will be fitted with a splint on the finger, but
he probably will not play. We will learn the truth the hard way. We
will learn how valuable Bledsoe is when he is not the starter
Sunday at Foxboro Stadium against the Bills. We will appreciate him
and be grateful for him and miss him _ when he is not in the
lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Fate has an absurd sense of humor that way. Only two weeks ago,
there were loud debates about whom you would rather have, Doug
Flutie or Drew Bledsoe. Some people looked at the 6-foot-5-inch
Bledsoe and wondered why he didn't move better. They wondered why
he seemed to do a Riverdance in the pocket. They wondered why he
never got on national television, let his face turn the color of a
fireball, and cuss out his teammates for not making a play.
</P>
<P>
   How silly.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Zolak, a very funny man who does hilarious sketches of his
teammates (most notably Todd Collins), expects to be the starter on
Sunday. ``I'll be ready to go,'' said Zolak, who once said that if
Deion Sanders was ``Prime Time'' he was ``local access TV or PBS.''
He was asked what he would call himself now. ``CBS,'' he said.
``Since Sunday's game is on CBS, and it looks like I'll be playing,
you can call me CBS.''
</P>
<P>
   Zolak does not have a lot of experience as a starter. His last
appearance was actually a co-start at the Paradise. That's when he,
Bledsoe, and Max Lane performed a stage-diving episode just over a
year ago. Zolak, though, is one of the good guys. He loved it
Tuesdat night when two young fans ran up to him outside the Roxbury
Goodwill in Boston and demanded that he take a picture with them.
He did. He is also a friend of Bledsoe's. He knows what it means to
replace his buddy, a certain Hall of Famer.
</P>
<P>
   ``My top three goes John Elway, Brett Favre, and Drew,'' Zolak
said of NFL quarterbacks. ``I've got to put Drew in the top three.
Mark Brunell is up there, too. You can never forget Marino and Troy
(Aikman), well Troy, he's got the jewelry. The jewelry (three Super
Bowl rings) matters.''
</P>
<P>
   Zolak, one of Bledsoe's film-studying partners, also knows who
throws the best ball in the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jeff George,'' he said. ``A lot of people don't talk about
him. But when you see him on film he blows you away. Me and Drew
agree on that.''
</P>
<P>
   So, he is asked, why don't most fans do the same with Bledsoe?
If you listened to some local sports conversations, you would think
Hugh Millen is calling the Patriot signals. Why is that?
</P>
<P>
   ``It comes with the position, I guess,'' Zolak answered.
</P>
<P>
   He's right. The hype of history and flawed perceptions rule.
Most people are afraid to touch the yellowing pages of history
books, afraid to find that what was always viewed as reverential is
actually attainable. Take Hall of Famer Len Dawson. He had 28,507
yards with Kansas City from 1962-75. Bledsoe has 21,232 yards in
less than half the time. He has missed four games in his career. He
is 3-3 in the playoffs, has won his only AFC Championship game and
lost his only Super Bowl. Fouts never got to the Super Bowl; Hall
of Famer Fran Tarkenton never won one.
</P>
<P>
   But that is the past and the future. The present makes you want
to give thanks for the quarterback. The Patriots are 6-5 and need
to win four of their remaining five games. That means they can only
afford a loss. So what if Bledsoe misses two starts? It doesn't
mean the Patriots can't win, but they will have to work harder than
they have all season to do it.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday they have Buffalo. Then they go on the road to
Pittsburgh and St. Louis. Their last two games are not easy: San
Francisco and the Jets. They will most certainly not put punter Tom
Tupa in at quarterback. With the kind of misfortune they have had
with injuries, the last thing the Patriots want to do is have
another injured special teamer (Godspeed, Troy Brown). So they will
go with Zolak, who has five career starts.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the Patriots will win all their games. They'll just have
to do it with things they don't have, such as a running game and a
strong pass rush. And they'll have to do it without something they
did have, such as a Hall of Fame quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Michael Holley is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
