<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-COMMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOW, A JUDGMENT TO RUSH? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ For most of this season, we've been unable
to put our finger on what's been troubling the Patriots. Sunday it
will be easy.
</P>
<P>
   If the fracture to quarterback Drew Bledsoe's right index finger
sidelines him _ which seems likely, if good sense prevails _ or
badly limits him _ which it obviously will, under any circumstance
_ the Patriots' problems against the Buffalo Bills will be easy to
point to.
</P>
<P>
   That the possible end of this sad season may have come wrapped
in glory seems fitting because it has been that kind of odd year. A
season that began with predictions of a Super Bowl trip has now
dissolved into headlines about a lame duck team fleeing to the
insurance capital of America to play a game in which there are few
assurances of anything, least of all success.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday night, with banners held high imploring Bob Kraft and
Thomas Finneran to rewrite their political version of ``High Noon''
and their fans on the edge of turning into a surly band of
malcontents, a nearly dead Patriot team held on at the last second
and beat the division-leading Dolphins. To have done anything less
would have been a death knell for a season shadowed by despair
dating back to the shocking loss of Curtis Martin last March to the
hated New York Jets. But the victory over Miami came wrapped in
another injury, the last-minute fracture Bledsoe sustained on his
throwing hand in the midst of the game-saving drive.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe and the Patriots survived that on adrenaline overload as
the quarterback so many fans have wrongly criticized and questioned
for five years ignored pain, pressure, and the inability to fully
grip the football to deliver the way it was always hoped he would.
Yet that moment of glory was surrounded by two ominous signs for
the team's immediate future: Bledsoe gripping his fractured finger
as he left the field and the apparent decision of Pete Carroll's
offense to ignore the coach's sideline pleadings for a timeout as
the final throw approached.
</P>
<P>
   Could anything be a more obvious indication of how Carroll's
team has begun to slip away from him than his charges looking
straight at him as he signaled for a timeout and then turning their
back and returning to the huddle to sail their own ship with
Bledsoe on the bridge?
</P>
<P>
   We can expect Carroll's players to say that they never saw him
signaling or heard him bellowing, and Carroll will agree. It is
what teams do after such a circumstance, because the truth will not
set them free, they fear; it will only complicate matters.
</P>
<P>
   So which do you believe? Empty words or your own eyes?
Individuals, including Kraft and Bobby Grier, will have to make
that determination on their own, but it is an issue for another
day. Today a more pressing matter is the fickle finger of fate that
seems pointed at Bledsoe and his Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   After surviving 13 injuries in recent weeks to key personnel,
can the Patriots survive one more? Can they get more splintered
heroics from Bledsoe or was that simply their last stand, a night
of glory swathed in one injury too many?
</P>
<P>
   If Bledsoe is unable to take snaps from center Dave Wohlabaugh,
would Carroll put him in a permanent shotgun formation and fire it
at the Bills without much threat of a running game to slow
Buffalo's pass rush? Or, if Bledsoe is unable to grip the ball and
his passes begin to soar or dip off-target _ as Bledsoe said some
did Monday night _ will they force-feed a running game that has
been on a starvation diet for a month?
</P>
<P>
   Since losing to the Jets Oct. 19, New England has rushed 98
times for 210 yards, a dismal 2.1-yard average. The bulk of that
back-breaking work has been done by No. 1 draft choice Robert
Edwards, who has carried 80 of those times for a too-hard-earned
182 yards, an average of 2.3 yards a carry. It is a dismal record
of performance yet Tuesday Carroll insisted he would stick with it,
especially now with Bledsoe added to the wounded.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to need that (running game) if Drew is not able to
play,'' Carroll said. ``Once you go dead in the running game, you
can survive one game or two games but (this time of year) you've
got to have it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we don't answer back this week it diminishes what we did
last week. It's no time for euphoria.''
</P>
<P>
   True enough, because what the dismal rushing numbers suggest is
that Bledsoe will be hard-pressed to rely on his ground game to
take the load off his finger, especially since just two weeks ago,
against these same Bills, it produced just 48 yards on 16 carries.
What that leaves him with then is his arm, and where that leaves
the Patriots is in a dilemma, because if he uses it, it will be a
nine-fingered attack, and if they go without it, they'll be relying
on a rusty attack.
</P>
<P>
   Is a healthy Scott Zolak or Tom Tupa _ who together have thrown
a grand total of 24 passes in the past three years _ a better
choice than a splintered Bledsoe? And will it matter whom they use
if they can't run the ball in a stadium that will have as many Doug
Flutie backers as Patriots supporters?
</P>
<P>
   These are questions that have to be answered to assess the
Patriots' chances of survival this season, and someone will have to
answer them.
</P>
<P>
   The question is who?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
