<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-25 12:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9054 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-INTERNET-2TAKES     11-25 0939
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-INTERNET-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PCS ARE REVOLUTIONIZING THE MUSIC INDUSTRY 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Three weeks ago, the popular band R.E.M. released its latest
album, Up. Within days, illegal copies of the disc could be had
literally anywhere on earth.
</P>
<P>
   Unscrupulous pirates have been selling cheap copies of recorded
music for years. But a new breed of pirates isn't &UR;  &LR;  making
crudely-dubbed cassette tapes. Instead, they're creating
high-quality digital copies of the music and publishing it on the
Internet, where anyone can have a listen.
</P>
<P>
   These audio thieves do their dirty work for pleasure, not
profit. And the tools of their trade are easy to find _ a computer,
an Internet connection, some inexpensive software, and contempt for
the copyright laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone is helping themselves to our property, and then, in a
strange Robin Hoodesque move, is offering that property to
others,'' fumes Bob Merlis, a spokesman for R.E.M.'s label, Warner
Bros. Records.
</P>
<P>
   Yet this computerized piracy may be the least of Merlis'
worries.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The same technology could radically change the world of
recorded music. It can be used by the recording industry itself to
transform the way music is &UR;  &LR;  distributed . Consumers may be able to
buy R.E.M.'s next album directly over the Internet, downloading the
music right onto their hard drives. Or they might not buy entire
albums at all, but instead download songs one at a time to create
their own ideal albums.
</P>
<P>
   All this could devastate the business of traditional music
retailers, on whom the record companies still depend for most of
their sales. And the record companies will have to redesign their
own business models to cope with a world in which consumers can be
far more selective about the music they buy.
</P>
<P>
   The pioneering technology that makes &UR;  &LR;  Internet music
distribution popular, known as MP3, was originally developed to
enable Hollywood studios to put high-quality movie sound onto
CD-ROM-sized disks. But MP3 also enables almost anyone with a
personal computer to make copies of recorded music that sound
almost as good as the original recording. Equally important, MP3
music files are tightly compressed so that hundreds can easily be
stored on a computer's hard drive, or downloaded from the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past year, MP3 has been transformed from a technical
curiosity to a popular entertainment system. Free or low-cost MP3
players, software available on many Internet sites, are being used
by millions to download and record MP3-formated music onto hard
drives. A few record companies and recording artists like Eric
Clapton and Dionne Warwick have embraced the technology as a
promotional tool. They issue sample cuts from new albums on the
Internet in MP3 format, and encourage visitors to download them and
listen.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are MP3 pirates who use ``ripper'' software to copy
CDs into the new format and distribute illegal copies far and wide.
``Anybody with a modern personal computer can pop a CD into the
computer and make an MP3 file out of it,'' says Michael Robertson,
president of MP3.com, a leading distributor of legal MP3 music on
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   MP3 piracy is still only a minor threat to the recording
industry. Most home computer users have slow Internet connections,
so it would still take five or six minutes to download a typical
MP3 song. Many music lovers would rather buy the disc and be done
with it.
</P>
<P>
   But this bottleneck is quickly disappearing &UR;  &LR; . Already tens of
thousands of Americans have high-speed Internet access at home,
through modems connected to their cable TV systems. And a new
system called ADSL will allow very fast downloads over standard
telephone lines.
</P>
<P>
   Dell Computer Inc. and Compaq Computer Corp., two of the biggest
PC makers, are now selling computers with built-in ADSL modems.
Most of the nation's telephone companies don't offer the new
service yet, but many have begun ADSL service in a few cities. Bell
Atlantic will start offering the service in Boston next year.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, downloading an entire album of songs will take just a few
minutes. And once they're downloaded, they can be converted back
into standard music CD format. Then the music can be ``burned''
onto traditional compact discs &UR;  &LR;  using a CD recorder. Prices for
these recorders are now falling below $200, and their growing
popularity opens a new frontier in music piracy.
</P>
<P>
   Scary as this might seem to the record companies, there's worse
to come. Graphics hardware maker Diamond Multimedia Systems Inc.
announced it would offer a $200 device called Rio, a sort of MP3
Walkman. Rio plugs into a computer and downloads up to an hour of
MP3 files from the PC's &UR;  &LR;  hard drive. Then the user can plug in
headphones and listen anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Rio raises the specter of a cheap, simple device that could make
downloading stolen music into a new national pastime. Last month,
the Recording Industry Association of America, or RIAA &UR; , &LR;  responded
with a federal lawsuit that sought to bar Diamond from selling the
Rio. The RIAA cited the 1992 Audio Home Recording Act, which
requires digital home recording equipment to have a circuit that
prevents making more than one copy of a recording.
</P>
<P>
   Diamond's attorneys responded that the Rio can only download
music from a computer. It can't load the MP3 files onto another
computer or any other digital device. That was good enough for a
federal judge, which rejected the RIAA's demand for an immediate
injunction against Diamond. The Rio is set to go on sale at the end
of November.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-25-98 1252EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981125.0148 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-25 12:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9056 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-INTERNET-2ND &LR;  &UR; T     11-25 0984
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-INTERNET-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... of November.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   But the RIAA isn't giving up. The group still believes it will
win its &UR;  &LR;  case against the Rio at trial. Meanwhile, the RIAA is
waging an aggressive campaign against Internet sites that feature
illegal MP3 copies of popular music. ``We get calls from bands and
managers every day, asking us to get their records off MP3 files,''
says RIAA president Hillary Rosen.
</P>
<P>
   In response, RIAA uses a Web ``crawler'', software that
automatically searches the Web for MP3 files. When any are found,
the software reports to investigators who visit the site to
determine if the MP3 files are legal. If they aren't, the RIAA
complains to the Internet provider where the files are hosted.
Usually, the files quickly disappear.
</P>
<P>
   But Rosen admits her campaign against the pirates is like
bailing the ocean with a CD case. She says that the Audio Home
Recording Act should be applied to all recordable CD-ROM devices
and MP3 recorders. They should all be required to add chips that
limit their ability to copy MP3 files. ``Technology has to provide
the solution,'' says Rosen.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, technology has already provided a solution _ software
that lets record companies sell their songs electronically over the
Internet, while maintaining control of their artistic properties.
The best-known of these secure Internet music systems comes from
Liquid Audio Inc. of Redwood City, Calif. The Liquid Audio system
boasts sound quality at least as good as MP3, but with built-in
encryption features that give music vendors plenty of control over
the downloaded songs.
</P>
<P>
   To download a free Liquid Audio player, the user must provide
personal information, so that he or she can be traced. Any Liquid
Audio music files he downloads can be transferred to another
computer but the files won't play back unless the new owner pays
for it. The file can be burned onto a CD, but only once. And while
a pirate could make copies from that single CD, each pirate copy
would contain a digital watermark, an encrypted code, that
identifies the person who first downloaded it, making it easy to
hunt down the music thief.
</P>
<P>
   Liquid Audio also contains a ``passport'' program that stores
credit card data. It enables the user to pay for an entire CD or an
individual song. An artist could charge a dollar or two to someone
who listens to a song. Knitting Factory, a Web site that sells
Liquid Audio recordings, uses a 10-cents-per-minute pricing scheme.
Download a three-minute song, and your credit card is charged 30
cents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody wins,'' says Liquid Audio spokesman Bill Woods.
``The consumer wins and the artist wins because they're going to
get paid.'' Woods argues that most consumers are honest, and will
gladly pay for Internet music if it's readily available. But up to
now, few record companies have been willing to offer on-line music
for fear of theft. Liquid Audio aims to change this.
</P>
<P>
   But what if Liquid Audio, MP3 and other technologies for digital
distribution of music succeed &UR; .  &LR;  Suddenly, the entire record
business will begin to look very different, for musicians, record
companies and retailers.
</P>
<P>
   Woods sees the change as good news for artists, who can now gain
public exposure faster and cheaper than ever. ``They don't have to
go into the studio for six months and come back with 72 minutes of
music,'' he says. Instead, a little-known independent band, or a
superstar outfit like R.E.M., could record just one song, and sell
it to all comers.
</P>
<P>
   Good for the band, perhaps, but disastrous for the record
company. ``It's a potential way to lose vast amounts of money,''
says Warner Bros.' Merlis. ``We have to record an entire album to
produce a viable product.'' Singles alone won't bring in enough
revenue, he says. Besides, Merlis warns of a sharp decline in the
quality of music, as artists stop designing complete albums with a
unified theme and just begin banging out hot-selling pop tunes.
</P>
<P>
   And what's to become of the traditional record store? Companies
like Tower Records, which sell millions of dis &UR; c &LR; s every year from
119 stores &UR;  &LR; in the United States, could see their sales decline if
large numbers of consumers buy music on-line. That would probably
anger retail executives who would find themselves in competition
with their erstwhile business partners, the record companies.
</P>
<P>
   Liquid Audio's Woods concedes that fear of a backlash from
retailers has made some record companies think twice about using
his firm's technology. ``Were they to do that, they would break the
covenant with their existing retail chain,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   For now, record companies are limiting their use of Liquid Audio
to albums by little-known artists, or teaser cuts from major
recording stars like Lyle Lovett. Woods thinks the major record
companies will also test the water by issuing downloadable versions
of older, out-of-print recordings rather than the latest hits.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Mike Farrace, Tower's vice president of worldwide
marketing, thinks the Internet &UR;  &LR;  could become a major channel for
all sorts of popular music. ``There's a possibility that this could
represent a dramatic and potentially significant...delivery
method,`` Farrace says.
</P>
<P>
   Already faced with growing purchases of CDs by mail from
Internet sites, Tower expects that electronic music delivery will
make it harder to keep the customers coming. ``We just have to be
sharper and better, and make it more fun and interesting to come
into a record store than to go onto the Internet,'' Farrace says.
</P>
<P>
   Just as online bookstores haven't driven traditional book
retailers &UR;  &LR;  out of business, record stores will certainly survive
the rise of downloaded music. But they'll have to offer an
appealing ambience and lower prices. Otherwise many of their
traditional customers could download R.E.M.'s next album instead.
They might not bother to pay for it.
</P>
</TEXT>
