<SLUG> BC-CHRISTMAS-TREES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHRISTMAS TREE BUSINESS FACES TOUGH COMPETITION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JO-ANN JOHNSTON  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALTAMONT, N.Y. _ The product development cycle is long and the
profit margins are slim, but the finished products sure do smell
good.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers can start catching a whiff this weekend, when
Christmas tree growers open up their plantations and ship trees to
retailers for the hectic and competitive Yuletide selling season.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, tree farmers say, a fresh tree you buy this weekend will
easily last through Christmas if properly cared for. So again this
year, New York farmers, who account for more than $30 million in
annual sales of trees and wreaths, will be touting the virtues of
their crops as they compete for sales with other top tree-producing
regions, including the Midwest, the Carolinas and Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Demand is usually strong at Weathered Willow Tree Farm in the
upstate New York community of Altamont, said Earl MacIntosh, who
owns the farm with his wife, Anne.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can sell them as fast as I can grow them,'' he said. Of
course, that's not so fast. It can take 12 years or more to grow a
tree from seedling to maturity in colder climates.
</P>
<P>
   So MacIntosh has stepped up his production cycle in recent
planting seasons by purchasing 5-year-old nursery transplants and
raising them for only another ``seven or eight years on top of
that, if I'm lucky.''
</P>
<P>
   The MacIntoshes run an elaborate Christmas tree operation.
Customers can come for either a daylong holiday excursion into the
countryside, or just a quick errand, the MacIntoshes say. They grow
a variety of different species, and sell most of them on a
choose-and-cut basis.
</P>
<P>
   Customers can ride up into the plantation fields on a wagon that
is pulled by Earl MacIntosh, driving his blue Ford tractor. He
makes stops at different spots where customers can shop for a
Fraser fir, a blue spruce, balsam fir or other variety.
</P>
<P>
   The customers typically use a borrowed angled bow saw to cut
down the tree of their choosing. Then, clutching their trees, they
hitch a ride back down the hill on the wagon. They pay for the
trees at a little cashier's booth in the front yard and may
purchase a wreath or hot chocolate, and then drive away.
</P>
<P>
   Another selection of precut trees is kept cool in a barn to sell
to customers in more of a rush.
</P>
<P>
   In the warmer months, like all other tree-farm operators,
MacIntosh ``shears'' the branches to get attractively shaped trees,
mows the grass between the trees and guards against the hazards of
insects, weeds, bad weather and deer nibbling on tree buds.
Typically, growers raise 1,000 trees an acre.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a case of just putting a tree out and letting it
grow; it doesn't work like that,'' agrees 89-year-old Willard Ives
of Brunswick, who still operates Mountain Gardens Tree Farm with
the help of his daughter. Ives has been raising trees for 40 years,
almost since Christmas trees first emerged as a commercial crop in
the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   So while a choose-and-cut operation demands extra seasonal
attention for six weeks or so, tree farming already is a heavily
labor-intensive business for much of the year, and hired help is
often hard to find.
</P>
<P>
   In the wider view of the business, creating a holiday ``tourist
attraction'' with a choose-and-cut venue probably isn't much more
work, and more important, probably is the best way to make money in
Christmas trees, said Bruce Carpenter, owner of River Bend Tree
Farm. He raises Scotch pines in Lake Luzerne. Carpenter currently
sells his trees wholesale to groups like the Kiwanis, usually for
about $12 a tree, or about half of what the groups charge retail
customers.
</P>
<P>
   He is only breaking even this way, he said.
</P>
<P>
   While the overhead is high, low prices are also undoubtedly part
of the problem.
</P>
<P>
   For years, there were too many trees on the market, with
less-expensive trees for sale at supermarket lots and convenient
retail parking lots.
</P>
<P>
   There also is competition from Canadian growers, who have a
built-in advantage in selling to the U.S. market because the
American dollar is so much stronger.
</P>
<P>
   In the short term, Carpenter is competing by stressing the
freshness of his trees and urging civic groups to buy local. He
labels his trees with ``Pride of New York'' tags developed by the
state Department of Agriculture and Markets to promote the state's
crops.
</P>
<P>
   Other farmers are doing the same, and supplementing profits by
selling wreaths, which, at $30 to $35 retail, can fetch more money
than trees.
</P>
<P>
   But these are just short-term tactics, Carpenter said. In the
longer term, it probably makes more sense to consolidate his land
holdings into one parcel and put up a barn. Then he can sell a
wider variety of accessories and refreshments, as the MacIntoshes
do, and keep the profit margins on the trees to himself.
</P>
<P>
   Still, slim profit margins are a fact of life in Christmas tree
farming, says Robert Norris, executive secretary of the New York
Christmas Tree Growers' Association Inc., which claims about 700
members.
</P>
<P>
   ``If somebody's making 10 percent, they're doing well,'' Norris
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
