<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-25 13:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9072 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHOPPING-AZR &LR;      11-25 0950
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOPPING-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKE PLANS BEFORE YOU SHOP SO YOU WON'T DROP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE M. SPITZA  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - Thanksgiving weekend is about feasts, football and, of
course, foraging for gifts.
</P>
<P>
   Retailers have candidly dubbed Friday ``Black Friday'' _ the day
when stores hope to start moving out of the ``red'' and into the
``black.'' Venturing out to the malls on what is one of the busiest
shopping days of the year is not for the shopping-challenged.
Parking trauma, pushy purchasers and long lines to see the big guy
(that would be Santa) can squelch even the most heartfelt
inclinations for peace on Earth _ not to mention goodwill towards
your fellow man.
</P>
<P>
   Heading out on your gift-buying adventure with a budget and a
strategic plan of attack, however, just may save your sanity. It's
also likely to lessen the damage done to your pocketbook. (Heaven
forbid, you may even have some fun.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Jolly good advice
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The best pre-shopping advice comes from a world-renowned expert
on holiday gift giving: Santa.
</P>
<P>
   ``Make a list and check it twice,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (A wise man, that Santa. A snappy dresser, too.)
</P>
<P>
   Compiling a list of every last person you plan to buy a gift for
is the first step toward reining in runaway holiday spending.
Playing Scrooge by settling on a maximum dollar amount for each
gift (including shipping) is the next step. Sure, you can have big
fun buying willy-nilly for everyone from Uncle Fred to Fido, but a
financial hangover is no way to start the new year.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Budgeting' is kind of a dirty word because it implies not
only tracking and monitoring your spending but restraining
yourself,'' said Tony Cook, managing editor of Quicken.com, a
leading personal-finance site on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main benefit (to budgeting) is that you are less inclined
to make impulse purchases that you will regret on Jan. 1, 1999.''
</P>
<P>
   According to a holiday-spending survey conducted by Intuit Inc.
_ maker of the Quicken personal-finance software _ 60 percent
ofAmericans don't set a holiday budget. Yet, 30 percent think they
spend too much on holiday gifts.
</P>
<P>
   Cook's advice is simple: Set a realistic budget and stick to it.
Plan your shopping. Know _ at least vaguely _ what you want to buy
for each person on your list before you leave for the mall. Avoid
shopping for the sake of shopping to lessen the chance of impulse
purchases. Finally, don't shop when you're tired, hungry or feel
pressured. (Translation: Don't wait until Christmas Eve to do your
Santa bit.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Budget matters
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Just how much the average American plans to spend this holiday
season seems to be up for grabs. The Intuit survey predicts $1,003
a household, up from $816 last year. A national survey released by
Syracuse University forecasts that shoppers will spend an average
of $977, up $200 from last year, according to its figures. Yet
another survey, by Deloitte &AMP; Touche and the National Retail
Federation, says consumers plan to spend $814 this year.
</P>
<P>
   These crystal-ball projections may vary, but each represents a
sizable outlay, which makes it worthwhile to consider in advance
what you plan to spend.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to give within your means,'' Cook said. ``You make
trade-offs. That's sort of unpleasant, but it's much easier to do
it before than after, when you are stuck with a bill you really
don't want to pay.''
</P>
<P>
   Figuring out just how much to spend is not an easy task. Frugal
financial specialists suggest spending only what you can afford to
buy with cold hard cash (no charge cards, please) _ and spreading
holiday purchases over several paychecks.
</P>
<P>
   Those planning to pull out the plastic are advised to charge no
more than they can reasonably pay off by March _ at the latest.
Putting all holiday purchases on a single low-interest bank card is
also recommended. This will consolidate your holiday debt, giving
you a single view of what you owe. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
When to shop
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With the ``Bah, humbug'' of holiday budgeting out of the way,
it's time to concentrate on a serious shopping strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Thanksgiving Day's newspaper is traditionally the biggest of the
year _ weighing in at several pounds and packed with oodles of ads.
Clipping sales ads and cross-referencing the items with the gifts
on your list is a good plan of attack. Mapping your shopping route
with the minimum amount of travel is also wise. Keep in mind that
mall parking lots will fill quickly, so an early start is advised.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix-area gift consultant Liz Lyons advises writing down what
you buy for every person on your list as you make your purchases.
</P>
<P>
   ``Noting every item you bought for that individual is absolutely
critical because, otherwise, you will forget what you purchased for
that person,'' she said. ``I guarantee it.''
</P>
<P>
   Because a lot of energy is spent finding a really good gift,
Lyons also suggests buying that very same item for several people
on your list. Especially if they don't know each other.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Lyons recommends clustering your shopping. This will
help keep stress and confusion to a minimum. For example, if you
have several children on your list, shop for all of them at the
same time in stores that cater to kids. If you have three or four
feminine-clothing gifts to buy, concentrate on finding them during
a single outing.
</P>
<P>
   One final note. Although the day after Thanksgiving may be the
busiest shopping day of the year, it is actually the last Saturday
before Christmas (Dec. 19 this year) that tends to be the day with
the biggest sales volume. This fact simply serves as another
incentive to get your holiday shopping done early. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
