<SLUG> BC-IMMIGRANT-FEAST-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLIDAY FEAST BECOMES A LANGUAGE LESSON FOR IMMIGRANTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANNIE NAKAO  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The first day of school is hard enough for
anybody, but Kenneth Mo, 8, had to deal with his very first pumpkin
pie, too.
</P>
<P>
   He and some 100 other immigrant students at the Chinese
Education Center in San Francisco took part in an American
tradition on Tuesday: their first Thanksgiving feast.
</P>
<P>
   Mo said the pie was ``ho-ho,'' or good, in Cantonese.
</P>
<P>
   Surrounded by their beaming parents and teachers, the children
experienced the quintessential American holiday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything's brand-new, everything is fresh,'' said teacher
Marian Fong. ``Like the pilgrims.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the children, grades kindergarten through 5, are Chinese
immigrants who have been in the country for no more than six
months. They spend a year in transition at the center, which uses a
bilingual approach in teaching non-English-speaking students.
</P>
<P>
   Principal May Huie sees Thanksgiving as a particularly
meaningful holiday for the newcomers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every culture has its way of celebrating family and
togetherness,'' Huie said. ``In America, Thanksgiving is the
holiday that perhaps best reflects family tradition and
togetherness.''
</P>
<P>
   As part of their Thanksgiving experience, the youngsters
compared their own immigrant experience with that of the pilgrims.
</P>
<P>
   ``Settling here, these kids also had a lot of relatives to stay
with,'' Fong said. ``The pilgrims didn't have relatives.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, food being the centerpiece of any Thanksgiving
experience, the children got a good grounding in preparing the
traditional meal.
</P>
<P>
   They went shopping for the essentials, and helped make teacher
Marlene Tran's ``delicious candy yams,'' stuffing and pumpkin pie.
</P>
<P>
   ``They read the whole recipe _ they know what they're eating,''
Fong said.
</P>
<P>
   Then it was time for the feast. The pie was a hands-down
favorite.
</P>
<P>
   Proud parent Yan Shao Xia ate her meal with the other parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my first Thanksgiving,'' she said through a translator.
``I like it because it's so special.''
</P>
<P>
   For Fong, the ritual is part of a transition.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're just at the very beginning. Most of my kids have been
with me only since August,'' she said. ``But they know a lot
already.''
</P>
</TEXT>
