<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WONG-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN CHINESE-AMERICAN ICON LEAVES AN INDELIBLE LEGACY 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM WONG  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ We never knew her as Foo Tooey Moo, ``Moo''
being a Cantonese word of respect for older women. Her
transliterated name was Soo Hoo Shee Tom. Neither of those names,
however, contained her true Chinese married family name, which was
Fong.
</P>
<P>
   This is not a recitation on the vagaries of Chinese names during
the Chinese Exclusion Act era of American history (1882-1943). It
is about one of the last, if not the last, old Chinese women of
pre-World War II Oakland Chinatown, where I grew up.
</P>
<P>
   Foo Tooey Moo was 92 years old when she died on Nov. 14. Her
passing punctuates the passing of an era, almost ineffably. It was
just this past summer that another Oakland Chinatown icon, George
Catambay, a barber of Filipino descent, died at the age of 93.
</P>
<P>
   In their own ways, both Mrs. Tom and Mr. Catambay epitomized the
compact, tight-knit Asian district of Oakland when legal
segregation was the law of the land. Not only did both manage to
survive hostile conditions, they also left enduring legacies in the
form of large and productive extended families.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Tom's wake and funeral brought out an overflowing crowd,
many of whom were of the same generation of her seven American-born
children, ranging in age from about 60 to early 70s.
</P>
<P>
   The services were like a reunion of the children of the old
Chinatown generation that struggled in the 1920s and 1930s and
finally began to prosper during the war years of the early 1940s.
(A major shipyard operated six blocks from Oakland's Chinatown.)
Many of these ``children'' have had children and grandchildren of
their own. They have worked and retired, living now in the suburbs
or the Oakland hills, far from the pulsating grit of flatland
Chinatown.
</P>
<P>
   According to the eulogy delivered by Beverly Low, one of the
daughters, Mrs. Tom was born in Guangdong Province in China in
1906, married when she was 19, and emigrated to Oakland in 1926.
Beginning in 1927, she began having children, seven in all. In
1943, she and her husband bought Man Lung, a grocery store.
</P>
<P>
   Tragically, her husband died six years later, leaving her at age
43 with seven children to raise. With almost no education and
limited English proficiency, she raised a family and made her small
business thrive. In all, she had 38 grandchildren, 39 great
grandchildren and one great great grandchild.
</P>
<P>
   After she retired from her business, she became a Christian at
the age of 74. Her daughter, Beverly, said her mother always
practiced the Golden Rule _ do unto others as you would have them
do unto you _ even before she embraced Christianity.
</P>
<P>
   My parents operated a restaurant around the corner from Mrs.
Tom's grocery store. One of my older sisters, Li Keng Wong, a
retired schoolteacher, told of our indebtedness to Mrs. Tom. When
my mother and her three young daughters emigrated to Oakland in
1933, Mrs. Tom ``reached out to our family and helped us in our
transition to a new strange world,'' Li Keng said in a letter to
Mrs. Tom at the funeral services. ``You were ever so thoughtful.''
</P>
<P>
   I, too, remember Mrs. Tom as a kind, caring, extroverted woman
who unfailingly asked about our family.
</P>
<P>
   Oakland's Chinatown today is much larger, filled with newer
immigrants of all ages. The outside world is less intimidating now
than it was when Mrs. Tom was a young parent. By bowling over huge
societal and personal obstacles, Mrs. Tom embodied the indomitable
can-do spirit of many immigrants, past and present.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (William Wong is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
