<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-25 13:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9134 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUTO-REVIEW-AZR &LR;      11-25 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-REVIEW-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MERCEDES, NISSAN MAKE KEY CHANGES  
 (ADV: EMBARGOED FOR SATURDAY, NOV. 28) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB GOLFEN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - Two very different types of vehicles _ a slick,
expensive sports car and a practical compact pickup truck _ share
the space this week.
</P>
<P>
   The Mercedes-Benz SLK Kompressor and the Nissan Frontier SE may
seem like the original odd couple, but they do have one thing in
common: each suffered from a serious omission in '98 that has been
rectified for '99.
</P>
<P>
   When the SLK appeared on the scene last year, there was
something about the wedgy two-seater that was just not right.
</P>
<P>
   It looked cool, especially when the trick folding top was down.
With its supercharged engine, it ran like a strong little bear.
</P>
<P>
   But it had a problem, pretty obvious to everyone except,
perhaps, Mercedes-Benz. For here was a hot little sports car that
came only with automatic transmission.
</P>
<P>
   So although well-heeled sports-car buyers scooped up every
stick-shift BMW Z3 and Porsche Boxster that came along, and even
Chevrolet Corvette was delivering a much higher percentage of
manual transmissions than projected, the SLK soldiered on with
automatic only. Yawn.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Mercedes sees the light and offers the SLK with
five-speed manual and a few other enhancements that help shed its
wallflower image in favor of something more flamboyant.
</P>
<P>
   What a difference a year makes. Stick shift is a huge
improvement in this car, creating a more lively feeling, more like
a sports car and less like a two-seat poser.
</P>
<P>
   Particularly enjoyable is the exhaust note that raps behind your
right ear when you have the top down. Handling is very
Mercedes-like, precise and agile, with a suspension that's a bit
soft for an all-out sports car.
</P>
<P>
   The SLK is much more pleasant with the top down, looking better
in profile and freeing you from the narrow confines of the small,
pagodalike top. SLK still has the only fold-away hardtop in the
business, combining the security advantages of a coupe with the
sensual pleasures of a convertible.
</P>
<P>
   The four-cylinder engine may seem small for the lofty price, but
a supercharger (that's the Kompressor) provides enough extra oomph
to be up to snuff with competitors Z3 and Boxster. With the stick
shift, the engine is unleashed, revving quickly into its power band
and feeling so much freer and more powerful than with the
automatic.
</P>
<P>
   The stick shift in our test car felt like it had undergone some
serious abuse from past journalist road testers, seeming vague and
disconnected in the first- and second-gear positions.
</P>
<P>
   The SLK still draws lots of attention on the street, turning
plenty of heads, especially female ones. It's really a honey,
though still much too expensive for most people to even consider.
The Sports package of upgraded wheels, tires and suspension added a
cool $4,000 to the base price.
</P>
<P>
   More down to earth is the Nissan Frontier, which gets a major
power boost for '99.
</P>
<P>
   Frontier is the latest pickup truck to wear the Nissan (nee
Datsun) badge since the Japanese company began exporting them to
the United States in 1959. Then, the diminutive pickup was more of
an oddity, but soon became a popular mainstay.
</P>
<P>
   Frontier is the latest, but for the past two model years, it has
been available only with a four-cylinder engine. It's a good four,
smooth and strong, but not really up to the torque war that is
raging among pickup-truck makers.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Frontier also has an available V-6, a 170-horse unit
that puts out 200 pound-feet of torque, enough to pull a
5,000-pound load or accelerate briskly from a stoplight. The new
engine is available only in four-wheel-drive King Cab truck models,
however, leaving all two-wheel-drive and short-cab models to make
do with the four.
</P>
<P>
   Our test truck, a pre-production model, had all the bells and
whistles available in the SE package. That included a dynamite
stereo system (with subwoofer built into the rear of the cab) and
standard bucket seats. The two jump seats in the back are really
small and should be considered only as occasional seating for
children or teeny adults.
</P>
<P>
   The Frontier has a generally kinder, softer suspension than
Nissan pickups of the past, with more creature comforts and
amenities than usually found in this range of truck. It has a nice
ride, though with its tall 4-by-4 suspension and bigger wheels and
tires, the handling can be kind of tippy.
</P>
<P>
   The rear wheels squeal a bit too easily on acceleration,
especially in curves, making the Frontier seem more squirrelly than
it really is. I didn't get a chance to take the Frontier off-road,
but I've driven plenty of Nissan trucks in rugged places, and they
pass muster. So I'm confident that the Frontier would do well under
harsh circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   So whether you're a well-off SLK driver or a working person
looking for a solid truck, these two have each moved up a notch in
ability and desirability. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mercedes-Benz SLK Kompressor &QL; 
 &QL; 
- Vehicle type: &QL; 
Two passenger, two-door roadster, rear-wheel drive. &QL; 
- Price as tested: &QL; 
$46,575. &QL; 
- Engine: &QL; 
Supercharged 2.3-liter in-line four, 185 horsepower at 5,300 rpm,
200 pound-feet of torque at 2,500 rpm. &QL; 
- Transmission: &QL; 
Five-speed stick shift. &QL; 
- Wheelbase: &QL; 
94.5 inches. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Nissan Frontier SE &QL; 
 &QL; 
- Vehicle type: &QL; 
Four passenger, three-door pickup, rear/four-wheel drive. &QL; 
- Price as tested: &QL; 
$22,740. &QL; 
- Engine: &QL; 
3.3-liter V-6, 170 horsepower at 4,800 rpm, 200 pound-feet of
torque at 2,800 rpm. &QL; 
- Wheelbase: &QL; 
116.1 inches. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
