<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-25 13:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9161 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LAWSUIT-SUBSIDY-CYBER     11-25 1137
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAWSUIT-SUBSIDY-CYBERTIMES-EDUCATION-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUIT CHALLENGES SUBSIDY FOR PAROCHIAL SCHOOLS 
</HEADLINE>
  By PAMELA MENDELS 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In what could well be the first lawsuit involving the Internet
and First Amendment principles that mandate the separation of
church and state, a Wisconsin group is challenging the ability of a
new state program to offer telecommunications subsidies to
parochial schools and religious colleges.
</P>
<P>
   The suit was filed in U.S. District Court in Madison earlier
this month by the Freedom from Religion Foundation Inc., a
Madison-based group that over the years has pressed for an
unbreachable wall between religion and government in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   The suit challenges a program that is part of Wisconsin's recent
Technology for Educational Achievement (TEACH) initiative, a
wide-ranging multi-million dollar government effort to provide
technology resources to schools, which was approved by the
Legislature last year.
</P>
<P>
   The program, Educational Telecommunications Access, offers
highly discounted rates for high-speed Internet access as well as
special video data lines to a range of educational institutions,
including public and private schools and private colleges. Those
approved to participate would pay about $100 monthly for Internet
access via a high-speed T1 line, while the state would pick up the
rest of the cost, about $600 a month.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs in the lawsuit, the Freedom from Religion
Foundation and three of its members, all taxpayers in Wisconsin,
say parochial schools and religious colleges should not be allowed
to receive the subsidies because their participation would
constitute an illegal state subsidy of religion. As of last summer,
13 religious elementary schools, 13 religious high schools and at
least 10 religious colleges in the state had been approved for the
subsidies, according to the complaint filed in court Nov. 4.
Jeffrey J. Kassel, a lawyer for the plaintiffs, said most of the
institutions had either Roman Catholic or Lutheran affiliations.
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, the First Amendment prohibits government
``establishment of religion,'' which refers to government
endorsement or support of any religion. Over the years, courts have
allowed government to help pay for certain non-religious activities
related to parochial schools, like transportation, Kassel said.
But, he asserted, they have also ruled that the government may not
subsidize services directly related to the religious mission of a
sectarian school.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, the U.S. Supreme Court sidestepped the issue
by declining to get involved in a Wisconsin case involving the use
of taxpayer-financed school vouchers. The court let stand a ruling
by the Wisconsin Supreme Court that held that a program in
Milwaukee in which poor students are given vouchers that may be
used at religious schools did not violate either the state or
federal constitutions.
</P>
<P>
   In the current lawsuit, Kassel maintains that state-subsidized
Internet access could be employed in two ways in parochial school
classrooms that would violate the First Amendment as well as the
``no establishment'' provisions of the Wisconsin state
constitution. For example, he said the Internet might be used by
teachers and students to gain access to church materials online.
But even if the Internet access were used for a seemingly secular
purpose, like gathering information for a science class, he argued,
the government would still be impermissibly advancing a religious
cause because the information would be presented in a religious
setting.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a subsidy to religious schools,'' Kassel said. ``The
schools will use it to fulfill their religious mission.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharon L. Schmeling, associate director of the Wisconsin
Catholic Conference, defended the program. For one thing, she said
the money used to pay for it comes from the state's universal
service fund, which is paid for by a tax on telecommunications
companies, not on taxpayers. ``The money is not taxpayer money,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Schmeling also asserted that to argue that the program violated
the First Amendment was to argue that churches should be ineligible
to use the emergency ``911'' telephone system, because that, too,
is paid for through the universal service fund. ``No one has
questioned the 911 program,'' she said. ``And every church in the
state can call 911 and get the police or ambulance to come.''
</P>
<P>
   But Kassel said this analogy did not work, because providing an
emergency service to a religious institution was not the same as
offering a benefit that could advance its religious cause. As for
the source of the money for the program -- individuals or companies
-- Kassel said this was irrelevant to the case. What mattered, he
said, was that government was involved. ``The state is taxing the
[telecommunications] companies, collecting money from the
businesses and passing it on to private schools,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce A. Olsen, assistant attorney general for Wisconsin, said
that the government would file a response by Nov. 24 and that he
needed to study the case more before commenting on it in detail.
But, he said: ``It's true there is recent Wisconsin legislation
that makes these subsidies available to public and private
institutions. And it's true some private institutions are
sectarian. As to whether that violates the First Amendment and the
state constitution, I think the state will be denying that.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Olsen and Kassel said they were unaware of any other cases
involving the Internet and the separation of church and state.
</P>
<P>
   The Wisconsin program is similar to the new federal ``E-rate''
initiative to subsidize telecommunications services in schools and
libraries around the country. That program, too, has been
embattled, but for different reasons. Opponents in Congress are
opposed to the new tax it imposes on telephone companies.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Wisconsin program, the federal effort would assist not
just public, but private and parochial schools. Kassel said he
would need to know more details about the E-rate program before
saying whether he thought it, too, ran afoul of the First
Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   -------
</P>
<P>
   RELATED SITES: (each address preceeded by http://www.)
</P>
<P>
   _ Freedom from Religion Foundation: infidels.org/
</P>
<P>
   _ Technology for Educational Achievement: teachwi.state.wi.us/
</P>
<P>
   -------
</P>
<P>
   (Pamela Mendels, a Manhattan-based writer, covers education,
government, censorship and civil rights issues for CyberTimes.)
</P>
