<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-25 13:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9162 &Cx1f; tab-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANTIPORN-CYBERTIMES-L     11-25 1238
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTIPORN-CYBERTIMES-LAW-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANTI-PORN LAW ENTERS COURT; DELAY FOLLOWS 
</HEADLINE>
  By CARL S. KAPLAN 
 Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After arguing that a new federal law intended to protect
children from Internet pornography could instead ensnare legitimate
cyberspace enterprises, civil rights groups and Web site owners won
a temporary delay of the measure in a Philadelphia court on Nov.
19.
</P>
<P>
   The temporary restraining order, issued by Judge Lowell A. Reed
Jr. of U.S. District Court, is the first action in what could be a
long court battle over the new law, which was to have gone into
effect Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The order delays implementation of the law, the Child Online
Protection Act (COPA), for 10 days, and the judge can renew the
order for a maximum of 10 more days. The court will conduct a
second, more leisurely preliminary injunction hearing on Dec. 8 and
9.
</P>
<P>
   Ann Beeson, a staff lawyer for the American Civil Liberties
Union, said that when the judge rules after the December hearing,
she expects that the losing side will appeal the decision to the
United States Court of Appeals for the Third Circuit in
Philadelphia, and then to the Supreme Court, though it is not
certain that the Supreme Court will accept the case for review.
</P>
<P>
   The law makes it a federal crime to knowingly make material
considered harmful to minors available on a commercial Web site,
unless some reasonable effort is made to restrict children's
access. An electronic ``brown wrapper,'' like a credit-card
checkpoint or other adult-verification system, would be considered
an adequate barrier. The law, which President Clinton signed a
month ago, is intended to protect children from visual or written
sexual material that would be considered obscene and that would
have no redeeming social or educational value.
</P>
<P>
   But critics of the law have said that it could have the effect
of punishing a store that provides free information about
contraceptives on its Web site, or even an online magazine that
publishes the independent counsel report detailing President
Clinton's encounters with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   The government and its opponents laid out their arguments in
filings with the court this week. The ACLU filed a brief on behalf
of a broad coalition that also includes the Electronic Privacy
Information Center, the Electronic Frontier Foundation, Salon
Magazine, the contraceptive retailer Condomania, and an online
publishers group whose members include The New York Times
Electronic Media Company and Time Inc., among others.
</P>
<P>
   The brief argued that the new law, in an effort to deny minors
access to potentially harmful speech, will unconstitutionally
suppress and chill a large amount of speech that adults have a
right to receive.
</P>
<P>
   In passing the new law, ``Congress made it a crime for adults to
communicate and receive expression that is clearly protected by the
Constitution,'' the ACLU said.
</P>
<P>
   An earlier congressional effort to restrict children's access to
sexual material on the Internet, the Communications Decency Act
(CDA), was struck down by the Supreme Court last year as a
violation of the First Amendment. That successful challenge, which
was also filed initially in federal court in Philadelphia, was
brought by the ACLU and other groups and individuals.
</P>
<P>
   When Congress drafted the new law, it tried to avoid the
pitfalls of the CDA. For example, the new law singles out a
category of speech -- ``harmful to minors'' -- that is arguably
narrower and less vague than ``indecent'' speech that the CDA would
have barred. In addition, the new law applies only to commercial
Web sites, while the old law was aimed at all Internet
communication, including e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   But in its filing with the court, the ACLU argued that the Child
Online Protection Act and the CDA share the same fatal flaws. It
said that the categories of ``indecent speech'' and ``speech
harmful to minors'' are both constitutionally protected for adult
viewing, and adult rights are restricted under either scheme.
</P>
<P>
   The ACLU also argued that the loose wording of the new law would
make it apply not only to commercial pornography sites, but also to
any free Web site supported by advertising revenues that posts
material considered ``harmful to minors.'' Thus the law would
threaten free publications that posted the Starr report, like Salon
Magazine and The New York Times on the Web, the ACLU said.
</P>
<P>
   True, Web sites could protect themselves if they instituted
credit-card verification gates to keep children out. But the ACLU
claimed that such a system could not be used by sites that have no
reason to take credit card numbers from users, like free news sites
or sites offering e-mail or chat services. Nor could free Web sites
easily use other means to verify the age of users, because this
would be prohibitively expensive, the ACLU said.
</P>
<P>
   The best and ``least restrictive means'' to shield children from
inappropriate sexual content on the Web is for parents to install
filtering software on home computers, the plaintiffs said.
</P>
<P>
   In response, the government claimed in its brief that the court
should interpret the new law as Congress intended, and consider it
only as it applies to Web sites that are in the business of selling
pornography for a profit.
</P>
<P>
   The government also asserted that Congress has a ``compelling''
interest in protecting children from harmful material, and that the
law's age-verification requirement was necessary and more effective
than private filtering software.
</P>
<P>
   ``New online sites are created daily and no software can
guarantee that it will block access to every site,'' the government
said.
</P>
<P>
   Eugene Volokh, a law professor at the University of California
at Los Angeles whose writings on Internet free speech and
censorship were quoted in the government's brief, said in an
interview that the constitutionality of the new law is ``a much
closer question than the CDA.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the CDA was struck down, in part, because it restricted
speech on the Internet in an unprecedented way. ``Nobody would
dream of having a Newspaper Decency Act,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the new law is a more difficult issue, because lower courts
have upheld so-called public-display laws that bar the display or
availability of material that is harmful to minors in places where
children may be present. A bookstore, for example, may be forced
under public-display laws to sell sexually oriented materials in a
special adult-only section, he said. Or an unattended news rack on
the street may not be allowed to display certain sexual magazines.
</P>
<P>
   ``These laws, which are very analogous to COPA, have been upheld
in a great majority of lower-court cases,'' Volokh said. ``Courts
have found that modest burdens on adults are justified in order to
shield children. Maybe those cases are wrong, but if they are
right, then COPA is not unprecedented,'' and the new law merely
extends some real-world restrictions to cyberspace, he said.
</P>
<P>
   -------
</P>
<P>
   (Carl S. Kaplan, a New York-based lawyer and journalist, was a
business reporter for New York Newsday.)
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
