<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-25 13:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9163 &Cx1f; tab-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PALMPILOT-CYBERTIMES-     11-25 0901
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PALMPILOT-CYBERTIMES-TRAVEL-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMPROVEMENTS FOR THE PILOT 
</HEADLINE>
  By STEPHEN C. MILLER 
 Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For those mobile Palm Pilot users who synchronize their data
using a laptop, the synchronizing cradle is not the most convenient
thing with which to travel. The cradle isn't heavy, but its design
is bulky and it doesn't fit neatly in computer bags.
</P>
<P>
   There is an alternative for Palm III users and those who upgrade
previous models to get the ability to transfer information using
infrared technology. The IBM WorkPad, the company's own brand of
the Palm Pilot, has the capability to ``HotSync'' to an IBM
ThinkPad using infrared.
</P>
<P>
   You can download the program that makes it work from the IBM Web
site. However, IBM only supports the infrared syncing on its own
machines. Since there is absolutely no difference in the operating
system for either brand, there should be no reason why one cannot
use the IBM program to turn on the infrared HotSync in the Palm
III. Palm Computing is mum on the issue -- not surprising since
they also manufacturer and sell the cradles.
</P>
<P>
   While there is no support or admission that the infrared will
work on Non-IBM Palm Pilot units, my Palm III doesn't seem to know
that. I've been doing cradle-less synchronizations for several
weeks. There doesn't seem to be a speed problem either. If the
infrared HotSync is slower than synchronization through the serial
port, I can't detect it. The difference may exist, but I'd need
much more sophisticated testing tools than my 
start-the-HotSync-go-to-the-kitchen-and-dump-my-cup-of-tea-in-the-si
nk-and-then-rinse-it-out timing method. In both cases, cradle or
infrared, the synchronization is complete when I come back.
</P>
<P>
   While the Pilot is great at organizing contacts, appointments,
to-do lists, etc., it fails at entering lots of text with any kind
of speed, even for experts in Graffiti, its special form of
writing. Perhaps it is because I'm a writer and a very fast typist;
my inability to enter anything in the Pilot other than small bits
of text is frustrating. The new GoType keyboard from Landware has
minimized that problem.
</P>
<P>
   You drop your Pilot into the keyboard's built-in cradle and then
all the functions can be done from the keyboard. The keyboard is
slightly smaller than a standard laptop keyboard, but it is large
enough for those of us who are touch typists. The unit is well
designed and when closed is about an inch thick.
</P>
<P>
   I wanted the keyboard so that I could write articles and long
documents into the Memo Pad. But you can completely control the
Palm Pilot with the keyboard. There are function keys for each of
the major functions and each is programmable through the software
provided with the GoType. I was able to write a long memo, copy it
and then paste into an e-mail message I created.
</P>
<P>
   The GoType is very light, partially because it doesn't have an
independent power supply. It runs off the batteries in the Pilot.
According to Ken Landau of Landware, the power drain is minimal.
``If your batteries last two weeks, using the keyboard will cause
them to last one week, six days and 22 hours,'' he said. So far, I
haven't noticed that the Palm Pilot's battery is draining any
faster when using the keyboard.
</P>
<P>
   The GoType keyboard sells for $79. I'd also suggest that you
spend another $20 for the stylish leather carrying case. It holds
the keyboard and the external two pockets can hold the Pilot, a
cell phone or other odds and ends. Now if only their keyboard had a
built-in modem so I could send my column without removing the Pilot
from the keyboard.
</P>
<P>
   There are times when even a Palm Pilot is too heavy. I'd always
liked the Franklin Rex. Its only drawback was that it was
read-only. You dumped your data onto it with no way to update
without doing it from a laptop or desktop PC.
</P>
<P>
   The new version, the Franklin Rex Pro, is interactive. You can
make changes, add new appointments, etc. The drawback is that you
must use its virtual keyboard, which forces you to input one
character at a time by navigating to each letter in the alphabet.
With some practice, you can move pretty fast, but it is still
tedious.
</P>
<P>
   On the plus side, the new TrueSyncPlus software from Starfish is
a major improvement over the previous version. The mapping of
matching fields in supported Personal Information Managers (PIM)
like Outlook, Act and Lotus Organizer is much simpler. The actual
syncing has the best logging system I've seen lately. It not only
tells you what went wrong, but also what it did about it. And all
of it is in English.
</P>
<P>
   I have an upcoming three-day seminar but the Rex can't handle
multiple day alarms. The message I got during the log process
informed me that the event would be placed in the Rex, but the
alarm would not go off on the Rex.
</P>
<P>
   -------
</P>
<P>
   RELATED SITES: (each address preceeded by http://www.)
</P>
<P>
   _ Palm Computing: palm.com/
</P>
<P>
   _ GoType Keyboard: landware.com/
</P>
<P>
   _ Franklin Rex Pro: franklin.com/rex/
</P>
<P>
   -------
</P>
<P>
   (Stephen C. Miller is assistant to the technology editor at The
New York Times.)
</P>
