<HEADER>
A9169 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEARST-NEWS-BUDGET-HN     11-25 0184
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-NEWS-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
  
 Wednesday, Nov. 25, 1998     
 Editors      The Hearst News Service will file the following
stories for Friday and Sunday. If you have questions, please call
Susie McBee or Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.    (The ``HNS'' tag
appears in all sluglines.)   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For Friday:
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ The Virginia Military Institute, in
its second painful year of unisex education, is still having
trouble teaching manners to its male cadets. They booed and jeered
when VMI's female cadets joined the previously all-male cheerleader
squad. Wait a minute. Why are the male cadets jealous? By MARIANNE
MEANS.
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   THOMPSON-COLUMN (Washington) _ The public's attitude toward Bill
Clinton is reminiscent of Abraham Lincoln's attitude toward Gen.
Ulysses S. Grant. When he learned that Grant, who had been winning
great victories, drank too much whiskey, Lincoln reportedly ignored
the complaint and instead proposed that his other generals be
provided with the same brand of whiskey. By ROBERT E. THOMPSON.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-25-98 1359EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981125.0166 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-25 14:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9207 &Cx1f; tad-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPOT-BJT-COX-1126     11-25 0517
