</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Cox News Service spot news budget for THURSDAY, NOV. 26,
1998.
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   WHITE-HOUSE _ WASHINGTON _ A day in the life of the White House
begins an hour before midnight when Susanna McGuire rubs her coded
photo ID across the electronic scanner at a wrought-iron gate,
punches in a personal number, then enters under the gaze of a
uniformed Secret Service agent. An ambitious young press aide who
will spend the night clipping papers for President Clinton's
morning news summary, McGuire is one of hundreds of human cogs who
make the White House a perpetual motion machine _ running day after
day, decade after decade, president after president. Unique in the
world, the building where the president lives and works is among
the most recognizable symbols of American democracy. It is a home
and a museum, a fortress and a bureaucracy, a playground and a
monument and a backdrop for TV newscasts. It is a place permeated
with the temptations of power, of course, but also blessed with the
virtues of community and continuity. (Dart, Cox News Service 3500).
</P>
<P>
   EDS: This is the CoxNet Focus page for this weekend. Also, Cox
photos and an Atlanta-produced graphic for this story have been
placed in the National folder on the Cox server.
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Moved Thursday, Nov. 19, and repeated Monday.
</P>
<P>
   NAACP _ WASHINGTON _ The NAACP was millions in debt a few years
ago, with enrollment declining. Now the civil rights group has $5
million in the bank and new vitality on the membership front,
especially with younger blacks. (Shepard, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Moved Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT-ARTS
</P>
<P>
   MJFOX _ Best known for his starring roles in ``Family Ties'' and
``Spin City,'' and film credits that include ``Back to the Future''
and ``The American President,'' Michael J. Fox breaks years of
silence by talking to PEOPLE candidly about his own experience with
the disease _ including undergoing brain surgery, and his decision
to go public: ``It's not that I had a deep, dark secret. It was
just my thing to deal with ... I think I can help people by
talking. I want to help myself and my family.'' (O'Briant, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   w/FOXSIDE _ What is Parkinson's disease and how is it treated?
(Guthrie, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   This is the Cox News Service spot news budget for Friday, April
3, 1998. We will update this budget at 6 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   Separate feature and commentary budgets move at 10 a.m. ET
Monday-Friday. Separate sports and business budgets move at 5 p.m.
Monday-Friday.
</P>
