<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV29-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For release Sunday, Nov. 29)  
 THE GOOD AND BAD SIDES OF BILL CLINTON ,
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT E. THOMPSON  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ If there were no 22d Amendment, a smiling Bill
Clinton told a town meeting in Tokyo two weeks ago, he might run
for a third term because ``I like the work.''
</P>
<P>
   That's an audacious ambition for a president standing on the
brink of impeachment. But audacity always has been a factor in
Clinton's upward mobility.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, there IS a 22d Amendment, which decrees that ``no
person shall be elected to the office of president more than twice
... '' So on Jan. 20, 2001, if not before, Clinton will become a
private citizen and have to find a new line of work to help support
his family and pay the huge legal fees that have accumulated as a
result of almost endless investigations into his private and public
activities.
</P>
<P>
   He can, like Richard Nixon and Jimmy Carter, write books based
on his experiences and his counsel to the republic and to future
presidents. He also can, if he chooses, return to the practice and
teaching of law, which is something Woodrow Wilson tried to do
after his presidency ended. But Wilson's venture failed because he
had suffered a debilitating stroke and was unable to take part
actively in the law practice he established with his former
secretary of state, Bainbridge Colby.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also can take to the lecture circuit and make a fortune,
emulating Ronald Reagan, who made millions from speeches in Japan.
In addition, like Gerald Ford, he can make money by serving on
corporate boards of directors.
</P>
<P>
   But while Clinton is seeking ways to fill his coffers and those
of his lawyers, the flood gates will open for historians and
pseudo-historians to cash in from the sale of books, magazine
articles and television documentaries dissecting and analyzing
Clinton and his times.
</P>
<P>
   Never before has the republic faced a situation quite like this.
Other presidents have sinned, but very often the people knew little
or nothing of their conduct.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Johnson was impeached by the House on 11 counts, most of
which grew out of his refusal to bow to the dictates of Congress,
dominated by radical Republicans who opposed Johnson's lenient
policies toward the post-Civil War South.
</P>
<P>
   In the Senate, where a two-thirds vote is required to convict,
Johnson was saved by a single vote and served out the remainder of
his presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Ulysses S. Grant's administration was tarnished by scandals in
which private citizens and public officials sought to line their
pockets at the expense of the government. But Grant, whose military
prowess won the Civil War for the North, rode out the crises and
remained popular.
</P>
<P>
   Like Clinton, Warren G. Harding and John F. Kennedy indulged in
extramarital sex in the White House. But the public did not learn
of those escapades until after the two presidents were dead. Nor
did the public learn of the Harding administration's Teapot Dome
scandal while Harding was alive.
</P>
<P>
   The closest parallel to the current situation can be found in
Richard Nixon's Watergate scandal. House and Senate hearings in
1973 and 1974 gave people their first lucid view of the tawdriness
that can exist within the Oval Office. The revelations were
shocking, as tapes of presidential conversations showed Nixon to be
dishonest and vengeful, a plotter who indulged in vile language,
contempt for many Americans and an attempt to use the CIA to
obstruct justice.
</P>
<P>
   As the impeachment process moved toward its climax, Nixon
finally realized that he would be found guilty, and he resigned.
</P>
<P>
   But at no time was there even a hint that Nixon was cheating on
his wife or indulging in a raucous sex life. Nor did Nixon, despite
his amazing career, possess Clinton's charisma.
</P>
<P>
   Now, however, the people once again have seen the shoddy side of
life in the White House. Clinton's bawdy behavior has been explored
and exploited in a continuous soap opera that has provided
newspaper readers and television viewers with more than their share
of shock and disgust.
</P>
<P>
   Once Clinton has left the White House, the big push will be on
to evaluate his policies and his conduct.
</P>
<P>
   The balance sheet should provide fascinating reading. On one
side of the ledger are the transgressions of a president who is not
exactly the ideal role model for young Americans: lecherous
behavior including the extramarital sex, lies to the public and the
federal grand jury about his relationship with Monica Lewinsky, the
Paula Jones affair and improper use of campaign funds.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side of the ledger are his achievements: a soaring
national economy that has produced bountiful employment, the first
balanced budget in 30 years, efforts to improve public education,
use of America's good offices to obtain peace in Northern Ireland
and the Middle East, his promise to use the budget surplus to save
Social Security, welfare reform and his determination to make life
better for blacks, Hispanics and other minorities. In a number of
key areas, he was prodded by a Republican Congress.
</P>
<P>
   But charm, intelligence and political perspicacity have carried
Clinton a long way. For all his sins, a majority of the American
people appear to forgive him and want him to get on with the
business of being president.
</P>
<P>
   The House Judiciary Committee's impeachment hearings, including
testimony by Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr, appear to have had
little impact on the public's feelings about Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   In those hearings there were no heroes, only partisans.
</P>
<P>
   The public's attitude toward Clinton is reminiscent of Abraham
Lincoln's attitude toward General Grant. When he learned that
Grant, who had been winning great victories, drank too much
whiskey, Lincoln reportedly ignored the complaint and instead
proposed that his other generals be provided with the same brand of
whiskey.
</P>
</TEXT>
