<HEADER>
A9232 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROSENFELD-SHORTTAKES2     11-25 0260
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSENFELD-SHORTTAKES28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SHORTTAKES: Didn't cook my goose
 &HT;    (Eds: Resending for those who need it.)
 &HT;    By Arnold Rosenfeld
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Our traditional Thanksgiving bird is smoked goose. Actually, I
only did it last year, but I was hoping to establish a family
tradition.
</P>
<P>
   I have one of those clay smokers that won't let you goof up. I
follow instructions. Charcoal. Temperature. Time. All precise. I
think I must have a lech for Martha Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   I thought last year's goose came off pretty well. Until
recently, when my daughter asked, ``Dad, are you going to smoke a
goose again for Thanksgiving?'' Sure, I said, I thought it came off
pretty well last year. Two weeks later, she said, ``Dad, you're not
going to smoke another goose for Thanksgiving.'' ``Are you'' had
become ``you're not.''
</P>
<P>
   Her views are a little suspect. She's a vegetarian and eats tofu
the shape of a meatloaf for Thanksgiving. ``Bill liked it,'' I
said. Bill is my oldest son. ``Bill doesn't want to hurt your
feelings,'' she said. I tried again. ``Debbie liked it.'' Deb is
Bill's wife. ``Debbie would never say she didn't like it. The goose
WAS TOO GREASY, DAD. `` Greasy? Greasy? What grease?
</P>
<P>
   So that was why I canceled my goose order at the supermarket
this year, and we had turkey. Went over pretty well, too. Martha
would have been proud.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Rosenfeld is editor-in-chief of the Cox Newspapers.
E-mail: arnold.rosenfeld(at)cox.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
