<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-25 14:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9305 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOLIDAY-RETAIL-HNS &LR;      11-25 1015
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLIDAY-RETAIL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RETAILERS ANTICIPATE GOOD TIDINGS THIS YEAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: PricewaterhouseCoopers, NationsBanc Montgomery Securities are
CQ)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By VICTORIA COLLIVER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Predicting holiday retail sales blends a curious
mix of pessimistic analysts and relentlessly optimistic retailers.
But this year, the humbugs and the revelers are in rare accord.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides expect a sales gain of about 4 to 6 percent over last
year, an increase strong enough to make the season merry and
lucrative for retailers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to find a dark cloud, at least at the moment. It's
very discouraging for the practitioners of this dismal science,''
said Carl Steidtmann, chief retail economist for the
PricewaterhouseCoopers accounting firm.
</P>
<P>
   A rebounding stock market, low unemployment and an increase in
consumer confidence _ along with other factors such as lower
interest rates and energy prices _ account for the high holiday
hopes. The consumer confidence index, reported Tuesday, rose 6.9
percent after four months of losses.
</P>
<P>
   The day after Thanksgiving, known among retailers as ``Black
Friday'' because of its reputation for putting stores into the
black, is considered the traditional start of the Christmas
shopping season.
</P>
<P>
   While retailers and industry experts have been making
projections for months, the outlook has become clearer as shoppers
start plowing through their lists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year at this time there was a lot disagreement,'' said
John Konarski, vice president of the International Council of
Shopping Centers, a New York-based trade group that represent mall
owners, developers and retailers. ``This year, almost everyone
agrees it is going to be a good year.''
</P>
<P>
   Konarski said his group was predicting an increase in sales of
about 4.5 percent, with a strong comeback in apparel sales.
</P>
<P>
   PricewaterhouseCoopers is even more bullish on its 1998
projections. Steidtmann said he expected a 5.5 percent increase in
sales growth. Last year, he said, the industry logged a 3.8 percent
increase, which was considered solid and decidedly better than the
previous two years.
</P>
<P>
   Deloitte &AMP; Touche's 13th annual holiday retail Mood Survey
reported that consumers nationwide would spend an average of $814
on holiday gifts this season, or 4.5 percent more than last year.
</P>
<P>
   While shoppers are still planning to spend the bulk of the
dollars in the last two weekends before Christmas, industry
insiders are seeing a change in when consumers are shopping.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Krugman, spokesman for the National Retail Federation,
said people were starting to shop earlier and were spreading their
shopping throughout the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``People aren't really confined to the November-December time
period,'' said Krugman, who could not explain the change. ``People
are doing their shopping well before and well after the holiday
season.''
</P>
<P>
   Krugman said this trend had shifted retailers' profit patterns
in recent years. Retailers used to rely on the Christmas shopping
season for 40 to 50 percent of the entire year's profits. Krugman
said that figure was dropping to as low as 25 percent for many
retailers.
</P>
<P>
   Retail experts also agree that there will be some changes in
where people are shopping this year.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Tashjian, senior retail analyst with NationsBanc Montgomery
Securities in San Francisco, said he expected traditional
department stores to lose a share of their market to specialty
retailers, like The Gap and Banana Republic. That is a change from
the past couple of years, when many specialty retailers were
struggling.
</P>
<P>
   Tashjian projects sales at stores open at least a year to rise
just 1 percent for department stores compared with an overall
increase of 4.5 percent for general merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   Tashjian blames the shift on a lack of distinction among major
department stores. ``Their predictability is hurting them,'' he
said. ``When you walk into the department stores, you see the same
10 labels.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Continuing a pattern built over the last several years, general
merchandise discounters such as Wal-Mart, Target and Kmart will
still reign supreme this holiday season. Tashjian expects a 5
percent increase for mass merchandisers.
</P>
<P>
   The International Mass Retail Association, an Arlington,
Va.-based group that represents 230 mass retailers, found similar
results when it surveyed 1,000 people nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   When asked where they were going to shop, consumers listed big
discount stores as their top destination for the first time since
the survey began in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Roberts, spokeswoman for the group, said convenience
and lack of time to shop were the main motivations behind this
switch. ``When you go to a category dominant store, you know you're
going to find what you want,'' she said, defining category dominant
as places like the hardware and household goods company Home Depot
and the electronics retailer Circuit City.
</P>
<P>
   As for what people are buying, apparel continues to top people's
wish lists. The usual suspects _ toys, jewelry, computer-related
items _ round out the gift requests.
</P>
<P>
   According to the International Mass Retail Association holiday
survey, which was funded by Eastman Kodak, clothes came out No. 1
for 47 percent of those questioned, followed by toys, consumer
electronics and housewares.
</P>
<P>
   What is noteworthy is the resurgence of consumer electronics.
They fell into a slump last year but are expected to rebound,
buoyed by low prices for personal computer and a slew of new
products such as DVD and digital cameras.
</P>
<P>
   NationsBanc Montgomery Securities is predicting a healthy 6 to 7
percent increase in consumer electronics sales.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone is convinced that low prices for PCs will mean
higher profits.
</P>
<P>
   ``With these new lower and lower prices on computers, I'm sure
the unit count will be way up, but I'm no sure the dollar count
will be up,'' said Al Aguiar, a retail consultant in Sacramento,
Calif.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
