<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE BUSINESS BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These business stories for release Thursday, November 26, 1998
and Friday, November 27, 1998, are moving today to clients of the
New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the financial (f) category. Stories also
moving in lifestyle will be marked with (f, l).
</P>
<P>
   Separate budgets move daily with spot news, features, sports and
commentary.
</P>
<P>
   All stories have moved, except those with an ETA.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS-MAGAZINES _ The long 1990s bull market has (A), been a
boon to Main Street thanks to the ``wealth effect,'' or (B),
``encouraged the tricksters'' and ``will leave many individuals
wrecked upon the shoals of greed and improvidence.'' Those
drastically different perspectives come from the December editions
of Smart Money and Harper's Magazine. (Walker, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   DELTA-NEWVP _ Delta Air Lines has named Martin C. White vice
president - consumer marketing, a position in which he will oversee
advertising as well as high-profile products such as the SkyMiles
program. White, 34, was recruited from rival US Airways, where he
was vice president- marketing programs and services. He previously
worked at Continental, as well as for a marketing firm that worked
for United. (Thurston, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   SANTA _ ATLANTA _ Santa's already in full swing by this point.
Most metro Santas made their grand entrances last weekend; some
took their mall thrones two weeks ago. It's an intense six weeks
for the mall Santa, a unique breed that stays in character all
year-round. Features local long-time and beginning Santas and a
Santa boot camp. (Bond, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   SHOPPING-BUDGET _ Before you head out to the big after T-Day
sales, take heed: Set up a budget. Prepare a shopping list. And
stick to that list. If you can't be prepared for a big financial
hangover in January. ``Heading to the mall without a concrete plan
is a recipe for a holiday hangover,'' said Suzanna Boas, president
fo the Consumer Credit Counseling Service of Greater Atlanta.
(Conwill, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   SYNOVUS _ ATLANTA _ Synovus Financial of Columbus has agreed
Tuesday to acquire Birmingham-based Canterbury Trust Company, an
institution with $1 billion in client assets under
management.(Chambers, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WORLD-TRAVEL _ Atlanta-based WorldTravel hasn't become one of
the nation's biggest travel companies by relying on storefront
franchises that entice passers-by with vacation scenes. Rather, it
concentrates on the behind-the-scenes, high-volume world of
corporate travel management and, increasingly, Internet bookings.
It also concentrates on growth. In October, WorldTravel vaulted
from No. 8 to No. 3 in the industry through a merger with BTI
Americas, a larger company based in Chicago. (Thurston, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   DELL-VISACARDS _ ROUND ROCK, Texas _ In a new bid to increase
sales to consumers during the holiday season, Dell Computer Corp.
is offering gift certificates, a Visa credit card and easier terms
in its leasing program. (Mahoney, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-AGENT-CUTS _ Just in time for the holidays, travel agents
hunker down for a depressing time of year. Seems they won't be
making much money, thanks to cuts in airline commissions, etc.
(Mahoney, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
