<HEADER>
A9390 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHARPS-MUSIC-LADN     11-25 0526
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHARPS-MUSIC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOROUGHLY BRAINWASHED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED SHUSTER 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The music is polished, the voice soulful, but it's
Gregg Alexander's melodies and lyrics that make his acclaimed
``Maybe You've Been Brainwashed, Too'' an album to come back to
often.
</P>
<P>
   The disc, credited to the New Radicals, which is really
Alexander, some musician friends and a couple of high-priced
session dudes, is the sort of record you just don't hear much
anymore.
</P>
<P>
   First of all, it's not simply a couple of catchy radio tunes and
a ton of filler, like so many other albums from new or developing
artists.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander, as Rolling Stone said in its recent review of
``Brainwashed,'' is clearly a deep thinker, and his songs stand
repeated listenings at home and on the radio, where the New
Radicals cut ``You Get What You Give'' has fast found a home.
</P>
<P>
   Grosse Point, Mich.-bred Alexander, 27, is essentially an
unknown quantity, even though he made an album for A&AMP;M in 1989.
After grunge arrived a few years later and swept away all that came
before, Alexander moved to Europe, where he had some of the dark
adventures chronicled in ``Brainwashed'' (MCA).
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of these tunes are based on experience, for better or
worse,'' Alexander said last week. ``There's definitely some strong
similarities between fact and fiction. Some of these songs are
really dark.''
</P>
<P>
   One of those songs might be album standout ``I Hope I Didn't
Just Give Away the Ending,'' in which the narrator meets a girl in
Amsterdam, they go off to buy illicit substances and end up ``doing
a porno film for coke/I hear I'm big in Japan.'' Eventually someone
dies, the police show up and ``I'm blamed in the confusion.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexander admits to listening to a lot of Steely Dan as well
Prefab Sprout's mid-'80s pop masterpiece ``Two Wheels Good.''
Adding to his new album's sheen are key contributions from such
high-profile session players as percussionist Lenny Castro and
pianist Greg Phillinganes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried a lot of different people to play piano, because it
was a real communal record-making process at the end,'' Alexander
explained. ``If there was a piano part and it didn't sound good,
I'd bring in two or three people and have them take a crack at
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Some have said Alexander's ``Brainwashed'' is as close to
blue-eyed soul as you get these days. Alexander, who produced and
arranged the disc, agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people who are prone to like the music are having an
emotional reaction to it,'' he said. ``When it gets under people's
skin, that's attributable to the fact that these songs aren't
lighter than air. There's an emotional content to the music.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexander _ who plans a Los Angeles date in the new year _ said
that when demo tapes of his New Radicals material began to
circulate in the industry last year, ``people started coming at me
with checkbooks.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he realizes that there are no guarantees in this
business.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know if it would be like that Steve Miller song _ `I
might get rich, I might get busted,''' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
