<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-$ADV27-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAH, RAH, SORT OF 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Friday, Nov. 27)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The male cadets of Virginia Military Institute, in
their second awkward year of unisex education, are still having an
attitude adjustment problem.
</P>
<P>
   After female cadets were added to the previously all-male
football cheerleader squad, the male fans did not react like the
gentlemen-officers they are in training to become. They booed,
jeered and threw peanuts at the women during home football games in
Lexington, Va. They shouted ``Get out of here. We don't want you!''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, for pity's sake. Get a life, guys. Are male VMI cadets all
terminally juvenile or is there too much beer sold at the games?
</P>
<P>
   This is an odd twist in the gender wars. Some of us thought that
equal rights were supposed to free women from having to be
cheerleaders on the sidelines while men got to be the players on
the central field. It is something of a role reversal that men are
now jealous that their female classmates are among the
cheerleaders.
</P>
<P>
   Some cadets circulated a petition claiming that watching fellow
students in short cheerleader skirts was creating ``sexual
tension.'' This would seem to mean it's fantastically easy to
arouse a VMI cadet. Cosmopolitan magazine, please take notice.
There's a story in this.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the male cadets are trying to argue it both ways. Some
contend the women aren't sexy enough. The ultimate insult was
delivered by Jason Clough, a cadet from Florida. ``They don't look
like cheerleaders,'' he said, because of their close-cropped
military haircuts. ``They look like men in skirts.'' Sure. Get a
new pair of glasses, pal.
</P>
<P>
   Gussie Lord, a sophomore female cheerleader, by now a veteran of
such macho male foolishness, responded sensibly, ``Just because we
go here (attend VMI) doesn't mean we're not feminine, that we're
not women.''
</P>
<P>
   Female cheerleaders are not a novelty at VMI. For years there
have been cheerleaders of both sexes, but the women were imported
from neighboring schools for VMI football games. This apparently
made them less threatening or provocative or whatever it is that
bugs the male cadets other than women who happen to share the same
classroom with them.
</P>
<P>
   VMI is not accustomed to a class of cadets composed of both men
and women equally eligible for cheerleading and every other
competitive campus leadership role. Other colleges take it for
granted that men and women can peacefully participate in school
activities side by side. But the male-oriented military atmosphere
at VMI makes such a comfort level difficult to achieve.
</P>
<P>
   VMI reluctantly surrendered its male-only status after the
Supreme Court ruled in 1996 that it could not simultaneously take
tax revenues from the state of Virginia and discriminate against
women. It was the last state-supported college in the country to
exclude women, having spent millions of dollars over six years
fighting integration. VMI's patrons could not raise enough money to
support the school privately. So they were legally forced to accept
women to keep state revenues flowing.
</P>
<P>
   This year's freshman class includes 50 women and 1,250 men. Two
women and 30 men dropped out earlier this year for undisclosed
reasons. Last year, the first in which women were admitted, there
were 31 female students.
</P>
<P>
   VMI President Josiah Bunting has taken serious steps to
encourage a civilized academic environment, hoping to avoid the
scandals that initially beset The Citadel in Charleston, S.C.,
after it was forced to accept female cadets against its will two
years before VMI's own transformation. Bunting has required
coeducation orientation sessions, seminars on the evils of sexual
harassment and committee studies on transition problems.
</P>
<P>
   Bunting insists he will punish anyone who physically abuses a
female student. But he also confessed last year to a National Press
Club audience that his heart was not with the women. He said he
personally thought admitting women was a bad idea bound to diminish
the importance and quality of VMI's military-style education.
</P>
<P>
   The cheerleader episode is more of a silly social commentary
than a serious threat to the principle of coeducation. But VMI
should be ashamed of itself. This is not the way that potential
leaders of our army should behave.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
