<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-25 15:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9398 &Cx1f; tth-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-HUSKIES-BENDER-SP     11-25 2643
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-HUSKIES-BENDER-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOB BENDER IS ON TOP OF HIS GAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BUD WITHERS  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bob Bender is at his favorite lunch spot near the University of
Washington campus. For a couple of hours, he's Norm or Cliff from
Cheers, at a hangout where everybody seems to know his name.
</P>
<P>
   ``Regular,'' Bender advises the waitress, and soon she brings
him a plate of rigatoni and a salad.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, there is a small gathering of thirtysomething women, a
couple of them with babies, and they're stealing he occasional
glance toward Bender. And you're not sure whether it's because he's
the basketball coach at the UW, or because, even at 40, he's not
all that far advanced from the campus heart throb he was at Duke a
decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very lucky,'' Bender is saying.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody says they're lucky. People who lose a limb in combat
say they're lucky because they weren't killed. But Bender is lucky.
Everything seems in order: A wife with an MBA from Duke, two
beautiful children _ one boy, one girl, naturally _ a life in a
gorgeous city and a job seemingly without the knifing pressure
common to his profession. What else is there?
</P>
<P>
   More than good fortune, though, perhaps this is the reality:
Maybe he's only gotten back what he's put into it. Maybe this is
what happens when you never utter an untoward word about anybody,
when you don't hold grudges, when you're willing to find out for
yourself somebody's a jerk rather than assume it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it's the Midwestern upbringing,'' said author John
Feinstein, a Duke classmate of Bender. ``Bob was obviously taught
by his parents to be nice to people. Bob can find that nugget of
good that exists in almost all people.''
</P>
<P>
   Some 5{ 1/2 years after Bender arrived at Washington, he has
accomplished something even more remarkable than last winter's
memorable thrust into March Madness.
</P>
<P>
   For so long, the operative question on Washington basketball
was, Can anybody possibly win here? Now it's, Why couldn't those
other guys?
</P>
<P>
   He came down the elevator at the Westin Hotel the evening of
April 8, 1993, expecting to be told in the lobby by UW athletic
director Barbara Hedges that for the second time in five years, he
had lost out to John Shumate for a job.
</P>
<P>
   Bender was ready for it. As a Duke assistant coach, he once was
buoyant and full of optimism that he would get the vacant job at
Radford, a small Virginia school. Back came a written reply: ``Dear
Applicant ... ''
</P>
<P>
   There also was his attempt at the position at Southern Methodist
in the late '80s, when Shumate won out. Now, with Washington a year
removed from an ugly succession of charges and counter-charges of
racism in the program, it made some sense that Shumate, an African
American, would land the position.
</P>
<P>
   Hedges surprised Bender with a job offer. And he retreated to
the elevator, ordered a pizza for him and his wife, Alice, and went
about rebuilding one of the most destitute programs in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies, authors of six straight non-winning seasons, were
not only bad, they were repellent. High school coaches were
alienated. Media warred with the coach. Hardly anybody showed up at
games. Nobody cared. And seemingly, nobody cared that nobody cared.
</P>
<P>
   The first thing Bender did was make it worse.
</P>
<P>
   Intent on attracting a player or two who could help the team
quickly, he recruited Derrick Croft, a guard from Skagit Valley
Junior College. Believing an NCAA rule prevented him from
off-campus recruiting for a certain period, he had Croft visit
campus.
</P>
<P>
   Then he was informed by a UW official it was an NCAA ``dead
period,'' with all recruiting prohibited. A week after he started,
he had committed an NCAA violation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm thinking, `Am I not the right person for this job?'''
Bender recalls now. ``How could I make this kind of mistake?''
</P>
<P>
   There would be more hard times. The Huskies would go 5-22 that
year. They would be 9-18 the year after. The program was creating
hardly a ripple of interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no pressure from the administration,'' says Ray
Giacoletti, an assistant coach on those staffs. ``But everybody was
questioning, Are we going to get this thing turned around? Bob kept
everybody focused and pushing on.''
</P>
<P>
   Even then, there was something intriguing going on. By the sheer
force of his personality, Bender kept a positive face on the
program. He had welcomed back two players kicked off the team in
the previous regime. He had retained the walk-on players. He opened
the doors to practice to the media _ not sometimes, all the time.
</P>
<P>
   He gave, and he got back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could see light at the end of the tunnel,'' he says. ``The
core was building. At the same time, we also knew the third year
that we had to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one told me that. I said that. Your third year, you should
be able to win.''
</P>
<P>
   At long last, they did.
</P>
<P>
   Lucky? You want luck? How about the day Bob Bender was a
freshman in high school at Quincy (Ill.) Catholic, playing for his
dad, Bob Sr.? He came out of the shower at the Illinois state
tournament in Champaign, fresh off a one-point loss to
Lawrenceville, and who is standing there wanting to shake hands but
Red Auerbach? Red Auerbach, the coach/deity of the Boston Celtics.
</P>
<P>
   ``He says, `Is your son really 14 years old?''' remembers Bob
Bender Sr. ```I'd like to meet him.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``I had an idea what he was like,'' says the younger Bender.
``Real crusty, matter-of-fact. It was, `Tell me I'm not good
enough. Tell me to work harder.'
</P>
<P>
   ``And that's what he did say.''
</P>
<P>
   Bender would soon know other big-name coaches. He grew to
6-foot-3, played point guard and was heavily recruited. Among those
he saw most at his games was Mike Krzyzewski, a young assistant for
Bob Knight at Indiana. Krzyzewski once saw him score 50 points in a
tournament game.
</P>
<P>
   Back then, the name Knight was magical. When he came to recruit
Midwest kids, they followed. Bender and his parents found his
honesty refreshing.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, that honesty would bury Bender. He struggled through a
freshman year at Indiana in 1975-76, a reserve on an Indiana team
that went 32-0, won the NCAA championship and is recognized as one
of the best of all time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't sense any problems with Bob,'' says Tom Abernethy, a
starting forward on that team. ``We were all focused on what we had
to do, being undefeated and all that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it was evident he was not happy. Some guys, when
they're not happy, can be very disruptive on a team.''
</P>
<P>
   Slowly, Knight was killing Bender, whose dad had not coached by
screaming. Every day, he would retreat to his dorm with his
freshman roommate, Rich Valavicius, two kids trying to survive the
most demanding coach in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Bender has always put it on himself, saying he wasn't mature
enough to handle Knight. But Valavicius, now a high school coach in
Huntsville, Ala., reveals what he and Bender what through.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got to the point _ and I think Bob had the same thing _ I
wanted to do so good for him, I didn't know whether to pass or
shoot,'' Valavicius says. ``He had my head all screwed up.''
</P>
<P>
   Well into the year, word got out that Bender and Valavicius
might want to transfer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Next thing you know, Knight calls us down to his locker room,
both of us,'' Valavicius says. ``We came in there, scared to death.
`Listen, you two s---heads. I heard you're leaving. What's all this
about?' I'd never been called a s---head before.''
</P>
<P>
   Terrified, Bender and Valavicius stammered out that no, there
was nothing to it. A little older, they might have known that
Knight blew up at everybody.
</P>
<P>
   Once, the team was sitting on a bus waiting to take them to an
NCAA regional game. Outside were Hoosier admirers, including
Knight's then-wife Nancy, and their infant son Pat, now an
assistant coach to his dad.
</P>
<P>
   SKRRK! Knight rammed open his window on the bus.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nancy!'' he bellowed. ``Get a bleeping coat on that kid!''
</P>
<P>
   Another time, Scott May, the superlative Indiana forward, had a
huge game in a one-point victory at Ohio State but the Hoosiers had
to survive a last-second missed layup by the Buckeyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just chewed out May,'' Valavicius says. ``Put his hand
through the blackboard and chewed him out.''
</P>
<P>
   The team boarded a bus, where it was halted by a passing train.
Two miles down the road was a gate where the bus could avoid the
train, but the driver waited.
</P>
<P>
   ``Knight is ticked,'' Valavicius says. ``He gets right in the
bus driver's ear and just chews him out. That man sat there and
looked straight ahead. He got 40 minutes of ass-chewing.''
</P>
<P>
   Bender returned in the fall of 1976, willing to give Indiana
another chance. Soon he realized it was no different, and he
summoned up the courage to go in and tell Knight he was leaving.
</P>
<P>
   ``You didn't go in just to see Coach Knight,'' Bender says.
``The first 15 minutes, I was just crying. It was one of the
hardest things I've ever had to do.'' But Knight was calm. He told
Bender to give it a day. Bender called his parents to tell them.
</P>
<P>
   The family spent two hours the next day with Knight. When it was
done, Bender was moving on.
</P>
<P>
   Soon afterward, Bender flew to Duke to begin the process of
school selection all over again. But Bill Foster, the coach, told
him he wasn't going to recruit him, so he spent most of his time
with the players.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wasn't there eight hours,'' the senior Bender says, ``and
he said he wanted to stay.''
</P>
<P>
   Bender immediately took to center Mike Gminski, and Foster was
recruiting a great freshman class that in 1978 would take the Blue
Devils all the way to the NCAA championship game, a loss against
Kentucky. Bender is the only player in history to take part in the
title game for two schools.
</P>
<P>
   When there was a debate over who should start at point guard
during that '78 season _ Bender or another transfer, Johnny Harrell
_ Bender made it work by accepting a role as a key substitute.
</P>
<P>
   After graduation, he got a quick look by the NBA, then went back
to Duke as an athletic fund-raiser. By 1983, he was wondering what
to do with his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realized I'm not very good at asking people for things,''
Bender says. ``Money, favors or anything. People were complaining
about the program, and I thought, `Why am I listening to this? I'd
rather be a part of it.'''
</P>
<P>
   By then, Krzyzewski had replaced Foster at Duke, launching his
illustrious tenure there with two losing seasons. Bender sought out
Krzyzewski, who needed convincing he should hire Bender to his
staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't just hire him, I wanted to make sure he really wanted
it,'' Krzyzewski said. ``Kind of like what you put a player
through.''
</P>
<P>
   There was an interview, and a second one and a third one. Bender
and Krzyzewski had played some occasional tennis, and Krzyzewski,
the deathless competitor, didn't think Bender fought him hard
enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``I shouldn't beat you,'' Krzyzewski told Bender. ``But I beat
you all the time.'' Eventually, Bender won over Krzyzewski. He
proved a valuable link from the principals of the Foster regime to
the ascendant Krzyzewski era.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a real people person,'' Krzyzewski said. ``As a result,
the acceptance level was big with the former players. I didn't know
that would happen, but it did.''
</P>
<P>
   It was about that time that Bender, in Charlotte with friends at
the grand opening of a condominium/shopping complex, ran into Alice
Hunter, a former coed at Duke. He called her and said they would
all be going to dinner that night, and wouldn't it be a great
business opportunity to see these Duke grads?
</P>
<P>
   ``I had that little angle,'' Bender said sheepishly. ``She wound
up coming to meet us, and we had a great time.''
</P>
<P>
   She eventually moved to Washington, D.C., returned to Duke for
an advanced degree, and they dated.
</P>
<P>
   Then one night, he got up from dinner at a Greek restaurant in
Durham and phoned her father in St. Petersburg, Fla. Moments later,
on a spring evening with the dogwoods in bloom on the Gothic-style
Duke campus, Bender asked Alice Hunter if she would marry him.
</P>
<P>
   She accepted, and quickly, he was off to take the head coaching
job at Illinois State.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not luck,'' insists Kevin Billerman, the coach at Florida
Atlantic and Bender's best friend. ``He held out a long time,
looking for the right woman. He wasn't ever going to go through a
divorce.''
</P>
<P>
   It is as difficult to find someone saying anything bad about
Bender as it is these days to find players who wear short
basketball pants. Somehow, he manages to bite his tongue when he
most wants to lash out.
</P>
<P>
   Early in his Washington tenure, he lost a standout local
recruit, Michael Dickerson, to Arizona. A year later, his staff
earned a verbal commitment from another Seattle plum, Jason Terry _
and then Terry backpedaled and went to Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to remember my past,'' Bender says. ``I had to make a
change. My gosh, how could I point a finger and say, `That's not
right?' You know what, he's a good example of what more kids need
to be able to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's won a national championship, so it's the right decision
overall. And he waited his turn.''
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, in one of his frequent conversations with Billerman,
Bender learned that Florida Atlantic had been stunned by the death
of one of its players.
</P>
<P>
   ``He called me every day for three weeks,'' Billerman said. ``He
investigated other coaches who had had someone die, and had them
call me.''
</P>
<P>
   There are those times when his parents are visiting, and
somebody will want a little chunk of Bender's time. ``The damn
phone never stops ringing,'' said his father. ``People are asking
him to do things. He doesn't have his palm out, he just goes and
goes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope his kids get to know him. I went through that, and it
was only on the high school level. And I really didn't get to watch
my three kids grow up.''
</P>
<P>
   More than one coach with an agreeable personality has found
himself out of a job for lack of discipline. But Bender tempers his
sunny side with a serious competitive streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``At Illinois State, we used to play two-on-two at lunch,''
Giacoletti said. ``Whether it was racquetball or basketball, he
hated to lose. And he wasn't going to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   What's down the road for Bob Bender? A higher-profile school
where an NCAA championship is more realistic? Does he have interest
in the NBA?
</P>
<P>
   ``None at all,'' he says. ``I couldn't coach 82 games.
Twenty-seven is draining.''
</P>
<P>
   Bender loves Seattle, a place just dispassionate enough about
Husky basketball that he and Alice can go out to places like Wild
Ginger and not be swarmed. At home, he has an infant son, and when
his 3-year-old daughter Mary Elizabeth wants to play Ariel from
Disney's The Little Mermaid, he has to be Prince Eric.
</P>
<P>
   ``His daughter,'' says Alice Bender, ``thinks he hung the
moon.''
</P>
<P>
   Bender's idyll is to spend the last years of his career at a
little school where nobody comes to interview him and he doesn't
have to speak at booster clubs or spend summer days watching
recruits at shoe-sponsored camps.
</P>
<P>
   His father scoffs at the idea. But Billerman says, ``I believe
it's something Bobby will do when he's 55 years old.''
</P>
<P>
   One place Bender apparently won't be is the University of Texas,
which courted him hard last spring before he removed his name.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were an outsider looking in, would that be a statement I
plan on being here a long time?'' Bender asks. ``Yeah.''
</P>
<P>
   Mixing with Texas officials and major boosters, he was asked the
question: ``What do you want to do with your career?''
</P>
<P>
   Bender stopped them with this: ``I just want to be a good
person.''
</P>
<P>
   The Longhorn faithful looked at each other. They made another
hire. So _ for who knows how long _ Washington is left with Bob
Bender, merely a good person.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
