<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-25 15:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9401 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-KIDS-SPI &LR;      11-25 2017
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-KIDS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LASTING MEMORIES WILL BE IN THE BAG WITH TIMELESS TALES FOR KIDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CECELIA GOODNOW  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nostalgia is always big at the holidays. As the millennium
approaches, some children's books are casting an especially long
backward glance at where we've come in past centuries. What better
time to take stock?
</P>
<P>
   You'll find a couple of such titles on our list of holiday
children's books, along with others whose appeal is, well,
timeless. From good-natured silliness to sober historical
perspective, there's something for nearly everyone.
</P>
<P>
   Read on!
</P>
<P>
   PICTURE BOOKS
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Christmas Crocodile,'' by Bonny Becker, illustrated by
David Small (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $16). Ages 4-8.
</P>
<P>
   The Christmas Crocodile doesn't mean to be bad, not really. He
just shows up under the tree on Christmas Eve with a lovely red bow
(which he eats), then innocently wreaks havoc on a twittery
Victorian family. Only a Grinch could resist this delightful romp _
written, incidentally, by a Seattle author. Comically overwrought
pictures add to the fun.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``No, David!'' by David Shannon (Blue Sky Press, $14.95). Ages
3-6.
</P>
<P>
   If this book captures the Zen of childhood mischief, it's
because Shannon was only 5, growing up in Spokane, when he wrote
the prototype. (He now lives in Los Angeles.) Here, the
fiendish-looking David tracks in mud, bangs a pot, yells, plays
with his food, even runs naked down the street as his harried
mother yells, ``No, David!'' Rest easy: It ends with childish tears
of remorse, a warm embrace and the reassuring words, ``Yes, David
... I love you!'' Recently named a New York Times Best Illustrated
Children's Book.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``To Everything There is a Season: Verses from Ecclesiastes,''
by Leo and Diane Dillon (Blue Sky Press, $15.95). All ages.
</P>
<P>
   The Dillons' artistic range is simply astounding. Here, in 16
elegant color spreads, these two-time Caldecott Medalists convey
the universality of life, death, joy and sorrow. Their artwork
draws inspiration from Egyptian murals, classical Greek vases,
medieval woodcuts, Thai shadow plays and other cultural sources _
creating the illusion that 16 distinct artists put this book
together. An afterword explains each picture's historical source.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Turn of the Century,'' by Ellen Jackson, illustrated by Jan
Davey Ellis (Charlesbridge Publishing, $17.95). Ages 5-9.
</P>
<P>
   Our kids have heard of Y2K, but what does a millennium mean?
This book takes us back 1,000 years, showing century by century how
an ordinary English or Colonial child might have lived. Jewel-toned
illustrations _ with decorative borders and cozy, happy-looking
children _ bathe this history in a rich, warm glow.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``My Nine Lives,'' by Clio (aka Marjorie Priceman) (Atheneum,
$16). Ages 6-adult.
</P>
<P>
   Clio the cat's remarkable nine lives, spanning 5,000 years, are
detailed in a scribbled, pen-and-ink journal her owner finds under
a couch. Unheralded, this feline appears to have named the
constellations, invented the sundial, sailed with Leif Eriksson and
made the Mona Lisa smile. Cleverly tongue in cheek, the ``journal''
includes an afterword that sets the historical record straight.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Look-Alikes,'' by Joan Steiner, photography by Thomas
Lindley (Little, Brown, $12.95). All ages.
</P>
<P>
   You'll be astounded at the clever little world Steiner has
created from everyday objects such as ticket stubs, cheese graters
and coin purses. In crisp photo spreads that resemble the ``I Spy''
books, Steiner has fashioned a whole village with fool-the-eye
details. Look closely: That bentwood soda-parlor chair is really a
pretzel, the hotel lamp a salt shaker and the vacuum cleaner a
razor. The book's 11 collages incorporate more than 1,000 amusing
look-alikes.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Disappearing Alphabet,'' by Richard Wilbur, illustrated
by David Diaz (Harcourt Brace, $16). All ages.
</P>
<P>
   Wordsmiths young and old will enjoy this witty ABC book by a
two-time Pulitzer Prize winner and former poet laureate. Droll
couplets lead us to reflect that without the letter A, cows would
be reduced to eating Hy. And if B were absent from Bat and Ball,
``there'd be no big or little leagues At All.'' Diaz's bold
computer graphics add a nice crispness, but in this linguistic
frolic, a word is worth a thousand pictures.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Squids Will be Squids,'' by Jon Scieszka and Lane Smith
(Viking/Peguin, $17.99). Ages 49-630 (in dog years).
</P>
<P>
   This duo, a sort of Dave Barry of the children's book world,
turn their demented humor to the ancient wisdom of fables. Through
parables such as ``Slug's Big Moment'' and ``Piece of Toast and
Froot Loops,'' we absorb valuable moral lessons, such as ``It takes
one to know one'' and ``He who smelt it dealt it.'' If you loved
``The Stinky Cheese Man,'' this one's for you.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Snowflake Bentley,'' by Jacqueline Briggs Martin,
illustrated by Mary Azarian (Houghton Mifflin, $16). Ages 4-8.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone knows that no two snowflakes are alike. For that we can
thank a self-taught Vermont scientist named Wilson Bentley, who
perfected a microphotography technique that captured snow crystals'
fragile beauty. There's a moral _ maybe an eccentric one, but still
a moral _ in this story of Bentley's lifelong obsession and his
dogged attempts to photograph thousands of individual snowflakes.
Azarian's richly colored woodcuts are irresistibly warm and
nostalgic.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Christmas Story,'' according to the Gospels of Matthew
and Luke, paintings by Gennady Spirin (Henry Holt, $19.95). All
ages.
</P>
<P>
   Spirin, who was born in Moscow on Christmas in 1948, brings his
classical training and Orthodox perspective to the story of Jesus'
birth, creating a book for the family to share year after year.
Aglow with traditional winged angels, haloed Madonna and sumptuous
borders, it is an elegant accompaniment to the Christmas story of
the King James Bible.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Tibet: Through the Red Box,'' by Peter Sis (Farrar Strauss
Giroux, $25). Ages 8-adult.
</P>
<P>
   Sis' father, a Czech filmmaker, was sent to Tibet in the 1950s
to film construction of the highway that opened Tibet to China. He
wandered, lost, for months, and experienced incredible mysteries
before meeting with the Boy-God-King in the forbidden city of
Lhasa. Sis, who heard the tale as a child, captures its dreamlike
quality with a scene-shifting mix of diary passages and present-day
narration. It's a book to savor slowly, filled with spidery script,
narrative asides and intricate, metaphorical artwork.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Circle Dogs,'' by Kevin Henkes, illustrated by Dan Yaccarino
(Greenwillow, $15). Ages 2-4.
</P>
<P>
   In the big square house live two circle dogs who run and sniff
and play until it's time to sleep. This account of their day reads
like one of Margaret Wise Brown's ``here-and-now'' stories _
simple, ``in the moment'' and full of sensory detail. Clink-clank,
clink-clank. Hear their tags? The two circle dogs wake up.
Flip-flap, flip-flap, swish, swoosh, swish, their tails wave.
Yaccarino's bold, stylized illustrations add a retro feel.
</P>
<P>
   CHAPTER BOOKS
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Soldier's Heart,'' by Gary Paulson (Delacorte, 106 pages,
$15.95). Ages 12-up.
</P>
<P>
   This dark, slender volume tells how 15-year-old Charley Goddard
comes to understand war, one battle at a time, after enlisting in
the Union Army in 1861. Always the master craftsman, Paulsen lays
out the bleak, shattering quality of war with cool fury. Though he
takes some literary license, the story is largely true.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone,'' by J.K. Rowling,
illustrations by Mary Grandr &UR; gfacute &LR; e (Scholastic, 309 pages,
$16.95). Ages 9-13.
</P>
<P>
   Harry spends a miserable 11 years with wicked relatives of the
Raold Dahl variety before finding reprieve _ and his destiny _ at a
boarding school for witches and wizards. Rowling's much-heralded
debut novel spares no detail in creating a magical world of owl
messengers, invisibility cloaks, three-headed guard dogs and
broomstick acrobatics. Some of it gets a little precious and
threatens to bog down the action, but the story is highly
imaginative and offers plenty of old-fashioned, escapist fun.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Count Karlstein,'' by Philip Pullman (Knopf, 243 pages, $17)
and ``Clockwork,'' by Philip Pullman, illustrated by Leonid Gore
(Scholastic, 112 pages, $14.95). Both ages 9-13.
</P>
<P>
   Until Pullman coughs up the final installment in his ``Dark
Materials'' trilogy, we must content ourselves with these lesser
but rewarding works. ``Count Karlstein,'' a slapstick ``thriller''
first published in Britain in 1982, is jolly good fun, with
fiendish villains and bumbling heroes crossing paths in a mountain
village. ``Clockwork,'' a new effort, is a chilling novella about
an apprentice clockmaker who sells his soul and a hapless writer
who begins a story without knowing how it will end. As polished and
finely balanced as a Swiss timepiece, it reads like a cross between
James Thurber and Hans Christian Andersen.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``No Pretty Pictures: A Child of War,'' by Anita Lobel
(Greenwillow, 193 pages, $16). Ages 12-up.
</P>
<P>
   Lobel, a painter and children's book illustrator, was only 5
when she fled the Nazis with her brother and their Catholic nanny.
After years on the run, the children were captured at a Polish
convent and sent to Auschwitz and other camps. With powerful
simplicity, Lobel describes the terror and, finally, the numbness
of their struggle to survive, and their attempt to reclaim their
childhood in Sweden after the war. Illustrated with family photos,
this poignant memoir is a 1998 National Book Award finalist for
Young People's Literature.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Key to the Indian,'' by Lynne Reid Banks, illustrated by
James Watling (Avon Camelot, 228 pages,$16). Ages 10-up.
</P>
<P>
   In this fifth and final installment of the ``Indian in the
Cupboard'' series, Omri and his father travel back 200 years to
help Little Bear save his Mohawk people from white raiders and
prepare for an uncertain future. There's a sad and serious
undercurrent to this fantasy adventure as Omri confronts the dark
legacy of injustice created by his ancestors.
</P>
<P>
   OTHER
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The 20th Century Children's Book Treasury,'' selected by
Janet Schulman (Knopf, 308 pages, $40). All ages.
</P>
<P>
   This marvelous collection is chock-full of favorites, from
classics such as ``The Story of Babar'' to recent gems such as
``Stellaluna'' and ``The Tub People.'' Most are unabridged, though
the artwork, by necessity, is compressed. Taken individually, most
of the stories are more charming in their original, stand-alone
format. But the scope of this book is breathtaking and the
selections are right-on. Includes reading-level guidelines and
brief author bios.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The New Way Things Work,'' by David Macaulay with Neil
Ardley (Houghton-Mifflin, 400 pages, $35). All ages.
</P>
<P>
   This updated version of the 1988 best seller features more than
80 pages of new material, including the workings of a computer
mouse, CDs, digital cameras and other electronic wizardry. Like the
original, this illustrated reference book explains the principles
behind everyday machines, from the block and tackle to the zipper,
and highlights amazing commonalities. (Betcha didn't know the
dentist's drill works on the same principle as early windmills.)
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Narnia: Complete Single Volume,'' by C.S. Lewis, illustrated
by Pauline Baynes. (HarperCollins, 524 pages, $50). Ages 8-up.
</P>
<P>
   Comprehensiveness is a mixed blessing. Heavy and cumbersome,
this fat book has vast gray plains of fine print, making it hard to
read. But, with hand-colored illustrations and bookmark, it's a
handsome gift book that delivers the seven-volume series at a
bargain price.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Stephen Biesty's Incredible Body,'' by Stephen Biesty,
written by Richard Platt (DK, $19.95, 32 pages). Ages 8-up.
</P>
<P>
   Biesty and Platt, whose books have sold 3 million copies
worldwide, take readers on a detailed journey through Biesty's
body, with cross-sections of eye, brain, heart and other innards.
Think of it as ``The Magic School Bus'' for grown-ups.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
