<HEADER>
A9404 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NAACP26-COX     11-25 0822
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAACP26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NAACP REJUVENATES ITS FINANCES AND FERVOR
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The NAACP, which sank into a financial and
scandal-laden morass that threatened its very existence four years
ago, is reclaiming its place as the nation's premier civil rights
organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're back. We're rested. We were always tan,'' quipped Julian
Bond, the veteran civil rights organizer who became chairman of the
National Association for the Advancement of Colored People last
February.
</P>
<P>
   Not only has the NAACP erased a once-staggering debt that
decimated staff and programs, but the 89-year-old organization has
reinvigorated its commitment to oppose hatred, racial polarization
and discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   The NAACP claims some credit for the large black voter turnout
that helped the Democratic Party narrow the GOP congressional
majority in this month's elections. And while it failed to defeat
an anti-affirmative action initiative in Washington state, the
NAACP is prepared to ``make this fight anywhere else,'' said Bond.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NAACP has reclaimed its rightful place as the voice of
people of color and others who believe in the power and the premise
that all persons are, in fact, created equal,'' said Kweisi Mfume
(pronounced Kwah-EE-see Oom-FOO-may), the former Maryland
congressman who became the NAACP's president and CEO in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, since Mfume's arrival two years ago, the NAACP has
replaced its debt with a $2.1 million surplus, rebuilt the staff at
its national headquarters in Baltimore, shaken up the staid
leadership in some of its 2,200 branches, expanded its worldwide
membership to 600,000 and established dozens of new youth and
college chapters.
</P>
<P>
   Since Bond's arrival last February, the NAACP has returned to
the fray of politics and nonviolent protests with renewed fervor
and, perhaps most important, has begun establishing ties with
organizations representing Hispanics, the soon-to-be-largest ethnic
group in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tools we used to combat white supremacy before _
organization, mobilization, coalition, litigation _ are the tools
we'll use to fight white supremacy today,'' said Bond, who helped
organize the Student Nonviolent Coordinating Committee (SNCC) in
the early 1960s. ``We're going to do the old things better.''
</P>
<P>
   This back-to-the-future strategy was evident in a recent
collaboration of Bond and Raul Yzaguirre, president of the National
Council of La Raza, the nation's largest Hispanic organization, in
attacking proposals to privatize Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   It also has been apparent in Mfume-led marches to protest the
Supreme Court's lack of minority clerks and in the NAACP programs
that rate the responsiveness of various industries to minority
customers.
</P>
<P>
   And in the wake of President Clinton's race initiative, which
tried to educate white Americans to the nature of ``white
privilege'' in the country, the NAACP is actively recruiting whites
to join its ranks , as it once did in the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many whites have thought they couldn't join,'' said Bond.
``Others have made the American assumption _ that solving racial
problems is a task for black Americans, the victims, and not
whites, the perpetrators.''
</P>
<P>
   Bond credits his predecessor, Myrlie Evers-Williams, for the
NAACP's renaissance. ``She restored integrity and honesty,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The widow of slain civil rights leader Medgar Evers took over
the chairmanship at the height of scandal and immediately began
crisscrossing the nation to convince disenchanted donors to resume
their contributions. Almost single-handedly, she erased half of the
organization's nearly $3 million debt.
</P>
<P>
   The NAACP had been rocked two years earlier when its board fired
then-executive director Benjamin Chavis for unauthorized use of
NAACP funds to settle a sexual harassment suit. Within six months
of Chavis's firing, several board members filed suit against
then-chairman William Gibson, alleging he had misused $1.4 million
in NAACP funds.
</P>
<P>
   Evers-Williams reluctantly ran against Gibson in early 1995. In
a bruising campaign that tugged at the seams of the NAACP, she won
by a margin of one vote. She then recruited Mfume, a rising
Democratic star in Congress, to take over the daily operation of
the organization.
</P>
<P>
   Mfume, in addition to helping Evers-Williams tackle the debt,
has made bridging the generation gap in the African American
community one of his top priorities, opening the NAACP to black
youths who had come to view the organization as aged and
irrelevant.
</P>
<P>
   At its October board meeting, the NAACP granted charters to
seven new youth chapters, pushing the nationwide total over 350.
</P>
<P>
   ``Failing to develop roles and responsibilities for our young
people now will certainly ensure our failure later,'' said Mfume.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
