<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-PHOTOGRAPHY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MASTERS ANCHOR LATEST SELECTION OF PHOTOGRAPHY BOOKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAUL JOSEPH BROWN  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Photography's relationship with the art world has always been
dysfunctional, an arranged marriage of difficult individuals.
</P>
<P>
   Our selections of the season's most compelling photography books
are anchored by two of the still young medium's few acknowledged
masters, Jacques Henri Lartigue and Henri Cartier-Bresson, both of
whom spent long periods of their artistic lives retreating from
great photographic acclaim into unacclaimed painting.
</P>
<P>
   They also include a great painter (Edgar Degas) who was an
accomplished photographer, an inspiring photojournalist (W. Eugene
Smith) who wanted his work to be seen as art, and a surrealist
painter (Man Ray) who adapted the techniques of photography to his
varied artistic impulses.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Jacques Henri Lartigue, Photographer'' by Vicki Goldberg
(Bulfinch, 288 pages, $95).
</P>
<P>
   In 1902, Jacques Henri Lartigue began making photographs with a
camera he thought God had given him because it made him so happy.
He confidently turned the camera towards the bourgeois French world
that comfortably surrounded him.
</P>
<P>
   He photographed his nanny waiting patiently for a huge ball to
return to Earth, his cat in midleap for its ball and a family
friend name Rico Broadbent being outrun by his valet. The
photographs are elegantly composed and absolutely joyful. The
photographer was 6.
</P>
<P>
   Later he would be enticed by the fanciful, fragile contraptions
that began to fill the streets and skies of the new century;
outrageously hatted and strutting corsetted silhouettes captured
along Paris' Bois de Boulogne and biplanes, gliders, kites,
balloons and cars of all sorts, the faster the better, career
across Lartigue's plane of focus.
</P>
<P>
   Lartigue's photographs define the belle epoque, a time separated
from our own by much more than a century.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``W. Eugene Smith. Photographs 1934-1975'' (Abrams, 352 pages,
$75).
</P>
<P>
   The greatest challenge to the documentary photographer is not
access to difficult subjects. Anything and anyone can be
photographed. A photographer who can't get access should try a more
amenable subject, weddings, for example.
</P>
<P>
   The point of documentary work, the reason photographers risk
their lives and often accept poverty in the pursuit, is to make
photographs that need to be seen. Unfortunately, writers, not
photographers, edit magazines and run publishing houses.
</P>
<P>
   W. Eugene Smith was tenacious in making the photographs and
hellbent on seeing them properly published. He fought often and
hard with his editors at Life over the publication of his landmark
photographic essays, a form he pioneered and mastered, inspiring
generations of obsessive photojournalists.
</P>
<P>
   This extensive monograph includes the classic Life essays,
Smith's stunning, unpublished documentary of Pittsburgh and his
most penetrating work exposing the tragedy of mercury poisoning in
Minamata, Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Smith died in 1978 at the age of 59 with $18 in the bank.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Tete-a-Tete: Portraits by Henri Cartier-Bresson'' (Bulfinch,
144 pages, $65).``A Propos de Paris,''  &UR; cf58 &LR;  by Henri
Cartier-Bresson  &UR; cf58 &LR; (Bulfinch, 167 pages, $55).``Henri
Cartier-Bresson Europeans'' (Bulfinch, 231 pages, $60).
</P>
<P>
   At 90, Henri Cartier-Bresson is a contemporary of the Leica, the
precise instrument he has wandered the globe with capturing the
lyrical, poetic images that have earned him his reputation as
perhaps the century's foremost photographer.
</P>
<P>
   HCB, in annoying Gallic fashion, is famously dismissive ...
``About photography I know nothing.'' HCB knows everything, what
little there is to know, about photography. He simply knows, no,
feels, how to fill his viewfinder and when to open the shutter.
</P>
<P>
   Cartier-Bresson's photographs are composed rather than taken.
``I weave around the subject like the referee in a boxing match,''
he has written. His photographs celebrate the medium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tete-a-Tete,'' a collection of Cartier-Bresson's portraits,
opens with a selection of his pencil drawings, which reveals one of
the century's true masters with a camera to be somewhat less
sophisticated with a pencil, the medium he has professed to prefer.
The photographs that follow are classics, the subjects elegantly
composed in their surroundings, the moment chosen to reveal the
subject through gesture, mood and light. Great photographic
portraits represent a successful dance between subject and
photographer. Cartier-Bresson was quite a dancer, partnering Jung,
Picasso and Matisse as well as William Faulkner, Che Guevara and
Martin Luther King Jr.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Propos de Paris'' is a collection of Cartier-Bresson's
favorite photographs of his home, a loving portrait of the City of
Light. In France, where photographers and philosophers are granted
celebrity status, Cartier-Bresson is a living treasure. This book
returns the compliment.
</P>
<P>
   In yet another entirely successful re-editing of
Cartier-Bresson's work from the 1920s to the 1970s, when he largely
gave up photography for painting, ``Europeans'' presents a gorgeous
portrait of a particularly European identity that predates the Euro
by decades. Polish and Irish and Italian priests, French and
Italian and Romanian farmers all inhabit different physical
landscapes. But framed by Cartier-Bresson's eloquent and
compassionate eye, absolutely tuned to gesture, sensitive to humor
and juxtaposition, these different nationalities reflect a common
European soul.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Passion and Line,'' photographs by Howard Shatz (Graphis,
224 pages, $50). ``Pool Light,'' photographs by Howard Shatz
(Graphis, 250 pages, $75).
</P>
<P>
   Dance is one of the photographer's most formidable challenges.
The standard photographic variables of moment, composition and
light become infinitely complex when multiplied by movement. In the
hands of a master such as Howard Shatz, dance photography can be a
startling transcendence of an immobile, two-dimensional medium.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Passion and Line,'' Shatz's command of his medium is equal
to his subject, many of the best dancers in America, gorgeously
lit, their movement captured at its peak expression.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Pool Light,'' photographer and subject trade the familiar
studio for a body temperature, strobe-lit pool, freeing the dancers
from gravity, their greatest restraint. The water, balanced to the
pH of human tears, becomes the medium upon which the photographic
compositions are executed to astonishing, dreamy effect.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``No Ordinary Land. Encounters in a Changing Environment''
photography by Virginia Beahan and Laura McPhee (Aperture, 108
pages, $35).
</P>
<P>
   Photographers tend to be solitary practitioners. The best light
comes early and late, the gear is heavy, the hours long, and the
pay typically meager.
</P>
<P>
   Beahan and McPhee have pursued a rare collaboration, dividing
the tasks and sharing the infrequent rewards, photographing
together the complex ways in which man interacts with the
landscapes in which we live. They share an eye for the paradoxes
inherent in the social landscape, where water is sometimes holy and
sometimes a resource for irrigating crops.
</P>
<P>
   Their large-format color images are at once finite and
dreamlike. In Iceland, children play in an opalescent hot springs
created by runoff from a geothermal plant. In Hawaii, a mother
cradles her infant on a red sand beach as a blue tide swirls at her
feet.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Shaking the Dust of Ages'' photographs and commentary by
Ljalja Kuznetsova (Aperture, 160 pages, $45).
</P>
<P>
   The globalization of our economy has overtaken the slim market
for documentary photography with publication of Kazakhstani
photographer Ljalja Kuznetsova's poignant collection of images of
gypsies and wanderers of the Central Asian Steppe.
</P>
<P>
   The Roma, like other indigenous cultures in the former Soviet
Union, subsisted in the benign shadow of Communist authority. When
the Soviet Union imploded, throwing off improbable independent
states like Kazakhstan, foreign investors and development followed,
putting new pressure on the Roma's nomadic ways. ``Shaking the Dust
of Ages'' is a poetic document of a marginal people in a little
known region.
</P>
<P>
   Other notable releases: `Margaret Bourke-White' (Bulfinch, $65);
``Man Ray: Photography Inside Out,''(Gingo, $65); ``Simple
Secrets,'' photographs by Walker Evans (Abrams, $25); ``State of
the Blues,'' photographs by Jeff Dunas (Aperture, $50);
``Reflections in a Looking Glass,'' photographs by Lewis Carroll
(Aperture, $50); ``Edgar Degas, Photographer'' (Abrams, $49);
``Another Africa,'' photographs by Robert Lyons (Anchor, 124 pages,
$35).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
