<HEADER>
A9406 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-STYLE-SPI &LR;      11-25 0883
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-STYLE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHIC GOES SIMPLER IN BOOKS ON STYLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SUSAN PHINNEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Flea markets, fashion runways and Hollywood stars from the '30s
and '40s are just some of the factors defining style as this
century wanes.
</P>
<P>
   For the past few years, publishers have been keen on quilting,
faux painting and dressing-to-match-your-personality books. This
year, judging from dozens of offerings, how to dress and live more
simply are hot topics.
</P>
<P>
   From biographies to architecture, here are some of the most
fascinating, thought-provoking books to hit the Lifestyle desk in
1998:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Chanel: Her Style and Her Life'' by Janet Wallach
(Doubleday, 180 pages, $35).
</P>
<P>
   In the fickle, fast-moving world of fashion, it's amazing for a
woman who has been dead since 1971 to still be a fashion force.
Gabrielle (known as Coco) Chanel championed simplicity _ little
black dresses, the sleeveless shell under a suit jacket.
</P>
<P>
   Inspired by the navy pants and striped sweaters worn by sailors
on a friend's yacht, she created classic casuals. Soft jersey suits
and deep pockets are other Chanel-isms.
</P>
<P>
   Wallach's lavishly illustrated book chronicles Chanel's rich and
famous lovers, her late-in-life comeback and the saga of her
perfume, Chanel No. 5.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Shabby Chic'' by Rachel Ashwell (Regan Books, 211 pages,
$30).
</P>
<P>
   This treasure hunting and decorating show-and-tell guide teaches
you how to shop flea markets (take a tape measure and collapsible
shopping cart), antique malls and secondhand sales.
</P>
<P>
   It gives recipes for reviving wicker, removing rust and mending
flea market apparel. Color photos show how beautifully fabrics,
dinnerware and fashions can be recycled.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Not So Big House'' by Sarah Susanka (Taunton, 200 pages,
$30).
</P>
<P>
   Subtitled ``a blueprint for the way we really live,'' this book
offers alternatives to the ``starter castles'' that have been
covering suburban America since the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Susanka, a Minneapolis architect, prefers quality over quantity,
a home with details that accommodate the occupants _ not just vast,
unwelcoming spaces. Her open floor plans and light-filled homes
make sense for Pacific Northwest lifestyles and an era of high
building costs.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Power of Glamour'' by Annette Tapert (Crown, 256 pages,
$40).
</P>
<P>
   Madonna and Nicole Kidman may be Hollywood fashion icons today,
but they're ing &UR; gfacute &LR; enues compared to Joan Crawford, Norma
Shearer and Carole Lombard _ stars who dressed like stars and
influenced millions.
</P>
<P>
   When Crawford wore a ruffled gown in a 1932 movie, Macy's
promptly sold 500,000 copies. When Crawford had accessories dyed to
match, same-color shoes and handbags became de rigueur.
</P>
<P>
   How these stars developed their personal, influential styles _
from Crawford's padded shoulders to Katharine Hepburn's passion for
pants (she hated garter belts) _ this is a gossipy good read.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Men of Color'' by Lloyd Boston (Artisan, 256 pages, $35).
</P>
<P>
   African-American men have long used fashion as a means of
self-expression. From zoot suits and hats to oversized jeans, from
Nat King Cole and Quincy Jones to Jesse Jackson and Denzel
Washington, this book documents the effect black men have had on
fashion.
</P>
<P>
   They understand non-verbal communication and what dressing with
attitude is all about.
</P>
<P>
   This book also is filled with practical tips. Menswear designer
Jeffrey Banks, for example, gets four pages on the selection,
construction, fit and other considerations when buying pants.
Cuffs, fabrics, care and maintenance are included.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Runway Madness'' by photographer Lucian Perkins (Chronicle,
120 pages, $24.95).
</P>
<P>
   This is a picture book of fashion shows, their audiences and
backstage antics.
</P>
<P>
   There's a hilarious photo of Vogue magazine editors squinting at
the runway, another of drag queen RuPaul and Kate Moss sitting
front-row at a Todd Oldham fashion show.
</P>
<P>
   It's an up-close-and-personal view of models, designers and
shows from 1987-97.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The New Cottage Home'' by Jim Tolpin  &UR; cf58 &LR; (Taunton, 231
pages, $29.95).
</P>
<P>
   Tolpin is another advocate of small-is-good architecture. While
many ``house books'' tend to focus on the East Coast, with perhaps
a token Midwest or California example, Tolpin's book of 30 cottages
includes several from the Northwest. It's territory the Port
Angeles resident knows.
</P>
<P>
   This book is ideal for someone planning a smaller home. Most
designs featured would be good fits for this region.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Fashion Book''  &UR; cf58 &LR; (Phaidon, 512 pages, $39.95).
</P>
<P>
   This is an A-to-Z guide spanning 150 years of the fashion
industry
</P>
<P>
   and 500 designers, photographers
</P>
<P>
   and models who have been influen-
</P>
<P>
   tial.
</P>
<P>
   Although 11 writers are acknowledged at the end of this tome, it
relies more on photographs than text. The entry for the late Edith
Head, legendary Hollywood costume designer, contains just a few
sentences about the sarong she created for Dorothy Lamour and her
clothes for Elizabeth Taylor. The rest of the page is an
illustration of Taylor in a white chiffon dress. In tiny print at
the bottom are the years of Head's birth and death.
</P>
<P>
   It's a reference book that's long on style, short on substance,
but very picturesque.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
