<HEADLINE>
TROLLEY ACCIDENTS COST SAN FRANCISCO THOUSANDS IN SETTLEMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CHUCK FINNIE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ When a trolley's power pole broke free and
smashed into the head of a pedestrian on a Market Street sidewalk
Saturday afternoon, it was portrayed as a freak accident. It
wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   At least four times in the past two years, including twice this
month, the city approved $242,000 in cash settlements with
pedestrians and owners of cars hit by poles, wires and falling
debris from its electrified buses, city records show.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Gescheidt, 40, of Noe Valley, remained in critical
condition Wednesday at San Francisco General Hospital after being
hit by a pole that came loose from a trolley Saturday afternoon.
The pole connects the bus to the overhead electrical wires that
power the bus.
</P>
<P>
   ``The number of incidents is way out of line, and we need an
explanation _ and fast,'' said Supervisor Tom Ammiano, who oversees
lawsuit settlements by the city.
</P>
<P>
   Even before Saturday's accident, Ammiano said he was concerned
enough that he had called a Municipal Railway representative into a
closed-door legislative session to discuss one of the settlements.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, he told me they sometimes miss the maintenance,''
Ammiano said.
</P>
<P>
   David Stumpo, the Municipal Railway chief operating officer,
said the transit agency has a vigilant program to keep the trolleys
safe and running, including monitoring and replacing parts
regularly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do a tremendous job, not to have more instances like
this,'' Stumpo said, noting that the trolley fleet is checked
daily. Moreover, each trolley gets a thorough inspection every
2,000 miles.
</P>
<P>
   However, he added, the poles and the mechanisms securing them to
the trolley and the overhead power wires experience considerable
stress on the street and can fail.
</P>
<P>
   City Attorney Louise Renne's office produced a list of recently
settled cases arising from trolley pole and related failures,
events Municipal Railway officials have said rarely resulted in
injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has happened,'' said Alan Siegel, a Municipal Railway
spokesman, ``but not very often.''
</P>
<P>
   Stumpo conceded the nature of the mechanics of the trolley and
the city's elaborate transit electrification system posed risks to
pedestrians and motorists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime you are walking nearby, you need to be aware,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   One safety precaution that may be in order, Stumpo said, is to
install protective roofing over transit islands where riders are
particularly exposed.
</P>
<P>
   A leading San Francisco plaintiffs lawyer who has sued the
Municipal Railway said the agency had responsibility to take steps
before now. She said the track record of accidents meant San
Francisco could be hit hard as a result of its latest trolley
accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``A city that is on notice about this kind of deficiency ... has
a duty to protect people and correct the problem,'' said Mary
Alexander, a past president of the Consumer Attorneys of
California.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's incident occurred just before 1 p.m. when Gescheidt
was walking alone along Market Street. The power pole came loose at
the base from a trolley and hit him in the back of the head.
</P>
<P>
   He never saw it coming, said his brother, Jack Gescheidt.
</P>
<P>
   ``My brother has a one-inch hole in his skull as a result of the
injury,'' Jack Gescheidt said, adding that the biggest danger now
was brain swelling and infection.
</P>
<P>
   A woman walking behind Gescheidt came to his rescue.
</P>
<P>
   ``She waded into a pool of blood and held her hand over his
wound, stroking his forehead until help arrived,'' Jack Gescheidt
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
