<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-25 15:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9417 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-Q&AMP;A-NYT &LR;      11-25 0301
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNINSTALLER PROGRAMS CAN EASE FILE CLEANUP 
</HEADLINE>
  (gm) 
 By J.D. BIERSDORFER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. What do commercial uninstall programs do that I can't do by
myself?
</P>
<P>
   A. Although Windows 95 and 98 include an Add/Remove Programs
utility, many users believe that this function doesn't quite clear
out all the remains of uninstalled applications. Unneeded temporary
files, outdated or unused fonts, DLL's (dynamic-link library
files), old shortcuts and duplicate files can be left behind,
taking up hard drive space and cluttering your system. The fear of
deleting a file that seems to be a leftover but is actually needed
by the system frightens many users into leaving it where it is.
</P>
<P>
   There are many programs that offer to do the dirty work for you.
Uninstall programs claim to remove applications and all their
supporting files safely and thoroughly, saving the user the trouble
of rooting around on the hard disk to track down and delete the old
parts.
</P>
<P>
   Cybermedia's Uninstaller software does this by examining all the
files on your computer, then making a database of what files go
with what programs. When it's time to get rid of a program,
Uninstaller can track down all the associated files and delete
them. Quarterdeck's Clean Sweep is another popular program in this
category. Perhaps because no software is infallible, both
applications offer backup options in case a file needed by another
program is accidentally uninstalled. Macintosh users wanting a
similar utility program might try Aladdin System's Spring Cleaning
software.
</P>
<P>
   Circuits invites questions about computer-based technology, by
postal mail to Questions, Circuits, The New York Times, 229 West
43d Street, New York, N.Y. 10036-3959 or by e-mail to
Q&AMP;A(AT)nytimes.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
