<HEADLINE>
WHEN YOU GO: DEVIL'S ISLANDS &HT;    
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   Getting there: Most airline connections to Cayenne, French
Guiana's capital, are via Miami and either Martinique or Guadeloupe
in the French West Indies. A travel agent can discuss options.
Buses operate between Cayenne and Kourou; a ferry connects Kourou
with le Royale (Royal Island), largest of the Devil's Islands. The
boat ride takes about one hour. Organized tours are available but
can be expensive; ask a travel agent for details. (Lonely Planet
recommends contacting Takari Tours in Cayenne at 31-1969 or Carbet
des Iles in Kourou at 32-0995.)
</P>
<P>
   When to go: Carnival season _ usually in February _ is festive.
But the most comfortable time to visit is between July and
December, when a dry climate prevails. Spring can be quite rainy.
</P>
<P>
   Documents: American visitors need a valid passport; a visa is
not required for stays up to 90 days.
</P>
<P>
   Additional information: Lonely Planet's ``South America''
guidebook is available at most area bookstores; retail price is
$29.95. This information can also be accessed on the Internet at
www.lonelyplanet.com.au/dest/sam/fqu.htm. Another good Web site is
www.city.net/countries/french_guiana.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
