<SLUG> BC-WILD-TURKEYS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILD TURKEYS MAKE STORE-BOUGHT VERSIONS TASTE LIKE NOTHING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC BRAZIL  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ While the carcasses of their dim-witted domestic
cousins repose _ stuffed and delicious _ on millions of American
tables as the centerpiece of Thanksgiving dinner, wily and wary
wild turkeys are flourishing throughout California.
</P>
<P>
   Theirs is one of the great environmental success stories of the
20th century _ a species rescued from the brink of extinction.
</P>
<P>
   In California, the wild turkey population was too small to
bother counting just 30 years ago. Today there are 100,000 of the
tall, long-striding birds, maybe more. They roost in 57 of the
state's 58 counties (all but urban San Francisco) and can be
legally hunted, spring and fall. And, despite their image, they are
not dumb.
</P>
<P>
   Wild turkeys are ``very stealthy, crafty and sharp,'' said Billy
Ogden, print production manager at Charles Schwab &AMP; Co. and
president of the Golden Gate Gobblers chapter of the National Wild
Turkey Federation.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got extraordinary eyesight and hearing,'' and even
when Ogden was wearing full camouflage, ``I've had 'em spook away
when they saw my eyelids blinking,'' he said, acknowledging that he
has yet to bag his Thanksgiving turkey during the fall season,
which ends Nov. 29.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the sport of hunting turkey is what saved the bird
from extinction. The plentiful birds at the harvest feast shared by
Pilgrims and Wampanoag Indians in 1621 had disappeared from 18 of
the 39 states in their historical range by the early 1930s. Habitat
destruction, along with meat hunting, had reduced their numbers to
about 30,000 nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   American hunters decided not to lose the traditional bird as
game. So, in 1973, they founded the National Wild Turkey
Federation, a 180,000-member organization which does for turkeys
what Ducks Unlimited does for ducks.
</P>
<P>
   Federation volunteers have given state and federal wildlife
agencies more than 100,000 wild turkey transport boxes and helped
relocate more than 145,000 wild turkeys nationwide. Federation's
Wild Turkey Super Fund has assisted with nearly 8,200 state and
national projects with expenditures of nearly $84 million.
</P>
<P>
   The effort was hugely successful in California, where the
federation pays half the salary of the state Fish and Game
Department's wild turkey coordinator. After all, wild turkeys are
not indigenous to California. They were introduced here in 1877,
transplanted wild stock captured in the Southwest and the eastern
slope of the Rocky Mountains. Now they are everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   That may please committed turkey hunters like Bob Moore, owner
of Broadway Bait, Rod and Gun in Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   ``They fly quicker than quail,'' he said. ``They're a very
sporty bird, not easy to kill. You've gotta be patient.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, in an unthreatening environment they
domesticate so easily that they often encroach on new rural
suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   Too darn easily, as far as Emily Libarle is concerned.
</P>
<P>
   Six months ago, several wild toms began roosting in a
100-foot-tall pine tree near Libarle's house in the Sonoma County
town of Cotati. She's had no peace since then.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're awful!'' she said. ``They fly! The males roost in my
pine tree. They make the biggest mess I've ever seen. They fight
and they make all kinds of noise and wake us up at 5 a.m.,''
Libarle said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not afraid of anything. They were fighting in one of
my flowerbeds, and I took a broom and started chasing them and it
didn't bother them _ they just kept on fighting.''
</P>
<P>
   Libarle is contemplating drastic action to end her turkey
torment. ``The pine tree is dead. I'm going to cut it down, so they
won't have a place to park,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Except for rubbing some humans the wrong way, wild turkeys
``have never been shown to interfere with anything else'' and have
had no adverse effect on California ecosystems, said Charlie Ryan
of El Dorado, regional director of the National Wild Turkey
Federation, which has 35 chapters in the state.
</P>
<P>
   They're a worry anyhow, said Emily Roberson, senior land
management analyst for the California Native Plant Society. ``We
know they're eating a lot of different things out there, but we
don't know their impact on native or rare plants or critters,'' she
said. ``They're eating something to be so successful here.''
</P>
<P>
   Wild turkeys can live to the age of five _ if they can avoid
predators like bobcats, foxes, raccoons, coyotes, skunks, hawks and
eagles. Hens lay as many as 17 eggs at a time. Toms reach a weight
of 25 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Hunters who have eaten wild turkey swear by its rich, non-gamey
flavor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Compared to it, a store bought turkey tastes like a
chalkball,'' Moore said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's delicious, the flavor is incredible; compared to it
domestic turkey is like eating cardboard,'' said Ryan, a country
boy who prefers to fillet the breast meat in strips, soak it in
buttermilk, flour it and fry it like chicken.
</P>
<P>
   No one claims first dibs on turkey drumsticks, though. They are,
ahem, athletic, just like the wild birds. Tough and stringy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
