<P>
   CLINTON-SCANDAL (Washington) _ A spokesman for Independent
Counsel Kenneth Starr says at least another 18 months, possibly two
years, will be needed to complete the investigations of President
Clinton that began with the Whitewater land deal and extended to
the president's sexual relationship with a young intern. By JOHN C.
HENRY.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TROLLEY-ACCIDENTS (San Francisco) _ San Francisco has approved
$242,000 in settlements in recent months for accidents involving
parts that fall from the city's electric trolleys. But officials of
the Municipal Railway say such accidents are rare and that the
trolley buses are routinely maintained. By CHUCK FINNIE. (Already
filed.)
</P>
<P>
   CEMETERY-SLAVES (Prairie Lea, Texas) _ Two men stand
sentry-still in a backroads cemetery. Herman Harris comes to the
point. ``There lies your great-great grandfather, the man who
brought my folks from Alabama as slaves,'' he tells the other man.
Addison Flowers Jr., the descendant of the slave owner, arrived
unexpectedly at Harris' door to ask permission to have his cremated
remains scattered over the cemetery. By ALLAN TURNER.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-SCHOOLS (Austin, Texas) _ Education Commissioner Mike
Moses says he will propose toughening the standards by which
schools are rated. But he says his proposals are not likely to have
the immediate impact that another new measure will have starting in
1999: Passing rates of special education students will be included
when the Texas Education Agency evaluates school performance. By
KATHY WALT.
</P>
<P>
   FIRE-RESCUE (Harlingen, Texas) _ Richard Guymon, a Border Patrol
agent-trainee, was heading out to work before dawn when he saw that
his neighbor's apartment was on fire. He broke in, rescued a
disabled woman and had the fire mostly put out by the time help
arrived. The victim is in fair condition with minor burns and smoke
inhalation. By JAMES PINKERTON.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
