<HEADER>
A9490 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUDIO26-MINIS-COX     11-25 0469
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO26-MINIS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Method Man, the hard core rapper from Wu-Tang Clan, shows his
soft side?
 &HT;    By Sonia Murray and Steve Dollar
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  RAP
</P>
<P>
   ``Tical 2000: Judgement Day''
</P>
<P>
   Method Man. Def Jam. 27 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   The rapper who ``came to bring the pain hard core to your
brain'' on his 1994 solo debut now has his sights on your soul. So,
from a safe distance, watch the self-described Ticallion Stallion
of the influential Wu-Tang Clan make apocalyptic ``Torture'' sound
funky. Another Method Man persona, Iron Lung steps up next, blowing
lyrical daggers and sense over a kazoo (``Suspect Chin Music''), a
piano plink (``Dooney Boy'') and a horn section blast (``Party
Crasher''). Finally, the guy women fell in love with on the 1995
summer song ``You're All I Need'' emerges on ``Break Ups to Make
Ups,'' an engaging, gritty glimpse of the heart of a hip-hop man.
All these characters are in two words, Method Man, the force behind
this multidimensional revelation.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ROCK
</P>
<P>
   ``Live on Two Legs''
</P>
<P>
   Pearl Jam. Epic. 16 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   The irony of Pearl Jam's long hiatus from touring was that the
moody Seattle band is one of rock's great live acts, a fact
reflected in how extensively its concerts are bootlegged. ``Live on
Two Legs,'' which comes fast on the heels of Pearl Jam's
late-summer tour, is official evidence. The material plays to the
group's strengths, emphasizing frontman Eddie Vedder's nascent
flair for folkie introspections, and movingly so. Tunes such as
``Off He Goes'' and ``Given to Fly'' apply the lessons of Neil
Young, R.E.M. and Led Zeppelin in ways that suggest the rock
tradition still has a spark or two left to strike. Meanwhile, the
shreiking garage-rock blowout of ``Evolution'' proves that Vedder
still has what it takes to go ape.
</P>
<P>
   ``Moon Pix''
</P>
<P>
   Cat Power. Matador. 11 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   Prodigal Atlanta songwriter and indie-rock sweetheart Chan
Marshall (a.k.a. Cat Power) makes the grandest gesture out of
seemingly compulsive understatement. Her songs can make you feel as
if you've intruded on a private moment, and the naked, emotional
undertow makes it hard to slip back through the door. Her third
full-length album is also her best, recorded with members of
Australian punk-folk outfit the Dirty Three. Strumming guitar or
accompanying herself on piano, the vocalist is haunting; the spare,
minimalist setting heightens the intimacy and limns everything in a
kind of plaintive mystery (think of Neil Young and ``After the Gold
Rush''). Deep down, songs like ``Colors and the Kids'' and ``Cross
Bones Style'' cast their spells in the unvarnished language of
old-time spirituals.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
