<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-NOTES26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Deutermann's only option? To enjoy all the thrills
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   P.T. Deutermann has adjusted well to life on dry land after 26
years at sea. Since moving to Baldwin County in Middle Georgia six
years ago, the retired Navy captain has found a new career as a
successful novelist.
</P>
<P>
   His first novel, ``Scorpion in the Sea,'' sold to TriStar
Pictures for $250,000, and his third novel, ``Official Privilege,''
has been optioned to Roland Joffe, who directed ``The Killing
Fields.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The screenplay is finished for `Official Privilege,' '' says
Deutermann, 57. ``Now we're just waiting.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, he's not waiting idly. Deutermann's fifth novel, ``Zero
Option'' (St. Martin's, $25.95), a thriller set in Atlanta, hits
stores this month. The novel is a complex tale of murder and a
scheme to sell military surplus from Fort Gillem on the black
market. Unfortunately, one of the surplus items is a cylinder of
Wet Eye, a hazardous biological weapon.
</P>
<P>
   When Criminal Investigative Service agent David Stafford is sent
to investigate, he hits a dead end until he is befriended by a
Georgia mountain woman and her psychic daughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to put things in my books that people might care
about,'' Deutermann says. ``If you talk about a disaster on the
moon, who cares? But if you talk about committing murder, or losing
a deadly chemical weapon in Atlanta, people care.''
</P>
<P>
   Deutermann admits he has taken some logistical liberties with
his plot. ``The Army's control system is a lot tighter than I
describe it in the book. They keep track of every weapon with
serial numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   But black market activity is common, especially in wartime, he
says. ``In Vietnam, for example, you had South Vietnamese employees
driving forklifts in the Saigon warehouses. It was quite easy for
whole crates to disappear.''
</P>
<P>
   For the psychic character in the novel, Deutermann talked to
police and to psychics. ``I take the paranormal with a grain of
salt, but some cops said they would use psychics when they were
stumped. They said if the psychics say a 6-foot Scandinavian did
it, then they'll go look for a 6-foot Scandinavian. I don't know
how they do it, but the real ones can.''
</P>
<P>
   Deutermann says he's gradually moving from matters military to
mainstream fiction, with the help of his wife. ``Her general
comment is that women appreciate people books _ novels with
relationships between characters about whom you care. When she
reads my stuff, if she can't sympathize with all the characters,
even the bad guys, then I'll go back and rework it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  WAR STORY: Talk about great timing. E. Randall Floyd's novel
``Deep in the Heart'' (Harbor House, $24.95), has caught the wave
of interest in the Civil War sparked by Charles Frazier's ``Cold
Mountain.'' Floyd's tale of a 19-year-old Civil War soldier has
sold nearly 50,000 copies since publication in late August.
</P>
<P>
   The novel is based on the true story of Wiley Nesmith, a soldier
from Wilkinson County who wrote dozens of letters to his wife
during the war. During his three years in most of the major battles
of the war, Nesmith's six brothers were killed.
</P>
<P>
   Floyd first saw the letters a dozen years ago, when Nesmith's
descendants contacted him about writing a book while he was
teaching at Georgia Southern College. Floyd told them he was too
busy at the time, but after reading the letters, he realized they
could be the basis of a deeply passionate story.
</P>
<P>
   ``The letters weren't eloquent in the usual sense,'' says Floyd,
who now lives in Augusta. ``He was just a young dirt farmer with
little education. But he wrote with such conviction and passion. He
did not like the war; all he wanted to do was do his duty and go
home to his wife.''
</P>
<P>
   Floyd originally intended to do the book as a narrative,
scholarly work, but he soon decided he would get a wider audience
if he turned it into a novel.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously his instincts were right. Floyd has been offered
paperback deals from major publishers and is negotiating film
rights. One of the people interested is Lee Murray, who produced
``Stolen Women'' for CBS television.
</P>
<P>
   Like ``Cold Mountain'' and other novels about the war, Floyd
believes ``Deep in the Heart'' has struck a chord because there was
never closure.
</P>
<P>
   ``The war never ended the way it was supposed to, especially
after Lincoln was assassinated. The idea of the Lost Cause will
never go away.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  PHANTOM REVISITED: Frederick Forsyth (``The Day of the
Jackal'') usually writes novels about assassins and war, but now
the British author has written a book about the Phantom of the
Opera. Sold to New Millennium Entertainment and scheduled for
spring publication, ``The Phantom in Manhattan'' takes the star of
the Andrew Lloyd Webber musical to New York.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  KUDOS: University of Georgia Press author Susan Millar
Williams is the 1998 recipient of the Julia Cherry Spruill
Publication Prize for her book, ``A Devil and a Good Woman, Too:
The Lives of Julia Peterkin.'' The prize is awarded annually by the
Southern Association for Women Historians.
</P>
<P>
   The book is the first full-scale biography of the Pulitzer
Prize-winning South Carolina author and plantation mistress.
Williams lives in McClellanville, S.C.
</P>
<P>
   KThursday, Nov. 26, 1998 The Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
