<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: E-mail to Gates: I feel your pain
 &HT;    (Resending to fix garble.)
 &HT;    By Stebbins Jefferson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Each morning when I read the newspaper, I look to the comics for
a bit of humor to jump-start my day. One day this week, however, I
found the best laugh in the Business section. There, I learned that
Bill Gates, the nation's richest man, has a lot in common with the
average computer dummy.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Gates is fighting an antitrust case. Like the rest of us,
he's finding out that e-mail is an unforgiving convenience.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department and 20 states are suing Mr. Gates'
company, Microsoft. They claim that to eliminate competition in the
computer software business, Microsoft embedded Internet browser
software into each Windows operating system. Microsoft's
competitor, Netscape, needs to sell its browser for the company to
grow.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Mr. Gates is accused of trying to create an
illegal monopoly to force out competitors. He denies it. Though
Netscape may have been hurt, he says, he's just trying to improve
his product and better serve consumers.
</P>
<P>
   The case seems to hinge on intent, not consequences. That's
where Mr. Gates' own electronic words _ he writes more than 100
e-mails a day _ could reveal more than he wants the court to know.
</P>
<P>
   In January 1996, for example, he messaged top aides that
``winning Internet browser market share is a very, very important
goal.'' When asked in court what he meant by that statement, he
said he couldn't remember. In fact, the Harvard dropout who hired
Harvard graduates and made them all millionaires has trouble
answering any questions related to e-mail. He can't remember what
he was thinking when he wrote the memo or what his words meant.
Alas, he can't even remember writing on that subject at all.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, I can identify with a multibillionaire. I know well
that feeling of total amnesia about past e-mail. I must confess I
have often stood at the juncture where the extraordinary brain of
Bill Gates meshes with the ordinary minds of millions of Americans
who have discovered with much anxiety that e-mail sent is e-mail
forgotten. None of us would want to explain our e-mail in a court
under oath.
</P>
<P>
   I am barely computer-semiliterate, but I did manage to use the
e-mail system of a couple of places where I've worked. At first,
being able to send colleagues messages without fear of being
overheard on a phone was a delightful perk. No longer was it
necessary to meet a friend by the water cooler or wait until we
could go to lunch to vent job frustrations. All I had to do was
type out my critical (and brilliant) judgments and zap them into
cyberspace. If the discussion was about workplace politics, I was
discreet enough to hit the ``delete'' key after such an exchange.
Some things are private. Or so I thought.
</P>
<P>
   One day, however, I lost some important information and thought
I must have inadvertently deleted it from the computer system. Not
to worry, the computer technician told me. He found the missing
information within the hour.
</P>
<P>
   I was elated. Then panic set in. Could somewhere in the bowels
of the system be all the messages I had ever e-mailed? What, or
whom, had I written about? I had visions of a drone sealed in the
woodwork perpetually monitoring all e-mail. Would he understand
that I had no conscious intent to do harm? I don't think so, but,
then, I can't remember what I've written.
</P>
<P>
   Once, I was so incensed by a boss' directive that after a
conference with him, I went back to my office fuming. Needing to
vent, I hastily wrote an e-mail to a compassionate co-worker. I was
just beginning to cool down when the e-mail came back to me. I had
zapped it to my boss. This man, who is not known to suffer fools
gladly, returned my message with this comment: ``You obviously
intended to send this to someone else.''
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to that experience, I fully understand why the brilliant
Mr. Gates suffered memory lapses on the witness stand. I've often
wondered whether I could explain my past e-mail if asked to do so.
Thank God I never was.
</P>
<P>
   Stebbins Jefferson is a columnist for The Palm Beach Post, West
Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
