<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    This ``girl power'' stuff is a bit much
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYT0N, Ohio _ Sisters, unite! We've got to reclaim ``girl
power.'' It's getting desperately late.
</P>
<P>
   It was bad enough when the Spice Girls commandeered the term.
Did you catch the trailer for their film? ``Is my skirt too
short?'' asks Posh Spice. When her friends answer in the negative,
she raises it.
</P>
<P>
   Girl power, indeed.
</P>
<P>
   Now cable viewers are being bombarded with the pre-pre-teen
version of girl power _ The Powerpuff Girls , which debuted last
Wednesday on Cartoon Network. It has been hailed as a breakthrough
_ girl finally achieves prime-time superhero status _ but appears
to be anything but.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, what's with the name? They're the Powerpuff Girls,
for crying out loud: Blossom, Buttercup, and Bubbles.
</P>
<P>
   And why are they ``saving the world before bedtime?'' Is it
because, typical women of the '90s, they're too busy earlier in the
day? Alas, this series is more '60s, than '90s, more throwback than
trailblazer.
</P>
<P>
   I tried to keep an open mind, however, as I watched the premiere
episodes with Teri Thompson, a University of Dayton communications
professor. She has conducted extensive research into
gender-stereotyping in cartoonland and found _ surprise surprise _
it's a boy's world out there.
</P>
<P>
   Our pretense of objectivity doesn't last long, however. Thompson
stopped the tape every few minutes in disbelief.
</P>
<P>
   Take the opening sequence: Professor Utopian, an absent-minded
professor type who looks like Rock Hudson, creates the Powerpuff
Girls in his laboratory. ``Sugar, spice, everything nice, these
were the ingredients to create the perfect little girls. . . .''
But the professor accidentally added an additional ingredient:
Chemical X.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty seconds into the show, and Thompson is already hitting
the pause button. They can't be powerful if they're just girls?
They need that extra ingredient, Chemical X. And how did that
particular letter happen to occur to them?
</P>
<P>
   The Powerpuff girls have round heads and insect-like bodies,
with oversized eyes like those poster waifs of the '60s. With the
exception of Buttercup _ a ``firecracker'' who ``kicks butt,''
according to ads _ they're always smiling, even when punching
evildoers.
</P>
<P>
   The other women in the show are either the apple-pie baking
girl-next-door, the evil, serpent-haired Seduca, or the wicked
would-be stepmother who snarls, ``From now on, you're forbidden to
use your superpowers, and must do things like normal little
girls!''
</P>
<P>
   Thompson hit the pause button again. ``Is this 1998 or what?''
</P>
<P>
   The show's message, she said, is that ``girls can be powerful _
but only if they're cute. Other than that, they're helpless or
manipulative.''
</P>
<P>
   Why worry? Isn't it all kitschy and silly and, well, just
cartoons?
</P>
<P>
   Thompson's 1994 study, conducted with then-colleague Eugenia
Zerbinos, suggests otherwise. After watching cartoons, children
were asked, ``What do boys do?'' and ``What do girls do?''
</P>
<P>
   The responses went like this: ``Boys rescue girls. Boys like to
fight and chase bad guys. Girls dress up and play with dolls. They
like to find boyfriends.''
</P>
<P>
   It matters, Thompson said, because this is what kids watch. It
matters because it shapes the way they think about gender roles.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, Powerpuff girls! Would you really like to save the world
before bedtime? Fire your scriptwriters. While you're at it, fire
all the producers and marketers who think the Spice Girls and their
ilk are proper role models for pre-teens.
</P>
<P>
   Now, that's what I'd call girl power.
</P>
<P>
   Mary McCarty writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
