<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Doctor Dolittle', from musical to movie, the two have almost
nothing in common
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Doctor Dolittle'' (PG-13) _ This raucous but uninspired
Eddie Murphy vehicle has almost nothing to do with the old Rex
Harrison musical. Murphy is John Dolittle, a busy doctor who has
neglected his wife (Kristen Wilson) and his two daughters. One day,
all kinds of animals start pestering him vocally _ often with crude
body-function humor. Despite the zing of some nuttier moments, the
lame, must-spend-time-with-kids plot keeps dragging the movie to
the ground. Priced to buy: $19.98. Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Sliding Doors'' (R) _ In this tepid romantic comedy, Gwyneth
Paltrow plays a modern Londoner who lives two parallel lives. In
one, she discovers her boyfriend John Lynch is unfaithful, and
builds a new life. In the other, she doesn't find out, and
continues her unhappy relationship. Both lives involve John Hannah
as a too-good-to-be-true cuddly soulmate. Good idea, but both of
Paltrow's characters are shallow and reactive, and the movie never
achieves the whimsy or romance it needs to sell its gimmick. Grade:
C+
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Artemisia'' (R) _ Valentina Cervi plays 17th-century painter
Artemisia Gentileschi, who broke through cultural barriers,
becoming one of the first respected female artists. The fact that
Artemisia accused her paining mentor (Miki Manojlovic) of sexual
assault unfortunately leads the movie into speculative territory,
turning an interesting character study into something closer to
cliched romance. In French with subtitles. Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
