<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-POP26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Three CDs no charm for `Egypt'
 &HT;    By Steve Dollar
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bever underestimate a mogul's ego. Or three, in this case
(Jeffrey Katzenberg, Steven Spielberg and David Geffen). In their
over-the-top bid to out-Disney Disney, DreamWorks has unloaded not
one, not two, but three separate albums tied to its big holiday
animation feature, ``The Prince of Egypt.'' It's your basic
biblical epic, with all the broadly drawn emotional moments and Old
Testament sagas you'd expect from a high-tech Judeo-Christian theme
park.
</P>
<P>
   One CD would have sufficed. And it's not the original
soundtrack. Though it's nothing special, the album does at least
boast a historic studio summit meeting between pop divas Whitney
Houston and Mariah Carey. ``The Prince of Egypt (When You
Believe)'' will be with us for a while, an octave-leaping version
of MTV's ``Celebrity Death Match'' that should satisfy fans of both
singers. There's also a grand finale featuring a ``We Are the
World''-style cast of gospel, country, pop and Hollywood stars
wailing and warbling. The disc is more entertaining when it doesn't
try so hard: Steve Martin and Martin Short romping through a
laundry list of ancient deities on ``Playing With the Big Boys,''
or vocalist Ofra Haza embodying Middle Eastern culture on ``Goodbye
Brother.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the two albums of music ``inspired by'' the movie, the
``Inspirational'' title is more successful. The prevailing
religious themes make more sense in a gospel format. CeCe Winans
steals the show with an impassioned ``The River,'' and Jars of Clay
evoke Nirvana (of all things) on ``Everything in Between,''
illustrating the diverse range of performers who can fit under the
same banner. Contemporary soul-stirrers such as Brian McKnight,
Take 6, Kirk Franklin and Shirley Caesar all rock the house. The
only clunker is rock video evangelist Carman, who is such an
astounding self-parody that he's impossible to listen to with a
straight face.
</P>
<P>
   But then there's the ``Nashville'' version, boasting songs so
clumsily or exploitatively ``uplifting'' that it sinks to the level
of kitsch. Truck stop jukebox hero Red Sovine _ or gravel-throated
penitent Johnny Cash _ could pull off this kind of melodramatic,
heart-on-the-sleeve stuff, but hearing Clint Black deliver
something called ``Slavery, Deliverance and Faith'' is simply
painful. The presence of Music City all-stars such as Wynonna, Pam
Tillis, Mindy McCready and Vince Gill only makes matters more
depressing.
</P>
<P>
   POP
</P>
<P>
   ``The Prince of Egypt: Music From the
</P>
<P>
   Original Motion Picture
</P>
<P>
   Soundtrack''
</P>
<P>
   Various artists. DreamWorks. 19 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   ``The Prince of Egypt _ Nashville''
</P>
<P>
   Various artists. DreamWorks. 17 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: D
</P>
<P>
   ``The Prince of Egypt _ Inspirational''
</P>
<P>
   Various artists. DreamWorks. 18 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   The verdicts: Two strikes, one hit.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
