</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOPPING-STRATEGY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Some people! They're organized, within their budget, finished
with their list _ and ready for post-holiday bargains
 &HT;    By Marylin Johnson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ While many of us will be out early Friday fighting the
masses in the malls, some organized souls have already wrapped up
their holiday shopping. A few have even finished addressing their
Christmas cards.
</P>
<P>
   Don't you just hate 'em?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sooo stressful to put things off,'' says Denise O'Connor,
42, of Alpharetta, Ga., who shops year round for 39 people so she
can ship her overseas Christmas gifts in July and mail out-of-town
presents by Nov. 1. ``As the holidays approach, I want to be able
to bake cookies, volunteer at church and go to parties,'' says the
stay-at-home mother of Sean, 12, and Caroline, 9. Come Dec. 26,
however, she'll be back shopping _ grabbing up bargains that might
be marked down by half or more.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional food saleswoman Deborah Kumpitsch, 31, also is
poised to start shopping for Christmas of 1999. But first she'll
wrap the presents for the 19 people on this year's list while
watching football this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not compulsive,'' insists the Marietta, Ga., resident, who
finished her Christmas shopping in mid-September. ``It's a
challenge to have the shopping done.'' The payoff? ``I don't have
to deal with mall traffic or parking, and I can spend money that I
saved by buying throughout the year on myself and my husband at the
after-Christmas sales.''
</P>
<P>
   For Atlantan Cherie Pentecost, 51, an administrative assistant
with AFC Enterprises, shopping for 365 days extends the Christmas
spirit throughout the year. And it gives her the luxury of choosing
thoughtful gifts. Early this year, she visited Amsterdam,
Netherlands, and bought a friend a piece of pottery that she
collects. Pentecost also presents friends with quilts and
decorative home furnishings that she has sewn throughout the year.
</P>
<P>
   Year-round shopping has its perks. But the best reason for doing
it? ``You never have a huge debt in January,'' says O'Connor.
``It's budgeted over the entire year.''
</P>
<P>
   Our intrepid shoppers have strategies that might be helpful to
the shopping-impaired who want to mend their procrastinating ways:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Everyone agrees: Keep a list or diary and check it more than
once. ``I keep my diary in the car,'' O'Connor says. ``If you don't
look at it regularly, you'll forget you bought Aunt Helen a teapot
in February.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Diaries are also helpful for tracking gifts that you purchase
and give year round: hostess and graduation presents, Valentine's
Day and teacher presents, stocking stuffers. And by stockpiling
those gifts, usually bought on sale, you always have an appropriate
item for the occasion.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Another tip from O'Connor: ``By shopping sales year round, you
can give a better gift than you normally would be able to afford.''
She remembers buying a $50 Nativity set where she works that was
marked down 60 percent. As a part-time employee, she got a 20
percent store discount on the purchase and ended up paying $16.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  These savvy shoppers don't limit their gift buying to one type
of store. ``I buy gifts at Target, Old Navy, CVS and Hallmark
stores, as well as Macy's and Rich's,'' says Kumpitsch. Other
shoppers have found bargains at yard sales, flea markets, fabric
stores and outlet malls.
</P>
<P>
   Our organized shoppers also have a special place in their homes
to store treasures. If you don't designate a spot, you won't be
able to find the gifts when you want to wrap them, they warn. The
place can be a shelf in the basement, an empty closet, even under
the bed. Many pre-wrap, so the children won't discover what Santa
has brought them.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor has also streamlined the wrapping process. She uses
wrapping paper only for out-of-town gifts. ``Paper wrap and paper
gift bags are too expensive,'' she says. For her family and close
friends, she buys holiday fabric at the end of the season _ at 50
percent off _ and makes her own reusable cloth drawstring gift bags
in various sizes. She currently has between 50 and 100 bags (her
friends know to return them) and no longer has to stay up late on
Christmas Eve wrapping packages.
</P>
<P>
   Even in the O'Connor household, though, there's always one
unavoidable last-minute present to buy.
</P>
<P>
   ``My husband drives me insane,'' says Denise O'Connor.
</P>
<P>
   Jim O'Connor waits until Christmas Eve to buy her gift.
</P>
<P>
   Our readers share their shopping tricks and gift-giving ideas.
It doesn't matter whether you're buying for next Christmas or just
getting started on this year's list:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  You don't have to be first in line. ``Hit Kmart, Wal-Mart or
Target the day after Thanksgiving around 9:30 or 10 a.m.,'' says
Brandice Abrams of Decatur, Ga. ``Believe it or not, the things you
want will still be there and you won't have to fight the crowds
when the doors first open.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Keep a gift-giving diary. Even if you don't shop year round,
diaries can still help frazzled shoppers keep track of gifts
they've purchased, says expert shopper Denise O'Connor.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Change your shopping philosophy. ``We have a rule in our
family: Gifts must be something to do, not something to have,''
says Donna Valentine, who lives in Atlanta. Her list might include
tickets to the movies, the theater or symphony, or a gift
certificate to a wine bar or for an in-line skating lesson. Another
suggestion: Make a donation to a charity in a friend's name.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Look for sales. ``Clearance racks at off-price stores such as
T.J. Maxx and Marshalls offer significant reductions,'' advises
Linda Jenkins of Marietta. She also suggests that you start buying
for the next Christmas right after the last one, when retailers are
trying to get rid of fall-winter items to prepare for spring
merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Don't hesitate if you see something you like. ``Buy it when
you see it,'' advises Deborah Kumpitsch of Marietta, Ga. ``The item
won't be there when you go back.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Make it fun _ and wear comfortable shoes. As part of a family
tradition, Elizabeth L. Murphy of Roswell, Ga., and her daughter go
to the mall the day after Thanksgiving every year. ``We look
around, getting ideas and enjoying the bustle of the crowd. We wear
our Christmas sweatshirts and jeans and sometimes spend the entire
day.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
