<DOCNO> NYT19981125.0232 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-25 16:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9561 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CEMETERY-SLAVES-HNS &LR;      11-25 1239
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CEMETERY-SLAVES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BURYING THE PAST: SLAVE DESCENDANT LETS EX-MASTER'S KIN USE
CEMETERY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ALLAN TURNER 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRAIRIE LEA, Texas _ Two men, one black and one white, stand
sentry-still, lost in reflection as they contemplate the fading
name on a granite tombstone in a backroads cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   The black man, Herman Harris, whose family owns the cemetery and
surrounding farmland, comes to the point.
</P>
<P>
   ``There lies your great-great-grandfather, the man who brought
my folks from Alabama as slaves,'' he tells the white man. ``Right
there _ mmh-mmh-mmh.''
</P>
<P>
   That Harris is friends with Addison Flowers Jr., the descendant
of the slave owner, is poignant. But the circumstance that brought
them here on this crystal-clear autumn day is more poignant still.
</P>
<P>
   They met last June when an ailing Flowers arrived unexpectedly
at Harris' doorstep to ask permission to have his cremated remains
scattered over the old family cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   Harris, 46, an administrator &UR;  &LR; at a nearby private prison,
recalls the encounter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was at the house getting ready to go to the Luling
Watermelon Thump parade when somebody knocked at my door,'' Harris
said. ``I thought, `Who's going to bother me now?' I went to the
door and this man said, `I'm Addison Flowers.' Oh, no. I knew
exactly who he was. I was shaking. I was overcome by a spiritual
feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   Flowers, a 50-year-old water-wastewater plant technician from
Houston, had no qualms about asking a favor of someone who might be
angry about historic injustices.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figured there were two answers they could give me: yes or
no,'' he said. ``I got the answer I wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   Prairie Lea, a community of 250 people in south-central Texas,
is about 145 miles west of Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Both Flowers and Harris agree that a warm friendship has grown
out of that meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``What his great-great-grandfather used to be doesn't mean
anything,'' Harris said. ``We can't help what happened 140 or 150
years ago ... Some people might have animosity over this type of
thing, but I don't. ...Who knows, if old Addison Johnson hadn't
brought us here as slaves, we might not own this property today.
</P>
<P>
   ``This man (Flowers) came to visit me. That was good. It was an
epiphany.'' &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Not much is known about Addison Johnson, the man buried in the
cemetery now owned by descendants of the slaves he held. He was
born in Virginia, founded a number of Baptist churches, lived in
San Augustine, then apparently raised cotton on the banks of the
San Marcos with the help of an undetermined number of slaves.
</P>
<P>
   He died in 1877 at age 64 to become, as his epitaph puts it,
``Another gem in the savior's crown, another soul in heaven.'' His
wife, who died in 1912, is buried at his side.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel pretty certain that he did not own a large number of
slaves,'' Flowers said. ``He was not a wealthy man.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the slaves was Henry Johnson, patriarch of what was to
become the Harris family.
</P>
<P>
   The freed slave and his descendants _ a long line of farmers and
preachers _ were buried in a separate cemetery near their church.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently in the early 20th century, the prominent McKean
family purchased the Johnson farmstead _ almost 300 fertile acres
in Guadalupe County across the San Marcos River from this tiny
Caldwell County community.
</P>
<P>
   During World War I, Harris' grandfather, Sam Harris, and other
members of his family operated a dairy for the McKeans.
</P>
<P>
   In 1936, the McKeans asked the Harris family to run the old
Johnson farm. Harris said his family's relationship with the
McKeans was one of mutual respect, even in a time and place marked
by lingering racism.
</P>
<P>
   ``The McKeans didn't care if you were black or white if you
worked,'' Harris said. ``My folks were hard-working, humble,
church-going people.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1946, the McKeans offered to sell the land to the Harris
family. ``They wanted my grandfather and his sons to own it,''
Harris said. ``They knew the story of us having worked that
property (as slaves). ... This wasn't a handout, it was a helping
hand.''
</P>
<P>
   Members of the extended family pooled their savings and were
ready to use veterans land program benefits available to younger
members who had served in the military. But the family still lacked
the $1,000 down payment necessary for the purchase.
</P>
<P>
   To raise the money, the family traveled to Kerr County to pick
pecans.
</P>
<P>
   The farm, costing $13,600, was jointly purchased by Sam Harris'
two sons. Today, it's owned by Herman Harris and his cousin, Seguin
City Councilwoman Maxine Harris Stokes.
</P>
<P>
   In 1956, oil was discovered on the Harris farm, and today the
land is the site of about 60 producing wells.
</P>
<P>
   Flowers said he is pleased with the Harris family's good
fortune.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tables,'' he said, ``have turned.'' &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
DIAGNOSED WITH PARKINSON'S DISEASE &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Reared in Katy _ about 25 miles west of downtown Houston _
Flowers said he long had known of his ties to Addison Johnson, who
moved to the Guadalupe County farm from San Augustine in 1851. But
he only occasionally visited the area of the old farmstead and
never had met members of the Harris family.
</P>
<P>
   Only when he was diagnosed with Parkinson's disease, a
progressive brain disorder that leads to loss of muscle control
and, sometimes, dementia, did Flowers begin to think of eternity
and the disposition of his mortal remains.
</P>
<P>
   Although treatment in some cases can minimize Parkinson's
symptoms for long periods, Flowers said he had witnessed his
father's slow decline from the disease. Like his father, he said,
he expects someday to ``just give up the will to live.''
</P>
<P>
   Flowers said the main reason he sought out the Harris family was
revulsion at the prospect of being buried in East Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``My ancestors had enough good sense to get out of East Texas,''
he said, ``and I don't see why I should go back. My wife is from
Apple Springs and she wants to be buried in deep East Texas where
the trees don't fork. Where you can call `Bubba' and five people
will answer. Myself, I want my ashes scattered at the old family
cemetery. I just don't have any use for pine trees or most of the
people who live under them.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond his distaste for East Texas, Flowers said he is eager to
meet Addison Johnson on ``resurrection morning.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Three people have been named after him _ me, my father and his
uncle _ and nobody knows why. I figured that if I were as close to
him as possible, at the resurrection, I could ask him some
questions. I'd like to ask him what he did that was so special that
we were named for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Flowers alludes often and without apparent emotion to his
disease, although his comments sometimes bring conversations to an
awkward halt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm already deteriorating,'' he said. ``There are times when I
can't take care of myself.''
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Flowers handed his ``business card'' to one of
Harris' relatives.
</P>
<P>
   It read:
</P>
<P>
   ``Addison Flowers Jr. Gentleman, scholar, master of seven dead
languages, defender of The Faith, Country and Freedom, unweaned
male child, lover of women and other objects of beauty, teller of
tall tales, dragon slayer, rescuer of damsels in distress.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The next time you get one of these cards,'' Flowers said,
``there will be a date on the bottom and you will know that I'm
dead. It's been a good life _ so far.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
