<DOCNO> NYT19981125.0233 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-25 16:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9570 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BETTY-FRIEDAN-$ADV29-     11-25 1118
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BETTY-FRIEDAN-$ADV29-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BETTY FRIEDAN SAYS CHILD CARE IS NOW THE KEY ISSUE FOR WOMEN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Nov. 29)   (Filed in ``w'' and ``l'' categories)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JUDY HOLLAND  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As the grande dame of feminism, Betty Friedan
helped lead women into a work world of better pay and improved
access to jobs and promotions.
</P>
<P>
   Now, at 77, this grandmother of seven says child care is the
next challenge for women.
</P>
<P>
   Feminists ``will not be able to declare victory until the
raising of children is seen equally as a man's responsibility as
well as a woman's,'' she declared in a recent interview.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. society is too ``mother-centered,'' in Friedan's view.
``Issues like child care are seen as women's issues and the
explicit assumption is that the mother is guilty if she goes to
work or school. Everything is the mother's job. But it should be a
combination.''
</P>
<P>
   Friedan says the single greatest need for women these days is a
national child-care program. This is one of her frequent topics as
she travels around the global lecture circuit.
</P>
<P>
   Friedan, who founded the National Organization for Women and was
its first president from 1966 to 1970, is critical of the
organization in its present mode.
</P>
<P>
   NOW ``lacks the proper leadership'' and should focus on trying
to make child care and parenting less daunting for working women,
rather than fighting for issues such as gay rights. Friedan coined
the term ``lavender menace'' in the 1970s when criticizing NOW for
adding lesbian issues to its agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Although Friedan doesn't mention the current NOW president by
name, her obvious target is NOW president Patricia Ireland. Under
Ireland's direction, NOW has focused on such issues as violence
against women, sexual harassment, abortion rights, family planning
and lesbian and gay rights.
</P>
<P>
   Ireland responds to the criticism by arguing that the feminist
movement ``is a movement that opposes oppression'' in any form.
From that vantage point, child-care issues ``are too narrow a focus
for the feminist movement,'' says Ireland, who goes out of her way
to praise Friedan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Betty has an extraordinarily important role in the history of
this wave of the women's rights movement and its current
campaigns,'' Ireland said. ``I would not relegate her to history,
she is very much an instigator and an active leader.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Ireland says Friedan only helped one segment of
American women. She ``gave voice to a particular constituency,
which was women like her, women who had been full-time moms and
wives and who had a disquiet that they had no name for. And it was
and is an important constituency. It gave a identity to the
burgeoning feminist movement.''
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Ireland describes herself as ``a full service''
feminist, dedicated to a broad range of issues including lesbian
rights, ``which to me, is a core value.'' She also says child care
should not be the top priority for women. Instead, it should be
getting equal pay at a time in which they earn 74 cents on the
dollar compared to men.
</P>
<P>
   Friedan, whose father was a wealthy merchant, describes an
affluent childhood in Peoria, Ill., in which her mother ``rang a
bell'' if she needed something.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Ireland, Friedan says the battle for women's rights is
just about won and says ``it's just a matter of time'' before women
reach full equality.
</P>
<P>
   Friedan is now the same age as veteran astronaut John Glenn.
Although she had her second heart valve replacement last year,
Friedan is going full blast, spending her mornings writing in her
large sunny living room in the Wyoming, an ornate apartment
building in the racially diverse Adams Morgan section of
Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   She fills her days and nights with lectures, panels, writing and
hobnobbing with the intellectual elite; she appears to relish her
role as a historic symbol for women's rights.
</P>
<P>
   Her living room is furnished with exquisite antique furniture,
brightly colored modern paintings and an oil portrait of herself
decades ago with longer, darker hair _ and with the books that
helped make Betty Friedan a household name.
</P>
<P>
   Friedan's most famous book, ``The Feminine Mystique,'' published
in 1963, helped spark the fight for equal rights and opportunities
for women. After producing other books on women's rights, she
broadened her repertoire in 1993 with ``The Fountain of Age,''
about how people will grow older with increased vigor and
creativity.
</P>
<P>
   Ben Wattenberg, a senior fellow at the American Enterprise
Institute who has known Friedan for many years, says she is an
``idea-preneur'' and an ``institution,'' whose book on aging ``is
worth its weight in gold.'' He says Friedan exemplifies how people
are increasingly growing older with vigor.
</P>
<P>
   Friedan's daughter, Emily, a pediatrician in Williamsville,
N.Y., said her mother always had an immense amount of energy, but _
referring to her mother's frenetic schedule _ adds: ``Some of us
think she's running, that she's trying to keep one step ahead of
the grim reaper.''
</P>
<P>
   Divorced for nearly three decades, she has two other grown
children, Jonathan an engineer in Philadelphia, and Daniel, a
Rutgers University physicist in Princeton, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Friedan goes out to lunch and dinner almost every day she's at
home in Washington, and she often attends social events or lectures
at clubs where she is a member, such as the Cosmos Club, the Arts
Club of Washington or the National Press Club.
</P>
<P>
   A small woman with wispy white-grey hair and a penchant for
offbeat clothing, she is often approached by middle-aged or elderly
strangers who stop to thank her for her role in the feminist
movement.
</P>
<P>
   While she doesn't cook, she is apt to invite friends over for
cocktails in her dining room, where she keeps a well-stocked bar on
a large mirrored antique sideboard.
</P>
<P>
   Friedan is a die-hard fan of President Clinton, and praises him
for policies that have helped women, such as expanding the earned
income tax credit for lower income families so they can use the
money for child care.
</P>
<P>
   These days, in her lectures and writing, she is casting out
broad intellectual nets in search of solutions to the dilemma of
how to strike a better balance between work and family.
</P>
<P>
   She has been cautious to include men as well as women in her
discussions of how to lighten the parenting load on working
mothers.
</P>
<P>
   ``A person with her history and visibility is capable of drawing
attention to ideas and can really exert influence,'' said William
Galston, a fellow at the Brookings Institution, a Washington think
tank. ``She is playing a leading role in a policy game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-25-98 1648EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981125.0234 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-25 16:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
