<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-25 16:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9574 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LIGHT-EMOTIONS-ART-2T     11-25 0921
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIGHT-EMOTIONS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INGO MAURER: MUNICH DESIGNER BRINGS EMOTION TO LIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo of is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
(gm) 
 By PATRICIA LEIGH BROWN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Twilight on the Brooklyn Bridge. A new moon has risen
on silent wings as the setting sun envelops the harbor in a golden
embrace.
</P>
<P>
   It is the time of day that Ingo Maurer, arguably the world's
Merlin of light, calls ``l'heure bleu,'' the bittersweet moment
when, unwilling to yield to darkness, the city summons forth light.
</P>
<P>
   The hour is also a feeling. ``Light is immaterial,'' he will
tell you, walking briskly among the pylons, wool scarf cascading
behind him. ``You grab it with your mind, your soul, your heart. I
think of it as a friendly ghost that surrounds us.''
</P>
<P>
   At times using little more than a bulb, the designer, from
Munich, Germany, has spent the past three decades capturing the
emotion of light in physical form. A sense of wonder is always
there: a fly alights on a three-dimensional hologram of a light
bulb (1977); for Kokoro, part of a new series, a quaking red heart,
made of pulled and folded paper, curls longingly around a tiny bulb
encased in wire.
</P>
<P>
   In this season of light, it is appropriate that Maurer, 66, is
the subject of ``Projects 66: Campana/Ingo Maurer,'' an exhibition
of his designs opening Friday at the Museum of Modern Art. The show
also features the work of the young Brazilian furniture designers
Fernando and Humberto Campana, who make handcrafted furniture from
cotton rope, garden hoses and other offbeat materials.
</P>
<P>
   In an era of aggressive Darth Vadar-like lighting, Maurer
celebrates lightness in joyful creations that at times seem more
like living creatures than objects. The son of a fisherman, he grew
up on an island on Lake Constance in southern Germany, and a part
of him, despite his worldly demeanor and a mane of silver hair
tucked fashionably behind his ears, remains the little boy
suspended over the bow of his father's fishing boat, peering into
the dappled reflections.
</P>
<P>
   Maurer's career has coincided with technical revolutions in
lighting, especially low-voltage tungsten halogen, which he has
exploited to the hilt for its minimalist qualities. But the essence
of his designs springs from what he calls ``hasard,'' the French
word for ``chance'' _ unexpected moments when light makes a sensual
impression. It can happen on the Brooklyn Bridge, or walking
through an olive grove and seeing the play of light when the wind
flickers the leaves. For him, it often happens in winter, when the
sun is low and alights on particles of dust, illuminating the
suspended movement in ``a kind of dancing.''
</P>
<P>
   Such ``sense impressions,'' as he calls them, can percolate for
years before Maurer, who has no formal academic design training and
began as a typographer's apprentice, finally translates them into a
design. ``I wait until the moment comes,'' he explained, his
conversation frequently interrupted by gestures. ``I don't force
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea for Ya Ya Ho (1984), perhaps his most influential and
copied design, was born on a New Year's Eve in Haiti. In this
graceful lighting system, which, like many of his designs, lets the
owner decide the final configuration, tiny halogen bulbs become
miniature tightrope walkers, suspended from cables stretching from
wall to wall. Radical in that it floats light in space with nearly
invisible structure _ achieving lightness quite literally _ it was
inspired by this memory: ``We came out into this little piazza, and
there were two strings running across it, with one huge glass light
bulb trying to fight the morning sun. I was so thrilled, because
the bulb had no socket, and was soldered straight onto the wire. I
could have stood there forever,'' he said, his ebullience emitting
wattage.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, he began designing Ya Ya Ho, an arduous
technical challenge that took two-and-one-half years and almost
left him bankrupt. (The loan officer said, ``Why don't you do
something rustic?'')
</P>
<P>
   ``Light is a very psychoactive material, if you can call it a
material,'' he said, as the bulbs of the Brooklyn Bridge were
beginning to make light. ``It can be tender, or determined and
strong. I can't think of a dull moment of light.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, Maurer has drawn inspiration from rigatoni pasta
and Alexander Calder. In his Munich studio, nicknamed the
``designery,'' he frequently experiments with found objects, most
famously a bunch of red plastic stork legs spied at Woolworth's
(the salesclerk wouldn't sell him legs without bodies, so, he
confesses, he stole them). ``I was immediately excited about those
legs,'' he recalled, still charged up. ``When I held them in my
hand, I knew exactly what I was going to do!'' The result was
Bibibibi, a charming avianlike lamp that looks ready to cross the
road.
</P>
<P>
   His Porca Miseria (``Damn It!'' in Italian) is an explosion of
broken dishes in which rays of light escape through skewed, broken
silverware and porcelain. More ``a burst of fury than a
chandelier,'' in the words of the Modern's associate curator Paola
Antonelli, it mimics Maurer's love of slow-motion implosions in
movies like ``Zabriskie Point.'' It was originally designed for the
sterile kitchen of a sprawling palazzo. ``People with a Borghese
attitude make me nervous,'' he said, somewhat conspiratorially.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   For Maurer, the essence of beauty remains a single light bulb,
the perfect meeting, he says, of poetry, industry and design. At
once strong and fragile, the bulb has been a leitmotif, from his
First Bulb lamp (1966), a Pop Art bulb-within-a-bulb to the recent
Edison hologram, in which 2,250 individual images of a light bulb
were bonded onto an acrylic cylinder, fulfilling his 20-year dream
of ``making light from a nonexisting light bulb.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a sense impression of a light bulb that, by hasard,
filled the hollows of his life and ultimately changed its
direction. In his early 30's, having spent three-and-one-half years
working as a graphic designer in San Francisco, he was lying on a
mattress in a cheap Italian pensione while on vacation, when his
mind drifted to the image of a naked light bulb, ``an impression of
light'' from his childhood. He remembered the bulb suspended from a
window his father had cut in the wall between the bathroom and the
anteroom. He began sketching a design on the mattress and went to
Murano, Italy, the glass-blowing center, to recreate it.
</P>
<P>
   One of the more unusual aspects of Maurer's career is that, in
contrast with most designers, he goes it alone, designing,
manufacturing and distributing his own products (he also
manufactures the work of others he finds interesting). Though
committed to risk creatively _ ``If you don't take risks, you never
know yourself'' _ his independent status rose not from confidence,
he said, but from the insecurity he felt as a young man who went to
work at age 15 after his father died. (His father, an inventor by
avocation, created a ham smoker that, in the hands of Maurer's
three brothers, became the foundation for a large company.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I was not a trained designer,'' he said, somewhat reluctant to
talk about it. ``I was an insider and an outsider at the same time.
So I preferred to go through my own torture.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, observes the English designer Ron Arad, a frequent
collaborator, ``His poetry doesn't die when it goes into
production.''
</P>
<P>
   For their work at the Tel Aviv Opera House, Arad recalled,
Maurer spent almost a year designing an inverted chandelier for a
huge egg-shaped cavity in the foyer. The day before the building
opened, Maurer ``decided it was kitsch, a gigantic piece of
jewelry, and replaced it with a single light bulb.''
</P>
<P>
   Though there is no Maurer style, his lighting _ you can't really
call many of his designs lamps _ is playful and modest, bringing
spaces alive without taking them over. He clings to humor and
lightness, he says, in part as a reaction to his native Germany.
``It's a heavy country,'' he observes. ``It is almost as if,
through my work, I am reaching for oxygen.''
</P>
<P>
   His studio, home to a 65-member design and engineering team, is
located in a converted laundry building on the Kaiserstrasse, the
Greenwich Village of Munich. Beyond design, the team comes up with
the technical wizardry to realize his ideas, including
never-before-seen sockets, bulbs, wiring and dimmers. Three years
ago, ``after living in sin for 23 years,'' as he put it, he married
Jenny Lau, whom he describes as ``the column of my enterprise,'' in
a Las Vegas wedding chapel on her 50th birthday. (Ms. Lau is the
computer wiz; he doesn't touch them.) He has two daughters from a
previous marriage, and he seems genuinely proud to announce, is a
grandfather three times over.
</P>
<P>
   Like a grandfather, he enjoys giving pet names to his objects,
calling his latest family, or tribe, of paper lights the MaMo
Nouchies _ now on display at Moss, a SoHo design store, starting at
$735, and the Museum of Modern Art Design Store _ ``Ma'' is for
Maurer, ``Nouchies'' for Isamu Noguchi and the ``Mo'' for Dagmar
Mombach, a friend who developed a special technique for dyeing
paper _ a material prized for its soft ``quieting'' light _ and
pulling and wrapping it in a way that reconfigures the fibers.
Maurer reveres paper; like light, it is endlessly variable.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, Maurer has gotten more involved with ``urban
scenography,'' creating light environments within buildings and,
most recently, the Munich subway system, for which he has created a
series of lighted handmade-aluminum domes within the stations to
give people a ``safe, comfortable, taken-care-of-feeling.'' At the
furniture fairs in Milan, Italy, and Cologne, Germany, his
environments have become latter-day equivalents of 1960's
happenings that draw as many as 10,000 viewers to villa courtyards
or bridges across the Rhine. He is designing a long, golden
floating aluminum ribbon for a Neo-Classical palazzo in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't capture light, he insists, but merely observes it. At
sunset in a desert near Cairo, a place he goes to unwind, he
recently saw a spectacle he will never forget: thousands of empty
plastic bags filled with air blowing in the wind. ``They were going
bufff!... bufff!... from side to side,'' he said rhapsodically,
recreating the motion, ``thousands of them making waves, waiting
for the breeze. Oh, it was wonderful! As far as I could see there
were bags filled with light'' _ light, a riddle that never ends.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
