<SLUG> BC-CIR-TRAINS-OPTIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAINS FOR THE PURIST TO THE NEWCOMER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Va., Vt.)  (With CIR-TRAINS) 
(js) 
 By LES LINE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The elaborate layouts that replicate real railroads in real
places in great detail are typically the province of modelers using
small-scale rather than traditional-size (O-gauge) trains, which
are approximately 1/48th the size of the prototypes.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the yearbook ``Great Model Railroads '99,''
published by Model Railroader Magazine, features a layout of the
old Boston &AMP; Maine Railroad's West Hoosic Division, which ran from
North Adams, Mass., to Bennington, Vt., as it looked in the 1950s.
The scale is HO (or half-O), and one inch on the model locomotive
equals 87 inches on the real thing. Smaller yet are N-scale (1:160)
trains that are decidedly not toys.
</P>
<P>
   The 22-by-26-foot B&AMP;M layout, created by Lou Sassi, includes a
high trestle, a stone-arch bridge, the Hoosac Tunnel and actual
buildings along the route, as well as trains that look like they've
been around the track more than a few years. As Chris Smithson, a
spokesman for MTH Electric Trains, said: ``No HO modeler with
self-respect would run an engine right out of the box. If they
didn't totally rebuild it, they'd weather it.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Lionel has introduced a Warhorse line of trains covered
with fake grit from smoking locomotives. Real trains rarely got
weekend baths.
</P>
<P>
   Newcomers or returnees to O-gauge railroading, on the other
hand, are usually content with building a layout that fits on a
4-foot-by-8-foot slab of green-painted plywood, adding a few
preassembled or snap-together plastic structures like a village
train station, a water tower, an engine house or a church.
</P>
<P>
   Catalogs from Lionel and MTH offer a number of track schemes for
a basement-corner layout as well as accessories. But if the urge to
run a larger and more realistic railroad strikes, the hobbyist can
turn to 3D Railroad Concept and Design from Abracadata
(www.abracadata.com). &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The program, for both Windows and Macintosh computers, lets the
user imagine a layout, add structures and scenery and run virtual
trains to test the design. The CD-ROM includes a comprehensive 3D
library of actual products, from trains to trees, from 60
manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   Abracadata also has a nifty computer game for make-believe
railroaders with no room for a toy-train layout. 3D Railroad Master
for Windows 95 and 98 puts you in the cab of a diesel engine with
realistic controls to adjust speed, change the train's direction,
blow the horn and hit the brakes to avoid game-ending derailments.
</P>
<P>
   The rumble of the train over the tracks is realistic if tiresome
after a time, and thankfully the pop background music can be turned
off. The progress of the Railroad Master train around a wide range
of layouts can be viewed from the cab, from the front of the
engine, from behind the caboose, from a helicopter hovering
overhead or from cameras that can be placed at random along the
tracks. Scenic backdrops range from desert to snow-capped mountains
to big cities.
</P>
<P>
   The timed games involve train orders to pick up and drop off
cars or cargo and range from easy to difficult. And if the
high-tech sound effects of the new O-gauge locomotives isn't
enough, a new 80-minute CD called ``The Fading Giant: Sounds of
Steam Railroading'' is available from O. Winston Link Railway
Productions (4920 Buckhorn Rd. S.W., Roanoke, Va. 24014; $20).
</P>
<P>
   O. Winston Link is the photographer who chronicled the last days
of steam on the Norfolk &AMP; Western Railroad in 1957 and 1958. He
also captured the sounds of N&AMP;W trains with what was
state-of-the-art equipment at the time and produced recordings that
have been unavailable for years.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-25-98 1652EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
