<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-25 16:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9584 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DURAS-BIOGRAPHY-2TAKE     11-25 1130
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DURAS-BIOGRAPHY-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW BIOGRAPHY REWRITES MARGUERITE DURAS' HEROIC STATURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ALAN RIDING   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ As writers often do, Marguerite Duras used her life as
raw material for her novels. More unusually, her literature then
took over her life to the point that a fictional character called
Marguerite Duras assumed control. The real Duras may have written
her books, but increasingly she lived in an imaginary world of her
own making. Unless, of course, she was merely playacting, which was
possible.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, she framed the basic question _ Who was Marguerite
Duras? _ that confronted Laure Adler when she set out to write the
first biography of Duras published in France since her death at 81
in March 1996. Not that Duras thought the question worth exploring.
Her biography, she said, already existed in her fiction. Unless she
had something to hide, which proved to be the case.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, on the sensitive topic of her response to Germany's
occupation of France in World War II, Duras portrayed _ and perhaps
believed _ herself to have been more heroic than the record
suggests. She remembered her time in the Resistance and ``forgot''
her earlier work with the Germans. And it was far from the only
occasion when her memory was selective.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the end of her life, she believed in the legend that she
had invented of her life,'' said Ms. Adler, 48, a historian by
training who now works as an editor at a French publishing house.
``She hid all the clues to her life, but with sincerity. She simply
did not want to remember certain things. In fact, she no longer
knew who she really was. Everything she created in her books became
truer than the life she had really lived.''
</P>
<P>
   During seven years of research and writing, then, it was Ms.
Adler's task to separate not lies from truth, but fantasy from
reality. For two years, she was able to listen to and interrogate
Duras, who by then was resigned to publication of the biography.
But perhaps because Duras was ailing, or perhaps because she was
quietly sabotaging the attempt to discover her, these interviews
often added to Ms. Adler's confusion.
</P>
<P>
   ``At times, I thought I was going crazy,'' the biographer
recalled during an interview on a balmy fall evening in a Left Bank
hotel. ``If I had known it would be that difficult, that she would
follow me night and day, even in my dreams, I would not have
embarked on the project. But once I had started, I could not stop.
I had to reach my destination, which was to find out if Marguerite
Duras truly existed as a woman or was the legend she had created.''
</P>
<P>
   What helped keep Ms. Adler going was a strong emotional bond
established with her subject in the late 1970s. At the time,
disconsolate over the loss of a child at birth, Ms. Adler stumbled
across Duras' novel ``The Sea Wall,'' which she said gave her ``the
will to live.'' She wrote to Duras at her Left Bank apartment on
the Rue de Saint-Benoit to thank her. and a friendship was born.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, before Duras became a best-selling author with ``The
Lover'' in 1982, Ms. Adler had read none of her books. ``Duras was
very loved by a very small number of loyal fans who were almost
like a sect,'' Ms. Adler said. ``I always had the impression that
she was very distant, very complicated and very narcissistic.''
</P>
<P>
   Even among female writers, Duras was not heralded.
</P>
<P>
   ``The aura of Simone de Beauvoir prevented Duras from existing
as a literary and intellectual force,'' Ms. Adler said. ``And in
pure literature, Marguerite Youcenar prevented Duras from taking
her natural place. Frankly, I don't think I would ever have entered
Marguerite Duras' imaginary world if it had not been for my special
circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, by the time she decided to write Duras' biography, Ms.
Adler felt she knew her subject well. Yet when she began her
research by reading all of Duras' books in chronological order,
starting with ``Les Impudents,'' published in 1943, she encountered
various styles and different worlds, ``the many writers who were
Marguerite Duras,'' as she put it. She also sensed that not all of
Duras' life was to be found in her books.
</P>
<P>
   She therefore traveled to Vietnam, where Duras was born and
reared and where her teen-age romance with an older man, recounted
in ``The Lover,'' took place. There Ms. Adler met people who had
known not only the lover in the story (``who was not as handsome as
she described him,'' Ms. Adler noted), but also Duras, her mother
and her older brother. And from this she put together a melancholic
picture of the young Duras.
</P>
<P>
   ``She lived an almost martyrlike childhood, her father dead,
without the love of her mother, disdained, humiliated, frequently
beaten by her mother and brother,'' Ms. Adler said. ``None of this
appears in her books, but I think it is one of the keys to
understanding her work. She wrote in order to suffer less, to purge
the pain and suffering she had known.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, when she moved to Paris to study law and political
science at 18, Duras felt liberated. She had a considerable sexual
appetite, Ms. Adler notes in her French-language biography,
``Marguerite Duras'' (Editions Gallimard), and she moved
comfortably in leftist intellectual circles. After graduation from
the Sorbonne, she married the writer Robert Antelme and found work
as a secretary in the French Ministry of Colonies, staying there
for a year after Germany occupied France in 1940.
</P>
<P>
   In uncovering what she calls Duras' ambiguous response to the
occupation, Ms. Adler also broke new ground. In her 1985 book, ``La
Douleur,'' later published in the United States as ``The War,''
Duras portrays herself as part of a French Resistance group headed
by Francois Mitterrand, who was France's president from 1981 to
1995. But like Mitterrand, who worked for the collaborationist
Vichy regime in 1941 and 1942, Duras joined the Resistance only in
mid-1943.
</P>
<P>
   More significantly, for one year beginning in July 1942, Ms.
Adler recounts, Duras worked for the Book Organization Commission
as secretary of the bureau that controlled paper supplies and, as
such, determined which books were published or censored. Many
authors were banned, but others depended on the whims and tastes of
the book commission. And there, Ms. Adler says, ``Marguerite in
effect decided.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Adler leaves open the question of whether, by working under
German orders, Duras was a collaborator, but she was disturbed by
the novelist's unwillingness to discuss the issue. ``Marguerite
waved away with her hand a question that irritated her,'' she
writes. ``She did not remember why or how she found herself in the
commission and pretended to give it no importance.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Another strange episode occurred in the summer of 1944 when
Antelme was arrested for work in the Resistance and, in hopes of
obtaining her husband's release, Duras befriended Charles Delval, a
Frenchman working with the Gestapo. Before Antelme was deported to
Germany (he survived the war and returned home emaciated one year
later), Duras and Delval were seen together so often that there was
speculation that they were having an affair.
</P>
<P>
   Yet after Paris was liberated in August 1944, Delval was seized
and interrogated by Mitterrand's Resistance group. In ``La
Douleur,'' Duras describes how she tortured him, a fact that she
later repeated in interviews, although no one apparently witnessed
her doing so. Certainly, Duras' fierce testimony against Delval
during his trial for collaboration helped persuade the court to
sentence him to death. ``Historians today believe that he did not
deserve to have been killed,'' Ms. Adler said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, what Ms. Adler calls ``a hallucinatingly bad novel''
was unfolding. Even before Antelme was arrested, Duras had taken a
young writer, Dionys Mascolo, as her lover. Yet after Delval's
arrest and during his trial, Mascolo had an affair with Delval's
wife, Paulette, with whom he had a child, born after Delval's
execution. Later, Mascolo returned to Duras, with whom he also had
a child, Jean.
</P>
<P>
   After the war, Duras joined the French Communist Party and,
while she was later expelled as part of a Stalinist purge, she
remained a committed leftist and participated in the May 1968
student movement. ``She ran through the streets like a gamine,''
Ms. Adler said. ``She participated in demonstrations, she moderated
meetings at the Sorbonne, she really believed that the revolution
would happen on the morrow.''
</P>
<P>
   By then, although still not a public favorite, Duras was a
prolific novelist, playwright and screenwriter (she wrote
``Hiroshima Mon Amour'' for Alain Resnais) while her personal life
included a succession of lovers.
</P>
<P>
   Then, from 1980, Yann Andrea Steiner, a homosexual 40 years her
junior, became the love, though not the lover, of the last 16 years
of her life. He encouraged her to publish ``The Lover'' and, as her
heavy smoking and drinking took an increasing toll on her health,
he also nursed her.
</P>
<P>
   ``She invented him even before they met,'' Ms. Adler said. ``She
had received letters from him and she created an image of him. When
they met, she turned him into this image.'' Steiner helped Ms.
Adler with her biography and when he read it, she recalled, he had
only one complaint: ``When I wrote that he slept in Marguerite's
bed, he said that was impossible because she talked and talked and
talked.''
</P>
<P>
   Unusually for a biography, Ms. Adler is also present in her
book, as if leading the reader through her research and discoveries
and frustrations. ``I felt this was more honest because there are
times when I do not know what is true or false, even what she has
told me,'' the author explained. ``I do not pretend to know the
truth about her. I have been re-reading some of her books and I
realize that I still have not fully understood her.''
</P>
<P>
   So, Ms. Adler was asked, does she like Duras less now that she
knows her better?
</P>
<P>
   ``No, a lot more,'' she said without hesitation. ``There were
times when I cried with rage at her violence, her egoism, her
spitefulness. I didn't like her ambiguity in the war. And I
couldn't stand the way she proclaimed herself to be a genius. But
she was also immensely courageous because she took the risk of
looking deep inside herself. She knew she was self-destructive, but
her writing saved her from madness. And that's what makes her a
great writer. In a memorably pure style, she speaks to us all.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
