<HEADLINE>
FORCE'S EIGHTH NHRA TITLE STOPS CLOCK ON MIDLIFE CRISIS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Twenty years ago, when John Force launched his NHRA Funny Car
career, his goals were as simple as arrive-and-survive.
</P>
<P>
   And smile for the camera.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first went to a race I wanted to do a burnout like Don
Prudhomme and Tom McEwen,'' said Force, rattling off the names of
his straight-line heroes. ``I wanted to stage, so somebody could
take my picture. I never thought about winning.''
</P>
<P>
   Seventy victories and eight championships later, Force has
established himself as the National Hot Rod Association's marquee
driver and its most marketable personality. Rising stars Gary
Scelzi (Top Fuel), Ron Capps (Funny Car) and Jeg Coughlin Jr. (Pro
Stock) spent 1998 positioning themselves to carry the NHRA into the
next century.
</P>
<P>
   Still, if professional drag racing hopes to narrow the
popularity gap enjoyed by NASCAR's Winston Cup Series, it will do
so riding along with ``Brute'' Force at 320-plus mph.
</P>
<P>
   But for how much longer? Force, 49, said recently he is five
years away from considering retirement. Force wistfully hints that
he is going Top Fuel racing one of these days, just like four-time
Funny Car champions Prudhomme and Kenny Bernstein.
</P>
<P>
   Force certainly found it tougher to win NHRA finals during 1998.
He won three, 10 fewer than during his blockbuster 1996 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a year where I'm fighting every minute,'' said Force,
who clearly was upstaged by Capps' five victories for car owner
Prudhomme. ``The fans know I'm slugging. They know a time will come
when I can't win.''
</P>
<P>
   That partly explains why Force is so proud of his eighth
championship. It is the most in Funny Car history but two fewer
than the 10 compiled by retired NHRA Pro Stock champion Bob
Glidden, drag racing's winningest driver.
</P>
<P>
   But Force's eight titles are one more than the seven won by
Richard Petty and Dale Earnhardt in Winston Cup, and ample fodder
for debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``To win the eighth title is a notch on the ladder, because
we're racing NASCAR,'' said Force, who has won all of his titles
during the 1990s. ``I know you can't compare Earnhardt or Petty
with me, but we can say we did something for NHRA Winston Drag
Racing. To have a stat where we did something like Earnhardt and
Petty, it's an accomplishment. It's like \Rwinning\S driver of the
year. It moved drag racing a notch on the ladder with NASCAR. It
was something for all of us. That's something I wanted to do.''
</P>
<P>
   For those with short memories, Force was voted driver of the
year in 1996 _ the first time a drag racer had won that prestigious
honor in its 30-year history. Force since has said that any number
of NHRA drivers _ from Glidden to Prudhomme to Bernstein to Shirley
Muldowney _ could have/should have won the award before he did.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just there at the right time,'' said Force, whose
off-beat personality and the NHRA's trademark fan accessibility
have proven a perfect match. ``If you let me out there by myself,
the stands would be empty. Yeah, I sell more stuff \Rsouvenirs and
collectibles\S than anybody, and I am a big name. But I ain't
carrying the sport. A lot of people say that, but I don't want to
allow myself to think that.''
</P>
<P>
   Force admittedly has an edge in one aspect of contemporary
motorsports _ corporate bucks and the technology money can buy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Castrol puts a ton of money in this car,'' said Force, driver
of the GTX Ford Mustang. ``You also have got to have the right
team, and I teamed up with the right guy in \Rcrew chief\S Austin
Coil. He is a genius in the sense that he creates his own
technology. I have Bernie Fedderly backing up Coil, a guy that ran
his own team and won championships. I have hired the right
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with that imposing support network, Force knows the clock
is ticking on his productive days inside the cockpit. Whether it be
in a Funny Car or Top Fueler, nobody outruns Father Time at
midlife.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like to talk about my age because then the sponsors
say, `What, he's getting too old,''' Force said. ``You've only got
to drive for five seconds, so a driver can last out here a long
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am going to go until the graveyard. This is what I do. I
don't have any other life.'' \Ntagtop:John Sturbin, (817) 390-7408.
THE BUZZ IRL
</P>
<P>
   Arie Luyendyk's days of racing at Texas Motor Speedway in Fort
Worth are over. Luyendyk, winner of the inaugural and controversial
True Value 500K night race at TMS in June 1997, plans to retire
after the 1999 Indianapolis 500 on May 30. That means he will not
participate in the third annual True Value 500K, the first race
after the Indy 500, on June 12. Luyendyk's only appearance in the
1999 Pep Boys Indy Racing League Series will be at the Indianapolis
Motor Speedway, where he will drive for team owner Fred Treadway
for a fourth consecutive year. A two-time Indy 500 champion,
Luyendyk does plan to attend other IRL events as a team consultant
and sponsor spokesman. Luyendyk, a vigorous 45, said his decision
to retire was influenced by family considerations. He and his wife,
Mieke, have four children. The oldest, 17-year-old Arie Jr., is
competing in Formula Ford 1600s. ``The timing is right for me to
stop,'' said Luyendyk, who has won four IRL races, including one in
each of the league's three seasons. ``I want to help my son with
his racing. Fortunately, I'm able to retire on my own terms, and I
don't think there could be any better place to do it than at the
Indianapolis Motor Speedway.'' Luyendyk's 14 Indy 500 starts
include victories in 1990 and 1997, and more than $5.2 million in
earnings at The Brickyard alone. ...
</P>
<P>
   Luyendyk's legacy at TMS, of course, revolves around his
postrace protest of Billy Boat's victory in that inaugural True
Value race. Luyendyk stormed into Victory Lane, where he was
promptly slapped in the head and knocked to the ground by team
owner and four-time Indy 500 champion A.J. Foyt. But after an
all-night audit by the sanctioning U.S. Auto Club, Luyendyk was
declared the winner. ...
</P>
<P>
   IRL officials have hired the firms of Wieden &AMP; Kennedy and
Golin/Harris International to oversee its latest advertising and
public relations efforts. The IRL's so-called ``strategic marketing
plan'' will incorporate advertising, marketing and promotion on
many levels, including TV, print, the Internet, point-of-purchase
and event-site activities. Golin/Harris, which includes an office
in Dallas, lists McDonald's, DaimlerChrysler, Michelin and Texas
Instruments among its clientele. Wieden &AMP; Kennedy has worked
globally with Nike, Microsoft, Coca-Cola, Miller and ESPN.
CART
</P>
<P>
   Several CART FedEx Championship Series teams have begun
off-season preparations and testing for the 1999 season.
Newman/Haas Racing unloaded its first 1999 Swift on Tuesday at its
Lincolnshire, Ill., base. Delivery of the third-generation,
American-built Swift was more than a month earlier than in the
previous two off-seasons. Christian Fittipaldi is scheduled to test
the Kmart Swift/Ford on Dec. 14-16 at Sebring (Fla.) International
Raceway. Teammate Michael Andretti is not booked to turn a wheel on
the Texaco Havoline Swift/Ford until mid-January. ...
</P>
<P>
   PacWest Racing kicked off the testing season last week, when it
became the first Champ Car team to run the 1999 Reynard chassis.
Mauricio Gugelmin spent three days shaking down a Reynard at
Sebring, logging 600 trouble-free miles on his Hollywood PacWest
Mercedes. ``We kept it simple, but looked at a lot of things,'' the
Brazilian said. ``At least I know I have a car that I can use the
brakes to attack corners, rather than a car that wants to attack
me.'' ...
</P>
<P>
   Team KOOL Green's Paul Tracy spent two days testing Firestone
tires at the Miami-Dade Homestead (Fla.) Motorsports Complex's
1.502-mile oval last week. Tracy ran 226 laps on the second day in
a 1998 Reynard/Honda. The team is scheduled to receive its first
1999 Reynard around Dec. 6, and Dario Franchitti plans to test it
Dec. 11-12 at Homestead. ...
</P>
<P>
   Team Rahal's Bryan Herta (Shell Reynard/Ford) and Max Papis
(Miller Lite Reynard/Ford) are scheduled to test their 1999 chassis
at Firebird International Raceway outside Phoenix next week.
World of Outlaws
</P>
<P>
   A Sprint Car powered by a Mopar (Chrysler) engine never has won
a race in the Pennzoil World of Outlaws Series. That stat should
change in 1999, the first season of a recently announced multiyear
sponsorship agreement between Team Mopar and the Kinser Racing
father/son duo of Karl and Mark Kinser. Karl Kinser has won 15
series championships as a car owner, most recently in 1997. Gary
Stanton, who has campaigned a Mopar-powered car on the tour since
1996, will handle the engine-building duties. ``This new motor has
everything in the right place, and we think it's got a ton of
potential,'' said Mark Kinser, who finished 93 points behind cousin
Steve Kinser in the 1998 WoO driver's championship. ...
</P>
<P>
   Steve Kinser's 1998 Outlaws title, his first since trying the
Winston Cup ranks in 1995, did not come in typical ``King of the
Outlaws'' fashion. Kinser logged his second-lowest victory total
during a full Outlaws season with six, but bagged his record 15th
title on consistency. In 65 ``A'' Main events, Kinser finished in
the top-five 42 times and in the top-10 in 58 races. \Nname:_ Len
Hayward
FAST LAPS
What off-season?
</P>
<P>
   Texas Motor Speedway will play host to several test sessions
during the first two weeks of December.
</P>
<P>
   Of most interest will be a Goodyear tire test involving NASCAR
regular Jeff Burton, winner of the inaugural 500-mile Winston Cup
race in Fort Worth in April 1997. The sessions on Dec. 8-9 will be
the first time a Cup driver has run full speed on the 1.5-mile
trioval since it was reconfigured and repaved after last spring's
water-marred Texas 500.
</P>
<P>
   Burton, driver of the No. 99 Exide Batteries Ford Taurus, is the
Roush Racing teammate of Mark Martin, who won last spring's Cup
race at TMS.
</P>
<P>
   Firestone kicks off the month with tests of its Pep Boys Indy
Racing League tires on Dec. 1-2. The tests will feature Plano's
Greg Ray, who recently signed a five-year contract as lead driver
for Team Menard.
</P>
<P>
   The IRL also has scheduled a test for five drivers looking to
secure their racing licenses for 1999. Three-time Indy 500 champion
Johnny Rutherford of Fort Worth and IRL regular Scott Goodyear are
scheduled to work with Ryan Newman of the U.S. Auto Club Silver
Crown series; Tony Elliott, USAC Sprint Cars; Jay Drake, USAC
Midgets, and Jac Haudenschild and Greg Hodnett of the Pennzoil
World of Outlaws Series.
</P>
<P>
   And A.J. Foyt Enterprises, home to reigning IRL champion Kenny
Brack and 1998 True Value 500K winner Billy Boat, tentatively has
scheduled a test for Dec. 10-11.
</P>
<P>
   All tests are closed to the public.
Last words
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the oldest driver in the IRL, so I'm like a senior
citizen. I can do what I want.''''
</P>
<P>
   _ Arie Luyendyk
</P>
<P>
   IRL driver who wants to retire after the 1999 Indy 500.
</P>
