<HEADLINE>
SHORT NEWS NOTES ON COMPUTERS   AND GADGETS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ga., Calif.)   (af)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   America Online made headlines this week for its deals with
Netscape and Sun Microsystems for $4.2 billion. Now the online
giant has made another deal, one that could net its new customers
... 50 cents?
</P>
<P>
   In a program it will roll out on mid-December, AOL (www.aol.com)
said it had authorized an online incentive company, Cybergold Inc.
of Berkeley, Calif., to pay 50 cents to every person who downloads
and installs AOL's chat software, called Instant Messenger.
</P>
<P>
   The program allows users to simultaneously send and receive
messages to one another through the Internet, without signing up
and paying for full AOL service.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, there is a catch. After a Web surfer downloads and installs
the software, Cybergold will place the 50 cents into a Cybergold
account. However, that money (which comes from fees paid by AOL to
Cybergold) can only be redeemed when the person accumulates $5 in
Cybergold credits. That means he or she must participate in other
Cybergold promotions (www.cybergold.com).
</P>
<P>
   One such program, for example, pays $5 for joining for a certain
period of time the Disney Blast online service. Nat Goldhaber,
chief executive of Cybergold, said the idea behind his marketing
concept was to provide ``an incentive to tell people that it makes
sense to pay attention.'' Translation: he wants to buy Web users'
attention.
</P>
<P>
   But why would AOL want to spend 50 cents to attract people to a
free service? The more chat-hungry surfers AOL attracts, the bigger
its user base _ which the company says is already at 35 million
people. And the more people who sign up, the more AOL can charge
advertisers who want to reach those users.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds like it might be worth holding out for 75 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Bell South has taken a page from the Lilliputians' book. Or a
pager, rather.
</P>
<P>
   In keeping with the theme in electronics of making
communications devices ever smaller, while cramming more functions
into them, Bell South is selling what it calls the Interactive
Paging Service.
</P>
<P>
   Well, gadget heads, it's not just a pager. That would be too
easy. It's also a device for sending and receiving e-mail. The
receiving part is obvious, but the sending is trickier, especially
given the diminutive size of the device.
</P>
<P>
   The 3{-inch tall by 2{-inch wide pager includes a tiny Qwerty
keyboard that lets a user send messages via wireless pager. The
keys do not lend themselves to penning a novel, but they get the
job done for messages, insisted John M. Kampfe, spokesman for Bell
South Wireless Data, a New Jersey-based subsidiary of Bell South
Corp. in Atlanta. ``You can type pretty quick with a little
practice,'' Kampfe said.
</P>
<P>
   The $359 pager can send messages to a telephone, where they can
be retrieved in the form of digitized voice mail. A second feature
permits two users of the pager to send e-mail instantaneously to
one another, with an interesting twist.
</P>
<P>
   If one user sends a message with the pager, he will know the
moment it is received, and also the moment it is opened by the
recipient. This, as Kampfe noted, may make it possible to know when
someone _ say, a boss or significant other _ isn't giving you the
time of day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now you know when you're getting blown off,'' he said. ``This
is positive acknowledgment to the max.''
</P>
<P>
   Next Tuesday , the Simon Wiesenthal Center in Los Angeles is
holding a conference called ``Internet 2000: Promise and Peril,''
designed to address privacy, free expression and hate on the Net _
and how to reconcile these ideas.
</P>
<P>
   One fact that is not in dispute, said Rabbi Abraham Cooper,
associate dean of the center, is that hate speech on the Net is on
the rise. In late 1997, the center found some 600 sites promoting
racism and bigotry on the Web. In a new study to be released in
January, the center found more than 1,000.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper said one new tactic of the hate-site promoters was to
target children with animation and games, like the site that
encourages children to play a Doom-like game in which the object is
to shoot Jews and African Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The Rabbi said that the typical antidote to such hate speech was
free speech, which lets the rational ideas compete with irrational
ones. But he said that antidote did not always work in cyberspace,
since a Web page promoting hate doesn't leave room for the
proverbial ``other side of the story.''
</P>
<P>
   To further illuminate the issue, and find ways to combat online
hate speech, the center on Tuesday will convene a roundtable with
business and legal luminaries, including Raymond Smith, chief
executive of the Bell Atlantic Corp., and Myer Berlow, senior vice
president of America Online. Later in the day, the conference will
address how teachers and schools can deal with these issues.
</P>
<P>
   The center's Web site, www.wiesenthal.com, will provide audio
from next Tuesday's events. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Major news organizations may wince at first glance at the latest
figures on the decline in popularity of their online sites.
</P>
<P>
   According to Media Metrix, an online research company that
compiles monthly figures Internet usage, in October, MSNBC
attracted 5.1 million unique visitors, down from 6.4 million in
September.
</P>
<P>
   CNN dropped to 4.6 million from 7.1 million; USA Today to 3.3
from 3.9 and The New York Times site to 1.6 million from 1.8
million.
</P>
<P>
   Did the nation suddenly become less interested in the day's
events? Only temporarily, according to Doug McFarland, senior vice
president of Media Metrix.
</P>
<P>
   McFarland says the declines seem so large only because they
follow a sharp rise in September, fueled by the publication of the
Starr report and other revelations about President Clinton and
Monica Lewinsky. More generally, the researcher said that the
recent historical data consistently showed that news site
popularity correlates very clearly with news events.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a pattern we have seen very, very consistently for three
years now,'' he said, adding, ``I try not to get into
prognostication, but I predict when we get the November data, the
traffic will be up because of the election.''
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of journalists, techies and salesman descended upon
Las Vegas recently for a sensory overload of a convention
experience known as Comdex. A research consortium believes there is
a much better way to have such a meeting of the minds, one that
makes it possible for visitors to never leave their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend, that consortium, Contact Consortium, a nonprofit
group based in Santa Cruz, Calif., that promotes the development of
online communities, held what may be the largest-ever virtual
conference. Called Avatars '98, the convention, appropriately, was
designed as a meeting place for individuals and companies
interested in virtual worlds, and the avatars _ those little online
pictures and animated stand-ins for real people _ that populate
them.
</P>
<P>
   In the three previous years, the Avatar conference was held
in-person in convention halls, but this year, the group decided to
``put our money where our mouths are,'' according to Bruce Damer,
director of the Contact Consortium (www.ccon.org).
</P>
<P>
   Some of the vestiges of the conventional convention remained.
Visitors signed in at the group's Web site, then proceeded to troll
a massive virtual convention hall, rubbing shoulders with other
avatars and stopping at virtual booths, which looked,
appropriately, like animated three-dimensional booths. Damer said
the convention site was modeled after the Sand's Convention Center
in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   To interact, the avatars could wave to one another, and speak by
typing their conversations onto the screen.
</P>
<P>
   In all, 4,000 people attended the 24-hour event, Damer said.
Alas, he does not expect the concept to ever totally replace the
in-person version, which enables colleagues, friends and
prospective business partners to press the flesh, not the mouse.
``They wear me out,'' Damer said, ``but I love them.''
</P>
<P>
   A good video game player needs good hand/eye coordination. But
one company contends it particularly favors good right-hand/eye
coordination.
</P>
<P>
   LefKey International, (www.lefkey.com) a Massachusetts company,
is hoping to revive the idea of the left-handed keyboard, aimed at
game players of that persuasion. The idea is not new, but never
caught on, according to LefKey's president, Mark Giordani, who said
he was negotiating deals with major catalog companies to carry the
keyboard (along with the company's left-handed mouse).
</P>
<P>
   So what makes the $129 keyboard left-handed? Nothing too fancy.
Principally, the number pad and Insert, Home, etc. keys are moved
to the left side, ostensibly allowing southpaws to use their
strongest hands on the arrow keys and number pad, from whence many
action games are controlled. Perhaps this will work well for
left-handed accountants too.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
