DONALDSON-CLINTON (Phoenix) - Celebrity newsman Sam Donaldson has a
confession to make: ``I've got to come absolutely clean . . . I
have been wrong about Bill Clinton all along,'' Donaldson told the
Valley Automobile Dealers Association Wednesday. ``I have been
wrong, wrong, wrong.'' Donaldson's mea culpa came in a speech that
touched on a debate raging in newsrooms across the country: Whether
the line between journalists and commentators is blurring too fast
and too much. By MICHAEL MURPHY. Story will move in the ``A''
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
SHOPPING (Undated) - Retailers have candidly dubbed Friday ``Black
Friday'' _ the day when stores hope to start moving out of the
``red'' and into the ``black.'' Venturing out to the malls on what
is one of the busiest shopping days of the year is not for the
shopping-challenged. Parking trauma, pushy purchasers and long
lines to see the big guy (that would be Santa) can squelch even the
most heartfelt inclinations for peace on Earth _ not to mention
goodwill towards your fellow man. Heading out on your gift-buying
adventure with a budget and a strategic plan of attack, however,
just may save your sanity. It's also likely to lessen the damage
done to your pocketbook. By ANNE M. SPITZA. Story moved in the
``L'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
LEIBOWITZ-COLUMN (Undated) - The story ran small in ``The Arizona
Republic,'' but my disgust was anything but. I read it three times,
not for its content, but for the directive that story positively
shouted. It's a simple mandate, a twist on Shakespeare. Let's kill
all the pollsters! They slaughtered politics first, see, then
barraged us with useless trivia. Now they've turned dangerous, as
this nasty little story shows. By DAVID LEIBOWITZ. Story moved in
the ``K'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
BROPHY (Phoenix) - Brophy Prep. The name rings with history and
