<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-25 17:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9656 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BROPHY-AZR &LR;      11-25 2477
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROPHY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JESUIT TEACHINGS PROMINENT IN BROPHY HIGH'S MISSION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB GOLFEN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Father Anton &UR; Renna was rattling around his empty
classroom, rain pounding the courtyard outside the open windows.
</P>
<P>
   The room was filled with the mossy smell of the rare all-day
rainstorm, mingled with the scent of damp, ancient plaster in the
70-year-old building, one of the original structures at Brophy
College Preparatory.
</P>
<P>
   ``They call this Renna weather,'' the Jesuit said, stroking his
gray goatee as he recalled his upbringing in Spokane, Wash.
</P>
<P>
   Renna's classroom was empty, but filled with life _ the
charismatic presence of the 64-year-old teacher; his ever-changing
collection of artwork, posters and models that decorate every
available space; and perhaps the lingering spirits of three
generations of boys taught in this room.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good to be here,'' he said. `'It really is good to be
here.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Academic excellence
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Brophy Prep. The name rings with tradition, an upper-crust
cachet and a promise of academic excellence. Now celebrating 70
years since its founding, the all-boys high school is the
pre-eminent secondary school in the state, boasting that 99 percent
of its graduates go on to college.
</P>
<P>
   Brophy's distinctive, mission-style main structure, punctuated
by its huge chapel tower, has stood on Central Avenue in Phoenix
since 1928. It was founded by the Society of Jesus on a $250,000
grant and a 25-acre site, then north of Phoenix, from Ellen J.
Brophy in memory of her late husband, William Henry Brophy.
Originally, it was envisioned as a Jesuit high school and college,
though that ambitious scheme was soon scaled back.
</P>
<P>
   Today, with a cadre of loyal students and alumni, instilled with
Jesuit teachings of ethics and community service, Brophy has
managed to carve out a lofty niche for itself.
</P>
<P>
   Renna has been teaching seniors at Brophy Prep for 34 years,
longer than anyone, and some consider him to be the embodiment of
the place, of what students, teachers and alum enigmatically call
the Brophy experience. Or simply, the Brophy magic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard that, and I would like to think that's the case,
though I'm not really sure I know what it means,'' the priest said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But this is my home and my life. This is not my job, it's not
my business, it's not something I'm paid to do. It's my daily
life.''
</P>
<P>
   That's a typical remark from faculty members, whether Jesuit
brothers or lay teachers, said Don Morgan Jr., class of '91 and at
just 25 years old, the director of alumni relations. His father was
also a Brophy grad, class of '65.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all struggle so much to explain that magic that is
Brophy,'' Morgan said. ``My dad always told me so much about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You almost have to experience it to understand why people call
me once a week who graduated in the '50s. They ask me how the teams
are doing, if Father Renna is still teaching English.''
</P>
<P>
   The teachers and administrators enjoy a special closeness and
friendship with the students, Morgan added, which fosters feelings
of community and the sense of loyalty.
</P>
<P>
   School vice president Adria Renke believes that the Jesuit
system of teaching fosters the sense of purpose associated with
Brophy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Justice, dignity, social conscience _ that's why people come
back,'' Renke said. ``It's not a touchy-feely school. It's a school
of the spirit.''
</P>
<P>
   Al Lyding of Phoenix, class of '62, is one of those who keeps
coming back, most recently to take Father Renna out to lunch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took two classes from Father Renna,'' said Lyding, a
Stanford University graduate and commercial real estate developer.
``He's just sort of a unique person. It's been a worthwhile
relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   Lyding's three sons went through Brophy, two of them graduating
from college and the other still attending.
</P>
<P>
   `'All three were baptized by Father Renna, all had senior
English with Father Renna, and all three got A's in English in
college.''
</P>
<P>
   Students say that Renna's classes are engaging and entertaining,
filled with his intelligence, dry wit and tall tales.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a natural born ham, and I have a captive audience,'' Renna
said. ``I just enjoy them a lot. And they've done a lot for me.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Sense of community
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When the students speak of Brophy, the word ``community'' comes
up often. School spirit, loyalty and closeness with the faculty
help create those feelings, they say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brophy has a real sense of community,'' said Rusty Kennedy, a
junior who's a Phoenix native and a member of the school golf team.
``Everybody looks after you and your well-being. You have the
feeling that the teachers really care.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Edward A. Reese, president of Brophy, said the bond
between teacher and student is critical to Brophy's Jesuit mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``The magic of the place: I think this is characteristic of
Jesuit schools that there's a feeling of belonging,'' Reese said.
``What the kids typically say is that the teachers are friendly
here, the teachers are our friends, the teachers care. That
translates out to love.''
</P>
<P>
   Morgan offers an anecdote telling of the student/faculty bond,
the teaching of values and how discipline is applied on an
individual basis.
</P>
<P>
   It seems that a teacher caught a student red-handed altering a
classroom attendence report, penciling in his buddy as present
instead of absent, Morgan said. But instead of sending the offender
to the dean for punishment, the teacher took him aside and spoke to
him, explaining the problem and the possible consequences.
</P>
<P>
   And that was it. No discipline report, no jug (as detention is
called at Brophy and other Catholic schools). At the end of the
school year, at the final Mass, the student stood up before his
class and told how the teacher's brief talk served as revelation.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said that if he'd been sent to the dean and given jug, it
wouldn't have meant as much, and he'd probably would have done
something like it again,'' Morgan said. ``But because this teacher
took the time to talk to him, it made all the difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Another factor that bonds the teachers and students is Brophy's
mission to involve all in community service. Using the Jesuit
slogan, ``Men for Others,'' as its guiding principle, Brophy tries
to instill the notion that those who are fortunate enough to attend
Brophy should be willing to give back to the community. Juniors are
required to complete 60 hours of community service, but the members
of every class are involved in going out and helping others.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kids who walk out of here walk out with a social
conscience,'' Morgan said. ``Every kid who goes here, these boys
donate 2,000 hours (total) of community service a month. I defy any
school anywhere to match that.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the places where Brophy students perform volunteer work
are the Arizona Recreation Center for the Handicapped; homes for
the elderly such as Chris Ridge Village and the Phoenix Living
Center; St. Vincent de Paul: Phoenix Dining Room; Veterans
Administration Hospital; the Loyola Project tutoring program;
Crisis Nursery; and Habitat for Humanity. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Great Depression troubles
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Though it was founded 70 years ago, Brophy celebrates its 50th
graduating class this year. The school went broke during the
Depression and closed down in 1935. Brophy reopened for a class of
freshmen boys in 1952.
</P>
<P>
   Now adjacent to Brophy is Xavier College Preparatory for girls
and St. Francis Xavier Elementary School, both operated by the
Phoenix Catholic Diocese separately from the Jesuit-run Brophy.
</P>
<P>
   There have been about 7,000 graduates of Brophy, Morgan said,
which seems like a low number until you consider that the
graduating seniors once numbered in the dozens. There are now 1,190
students attending ninth through 12th grades, drawn from 109
elementary schools throughout Arizona. About 60 percent of the
students are Catholic.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, Brophy has more applicants for the freshman year than
it can fill. The entrance requirements are high, and along with
good grades and entrance-test scores, applicants have to write an
essay about why they want to attend Brophy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good problem to have,'' Renke said of about being able
to choose the best students from a sea of applicants. ``But we hate
to turn them away.''
</P>
<P>
   Recently, Brophy's faculty, staff and alumni were embroiled in
conflict and disunity as the new administration of Reese, Renke and
principal Edwin J. Hearn Jr. took over the reins of the school two
years ago from an administration that had been in place for more
than a decade. There was resistance to some academic and policy
changes, some personality conflicts and the resignation of several
faculty members.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan said he believes the situation has been overblown, that
much of the problems revolved around rumors and accusations such as
that the school would go coed or that the dress code would change
radically. Neither happened. In any case, he added, the conflict
seems to be largely resolved, with few staff members harboring bad
feelings. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Traditional values
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Barone, a professor of education at Arizona State
University, was himself taught at a Jesuit prep school in New
Orleans, and said he knows firsthand about the classical education
and traditional values taught behind the walls at Brophy.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you compare their curriculum to the curriculum of most
public schools, there's that emphasis on classical languages, the
traditional disciplines,`` Barone said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It certainly does have a reputation for being an excellent
school. I get this from students that I've had who went there,
basically impressions that I've gathered over the years. It's a
place where they're very serious about education and they execute
it very well.''
</P>
<P>
   Barone also noted the Jesuit emphasis on leadership and values
as something that is held apart from the academic life, but just as
critical, calling it ``an emphasis on certain kinds of values, kind
of a hidden curriculum that emphasizes a different way of looking
at the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Barone shrugs at Brophy's tout of 99 percent of its graduates
going to college, calling it relatively easy to accomplish when you
get to hand-pick the student body. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Seeking a new image
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Though Brophy boasts of its students as among the best
academically, the faculty and staff are working hard to dispel its
image as an elite institution for well-off families.
</P>
<P>
   The tuition is steep, about $5,200 a year, with financial aid
offered to those students in need who show the requisite academic
merit. The school says that no one with the desire and ability to
go to Brophy will be turned away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jesuit schools were established to teach the
lower-middle-class Catholics,'' Renke said, adding that the school
seeks out the best students, then tries to make sure they can
attend Brophy, whether their families can afford it or not.
</P>
<P>
   ``As for the rap that we're just a rich kids' school, that's the
biggest myth,'' Renke said. ``We take that rap all the time, but a
third of our kids typically is on financial aid.''
</P>
<P>
   Morgan said the school is giving out $800,000 in student aid
this academic year, supported by grants and alumni gifts. None of
the scholarships are athletic, all based on academics, he added,
trying to defuse another persistent image.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Morgan noted that Brophy has had plenty of fiscal turmoil of
its own over the years. The 20 years of being closed down was not
by choice but because of money.
</P>
<P>
   ``Originally, we (the school) were not in the black until my
freshman year of Brophy in 1988,'' he said. ``When my dad was here,
they had to sell St. Christopher medals to help pay the power
bills. The perception that Brophy was always a wealthy school was
always a little bit off.''
</P>
<P>
   An ambitious building plan to expand Brophy's facilities and
modernize the classrooms has been drawn up, but the money to
construct it has been slow coming, probably meaning that the
construction, once it's begun, will take many years to complete. &QL; 
 &QL; 
No women, please
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The question often comes up: When will Brophy succumb to a
changed society and finally admit female students? Not likely
anytime soon, comes the answer.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan noted that Brophy and Xavier share some classes, allowing
the male and female students to interact with each other as well as
take classes together.
</P>
<P>
   Renke, whose daughters attended Xavier, said part of the
tradition of Brophy involves the concept of turning young boys into
young men.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the tradition of this particular school,'' the vice
president said.
</P>
<P>
   There have been changes over the years. Father Renna recalls
that when he arrived 34 years ago, the teachers were Jesuits and
the only woman on campus was a secretary.
</P>
<P>
   ``And there was a football coach, Coach Novak, who eventually
had his sons and grandsons go through here,'' the priest said. ``As
time's gone on, we're fewer Jesuits. We have some women teachers
now, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Father Renna represents the continuum of Brophy, the
dedication and teaching skill, the need to bring a sense of values
to the classroom. He's one of the things that haven't changed in a
generation, to the point that a recent postcard sent out to the
school alumni had on it a photograph of Father Renna in his
classroom. On the top of the picture, it says, ``Some things never
change . . .''
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole thing about this place, even the place itself has a
certain something about it,'' Father Renna said. ``It's been a
remarkable experience for me. I know this, I'm at the right place.
This is it. God's been good to me.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Brophy Broncos &QL; 
Brophy College Preparatory, &QL; 
4701 N. Central Ave., Phoenix.  &QL; 
WHAT: A four-year independent college prep high school with an
all-male student body; owned and operated by the Society of Jesus,
known as the Jesuits. &QL; 
FOUNDED: Sept. 10, 1928, on a 25-acre site donated by Ellen A.
Brophy. The school opened with three buildings and 25 students. &QL; 
ENROLLMENT: 1,190 male students. &QL; 
FACULTY: 85 full-time faculty and staff, 65 percent with Masters
Degrees or higher. &QL; 
PRESIDENT: Father Edward A. Reese, S.J. &QL; 
PRINCIPAL: Edwin J. Hearn Jr. &QL; 
CAMPUS: Designed by John Rinker Kibbey and constructed in the
Moorish-influenced, Spanish colonial style of early Spanish
missions in the Southwest. The student chapel is the focal point of
the original campus, with its distinctive tower and arched
walkway. &QL; 
ADMISSION: Draws from 109 feeder schools from throughout Arizona,
77 public, 22 Catholic and 10 private/independent. For the current
freshman class, there were 560 applications for 330 openings, with
criteria for admission based on academic records, recommendations,
test scores and personal interviews. &QL; 
MASCOT: Bronco. &QL; 
COLORS: Red and white. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-25-98 1718EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
