<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-25 17:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9686 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUDIO-HOLIDAYMUSIC-CO     11-25 0755
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-HOLIDAYMUSIC-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    For the holidays: Christmas music
 &HT;    By Steve Dollar, Sonia Murray, Richard L. Eldredge, Shane
Harrison and Russ DeVault
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jingle bells, y'all. The market for holiday-themed music floods
this time each year, as CD shelves swell with mirthful hit-making
by pop stars, both vintage (Bing Crosby) and newly minted ('N
Sync). It can get confusing, so here's a handy guide to some of the
more noteworthy and, occasionally, avoidable yuletide releases:
</P>
<P>
   POP
</P>
<P>
   ``The Complete Decca
</P>
<P>
   Christmas Songbook''
</P>
<P>
   Bing Crosby. MCA.
</P>
<P>
   44 tracks (2 CDs).
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Your grandfather's Christmas album. This double-disc collection
gathers seemingly every tinsel-draped tune ever recorded by Der
Bingle for the Decca label. It's pretty hard to resist, right down
to the cover shot of Crosby smoking a pipe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Christmas Caravan''
</P>
<P>
   Squirrel Nut Zippers.
</P>
<P>
   Mammoth. 10 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   A yuletide offering as nutty and unique as the act's other
recordings. Concentration on hip original compositions such as
``Hot Christmas'' set it a notch above.
</P>
<P>
   ``Merry Christmas . . .
</P>
<P>
   Have a Nice Life!''
</P>
<P>
   Cyndi Lauper. Epic/Sony.
</P>
<P>
   11 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   File this under: Santas just wanna have fun. An original, nicely
executed effort with Lauper reteaming with ``Time After Time''
composers Rob Hyman and Eric Bazilian to create some fun new
holiday-themed tunes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Christmastime''
</P>
<P>
   Michael W. Smith. Reunion.
</P>
<P>
   12 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C-
</P>
<P>
   The saccharine and overblown orchestration on Smith's holiday
offering is one spoonful over the line. Some traditional yuletide
tunes manage to hold up to the onslaught, but a little restraint
would've made this much more joyous.
</P>
<P>
   ``Home for Christmas''
</P>
<P>
   'N Sync. RCA. 14 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   An 'N Sync Christmas is very much like 'N Sync on any other day.
The quintet's vocals on this collection of romance-minded (``In
Love on Christmas'') original songs are tolerable, yet thin. The
only thing you'll get after listening to these yearnings is your
teenage daughter's need to have this under the tree. CLASSICAL
</P>
<P>
   ``A Gala Christmas in Vienna''
</P>
<P>
   Placido Domingo, Sarah Brightman, others. Sony Classical.
</P>
<P>
   20 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   An all-star blowout with the Vienna Symphony mixes-and-matches
operatic figures with Christmas' greatest hits. For anyone who
always wanted to hear Placido Domingo sing ``Santa Claus Is Coming
to Town.``
</P>
<P>
   BLUES
</P>
<P>
   ``12 Songs of Christmas''
</P>
<P>
   Etta James. Private Music.
</P>
<P>
   12 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   Always regal and classy, the only drawback here is James'
decidedly dull musical choices. Does the world really need another
serving of ``The Little Drummer Boy?'' Rum-pum-bummer.
</P>
<P>
   GOSPEL
</P>
<P>
   ``Christmas With Shirley Caesar''
</P>
<P>
   Shirley Caesar. Myrrh. 11 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   Rare is an inspirational album where Shirley Caesar's voice is
simply not enough. This is that exception. Caesar's clipped
phrasings from opener ``Hark! The Herald Angels Sing'' to the more
inspired ``O Christmas Tree'' somehow make even this gospel legend
sound uncomfortable singing his praise.
</P>
<P>
   Rythm and Blues
</P>
<P>
   ``Christmas With Babyface''
</P>
<P>
   Babyface. Epic. 10 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Santa Babyface glides into these traditional covers bearing
unexpected jazz stylings. But the real treat is when he settles
into his usually likable soul on this album's standout, ``I'll Be
Home for Christmas,'' with jazz/gospel a cappella group Take 6.
</P>
<P>
   COUNTRY
</P>
<P>
   ``Breath of Heaven''
</P>
<P>
   Vince Gill. MCA. 11 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   Both religious and secular tunes get a nicely relaxed treatment
from Vince Gill, one of Nashville's premier vocalists and pickers.
He plays it pleasantly on tunes from ``Winter Wonderland'' to ``O
Come All Ye Faithful'' and even avoids turning ``Blue Christmas''
into a downer.
</P>
<P>
   BLUES-ROCK
</P>
<P>
   ``What's in That Bag?''
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Leavell. Capricorn.
</P>
<P>
   13 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   Keyboardist and Macon-area resident Chuck Leavell, just off the
road with the Rolling Stones and set to rejoin them for an arena
tour opening in January, somehow found time to collect personal
favorites and turn them into one of the season's most eclectic
releases. The glue that holds the package together is three parts
Leavell's keyboard artistry and one part his gruffly bluesy vocals.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-25-98 1726EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981125.0249 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-25 17:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9688 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUDIO-HOLIDAY-BOXSETS     11-25 2042
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-HOLIDAY-BOXSETS-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   For the holidays: Boxed Sets
</P>
<P>
   By Steve Dollar, Shane Harrison, Doug Hamilton, Bo Emerson Russ
DeVault, and Kathy Janich
</P>
<P>
   One of the staples of the holiday consumer binge, boxed sets of
CDs devoted to a particular artist or style of music make for
impressive ``oooohs'' and ``ahhhhs'' once the gift-wrapping comes
off. Record companies love them because the collections usually
recycle previously released _ or, at least, previously paid for _
recordings, and can sometimes generate a fresh burst of interest in
their subject. Fans love them because, well, what fan wouldn't want
a snazzily packaged survey of a favorite rock singer or jazz
guitarist, with a small novel's worth of critical notes and
interviews, and the songs remastered with the latest digital
gewgaws?
</P>
<P>
   Here's a glance at a batch of recent boxed set releases, with
tips about what makes each unique (or not):
</P>
<P>
   POP
</P>
<P>
   ``Transistor Blast''
</P>
<P>
   XTC. TVT. 51 tracks. (four CDs).
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   Retail price: $44.99
</P>
<P>
   Bonus factor: Many previously unreleased performances.
</P>
<P>
   A gathering of live recordings from a band that was never fond
of performing live might seem an iffy proposition. Two of these
discs are concert recordings from 1978-79 and a powerful set at
London's Hammersmith Palais in December 1980, when the band's pop
confections still had a punky edge. After calling a halt to
roadwork in 1982, the trio still made live-in-the-studio
appearances on radio, including John Peel's popular BBC show. The
other two discs document those sessions from 1977-89. Entertaining,
if less than essential.
</P>
<P>
   ``Judy''
</P>
<P>
   Judy Garland. 32 Records. 66 tracks. (four CDs).
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   Retail price: $76.97
</P>
<P>
   Bonus factor: Includes a 95-page booklet, a 32-minute video from
her 1960s TV show and duets with the likes of Barbra Streisand and
Count Basie.
</P>
<P>
   If you think Judy Garland is defined by ``The Wizard of Oz,''
think again. This collection takes us over the rainbow and back
again, from her vaudeville beginnings at age 7 to a dramatic London
gig in 1969, months before her death at age 47. Don't miss ``Zing!
Went the Strings of My Heart,'' sung flawlessly by Judy at age 13.
What made Garland great is all here: her versatility (we get jazz,
blues, show tunes and more); her energy; her vulnerability. Judy
Garland didn't hide her emotions, she sang them. Lucky for us she
shared her best and worst of times.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Look of Love''
</P>
<P>
   Burt Bacharach. Rhino.
</P>
<P>
   75 tracks. (three CDs).
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Retail price: $49.98
</P>
<P>
   Bonus factor: Splashy packaging, song-by-song annotation and a
stunning variety of artists, from Dionne Warwick to Elvis Costello.
</P>
<P>
   It would take a remarkably consistent career not to show some
cracks over the course of a 75-song retrospective. While this
exhaustive set makes clear that songwriter and arranger Burt
Bach-arach is a pop visionary, the architect of a sound
unparalleled in its plushness and sophistication, it also reveals
brief but serious lapses into cheesiness. Bacharach's best songs,
including ``Walk on By'' and ``I Say a Little Prayer,'' performed
by his muse, Dionne Warwick, sway with a swinging '60s breeziness
that's sorely lacking in today's radio fodder. His worst, say, ``Me
Japanese Boy I Love You'' by Bobby Goldsboro or Christopher Cross'
``Arthur's Theme,'' could be the piped-in Muzak on the elevator to
hell.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guilty: 30 Years
</P>
<P>
   of Randy Newman''
</P>
<P>
   Randy Newman. Rhino/Warner Archives/Reprise. 105 tracks. (four
CDs).
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Retail price: $59.97
</P>
<P>
   Bonus factor: A disc of demo recordings; booklet with acerbic
asides on various titles.
</P>
<P>
   Subtitle this compilation of Randy Newman's greatest hits and
most sanguine obscurities the sentimental journey of a misanthrope.
One of the most original songwriters to emerge in the 1970s,
Newman's wickedly skewed views on the human condition lent teeth to
music-hall Americana and West Coast soft-rock formula
(``Rednecks,'' ``I Love L.A.''), amply documented here. That gave
way to the soundtrack work (``Ragtime,'' ``Toy Story''), which is
the least interesting aspect of a long-overdue collection.
Completists should be delighted, however, to finally have ``Gone
Dead Train'' _ Newman's contribution to the ``Performance''
soundtrack _ on CD.
</P>
<P>
   ROCK
</P>
<P>
   ``Tracks''
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Springsteen. Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   66 tracks. (four CDs).
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   Retail price: $69.97
</P>
<P>
   Bonus factor: Material previously available only on bootlegs.
</P>
<P>
   An ultimate keepsake for any hard-core fan of Bruce Springsteen,
the expansive ``Tracks'' covers the long arc of the singer's career
_ from his nascent ``street poet'' phase heralded by ``Mary Queen
of Arkansas'' to the mature, Woody Guthrie-influenced populist of
``The Ghost of Tom Joad.'' Compiled by Springsteen and cleanly
remastered, the songs offer a parallel perspective on the Boss'
indefatigable rock classicism and New Jersey grit. Perhaps
predictably, the 1970s outtakes are the most fun, but gems are
scattered throughout.
</P>
<P>
   ``The John Lennon Anthology''
</P>
<P>
   John Lennon. Capitol. 93 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   (four CDs).
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   Retail price: $72.97
</P>
<P>
   Bonus factor: Outtakes offer listener that ``fly on the wall''
sensation.
</P>
<P>
   Anthologized to the nth degree, all things Beatles-related seem
to spring from a bottomless vault. But with this latest box it's
hard to imagine there's much meaningful fodder left in the John
Lennon archives. It's a nice one to have, with extensive
supplementary texts by Yoko Ono and critic Anthony DeCurtis, and
all kinds of amusing and revealing audio verite snippets that range
from studio outbursts to candid home recordings. But there's too
much of only passing interest to anyone not a committed fan. Seek
out the John 'n' Yoko reissues on Rykodisc first, then investigate
this.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nuggets: Original Artyfacts
</P>
<P>
   From the First Psychedelic Era,
</P>
<P>
   1965-1968''
</P>
<P>
   Various artists. Rhino.
</P>
<P>
   118 tracks. (four CDs).
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   Retail price: $59.97
</P>
<P>
   Bonus factor: CD version of an out-of-print LP anthology
quadruples its size.
</P>
<P>
   This new ``Nuggets'' is a marvelous, overgenerous slab of folk
history, an amped-up version of the 1972 Lenny Kaye-produced
garage-sale double album, with more junk and treasure. Documented
here is that '60s flowering of American can-do when home-grown
rockers cranked out pop just as stupid and good as the previously
dominant British Invasion brand. Not every greasy teen started a
garage band in 1965, but after listening to this, it sure seems so.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sho' Nuff''
</P>
<P>
   The Black Crowes. American.
</P>
<P>
   56 tracks (five CDs).
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Retail price: $49.97
</P>
<P>
   Bonus factor: Extra tracks on band's four albums; fifth CD is
five live cuts.
</P>
<P>
   If you've got the four studio albums by the Atlanta-born Black
Crowes, it's difficult to justify the purchase of the cleverly
packaged box unless you're a completist or want to give a friend
the gift of the band's gutsy blues-rock. There are two bonus tracks
on each of the four albums, but what's really new is the five live
cuts from 1995 concerts in New York's Beacon Theatre.
</P>
<P>
   COUNTRY
</P>
<P>
   ``The Complete Country &AMP; Western Recordings: 1959-1986''
</P>
<P>
   Ray Charles. Rhino.
</P>
<P>
   92 tracks. (four CDs).
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   Retail price: $49.97
</P>
<P>
   Bonus factor: Classy booklet boasts extensive notes, interviews
and photos.
</P>
<P>
   What pop pleasures trump the sheer soulful splendor of Ray
Charles singing ``Busted,'' with a sassy horn section swinging
behind him, or pledging ``I Can't Stop Loving You'' with the
uncanny timing in his phrasing underscored by a diaphanous chorus?
None. Not a flipping one. As this box testifies, yet again,
Charles' 1962 album ``Modern Sounds in Country &AMP; Western Music''
was revolutionary. That and subsequent C&AMP;W-themed volumes are
featured here. Surprisingly, the 1980s duets (with Merle Haggard,
George Jones, Willie Nelson and others) outlast some inherent
corniness to sound better with age.
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Dollar
</P>
<P>
   -- Soundline number: 430
</P>
<P>
   JAZZ
</P>
<P>
   ``The Complete Blue Note Sessions''
</P>
<P>
   Herbie Hancock. Blue Note.
</P>
<P>
   54 tracks. (six CDs).
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   Retail price: $102.97
</P>
<P>
   Bonus factor: Some unreleased alternate takes; good historical
booklet.
</P>
<P>
   Before he became the visionary funkateer of the '70s
(``Chameleon'') and '80s (``Rockit''), Herbie Hancock was nearly
the most gifted jazz pianist of his generation. Like saxophonist
Wayne Shorter, his colleague in Miles Davis' great 1960s quintet,
Hancock was brilliant at an early age. His series of Blue Note
albums (collected here, with some alternate tracks and
contributions to others' albums) offer complex, sophisticated and
bracingly hip perspectives and a little future shock: Tunes such as
``Watermelon Man'' and ``Cantaloupe Island'' suggest that Hancock
always had a killer pop instinct lurking behind a serious guise.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Complete Bitches Brew Sessions''
</P>
<P>
   Miles Davis. Columbia/Sony Legacy.
</P>
<P>
   21 tracks. (four CDs).
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   Retail price: $69.97
</P>
<P>
   Bonus factor: Two discs full of unreleased tracks; detailed
booklet.
</P>
<P>
   When Miles Davis recorded ``Bitches Brew'' at the end of the
1960s, he drew a line in the sand. After he embraced the electric
textures, group improvisations and studio editing techniques the
album flaunted, he never looked back. Purists howled, but the
trumpeter was mapping previously uncharted terrain, a frontier that
is now a populous province. The birth of ``jazz-rock'' can now be
heard as a forecast of ambient sound-craft and the seething,
propulsive exploration of a million disc jockeys. Part of an
immaculate campaign of Davis reissues, the box is generous with
bonus tracks that are less essential than you'd hope.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Classic Quartet: Complete Impulse! Studio Recordings''
</P>
<P>
   John Coltrane. Impulse!
</P>
<P>
   63 tracks. (eight CDs).
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   Retail price: $89.97
</P>
<P>
   Bonus factor: A ``works in progress'' disc of outtakes that
offers a peek at
</P>
<P>
   Coltrane's creative process.
</P>
<P>
   After his death, in 1967, at age 40, the tenor and soprano
saxophonist became a secular saint: a touchstone for legitimacy and
stature sought by ecstatic outsiders and swinging neo-boppers
alike. This monolithic box shows why: Coltrane led one of the
single greatest bands of all time. With pianist McCoy Tyner,
drummer Elvin Jones and bassist Jimmy Garrison, the so-called
``classic'' quartet made music of delicacy, drive and divine
passion. These studio sessions, which span 1961-65, offer
everything from ballads to ballistics and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   ``Empire''
</P>
<P>
   Tim Berne. Screwgun.
</P>
<P>
   20 tracks. (five CDs).
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Retail price: $55
</P>
<P>
   (post-paid from 104 St. Marks Ave., Brooklyn, NY 11217)
</P>
<P>
   Bonus factor: Funky low-budget package includes a tasty recipe
for vegetable stew.
</P>
<P>
   Wynton Marsalis wasn't the only wunderkind trying to redefine
jazz in the early 1980s, nor was his the only meaningful path. By
1981, saxophonist Tim Berne had already released five albums on his
own Empire label, bridging the so-called ``loft jazz'' scene that
fostered a fugitive avant-garde of the 1970s and the so-called
``downtown'' music scene that would arise in the '80s. Four of
these expansive, open-structured sessions are reissued for the
first time on CD, part of a rich chapter in the secret history of
pop culture during the Reagan era _ and groovy testimony to the
virtues of artistic pluck.
</P>
<P>
   CLASSICAL
</P>
<P>
   ``25 Years''
</P>
<P>
   Kronos Quartet. Nonesuch. 106 tracks. (10 CDs).
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   Retail price: $99.97
</P>
<P>
   Bonus factor: A wealth of previously unreleased pieces; nifty
booklet.
</P>
<P>
   Hipper than your average chamber group, the Kronos Quartet has
aggressively promoted the music of living composers while reveling
in a bit of rock-star flash. The quartet is notorious for covering
Jimi Hendrix's ``Purple Haze,'' but it's also introduced the work
of Philip Glass, Terry Riley, John Adams and a number of Asian,
African and Eastern European composers to a wider audience. The
outfit's anniversary box is a stylish recap, eclectic,
investigative and fun.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
