<SLUG> BC-HESAID-SHESAID-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SHE SAID: Let us give thanks for a feast cooked by somebody else
 &HT;    By Maureen Downey
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In Bo's family, conversation served as the centerpiece
of the Thanksgiving table. In my Irish-Italian family gatherings,
the conversation never went much beyond ``pass the turnips'' or
``more gravy, please.''
</P>
<P>
   Our Thanksgiving menu today amounts to a midnight snack in
comparison to my New Jersey clan's button-popping smorgasbord.
There are more of them, so the collective effort is far more
sumptuous.
</P>
<P>
   But it's less the numbers than lack of time that's the real
hurdle to stuffing the turkey and the guests in my household. I
wish the Pilgrims had held off until March to express their
gratitude.
</P>
<P>
   Thanksgiving coincides with the end of recreation league soccer,
the beginning of basketball and the onslaught of holiday choirs,
Scout service projects and Christmas plays. The choice is whether
to costume a pageant shepherd or dress the big bird.
</P>
<P>
   With school reports suddenly due, I'm scouring the Internet with
my fifth-grader for images of American alligators instead of baking
pies. The potatoes go unpeeled as my 7-year-old
geometrician-in-training and I identify triangles, hexagons and
octagons in the neighborhood skyline.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, we solved the problem by buying a ready-made
Thanksgiving dinner from a caterer. Granted, a roast turkey that
came out of a cardboard box instead of a hot oven didn't taste or
smell the same.
</P>
<P>
   It was much, much better.
</P>
<P>
   HE SAID: Eat whatever you want: Traditions all start somewhere
</P>
<P>
   By Bo Emerson
</P>
<P>
   c. 1998 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Because of time and distance and our busy modern
lives, my extended family can't assemble and enjoy our traditional
Thanksiving celebration, which revolves around eating, drinking and
arguing.
</P>
<P>
   We've tried fighting with each other long-distance, using
conference calls and Internet chat rooms, but it's just not the
same.
</P>
<P>
   Since Maureen won't argue with me during off hours, I've had to
improvise. Now my siblings and I, spread across Georgia,
Connecticut, North Carolina and South Carolina, pursue our own
holidays. It's not the same as the good old days, but not bad.
</P>
<P>
   Laurie will be cooking, Lucy crafting, Ellen sculpting, and
brother John, a man after my own heart, celebrating in a more
meaningful way:
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to kill a bird by hand,'' says John, the South
Carolinian. ``It used to be a turkey, when they were more plentiful
in the Columbia area, but due to urban sprawl I have to use
whatever I can get my hands on: a pigeon, a robin, a titmouse,
whatever.''
</P>
<P>
   John is joking a little bit, because, like me, he finds
Thanksgiving and bad football and Pilgrims depressing. ``All I can
think of is those guys freezing to death.''
</P>
<P>
   So John has unhitched Thanksgiving from its dubious historical
moorings and made it into a ``nonsectarian blowout.''
</P>
<P>
   Maureen and I have done much the same. Our meal, for example,
doesn't conform to the traditional pattern, since each child gets
to pick one dish. This year's feast will include egg rolls and
Jell-O pudding.
</P>
<P>
   Traditions never suffer from a little rewriting.
</P>
<P>
   Write married staffers Maureen Downey and Bo Emerson at Cox News
Service P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302. E-mail them at
mdowney(at)ajc.com or bemerson(at)ajc.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
