<DOCNO> NYT19981125.0251 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-25 17:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9691 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CNBC-ATTITUDE-COX     11-25 1919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNBC-ATTITUDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Maybe it sounds like ESPN, but CNBC's buzz is all biz
 &HT;    By Drew Jubera
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Few things are less telegenic in a made-for-TV world than the
opening each business day of the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   It is deadly, deadly stuff. At exactly 9:30 a.m., Monday through
Friday, the head of the exchange and a few guest suits ring a bell
from a platform above the trading floor. Often they toss in
something goofy, to recognize a newcomer, or as part of, like, a
theme. You'd have to be there. It's the Wall Street equivalent of a
ceremonial first pitch, an act so unmemorable not even C-SPAN
trains a camera on it.
</P>
<P>
   But CNBC does. Each morning the gimlet-eyed cable network that's
shattering TV's business news conventions with its eccentric blend
of financial insight and workaday loopiness counts down to the
opening bell, shows it being rung, then analyzes it with the wry
skewering the tradition invites.
</P>
<P>
   ``A bunch of basketball coaches are trying to kill traders on
the floor with orange objects,'' anchor Mark Haines deadpanned one
morning as four coaches joined the NYSE chief in tossing out toy
basketballs to celebrate the start of the college basketball season
in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people should wear those hats, and some people
shouldn't,'' Haines observed another morning as the opening-bell
guys donned black British bowlers to welcome a London-based company
to the exchange. The bowlers sat jauntily on some heads and settled
far below the ears of others, who looked like they'd just come to
the exchange from a drunk tank.
</P>
<P>
   CNBC might be the clearest signal yet that the Information Age
has entered its Era of Attitude. It is hard to imagine a drier
prospect for a TV network than programming 14 1/2 hours a day with
the likes of business mergers, quarterly earnings reports and the
gyrations of the Dow. But CNBC _ all business by day and all talk
by night _ has infused the button-down, proper-attire-required look
of traditional business coverage with the irreverent spirit of
``Dilbert.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as ESPN's ``SportsCenter'' captures the wisenheimer esprit
of sports fans, so has CNBC's business coverage adopted the prickly
irony that percolates beneath many of those dark suits on Wall
Street. Amid its business boilerplate, CNBC has the unscripted,
behind-the-scenes feel of a TV show about a TV show, like ABC's
``Sports Night.''
</P>
<P>
   Cameras catch guys at their desks while they're still on the
phone, or putting viewers on hold while they peck at a computer for
a name they can't remember. Coats come off and sleeves roll up. We
hear what sounds like the between-cubicle banter that goes on in
any high-rise shop (anchor to reporters on a split screen,
following a story about a wine conglomerate: ``Why don't you and
Bauman drop over later. I have some Night Train and Thunderbird,
and I have a very good date on that.'' Reporter: ``Good date?''
Anchor: ``Yeah. Thursday.''). A retired pro football player once
e-mailed Haines to say he watched CNBC's business coverage because
it reminded him of the locker room during his playing days.
</P>
<P>
   That's just what CNBC has in mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to watch `SportsCenter' (on ESPN) and say, `Man, if
there was any way to do that with a business format, you'd have a
real blockbuster,''' says Matt Quayle, producer of ``Squawk Box,''
a kind of daily stock market pre-game show from 8 to 10 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``So when I was putting the show together, that's what I was
thinking about. While business news is very serious and there's a
lot of money at stake, there are times you have to play by the
rules and other times when you can have fun.''
</P>
<P>
   CNBC reporters are called by nicknames such as ``the Kahuna,''
``the Brain'' and ``the Bond Babe.'' Sound effects and props
sometimes appear when certain companies are mentioned: Cheesy disco
is cued when music compilation giant K-Tel makes news; a can of
Spam appears when Hormel's name pops up.
</P>
<P>
   Noon's ``Power Lunch'' might feature whatever stock watcher Joe
Kernen (the Kahuna) is eating at his desk; the other day it was
split pea soup. He spooned it up while lamenting how reporter David
Faber (the Brain), seated at a desk across from him, wasn't named
this year's sexiest man by People magazine. Kernen theorized it was
a Time-Warner conspiracy, since Time-Warner owned People and CNN, a
CNBC rival. It was like he forgot he was on TV.
</P>
<P>
   When someone later mentioned actor Marky Mark, Kernen ruminated
he'd like to be Dirk Digler, the porn star role Mark played in
``Boogie Nights.'' On the day that wine story broke, anchor Liz
Claman, called by a co-anchor ``the news yenta,'' noted that she
loved wine _ as long as it came in a box. ```Just a Box of Wine,'
'' Kernen mused of an old Grateful Dead tune. ``Love that song.''
</P>
<P>
   Executive producer Kevin Magee explains the ad-libbed punchiness
that often infects his talent: ``It's because we're on so damn
long. For 14 1/2 hours, you can't fake anything. Every quirk of
personality comes out _ good, bad or indifferent.'' ``Business news
is just too dry,'' adds Kernen, 42, a coatless, self-mocking former
stockbroker who's one of CNBC's most popular personalities. ``If
you can do it and amuse yourself, you're probably going to amuse
others.''
</P>
<P>
   This mix of iron and irony works. The network's business day
ratings in October averaged 290,000 households, up 34 percent over
last year. And like the Weather Channel during hurricane season,
the numbers explode when the market turns extreme. On Aug. 31, more
than one million homes watched CNBC after a battered stock market
closed _ the most in the network's nine-year history. The previous
high was in October 1997, when the Dow nose dived 554 points. CNBC
had its highest business-day average ever the next day _ when the
market roared back.
</P>
<P>
   Who watches? Pros and market junkies and retirees, for sure, who
get a kick eyeballing a stock ticker crawling continuously across
the screen, or who tune in to glean something insiderish from
CNBC's impressive parade of CEO and analyst interviews.
</P>
<P>
   But there's also a wider audience out there than there used to
be _ an audience that includes people like . . . you. More women,
more Gen X'ers, more regular Joes and Jills looking to make a
better buck from their mutual funds than their parents did with
passbook savings. They want to be both educated and entertained.
With almost half the country now in the stock market, either as an
active investor or with a retirement fund, CNBC recognizes, as
Georgia State University economic guru Donald Ratajczak says of
televised business coverage, ``they better add a little life to it
or it gets deadly dull in a very short period of time.''
</P>
<P>
   But rather than force color on corporate America's charcoal gray
image, Ratajczak says CNBC actually reflects it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Go into the trading floors of large financial centers and
there's always somebody joking around. There's that humorous vein
in that type of audience, and these guys capture it pretty well.
They don't take things very seriously. They're always saying things
like, `Wow, look at that deal. Why in the world are they doing
that?'
</P>
<P>
   ``(Louis) Rukeyser (host of PBS's long-running ``Wall Street
Week'') has his own sayings and uses plays on words _ that isn't
what you get on the trading room floor. And (CNN's) `Money Line'
with Lou Dobbs is a little bit too straight. They're trying to
loosen it up, but that effort's more in their promotions than on
the show. On CNBC, they take their coats off, just like what you
see in the trading rooms.''
</P>
<P>
   How much does Ratajczak watch?
</P>
<P>
   ``More than I need to.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the wackiness,'' agrees Sheryl Spiva, 38, a Cobb
County-based regional manager for Charles Schwab investments. ``It
puts an interesting spin on what I look at from a very sterile
approach every day. I come home from work and pull out my little
stepper and say, `OK, what's going to entertain me while I'm going
through this boring stuff.' And I end up on CNBC.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know clients respond to what they hear there,'' Spiva adds.
``It demystifies (the market) so it's not so intimidating.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They kid around, which is good,'' says M.J. Nathanson, a
retired salesman and business owner who spends most days watching
CNBC and checking his investments on the lobby computer at the
Cumberland-area Schwab office.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just can't listen to this stuff day in and day out, hour
after hour, without it. The use of humor when people are making or
losing millions lets you know they're reporting what's really going
on.''
</P>
<P>
   While ESPN's ``SportsCenter'' has become TV's gold standard for
the info-soaked Era of Attitude, it doesn't always travel well.
Sports shows on both CNN and Fox blatantly imitate ESPN's yuk-it-up
air, and come off loud and silly by comparison.
</P>
<P>
   CNBC is virtually by itself in adopting this tone with business
news. The closest over-the-air equivalent is public radio's
``Marketplace,'' a breezy half hour each weeknight that alternates
between nuts-and-bolts reporting and offbeat features.
``Marketplace'' came to the same conclusion as CNBC.
</P>
<P>
   ``The democratization of the stock market means you have to
reach out to more people,'' says senior editor and host David
Brancaccio. ``There was something about the old way of reporting
business news that said this is people's retirement money you're
talking about, it's not to be taken lightly. I just reject that. If
I'm not having a good time doing this, people are going to tune me
out and listen to rock music.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're cool. I admire them,'' Brancaccio adds of CNBC and its
place in today's ticker-driven culture. ``The question is whether
10 years from now when kids in high school are going to a
1990s-theme dance, will they go dressed as CNBC anchors and
brokers?''
</P>
<P>
   CNBC succeeds where others fall flat because what you see is
pretty much what it is. Most of the dozen or so on-air people have
known each other for years; three of them went to college together.
They project a been-there, seen-that savvy that steps just this
side of cynicism; an in-this-together attitude that makes hedge
funds and bond yields accessible to pros and newcomers, men and
women, Gen X'ers and Gray Panthers.
</P>
<P>
   Plus they're funny, even though they don't look funny, which
makes them that much funnier.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very loose, very comfortable with each other. It's a
cliche, but we're kind of like a family,'' says anchor Sue Herera,
on-air since CNBC's 1989 debut. ``It creates an almost intimate
relationship with the viewer.''
</P>
<P>
   They all have their groupies. Herera says she gets wedding
anniversary and birthday cards from viewers; after a recent speech
in Milwaukee, a longtime fan exclaimed during dinner to the
currently-blond Herera, ``I knew you when you were a brunette!''
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Thank you for that,''' Herera recalls.
</P>
<P>
   Haines says the kind of office-mate connection CNBC establishes
with viewers is either there or it isn't. A show can be tweaked
with graphics and production values, but this sort of on-air byplay
can't be contrived without looking . . . contrived. In a
phoney-baloney medium like TV, nothing plays like the real thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The chemistry that's developed between the people here just
evolved,'' says Haines. ``Management isn't smart enough to think
this stuff up _ which is true of almost all successes that happen
on TV.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
