<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-25 17:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9694 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-49ERS-HNS &LR;      11-25 0694
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-49ERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
49ERS PLAN TO TAKE THURSDAY OFF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN CRUMPACKER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA CLARA, Calif. _ A couple months ago, when the weather was
mild and so was the opposition, Steve Mariucci was recognized in
this space for his humanitarian approach to coaching in the NFL. He
gave his players extra time off to rest and heal up from the hurt
inherent in playing the game.
</P>
<P>
   The players loved it, of course, and responded by playing well
in the early going. What a great guy this Mariucci is, they said.
Swell fellow. Don't change a thing.
</P>
<P>
   Then the 49ers hit a wall along with the arrival of autumn. In
the last four games they are 2-2, a month of play characterized by
spotty performances on both sides of the ball. It's no accident
that during that time the Atlanta Falcons beat them and moved into
the lead in the NFC West.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes word that Mariucci, Gandhi in an Italian suit, will
give his players Thanksgiving off. For what? Certainly not for
stalwart play. This is a team that needs work, not more down time
on the old La-Z-Boy.
</P>
<P>
   Just listen to one of the principals: ``We need to play
better,'' Steve Young said. ``We're playing decent football, but
we've got to play better. ... We have set a tremendous standard. We
have set the bar up high and demand that we meet it. We're very
vigilant. We work hard to keep that bar high.''
</P>
<P>
   Then they should continue to work to keep that bar high instead
of spending time in one.
</P>
<P>
   Mariucci's rationale is that this is a ``long'' week, in that
the 49ers don't play again until Monday night against the New York
Giants. Getting in normal practice days on Friday and Saturday for
a Monday night game is the same as working on Thursday and Friday
in preparation for a Sunday game, he said.
</P>
<P>
   If you're Mike Shanahan in Denver, you give the Broncos
Thanksgiving off. If you're Denny Green in Minnesota, you give the
Vikings Thanksgiving off. If you're Ray Rhodes in Philadelphia, you
give the Eagles Thanksgiving off and every day thereafter and start
over again in July.
</P>
<P>
   If you're Steve Mariucci in Santa Clara, you keep drilling the
49ers, even on a day devoted to the overconsumption of turkey, that
noble bird. Have the boys come in for 90 minutes of crisp work in
the late morning, then send them off to their families and friends
to enjoy the rest of the day in some overheated room bloated on
turkey and stuffing and the glut of items curiously referred to as
``all the trimmings.'' (Where I come from, trimmings is what you
get when you mow the lawn.)
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Rice made news this week for speaking out about his team's
inconsistent offense and his desire to be more involved in it, like
he was in the loss to Atlanta, when 19 passes were aimed in his
direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe my standards are too high,'' Rice said. ``I'm not just
looking forward to going to the playoffs. I want to win the whole
thing. Right now the team has been up and down and I don't think we
have the team (to do it). We've got to get the job done, and it's
not happening right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Funny, but that sounds like someone who thinks his team should
be working to get better instead of taking another day off, even if
it is Thanksgiving. There's nothing like a little physical activity
to sharpen the old appetite.
</P>
<P>
   When George Seifert was the coach in these parts, paranoia
overcame humanity and the 49ers practiced on Thanksgiving, even in
the 14-2 years. The players got their work in from 10-11:30 in the
morning then departed for the holiday. Nobody complained, although
fullback Tom Rathman used to holler at reporters for wasting time
watching practice on Thanksgiving when they should be at home with
their families.
</P>
<P>
   (Note to Tom: Ever hear of holiday pay? Double-time-and-a-half,
baby!) It's too late, though. The schedule has already been posted
in the locker room. There's an icon of a turkey on Thursday with
the note ``players off.''
</P>
<P>
   That's too bad. The 49ers need the work. At 8-3, they will be a
playoff team but their stay in the postseason may be like jumping
in an icy lake: in and out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
