<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-$ADV29-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT TO DO ABOUT YELLOW POURED FLOOR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, November 29, 1998; normally moves Friday)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOTTON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I have poured floors. In the bathroom the poured floor has
yellowed. How can I get rid of that yellow stain? Can I put ceramic
tiles or even resilient (vinyl) tiles on that floor?
</P>
<P>
   IRGINIA TURNER, Kingston, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Poured floors were popular 20 to 30 years ago, and eventually
went out of favor. The floor was made by combining tiny colored
flakes, with clear vinyl that was poured in place.
</P>
<P>
   To answer your questions: no way, yes and yes. It is unlikely
that you can reduce that yellow stain. White or light-colored vinyl
may develop yellow stains, which I think are chemical, not
physical. Floor people have no solutions, to my knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, you can put vinyl tiles over the floor; use peel-and-stick
tiles. You can also install ceramic tiles with a thin-set mortar or
adhesive.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My son is finishing his basement, installing a plasterboard
wall, but he also wants to have it plastered. A plasterer said he'd
seal the plasterboard and then skimcoat. Another said this won't
work. What can my son do now?
</P>
<P>
   ALLEN KRAUSE, Northborough, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I'd go along with the man who said a skimcoat will not work
over sealed plasterboard. It might work, but it is too iffy, in my
opinion. A skimcoat is designed to go over Blueboard, a special
plasterboard with a rough, sandpapery surface, which the skimcoat
clings like crazy.
</P>
<P>
   I suggest your son have the plasterboard seams taped and covered
with joint compound (also covering the nail or screw heads). If he
really wants a skimcoat, he can put Blueboard over the plasterboard
or take off the plasterboard and put Blueboard on.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Miguel Mitchell of Rockport, Mass.to tell us of a grave error
the handyman made in suggesting ways to clear a drain of mortar
that was spilled into the drain. This question was asked by G.A. of
Windham, N.H.
</P>
<P>
   The handyman suggested using muriatic acid, which would attack
the mortar without harming the drain. He also said that nonenzyeme
Drano might also work.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Mitchell, visiting scientist and chemistry lecturer at
Northeastern University, wrote that the handyman described
``nonenzyme Drano'' as an acid. ``Actually, the active ingredient
in Drano is sodium hydroxide, a very powerful base,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone decided to combine Drano with muriatic acid to
clean pipes, they would be in grave danger. Strong acids and bases
react violently. In combination with muriatic acid, Drano would
erupt into a spray of superheated, corrosive steam. Let your
readers know that Drano is not an acid and should never be combined
with muriatic acid.''
</P>
<P>
   Excellent point, Dr. Mitchell, and appreciated by the handyman.
At least the handyman did not suggest combining the two materials.
In fact, one should never combine two chemicals designed to do the
same thing.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I had a rubber roof put on a flat garage roof; it is OK after
four years except for a gouge about 2 inches wide and 4 inches
long, as if made by an animal trying to get in. Where can I get a
patch to cover this roof? The installer went out of business. And
how best can I glue on a patch? I have used a special glue in
repairing wet suits, but I just don't know where to find a patch.
</P>
<P>
   ARTHUR ROSENBERG, West Newton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. As a temporary fix, cut a piece of roll roofing and secure it
with phenolic vinyl (PhenoSeal, a widely available adhesive caulk).
Even an old inner tube would do. You can try any lumber store or
possibly a roofer willing to cut you off a piece. A roofer is
unlikely to do a small job.
</P>
<P>
   Short of that, does anyone know where rubber roof material in
small amounts can be bought? The handyman would like to know. So
would Arthur Rosenberg.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have a see-through fireplace that converted from a
one-hearth unit, so there is a hearth facing one room and another
facing another room. It smokes like crazy. Would a flue booster
work? We put in glass doors so that only one side is open, without
success. A contractor suggested sealing the floor and the
foundation.
</P>
<P>
   PHYLLIS LEVINE, Boxford, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. A flue-booster, a fan at the top of the chimney, more
accurately called a draft booster, might work, but you still need
more air for the fire to burn well without smoking. For starters,
open a window in the room to provide more air. If that works, fine,
except you will freeze your tush off; so, provide the fireplace
with its own air; install a PVC duct from outdoors to in front of
the fireplce.
</P>
<P>
   See-through fireplaces, even one built from scratch, do not work
very well. Conversions are worse. Sealing the floor and the
foundation will make things worse, because the fire is trying to
pull air from house and basement.
</P>
<P>
   Your best bet is to provide the fireplace with its own air, and
if necessary, put in a draft booster. And, brick up one of those
openings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader
questions. Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107. The
Handyman chats on line Thursdays, 1-2 p.m, at
http://www.boston.com, keyword: Chat.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
