<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-25 17:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9732 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUTO-REVIEW-$ADV29-BO     11-25 1204
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-REVIEW-$ADV29-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WINDSTAR'S A CLASSY VAN, BUT IT'S A CROWDED CLASS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)  
 (For release Sunday, November 29, 1998; normally moves Friday)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN R.WHITE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You can't lead by playing catch-up. Nowhere is that more evident
than in the auto business _ especially in the Van Wars. At
Chrysler, they figured that out a long time ago. At Toyota and
Honda, they just figured it out. At Ford, as innovative as that
company can be, they're still a little slow off the mark.
</P>
<P>
   The '99 Windstar might have been the van leader, if the other
guys had stood still. But the other guys didn't, which puts Ford
about even with Chrysler overall, a tad behind Honda, perhaps,
thanks to that company's innovative interior design _ more than a
tad if Honda Odyssey manages to equal Windstar's five-star safety
rating.
</P>
<P>
   What's really funny about it all, is that Ford had the jump on
everybody way back when _ that's funny as in ``odd.'' At Ford, it's
probably not a laughing matter.
</P>
<P>
   Back in the mid-'70s, Ford's Hal Sperlich had a vision _ a
front-drive minivan. Henry Ford II didn't share the vision; Hank
the Deuce wanted no part of front-drive minivans or front-drive
anything else just then. Sperlich insisted; Ford resisted. Sperlich
lost the argument and his job at Ford, found gainful employment
with a foundering Chrysler Corp., where he also found the
front-drive K-car in the works, a perfect platform for his vision.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhat later, Lee Iacocca, too, after a split with Henry II,
left Ford to take over the sinking Chrysler ship and engineer its
rescue and recovery _ but the minivan wasn't Iacocca's baby, and
neither was the K-car, even though he promoted both of them as only
the master pitchman could. It is one of those sad facts of history
that the quiet work of the inventive genius often fades from memory
while the lingering echoes of the pitchman are etched in the public
consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   Chrysler's desperation and Sperlich's vision gave birth to a new
kind of vehicle and a whole new market _ and Chrysler owned it. It
took two decades for a serious challenge to Chrysler minivan
dominance to manifest itself, and the struggle for van sales is
giving the consumer a splendid array of choices. The leadership is
not clear _ the top manufacturers all offer roomy vans with
innovative seating, lots of cupholders, two sliding doors, and
reliable engines. On top are Chrysler, Ford, Honda, and Toyota, not
necessarily in that order, and right there is the somewhat smaller
Mercury/Nissan joint venture. Far back is everybody else.
</P>
<P>
   Honda's Odyssey would seem to be the current leader, based on
innovative interior design _ a disappearing seat, flat load space,
and a spare tire conveniently inside under the floor, plus the
almost mandatory twin sliding doors. But Ford Windstar has a
five-star crash rating, Toyota Sienna offers the cachet of Toyota's
impeccable reputation for reliability, and, of course, Chrysler has
all that experience and seats that roll on wheels _ and the biggest
chunk of the market. General Motors offers redesigned versions of
its ``Dustbuster'' collection in Pontiac, Chevy, and Oldsmobile
flavors, and General Motors has a reputation for ... a long history
of blunders.
</P>
<P>
   Your columnist has been happily tooling about in a 1999 Ford
Windstar SEL, a $30,415 vehicle with lots of doors, a 3.8-liter V-6
engine, plenty of standard features, and a few extra trinkets that
boost the tab to $32,850 _ plus, of course, the $580 delivery tab.
If you can make do with one door less and a 3.0-liter V-6, you can
buy the Windstar and its five-star crash rating for $18,375 plus
delivery, still very well equipped with such as 4-wheel antilock
brakes, AM/FM stereo, power steering, 4-speed automatic
transmission, tachometer, two power outlets up front, and lots of
other bits _ but no AC at the base price. In between are three
other levels of refinement.
</P>
<P>
   The SEL is a virtual palace on wheels with leather, CD player,
extra interior lighting, an extra power outlet in the rear of the
vehicle (very convenient for campers and outdoor lovers, probably
the least likely group to buy a van this fancy), message center
with trip computer and compass, automatic headlights, etc. In
addition, the tested model had the trailer package (no serious
trailers need apply, but small boats and campers are fine), the
backup warning system, and the optional side air bags _ front bags
are standard, of course.
</P>
<P>
   The backup warning system sounds an intermittent beep when there
is an object behind you and you are in reverse gear. The closer you
get, the faster the beeping. Close to within eight inches, and the
beep becomes a steady tone. I loved it for the up-close warning,
but the thing was sensitive enough that it picked up things on the
sidewalk across the street as I backed out of the driveway _ one
doesn't need a warning at that long a range.
</P>
<P>
   On the road, it is very nice to drive, but its 150-horsepower
V-6 tends to creep a bit; speed control on the interstate is
advised _ provided you can manage to stay awake. Acceleration is
good, the ride softish, the road manners and handling quite good _
not quite as crisp as the Honda Odyssey, not afflicted with the
annoying understeer of the Olds Silhouette sampled a while back.
</P>
<P>
   Controls score well for convenience _ nice AC/heater controls
(front and rear), fair radio controls (although too many of them,
and a bit too closely packed), convenient placement of window and
door-lock switches. The power side doors operate either by pulling
on the handle to start a door in motion or by electric switches
over the windshield _ which has a lockout function to disable the
other controls _ buttons in the B-pillars, exposed when the doors
are open, will serve as an alternative closing mechanism.
</P>
<P>
   The glove box is small, but there's lots of storage in this
model, bins, a drawer, a cargo net. It's the overhead storage array
that got me. At the brow of the windshield is the first
compartment, hiding a fold-down wide-angle mirror for unobtrusively
checking the rear passengers _ it doesn't interfere with the
rear-view mirror. Then comes a flip-down coin holder, a flip-down
eyeglass compartment, and last, a flip down something-or-other with
a Velcro lining. The array ends with an overhead map light.
</P>
<P>
   Windstar SEL is elegant, versatile, quiet, comfortable, and this
sample delivered 22.2 miles per gallon _ not bad for a living room
on wheels. It's safe to say that Ford has pretty well caught up _
but leap frog, not catch-up, is the winning strategy.
</P>
<P>
   How to choose a van? Well, there isn't a whole lot separating
the top contenders from one another. Start by selecting the
features you absolutely must have, then the things you'd really
like to have, then make the important choice: a dealer or dealers.
It's among dealers where the significant differences are to be
found.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader
questions. Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107. The
Handyman chats on line Thursdays, 1-2 p.m, at
http://www.boston.com, keyword: Chat.)
</P>
</TEXT>
