<HEADLINE>
_SKIERS MUST BEWARE LIGHTNING IN WINTER  
 _WOMEN'S ARRYTHMIA RISK SAID TO BE GREATER  
 _STUDY CALLS FOR EARLIER DIABETES SCREENINGS  
 _SMOKING FOUND TO FAIL AS A WEIGHT-LOSS AID  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DOLORES KONG  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
 
 Skiers must beware lightning in winter
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lightning isn't just a summertime worry for golfers, boaters,
and hikers. It can also be a winter hazard for skiers.
</P>
<P>
   A new study documents two examples from the Colorado slopes.
</P>
<P>
   In Vail, one skier, a 38-year-old man, was struck by lightning
just after getting off the ski lift, and died. In Breckenridge, a
ski patrol member was struck while on the way to a rescue. He
briefly lost consciousness and the lightning burned the corneas of
his eyes, but he survived.
</P>
<P>
   While a winter lightning storm is rarer than a summertime one,
it can be more dangerous, according to the study's authors, led by
Michael Cherington, a Denver lightning specialist.
</P>
<P>
   In winter, a lightning storm's warning signs can be less obvious
and its electrical charge more powerful, said the study in the
British Journal of Sports Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Winter lightning usually occurs during the falling of snow
pellets _ a mixture of ice crystals made up of supercooled cloud
droplets and bigger ice particles, and typically smaller and
spongier than hail, according to the authors.
</P>
<P>
   The study and an accompanying commentary recommend that when
such conditions exist, skiers, and snowboarders should take
appropriate shelter _ that is, not under a tree.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Women's arrythmia risk said to be greater
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Women are at higher risk of experiencing a rare but potentially
fatal heart rhythm disturbance after taking a widely prescribed
antibiotic used to treat everything from urinary tract infections
to acne, according to a new study.
</P>
<P>
   Out of 346 reports of cardiac arrhythmias associated with
erythromycin between 1970 and 1996, 58 percent of them occurred in
women and 32 percent in men. Gender was not specified in the the
remaining 10 percent of reports made to the Food and Drug
Administration, said the study in the current issue of the Journal
of the American Medical Association.
</P>
<P>
   Differences in the number of prescriptions written for women and
for men did not account for the gender difference in the arrhythmia
reports, write the researchers from Georgetown University Medical
Center.
</P>
<P>
   Neither did the researchers think differences in reporting drug
side effects to the FDA explain the higher number of cases
involving women. Reports to the FDA are made voluntarily and thus
could underestimate the number of women experiencing arrhythmia
after taking erythromycin, the study said.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers said their findings confirm a gender difference
in drug-induced arrhythmia that has already been found in studies
of another class of drugs, a type of heart medication. They
theorize that female sex hormones may play a role in susceptibility
to the arrhythmia.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Study calls for earlier diabetes screenings
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Blindness and other complications from a common form of diabetes
can be reduced by as much as 35 percent if people are screened for
the disease starting at age 25, rather than at the currently
recommended age of 45, according to a new US study.
</P>
<P>
   The benefits can be even greater for people at highest risk of
diabetes, including blacks and those who are severely overweight,
write the researchers from the US Centers for Disease Control and
Prevention, in the current issue of the Journal of the American
Medical Associaiton.
</P>
<P>
   Using a complex computer model, the researchers calculated the
costs of an early, one-time screen during a routine doctor's visit,
and the benefits of quicker detection of so-called Type 2 diabetes.
However, the model did not factor in the costs of repeated
screening or patients' inability to comply with treatment. Type 2
diabetes, once known as adult-onset diabetes, is usually treated
with changes in diet and pills.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers acknowledge that private insurance companies may
not have the financial incentive to cover an earlier diabetes test,
which can cost from $28 to $106, depending on the test. That's why
they recommend that government insurers, like Medicare and
Medicaid, consider adopting the earlier screening.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Smoking found to fail as a weight-loss aid
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The notion of smoking to lose weight does not appear to be true,
finds a new study of 4,000 young adults, aged 18 to 30.
</P>
<P>
   Those who smoked or began smoking during the seven years of the
study did not shed pounds. And while black smokers appeared less
likely to gain weight with age, whites who smoked appeared just as
likely as non-smokers to get heavier as they got older.
</P>
<P>
   But the study in the Journal of Consulting and Clinical
Psychology did find that people who quit gained more weight than
those who kept smoking or never smoked at all, with an extra 9 to
15 pounds attributable to quitting.
</P>
</TEXT>
