<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSINESS-MAGAZINES26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wall Street represents big divide over opposing views
 &HT;    By Staff reports
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The long 1990s bull market has: (A) Been a boon to
Main Street thanks to the ``wealth effect''; or (B) ``Encouraged
the tricksters'' and ``will leave many individuals wrecked upon the
shoals of greed and improvidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Those drastically different perspectives come from the December
editions of Smart Money and Harper's Magazine.
</P>
<P>
   In Smart Money, Pulitzer Prize-winning journalist James B.
Stewart credits the bull market with rescuing financially troubled
Quincy, Ill., a ``microcosm of the U.S.'' that he said has changed
more in the past 10 years than in the previous 50.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest and most prosperous city in Illinois in the 19th
century, with its Mississippi River commerce, Quincy's downtown by
1990 ``looked like Beirut,'' the mayor told Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   But the opportunities and money generated by the 1990s bull
market boosted individual and family businesses. Now, even the
downtown ``is looking up.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Although certain of the town's economic problems remain
unresolved, there is agreement that the decade has rescued Quincy
from what seemed like a slow slide into oblivion.'' Stewart writes.
</P>
<P>
   If that's true, it's in spite of Wall Street, contributing
editor Ted C. Fishman writes in Harper's.
</P>
<P>
   Most people probably assume financial markets play by the rules
of supply, demand and the Securities and Exchange Commission, and
that ultimately, ``fortune favors the lucky and the smart and the
diligent,'' writes Fishman. ``The idea, simply, is wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Although stock exchanges and brokerages are famously bullish
on American free-market capitalism, (for an individual) to
participate in the markets is necessarily to play by the house
rules _ unfair, inefficient and closed,'' he concludes.
</P>
<P>
   Betting on Greenspan
</P>
<P>
   The surprise cut in interest rates Oct. 15 should not have come
as a shock to anyone who is familiar with Alan Greenspan's past,
Money (December) says of the Federal Reserve chairman. ``Greenspan
is predictable, and that's good,'' it contends.
</P>
<P>
   Back on track
</P>
<P>
   Once the dominant force in business _ and politics _ railroads
have lost market share for 50 years or more. But they are on a roll
again, Individual Investor (December) reports. And the best play
for individual investors may be the companies that supply them.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine recommends Johnstown America Industries, which
makes freight cars, among other items; Varlen, which makes
precision-engineered transportation products; and Westinghouse Air
Brake, which makes a wide range of products _ including air brakes.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
