<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Delta gets new marketing VP
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Delta Air Lines has named Martin C. White vice
president-consumer marketing, a position in which he will oversee
advertising as well as high-profile products such as the SkyMiles
program.
</P>
<P>
   White, 34, was recruited from rival US Airways, where he was
vice president- marketing programs and services. He previously
worked at Continental, as well as for a marketing firm that worked
for United.
</P>
<P>
   At Delta, he replaces Gayle Bock, who abruptly left Delta last
spring after leading the airline's first advertising agency switch
in 50 years. White reports to Fred Reid, the airline's newly
installed executive vice president-marketing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Martin has developed successful marketing and customer service
strategies and programs for airline alliances, new branded
products, corporate identity and brand imagery, frequent flier
programs and other critical marketing activities, all of which are
very relevant to work under way at Delta,'' Reid said.
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA
</P>
<P>
   _ BellSouth: The telecommunications company said Francis A.
Dramis Jr. has been named executive vice president and chief
information officer. In the position, a new one for BellSouth,
Dramis will be responsible for all information technologies across
the corporation. He will report to Chairman and Chief Executive
Officer Duane Ackerman.
</P>
<P>
   Dramis, 50, has worked with AT&AMP;T, including Bell Labs, and is
former president and chief operating officer of Telic Corp. He has
also served as chairman and CEO of Network Management Inc. in
Fairfax, Va. He will join BellSouth from CIO Strategy Inc., a
Clifton, Va.-based information technology consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
