<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-25 18:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9747 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SANTA26-COX     11-25 0931
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SANTA26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Santa's continuing education
 &HT;    By Patti Bond
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In these complicated times, it takes more than a real
beard and big belly to be a professional Santa Claus.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, cheerfulness and patience and all the warm and fuzzy St.
Nick virtues count _ but the stuff that separates the Big Guys from
the elves is an intrinsic mix of wisdom and common sense. The
visions that dance in little heads can turn Santa's mall throne
into a therapist's chair of sorts.
</P>
<P>
   The wish list can get tricky, ranging from moderately delicate
(``All I want is a big dog'') to sobering (``Can you bring Daddy
back for Christmas?''). And there's always a mom or two who tells
Santa to make the kid buckle down on homework.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every year, the questions are becoming more difficult, and the
social issues are getting tougher, too,'' said Jim O'Connor,
president of Atlanta-based O'Connor Promotions Inc., a company that
places Santas in 16 shopping centers around the Southeast,
including about half of the malls in metro Atlanta. ``A big part of
our job is to learn how to react to the children's questions.''
</P>
<P>
   Social quandaries aside, there's no room for technophobes at
Santa's North Pole distribution center, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ten years ago, the kids were talking about Barbie; now they
want to know about CD-ROMs,'' O'Connor said. ``Kids seem so much
smarter than when I started the business 14 years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Even wise old Santa needs a refresher course on his social
skills, so every year just before the holiday season, O'Connor
rallies his troop of Santas in what seems like a combination boot
camp-pep rally-support group. This year, the Santas met at Planet
Hollywood in downtown Atlanta on the second Sunday in November.
</P>
<P>
   It's somewhat unnerving at first to watch a room full of
costumed Santas roll up their red velvet sleeves and tackle the
issues of damage control. This particular group will see 250,000
children this season. With the interests of eager children, parents
and mall management in mind, O'Connor pounds home the mantra for
Santa throughout the five-hour class.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone gets treated the same, whether it's 10 a.m. or 10
p.m.,'' he says. The list of dos and don'ts is routine for the most
part. Santa always smiles, he always listens, but he never promises
anything, especially when it comes to pets.
</P>
<P>
   And here's a sobering reality check: Santa must always keep his
white-gloved hands in sight.
</P>
<P>
   With those thoughts in mind, this bunch seems to concentrate on
the never-ending duties of their timeless celebrity status.
Although Santa's beard needs a quick salon touch-up just before the
season, the pros stay in character all year long.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no off days for us. You've got to be Santa 24 hours
a day, seven days a week,'' says Tom Chapman, a retiree who works
as an usher for the Atlanta Braves. Chapman's year-round whiskers
look so realistic that even in the middle of the summer stadium
patrons sometimes even ask for a picture with ``Santa.''
</P>
<P>
   There are plenty more stories of encounters at supermarkets,
banks and on the street, but when talking about some of Santa's
more serious interactions on the job, the mood turns from jolly to
woeful.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the stories will break your heart,'' said Johnny
Hammond, who works a daytime shift at Southlake Mall in Morrow.
Hammond's blue-gray eyes well up when he talks about a visit with a
9-year-old girl and her 3-year-old brother who was struggling with
a tracheotomy. ``She was talking for him and telling me what they
wanted. But when her mother was paying for the photo, she ran back
to me and said, `What I really want is for my brother to live
another year.'''
</P>
<P>
   Interaction with parents is demanding, too. After all, Santa is
not only representing the season, he's also representing the
shopping center. ``Santa is a goodwill ambassador for the mall,''
said Sue Adamo-Carpenter, marketing director for Cumberland Mall.
And keeping the parents happy is a big part of the job, marketers
say.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I interview Santas, I'm looking for how they handle the
parents as well as the children, because they've been in line for
an hour, too,'' said Lisa Shepherd, marketing director for North
Point Mall in Alpharetta.
</P>
<P>
   Marketers are becoming more diligent in their choices of Santa,
with good reason. Last year brought a variety of stories about
Santas gone bad. In one of the most shocking examples, a man
playing Santa at a metro Seattle mall was arrested for rape and
child molestation. In New Jersey, a Santa was busted for
shoplifting, and in Brooklyn, a boy recognized a mall Santa as his
deadbeat dad. The mother and estranged husband consequently had a
tussle near Santa's throne in full view of a line of youngsters.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Santa can cause quite a stir, even when he's just taking
a bathroom break. ``Never leave the set by yourself,'' O'Connor
tells his class. ``Always take a helper with you 'cause you'll get
mobbed.'' By the end of the day, it's clear that Santa has to keep
his cool.
</P>
<P>
   It could be argued no one's more suited for the job than North
Point's Tom Sisk, a child and adolescent psychologist in the
off-season. ``There aren't too many surprises with my background,''
says Sisk, who's starting his first year as a mall Santa. ``My job
as Santa has a lot of the same specifics.''
</P>
<P>
   The first week has been fairly standard, he says. ``So far, just
a lot of requests for Barbies, bicycles and Teletubbies.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
