<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-25 18:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9748 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHOPPING-BUDGET26-COX     11-25 0640
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOPPING-BUDGET26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Don't head to the mall budget-free
 &HT;    By Vikki Ramsey Conwell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Before you head out for the sales tomorrow, here's a
warning from Consumer Credit Counseling Service: Unless you've
already set up a holiday spending budget and prepared a shopping
list, don't go. Stay home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Heading to the malls without a concrete plan is a recipe for a
holiday hangover,'' said Suzanne Boas, president of CCCS of Greater
Atlanta. ``It's a dangerous time to be operating without a budget
because it's an easy way to let your heart rule your head. You'll
wake up in January to quite a rude awakening when the bills come.''
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, the day after Thanksgiving marks the beginning of
the holiday shopping season. Americans hit the stores in a mad rush
for early-bird specials and discounts.
</P>
<P>
   ``This type of frenzied environment can lead people to get
carried away and spend more than they can afford,'' said Boas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all dream of the perfect holiday, complete with a pile of
gifts, but the desire to fulfill this fantasy can cause us to
forget the reality of our personal financial limits.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the National Retail Federation, consumers expect to
spend an average of $814 on holiday gifts this year, up 4.5 percent
from last year. But people generally underestimate their holiday
spending, consumer experts say, and the strong economy may coax
some into spending more than they'd planned. Also, surveys
indicate, fewer than half of Americans set up a holiday spending
budget, and many purchases are put on credit cards.
</P>
<P>
   That could mean trouble for those who are already overextended.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many people buy without thinking,'' said Andy Jacob, president
of World Wide Financial, a consumer lending company which
specializes in people with credit problems. ``They know they are
spending more money than they should, but they are into immediate
gratification. They want what they want today, and they put
themselves in a position not to be able to pay off the debt during
the year.''
</P>
<P>
   According to a recent CCCS survey, 70 percent of respondents
reported holiday spending put them deeper in debt, and 30 percent
are still paying off bills from last Christmas. Of those who admit
to overspending, 53 percent said they ``got carried away,'' 39
percent cited last-minute purchases and gifts costing more than
expected, and 33 percent claimed poor planning.
</P>
<P>
   Shoppers also need to resist the urge to throw in ``goodies''
for themselves when shopping for others, experts cautioned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Make sure you can afford it,'' Jacob said. ``It will save you
a lot of pain down the road.''
</P>
<P>
   HOW TO AVOID OVERSPENDING
</P>
<P>
   _ Write down your total debt at the top of your shopping list,
as a reminder of how much money you already owe.
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't shop in a rush. When you're pressed for time, you're
more likley to overspend.
</P>
<P>
   _ Visit the mall at less crowded times. Shop early in the week
and early in the day.
</P>
<P>
   _ Think twice before you buy. Ask yourself if the gift is
appropriate for the recipient and in your price range.
</P>
<P>
   _ Use cash when possible. Doing so forces you to stick to your
pre-set spending limits.
</P>
<P>
   _ If you're going to use credit cards, create a plan to pay off
purchases within 90 days of the holidays.
</P>
<P>
   _ Try to use the credit card with the lowest interest rate.
</P>
<P>
   _ Track your spending. As you buy, cross out the names on your
list and record the amount spent.
</P>
<P>
   _ Put off some shopping. If there are people you won't see until
after the holidays, trade gifts with them then so you can take
advantage of post-holiday sales.
</P>
<P>
   _ When you're done shopping, stop! Extra trips to the mall will
lead you to spend more money.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
