<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-25 18:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9751 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SYNOVUS26-COX     11-25 0248
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SYNOVUS26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Synovus to purchase Canterbury Trust
 &HT;    By Rob Chambers
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Synovus Financial of Columbus, Ga., has agreed to
acquire Birmingham, Ala.-based Canterbury Trust, which manages $1
billion in assets. Terms of the stock transaction were not
disclosed. The deal is expected to close in the first quarter,
subject to regulatory and shareholder approval.
</P>
<P>
   The Birmingham company's clients tend to be large institutions.
Half of its business is foundation management, said Synovus
Financial spokesman Pat Reynolds. The rest is focused on employee
benefits, personal trusts and custodial services.
</P>
<P>
   The company will become a division of Synovus Trust Co. of
Alabama. Canterbury Trust was founded in early 1992. Synovus
Financial became a 20 percent owner when it bought First Commercial
Bancshares of Birmingham, which had held the stake, later that
year.
</P>
<P>
   The planned purchase of the remaining shares ``broadens our
existing Synovus Trust product offerings, which is part of Synovus'
overall plan to expand its product lines,'' Reynolds said.
</P>
<P>
   Synovus Financial, with $10 billion in assets, is the
second-largest banking company based in Georgia. It owns 35 banks
in Georgia, Alabama, Florida, and South Carolina. Synovus Financial
also owns 80.7 percent of Total System Services, a large card
processor also located in Columbus.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-25-98 1802EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981125.0274 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-25 18:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9752 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WORLD-TRAVEL26-COX     11-25 0945
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLD-TRAVEL26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WorldTravel beginning to go places
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The usual travel agency trappings _ posters of Waikiki
Beach, cruise line brochures, maybe a model airliner on a stand _
are conspicuously absent at the offices of WorldTravel Partners.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta-based WorldTravel hasn't become one of the nation's
biggest travel companies by relying on storefront franchises that
entice passersby with vacation scenes.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, it concentrates on the behind-the-scenes, high-volume
world of corporate travel management and, increasingly, Internet
bookings.
</P>
<P>
   It also concentrates on growth.
</P>
<P>
   Last month WorldTravel vaulted from No. 8 to No. 3 in the
industry through a merger with BTI Americas, a larger company based
in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   The name of the combined company remained WorldTravel, and the
home office stayed in Atlanta, in the tony Lenox Park office
complex. Annual air booking volume more than tripled to $3.3
billion, and employment jumped to 5,000 from 1,800.
</P>
<P>
   The deal capped a swift climb to the top rungs of the industry
by WorldTravel, which only a decade ago was a regional agency with
$50 million in annual air bookings.
</P>
<P>
   Now, only American Express Travel Services, an arm of the New
York financial giant, and Carlson Wagonlit, a venerable travel firm
based in Minneapolis, are bigger.
</P>
<P>
   Privately held WorldTravel has a sister company, Dallas-based
Travel Technologies Group, that develops travel software. Another
sister firm, Online Fulfillment Services, processes Internet
bookings at a center in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of our in-house technology base and entrepreneurial
style, we're a fast-moving company,'' Chief Executive Jack
Alexander said. ``Life at the millennium demands that. People want
service now.''
</P>
<P>
   The WorldTravel-BTI Americas linkup reflects a wave of
consolidation among travel management companies, which are joining
forces to build purchasing leverage and bigger client bases.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone compiling a list of the nation's Top 10 travel
management firms these days would be wise to use a pencil rather
than ink,'' Travel Agent magazine noted in a cover story on the
WorldTravel-BTI merger, which it called a ``mega-match.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We think there are going to be a handful of brands in this
industry, and ours will be one of them,'' said Danny Hood, a
WorldTravel veteran who is co-president of the merged company along
with former BTI Chief Ralph Manaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``There may still be thousands of travel agencies,'' Hood added,
``but only a few companies that will offer the global services to
handle a $100 million corporate account.''
</P>
<P>
   About 80 percent of WorldTravel's business involves corporate
travel accounts. Clients include Turner Broadcasting, Arthur
Andersen, Motorola and Dow Chemical.
</P>
<P>
   WorldTravel operates in-house travel agencies for large clients,
and it has reservation centers around the country to take calls
from smaller business customers. The company negotiates fee-based
contracts for its services, shielding it somewhat from airline
commission cuts that are making life difficult for small travel
agencies.
</P>
<P>
   One area Alexander and Hood say is primed for growth is
corporate meetings management, which they view as a natural adjunct
to the core business.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a tremendous opportunity to help companies understand,
organize and operate meetings,'' Alexander said.
</P>
<P>
   WorldTravel also is making its mark on the Internet. Online
bookings still account for only a small fraction of all travel
bookings, but growth is steep.
</P>
<P>
   Online Fulfillment, the WorldTravel sister unit, processes
bookings made through Microsoft's Expedia Travel site, among
others. Once an online booking is completed, the company handles
the back-office work and sends out tickets or itineraries.
Customers who need more service deal with its agents. Revenue per
transaction is lower than in traditional bookings, but so are
costs, because much of the work is automated.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander likens the work to credit-card processing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see ourselves as a Total Systems or First Data,'' he said,
referring to two firms big in credit-card processing. ``It's a
volume game, and those with big volume can do well.''
</P>
<P>
   WorldTravel is owned mostly by Dutch real estate investor John
A. Fentener van Vlissingen. Alexander, an accountant by training,
was working for van Vlissengen and helped engineer a 1987 buyout of
WorldTravel Advisors.
</P>
<P>
   The company bought 30 smaller agencies, picking up more business
accounts, and in 1992 put them all under the WorldTravel Partners
brand.
</P>
<P>
   By the beginning of this year, the company had grown to about $1
billion in annual bookings. But Alexander and Hood felt a merger
was needed, and BTI Americas _ the product of a previous merger _
was on the market. Its geographical strength in the Midwest
complemented WorldTravel's presence in the South and East.
</P>
<P>
   BTI Americas brought with it $2.3 billion in annual air
bookings, along with 53 franchises with an additional $600 million
in bookings. It also brought the American partnership in Business
Travel International, a global marketing alliance.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are three types of agencies: mega, super-regional and
local,'' Hood said. ``We were kind of stuck at the super-regional
level. The biggest thing the merger gave us was the size and scope
of being No. 3. That means a lot of purchasing leverage. Size
matters with suppliers.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexander said he expects some growth in the Atlanta
headquarters employment as a result of the BTI Americas deal.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
