<SLUG> BC-GRACE-FAMILIES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR MILLIONS, THANKSGIVING A TIME TO SAY GRACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIEGO RIBADENEIRA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ As millions of people gather before bountiful feasts
Thursday, blessing the meal is a cherished and longtime tradition
for many families. Thanksgiving and grace do seem to go together,
even for the unchurched.
</P>
<P>
   Though the holiday seems at times to have been reduced to
gorging and football, many families say they try to retain a sense
of why the holiday was created when the Pilgrims sat down to the
first Thanksgiving meal 377 years ago _ gratitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``Grace forces us to take a moment and hopefully think seriously
of what we have been given,'' said Patrick E. Knight, 76, who will
lead the prayer for about 10 family members who will gather at his
home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes things get so hectic we lose sight of what
Thanksgiving is all about.''
</P>
<P>
   Some, like the Sides family, have unique ways of doing that. For
years William Sides would read the story of the first Thanksgiving
and then carefully set five kernels of corn on each person's plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a way to remind us that we were lucky that we never had
to worry where our next meal was coming from and that a lot of
people weren't so lucky and maybe we should try and think of what
we could do for them,'' said Bill Sides Jr. ``Sometimes he would
get upset if one of the children was fidgeting or someone wasn't
paying enough attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Sides is not sure what's going to happen this year when the
extended family comes together at Sides' brother's house in Acton.
His father died in February.
</P>
<P>
   But Sides does not want his dad's tradition to die. ``We won't
decide what to do until we get to my brother's,'' he said. Bill and
Michelle Young try to inject a little humor into the Thanksgiving
grace with the help of a bag of M&AMP;M's. They insert the candies
inside napkins at the table.
</P>
<P>
   ``However many M&AMP;M's you get, that's how many things you have to
say you are thankful for,'' said Michelle Young, who will spend
Thursday first at her in-law's house and then at her sister's home.
</P>
<P>
   Young, however, faces a bit of a dilemma when she goes to her
sister's. Saying grace, she said, ``is a little bit difficult
because in my family a lot of them don't believe in that. So to
break the ice, I'll typically look at my mom and dad and say,
`You're all a bunch of heathens.' And then they'll look at me and
my husband and say, `OK, you say the prayer.' And then I will and
it'll be OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Some families, like the Riveras of Worcester, say grace only on
special occasions like Thanksgiving.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  ``We all have such crazy schedules with work, school, sports
that we rarely eat together as a family,'' said Carlos
Rivera. &UR;  &LR; ``But Thanksgiving is when we put all that stress aside
and my brother comes up from New York, my sister comes out from
Boston and all the kids are together.
</P>
<P>
   ``So we go around the table and each person says what happened
in the past year they are thankful for,'' he said. ``It's just nice
to have the time to stop and reflect on that. That's sort of what
grace is for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Other families, like the Coates of Northborough, Mass., say
grace before every meal. But on Thanksgiving, she said, the family
tries to find at least one ``special way in which God has provided
or done something in our lives.''
</P>
<P>
   She and her husband, Mike, will celebrate Thanksgiving at home,
and Coates said she will thank God for helping see her family
through after her husband was laid off.
</P>
<P>
   Eden Grace, a Quaker, has a different grace practice. Because
Quakers typically worship in silence unless they feel moved by God
to speak, her blessing is usually just a silent moment before
eating.
</P>
<P>
   But her mother is a musician and not a Quaker so the family
custom is for Eden Grace to sing grace in the form of a canon in
Latin.
</P>
<P>
   Alison and Kenneth Stephenson have had the same Thanksgiving
grace tradition for seven years. They sing a grace song written by
Alison's brother-in-law, a former high school music teacher and
percussionist with the Miami Symphony Orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's wonderful because each year he adds a new verse for any
new baby or anyone else who's joined our crew,'' said Alison
Stephenson who will be hosting about 15 guests in her home.
</P>
<P>
   Imani Smith's grace tradition may have to change this year. Her
grandfather, who always sits at the head of the table, has said
grace for years, but he may not this year because his daughter _
Smith's mother _ died of a heart attack in February.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mom was the one who always influenced us to make sure we
got together on Thanksgiving as a family,'' said Smith. ``And now
she's gone and it's going to be hard on my grandfather. I would
like to do the grace as a tribute to him and to her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'll tell God that the table looks different this year
because we're missing someone who was so important to us,'' she
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
