<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZOLAK REVVED UP FOR HIS BIG CHANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Scott Zolak is going to ask if he can borrow
Drew Bledsoe's Porsche this week. After all, starting quarterbacks
drive Porsches.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, if Zolak does replace the injured Bledsoe Sunday and
beats the Buffalo Bills, he might be able to afford his own.
</P>
<P>
   The decision on who plays quarterback for the Patriots probably
won't be made until Bledsoe takes the practice field Friday. But it
may not be made until game time. And there's always the possibility
that Bledsoe starts, is unable to play effectively, and Zolak comes
off the bench.
</P>
<P>
   If Zolak plays well in Bledsoe's place, he may set himself up
for a nice contract _ if not here, then somewhere else _ when he
becomes an unrestricted free agent at the end of the season. Zolak,
who hasn't started a regular-season game since Oct. 1, 1995,
wouldn't have much competition in the market, because it'll be a
lean year for free agent quarterbacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not thinking about that yet,'' said Zolak Wednesday. ``I
still don't know if I'll play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Depending on how I play, there might be a difference in what
I'm driving. I'm not thinking about that, though. It's a crucial
situation and we're 6-5 and fighting to make the playoffs. It's a
crucial game and I don't want to let these guys down. If I don't
prepare as the guy, I'd just be cheating myself and the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Pete Carroll said he will have three active quarterbacks
on the roster Sunday and he also re-signed Northeastern's Jim
Murphy to the practice squad Wednesday so Murphy could work on the
scout teams and play Doug Flutie's part in practice.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe, who fractured the index finger on his right hand in two
places while directing the game-winning drive against the Dolphins
Monday night, said Wednesday, ``It's a little sore, a little
swollen. I really won't know what the scenario is until Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll wait and try to throw. If I can hit what I'm aiming at,
I'll play. If I can't hit what I'm aiming at, I won't play. It's
pretty simple.''
</P>
<P>
   Simple, but complex.
</P>
<P>
   If Bledsoe can't play, Zolak has to step in cold and try to get
down the timing with receivers he normally doesn't throw to as the
second-string quarterback. He'll be put into the Patriots' new
spread-out formation, which seemed perfectly suited for Bledsoe.
</P>
<P>
   Zolak is much more mobile than Bledsoe, so should we expect him
to run more?
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going with the same offense,'' said Zolak. ``I can throw
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll said: ``We will adjust some. Zo hasn't played football
in a long time. We have a feeling that Zo has an understanding of
the things we need to get done.''
</P>
<P>
   Zolak had lots of support from his teammates Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't think of anyone else I'd rather have step in there
than Scott,'' said middle linebacker Ted Johnson. ``He's a fiery
guy and I know he can lead us. We'll throw our full support to
Scott and help him any way we can. But I think the team feels good
with Scott.''
</P>
<P>
   Zolak said he's in every game mentally. He has been to every
practice for eight years. But he knows the situation. He may be
asked to replace a man who threw for 423 yards and pulled out one
of the gutsiest games of the season on ``Monday Night Football.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to go out there and play loose, like I always do, and
be myself,'' said Zolak.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe, too, has rarely missed a practice, but Wednesday he
walked around the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time I've had to deal with a broken
finger,'' said Bledsoe. ``I've always been fortunate because QBs
tend to bang their hands against helmets and pads, but in this case
(defensive tackle Shane Burton) happened to have his hand where I
was releasing the ball and I stuck my finger in his palm, and there
you have it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe came to the sidelines, wondering whether he could go
back out and help the team. His finger was numb. He was throwing
the football with four fingers.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what made the decision so difficult,'' he said. ``It
wasn't a situation where it hurts and you stay in the game. I just
didn't know if I could throw the ball accurately to help us. I felt
I needed to go to the sidelines, but it was a dilemma.''
</P>
<P>
   If on Sunday his finger felt the way it did at the end of the
Miami game, could he play?
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' he said. ``I don't think so.
</P>
<P>
   ``If on Friday it's close, then we'll wait until game time.
We'll evaluate it Friday and then again at game time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was fortunate and the team was fortunate that some of those
(passes in the Miami game) weren't intercepted. If I can't throw
with precision, then Scott will come in and play.''
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe will experiment with different splints; he had a mold
taken of his finger Monday. One tough aspect will be taking snaps.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I don't play, it's not over,'' said Bledsoe. ``Scott is a
very good quarterback and Scott will come in and give us a good
effort and he'll win the game for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Zolak has the same confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eight years in the league and I've been through the mill
watching this kid (Bledsoe) play and working with him,'' said
Zolak. ``I go through it mentally in practice. That's what I get
paid to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``You definitely want to play, but I know my role the last six
years. We have a good relationship. There are a lot of starters and
backups who don't get along. He's the man here. He's the franchise
guy here. I just have to go out and do what I get paid for.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a strange juxtaposition Wednesday. Zolak strapped on his
helmet. Bledsoe was on the stationary bike. At one point Bledsoe
was about to start work on his running when Carroll called him over
to watch the first-team warmups.
</P>
<P>
   All the while, Bledsoe kept his hand, with the finger wrapped
and in a splint, tucked in the pocket of his warmup sweater.
Earlier in the day, when Steve Grogan presented him with the Miller
Lite NFL Player of the Week award, Bledsoe shook Grogan's hand with
his left hand.
</P>
<P>
   Everything indicates that Bledsoe will likely miss a game for
the first time since October 1995. And that the season on the brink
will rest on the 6-foot-5-inch, 230-pound frame of Scott Zolak.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
