<SLUG> BC-PATRIOTS-STADIUM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONNECTICUT LEADERS AGREE TO USE SURPLUS TO BUILD STADIUM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TINA CASSIDY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Governor John Rowland and Connecticut legislative leaders
Wednesday agreed in principle to use some of their state's budget
surplus to help fund the New England Patriots stadium, proposed for
downtown Hartford.
</P>
<P>
   Officials also scheduled debate on the plan for Dec. 15, when
the General Assembly would be called back for a special session to
vote on the memorandum of understanding that Patriots owner Robert
Kraft signed with Rowland last week to move the National Football
League franchise from Foxborough, Mass. in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The publicly-funded stadium project, including infrastructure
improvements, would cost $350 million. Connecticut's budget surplus
for fiscal 1999, which ends June 30, is currently estimated at $171
million, a spokesman for Rowland said.
</P>
<P>
   While the state ended last year with a $610 million surplus,
budget experts said the fiscal year could end with at least a $300
million surplus, in which case $50 million could be set aside for
the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The state would issue bonds for the rest of the project, Rowland
said Wednesday, after a meeting with House and Senate leaders.
</P>
<P>
   So far, lawmakers have not earmarked the surplus for other uses,
such as a rebate to taxpayers. Wednesday, they agreed in principle
to set aside any amount necessary to supplement the state's
expected $250 million bond issue for the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``That should alleviate some of the concerns of the members of
the Legislature who are concerned about borrowing,'' said Dean
Pagani, a spokesman for Rowland. Borrowing ``was a little bit of an
issue in the last governor's race, but not an overwhelming issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in Boston, state representatives and Governor Paul
Cellucci said they were surprised by statements that House Majority
Leader William Nagle made in Wednesday's Boston Globe, saying there
is a ``willingness to at least talk'' with Kraft.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish they said that last summer. We might have been able to
work it out,'' Cellucci said of the Legislature's failure to
resolve differences in House and Senate proposals, separated by $13
million. ``If, in fact, the House is willing to do that, it's good
news. But, depending on what Connecticut does now, it might be too
late.''
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci said he did not know what to make of Nagle's comments
and sounded resigned to the idea that the Patriots will leave if
Connecticut lawmakers approve the lucrative plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a convention center we will start building next year
that, in terms of the economic impact ... will dwarf the economic
impact of the Patriots,'' Cellucci said.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Jo Ann Sprague, a Republican, said she was one of
the many House members who made their concern about the team
leaving known to Massachusetts Speaker Thomas M. Finneran, Nagle's
boss.
</P>
<P>
   ``Apparently he has spoken to the speaker,'' Sprague said. ``I
was very pleased. It looks like there's some room for coming back
to the table again if all things don't go well in Hartford. I know
the members and our constituents have let the speaker know that
we're concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   But Nagle's offer to renegotiate with Kraft did not seem to
rattle confident Connecticut lawmakers. They're sticking to their
original mid-December date to reconvene for a vote on the deal,
under which Kraft agrees to build a hotel next to a proposed
convention center and move the team, corporate offices, and
training facilities there.
</P>
<P>
   ``The view from here is the state of Connecticut has a deal to
negotiate exclusively with the Patriots till the end of the year,
and, if things don't work here, all bets are off,'' Pagani said.
``And clearly the Legislature in Massachusetts is going to do
whatever it feels is in the best interest of Massachusetts. But the
same thing is happening down here.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Pagani said that Nagle's statements did not put any
pressure on the Hartford deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anybody's looking at it as a race,'' Pagani
said. ``We feel we're in a good position to close the deal. All
that's left is a vote in the Legislature.''
</P>
<P>
   Reached at home Wednesday, Nagle said it was too early to
discuss alternative stadium proposals, which he hinted at in the
earlier interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always moveable pieces in those things,'' Nagle said.
``But it's too early to say. ... The public perception is the door
is shut and locked and nailed shut. That isn't the case.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
