<SLUG> BC-PINOCHET-LEGAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PINOCHET CASE TO SPUR OTHER INQUIRIES, OBSERVERS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLUM LYNCH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Life will never be the same for the world's
aging dictators whether or not General Augusto Pinochet stands
trial in Spain for genocide.
</P>
<P>
   Human rights advocates and legal scholars said the decision
Wednesday by Britain's highest legal authority to deny immunity to
the former Chilean ruler will encourage governments and courts
around the globe to take a new look at old political crimes.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling also signaled a growing willingness among national
courts to embrace the notion, long enshrined in international law,
that perpetrators of genocide or crimes against humanity can be
prosecuted anywhere in the world.
</P>
<P>
   France, Germany, Italy, Belgium, and Switzerland, among others,
have begun to seek Pinochet's extradition for murdering citizens of
their countries during Chile's ``dirty war.'' The phrase refers to
more than 3,000 political opponents whom Pinochet is charged with
murdering between 1973 and 1990, when he left office.
</P>
<P>
   Also, lawyers in the US Department of Justice have begun to
consider the extradition of Pinochet in connection with the 1977
assassination of exiled Chilean socialist Orlando Letelier and his
American associate, Ronny Moffit.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has clearly broken the ice,'' said Kenneth Roth,
executive director of Human Rights Watch. ``This decision will give
future tyrants pause before they embark on a path of mass murder.''
</P>
<P>
   The divided ruling by Britain's five Law Lords within the House
of Lords rejected arguments that a British law shielding foreign
heads of state from prosecution applies to former leaders for
crimes against humanity. Britain's Home Secretary, Jack Straw, is
expected to decide on Dec. 2 whether to extradite the 83-year-old
former Chilean strongman.
</P>
<P>
   ``The British court essentially ruled that torture is not part
of the job description,'' said Robert O. Weiner, an expert on
international law at the Lawyers Committee for Human Rights.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since the Nuremberg war crimes trials were established to
try Nazi war criminals, national courts have possessed the
authority to prosecute war criminals and oppressive dictators,
according to experts. But they have rarely exercised it.
</P>
<P>
   Weiner said this case alerts judges around the world to pursue
charges against other alleged war criminals. ``There is the
potential under American law to try extraterritorial crimes,''
Weiner said. ``Whether they will use that power is a matter of the
justice department and the courts.''
</P>
<P>
   Pinochet was arrested in London during a visit for medical
treatment. He was detained by British authorities after a Spanish
Judge, Baltasar Garzon, requested his extradition to stand trial in
the murders of Spanish citizens in Chile during Pinochet's reign.
</P>
<P>
   The pursuit of Pinochet signals a ``new era of enforcement''
against past and present war criminals, Louise Arbour, the chief
justice of the UN war crimes tribunals for Rwanda and the Balkans,
said in a recent interview.
</P>
<P>
   She cited the arrests last summer in Kenya of Rwanda's former
Prime Minister on charges of genocide and the hunt by NATO troops
for indicted Bosnia war criminals Radovan Karadzcic and Ratko
Mladic as the most recent examples.
</P>
<P>
   ``The intiative of Spanish Judge Baltasar Garzon to ask for
Pinochet's extradition would have been unthinkable not so long
ago,'' added Mary Robinson, the UN High Commissioner for Human
Rights. ``Both were made possible by a turn in the tide of
international law.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite enthusiastic reaction from the human rights community,
the Clinton administration response to Wednesday's decision was
muted.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been informal discussions in the Justice Department
as to whether there is a legal basis to indict him under US law and
seek his extradition,'' said White House spokesman David Leavy.
``But Pinochet's current status is an issue for the British and
Spanish judiciaries to work out and it would be inappropriate for
us to comment.''
</P>
<P>
   Alfred Rubin, professor of international law at the Fletcher
School of Law and Diplomacy at Tufts University, was critical of
Wednesdaythe decision. He thinks the extradition of Pinochet to
Spain would be ``a step we would all live to regret, not just the
supporters of Augusto Pinochet.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no reason why Judge Garzon cannot ask the United
States to extradite Henry Kissinger,'' Rubin said. ``After all,
Kissinger was involved in the overthrow of Salvador Allende by
Pinochet. And if Nixon were still alive, there would be no reason
why Spain, or Cambodia, could not ask for his extradition.''
</P>
<P>
   (Globe Reporter Paul Langner contributed to this story.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
