<HEADLINE>
AIRLINE'S SECURITY DEVICES WORKING, FAA SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS C. PALMER JR.  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Federal Aviation Administration said Wednesday that
passenger security devices at AirTran Airways at Logan airport are
working properly.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA tested the airline's metal detector and other security
machines after an ex-security supervisor's allegations of faulty
equipment appeared in the Globe.
</P>
<P>
   FAA regional spokesman James A. Peters said federal law
prohibits disclosure of information about the failure of airport
security devices, or about investigations involving failure.
</P>
<P>
   But Peters said on Monday that the FAA was taking seriously the
claims of Thomas M. Ross, a former security supervisor with the
company that conducts passenger security screening for AirTran
Airways, formerly known as Valujet.
</P>
<P>
   Ross said that three different security devices at Terminal D at
Logan airport had intermittently flunked FAA tests since
mid-August. He said he notified both the FAA and the Massachusetts
Port Authority and nothing was done.
</P>
<P>
   The security screening for AirTran is done by a company called
Globe Aviation Services, which employed Ross until recently. Globe
Aviation executives did not return phone calls from a reporter.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for AirTran in Orlando, Fla., said this week that
the company also had not been able to reach Globe Aviation about
the alleged problems. Cara Maruskin, the spokeswoman, said the
company had not been notified by the FAA that its equipment had
failed tests in August and again in October.
</P>
<P>
   However, Peters, FAA spokesman for the New England region, said,
``We would notify them of what we found, right away, absolutely.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Peters could not confirm that the devices failed, as Ross
noted in his logs and charged in his letters, he did say that the
FAA was investigating. He would not give details.
</P>
<P>
   Peters said that after the Globe article appeared on Tuesday new
tests were done.
</P>
<P>
   ``The equipment is working, and it is up to FAA standards,'' he
said. ``And we will continue to monitor that.'' Though Peters said
the FAA requires airlines to repair broken security equipment
immediately, Ross said that had not been done in the case of
AirTran.
</P>
<P>
   Ross said Wednesday that he was sending copies of all of his
documentation to the inspector general of the U.S. Department of
Transportation. He said he was also sending the material to the
president of Globe Aviation Services, which does security for
Northwest Airlines as well as AirTran.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
