<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SCANDAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARR MAY NEED ANOTHER 2 YEARS BEFORE ENDING CLINTON
INVESTIGATIONS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ At least another 18 months, possibly two years,
will be needed by independent counsel Kenneth Starr to wrap up his
investigations of President Clinton, a Starr spokesman said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Although Starr has reported possible impeachable offenses to
Congress, his spokesman Charles Bakaly said the investigations have
not ended and decisions have yet to be made about whether to seek
criminal charges against Clinton for trying to conceal his affair
with former White House intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Bakaly said it would be improper for prosecutors to discuss
potential indictments, but agreed it would be ``fair to conclude''
that Starr still has the option of seeking indictments against
Clinton or others who might have been involved in trying to
cover-up his affair with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   And if charges are filed against Clinton, either after he is
removed from office by Congress or when his term expires in early
2001, Starr's operation would remain in business even longer.
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of two more years of Starr's investigation ``will
send chills down the spines of most taxpayers because it appears
(Starr and his staff) are out to set an unassailable record for
independent counsels,'' said White House spokesman Jim Kennedy,
referring to the $40 million spent so far by Starr to investigate
Clinton. ``It's like the nosy house guest who doesn't leave.''
</P>
<P>
   During a breakfast meeting with reporters, one of several public
appearances by Starr and his spokesman this week, Bakaly said the
independent counsel expressed concern that his investigation of
Clinton ``has been made so personal'' by the president and his
supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Bakaly said that Starr, a former federal appeals court judge and
solicitor general during the Bush administration, was widely
respected when he was appointed in August 1994 to take over the
investigation of Clinton's Arkansas business dealings.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Starr ``has been transmogrified into something
else,'' Bakaly said, contending the White House has portrayed the
investigation as a personal battle between Starr, who receives low
marks in public opinion polls, and Clinton, whose job performance
ratings have been near an all-time highs during the sex scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Starr ``does not believe he's out of tune with the American
people,'' Bakaly said. ``He recently expressed frustration with the
effect of the (White House) stonewalling strategy'' and expressed a
``frustration, a concern that people can lie and perjure themselves
and get away with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Starr took over the investigation of Clinton's Arkansas business
dealings known as Whitewater after Robert Fiske was forced out as
head of the inquiry that began in January 1994. During the past
four years, Starr's mandate has been expanded to include possible
misuse of FBI files, the death of White House counsel Vincent
Foster, the White House travel office firings and the Lewinsky
matter.
</P>
<P>
   In early September, Starr sent Congress a 453-page report filled
with salacious details alleging that Clinton lied under oath,
obstructed justice, tampered with witnesses and abused the power of
his office in an effort to cover up the 15-month affair he and
Lewinsky acknowledge they engaged in at the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing last week before the House Judiciary Committee, which
is conducting an impeachment investigation of Clinton, Starr said
the FBI files and travel office cases had yielded no impeachable
offenses against the president. Starr also said he had found no
impeachable offenses in the Whitewater business deals. The Foster
case was closed 13 months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Still awaiting prosecution by Starr are Susan McDougal, who has
been charged with obstruction of justice and criminal contempt for
refusing to talk to a federal grand jury, and former Deputy
Attorney General Webster Hubbell, who was indicted a third time
earlier this month on perjury charges.
</P>
<P>
   The charges against McDougal and Hubbell stem from their
involvement in Whitewater, and both are considered key to
uncovering any wrongdoing by Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if everybody came in tomorrow, the office would be in
existence for a minimum of one and a half to two years,'' Bakaly
said during a breakfast meeting with reporters.
</P>
<P>
   While Starr could step down and let someone else complete the
inquiry and oversee remaining prosecutions, Bakaly said, ``my
feeling is that he is committed to making the prosecutive
decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Starr steps down, he is required by law to submit a
report to the three-judge panel that appointed him, detailing his
investigations of Clinton's Whitewater involvement, the travel
office, the FBI files and the Lewinsky matter.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, before the office headed by Starr can close,
litigation fees must be negotiated with lawyers for people drawn
into the investigations. The law allowing appointment of
independent counsels allows for reimbursing some legal fees for
targets of the inquiry if the prosecutor finds they were not
involved in wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence Walsh, the independent counsel who investigated the
Iran-Contra scandal, was appointed in 1986. His inquiry did not end
until March 1994, and the final bills from the office were not
settled until well into 1995, when the tab topped $47 million.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation of abuses at the Department of Housing and
Urban Development, which began in 1990, ended earlier this month
after a run of more than eight years. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
