<SLUG> BC-PLYMOUTH-NATIVE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMONSTRATORS PLAN RETURN TO PLYMOUTH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds.:   All names are cq)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CINDY RODRIGUEZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A year after Native American demonstrators clashed with police
in Plymouth, Mass., sparking accusations of police brutality, an
estimated 1,000 demonstrators will return Thursday, hoping to
balance the town's ``propagated myth.''
</P>
<P>
   While Town Manager Eleanor Beth welcomes the demonstrators, the
Police Department plans to have all of its 100 officers on duty _
just in case.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope nothing happens,'' said Lt. Kevin Fahy.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, police arrested 25 demonstrators after they refused
to leave. Some witnesses said police used excessive force. Several
demonstrators, dubbed the ``Plymouth 25,'' filed lawsuits against
the town.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Plymouth settled with the United American Indians of
New England, paying the organization $135,000 _ most of which will
be used to educate people about indigenous history _ for dropping
the lawsuits. In turn, the town dropped charges. Police were upset
about the settlement, which they say implies wrongdoing on their
part last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's going on in Plymouth is that they're making a lot of
money off this false representation of Thanksgiving,'' said
Mahtowin Munro, a Lakota Indian who lives in Eastern Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pilgrim's Progress,'' the town's annual Thanksgiving tribute
will draw hundreds to watch 51 townspeople dressed as Pilgrims _
clutching Bibles and muskets _ walk from Plymouth Rock, through the
town Square, to the Church of the Pilgrimage.
</P>
<P>
   The 10 a.m. event will end long before a noon ``Day of
Mourning'' demonstration begins, during which an estimated 1,000
demonstrators will speak out about issues affecting Native
Americans. Munro said the Thanksgiving myth, that Pilgrims were
kind to Indians, is just one of many issues that will be discussed.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the settlement allows the United American Indians of New
England to demonstrate every Thanksgiving, but asks organizers to
notify the town about how many people they expect and the march
route, said Beth.
</P>
<P>
   She said the town was glad to settle.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they had filed multiple civil suits, it would've cost the
(town's) insurance company a great deal of money,'' said Beth. ``We
worked really hard on this settlement.''
</P>
<P>
   Beth said $100,000 was put in escrow with the American Civil
Liberties Union, until the Native American organization has filed
incorporation papers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the fact that everyone sat down and talked will go a
long way toward making it a peaceful day,'' Beth said.
</P>
<P>
   Munro says she wants peace, too, but hopes to wake Americans up
to historical facts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The US was built on the theft of native land, the genocide and
enslavement of native people, and the kidnapping and murder and
enslavement of people of African decent, who built this country,''
Munro said. ``That's not pretty.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not interested in making people feel guilty,'' she
continued. ``We just want people to know the truth. Then, maybe we
can have an intelligent discussion about what's going on in 1998.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
