<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A HOLIDAY GUIDE FOR LIVING A LIE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - I'd like to pause, now, at the very beginning of the
season in which we celebrate ``peace on earth and goodwill toward
men,'' to let each and every one of you know, from the bottom of my
heart, that Debi Avila of Phoenix is an undeniable, confirmable
liar.
</P>
<P>
   For which I personally thank God.
</P>
<P>
   There are many valuable lessons we learn during the Christmas
holidays. Lessons about kindness and virtue, generosity and
benevolence, charity and integrity.
</P>
<P>
   Most important of all, at least to me, is how the season teaches
us that if, by some miracle, our world were filled with nothing but
square-dealing, straight-shooting, completely honest individuals,
there would be no need for newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   That's why I'm telling you, now, about Debi Avila.
</P>
<P>
   The liar.
</P>
<P>
   Late last summer I wrote an article that began, ``The message
was recorded at 8:22 a.m. Tuesday, Aug. 4. The caller, a woman,
spoke for 30 seconds.''
</P>
<P>
   The heart of her message was: ``Mr. Montini, my name is Debi.
I'm . . . I'm dying of liver cancer, and I just I wanted to tell
you thank you very much for your articles. Now that I have so
little time, I'm thanking all the people that have done something
special for me in my life. . .''
</P>
<P>
   I'm gullible.
</P>
<P>
   I bought into this.
</P>
<P>
   I produced a sloppy-wet-kisses kind of column about how it
wasn't Debi who should thank someone like me for doing his job, but
me who should thank Debi for reminding me about what's important
and blah blah blah.
</P>
<P>
   After that story appeared, several of Debi's friends recognized
her and called my office. I was able to reach her not long
afterward.
</P>
<P>
   She told me that more than a year ago she was diagnosed with
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   In the early stages, it cost her an eye.
</P>
<P>
   Her friend, Laurie Ramirez, remembers those days. ``A lot of us
were scared to death for her,'' she said. ``But Debi, she just goes
on. She actually started collecting funny `eye ball' stuff. To make
us laugh. That's her personality. She's incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   When the cancer spread to Debi's liver, she was told she
wouldn't last six months, and to prepare for death.
</P>
<P>
   She ``retired'' from her job at a local courthouse, and began a
series of experimental chemotherapy treatments.
</P>
<P>
   She ain't dead yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Laurie says it's because I'm ornery,'' Debi told me Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   She finished her latest round of chemo early in November, and
will find out more about her condition in December.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, she's making plans for the holidays, enjoying
her family, which includes a 4-year-old granddaughter, and planning
a vacation trip with friends for February.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are things I never expected to do in my life,'' she
said. ``One of them was organizing my own funeral. But I've done
that and, to be honest, I found it liberating. After the initial
shock of hearing you have cancer, and the mourning you go through,
it was like, `Hey, it can't get any worse.' Once you accept it, it
almost sets you free.''
</P>
<P>
   She's done many of the things that most of us say we'd like to
do, but never get around to doing.
</P>
<P>
   One of them was thanking people for the little things.
</P>
<P>
   She's contacted everyone from her dog's veterinarian to Carol
Burnett (who wrote Debi a nice note in response).
</P>
<P>
   ``The two weeks after chemo are difficult,'' she says. ``But the
three weeks after that are great. I always wanted to retire young.
Now, I am. Also, before I was always worried about my weight. Now I
say, hey, I'm going to die fat. And happy. I have wonderful
friends. A great family. I'm going to enjoy every minute, no matter
how long that is, right up to the end.''
</P>
<P>
   She's come a long way since leaving that misleading message on
my answering machine in August. She's even willing, now, to finally
admit the truth.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, she has cancer.
</P>
<P>
   But she's not dying. She's living. &QL; 
E.J. Montini can be reached at ed.montini(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
