<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-NOTEBOOK26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Women's GT circuit hits road courses next season
 &HT;    By Kent Mitchell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Don Panoz's American Le Mans Series involves a lot
more than racing sports cars for 10 hours.
</P>
<P>
   The latest addition is the Women's Global GT Series. The series,
featuring female drivers driving the Panoz GT-RA, starts on the
nation's road courses in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Indianapolis 500 veteran and renowned road racer Lyn St. James
has been named executive director of the series, which will feature
women drivers in equally prepared sports cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need a platform to highlight women as drivers,'' said St.
James.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an opportunity to bring women to the forefront on a
regular basis in a credible, viable series.''
</P>
<P>
   The series champion will have the opportunity to drive in a GT
series in the 2000 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The Le Mans Series also added another venue, Sears Point Raceway
near Sonoma, Calif., for the July 23-25 weekend.
</P>
<P>
   One thing missing in the Le Mans series, and sports car racing
in general, will be the GT1 cars. They have been ruled out
altogether in the 24 Hours of Daytona sanctioned by the United
States Road Racing Championship. In the American Le Mans Series and
at the 24 Hours of Le Mans, GT1s such as the Panoz cars will be
included in the LMP1 _ Le Mans prototype _ category, along with
open-cockpit cars.
</P>
<P>
   GT2 will replace GT1 as the leading sports car class, and GT3s
will continue racing.
</P>
<P>
   Indy Racing League
</P>
<P>
   Pep Boys Indy Racing League champion Kenny Brack and car owner
A.J. Foyt were the biggest winners Saturday night at the league's
annual awards banquet, sharing the evening's biggest award, the Pep
Boys Million, a $1 million bonus for winning the season
championship. Brack didn't win the IRL trifecta _ he got Charlotte
and Atlanta but missed Las Vegas _ so he didn't get to share the $1
million prize with a fan, but did anyone win anything? You bet.
Brack can thank former B-52 pilot Ronald Ace of Baltimore for the
$50,000 each won after Ace's name was drawn Nov. 21. . . . Fans
will have a chance for some live Internet chat with John Paul Jr.,
(www.kecocoatings.com), 4-6 p.m. Dec. 3 and noon-2 p.m. and 4-6
p.m. Dec. 4.
</P>
<P>
   Drag Racing
</P>
<P>
   Warren Johnson of Duluth, Ga., received applause, accolades, and
a $125,000 bonus check at the NHRA Winston Championship Awards
Ceremony at the Cerritos Center for the Performing Arts in
Cerritos, Calif., on November 17. After runner-up finishes in 1996
and 1997, Johnson was crowned the Pro Stock champion for the fourth
time in the last seven seasons. The Johnsons, Warren and son Kurt
of Lawrenceville, were the only Pro Stock drivers to qualify at
every event in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   CART
</P>
<P>
   Championship Auto Racing Teams has announced its aerodynamic
regulations for the 1999 FedEx Championship Series season. The
short-track package is the same as the aerodynamic package formerly
used at superspeedway events, before the introduction of the
Handford Device and tunnel blockers. Ferrous-alloy brake discs are
required, and use of brake scoops is permitted. The minimum
race-car weight of 1,550 pounds for intermediate and short-oval
events remains unchanged.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
