<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fort Valley's daunting task
 &HT;    By Earnest Reese
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Saturday in the quarterfinals of the NCAA Division II
playoffs, Fort Valley will become the latest team to challenge
Carson-Newman's home dominance.
</P>
<P>
   Fort Valley has the best record in school history at 11-1 and
won its first-ever playoff game last week with a 21-14 road victory
over Delta State. Next for the Wildcats will be Carson-Newman,
which defeated West Georgia 30-20 last week for its 33rd win in its
last 34 home games.
</P>
<P>
   Leading the way for Carson-Newman (10-1) is a pair of Fort
Valley natives _ running back Melvin Oates and receiver and return
specialist Jacques Rumph.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very much aware of Carson-Newman's success at home, but
we're going to show up and play,'' Fort Valley coach Kent
Schoolfield said. ``What we've got to do against them is avoid
turnovers, make some big plays and have some fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Fort Valley State's success so far has been predicated on big
plays. Freshmen James Schoolfield and Cleo Stinyard have had key
kickoff and punt returns that have led to a pair of victories.
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats defense, led by linemen Peppi Zellner (6-foot-6,
260 pounds), Darryl Clark (6-3, 285) and Tramarcus Powell (6-3,
295), has mustered a few game-winning efforts. Fort Valley's first
touchdown this past weekend came as a result of an 84-yard return
of an intercepted pass by junior safety Jamaal Garman.
</P>
<P>
   Junior Will Mitchell, a third of the strong linebacker corps
that includes junior Jarrod Johnson and sophomore Marcus Lee of
Decatur, had two interceptions that killed Delta State drives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those guys have all played outstanding football for us all
year,'' Schoolfield said. ``But in the second half (of the Delta
State game), our quarterback was super. He must've called at least
a dozen plays on his own and made them work.''
</P>
<P>
   With the game tied 7-7 at halftime, junior quarterback Renotto
Solomon directed two second-half scoring drives. He finished
15-for-22 for 231 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Although Solomon and senior running back Bryan Holmes (899 yards
rushing) have had their moments, as have receivers Marcus Clayton
and Schoolfield at wideout spots, Fort Valley has yet to put it all
together in one game, according to its coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still experiencing some of the same problems we did
early _ in terms of consistency,'' Schoolfield said. ``We were bad
in the first of the Delta State game and pretty good in the second
half. But we haven't played team ball in all three phases _
offense, defense and special teams. Going into this game, we're
probably overdue.''
</P>
<P>
   DIVISION II QUARTERFINALS
</P>
<P>
   SATURDAY'S GAMES
</P>
<P>
   Shepherd (10-1) at Slippery Rock (11-1), noon
</P>
<P>
   Fort Valley State (11-1) at Carson-Newman (10-1), 1 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Northern Colorado (11-1) at Northwest Missouri State (12-0), 1
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Texas A&AMP;M-Kingsville (10-2) at Central Oklahoma (12-0), 2 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
