</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-QUINCYCARTER26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Full circle for Quincy Carter
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ Quincy Carter attended his only Georgia-Georgia
Tech game at Bobby Dodd Stadium in 1995 as one of the Yellow
Jackets' prized recruits.
</P>
<P>
   Carter, then a senior and Parade All-America quarterback at
Southwest DeKalb, watched two quarters of the Bulldogs' 18-17 win
before leaving to dismantle McEachern High later that day in a
first-round state playoff game.
</P>
<P>
   Who was Carter cheering for? ``Tech,'' he answered with a grin
this week.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Carter will be the center of attention when No. 12
Georgia and No. 17 Georgia Tech meet in Sanford Stadium. After
accepting a scholarship to play for the Yellow Jackets in February
1996, Carter walked away from football for two years. When he
decided to return to the gridiron earlier this year, Carter spurned
his initial promise to Tech, instead choosing, of all places,
arch-rival Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know exactly why he didn't come back to Tech,'' said
Yellow Jackets punter Rodney Williams, a high school teammate of
Carter. ``There are a lot of stories going back and forth. I was
disappointed he reneged on his word. I guess he felt it was a
better place for him to get a chance to play right away. It seems
like it's worked out for him.''
</P>
<P>
   After beating out a handful of candidates to replace Mike Bobo
as the Bulldogs' starting quarterback, Carter has rewritten
Georgia's freshman passing records. In 10 games, Carter has thrown
for 2,259 yards and 12 touchdowns on 160-of-259 passing, leading
the Dogs to an 8-2 record. He also is the Dogs' second-leading
rusher, with 290 yards and four scores.
</P>
<P>
   ``Neither team would be where they are without (the
quarterbacks),'' Georgia coach Jim Donnan said, referring to Carter
and Tech's Joe Hamilton. ``Both have really kind of carried the
offense on their shoulders. As I told Quincy, you can't get caught
up in a stats game against them. You've just got to run the team.
The big thrill in this game is getting the `W.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The big thrill for Georgia Tech would be ending its seven-year
drought against the Bulldogs. Doing it against Carter, who left
them with the feeling of a jilted prom date, would make it that
much sweeter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Me and (Tech linebacker) Donte Booker, we used to see (Carter)
at the mall,'' Yellow Jackets defensive end Jesse Tarplin said.
``He'd talk about how he's coming back, not that we took him
seriously. If he had come back, it would have been a hard challenge
for him to get a (starting) spot. He probably didn't want to come
here because of that. I understand that. It's the point of him
saying he'll come back.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter, a 6-foot-3, 225-pound native of Decatur, says he wasn't
intimidated by the presence of Hamilton, who had entrenched himself
in the starting role after a strong 1997 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't affect me at all,'' Carter said. ``Just because a
quarterback was there didn't have anything to do with it. If you
really look at it, I think I came to a school with four other
quarterbacks who could be starting at any school right now. That's
four more quarterbacks I had to worry about, rather than just one.
I think I went to the hardest school to start at.
</P>
<P>
   ``Georgia was a great opportunity where they'd just lost their
starting quarterback and they were coming off a 10-2 season. With
me signing with Tech and then going to play baseball, my first
question was, `Is there still some real animosity because I left?'
I still had to worry about all those other things. I don't think
Joe played any kind of role in what school I chose.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Carter points to a soured relationship with Georgia
Tech coach George O'Leary. Former Yellow Jackets defensive
coordinator Brian Baker, who recruited Carter, left Tech six days
after Carter signed to become the San Diego Chargers' defensive
line coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of felt (Baker) was going to leave at the time,'' said
Georgia offensive lineman Jonas Jennings, a close friend of Carter,
who also was recruited by Baker. ``Quincy ended up signing with
Tech, but then (Baker) left.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary was left in the dark when Carter signed a minor-league
baseball contract with the Chicago Cubs in 1996. Carter's baseball
contract included a clause that prohibited him from playing
football for four years. When Lonnie Cooper, Carter's agent,
negotiated a deal last year that allowed him to play both sports,
Carter informed O'Leary that he was returning to football.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've only spoken to Quincy one time (since he chose
baseball),'' O'Leary said. ``That was when he stopped by my office
to let me know he wanted to get back in football.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary says his next communication from Carter came in the form
of a letter, informing him that Carter wanted to be released from
his letter of intent with the Yellow Jackets. Georgia Tech refused
to release Carter, but Carter eventually won an appeal to the NCAA,
which allowed him to enroll at Georgia last spring and begin
playing football this fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really care,'' O'Leary said. ``I'm very happy with the
character of the kids I have at Georgia Tech. ... You can't harbor
hard feelings for someone you never had. My problem is the national
letter of intent and this interpretation of what a letter of intent
is. What is a letter of intent if it doesn't mean anything?''
</P>
<P>
   The schools' dispute over Carter has added more emotion to one
of South's most heated rivalries.
</P>
<P>
   ``It won't be too much for Quincy,'' Jennings said. ``He's a guy
that can obviously handle the pressure. Tech will try to get after
everyone, but I don't think there's a hit out on him or anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I actually hope Quincy doesn't get caught up in this,'' he
said. ``Don't get me wrong, I hate Georgia. But the fact is we were
friends before, and I hope we'll be friends afterward. The rivalry
was here before us, and it will be here when we're dead and gone. I
hate the both of them (Georgia and Carter) until after the
season.''
</P>
<P>
   Staff writer Carroll Rogers contributed to this article.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
