<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-NOTES26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lack of migration stalls duck opener
 &HT;    By Scott Bernarde and Kent Mitchell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Other than local wood ducks, opening weekend of
waterfowl season was pretty slow.
</P>
<P>
   Migratory ducks haven't reached Georgia yet, said Kent
Kammermeyuer, a biologist with the Wildlife Resources Division of
the state Department of Natural Resources.
</P>
<P>
   As for the renewal of duck hunting on Lake Lanier, Kammermeyer
said, ``I haven't heard a word about it.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the only shotgun heard on Lake Lanier this weekend
might have been on the committee boat of the Lanier Cup Regatta,
signaling the start and finish of the race.
</P>
<P>
   The regatta, by the way, ended early because of lack of wind.
</P>
<P>
   Accidental lunker
</P>
<P>
   It isn't a state record, but for a couple of grandparents in
their 70s, it was the fish of a lifetime, even if it was an
accident.
</P>
<P>
   Wilma Sapp, 75, and Cecil Sapp, 77, of Baxley were netting
shrimp for bait recently when they caught something a little
larger, a 63-pound black drum. The state record is 86 pounds, 8
ounces.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a lifetime first, and last,'' Mrs. Sapp said. ``I'll
never live long enough to do that again.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Sapp was handling the net when the big fish was caught.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I pulled it, I said, `I have something big.' My husband
said it was probably shells. I said, `No, it's moving.' It took
both of us to get him in. He's not pretty, but he's the biggest
fish I ever caught.''
</P>
<P>
   Champion of champions
</P>
<P>
   Larry Head of Loganville and Mike Lee of Lilburn teamed up to
win the 11th annual Georgia State Championships/Highland Marina
Invitational bass tournament last weekend on West Point Lake. The
two caught two five-fish limits weighing at total of 26.46 pounds
to win the two-day event and the first-place prize of $15,000 in
cash. They fished red clay banks in the middle of the lake with a
variety of lures. Jimmy and Jeanne Millsaps of Canton finished
second with 21.78, earning them $7,500. Allen Brooks of Acworth and
Pat Ratanjantra of Kennesaw were third ($4,000) with 20.42, and
Mike Jones and Glen Miller of LaGrange took fourth ($2,000) with
19.28.The tournament attracted 257 teams from six states, all
qualifiers by finishing in the top five in significant tournaments
held on Georgia lakes in the past year.
</P>
<P>
   A different spin
</P>
<P>
   What lifted Gary Dobyns to the second-round lead in the
Bassmaster California Invitational on Lake Shasta in Redding,
Calif., last weekend wasn't necessarily the reason he won the
tournament. Yes, his Day 2 catch of 14 pounds, 8 ounces provided
more than half of his winning total of 27-2, but it was his switch
to plastic worms on the final day that gave him enough in windy and
rainy conditions to edge Rob Vander Kooi by a mere 15 ounces. The
first two days, Dobyns had caught all of his fish, including a
largemouth that weighed 7-9, on a double-bladed (No. 4 nickel
Colorado/No. 5 gold willow) spinnerbait. He changed to plastics in
Day 3 after the spinnerbaits failed early, even though the Yuba
City, Calif., pro thought the conditions were right for the bait to
catch fish near the bank. ``It is really hard for a guy hung up
throwing reaction baits to go back to throwing a worm,'' he said.
``It just kills me to slow down and throw a worm. I absolutely hate
it. But you just have to make sure you have the five because you
never know what's going to happen.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
