<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPRAWLING LAVENDER  
 FOOLING HYACINTH  
 EVERGREENS IN A HURRY 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: The (AT) in the last graph should be replaced with the
typographical ``at'' symbol.) 
(js) 
 BY DORA GALITZKI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sprawling Lavender
</P>
<P>
   Q: While cleaning up my garden this fall, I realized that my
once beautiful four-year-old lavender plants are now beginning to
look sparse and leggy. Any suggestions?
</P>
<P>
   A: Sharpen your pruning shears, and then put it away. You are
way behind on your pruning, but hardy lavender should be pruned in
spring, when the small nodes along the branches begin to swell, but
before actual growth starts, or in summer right after it flowers,
not now.
</P>
<P>
   Pruning back about one-third to one-half the length of the
branches every year encourages branching lower down and keeps
lavender growing upright, avoiding the sprawl that comes from its
tendency to become woody and open up in the middle, after about
three years without pruning. This isn't just a question of
esthetics; sprawl can be dangerous. It leads to leaves touching wet
soil, a great point of entry for any enterprising fungus looking
for some work to do. Disease, of course, weakens a plant, making it
more susceptible to winter damage. A dressing of sand around the
base has been shown to be beneficial when growing lavender because
it warms the soil and keeps water away from the leaves.
</P>
<P>
   Spring is also the time to embrace your lavender, so just before
pruning, run your hands up through the dead leaves, letting them
fall away. You'll get that stick-garden look, but in a few weeks
the flush of new growth will show off the spring in your garden.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fooling Hyacinth
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can you help me break a cycle of disappointment? I've tried
forcing Dutch hyacinth bulbs for winter bloom, even buying the
special glass vases, but the result is always the same _ tiny
flowers, hidden among the foliage. I give them plenty of bright
light, so why won't they come up where I can really see them?
</P>
<P>
   A: They hide because they haven't gone through a full cycle of
seasons. So give them a short winter, and they'll be ready to act
more as if it's spring. Dutch hyacinths, like many other bulbs,
need a cold period to prepare them for spring bloom. Often catalogs
and nurseries offer ``prepared'' bulbs, which have been given a
controlled temperature treatment. Unfortunately, that sounds as if
the bulbs are ready to bloom. They're not. The preparation reduces
the needed cold, dark period from at least 14 weeks at 40 degrees
to only 10 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Without that period the flower stalks will fail to elongate and
the flowers, hidden in the foliage and much less spectacular than
they could be, will open from the top of the short stalk downward.
With a proper cool period, the stalk will grow longer and the
flowers will open in the right sequence, from bottom to top. So put
the bulbs in their forcing jars, and put the jars in the back of
your refrigerator for the right amount of time. Give them winter,
and they'll give you spring.
</P>
<P>
   Prepared Dutch hyacinth bulbs are still available from McClure &AMP;
Zimmerman, 108 W. Winnebago, P.O. Box 368, Friesland, Wis. 53935,
(920) 326-4220, free catalog.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Evergreens in a Hurry
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you have any information about the fastest-growing
evergreens?
</P>
<P>
   A: It really depends on your needs. Most requests for
fast-growing evergreens come from people who discover that the new
neighbor collects junk cars. If that's the case, then a fast grower
like white pine may not be a good choice. While it grows as much as
50 feet in 25 years, it eventually loses some lower branches,
letting the glint from those old hubcaps shine through. It is also
sensitive to salt, making it a poor roadside choice if your
community uses salt in winter.
</P>
<P>
   Is your site wet? The tall, slender Atlantic white cedar
(Chamaecyparis thyoides) will do just fine.
</P>
<P>
   Are you making a hedge? Canadian hemlock works well, but woolly
adelgid attacks mean a high-maintenance obligation.
</P>
<P>
   I know you see Eastern arborvitae (Thuja occidentalis)
everywhere, but it does make an effective, quick-growing hedge. A
handsomer version, the Western or great arborvitae (Thuja plicata),
does well from Boston and Cincinnati to Raleigh, N.C., despite the
Western connotation of its common name.
</P>
<P>
   A grouping of three to five tall, pyramidal Japanese cryptomeria
form a screen, not really a hedge, although a single specimen tree
looks better. The feathery Leyland cypress (x Cupressocyparis
leylandii) gives a more columnar screen and grows in coastal areas
from Massachusetts to Florida.
</P>
<P>
   For large, single specimens, Norway spruce (Picea abies) and
Atlas cedar (Cedrus atlantica) grow quickly when young, then slow
down.
</P>
<P>
   Spend a little time looking before you buy. Large evergreens are
a strong presence in the landscape, summer and winter. This is a
great season to go to public arboretums and botanical gardens and
look at mature examples. Do you have the room? Is it as cute at 30
feet, or at 80, as it is in a container?
</P>
<P>
   Address questions to Garden Q.&AMP; A., The New York Times, 229 W.
43rd St., N.Y., NY 10036, or by e-mail to gardening(AT)nytimes.com.
Those of general interest will be published. Unpublished questions
cannot be answered individually. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-25-98 1850EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
