<SLUG> BC-FIRE-RESCUE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BORDER PATROL TRAINEE SAVES WOMAN TRAPPED INSIDE BURNING APARTMENT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: Irvine, Calif.) 
(Eds.: Guymon is cq) 
 
By JAMES PINKERTON 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARLINGEN, Texas _ U.S. Border Patrol trainee Richard Guymon
didn't have heroics in mind when he left his new apartment before
dawn Wednesday. In fact, at 4:45 a.m. the rookie was headed to his
car to retrieve the government-issue boots he forgot to polish.
</P>
<P>
   But Guymon smelled smoke coming from the apartment below his,
and ran to investigate.
</P>
<P>
   What he found was a woman overcome with smoke who, because of
prior injuries, was trapped inside her burning apartment. After
pulling her out, he even extinguished the fire with a garden hose.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard a muffled groan for help, and I went to the window
thinking a person was talking out the window, but it was shut,''
said Guymon, 32, a native of Irvine, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   When he reached the apartment door, Guymon was met by thick,
acrid smoke. He yanked open the screen door, and found a woman
slumped against the door. Inside the apartment, he could see the
carpet and a hospital-type bed in flames, the mattress and plastic
cover putting off heavy, choking smoke.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some arms flopped out as soon as I opened the door, so I
pulled her out,'' Guymon said.
</P>
<P>
   After determining his neighbor was breathing and did not require
CPR, Guymon ran to other apartments to get someone to call an
ambulance and the Fire Department. He didn't know any of his
neighbors, since he only moved into the apartment complex two weeks
earlier after reporting to work in Port Isabel, his first duty
station.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took me, it seemed like forever, to get someone up,''
Guymon recalled. ``I just wanted someone to call 911 and get an
ambulance and get a blanket to cover her up, just to get her
comfortable until someone could come.''
</P>
<P>
   Satisfied his neighbor was out of danger and help was on the
way, Guymon picked up a garden hose and began to douse the flames.
He had them under control when Harlingen firefighters arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Elliott, a spokesman for Valley Baptist Hospital, said the
49-year-old woman is in fair condition. She was being held for
observation after receiving treatment for minor burns and smoke
inhalation, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Harlingen fire officials say Guymon's actions probably saved the
woman's life, and prevented the fire from spreading to other
apartments. They are considering him for a commendation.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it wasn't for him, it would have been worse. He did the
right thing,'' said Ramon Gomez, a fire inspector for the
department's fire prevention bureau. ``She might have died. The
smoke is what kills, that's what does most of the damage to people,
not the fire.''
</P>
<P>
   Fire officials determined the fire was started by cigarettes,
Gomez said.
</P>
<P>
   Border Patrol officials were proud of their trainee.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a good thing he did, he saved a life for the
holidays,'' said Mark Butler, the assistant patrol agent in charge
of the Port Isabel station.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're glad to have an agent of his caliber. Although he's new
to this line of work, (he) is able to react in that kind of
situation. That's fabulous.''
</P>
<P>
   Guymon is thankful his neighbor, whom he had never met and still
does not know by name, was able to hang on until he could help her.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was propped up against the door, calling for help, and I
don't know how she endured it ... I could only endure it for two
seconds. It was really a choking-type smoke and you can't
breathe.''
</P>
<P>
   Guymon, homesick for his family in California and not having
time to make friends since moving to South Texas, says helping
someone has made a lonely holiday easier.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really thankful for what I have. Because I found out she's
alone, sick and is incapacitated, and now her apartment is all
messed up.'' Guymon said. ``But if she needs some help, I'm right
upstairs.''
</P>
<P>
   And while Guymon, who is single, will spend Thanksgiving Day
patrolling the banks of the Rio Grande on the 6 a.m. to 2 p.m.
shift, he and other agents will still observe the holiday.
</P>
<P>
   His supervisors say a private citizen who owns property along
the river _ grateful for the stepped-up border control _ has
invited patrol agents to drop by and share a turkey dinner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thanksgiving will not be a loss,'' said supervisor Butler.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
