<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DONALDSON-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WRONG ABOUT CLINTON ALL ALONG,' SAM DONALDSON ADMITS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Celebrity newsman Sam Donaldson has a startling
confession to make:
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to come absolutely clean . . . I have been wrong
about Bill Clinton all along,'' Donaldson told the Valley
Automobile Dealers Association on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been wrong, wrong, wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Donaldson's mea culpa came in a speech that touched on a debate
raging in newsrooms across the country: Whether the line between
journalists and commentators has become too blurred.
</P>
<P>
   Donaldson, a veteran White House reporter and a fixture on ABC's
influential Sunday morning show ``This Week With Sam Donaldson and
CokieRoberts,'' acknowledged that as an on-air political
commentator, he goofed when it came to predicting Clinton's rise
and fall.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, Donaldson said the then- Arkansas governor had too much
political baggage to be elected president.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, after the GOP swept the congressional elections,
Donaldson said Clinton couldn't be re-elected.
</P>
<P>
   And in January, a few days after the Monica Lewinsky scandal
erupted, Donaldson said on ``This Week'': ``Mr. Clinton, if he's
not telling the truth and the evidence shows that, he will resign,
perhaps this week.''
</P>
<P>
   Donaldson said Wednesday he misread Clinton's tenacity and the
public's attitude about the Lewinsky affair.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been wrong about big things about Bill Clinton, and
clearly I've been wrong because I did not understand the electorate
. . . and I'm a political reporter,'' Donaldson said in an
interview after his noontime speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe the crime of perjury is serious, and I think it
should be punished, but that's my personal opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   The role of reporters-as-commentators has sparked widespread
newsroom hand-wringing about whether journalists, particularly
those in television, are galloping into a twilight in which facts
and opinions become indistinguishable.
</P>
<P>
   Donaldson said the debate is legitimate.
</P>
<P>
   But he also said the news business is changing so fast that the
old rules separating journalists from commentators often don't
apply.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like doing you-know-what against the wind to say, `Well,
we're not going to do this,' '' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, we are not only doing it, but in my estimation,
with the growth of cable channels and the people who populate them,
we are all going to be doing this.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``If I thought it was really beyond the pale, I
obviously would not do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Donaldson is one of the most high-profile newsmen to face
questions about the conflict between those who report the news and
those who make on-air political commentaries.
</P>
<P>
   Yet he is hardly alone. Roberts also dishes out opinions.
</P>
<P>
   Donaldson noted that virtually every Capitol Hill reporter this
year predicted Republicans would pick up House seats in the wake of
the Lewinsky scandal. And all of them missed the boat _ the GOP had
a net loss of five seats in the mid-term election.
</P>
<P>
   ``I acknowledge I'm wrong, but I'm in a sea of faces . . . not
just one bozo who didn't get it,'' Donaldson said.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to Clinton, the newsman said he underestimated the
president's never-give-up approach and the willingness of White
House aides to deny, stonewall and to attack critics.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'd done the things he's accused of, I would find a hole in
New Mexico, I'd crawl into it, and I'd put a big rock there,
because I wouldn't want you to look at me, because I'd be
ashamed,'' said Donaldson, a New Mexico native.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't have any shame. He knows no shame . . . and I'm not
here to say the president should be ashamed.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Michael Murphy can be reached at michael.murphy(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
