<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-25 19:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9850 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRO     11-25 0741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; A PLEA FOR THANKSGIVING &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Before we break bread together, let us stop for a moment today
to consider _ and cross our fingers for _ the 30-something San
Francisco screenwriter _ ``extremely fit and comely,'' by her own
description, who recently placed a Personals ad in the New York
Review of Books. Among other attributes, she's seeking:
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone who loves to play and who savors the details as we sit
across the gothic wooden table laden with sumptuous organic feasts,
our well-loved friends coming for Sunday dinners, stories and
discourse infused with sovereign thought, self-possessed rebellion,
deep compassion and shameless discovery.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps you, on the other hand, are sitting down today at a
Formica table, eating a plate of fast-food french fries with a
bunch of strangers whose thoughts aren't sovereign (perhaps even
strangers like Personals, who's clueless as to what a sovereign
thought is).
</P>
<P>
   Whatever. Seize the day, if not the drumstick.
</P>
<P>
   P.S.  &UR; Cal Fussman &LR; , an essayist writing in the latest Esquire
about alleviating the stresses of everyday life, says that an
old-fashioned food fight is a useful form of stress management.
</P>
<P>
   P.P.S. A cautionary tale, on the other hand: ``I sat down with a
book and waited for the cranberries to start popping, which they
soon did,'' writes &UR; Andrew Solomon &LR;  in the latest issue of Food &AMP;
Wine. ``It was only afterward that I noticed the words `a covered
pot. ...' My little kitchen looked like the scene of a shoot-out.''
Solomon, says the author's credit at the end of the story, is
working on a book about depression.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HOLIDAY GIFT GIVING &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``Wearing these light, sheer colognes will take you back to a
summer day redolent of freshly cut grass, warm, loamy soil or
tomatoes ripening on the vine,'' says the copy from Gardeners Eden,
a catalog in which  &UR; Kate Hanson &LR;  dug for treasures.
</P>
<P>
   One bottle of Dirt cologne will set you back $12. A set of three
fragrances, including Dirt, Grass and Tomato, costs $30.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Susan Schwartz &LR; 's new book, ``Teddy Bear Philosophy''
(Andrews McMeel; $12.95), has some supportive words for the
formerly feathered victims of the day: ``When life knocks the
stuffing out of you, be sure to put it back in.''
</P>
<P>
   - If today's feast leaves you worried about your waistline, the
New York Times reports that figure-conscious people in New York are
ordering their bagels ``scooped,'' that is, with the inside dough
spooned out. And if that's not enough, social X-rays are ordering
their bagels with a ``deep scoop.'' Does anyone know how to bake a
crust-only bagel?
</P>
<P>
   - French fries are ordered more often than any other restaurant
dish in America, reports Rolling Stone. In 1960, the magazine
reports, the average American ate 3.5 pounds of frozen french fries
a year. In 1997, the average American ate 30 pounds of french fries
a year.
</P>
<P>
   - ow to decorate your table? Never mind &UR; Martha Stewart; &LR;  ``Nash
Bridges'' regular  &UR; Yasmine &LR;   &UR; Bleeth &LR;  gave US magazine her
Thanksgiving Day decorating tips: ``Use miniature gourds, carved
out in the middle, for candleholders. (I use a grouping of five to
seven, not just a pair).'' Adventurous homemakers might even go so
far as to use nine, or 11.
</P>
<P>
   - Forbes FYI warns about the perils of nutmeg. A man who
consumed four nutmeg kernels with a half-liter of vodka ``became
tingly all over, his heart began to race and he started
hallucinating,'' effects that lasted for 27 hours. ``Why do you
think they call it nutmeg?'' asks the magazine.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``Elizabeth invited me to partake in her private afternoon &LR; 
 &UR; delight. Sensing my apprehension, she urged me to try these &LR; 
 &UR; exquisite sapphires from the sea and I'm glad she did. As we &LR; 
 &UR; spent the afternoon in her boudoir, visiting, laughing and &LR; 
 &UR; devouring spoonfuls of the most scrumptious thing I had ever &LR; 
 &UR; tasted, I remember thinking to myself in between sips of &LR; 
 &UR; champagne that life just couldn't get any better.'' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; - From ``Hollywood Dish'' (Angel City Press; $29.95), &UR; Nick &LR; 
 &UR; Grippo' &LR; s new book of recipes, ``Tips and Tales of a Hollywood
Caterer.'' The boudoir-sharing  &UR; Elizabeth &LR;  is  &UR; Taylor  &LR; and the
sapphires are caviar.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``I'm especially fond of his Caesar salad with homemade &LR; 
 &UR; Parmesan croutons.'' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; - From Elizabeth Taylor's slightly more matter-of-fact
introduction to Grippo's text.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
