<HEADLINE>
A&AMP;M QUIETLY STAYING IN HUNT FOR NATIONAL TITLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   They stand, quite simply, as the Northwestern Mutual Life of the
Bowl Championship Series.
</P>
<P>
   The Quiet Company. The sleeping giant in the race for the Fiesta
Bowl. The team no one north of the Red River wants to mention when
discussing potential national championship contenders.
</P>
<P>
   Don't think for a minute that the Texas A&AMP;M Aggies are
complaining about their place in college football's pecking order.
Quite the opposite, in fact.
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;M, ranked sixth in both major polls, holds down the No. 5 spot
in the BCS rankings. The BCS computer will update its pecking order
twice more before its top two teams shuffle off to Tempe, Ariz.,
for a Jan. 4 date in the Fiesta Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   If the Aggies (10-1) win their remaining games and Tennessee
(10-0) and UCLA (10-0) stumble between now and Dec. 5, A&AMP;M will
reprise its Aug. 31 matchup against Florida State (11-1) in the
Fiesta Bowl. But this time, a national title would be on the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're on the outside, looking in,'' linebacker Dat Nguyen
said. ``But you can't deny it's a possibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Sure, it's a long shot. But the dominos have fallen right this
season for A&AMP;M, which heads into tomorrow's 10 a.m. contest against
Texas with a 10-game winning streak. Even better, they have fallen
in relative anonymity, which has allowed a team with a popgun
offense and a blowtorch defense to steadily climb the BCS ladder
with a minimum of pressure until the top rung has become visible.
</P>
<P>
   Even now, this week's pregame foucs isn't on the Aggies. It's on
Texas tailback Ricky Williams, who needs 63 yards to break the NCAA
career rushing record held by Tony Dorsett (6,082 yards). On Dec.
5, the lion's share of pressure in the Big 12 championship game
falls on Kansas State (11-0), which sits two spots ahead of A&AMP;M in
the BCS rankings and will be playing for its first conference title
since 1934.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just rolling along, not worried about trying to draw
people's attention,'' A&AMP;M tailback Dante Hall said. ``But we know
we've put ourselves in position for a lot of great things. We're
down to a three-game season. If we win all three, anything can
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Including a national championship.
</P>
<P>
   But the Aggies, even with victories the next two weeks, will
need some help to make their final game a Fiesta in the desert.
A&AMP;M's best hope rests with Arkansas (8-2) or Mississippi State
(7-3) upsetting Tennessee in the Southeastern Conference title game
and Miami (7-2) knocking off UCLA in its regular-season finale.
Both games are set for Dec. 5.
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;M's odds for reaping the benefits of a season-ending,
double-upset Saturday are slim and none. But this is college
football, where strange things happen on a weekly basis. Things
like Michigan State 28, Ohio State 24. Or even North Carolina State
24, Florida State 7.
</P>
<P>
   That is why A&AMP;M coach R.C. Slocum is holding out hope that his
team can tiptoe quietly into position for a bell-ringing finish to
the 1998 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's still some big games left to play. With each one,
there's a chance something positive can happen to change our
position a little bit,'' Slocum said. ``But we don't have any
chance unless we win these next two games. And we're practical
enough to know none of it matters if we don't focus on the next
challenge, and that's playing Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   At college football's quiet company, they're taking it one
silent step at a time.
QUICK HITS Family ties
</P>
<P>
   Texas A&AMP;M tight end Dan Campbell, a Glen Rose High School
graduate, understands a thing or two about divided family loyalties
during A&AMP;M-Texas week.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell's cousin, Rocky Allen, was a Texas defensive end from
1986-89.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why my mom's side of the family are all big Texas
fans,'' Campbell said. ``All year, they've been coming to watch me
play and it's been, `Go, Aggies.' Now, when we play the Longhorns,
it's, `Sorry, I can't root for you.' That eats you up a little
bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Campbell, who grew up on a cattle ranch near Walnut Springs,
said he knew his cousin's school was not for him when former Texas
assistant coach Bucky Godbolt made a recruiting visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were some stray goats out by the creek,'' Campbell said.
``And Coach Goldbolt asked me, `What are those black deer doing out
there?' My dad and I laughed about that the rest of the night ...
Believe it or not, as stupid as that story is, it might have had a
lot to do with my decision. I knew right then that Texas didn't fit
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about his first impressions of A&AMP;M coach R.C. Slocum,
Campbell said: ``He fit in perfect. We were a match from the
start.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, Slocum did not misidentify any farm animals during his
visit to the Campbell ranch.
Supporting Williams
</P>
<P>
   Texas tailback Ricky Williams, the probable front-runner for the
Heisman Trophy, said he would not be bothered if Kansas State
quarterback Michael Bishop beats him out in balloting for Big 12
Offensive Player of the Year honors. A survey taken last week of
league coaches, who do the voting, indicated that could happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't agree more,'' Williams said of Bishop's status as
the league's top offensive player. ``He deserves it. He carries
that team.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas A&AMP;M linebacker Dat Nguyen, a finalist for the Butkus and
Lombardi awards, begs to differ.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that happens, that's like me winning the Butkus and being
second-team all-conference,'' Nguyen said. ``It's pretty weird. It
doesn't make any sense.''
Extra Points
</P>
<P>
   Texas linebacker Aaron Babino will replace the injured Anthony
Hicks (knee) in the lineup for tomorrow's game against A&AMP;M. Hicks,
a starter since Sept. 26, has been somewhat of a good-luck charm
for the Longhorns' defense. In games that Hicks has started and
finished, Texas is 6-0. When he has not, Texas is 1-3 ... Add the
name of Johnnie Cochran to the list of players in the Oklahoma
coaching saga. No, the former attorney for O.J. Simpson is not
among the myriad candidates rumored as potential successors to the
ousted John Blake. But Cochran may soon be the former OU coach's
representative in negotiations to sweeten his severance package
with the school. The two are longtime friends. As for the sticking
point, OU administrators say Blake is due $115,000 in base salary
for each of the remaining years on his contract, which goes through
the 2000 season. Blake seeks a deal closer to his $501,000 annual
package that also included income from radio and TV shows, as well
as a shoe contract ... Look for OU administrators to sign off on a
package in the $850,000 range for Blake's successor. That could be
enough to turn the head of Georgia coach Jim Donnan, who recently
received a new contract worth $625,000 per season. If not, it
should be enough to land the marquee name OU administrators seek if
Donnan opts to stay put ... How ground-bound is the Nebraska
offense? Wide receiver Matt Davison has 30 catches, the most by any
Cornhuskers player since tight end Johnny Miller had 31 in 1991 ...
Kansas State's David Allen has 771 yards in punt returns. That's
185 more than the next closest ``team'' in the NCAA season
statistics (Arizona, at 528 yards) ... Stung by seasonlong
criticism about a soft nonconference schedule that could be a
stumbling block to a national championship showdown in the Fiesta
Bowl, Kansas State officials recently completed their 1999 slate of
outside opponents by adding Utah State (3-8). School officials
already had dates with UTEP (3-8) and Temple (2-9), with all games
in Manhattan, Kan. Some things never change ... Texas Tech tailback
Ricky Williams (1,582) nipped Missouri's Devin West (1,578) by 4
yards to finish second in the Big 12 rushing race to another guy
named Ricky Williams. But he needed an extra 23 carries to do it.
</P>
</TEXT>
