<P>
   The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following general
stories for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs of
Thursday, Nov. 26 and thereafter. For questions about stories,
contact Jeremy Bagott at the Daily News, (818) 713-3702.
</P>
<P>
   BOYS-BURNED (Los Angeles) _ Three 17-year-old Hart High School
athletes were burned early Wednesday, when a methanol-fueled
``cannon'' device being used in a physics class experiment
exploded. The explosion, which was seen by the entire physics
class, caused a blast of 3,000-degree air that critically burned
varsity soccer player Chris James and injured two friends. James
suffered third-degree burns over 35 percent of his body, and was
airlifted to Sherman Oaks Burn Center. By Patricia Farrell Aidem.
(Will move in the ``a'' national and ``n'' California news file.)
</P>
<P>
   LA-VALLEY-SECESSION (Los Angeles) _ On the final day Valley VOTE
collects petitions to trigger a study of San Fernando Valley
secession from Los Angeles, volunteers predict they will have
200,000 signatures, a cushion of 35,000. By David R. Baker. (Will
move in the ``n'' California and ``a'' national news files.)
</P>
<P>
   SMOKERS-HOARDING (Los Angeles) _ With a new 50-cent cigarette
tax on top of a 45-cent price hike imposed by tobacco wholesalers,
smokers are crowding Costco and other stores where the prices have
not risen _ yet. By Lee Condon. (Will move in the ``f'' financial,
``n'' California and ``a'' national news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SHOP-FRENZY (Los Angeles) _ Most people will spend tonight
digesting turkey and wondered whether it's possible to eat just one
more slice of pumpkin pie. Not Lori Killam and her mother. They
will be plotting their shopping strategy, mapping out an early
morning route from department store to department store that will
maximize the number of freebies they get and discounts they can
take at the cash register. Their mantra is simple: The early bird
gets the deals. By Enrique Rivero. (Will move in the ``f''
financial, ``n'' California and ``a'' national news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CELEB-MEALS (Hartlaub, Hiestand) w/photos _ Jennifer Love
Hewitt, Leeza Gibbons and Henry Winkler are among the celebrities
dishing up Thanksgiving meals at the LA Rescue Mission. And the new
San Fernando Valley Rescue Mission will sponsor its first
Thanksgiving dinner for about 400 homeless people. By Jesse
Hiestand and Peter Hartlaub. (Will move in the ``n'' California and
``a'' national news files.)
</P>
