<SLUG> BC-PINOCHET-IMMUNITY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITISH REJECT IMMUNITY IN PINOCHET EXTRADITION CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON - In a stunning reversal that will have implications for
despots all over the world, Britain's highest court cleared the way
Wednesday for the extradition of Chile's former dictator Augusto
Pinochet to face charges that he tortured and murdered political
opponents.
</P>
<P>
   By a 3-2 vote, the Law Lords in the House of Lords, Britain's
upper house of Parliament, overturned last month's decision by the
nation's High Court that had cited sovereign immunity in ruling
that Pinochet could not be prosecuted for the repression he
oversaw, including at least 3,000 state-sanctioned murders, during
his 1973-1990 reign.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers here acting on behalf of Spanish authorities who lodged
the warrant for Pinochet's arrest appealed the High Court decision.
They argued that Pinochet's crimes were against humanity, making
him ineligible for sovereign immunity.
</P>
<P>
   By the slimmest majority, the law lord judges decided that the
principle of sovereign immunity did not apply to Pinochet because
he had overseen grievous violations of human rights, including the
torture and murder of ordinary men, women and children.
</P>
<P>
   One of the judges, Lord Steyn, said that to allow Pinochet to
invoke sovereign immunity to escape his actions was to suggest that
Hitler could have done the same to escape prosecution for imposing
the Final Solution to exterminate Jews.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict was delivered in dramatic fashion in a hushed House
of Lords chamber full of tension. One by one, the five judges,
dressed in dull business suits that contrasted vividly with the
mostly empty red benches of the chambers, rose to render briefly
their decisions. The verdict was in doubt until the fifth judge,
Lord Hoffman, stood and broke the two-two tie, saying, ``Senator
Pinochet does not have immunity from prosecution, and I, too, would
therefore allow the appeal.''
</P>
<P>
   Lord Hoffman's terse remarks were interrupted by gasps from the
visitor's gallery, which was packed with both those who love and
loathe the former Chilean strongman.
</P>
<P>
   There was pandemonium on the streets surrounding Westminster,
where most of those gathered were Chilean exiles who hate Pinochet,
including the relatives of some of his victims.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you, Jesus!'' one man kneeling on the ground cried
repeatedly in Spanish, tears streaming down his cheeks.
</P>
<P>
   Pinochet's reaction was said to be more subdued, as news of the
verdict ruined his 83rd birthday. He was informed of the verdict in
the North London hospital where he is recovering from back surgery,
and where he is under armed guard.
</P>
<P>
   So sure were Chilean officials that Pinochet was going to be
released that a Chilean air force jet, equipped with medical
equipment, has been waiting for a month at the Royal Air Force base
in Oxfordshire.
</P>
<P>
   It will have a much longer wait. Pinochet is due in court here
next Wednesday for an extradition proceeding here. The extradition
process could last for weeks, or even months. Spain is just one of
a number of European countries that have lodged warrants demanding
Pinochet's arrest for murder, torture and genocide.
</P>
<P>
   Home Secretary Jack Straw must now decide if Pinochet will face
an extradition hearing next Wednesday at Bow Street Magistrate's
Court. Like many of the Labor Party leaders who form the British
cabinet, Straw was in his youth a vocal supporter of Salvador
Allende, the democratically elected leader of Chile who Pinochet
overthrew in a CIA-backed coup in 1973. Allende died during the
events under mysterious circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Acknowledging his past activism against Pinochet, Straw made the
extraordinary claim soon after Pinochet's arrest that he would not
allow his earlier political views to inform his decision on whether
to extradite - a claim that rings hollow to Pinochet's supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately after Wednesday's decision, former prime minister
Margaret Thatcher, a friend of Pinochet who hosted him for
cocktails at her Belgravia home two weeks before his Oct. 16 arrest
at a London hospital, called on Straw to cancel Pinochet's
extradition on humanitarian grounds, citing Pinochet's age and
failing health. Earlier this year, Straw had cited similar grounds
in refusing to extradite Roisin McAliskey, the daughter of Irish
radical Bernadette Devlin McAliksey, to Germany to face charges for
an IRA bombing. The younger McAliksey suffering from depression
during her long detention, during which she gave birth to a child.
</P>
<P>
   But Pinochet's supporters were so sure of victory that they may
have unwittingly undermined his ability to cite his failing health
as a reason to escape extradition. Last week, apparently sure that
the High Court decision would be upheld, Pinochet's supporters said
he was healthy and ready to fly home to Chile as soon as the law
lords delivered their ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Underscoring how closely this case had been followed in the
international community, representatives from human rights groups
were here en masse for the verdict. Reed Brody, the advocacy
director for the New York-based Human Rights Watch, seemed to voice
the consensus of the groups when he said the decision was ``a wake
up call to tyrants around the world who think about embarking on
mass murder.''
</P>
<P>
   But Pinochet's supporters denounced the decision as a craven
capitulation to left-wing agitators and a violation of Chilean
sovereignty. As part of a deal approved by Chileans, Pinochet was
allowed to step down in 1990 in exchange for his freedom from
prosecution and his granting of democratic elections.
</P>
<P>
   The law lords' decision came several weeks after hearing
extraordinary set of arguments. Alun Jones, the lawyer who argued
on behalf of the Spanish authorities who want Pinochet to face
charges for killing Spanish citizens, said it was ``repugnant'' to
suggest Pinochet was entitled to immunity. He said a body of
international law developed throughout the 20th century made a
mockery of Pinochet's claim that, because Chileans accepted a deal
in which he stepped down in exchange for not being prosecuted,
other countries had no jurisdiction.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the alleged murders by Pinochet of more than 3,000
people, including children, and disappearances of another 1,000 who
have never been accounted for, Jones said, ``It is not part of the
function of the head of state, under English or international law,
to behave like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones also claimed that some of the crimes of which Pinochet is
accused took place during and immediately after the 1973 coup he
led, before he could be considered a head of state. Pinochet's
lawyer, Clive Nicholls, scoffed at that claim, saying, ``There's no
suggestion that anyone else was head of state at this time.''
</P>
<P>
   While Pinochet is expected to recover from back surgery, the
principle of sovereign immunity that he expected to shield him
while receiving medical care here may be irreparably damaged. Some
legal observers believe it means that despots like Yugoslav
president Slobodan Milosevic or Iraqi leader Saddam Hussein would
leave their own countries at their peril.
</P>
<P>
   Pinochet's ordeal here is ironic as it is divisive.
Conservatives here view him as an old ally who helped Britain
during its 1982 war with Argentina over the Falkland Islands.
Liberals say it is outrageous that Pinochet has come here regularly
to shop and use London's great hospitals and restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   Pinochet is an avowed Anglophile and a great admirer of London,
the city that has now for almost two months been his prison. He
shopped at Burberry's, admired the city's war memorials, and said
he was most attracted to Britain because it was ``civilized.'' But
now diplomats from Chile accuse Britain of disregarding one of the
bedrocks of civilization - international law.
</P>
<P>
   Chilean officials complain that Britain has trampled on the
long-established principle of sovereign immunity. But British
officials have insisted that they acted properly when receiving an
extradition request from Spain.
</P>
<P>
   A British Home Office spokesman acknowledged that Pinochet was
traveling under a diplomatic passport when arrested, but said
immunity applies only to a serving head of state or diplomats
specifically assigned to Britain. The law lords who ruled against
Pinochet Wednesday cited similar reasoning, saying that Pinochet is
no longer a sovereign.
</P>
</TEXT>
