</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-NOTES26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons coach looking for more progress from Chandler
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Quarterback Chris Chandler did not practice Wednesday
and, although he was walking without the removable cast worn on his
sprained right ankle Monday and Tuesday, he still has a limp.
</P>
<P>
   After a practice in which 44-year-old backup Steve DeBerg and
second-year veteran Tony Graziani split time with the No. 1
offense, coach Dan Reeves was not optimistic Chandler will play
Sunday at St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was not encouraged by Chris. He didn't move well at all,''
Reeves said. ''I thought he would move around a lot better than
that. He would have to make a lot more progress before he would be
ready to practice (today).''
</P>
<P>
   Every time Chandler plants his right foot to throw, he feels
significant pain. ''It's still very sore,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   When Chandler missed the Oct. 25 game against the Jets, a 28-3
loss, DeBerg started, completing 9-of-20 passes for 117 yards and
one interception. Graziani played most of the second half,
completing 7-of-14 passes for 86 yards and one interception.
</P>
<P>
   Graziani, who is far more mobile than either Chandler or DeBerg,
has made notable progress. Against a Rams pass rush that has 37
sacks and behind an Atlanta line that has allowed 40 sacks, that's
worth considering.
</P>
<P>
   ''Chris has been a great role model for (Graziani),'' Reeves
said. ''His arm is stronger (than last year) and . . . players have
more confidence in him.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think he's going to be a good quarterback in this league.
We'll do what gives us the best chance to win, and mobility may be
a part of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Injury update
</P>
<P>
   Reeves said Tim Dwight, who has missed four straight games with
a strained medial collateral knee ligament, will probably dress out
Sunday, and return punts and kickoffs. . . . CB Ronnie Bradford is
almost certain to return to the lineup after missing two games
entirely and two additional starts because of a strained MCL.
Michael Booker, who played well in Bradford's absence, will spell
him and be involved in nickel and dime defenses. . . . FB Bob
Christian continues to cope with either stretched or pinched nerves
running from his right ear down into his right arm. He practiced
Wednesday, but was held out of contact. Whenever his head is
snapped the wrong way, he suffers numbness in his right arm. He is
listed as questionable. . . . CB Ray Buchanan missed practice with
a sore hamstring. It has been bothering him since the Nov. 15 game
against San Francisco. ''It's just precautionary, to rest it,''
Buchanan said. ''It doesn't limit me, but it gets sore. I'll
play.'' . . . S Chris Bayne (hamstring), who has missed two
straight games with a strained hamstring, practiced and is
questionable. . . . St. Louis QB Tony Banks (sprained ankle), RB
Jerald Moore (broken rib)and WR Isaac Bruce (hamstring) did not
practice Wednesday. Banks insists he'll play. Rookie RB Robert
Holcombe is likely to start for Moore, and Bruce is doubtful.
</P>
<P>
   Bonus time
</P>
<P>
   Because the Falcons are doing so well, the team will end up
paying quite a bit more after the season in incentives, and RB
Jamal Anderson is at the top of the list.
</P>
<P>
   With a career-high 1,138 rushing yards, third in the NFL, he is
62 yards away from activating clauses in his contract calling for
as much as $1.1 million in bonuses.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever money the Falcons have left under the salary cap after
the season (currently less than $800,000) can be committed to such
incentives. The team also can carry them over to next year's cap.
Often, bonuses are added onto a player's base salary the following
year.
</P>
<P>
   Extra points
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons signed QB Sherdrick Bonner to the practice squad,
where he replaced LB Malcom Hamilton after the Redskins signed
Hamilton to their active roster. The lefthanded Bonner plays in the
Arena League for the Arizona Rattlers. His coach is Danny White,
who was a backup and starting QB when Reeves was offensive
coordinator of the Cowboys from 1977-80. . . . Atlanta worked out
Albany native and former Clemson DE Brett Williams, who was in
training camp with the Cowboys. . . . The Falcons still have not
worked out all the small details in an agreement to hold training
camp at Furman University in 1999, with options in 2000 and 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Ticket talk
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons, who can sew up a playoff berth with a win Sunday,
may announce playoff ticket prices Friday or Saturday. The league
has a say in those prices, but since Atlanta has the lowest average
ticket price in the regular season at about $31, the Falcons also
are likely to have the lowest playoff tickets. Season ticket
holders will have first priority, and then fans who pay a deposit
on season tickets for next year will have next priority. Those
tickets would go on sale to the public after the middle of
December.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
