<HEADLINE>
TEXAS EDUCATOR TO PROPOSE TOUGHER STANDARDS ON STUDENT EXIT EXAMS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KATHY WALT 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Texas Education Commissioner Mike Moses said
Wednesday he will propose toughening the standards by which schools
are rated by adding algebra exams and continuing to raise the
minimum passing rate.
</P>
<P>
   While those measures likely would reduce the number of public
schools that get the highest ratings of ``exemplary'' and
``recognized,'' neither is likely to have the immediate impact that
another new measure will, Moses said.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning this school year, special education students' scores
on the Texas Assessment of Academic Skills tests will be included
when the Texas Education Agency evaluates school district and
campus performance. Including these students is expected to slash
by 38 percent the number of top-ranked ``exemplary'' schools and by
25 percent the number that this year got the second-highest rating
of ``recognized.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That does cause some concern for school districts,'' Moses
said. ``It looks like the number of exemplary schools will probably
fall in the neighborhood of 400 schools, and the number of
recognized schools could likely fall by that many as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Last school year, a record 1,042 campuses were rated exemplary
and 1,617 were deemed recognized.
</P>
<P>
   Although Texas schools have been administering TAAS exams to
special education students, their scores have not been calculated
in the statewide accountability system.
</P>
<P>
   TEA figures for last school year show that the passing rates of
special education students ranged from a high of 43 percent of
third- and fourth-graders to a low of 19 percent of high school
juniors trying to pass the exit level test needed for a high school
diploma.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Jack Christie, chairman of the State Board of
Education, said that Texas students also could soon be facing more
rigorous TAAS exams.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1999, I predict we will toughen the test itself'' by adding
other subjects, like social studies, science or health science, to
the battery of courses over which students in elementary school are
tested, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Moses said he will propose next week that the Algebra I
end-of-course exam be added to the accountability system and that
the minimum passing rate for schools to be rated ``acceptable''
continue to rise 5 percentage points a year until 2004, when 70
percent of students would have to pass all TAAS tests before a
school campus is considered acceptable.
</P>
<P>
   TEA spokesman Joey Lozano said it is unclear how soon those new
standards, if approved, would take effect.
</P>
<P>
   Texas has been hiking the passing rate standard for an
acceptable rating by 5 percentage points a year since 1993, when
only 25 percent of students needed to pass. When schools are rated
at the end of this school year, at least 45 percent of all students
and of all student groups must pass the test for a school to be
listed as acceptable.
</P>
<P>
   Moses said he has been talking about adding the algebra exam to
the accountability system in speeches to legislators, school
superintendents and other educational groups around the state for
the past three weeks or so. While he has the authority to continue
raising the passing rate standard for schools, legislative approval
is needed to add the algebra I exam to the mix.
</P>
<P>
   Student scores on the algebra I end-of course exam have been
disappointing ever since TEA began field-testing the exam several
years ago. Although scores have risen for the past three years,
still, only 39 percent of students passed the exam last spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we need to continue to look to see if there are other
things we want to do,'' Moses said. ``It seems as though when we
put something in the accountability system it gets a lot of
attention, which is a good feature of the accountability system.
That means that teachers and principals pay attention to those
things upon which their schools are going to be rated.''
</P>
<P>
   Making student performance on the algebra test part of the
school ratings might help raise student performance in that course,
Moses said.
</P>
<P>
   The TAAS test is at the heart of the school accountability
system. Students are tested in reading and mathematics in grades
three through eight. Fourth-graders take an additional test in
writing, and eighth-graders also are tested in writing, science and
social studies. High school students must pass an exit-level TAAS
test to get a diploma.
</P>
<P>
   School ratings are based on the percentage of all students
passing and the percentage of students passing in specific ethnic
and low-income groups.
</P>
<P>
   Despite most education officials' contention that the TAAS is
demanding and a nationally recognized program, it has come under
criticism recently from a variety of groups. Some teachers have
criticized the program, saying it forces teachers to spend a
disproportionate amount of time teaching only material covered on
the test.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, a group of out-of-state researchers, hired
by the Tax Research Association of Houston and Harris County,
attacked the test as too easy.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
