<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-CLINTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMPEACHMENT CHAIRMAN SETS DEADLINE FOR CLINTON TO RESPOND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER AND LOUIS D. PALMER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Frustrated by the White House response to the
impeachment inquiry, House Judiciary Committee Chairman Henry J.
Hyde Wednesday abruptly issued a deadline of Dec. 2 for President
Clinton to say if he will present a defense against allegations
stemming from his sexual affair with Monica S. Lewsinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde, who previously said he would not invite Clinton to testify
because he did not want to ``embarrass'' him, wrote to the
president Wednesday that he will ``allow'' him or his attorneys to
present his case to the committee.
</P>
<P>
   Amid growing pressure in Congress to resolve the matter quickly,
Hyde's letter to Clinton stated, ``I am prepared to schedule your
presentation for as early as Tuesday, December 8,'' barring further
developments.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials said Clinton's legal defense team will
prepare a response to the letter, which Hyde issued on the same day
that Clinton had been expected to answer 81 questions from
committee Republicans about his relationship with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   The White House said the responses to the questions will be
provided tomorrow instead, prompting a testy reaction by Hyde.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite repeated requests for more than a month, the White
House has yet to provide the committee with any materials that tend
to exonerate you or even dispute the evidence submitted in the
referral of the Office of Independent Counsel,'' Hyde stated in his
letter to Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   If the White House does not provide ``complete and specific
answers'' by Monday, Hyde warned, ``I have no course but to urge
the full committee to subpoena those answers.''
</P>
<P>
   A White House spokesman, James Kennedy, said Hyde apparently
knew when he wrote the letter that Clinton was expected to answer
the 81 questions by tomorrow, as aides had said he would do by the
end of the week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure what the point of his letter is,'' Kennedy said.
``As for the other issues he raises, we will respond to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Charles Bakaly III, spokesman for independent counsel
Kenneth W. Starr, said in a breakfast meeting with reporters that
the independent counsel's office is likely to remain active through
the end of Clinton's presidency in wrapping up investigations and
criminal prosecutions.
</P>
<P>
   Bakaly said Starr has not ruled out seeking criminal charges
against Clinton stemming from the Lewinsky matter after Clinton's
term ends. Starr and committee Republicans have cited Clinton's
alleged perjury before a federal grand jury as the most serious
charge against him.
</P>
<P>
   But Bakaly indicated that the perjury allegation may be hard to
sustain in court. ``Perjury is not always the easiest case to
bring,'' he said. ``Perjury cases are tough to prove.''
</P>
<P>
   At the White House, officials said Clinton will answer the 81
questions from committee Republicans without admitting he committed
any crime or impeachable offense stemming from his sexual liaisons
in the White House with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Starr, who Wednesday faced a new attack from commmittee
Democrats on his handling of the case, has cited ``substantial and
credible'' evidence in the referral he sent to Congress that
Clinton may have committed 11 impeachable offenses, including
perjury, obstruction of justice, and abusing the power of his
office.
</P>
<P>
   Starr defended his inquiry last week under cross-examination by
committee Democrats and Clinton's private lawyer, David E. Kendall.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde's letter to Clinton continued: ``The failure to provide any
exculpatory information, together with Mr. Kendall's failure to
contest a single fact in the Referral when questioning the
Independent Counsel, lead to the conclusion that the White House
does not dispute any of the factual evidence presented in the
Referral and supporting materials.''
</P>
<P>
   Hyde said Clinton's cooperation is vital if the committee is to
achieve his goal of completing its inquiry by the end of the year.
Hyde wants the panel to vote on articles of impeachment the week of
Dec. 7 and, if they pass, send them to the full House for action
the following week.
</P>
<P>
   ``The committee is reaching the critical stage of this
process,'' Hyde's letter stated. ``Time is of the essence for you
to provide any factual basis which disputes the allegations against
you &UR;  &LR; ... &UR;  &LR; Now is the time for cooperation.''
</P>
<P>
   But the committee Democrats also want answers from Starr. In a
letter, the panel's highest ranking Democrat, Representative John
Conyers Jr. of Michigan, asked Starr to answer 19 questions on
topics ranging from alleged news leaks by his deputies to their
treatment of Lewinsky during their first meeting in January.
</P>
<P>
   The questions are ``simply an attempt to clarify the factual
record where Mr. Starr was vague, evasive, forgetful or not
altogether candid'' when he testified last week before the
Judiciary Committee, said Jim Jordan, spokesman for the panel's
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Bakaly defended Starr's testimony, saying, ``He's a man of law,
not of politics or polls.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
