<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-25 19:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9871 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-FALCONS-ANDERSON-     11-25 0395
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-ANDERSON-CONTRACT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Anderson contract extension in works
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ At the request of the Atlanta Falcons, the agent for
Jamal Anderson has given team officials a contract extension
proposal that would make the five-year veteran one of the five
highest-paid running backs in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   No deal is imminent. And neither Anderson, Oakland-based agent
James Sims or Falcons general manager Harold Richardson would
discuss specifics.
</P>
<P>
   But Anderson, 26, confirmed that he and Sims have used as a
framework for their initial proposal the contracts of Denver's
Terrell Davis, Detroit's Barry Sanders, Dallas' Emmitt Smith, the
Jets' Curtis Martin, Green Bay's Dorsey Levens and Minnesota's
Robert Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Their contracts average roughly five years and $23 million,
which is believed to be in the ballpark of Anderson's proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had prepared myself mentally to play through my current
contract (and test the free-agent market),'' said Anderson, whose
contract runs through the 1999 season. ``Just in the last week or
so, this all changed. I'm just looking for what most (high-profile)
backs are getting, about five (extra) years.''
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons have multiple reasons to begin offering contract
extensions, especially to Anderson, who has become one the league's
top rushing threats with his third straight 1,000-yard season.
</P>
<P>
   He ranks ninth on the team with a salary this season of $1.2
million. The closer he gets to free agency, the more difficult it
might be to keep him. He is slated to make $1.6 million next
season.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the contracts of two Falcon starters expire after this
season and those of 15 starters expire following next season,
although the team will maintain rights to several.
</P>
<P>
   The team does not want to be in a position of having to re-work
numerous contracts next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always are interested in extending players that are
contributing and keeping them for the long run,'' Richardson said.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons are not likely to pay Anderson more than quarterback
Chris Chandler, who in September signed a five-year, $27 million
contract that included a $6 million signing bonus and an average
salary of $4.68 million over the final four years of the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
