A9874 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CORD-BLOOD-BOS &LR;      11-25 0976
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CORD-BLOOD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UMBILICAL BLOOD CAN HELP CANCER PATIENTS, STUDY SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DOLORES KONG  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Blood from a newborn's umbilical cord works at least as well as
bone marrow from an unrelated donor for patients with cancer and
other diseases requiring a marrow transplant, according to the
largest study to date of the blood's life-saving potential.
</P>
<P>
   Considering the shortage of bone marrow donors worldwide and the
difficulty in finding a close enough genetic match, particularly
for minority patients, such cord, or placental, blood is a vast
untapped resource, say the study's authors and others in the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has far-reaching implications,'' particularly for cancers
like lymphoma and leukemia, said Dr. Curtis Cetrulo, president of
the International Cord Blood Society and a Tufts University
professor, who is familiar with the study in today's New England
Journal of Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you saved all the placental blood that is now discarded in
the United States, anybody who ever needed bone marrow
transplantation could find a compatible donor,'' said Cetrulo, an
obstetrician in private practice, who is affiliated with South
Shore Hospital in South Weymouth, Mass. ``It has that potential.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Pablo Rubinstein, lead author of the study and director of
the placental blood program at the New York Blood Center, said
transplant centers are already beginning to favor cord blood over
bone marrow from unrelated donors.
</P>
<P>
   ``More and more people are realizing that this indeed has
advantages that are very helpful,'' he said. For instance,
Rubinstein said, cord blood is relatively easier to obtain than
bone marrow, it's less likely to transmit viral infections and it
poses a lower risk of serious graft-versus-host disease, a
potentially fatal complication of transplantation.
</P>
<P>
   Still, cord blood does not take the place of what is usually the
optimal situation _ a sibling with perfectly matched bone marrow.
</P>
<P>
   The National Heart, Lung, and Blood Institute, which first
funded the New York Blood Center in 1992 to set up a cord blood
bank, welcomed the results. ``They clearly advance the field,''
said Dr. Claude Lenfant, director of the institute, in a statement,
although he cautioned the findings need to be confirmed by further
research.
</P>
<P>
   The study reported the results of cord-blood transplants in 562
patients worldwide, including four in Massachusetts, performed
between August 1992 and January 1998. The blood all came from the
New York Blood Center, which used federal funds to set up the
mechanism to take donations, type the blood and freeze it for later
use.
</P>
<P>
   Cord blood, like bone marrow, contains the stem cells that help
rebuild a patient's diseased or damaged blood system. But it
appears that those found in cord blood have a special quality,
leading to a lower risk of serious graft-versus-host disease and
allowing a less perfect match than required for bone marrow.
</P>
<P>
   While bone marrow transplant is used as part of treatment in a
variety of diseases, including solid tumors like breast cancer, the
study looked only at such blood-related diseases as leukemia.
</P>
<P>
   As with people who receive bone marrow from donors, however,
people receiving cord-blood transplants may die or suffer a relapse
of their disease.
</P>
<P>
   Severe graft-versus-host disease occurred in 23 percent of
patients in the study, while the rate of relapse for patients with
leukemia reached 26 percent at the end of a year.
</P>
<P>
   Of the four patients with leukemia who were transplanted in
Massachusetts hospitals over the last couple of years, three of
them died.
</P>
<P>
   A 44-year-old woman with chronic myelogenous leukemia died after
her disease came back, while a 50-year-old woman with the same form
of leukemia died as a result of complications from
graft-versus-host disease, said Dr. Donald Higby, chief of
hematology and oncology at Baystate Medical Center in Springfield,
Mass. At the time of the cord-blood transplants, both women had
advanced disease, and neither of them had a closely matched bone
marrow donor.
</P>
<P>
   Even with publication of the worldwide cord-blood transplant
results, Higby cautioned, ``I think there still needs to be a lot
worked out before we call it a major advance.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Eva Guinan, of Children's Hospital and Dana-Farber Cancer
Institute in Boston, said one infant who received a cord-blood
transplant died from infection. The other patient, a boy from the
Boston area, has problems with graft-versus-host-disease, but has
not seen a recurrence of the leukemia.
</P>
<P>
   The Dana-Farber is one of several medical centers involved in a
federally funded, $30 million study of cord-blood transplants, to
better understand their use. The hospital is kicking off its arm of
the study next week, according to Guinan.
</P>
<P>
   Although cord blood holds out much potential, it is difficult to
set up a system to save and preserve donated blood, as the
experience of a cord blood bank at UMass Memorial Health Care
demonstrates.
</P>
<P>
   In September, the blood bank stopped accepting donations, after
collecting, typing and freezing about 2,000 cord bloods in 18
months. The blood is still available at UMass through an
international cord blood registry, and has been used for
transplants in a number of cases, including one in Australia. But a
funding crunch forced the hospital to stop accepting new donations,
said Mark Shelton, director of public affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Several commercial cord blood banks exist in Massachusetts and
nationwide, offering parents the possibility of saving their
children's cord blood in case they develop leukemia or other
diseases later on. Rubenstein said too little studying has been
done to show that using one's own cord blood to treat leukemia
would work, and he added he doubts it would.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
