<HEADLINE>
GASH ON ZOLAK: `DANGEROUS' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He has seen what the rest of us haven't. And Sam Gash has had a
better ``in'' than the rest of us when it comes to Scott Zolak.
</P>
<P>
   ``Zo is dangerous,'' said Gash yesterday from Buffalo, where he
and the rest of the Bills were preparing for Sunday's critical AFC
East game against the Patriots in Foxborough.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess people don't think of Zo as being dangerous,'' said
Gash, who played fullback for the Patriots from 1992-97. ``He has
the happy-go-lucky way about him, but when he is on the field,
playing the game, he plays with a lot of fire. He's a competitor.
He is always prepared to play. He studies. He knows what the game
is all about. But the thing that could bother us the most with Zo
playing is that the ball comes out in a hurry. It will be hard for
our guys (pass rushers) to get after him.''
</P>
<P>
   Gash is looking forward to this homecoming.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played there six years,'' he said, before catching himself
and adding with a laugh, ``Make that 5 1/2. I know all the guys.
They know me. We just had a great game against each other a few
weeks ago in Buffalo. There was a lot of intensity on the field
that day, and we expect it will be the same in this game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know there is a lot at stake in this game. You have four
teams fighting for the division title, and because of that, the
teams that don't win it might be left out of the wild-card race
because we will be beating each other right down to the final
Sunday of the season. I think that's when it will be decided. The
last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we will be pressing for this game. Our game plan
will be to do what we do best: run the ball. I watched the film of
their game against Miami and they did a great job of stopping the
Miami run.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the key to the game. Miami likes to run the ball,
control the tempo of the game, and keep their defense off the
field. But the Patriots won the battle of the clock and that was
important at the end of the game. The Miami defense was out on the
field in the final drive more than they have been used to, because
their offense could not control the clock with the run.
</P>
<P>
   ``This game will be like that. Both teams will try to control
the clock. Their defense is tough to run against, to try to sustain
drives. I'm sure they will come up with a couple of things to try
to disrupt (Doug) Flutie and the way he does things.''
</P>
<P>
   Gash feels this encounter has all the makings of a special game.
Flutie coming home. Drew Bledsoe injured. Four o'clock kickoff.
National television. The Bills needing to win to keep a piece of
first place. The Patriots one game behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we all know each other's schedule the last five
weeks,'' said Gash. ``All of us will be looking at the scoreboards
to see what Miami is doing, the Jets. A team could go 9-7 in our
division and not make the wild card. Every game is important. I
don't think any team will separate itself from the pack.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a great, hard-hitting game in Buffalo. I know it was
hard going up against guys like Ted Johnson and Tedy Bruschi every
play, head to head. I think Ted is the best inside linebacker in
the league. He plays full speed all the time and when you meet him
head-on, it hurts. He's very physical.''
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo has lived by the run this year. Even though Flutie has
gotten the bulk of the publicity, the teams that have beaten
Buffalo this year, with the exception of one (the Rams), have shut
down the running game.
</P>
<P>
   The Bills come into this game averaging 138.5 yards per game on
the ground, compared with 81.9 for the Patriots, playing virtually
the same schedule. Buffalo has 76 first downs via the run to 43 for
the Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   Antowain Smith does the bulk of the work for Buffalo, averaging
3.8 yards per carry. However, the venerable Thurman Thomas, who is
not getting beat up as he did when he was the workhorse of four
Super Bowl teams, has come on strong lately in a part-time role,
averaging 4.4 yards.
</P>
<P>
   This game does not figure to come down to Flutie and Zolak; it
should be decided in the battle between the Bills' offensive line
and the Patriots' front seven on defense.
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo's defense can be susceptible to the run, but New England
does not have the rushing game to exploit that. And the Bills'
defense, featuring a surging Bruce Smith, is as tough as any in the
league on third and long, when it uses a fourth down lineman
(Marcellus Wiley) and comes after the passer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both teams have their backs against the wall,'' said Gash.
``That's why this game is going to be so much fun. A football
player lives to play in this kind of game.''
</P>
<P>
   And no one ever said that Sam Gash wasn't all football player.
</P>
<P>
   (Will McDonough is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
