<SLUG> BC-WELFARE-ECONSCENE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ECONOMIC SCENE: PROFITS IN JOB TRAINING FOR WELFARE RECIPIENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich., N.Y.)  (bl) 
 By MICHAEL M. WEINSTEIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A robust U.S. economy has provided a respite _ until the next
recession _ from the provisions of the 1996 Welfare Reform Act that
threaten to withdraw aid from millions of poor families. But now a
longer-term, if still partial, answer is slowly emerging.
</P>
<P>
   Prodded by the Welfare to Work Partnership, a nonprofit
organization run by Eli Segal, a former adviser to President
Clinton, companies are connecting with community groups to recruit,
train and hire welfare parents for entry-level jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The motive,'' says Segal, ``is the most reliable of all:
profit. Companies are finding that properly trained welfare
enrollees stay at their job longer than other recruits, cutting the
firms' recruitment and training costs.''
</P>
<P>
   Beginning in early 1997, the partnership initially signed up
about 3,200 companies to hire an estimated 135,000 welfare
enrollees for entry-level jobs. About three-fourths of the hires
are for full-time work with health benefits. The program has now
expanded to about 7,500 companies.
</P>
<P>
   The partnership's key strategy is to link companies to nonprofit
community groups, like Goodwill Industries International and
churches, that specialize in recruiting, training, counseling and
mentoring welfare parents. The idea is to provide enrollees with
the English, math and so-called ``soft skills'' _ manners and
attitude that qualify welfare recipients for an employer's own
training program. The community groups also provide counseling and
mentoring once the welfare recipient enters work.
</P>
<P>
   The initial hires were in all the expected unskilled corners:
fast-food restaurants, clerical positions, retail sales. The
obvious question is whether the partnership's strategy could be
expanded to handle any number close to the 2 million or or so women
now on welfare who will soon need jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The new wrinkle is that the partnership has pierced high-pay
white-collar jobs in industries that are expanding. Next week the
partnership will announce in New York City new commitments by banks
and other financial institutions. Therein lie the seeds of
replication.
</P>
<P>
   Take Chase Manhattan. The bank has set up three tracks for
hiring welfare enrollees. The first uses Wildcat Services Corp. to
train welfare enrollees to become bank tellers at Chase's branches,
using Chase terminals and computer programs. Chase then puts these
hires through its own two week training course.
</P>
<P>
   The distinct feature of the program is that Wildcat is training
enrollees to perform Chase-specific tasks. Carol Parry, who
oversees the program for Chase, says that her ``managers are
thrilled with their new recruits, and the welfare recipients say
they are ecstatic to be working at Chase.'' Typically, she says,
about half of Chase's new tellers leave within a year, forcing
Chase to spend between $3,000 and $5,000 to recruit and retrain a
replacement. But, so far, only about 10 percent of the tellers it
has hired through Wildcat have left.
</P>
<P>
   Chase has turned to two other nonprofit groups to train welfare
enrollees to serve as customer service representatives, answering
customer phone calls about Chase bank products, and as back-office
workers, reconciling transactions on Chase's automated teller
machines.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, Salomon Smith Barney has also turned to Wildcat to
train welfare enrollees specifically for its entry-level jobs. So
far, more than 90 percent of the enrollees that Salomon has hired
under the program remain employed two years later. Republic
National Bank, which promises a job to each graduate of its
program, trains 120 welfare recipients a year.
</P>
<P>
   Segal's point is that by expanding beyond fast food and retail
sales, the partnership strategy opens the possibility that
employers will absorb most if not all of the welfare recipients
that will flood into the labor force over the next several years.
</P>
<P>
   There is some independent evidence that Segal's optimism may be
justified. Professor Harry Holzer of Michigan State University
surveyed employers in three Michigan metropolitan areas, finding
that almost 9 percent of the their jobs over the next year would be
open to welfare recipients, even those without high school diplomas
or work experience. That number is many times the size of the
welfare population that will need work.
</P>
<P>
   There remains a serious problem of matching unemployed
recipients to willing employers _ the very task that the
partnership was set up to accomplish.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, not all the evidence is encouraging. The Holzer study
emphasizes that the employers' willingness to hire is tied to
temporarily tight labor markets and that many employers are located
beyond the reach of most welfare enrollees.
</P>
<P>
   Professor Sandra Danziger and her colleagues at the University
of Michigan surveyed women on welfare in an urban county in
Michigan early in 1997 and followed up with interviews about nine
months later. The study found that of the women who were not
already working, perhaps half were potentially hirable, especially
if they were to receive the type of counseling and mentoring
services offered by Segal's program. But many of the women
enrollees faced serious and multiple employment barriers. Some of
those barriers are physical. About a third of the women suffer from
mental problems like depression. A third have not finished high
school. Half the women lack access to transportation. The welfare
recipients suffering multiple handicaps _ about half the group _ do
not easily find work. In the study, only about 5 percent of the
women suffering from seven or more of these barriers were working.
</P>
<P>
   Its easy to list reasons why optimistic signs that
welfare-to-work programs are succeeding are just that, optimistic.
The Danziger study identifies and measures the obstacles. Sixty
years of experience under modern welfare laws proves the point.
</P>
<P>
   But it is equally valid to stress the good news. The Holzer
study says employers are prepared to hire welfare recipients. The
partnership results, though skimpy because they come from a program
still in infancy, say that promises can be translated into
permanent jobs, a mellow note on which to start the holidays.
</P>
</TEXT>
