<SLUG> BC-POPLIFE-RECORD-SALES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARTH BROOKS ALBUM SETS SINGLE-WEEK SALES MARK 
</HEADLINE>
  (rl) 
 By NEIL STRAUSS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Last Tuesday became known in the music business as
Super Tuesday after a glut of major records were released
simultaneously for the holidays by superstars like Garth Brooks,
Whitney Houston, Mariah Carey, Jewel, Method Man and Seal.
</P>
<P>
   But before the results of this Thanksgiving music battle were
announced, Brooks, the country-music titan, had already planned a
victory news conference at the Rainbow Room in Manhattan. Despite
many sales disappointments by superstar acts this year, he was
confident that his ``Double Live'' album would break the
music-industry record held by Pearl Jam for most albums sold in a
week: 950,000 copies in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   The results, announced Wednesday by Soundscan, a music-retail
monitoring company in Hartsdale, N.Y., show that his confidence was
not misplaced. Brooks far outdistanced his competitors. ``Double
Live'' sold 1.09 million copies, a figure all the more impressive
for a two-record live set that contains only three new songs. One
of many marketing schemes that helped the album's sales is that it
was sold for the price of a single CD, around $14, for its first
weeks on sale.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the multimillion-dollar campaign included screening
a live performance on closed-circuit television in 2,400 Wal-Marts
on the day the album came out, releasing seven different packages
of the album for collectors, appearing on the ``Tonight'' show,
performing a concert special on NBC and garnering headlines by
making the claim that the record would sell more than a million
copies its first day out.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks has said his goal is to sell 100 million ``Double Live''
records over time, which is more than the sales of all his previous
records combined: 82 million, in itself a record for the most
albums sold by a solo artist.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Litwak, a vice president at Trans World Entertainment, which
supplies records to more than 500 U.S. stores, credited the album's
success to Brooks' broad-based appeal and the marketing savvy of
Capitol Nashville president Pat Quigley. Although ``Double Live''
even sold well for Trans World in cities like New York and Chicago,
it was not Trans World's biggest album of the week. That honor went
to a rap album, Method Man's ``Tical 2000: Judgment Day.''
</P>
<P>
   Overall, among the other albums released last week, Method Man
came in at No. 2, selling 411,000 copies. And in the race between
the divas Mariah Carey and Whitney Houston, both of whose albums
featured the same Carey-Houston duet from ``The Prince of Egypt,''
they lost to Jewel, who sold more than both of them combined with
the third biggest record of the week, ``Spirit.'' Ms. Carey's ``No.
1's'' came in at No. 4 and Ms. Houston's ``My Love Is Your Love''
disappointed at No. 13.
</P>
<P>
   The weeks surrounding Thanksgiving are the biggest and most
crucial for the record business, and such numbers, retailers said,
pointed to a good year for sales as the business rebounds from a
period of flat sales in the mid-90s.
</P>
<P>
   Several record retailers see a trend in the success of niche
genre albums by Brooks and Method Man over those of artists who
appeal to a more broad-based audience like Jewel and Ms. Houston.
They said that one reason this was shaping up to be a successful
holiday season was that record companies catered to the diversity
of consumers this year with releases by major acts across the
board. And with new albums released last Tuesday by Metallica,
2Pac, Pearl Jam and the Wu-Tang Clan's RZA, record retailers expect
the sales surge to continue.
</P>
<P>
   Promoters File Suit
</P>
<P>
   Despite the recent success of black artist-owned labels like No
Limit and Bad Boy, few in the music business disagree with the
contention that there is a proportional lack of black executives in
the upper echelons of the business, especially at major labels. A
lawsuit filed last Friday in U.S. District Court in Manhattan
points to an even greater disparity in the music business: the lack
of successful black executives in the concert business and, even
more so, of black concert executives working with white acts.
</P>
<P>
   The suit, filed by five concert promoters from around the
country, charges 11 major promoters and booking agencies (including
SFX Entertainment, the William Morris Agency and Creative Artists
Agency) with antitrust and civil rights violations. The promoters
claim to have been locked out of promoting concerts by white acts
as well as successful black ones. They are seeking $700 million in
damages.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've worked with Michael Jackson,'' said Leonard Rowe, a
plaintiff and head of the Black Concert Promoters Association and
Rowe Entertainment, an Atlanta promoter. ``But I've never been
solicited by a white act as long as I've been in the business, and
that's 23 years. I've tried to talk to the booking agents, but they
turn a deaf ear on us every time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever you have an up-and-coming black act we get the job
and do all the work: passing out fliers in the community, putting
up posters in the restaurants,'' he said. ``But whenever that act
gets to a status where all we have to do is buy an ad on the radio
or newspaper and the concert sells out, we are eliminated. The
white promoters take those acts as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Several defendants, including William Morris, Creative Artists
Agency and SFX, either declined to comment on the suit or did not
return calls.
</P>
<P>
   But Bob Grossweiner, who covers the concert business for the
trade magazine Performance, said that the plaintiffs had a strong
case, pointing to the absence of black booking agencies and the
stranglehold of ``a family of promoters who started out in the late
'60s in the infancy of cross-country touring.''
</P>
<P>
   The pop concert business has always been an intensely
competitive one in which one or two promoters in a city are
responsible for nearly all the major concerts, in part because they
own or make exclusive agreements with concert halls and arenas.
</P>
<P>
   Such practices have come under increased scrutiny lately. This
new lawsuit joins a flurry of antitrust accusations levied at a
rapidly consolidating industry, including a Justice Department
antitrust probe into acquisitions made by SFX, a company that in
two years has spent more than $1 billion acquiring more than half
of the concert promotion business in the United States in addition
to venues in most major cities.
</P>
</TEXT>
