<SLUG> BC-PENELOPE-CRUZ-FILMS-$ADV29-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SPANISH SIREN, HEADING WEST  
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, NOV. 29)
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 By MATT WOLF   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Screen beauties are hardly a novelty, but even within the realm
of celluloid sirens, the Spanish actress Penelope Cruz elicits
unusual adoration from her directors.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's simply gorgeous, he said helplessly,'' the director
Stephen Frears said, well, helplessly, of his decision to cast Ms.
Cruz, 24, in her first U.S. film, ``The Hi-Lo Country.''
</P>
<P>
   The Madrid-born performer plays Billy Crudup's consolation
prize, inasmuch as the woman whom the leading man really wants _ a
kittenish Patricia Arquette _ has chosen his best friend (Woody
Harrelson) instead. (The movie, set in the Southwest in the
aftermath of World War II, opens on Dec. 30.)
</P>
<P>
   ``She decides to live with that pain,'' Ms. Cruz said of her
character Josepha's status as the patient runner-up for Crudup's
heart. ``It's worth it for her to wait. She's a very strong
woman.''
</P>
<P>
   Frears recalled how he chose Ms. Cruz. ``A tape appeared on my
desk. I went and looked at it, and there was Venus.'' As for his
verdict after the New Mexico shoot? ``She's absolutely gorgeous,''
he reiterated. ``And very, very good, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Closer to home, the Spanish filmmaker Fernando Trueba was no
less enthusiastic.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has exploded as a woman, as an actress, as everything,''
said Trueba, who directed Ms. Cruz when she was just 17 (as the
youngest daughter in ``Belle Epoque,'' which won the 1993 Oscar for
Best Foreign Film) and in her most recent film, ``The Girl of Your
Dreams.''
</P>
<P>
   That movie, which opened recently in Spain, gives Ms. Cruz her
largest role to date. She plays an Andalusian actress-singer
displaced to 1938 Berlin who becomes a reluctant plaything of
Hitler's minister of propaganda, Joseph Goebbels.
</P>
<P>
   On screen, Ms. Cruz projects an unblemished self-possession.
Sounding mostly fatigued, Ms. Cruz spoke by telephone from Madrid
during a break from work on the new Pedro Almodovar film, ``All
About My Mother,'' in which she plays a pregnant nun. ( She also
appears briefly as the painfully pregnant mother at the start of
the Almodovar's 1997 film, ``Live Flesh.'')
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a little bit tired; I'm very busy,'' Ms. Cruz said in
halting English. ``I always try to have some months between one
movie and the other. On this occasion I didn't want to say no to
these movies.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Cruz has two more films scheduled to open in the United
States this spring. In one, ``The Man With Rain in His Shoes'' _
the Spanish director Maria Ripoll's quirky romantic comedy set in
contemporary London _ Ms. Cruz dons glasses to play a budding
writer who, once again, is the jilted hero's second-best option.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am 10 minutes in the movie, maybe 15,'' Ms. Cruz said. ``I
did it because the story is very magical; she's a very sweet
character.''
</P>
<P>
   A similar sweetness relieves the lurid self-absorption of ``Open
Your Eyes,'' Alejandro Amenabar's psychological thriller. Ms. Cruz
plays Sofia, girlfriend to the narcissistic Cesar (Eduardo
Noriega), who finds his life _ or, at least, his vanity _ upended
when his face is destroyed in a car crash.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about how bad is the importance of beauty in this
society,'' Ms. Cruz said of the film, ``because it really is, and
that's something sad.''
</P>
<P>
   But what of the actress's own beauty, which may help launch her
on an international career?
</P>
<P>
   ``I can look good, and I can look ugly, if I want,'' she said.
``I don't think I am beautiful. I don't think I am perfect.''
</P>
</TEXT>
