<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHAWS-STAR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHAW'S PARENT TO BUY STAR MARKETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Amid rapid consolidation in US supermarket industry,
Shaw's Supermarkets Inc. confirmed Wednesday that its British
parent, J Sainsbury plc , has reached an agreement to buy Star
Markets Co., a chain of 53 stores.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw's declined further comment on a deal that gives the East
Bridgewater, Mass. chain more size to compete with Stop &AMP; Shop
Cos., New England's biggest supermarket player, but Star put the
price tag for the long-rumored deal at $490 million, including the
assumption of debt. Star Markets is based in Cambridge, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   At first glance, that would seem to be a hefty premium on the
$285 million that Henry Nasella and New York investment firm
Investcorp International paid to buy the much smaller chain of 31
Star stores in 1994. But Nasella pointed out that during the last
four years ``We almost doubled the size of the company.''
</P>
<P>
   Nasella, who began his supermarket career bagging groceries at a
Star in 1963, added that Sainsbury was ``ecstatic to buy Star, and
that's reflected in the purchase price.''
</P>
<P>
   No layoffs are likely at Star stores, said Nasella. He said he
will continue to work for the combined chains in an undefined role
for an unspecified period of time.
</P>
<P>
   The future of about 200 Star headquarters staffers is less
clear. Star's total work force numbers just over 10,000.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw's newly appointed chief executive, Ross McLaren, is
expected to run the combined chains for Sainsbury.
</P>
<P>
   Once the sale is completed sometime early next year, the Star
name could gradually disappear from the local marketplace. The
first Star Market opened in Watertown in 1915.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Star's four Wild Harvest natural food stores, the
acquisition would give Shaw's a missing piece to its geographical
puzzle in New England.
</P>
<P>
   According to company legend, Shaw's heirs feuded in the 1920s,
and to avoid a family food fight, the head of family divided his
empire, giving one son an operation based in Portland, Maine, where
the chain originated in 1860, and the other son was given a
division based in Brockton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   To keep the peace, Boston was declared off &UR;  &LR; limits to the two
squabbling brothers.
</P>
<P>
   Whether true or not, Shaw's had no stores in Boston until
recently and only a handful of its 126 stores are located in the
city's nearest suburbs. Star stores, by contrast, are heavily
concentrated in Eastern Massachusetts within Route 128.
</P>
<P>
   Because there is so little geographical overlap, the acquisition
of Star by J Sainsbury is not expected to raise the same antitrust
concerns that became an issue when Royal Ahold NV of the
Netherlands bought Stop &AMP; Shop for $2.9 billion in 1996. Stop &AMP;
Shop is based i Quincy, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   To win approval of the Stop &AMP; Shop deal, Royal Ahold ultimately
agreed to divest some stores to satisfy critics who argued that the
merger might otherwise stifle competition and stick consumers with
higher food prices.
</P>
<P>
   As supermarket chains merge throughout the country, and Wal-Mart
Stores Inc. takes aim on on the grocery business, food behemoths
are emerging, squeezing the mid-size players such as Shaw's and
Star.
</P>
<P>
   In October, Ohio-based Kroger Co. announced plans to acquire
Fred Meyer in a $13 billion deal that will create the largest
supermarket chain in the country.
</P>
<P>
   With 2,200 stores in 31 states, the combined chain projects
annual sales of $43 billion. Six other chains, including Wal-Mart
and Stop &AMP; Shop parent Royal Ahold, had 1997 sales in the United
States of $19 billion or more. (About a quarter of Ahold's US sales
came from Stop &AMP; Shop.)
</P>
<P>
   By those standards, Shaw's and Star are small. Shaw's had 1997
sales of $2.8 billion, and Star had sales of $1.03 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't need flash cards to see consolidation is happening
in a big way,'' said Craig Faucher, editor of the Griffin Report of
Food Marketing, a trade publication.
</P>
<P>
   As big chains combine, they gain efficiencies and more buying
power with their vendors, and that means the giants can offer lower
grocery prices to consumers than smaller rivals.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, mid-sized chains now face a dilemma. To compete
with the big players, they either have to expand rapidly, often by
acquisition, or they have to put themselves up for sale.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're a mid-sized chain, you really feel under pressure to
either grow or sell,'' Faucher said.
</P>
<P>
   Besides added size and complimentary geography, Shaw's and Star
each bring something to the table for a bigger and better regional
grocery chain.
</P>
<P>
   Taking a European approach, Shaw's is skilled at persuading
customers to by its own store branded goods rather than national
brand names. If a customer buys Shaw's corn flakes instead of
Kellogg's, customers may get lower prices, but Shaw's also enjoys a
higher profit margin. &UR;  &LR; About 40 percent of Shaw's sales are for its
own brands, compared with about 20 percent for most US chains.
</P>
<P>
   Star, meanwhile, has become an expert at operating urban stores
in places other chains stay away from. One Star does business over
the Massachusetts Turnpike, another in a new Cambridge hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Besides dabbling in juice bars and in-store daycare centers and
Starbucks coffee cafes, Star has also expanded into natural foods,
which have a much higher profit margin than typical groceries _ as
much as 10 percent versus 1 or 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The deal may make sense for other reasons. Star has been running
losses of $8 million to $9 million, and allying with J Sainsbury
makes it part of a large food empire.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, J Sainsbury lost a chance to gain control of
a big Maryland-based supermarket chain to Ahold, Stop &AMP; Shop's
parent. Acquiring Star gives J Sainsbury a much needed bigger
presence in the United States at a time when the company has been
having some ups and downs in Britain.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
