<SLUG> BC-BKN-LOCKOUT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBA TALKS STALL AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   No turkey jokes today. And no negotiations this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA and its players may have to hope that they can settle
their five-month lockout with telepathy, because negotiations don't
seem to be working.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, the league announced it would forgo a planned
Saturday bargaining session because the union would not agree to
three pre-conditions. Any momentum gained from last Friday's
marathon session _ and there was some, but not a lot _ has been
stalled and no new talks are scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, NBA players will be home for Thanksgiving, which we
have known for a while, home for Christmas, which we just learned
this week, and possibly home for Martin Luther King Day, Easter,
and Memorial Day, too. The league has not announced a so-called
``drop dead date'' to cancel the season and union chief Billy
Hunter said in a conference call Wednesday that ``the odds are
against'' canceling the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think (a deal) can be achieved. If I didn't, I wouldn't say
that,'' Hunter said.
</P>
<P>
   But Hunter also said that he was not going to come to the table
after agreeing to league-dictated terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is quite apparent that we cannot negotiate against
ourselves or with a gun to our heads,'' he said. Wednesday ``We are
prepared to meet and all issues are up for discussion. But we will
not agree to any set of pre-conditions.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Hunter, he received a fax from NBA deputy
commissioner Russ Granik saying the union would have to accept the
league's position on timing rules, percentages, and the escrow tax
for talks to take place. Hunter referred to the fax as an
``ultimatum.'' He said he called back to say the union would do no
such thing and said that Granik told him there was no reason to
meet Saturday. The league then announced that the session was
canceled.
</P>
<P>
   The timing rule affects teams that sign free agents. The league
wants such a team to be prevented from going over the cap to
re-sign its own players, a device known as the Larry Bird
exception. ``We're not going to see Bird bastardized,'' Hunter
said.
</P>
<P>
   The other two issues relate to the overall percentage of NBA
revenues the union is willing to accept, now believed to be 58
percent. The league blew up the previous agreement because the
number exceeded 51.8 percent, an agreed-upon deal-breaker. The
escrow tax would go into effect if player salaries exceeded
whatever the final percentage figure happens to be.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the major ``breakthroughs'' have come in areas that
address potential overages, but not the figure that would trigger
the overage. That's akin to deciding that you want doors on your
new car, but haven't decided how much you can spend on the vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   Hunter also accused the NBA of playing ``mind games'' with his
constituency and trying to ``weaken our resolve'' by making it seem
a deal might be close. However, commissioner David Stern and Granik
both said after Friday's session that there was still a
considerable divide between the sides.
</P>
<P>
   Granik sees no way that play can occur in 1998, given that there
are no new talks planned and any agreement would likely be followed
by three to four weeks of training camp. NBC, which was not
scheduled to televise a game until Christmas, has lost its
ratings-monster doubleheader that day because of the impasse.
Instead, the network will show, ``It's A Wonderful Life.''
</P>
<P>
   The network does not have another telecast scheduled until Jan.
16, which gives you some idea of how important it considers the
first two months of the schedule to be. And this is from a network
that lost pro football.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
