<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATRIOTS-LUXURY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LITTLE IMMEDIATE INTEREST IN PATRIOTS' LUXURY BOXES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GREGG KRUPA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The use of luxury boxes and other premium seating is a key part
of the financing for the $280 million stadium proposed for the New
England Patriots in Hartford, Conn., but interviews with about a
dozen top companies in the state reveal little immediate interest
in helping the taxpayers in Connecticut foot the bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our overall sports sponsorship has been trimmed back and we
don't pay for luxury boxes,'' said IBM's John Buchholz. ``We looked
at it across the board, and we just decided to do other things for
corporate meetings and functions.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Tenneco said the company is reorganizing and any
such plans are on hold for the long term.
</P>
<P>
   And even some of the companies that stadium proponents assert
will be prime players in purchasing the boxes and seats say they
would prefer to wait and see.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's inappropriate to speculate on how we might
approach this at this point,'' said Fred LaBerge, corporate
spokesman for the insurance firm Aetna, which is located in
Hartford. ``At the same time, when it comes to promoting special
causes around Hartford, we have been in the forefront of providing
support.''
</P>
<P>
   In interviews with 10 of 18 of Connecticut's Fortune 500
companies, and other interviews with an additional group of law
firms and public relations agencies, revealed only one company and
a law firm immediately pledging to buy a luxury box. But both the
the company and the firm are closely tied to the redevelopment of
Hartford, and the stadium is a major part of that. Phoenix Home
Life Mutual, is chaired by Robert Fiondella, a major driving force
behind the stadium plans and the revitalization of Hartford. And
Peter Kelly, a partner in the law firm, Updike, Kelly and Spellacy,
is a former chairman of the state's convention center authority.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to buy a box and split it with another firm,''
Kelly said. ``I think the corporate support will be very
significant. I don't think that there'll be one corporate box empty
in that stadium.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Virtually every company I talked to is considering taking a
box,'' Fiondella said. ``The reaction I've had is that people will
support it.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the Patriots, they are ideally positioned. If they sell
do not sell all of the seats, they still reap a significant profit
from them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the state is very comfortable that the businesses in
the state will get behind this, and that is why the deal is
structured like it is,'' said Jonathan Kraft, Patriots vice
president. ``It was a risk they thought we could manage.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we know nothing about the business community in
Connecticut,'' Kraft said. ``We know about the New England football
fans in general and we know about Boston, and the businesses in our
area. So, we said to them, `You have to make us comfortable.' ''
</P>
<P>
   A variety of sources in sports and business say that for reasons
of geography and a lack of experience in dealing with professional
sports teams, the Connecticut market for luxury boxes and other
preferred seats will be hard to crack.
</P>
<P>
   Some point to the state's only other experience with a major,
professional sports franchise _ the National Hockey League's
Hartford Whalers _ as evidence of a lack of support for such
spending.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say it's going to be a big challenge,'' said Thomas
Gutteridge, dean of the University of Connecticut School of
Business Administration. ``When we lost the NHL franchise, the
Whalers, that was a big part of it, the lack of corporate support.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the state is kind of balkanized,'' Gutteridge said.
``And it is a real challenge to get people in Connecticut to think
of it as Connecticut, as opposed to southwestern Connecticut, or
southeastern Connecticut, or Hartford.''
</P>
<P>
   By any measure, the sale of the high-end seating is a crucial
component of the stadium deal now under review in Hartford.
</P>
<P>
   The state is offering to pay for the entire $350 million stadium
project, which includes infrastructure improvements and parking.
The debt payment is expected to be $25 million per year for 30
years, state officials say. To help finance the deal, the state
expects to collect about $12.2 million in annual revenue from the
operation of the stadium and income taxes on the team at the
beginning of the deal, and more as time goes on.
</P>
<P>
   According to the state, those high-end seats will generate $4.5
million at the beginning of the deal, while the general seating
will result in only $2.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   Dean Pagani, the spokesman for Rowland, said that the state has
banked heavily on businesses picking up the tab for luxury boxes
and premium seats Financing of the guaranteed payment to Kraft is
not included as part of the current plans to finance the $350
million deal. ``It would be an additional cost,'' Pagani said.
</P>
<P>
   But if the state has to pay Kraft for a share those seats _ an
arrangement guaranteed by the memorandum of understanding signed by
Kraft and Roland last week, not only would the revenue projection
have to be slashed _ it could end up costing the state up to $17.5
million a year to pay for the boxes and seats.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, as the financing of the stadium continues over a 30
year period, the state is assuming that the revenue from those
seats will eventually grow to $25 million per year, as more and
more companies spend increasing amounts.
</P>
<P>
   It is clear that without significant support from corporate
Connecticut, the state and the taxpayer will foot the financial
burden for the stadium project _ the only one proposed for the NFL
that includes taxpayers money for the purchase of luxury boxes and
seats.
</P>
<P>
   While some Connecticut officials like Speaker of the House
Thomas Ritter are assuming that the state's guarantee to Kraft on
the high-end seats will never be implemented because businesses
will gobble up the seats, others are less than sure. Indeed,
several observers were unanimous in saying that the very fact that
the guarantee is in the memorandum of understanding between Kraft
and Roland indicates Kraft's concern that the boxes may not sell.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is a real comment on the market that they are
entering into that the deal contains the provision for the state
picking up those tickets,'' said Boston lawyer Lyman G. Bullard
Jr., a nationally known specialist in sports law. ``It clearly
reflects Kraft's concern that Hartford is just not really up to the
task of attracting the corporate support he needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the assumption there is that they're going to have to
go down to Fairfield County, to Giants and Jets country, to attract
the support, and that is going to be a tough sell.''
</P>
<P>
   Other observers say that corporate support for the stadium is so
uncertain in Connecticut that the Boston-area and even Providence,
R.I. must continue to heavily support the team if the revenue
projections are to work out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be an interesting question to see whether Boston firms
support the team if it moves,'' said Hal R. Tovin, director of
marketing for Citizens Financial Group, Inc. ``Citizens has a bank
operation in Connecticut and it is certainly something we will take
a look at.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard A. Higginbotham, president and chief executive officer
of Fleet Bank in Connecticut, said that the Boston-headquartered
bank is aggressive in using sports teams to market the company in
all of it locations, whether it is Boston, New York City or
Hartford.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do have a luxury box and some seasons tickets in
Foxborough,'' Higginbotham said. ``Absolutely, we will be
supportive in Hartford.''
</P>
<P>
   When a number of officials and businessmen involved with with
the stadium proposal are asked about the potential corporate for
support for the stadium, most react with a mixture of instinct,
prognostication and perhaps a little wishfulness. Despite the
state's gung-ho approach to its financing scheme, no one can
identify a specific study or any marketing research that says
companies will pay for the luxury boxes and premium seats. Jonathan
Kraft said that the team has already received a number of calls
about about luxury boxes and premium seating since the announcement
of the proposed deal, and the 10,000-seat waiting list for season
tickets has gown by 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two Boston companies I will not reveal have asked about the
boxes,'' Kraft said. ``It just shows that this really is not moving
the franchise. This is getting a new stadium in our territory.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
