<SLUG> BC-FBN-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAILEY FACES TOUGHEST TEST FROM NO. 1 FAN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Chan Gailey climbs behind the wheel of his car tonight for
the drive home from Texas Stadium after the Cowboys-Vikings
Thanksgiving Day game, he'll steel himself for the worst.
</P>
<P>
   He will, by that time, have gone head to head with one of the
most talented teams in the NFL in the Vikings. He will have met
with his players and, win or lose, faced tough questions from the
media after the game.
</P>
<P>
   But his sternest test will come on the drive home.
</P>
<P>
   Some of us have back-seat drivers.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey lives with a back-seat coach.
</P>
<P>
   Meet Laurie Gailey, Cowboys head coach emeritus.
</P>
<P>
   ``You think you guys give me a hard time,'' Gailey likes to joke
with reporters. ``You're easy compared to my wife.''
</P>
<P>
   Take the Cowboys' 15-penalty performance Sunday against Seattle.
Please.
</P>
<P>
   ``She laid into me about all those penalties,'' Gailey says with
a rueful laugh. ``She didn't even wait for us to get out of the
parking lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Gailey's response: ``Tell me about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Like dutiful husbands everywhere, Gailey bites his tongue and
takes his medicine. After all, the lady with the sharp critique is
also the one who fixes the oyster dressing each Thanksgiving.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love oyster dressing,'' Gailey says, and you can almost see
his mouth watering as he speaks. ``I can't even begin to describe
how good it is.''
</P>
<P>
   If Gailey looks a little plumper on the sidelines today, blame
Laurie. The Gailey family had their Thanksgiving dinner last night
and yes, she prepared her famous oyster dressing, a recipe handed
down from her mother and one you can get in the ``1998 Cowboys'
Wives Cookbook'' that just came out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I must have eaten it the first time at her mother's house,
back when we were dating in 1969 or '70,'' Gailey says, his eyes
rolling at the memory.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looks forward to Thanksgiving because he looks forward to
that all year,'' Laurie says. ``I think it's why he married me.''
</P>
<P>
   Since her mom wasn't available, Laurie was the next best bet to
guarantee the annual appearance of oyster dressing on Chan's
Thanksgiving table.
</P>
<P>
   Along with a great cook and his best friend, Gailey soon
discovered he had married an inveterate football fan, one who very
much enjoyed taking an active part in her husband's world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have an opinion, and I'm just like any other fan out
there,'' Laurie says. ``But when we lose, I'm very careful. I don't
say very much.''
</P>
<P>
   Gailey learned very quickly that Laurie had a discerning eye for
the intricacies of football.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's been doing this for a long time,'' he says. ``She's very
knowledgeable about the game; extremely knowledgeable. She used to
surprise me with some of the things she'd bring up, but I stopped
being surprised a long time ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It kind of got to me at first. `Who are you to be questioning
me?' She just wanted to be involved. We love to needle each other
about things. She just likes to let me know when she understands
when something's not right.''
</P>
<P>
   Their discussions on the drive home have become part of the
repartee that both enjoy.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just laughs most of the time,'' Laurie says. ``He knows
it's coming, and he's a pretty good sport about it. I pick and
choose. I know him well enough to know when to say something and
when not to.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really have my own opinion. I don't just get it from what I
read or what I hear. I'll ask him things like, `What happened when
you called that timeout?' or `What was that play when Ernie caught
that pass on the sideline?' Things like that.''
</P>
<P>
   No, Laurie insists, she didn't help Chan design his offense,
which is almost as famous as her oyster dressing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know a lot about the X's and O's exactly,'' she says.
``And I'm not sure how much he listens to me, really. I think maybe
he probably thinks, `well, if she's saying it, then that's probably
what John Q. Public is saying.' I'm not so sure he knows exactly
what people are saying out there, he's so into his work.''
</P>
<P>
   Gailey listens and smiles a lot, amused and almost always amazed
at his wife's insight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do I get a kick out of it? I'm not sure that's the right
response,'' Gailey says with a chuckle. ``I'm just very
appreciative that I have a wife who cares and is involved and who
wants to win. She can say anything she wants, but let somebody else
say something and she's ready to fight. That's kind of the way it
is with families.''
</P>
<P>
   That's why Gailey will look at tonight's drive home with mixed
emotions. As usual, he knows he'll have to have some darn good
answers to her pointed questions.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, at the end of the drive, with any luck there should
be some of that leftover oyster dressing.
</P>
<P>
   It's a give-and-take relationship that he's happy to have lived
with for 25 years and counting.
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Reeves is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
