<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-25 20:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9975 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THANKSGIVING-COACH-TE     11-25 1565
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THANKSGIVING-COACH-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLLEGE BASEBALL COACH LOST A LEG TO CANCER, BUT FOUND SOMETHING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   At some point today, Butch McBroom, like millions of others
across this country, will bow his head to say thanks.
</P>
<P>
   Like yours, McBroom's prayer will start simply.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks, Lord, for the bountiful food on the table.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks for the love of family and the support of good friends.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks for the great outdoors, the animals and birds, the
forests and the seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks for a career and an avocation that provides so much
satisfaction.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks for life.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks even, for the empty pants leg that flutters where muscle
and sinew once worked in harmony, where blood once flowed.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, thanks even for that which is no longer there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe this happened for a purpose,'' McBroom said, ``and
I'm a better person because of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen years after his left leg was amputated at the hip
because of cancer, McBroom has reached a point where he sometimes
wonders to himself what he would do if wheeler-dealer Satan
suddenly showed up at the door and offered him a trade.
</P>
<P>
   His left leg back for his life as it is now and the person he
has become.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would I make that deal?'' he wondered aloud. ``My life today
to have my leg back? As much as I'd like to have two legs again and
throw these crutches away, I'm not actually sure that I would.''
</P>
<P>
   McBroom, who will begin his 26th season as head baseball coach
at UT-Arlington in January, is sitting on the front porch of a log
cabin buried deep in a forest of oak and mesquite on 175 acres of
prime hunting land, about 80 miles southwest of Fort Worth and 20
miles north of Stephenville in Erath County.
</P>
<P>
   This is McBroom's Xanadu, if you will, his own little piece of
heaven on earth. He can sit on the porch in the early mornings,
sipping his coffee and watch deer feeding in the meadow 50 yards
away.
</P>
<P>
   At dawn last Easter morning, McBroom took his Bible, climbed
aboard a four-wheeler, and drove it to the top of what passes for a
mountain in Texas. From there, he looked across the land and
watched the sun come up as he read passages from the Easter story.
</P>
<P>
   There's a direct line from the leg McBroom lost in 1983 to this
cabin and this land that he loves so much. The $500,000 malpractice
settlement he received after losing his leg in '83 _ the cancer was
originally misdiagnosed _ was what allowed him to afford to buy
this place four years later.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what complicates the deal,'' McBroom said. ``I love
this place so much, I don't know that I'd give it up for
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   But there's more than that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a much better person now than I was then,'' McBroom said
without hesitation. ``I stop and smell the roses. I consider people
where I didn't before. I don't rush through life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really know the power of having Jesus Christ in your life
and what that means. I didn't understand that fully before. I have
taken my handicap and done things that I would not have done had I
had two legs, speaking engagements, things like that. I talk to
kids who are handicapped regularly. I think, I hope, that I've made
a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   No deals with the devil necessary for McBroom. He made his
covenant with a higher power a long time ago. `Bolt of electricity'
Eighteen years ago, it started as a small knot in the back of his
left thigh. Irritating, sure, but no big deal, McBroom thought.
Nothing an athletic, energetic 37-year-old college baseball coach
would let bother him. Besides, the doctor kept telling him it was
nothing to worry about.
</P>
<P>
   It turned out to be a rare, slow-growing, cancerous tumor that
was attached to the lining around the sciatic nerve in his left
hamstring. When McBroom, who grew up in Fort Worth and graduated
first from Carter-Riverside High School and then Baylor University,
first noticed it, it was the size of a raisin. When doctors removed
it surgically three years later, it was the size of Nerf football
and weighed a pound and half.
</P>
<P>
   McBroom went through chemotherapy and radiation treatments but
in June '83, there was reoccurence of the cancer. This time there
was no hesitation by his new doctor at Baylor Hospital in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't ease into it or anything,'' McBroom remembered. ``He
just said flat out, `We're going to have to amputate your leg.' I
got sick. I literally got sick at my stomach and had to lay down.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next two days was like I was in a state of disbelief that
it was really going to happen. I did a lot of praying, a lot of
soul-searching. I just finally said, `Hey, if this means saving my
life, let's go do it.'''
</P>
<P>
   It was one night shortly before the surgery in August when
McBroom had the experience that will stick with him for the rest of
his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was lying in bed, and I was praying, saying `What am I going
to do?' I was praying for God to heal me. And I heard a voice
within me say, `I'm going to heal you of the cancer, but you're
going to lose your leg.' I felt like I'd had a bolt of electricity
go through me from my head to my toes. I knew then I'd never have
to worry about cancer again.
</P>
<P>
   ``From that point on, I focused on what was left and not what
was gone. I made up my mind that whatever I could possibly do, I
was going to keep doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   For the first five days after his leg was amputated, a feverish
McBroom lay in a pool of sweat in his hospital bed, the leg that
was no longer there causing him agonizing pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't prepared for how tough it was going it be,'' McBroom
recalled. ``For five days it felt like my left ankle was being
crushed.''
</P>
<P>
   Five days later a gaunt and haggard McBroom left the hospital 50
pounds lighter. On his way home, he stopped by the UTA baseball
field to talk to his players.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was amazing,'' said John Mocek, who left his job as
athletic department business manager to become McBroom's assistant
coach for the next 14 years. He is now the school's assistant
athletic director in charge of business operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We stopped practice for about 10 minutes and Butch sat on the
outside of the fence, near the dugout, and the guys came out and
milled around him because they couldn't believe it, couldn't
believe that he was there after what he'd been through,'' said
Mocek, who first played for McBroom at Union College in Jackson,
Tenn., and then followed him to UTA. ``He said he was going to do
it, and he was at workouts within another week.''
</P>
<P>
   McBroom wheeling around on his crutches is a familiar sight now
at UTA. He has become an avid skier and, he says, a better golfer
than he was with two legs, ``because I don't try to hit it so
hard.''
</P>
<P>
   He can't do some of the things he always loved _ pitching
batting practice, hitting fungoes, coaching third base _ but it has
always been the interaction with the players that mattered most,
and he still has that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've gone back and helped with his baseball camps after he
lost his leg,'' said former Mavericks infielder Danny Smith, who
graduated in 1981 and manages Applejack's Liquor Store in
Arlington. ``I think it's made him appreciate life more. He knows
he was lucky.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a different outlook on life now. I think it's like guys
who have been through war, or in a prison camp, and they know and
appreciate what they have now more than they ever did before.'' A
love for coaching McBroom is a four-time Southland Conference coach
of the year and had 14 consecutive seasons of 30-plus victories.
Sixty-two of his former players have gone on to play professionally
and 41 have entered the coaching ranks, including his son Chad, who
is the assistant varsity baseball coach at Mineral Wells High
School.
</P>
<P>
   There's a certain pride in a father who sees his son following
in his own footsteps, knowing that perhaps he has passed on the
love of a noble profession like coaching and teaching.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm thankful that God has allowed me to do what I do,''
McBroom said. ``I love coaching. I absolutely love it. I love the
competition, but I think seeing kids go out and become men is what
I enjoy most of all.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you don't see that until they've been away for a
couple of years and then come back. To see them mature and start
families of their own, to see so many of them become great young
men and to hope that maybe I had some influence on that somewhere
along the line, that's important to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Players have changed in the quarter-century since McBroom came
to UTA, and not always for the good.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many kids today refuse to take responsibility for
anything,'' McBroom says. ``Nothing is ever their fault. I wish
parents would understand that loving a kid is not giving him
everything he wants. Loving that kid is giving him direction,
making him get out on his own, letting him fail, because without
failing, he'll never learn how to succeed.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes young people have to fall, like McBroom has fallen,
his crutches flying one way, his body pitching the other.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to take forever,'' McBroom said, ``because I can't
wait to pick myself up and keep going.''
</P>
<P>
   Keep up if you can.
</P>
<P>
   It's another way of proving the old adage. To really know a man,
to know his life, to understand who he really he is, where he's
been and where he's going, it's simple.
</P>
<P>
   Just walk a mile in his shoe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
