<SLUG> BC-OPEC-MEETING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPEC PREPARES PLAN TO PREVENT FURTHER DROP IN OIL PRICES 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By AGIS SALPUKAS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   After a day of meetings, members of the Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries appeared to be nearing an agreement
on what action they will take to try to keep oil prices from
falling further, but a spokesman for the group said Wednesday that
there were still more issues to discuss.
</P>
<P>
   The spokesman, OPEC secretary general Rilwanu Lukman, said
Wednesday in Vienna, where the group is meeting, that ``we are
still discussing everything,'' according to a Bloomberg News
report.
</P>
<P>
   Lukman said the group will reconvene Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   John Lichtblau, the chairman of the Petroleum Industry Research
Foundation, Inc., a research group for the oil industry based in
New York, said OPEC had little choice but to extend the production
cuts it made earlier this year. Those reductions have helped to
keep oil prices from collapsing.
</P>
<P>
   ``What else can they do?,'' he said. ``They already have an
agreement. It's unlikely that they will not extend it.''
</P>
<P>
   There has been dissension among members of the group on what
course to take. Some major producers such as Iran have asked Saudi
Arabia to make deeper cuts. Venezuela has been reluctant to extend
the cuts that the group agreed to last June, which have helped to
keep crude oil prices from dropping below $10 a barrel.
</P>
<P>
   The group agreed this past spring to reduce production by 2.6
million barrels a day, about 3 percent of the daily world supply of
74 million barrels.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts had expected the group to simply extend the current
level of cutbacks but even that could be in doubt due to the
differences among the members.
</P>
<P>
   Dissension among OPEC members was viewed as one reason why crude
oil futures prices fell Wednesday. Crude oil for January delivery
fell 29 cents, or 2.6 percent, to $11.86 a barrel on the New York
Mercantile Exchange, close to the 12-year low of $11.42 reached
June 15. Prices have fallen about 40 percent from from late last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, inventories keep building up in the United States as
the driving season winds down.
</P>
<P>
   The American Petroleum Institute, the industry trade group,
reported Wednesday that a rise in imports of oil, which hit near
record levels last week, was a major reason for the increase in
crude oil inventories.
</P>
<P>
   There are huge forces adding to the extra supplies that are
beyond OPEC's ability to manage, such as the economic slump in
Asia, increasing exports of some non-OPEC producers such as Russia,
and unseasonably mild weather in the United States, which has
reduced demand for heating oil.
</P>
<P>
   Politics is also at work with Venezuela, a major producer,
becoming restive in keeping down its exports due to a coming
election Dec. 6.
</P>
<P>
   Saudi Arabia has been aggressive in building up its exports to
the United States to offset some of the loss of revenue due to
steep drop in the price of oil.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
