<SLUG> BC-MARILYN-MANSON-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARILYN MANSON: NOT EASY TO KEEP BEING OUTRAGEOUS 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By JON PARELES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A big flashing sign spelled out ``DRUGS'' on the
stage of the Hammerstein Ballroom on Monday night. And Marilyn
Manson, wearing a sparkly red outfit with garters, thigh-high boots
and a codpiece-thong combination that left his buttocks bare, did
his parody of a preacher, declaring that God spoke to him and said
that Jesus Christ invented marijuana, cocaine and LSD.
</P>
<P>
   Determined to offend both church and state, Manson was trying
hard to hold on to his role as the corrupter of American youth.
American youth may have other ideas, like treating him as mere
entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Manson is already facing the predicament of anyone who builds a
career on shock value: shocks wear off fast. Two years ago, when he
released ``Antichrist Superstar'' (Nothing/Interscope), he
titillated fans and scandalized fundamentalists by tearing up
Bibles and miming sex acts, while Internet rumors built his aura by
portraying his shows as orgies of raw sex and bloody sacrifices. It
was easy to miss the skepticism _ about stardom, demagoguery and
the hard sell _ that was also part of the songs, and Manson thrived
on the notoriety. But he couldn't top it.
</P>
<P>
   His current album, ``Mechanical Animals'' (Nothing/Interscope),
revives the artifices of glam-rock. As the songs lash out against
dehumanization _ from drug-induced numbness to loveless sex to
media brainwashing _ the music harks back to mid-1970s David Bowie
and to early disco; it's more melodic than Manson's past songs,
relying on tunes as well as howling and brute force.
</P>
<P>
   Onstage, Manson wore glossy costumes and feathered accessories,
not the rags and stage blood of his Antichrist act. He was using
the glittery trappings of show business to decry the hollowness of
a show-business mentality.
</P>
<P>
   But a clean and shiny Manson just isn't as scary as the old one,
even with a band whose guitars generate sternum-vibrating power
chords while the drums summon an earth-shaking stomp. (The band's
drummer, Ginger Fish, had a kit with three big bass drums, although
he only had two feet.) Manson's listeners are used to show business
that pretends to subvert or attack insincerity and materialism;
it's the gimmick behind every other youth-oriented ad campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Compared to his old battle with all authority, distress over
phoniness is a relatively minor concern, and his tales of
alienation and anguish don't play as well as his old hostility.
That's why, although songs like ``I Don't Like the Drugs (but the
Drugs Like Me)'' are antidrug, he acted as if he were flouting
taboos.
</P>
<P>
   The parts of the show that drew the biggest applause were
revived from the Antichrist tour, including a song with Manson
walking around on stilts and long canes, looking like a giant
insect, and a song where he ranted from a pulpit and tore up one
more Bible. He feigned sex with his backup singers; he rubbed his
codpiece. At the end of the show, he pulled down the drum kit while
the other musicians abused their own instruments. And it all seemed
like a rerun _ one more step on the way to Manson's appearance,
circa 2005, as one of the Hollywood Squares.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-25-98 2100EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981125.0370 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-25 21:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9982 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-WOLF-COLUMN-LADN     11-25 0846
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-WOLF-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RILEY SHOULD BE REWARDED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The postseason awards are starting to roll out, and all that
should be said is, expect the expected.
</P>
<P>
   You already know that Texas tailback Ricky Williams will win the
Heisman Trophy. That was guaranteed when he made the cover of
Sports Illustrated.
</P>
<P>
   But it would be nice if some courageous choices were made
instead of just giving awards to whoever has the best record or
stats.
</P>
<P>
   A perfect example is the Pacific-10 Conference's Coach of the
Year award.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA's Bob Toledo will probably win because the Bruins look like
they will make the Fiesta Bowl and could win the national
championship. Or maybe Arizona's Dick Tomey will be rewarded for
leading the Wildcats to a 10-1 record heading into Friday's game
with Arizona State.
</P>
<P>
   But in terms of pure coaching, the winner should be Oregon
State's Mike Riley.
</P>
<P>
   Riley has taken over the worst program in the conference and led
the Beavers to their best record (5-6) since 1971. He brought them
within a whisker of a bowl bid and defeated archrival Oregon for
only the fourth time in the past 24 years.
</P>
<P>
   With a walk-on quarterback, Riley came within one point of
defeating Washington (35-34) and Cal (20-19), and took UCLA to the
wire (41-34).
</P>
<P>
   Heaven forbid that the coaches will get together on their
conference call and do anything but the predictable. The coaching
award will probably be rubber-stamped so fast, Riley's name won't
even be mentioned.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, the coaches won't spend too much time worrying about
themselves if they're arguing about who the first-team quarterback
should be.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA's Cade McNown, who just won the Unitas Award, has led the
Bruins to a perfect 10-0 mark. He's thrown for 2,617 yards, with 18
touchdowns and 10 interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   Will it be enough to keep Oregon's Akili Smith on the second
team? Smith has thrown for 3,307 yards, with 30 touchdowns and
seven interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   McNown's efficiency rating 146.3. Smith's is 170.4. McNown is
probably the toughest quarterback in the nation, and the best at
pulling out a late victory.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the coaches have one tough decision to make, after all.
</P>
<P>
   Out of control: Some of the thousands of fans who rushed
Mississippi State's field got unruly after the Bulldogs upset
Arkansas. One man jumped on the back of Hogs guard Russ Brown. The
man was thrown off and came at Brown again. Brown, who bench
presses more than 500 pounds, drilled him in the face and that
settled the matter.
</P>
<P>
   Security personnel who witnessed the incident said Brown acted
reasonably and faced no disciplinary action from Arkansas coach
Houston Nutt.
</P>
<P>
   Worth the wait: Minnesota's fifth-year seniors never had carried
a trophy off the field, until Saturday's 49-7 romp over Iowa. Until
then, those seniors had lost every time the Gophers played for the
Little Brown Jug (Michigan), Paul Bunyan's Axe (Wisconsin) or Floyd
of Rosedale (Iowa), which is actually a pig, and apparently weighs
close to the real thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``That pig is heavy,'' Gophers fifth-year senior linebacker Parc
Williams said. ``My shoulder was starting to get tired.''
</P>
<P>
   Off the hook: If any bowl begged for the worst _ and was granted
its wish _ involving a local team, it was the San Diego-based
Holiday Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Had San Diego State qualified for the WAC title game, then won
it, Holiday officials could have had to choose between the Aztecs
and Nebraska to play opposite a Pac-10 team in the Dec.30 game.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would definitely (have been) a no-win situation for us,''
John Reid, the game's executive director said. ``There's no way we
(could have) made everyone happy with that one.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cornhuskers have already promised a contingent that could
reach 30,000 if invited to San Diego. The key, besides a better TV
rating, is the new money that would be poured into the economy from
those visiting Huskers fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be huge,'' Reid said. ``From the image standpoint to
the hotel rooms... everything would be phenomenal.''
</P>
<P>
   Nebraska took 33,000 to its nonconference game at Cal this
season.
</P>
<P>
   No answers: Penn State was outscored 79-12 in its three most
important games of the season, conferences losses at Ohio State,
Michigan and Wisconsin, all of which finished in a three-way tie
for the Big Ten title.
</P>
<P>
   In their last five conference defeats last season and this
season, the Nittany Lions have been clobbered by a 162-34 margin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know where our team is,'' coach Joe Paterno said. ``I
don't know whether we just played three teams that played so well
or are so much better than we are.... I wish I had the answers, but
I don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemson candidates: The short list at Clemson reportedly
includes Tulane's Tommy Bowden, Virginia Tech's Frank Beamer,
Mississippi's Tommy Tuberville and Miami's Butch Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Over at South Carolina, Lou Holtz has emerged as the top
candidate, thanks to his tight relationship with athletic director
Mike McGee. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
