<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-25 21:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9983 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-SKUBE29-COX     11-25 0963
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-SKUBE29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EMBARGOED UNTIL NOVEMBER 29
 &HT;    Unseen hands can be writer's guardian angel or a usurping
nightmare
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In literature, even more than in journalism, the editor's hand
is unseen and unsuspected. Browsers in the bookstore look for
labels like anyone else. The label is the author's name. The book
that says ``By John Irving'' has a better chance of being picked
up, opened for inspection and eventually bought than the book that
says ``By Irving Johnson.'' Brand names sell, whether it's books or
beans.
</P>
<P>
   But the name on a book also, of course, implies things personal.
Immersed in a novel, readers assume _ not always consciously _ that
the words and the story are the author's. (What else does it mean
to say ``By John Irving''?) It is not an unreasonable assumption.
Editors, even when their existence is acknowledged, are
afterthoughts. Most readers, even if they've heard of Maxwell
Perkins, couldn't say what editors do, only that they're somehow
involved. But it doesn't matter; it's the author that counts.
</P>
<P>
   One would think so, and yet the strange relationship between the
late Raymond Carver and Gordon Lish, as D.T. Max wrote recently in
The New York Times Magazine, raises issues that could almost be
called truth-in-labeling. At the least, it leads one to wonder how
much of a book was Carver and how much was Lish.
</P>
<P>
   One byline, two voices
</P>
<P>
   No one knew this better than Carver, who died in 1988. Grateful
at first for Lish's editorial experience, he later resented his
editor's intrusive hand _ much as Thomas Wolfe broke with Perkins
because he was hurt that people said he was only a volcano of words
whose work Perkins funneled into a novel. But where Perkins served
as a midwife, Lish did something very different. He not only cut
words and passages, but did wholesale rewriting. In Carver's
short-story collection ``What We Talk About When We Talk About
Love,'' for example, Lish rewrote 10 of the 13 endings.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the spare, ``minimalist'' prose that made Carver an
avant-garde writer of the late '70s and early '80s _ and
establishment fiction today _ was as much Lish's doing as Carver's.
But no one knew it at the time _ only Lish and Carver, and then
Carver's widow, the poet Tess Gallagher, and a small circle of
literary friends in whom he confided his misgivings. Perhaps only a
writer knows how essential stylistic control can be, but also how
the desire to be published, to see one's words in print, can tempt
one to bargain with the devil.
</P>
<P>
   Seven years ago, Lish's papers were sold to the Lilly Library at
Indiana University, enabling scholars and journalists such as Max
to see the extent to which Carver's reputation rested on the
handiwork of an editor whose own fiction sold poorly. Reading
Lish's fiction, Max writes, was like ``looking at the gears of a
clock that's missing a face.'' It was sterile, cold, artificial.
</P>
<P>
   Carver, whatever his deficiencies, was none of those things. But
_ like many fiction writers today _ he almost certainly needed an
editor who was more than a midwife; he needed someone who could
help him write English prose. ``Lish,'' D.T. Max writes, ``was
constantly on guard against what he saw as Carver's creeping
sentimentality. In the original manuscripts, Carver's characters
talk about their feelings. They talk about regrets. When they do
bad things, they cry. When Lish got hold of Carver, they stopped
crying. They stopped feeling. Lish loved deadpan last lines, and he
freely wrote them in.''
</P>
<P>
   `Bullying and competitive' changes
</P>
<P>
   More often than not, Max thinks, Lish's revisions were for the
better: ``His additions gave the stories new dimensions, bringing
out moments that I was sure Carver must have loved to see.'' It was
other changes _ ``bullying and competitive'' _ that were troubling.
``Lish,'' Max writes, ``was redirecting Carver's vision at the
service of his own fictional goals. The act felt parasitic.'' Lish
saw himself as Carver's ventriloquist. ``I could not believe no one
had stumbled onto what was going on,'' he told Max.
</P>
<P>
   Unseen hands have been suspected of holding the pen before, of
course. People have speculated _ with no evidence _ that Harper
Lee's childhood friend Truman Capote was the real author of ``To
Kill a Mockingbird.'' But here, in the archives of the Lilly
Library, was a case where two hands were clearly visible.
</P>
<P>
   When Carver broke with Lish, the rupture was never healed, and
Lish, now retired, told Max that while he doesn't enjoy talking
about ``the Carver period,'' he was bitter over the betrayal by
``this mediocrity'' he claims to have made a celebrity.
</P>
<P>
   For Carver's friends and his widow, Lish's words _ and his
papers at the Lilly Library _ are less an embarrassment than a
diminution of a reputation they believe was rightfully Carver's.
His later work, published after Lish was out of the picture, shows
a fuller, more developed voice. But their loyalty, as Max writes,
``goes deeper than his work. Born in the rural Northwest, Carver
was the son of an alcoholic sawmill worker and a waitress. He first
learned to write through a correspondence course.'' He wrote about
the working poor. Before his death from lung cancer at age 50, he
had known poverty and had struggled with his own alcoholism. ``His
life,'' as Max writes, ``inspired faith, not skepticism.''
</P>
<P>
   Writing, as the cliche goes, is always an act of faith, and any
writer is forever appreciative of the guardian angel he calls his
editor. But it is finally the words that count most, and the
knowledge that they are his and not someone else's.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  E-mail: mskube(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
