A9984 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COSMETICS-MEN-COX     11-25 0473
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COSMETICS-MEN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EMBARGOED UNTIL NOVEMBER 29
 &HT;    Line aims to conceal men's fear of makeup
 &HT;    By A. Scott Walton
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   No one questions the age-old male practice of smearing
greasepaint over the face for camouflage while hunting or warring.
</P>
<P>
   So why should anyone question if a man wears Camo to conceal
blemishes while he hunts for a new job or does battle in a
courtroom?
</P>
<P>
   That's what Nashville-based makeup artist Michele Probst says in
defense of her year-old line of flaw-fixing facial products for
men. Probst's Menaji brand Camo concealer, 911 eye gel, lip balm,
moisturizer, masque and skin toner grew out of her experience
making up the faces of men such as Vice President Al Gore, Dallas
Cowboys quarterback Troy Aikman and world boxing champion Evander
Holyfield for their public and television appearances.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started getting requests for little cosmetic kits my clients
could keep with them and use when I wasn't around,'' Probst said.
Politicians and television announcers routinely wear makeup, she
said, and it's only a matter of time before cosmetics catch on
among men in other professions as well.
</P>
<P>
   Tired eyes, sagging skin, dry lips and blemishes can all detract
from the impression a man makes on the people he works with. By now
it's a well-known fact that more men are resorting to cosmetic
surgery to make them appear more youthful and attractive as they
advance in age and their careers.
</P>
<P>
   Men aren't immune to vain tendencies. But they're generally not
comfortable with the notion of entering that female-dominated
domain of cosmetic use either.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't use the `M' word (makeup) because we know it puts
lots of men off,'' Probst said. To distinguish her ``camouflage''
products from makeup, she sells Menaji mainly in specialty shops
such as Bachrach menswear store at Cumberland Mall in Atlanta. And
unlike makeup, which embellishes the eyes and lips and cheekbones,
Menaji products were formulated to blend in invisibly against the
skin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Half the battle is getting the products into a man's
bathroom,'' Probst said. ``Once they see you can't see the products
on, they're more confident about using them.''
</P>
<P>
   The products range in price from $12 for the lip balm to $30 for
the eye gel. That may sound pricey, but Probst contends that it's
more the fear of being seen buying cosmetics than the cost that
makes men reluctant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fifty percent of our sales at retail are women buying for the
men in their lives. And another large percentage of our sales _ to
men _ are made over the Internet because of the anonymity it
provides.''
</P>
<P>
   For more information about Menaji, call 1-800-551-5067 or check
out the Web site at http://www.menaji.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
