-- Nancy Clarke, the White House head florist, keeps fresh flowers
in practically every room while being mindful not to aggravate
President's Clinton's. Overseeing a staff of four full-time
designers in the basement flower shop below the North Portico,
Clarke has accommodated floral tastes of first ladies since Nancy
Reagan hired her in 1981. (Rick McKay/Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) WASHINGTON -- Nov. 25, 1998 -- WHITE-HOUSE-2-COX, 11-25
-- White House pastry chef Roland Mesnier. ``Sometimes, after 18
years, it's hard to come up with ideas,'' says Mesnier who cooks in
a tiny kitchen jammed between the state floor and the family
quarters. Mesnier has created pastries in kitchens in Paris, London
and Bermuda and was cooking at the Greenbrier in Virginia in 1980
when Rosalynn Carter hired him for the White House. (Rick McKay/Cox
News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) WASHINGTON -- Nov. 25, 1998 -- WHITE-HOUSE-1-COX, 11-25
-- White House pastry chef Roland Mesnier watches as his longtime
assistant, Franette McCulloch removes a raspberry and chocolate
cake from its mold. Cooking separately in a tiny kitchen jammed
between the state floor and the family quarters is Mesnier's theme
desserts have become the sweet stuff of legend. (Rick McKay/Cox
News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) CHANGSHA, China -- Nov. 25, 1998 -- CHINA-BEETLE-COX,
11-25 -- Wood for packing cases awaits assembly at the Changsha
Pump Works in Southern China. Under a soon-to-be enforced American
regulation, wood packing like this will have to undergo expensive
treatment to kill the pernicious Asian long-horned beetle before it
can enter the United States. This factory is setting up a special
workshop to treat all wood bound for America. (Joseph P.
Albright/Cox News Service)
</P>
