 MCI Customers Say They Were Overcharged  &HT;       
 By Deborah Solomon 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Some customers of MCI WorldCom have filed two lawsuits against the
telecommunications giant, charging that it unfairly overcharged
subscribers for long-distance calls.
</P>
<P>
   Two class-action suits were filed in the wake of a Federal
Communications Commission decision this month ordering MCI WorldCom
to stop charging its highest rates to certain customers.
</P>
<P>
   The telecommunications company had been charging some
long-distance customers 38 cents per minute with a $2.49 surcharge
for domestic calls.
</P>
<P>
   Those rates, among the highest in the industry, were applied to
customers who had signed up with MCI, but were dropped from MCI's
discount calling plans because they didn't pay their bills within
90 days. Instead of just cutting off service to customers who don't
pay their bills, MCI continued to provide service, but at a higher
per-minute rate.
</P>
<P>
   The FCC ruled that practice was ``inherently confusing and
therefore, unreasonable'' and ordered MCI to stop. It also noted
that MCI may have been charging the higher rates to some customers
whose bills were in good standing.
</P>
<P>
   In a filing with the FCC, MCI said only about 1 percent of its
customers were affected, but two class-action lawsuits filed this
week say the number is much higher.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Girard, a San Francisco attorney, said hundreds of
thousands of MCI customers were charged the higher rates and should
get a refund. He filed a lawsuit in U.S. District Court in
Washington, D.C., seeking reimbursements for any MCI customer
affected by the rates, known in the industry as ``casual calling''
rates.
</P>
<P>
   Another law firm in Pensacola, Fla., has also filed a similar
suit seeking reimbursements for MCI customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that MCI has been applying the casual calling rates
to individuals who were not past due in their bills and they've
applied that in circumstances that have nothing to do with the
fault of the user,'' Girard said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It remains to be seen whether it was accidental or intentional
but we think customers are entitled to a refund.''
</P>
<P>
   Girard said MCI customers can determine if they were affected by
checking their bills for a surcharge.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Papantonio, an attorney in Florida, said he believes 5
percent of MCI's customers were charged the higher rates.
Papantonio said MCI probably owes customers several hundred
thousand dollars in reimbursements.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the affected customers included people who had moved to
another address and assumed they were still getting their old MCI
rate. Others were customers who had asked to be switched to a
different long-distance carrier, but whose requests were never put
through. In the interim, they were inadvertently dropped from the
subscriber list and charged the higher rate.
</P>
<P>
   The FCC did not fine or punish MCI, but said it would keep a
close watch on the company and could take ``remedial action'' in
the future.
</P>
<P>
   After the decision was issued, MCI said it would drop nonpaying
customers, rather than providing them with the long-distance
service at higher rates. The company did not return calls seeking
comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
