<SLUG> BC-COMPARE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Shopping the E-Mall  &HT;       
 By Jamie Beckett 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Frustration, traffic jams, confusing pricing, no sales help. It's
not the mall _ it's the Web.
</P>
<P>
   With thousands of Web stores selling millions of items, finding
what you want online can be a chore. Enter the comparison-shopping
sites, which search other online shopping sites and promise to
ferret out the best deals. Once they scout out a product, most of
the comparison sites direct you to purchase it directly from the
e-retailer.
</P>
<P>
   But after a few days of trying to shop these sites, the mall is
looking more attractive.
</P>
<P>
   Comparison shopping on the Web can locate bargains. But too
often, the searches are clumsy, inaccurate or incomplete. All of
the sites omitted small online retailers. If you know what you
want, the Web is a great marketplace and the comparison sites can
provide a general idea of where to get it and what you might pay.
But if you don't, you'd better do your homework first.
</P>
<P>
   The Chronicle made a shopping list of items it hoped to buy on
the Web _ a Holiday Barbie, a Sony Digital Video Disc player, a
Black &AMP; Decker cordless drill, a copy of Tom Wolfe's new novel and
a pair of Nike Air Jordan athletic shoes. Then, we put five of the
comparison-shopping sites to work: Yahoo Shopping
 &LR; (shopping.yahoo.com &LR; ), Excite Product Finder  &LR; (jango.excite.com), &LR; 
Amazon.com's Junglee  &LR; (www.junglee.com), &LR;  mySimon
 &LR; (www.mysimon.com &LR; ) and bottomdollar  &LR; (www.bottomdollar.com). &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, we weren't counting on the shopping ``bots'' _ so
called because most act like electronic robots, going out to the
Web to find, retrieve and deliver information _ to do our holiday
shopping. Only two items _ the doll and the book _ were easy to
find. As for the DVD player, the drill and the shoes, we'd have had
better luck in the stores.
</P>
<P>
   We started with the Barbie, this year's version of the glittery
Yuletide doll. Excite's shopping engine found the largest number of
Barbies _ eight _ and what appeared to be the best price, $19.99
from FAO Schwarz. But the apparent bargain turned out not to be.
Besides being the 1997 Holiday edition, the sale Barbie was out of
stock.
</P>
<P>
   The second-best price, $29.97, came from Wal-Mart online, a site
located by Excite, mySimon and bottomdollar. Junglee, which only
searches merchants that pay to be listed, omitted Wal-Mart and
counted eToys' $32.99 Holiday Barbie as its best deal.
</P>
<P>
   Although we thought we'd done a fairly straightforward search,
some of what came back puzzled us. The mySimon bot inexplicably
retrieved three Teddy Bear listings along with the Barbies.
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo, which first searches affiliated merchants before
expanding to the Web, initially located only Barbies sold by FAO
Schwarz and Toysid, both for over $40.
</P>
<P>
   When the search was extended to the entire Web, Yahoo found,
among other things, Shrimp on the Barbie, a Wonder Bra called Miss
Barbie, a Holiday Ham and a Pine Cone Holiday Tin. But not one
Holiday Barbie.
</P>
<P>
   The second item on our list was the Digital Video Disc player,
which promises better sound and picture quality than a VCR. This
one was tough because we didn't really know what we should look for
in a DVD player and had no salespeople to assist us.
</P>
<P>
   For the purposes of the story, we decided on Sony's DVP-S500D, a
midlevel DVD player. Once again, Excite gave us the largest number
of listings, retrieving two of that model. But the low-price leader
was bottomdollar, which found one for $399 from J&AMP;R Music World _
$100 cheaper than the best price of the other sites. Yahoo found
one for $539.95 from Tek Gallery. Junglee only sent us to
Crutchfield's Web site, which provided specs on the equipment but
required you to call an 800 number for the price.
</P>
<P>
   Next up, the Black &AMP; Decker cordless drill. We didn't have a
model in mind, which was a good thing because only one of the
shopping engines, Yahoo, could find any cordless drills by Black &AMP;
Decker, and that was on its search of the entire Web.
</P>
<P>
   We decided to give our shopping sites an easy one and took a
look for a hardcover edition of Tom Wolfe's new novel, ``A Man in
Full.'' Four of the sites found it easily. But bottomdollar snagged
the best deal, landing a copy for $14.48 from shopping.com.
</P>
<P>
   Excite doesn't list books because it has a marketing agreement
with Amazon.com. After paying millions to be Excite's exclusive
bookseller, Amazon.com didn't like the idea of being stacked up
against competitors. Elsewhere on its site, Excite directs
book-buyers to Amazon.com and only Amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   But the book search also netted a few surprises. According to
the sites, we could spend up to $396 for the very same book if we
were so inclined. We were not able to learn if this would buy us a
diamond-encrusted edition or if it would ensure that the author
gave a personal reading of the novel at our house.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the Nikes. A cinch, or so we thought. But only Yahoo
could find a way to buy the hot Air Jordans online, and that was
after we did a Web search. Yahoo's own shopping site did not
include it. Three other sites _ Excite, bottomdollar and mySimon _
don't list shoes.
</P>
<P>
   But Junglee really puzzled us. When we searched for Nike under
``shoes,'' it retrieved a list that included shorts and caps _ but
no shoes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
