<SLUG> BC-MONTGOMERY-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Montgomery Promotions Designed to Halt Defections  &HT;       
 By Sam Zuckerman 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
The recent executive shakeup at NationsBanc Montgomery Securities
is a gambit to build a core of loyalists at an investment bank
that's been racked by high-level defections, people close to the
firm said.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, the San Francisco firm unveiled a sweeping
reorganization of its sales, trading and research operations.
</P>
<P>
   Montgomery created a new supermanager position, director of
equities, and tapped Kent Logan, its longtime sales chief, to fill
it. In the new postion, Logan, 54, supervises sales, trading and
research.
</P>
<P>
   The firm also elevated several rising stars, most notably Scott
Kovalik who was promoted from chief Nasdaq stock trader to director
of trading. Logan's deputy, Craig Johnson, 44, rose to head of
sales.
</P>
<P>
   The previous head trader, 51-year-old Robert Kahan, resigned to
make way for Kovalik, 34. Jim McMahon, head of sales trading, also
left the firm.
</P>
<P>
   By promoting several key players, Montgomery's new chief
executive Lewis Coleman created a team of managers motivated to
stay, said insiders and investment banking rivals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're providing opportunities for younger, rising corporate
managers,'' Logan said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Shoring up management is critical at Montgomery following a
demoralizing conflict between the firm's owner, North Carolina's
BankAmerica Corp., and its founder and former chief executive,
Thomas Weisel.
</P>
<P>
   Weisel quit Montgomery in September after a dispute with
BankAmerica over control of the junk-bond business. About half a
dozen senior managers, including technology investment banking
chief Sanford Miller, followed him out the door.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of Weisel's departure, rival firms said they were
planning to poach top Montgomery staff members. Montgomery insiders
said dozens of managers and employees could jump ship early next
year after 1998 bonuses are paid.
</P>
<P>
   Logan's promotion cemented his loyalty to Montgomery. ``I intend
to end my career here,'' the new director of equities said.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, the rise to head trader could keep Kovalik on board.
Praised by rival investment bankers for his unusual combination of
stock-trading skill and management acumen, Kovalik was considered a
prime recruitment target.
</P>
<P>
   Logan played down the notion that Montgomery's reorganization
was aimed at stanching defections.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would draw the analogy to a Silicon Valley company,'' he
said. ``We're moving from an entrepreneurial culture ... to the
next level.''
</P>
<P>
   Logan said the new structure, with an additional layer of
management, is designed to support ``a major buildup'' as the firm
gears up to do business with customers of its parent bank in
addition to its traditional clients among smaller, fast-growing
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Montgomery is shooting to double its revenue in the next three
years and move up from its current rank as the nations's
ninth-largest investment bank to one of the top five, Logan said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
