<SLUG> BC-COMPSIDE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 How Online Comparison Sites Work  &HT;       
 By Jamie Beckett 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Online shopping was a novelty last holiday season. This year, it's
a phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   Web shoppers are projected to spend $2.3 billion this holiday
season, twice what they did a year ago. That's a whole lot of mouse
clicks, but the dollars are still puny compared with traditional
retailing, where shoppers are expected to part with some $3 billion
every day between now and Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   Looking for a way to shift the balance a little, Internet
retailers and others are offering something you can't get at the
mall without wearing out your shoe leather _ comparison shopping
Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   The comparison sites work much like the search engines most Web
surfers already use, but in this case, they scan the Web or a
database for the best deal. Shoppers can search for a specific item
and, depending on which site they're using, specify price,
manufacturer and other particulars. Because they promise to add
both traffic and revenues, major Web players are clamoring to add
comparison shopping sites.
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo rolled out its version last week. In the past year,
Internet gateways Excite and Infoseek, online bookseller Amazon.com
and online search-engine developer Inktomi bought companies that
offer comparison shopping technology. Excite and Amazon.com's sites
are up; Infoseek's and Inktomi's are being developed.
</P>
<P>
   For Internet shoppers, the comparison sites don't always
deliver. But for the Internet gateways, or portals, such as Yahoo,
Excite and Infoseek, they can be a way to turn Web surfers into Web
spenders.
</P>
<P>
   ``The portals know how to build traffic. Now they need to figure
out a way to make money off that traffic,'' said Julia Pickar,
industry analyst for Zona Research in Redwood City.
</P>
<P>
   One way is e-commerce. Most sites collect a fee every time they
direct a sale to a merchant, usually a small percentage of the
purchase price.
</P>
<P>
   For the merchants, the sites are a way to win new customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the merchant's standpoint, it's very efficient,'' said
Jeff Mallett, chief operating officer at Yahoo. ``When they
(comparison shoppers) get there, they're ready to buy.''
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, the sites can put smaller online e-retailers on
the same footing as the giants.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you search books, a Powell's Books is listed on the same
page as its biggest competitors but at a very low cost. Yet they
spend only a fraction of what Amazon.com does on advertising,''
said Nicole Vanderbilt, senior analyst at Jupiter Communications in
New York.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-25-98 2113EST &QL; 
