<SLUG> BC-HONDURAS-AID-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STADIUM BECOMES AN ARENA OF BASIC HUMAN NEEDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY SANCHEZ  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN PEDRO SULA, Honduras _ On his first day in the world, the
infant boy snuggles closer to his mother, Jessica Marina Garcia, on
the metal cot they share. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   They have just returned from the hospital to their ``home'' _ a
plot of concrete under the stands of Estadio Olimpico on the
outskirts of town. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the stadium was the site of the Central American
Games. Now it's a haven for the Garcias and 502 other families who
lost everything to Hurricane Mitch. They are among the estimated 2
million left homeless in Honduras. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But some schedules even a hurricane can't disrupt: Children must
be fed, bathed and clothed. And babies will be born. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So daily routines in the shelters largely revolve around the
needs of children. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The hospital where Garcia delivered this child _ her firstborn _
supplied her with one outfit for the baby: yellow knit booties, a
matching cap and a shirt that snaps in front. She has one cloth
diaper. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In addition to settling on a name for their son, now she and her
husband must figure out how to provide the necessities for their
infant. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At least they already had staked out a prime spot at the
stadium. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Garcias' temporary home is about the size of an average
American bathroom, near an area where vendors used to sell soft
drinks and snacks to soccer and track fans. The walls are four
sheets; the roof, a blanket. The only building materials here are
those that can be tied together. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A row of tarps where more people live lines the edge of the
parking lot. Imagine Arrowhead Stadium with families living under
makeshift tents encircling the entire outside rim. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some families managed to save a few hens and chicks from the
flooding. The birds run around the stadium, pecking for food in the
gravel. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Other hurricane survivors were lucky enough to haul out boxes of
clothes, furniture, soiled mattresses, a few photos or perhaps a
radio. Those with nothing sleep on the concrete. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Grids of rope and wire cross the stadium, forming clotheslines
for the people. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Children outnumber adults at least 3 to 1. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In one area, a woman struggles to sweep up dead flies as her
baby screams at her ankles. She keeps sweeping, letting the baby
wail. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For a minute, she seems to be pondering her dilemma. Which takes
precedence? Stopping to pick up the child, or sweeping away the
dead bugs before her child finds them? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   She picks up the baby. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, naked toddlers escape from their mothers as the mothers
try to bathe them with bowls of water carried from sinks in the
stadium bathrooms. Babies throw temper tantrums under the concrete
steps of the stadium. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But the children are helpful too. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A common sight is children hauling plastic buckets of water from
the 2,500-liter tanks in the parking lot. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And a brigade of youngsters with brooms attacks the concrete
every Sunday after the fire department comes to spray the area with
water. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I lost everything, my home, my bed,'' said Maria Suyapa Lopez,
whose third grandchild was born in a shelter Friday. ``But the most
important thing is your children, and as you can see, everyone here
is safe and healthy.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Making sure things stay that way is the crusade of Leonarda
Fernandez de Castellanos. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fernandez, a nurse, oversees the stadium shelter as part of her
job with the city's relief agency. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``/{Buenas dias/},'' she greets the families, as she takes the
first of her twice-daily walks around the stadium. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The smell of beans and bananas frying on kerosene stoves fills
the air. Other people have built stoves with bricks for a base,
wood for fire and a metal trash can lid for a griddle. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Wash your hands, wash your face,'' Fernandez yells, after
pointing out some standing water and trash she wants removed. ``The
dirt brings flies and disease.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fernandez is also in charge of distributing rations. Every 10
days, each family gets 30 pounds of rice, beans and corn. They also
receive flour, oil and sometimes milk. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Teresa Jesus Castaneda, it is not enough. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   She has forgotten how long she has been at the stadium, she
says. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know, maybe about a month,'' she says. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Her neighborhood, Asentamientos Humanos, flooded in the
hurricane. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Castaneda has 12 children. The youngest, 5-month-old Brian Jose
Benitez, is asleep in a hammock, giving her a welcome break. He has
been sick with vomiting and diarrhea. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The bottle tucked under the baby's arm holds the last of the
powdered milk. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It is so hard, trying to take care of, keep track of, so many
children here,'' she says. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Her husband is out trying to buy vegetables to resell for a
profit. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Like many in the stadium, Castaneda is living beside the family
who were their neighbors before the flood. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Older children from both families take turns watching the
littlest ones while the mothers and fathers leave to find work in
town. The government has offered extra food to people who will
sweep the streets of debris from the flooding. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Relief workers are trying to consolidate the 260 shelters in the
San Pedro Sula area. The stadium will be used for another two
months, Fernandez estimates. Maybe longer, depending on how long it
takes to relocate everyone. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Edelmira Quiroz arrived at the stadium from another shelter on
Sunday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Most families are brought in military trucks. But Quiroz came in
a horse-drawn cart, with possessions from her family and two others
piled inside. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   She doesn't complain, but neither can she forget. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``When we finally move into a new house, we will remember this
misery,'' Quiroz said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
