<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA FINDS HIDDEN TREASURE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico _ He was not a McDonald's All-American. He
did not criticize Kansas coach Roy Williams' substitution pattern.
He was not a lauded foreign player who came to America for prep
school, then thrilled college and pro scouts.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Barnes was the lowest-rated of UCLA's recruits _ the
``throw in'' _ but he's been the biggest surprise of the early
season and may start today when UCLA faces San Francisco in the
first of three games in the Puerto Rico Shootout.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Barnes doesn't start, he'll be one of the first players
off the bench. Such is the impression he's made on the coaches, the
impact he's made on the court and the recovery he's made from
offseason foot surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``People saw him as a throw-in,'' Bruins coach Steve Lavin said.
``They'd say, `You also got that football player from Sacramento.
What's his name?'
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, he's been a surprise, but only in terms of how quickly
he's developed. We knew he was good, we just thought it would take
him longer to get to this point.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnes started and played four positions in the season opener
against Santa Clara, scoring nine points and grabbing eight
rebounds in 28 minutes. At 6-foot-8, he's UCLA's most versatile
player _ an updated version of J.R. Henderson _ and one of its most
resourceful. He often does his best work without the ball, content
to rebound, defend and make his offensive-minded teammates look
good.
</P>
<P>
   But surprised? No, he's not surprised.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew how good I was, but I wasn't able to show it in high
school,'' he said. ``Yeah, I have something to prove, being the
least-talked about of the freshmen. But I know if I was healthy, I
would have made the McDonald's (All Star) game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins first noticed Barnes in April 1997, at an all-star
game at the end of his junior season. Like Henderson, he understood
not just his role but everyone else's. And he fit the part
physically. UCLA wanted a big-wing recruit to replace 6-6 Charles
O'Bannon and 6-5 Toby Bailey.
</P>
<P>
   But Barnes had sprained the big toe on his left foot while
playing football for Del Campo High the previous fall, and the more
he played, the worse it got. His super spring gave way to a timid
and ineffective summer, and his rating dropped.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a top-20 talent who played himself into a top-50 or
top-100 player,'' said UCLA assistant Jim Saia, who recruited
Barnes. ``He didn't have a good summer. He wasn't the same player I
had seen in April, but we knew why, and we stuck with him.''
</P>
<P>
   The big schools didn't know why, didn't ask, and they stayed
away _ leaving the recruitment to Arizona, UCLA and Cal. Saia saw
Barnes again last September at a tournament at Long Beach City
College, and was so impressed he returned to Westwood and
immediately told Lavin, ``He have got to sign this kid.''
</P>
<P>
   A longtime fan, Barnes committed during UCLA's in-home visit.
Grateful for the chance and aware of his sagging reputation, he
said to Lavin and Saia: ``Don't worry. I'll show everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   The skeptics remained. As the Bruins slowly accumulated the
nation's No.1 recruiting class, coaches and evaluators wondered why
UCLA had wasted a scholarship on a skinny, timid kid from
Sacramento who seemingly lacked the jumper to play guard and the
toughness to play forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``UCLA asked me why I was shaky, so they knew what was going
on,'' Barnes said. ``But nobody else asked. A lot of people doubted
me. It was hard having the outside world looking in and not knowing
what was happening.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnes broke the toe playing football last year, but thought he
had aggravated the sprain. He missed the first half of the
basketball season, then returned to average 30 points and 10
rebounds. Bone spurs formed, the pain persisted, and eventually the
break was diagnosed.
</P>
<P>
   He had surgery in July and did not play for 2{ months. When
UCLA's practice began Oct.17, the soaring expectations that
accompanied freshmen JaRon Rush, Ray Young, Dan Gadzuric and Jerome
Moiso did not follow Barnes. Not even the coaches believed he would
develop this quickly. But he dropped 20 pounds, ran himself into
shape and slowly regained his timing.
</P>
<P>
   Now the career that began in obscurity looks as bright as the
others. Barnes is more advanced than Young, more physical than
Moiso, bigger than Rush and more versatile than Gadzuric. He's
unselfish, tougher than anyone thought, and vital to UCLA's
success.
</P>
<P>
   ``Matt does so many things on the floor, and he's a player who
can play with great players,'' Saia said. ``In that way, he fills a
niche for us. He's finally playing like the guy we saw before his
injury.''
</P>
</TEXT>
