r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOLIDAY-TRAVEL-KAN &LR;      11-25 0416
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLIDAY-TRAVEL-KAN </SLUG>
  
 Holiday travel will benefit from extremely low gasoline prices  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JENNIFER MANN  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you're driving over the river and through the woods to
grandmother's house this Thanksgiving, add cheap gasoline prices to
your list of blessings. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City continues to be treated to the cheapest fuel prices,
considering inflation, since anyone started keeping statistics. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That trend began a year ago with the Asian economic meltdown,
which continues to put a big damper on demand. That, coupled with
surging supplies, equals historically low prices. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The average cost of self-service regular unleaded gas in Kansas
City is 88 cents a gallon, down almost 18 percent from last
Thanksgiving. The cost of self-service regular unleaded at the pump
_ not accounting for inflation _ is the cheapest it's been in 10
years, when it averaged 81 cents a gallon in 1988. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Area residents on the Kansas side of the state line can probably
expect to pay a bit more because Kansas has higher fuel taxes _ 18
cents a gallon compared with 17 cents in Missouri. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And although gasoline prices throughout the nation are at
historic lows, Kansas City's are among the lowest. For instance,
the average for self-service regular unleaded on the West Coast is
$1.19. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The geographic location of Kansas City gives it a big leg
up,'' said Mike Right of the AAA-Auto Club of Missouri. ``It's got
good access to pipelines, highway systems and barge traffic.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Another factor in the area's favor, Right said, is heavy
competition. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If the Asian economy hadn't fallen apart, drivers would be
paying substantially more per gallon, the Energy Department said in
a recent report. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Asian fallout is expected to help keep gasoline prices low
for at least the next decade, the report says. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Russian economic crisis has had a minimal impact on overall
prices because it has big supplies of crude oil within its borders.
Japan, on the other hand, has virtually none. And although China is
on the verge of becoming a big crude-oil producer, it will still
have to rely heavily on imports. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mike Shanahan of the American Petroleum Institute in Washington,
D.C., said that even with low prices at the pump, it's still
economically viable for companies to continue producing. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Overproduction right now is extreme,'' Shanahan said. ``Of
course, that's good for consumers.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
