A0027 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CARDS-THANKSGIVING-KA     11-25 0683
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARDS-THANKSGIVING-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEASON'S GREETINGS ARRIVE EARLY FOR THOSE SENDING THANKSGIVING
CARDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rodney LaMothe, president of Industrial Park Realty in Kansas
City, dumped a decadeslong tradition of sending company Christmas
cards. So far, reactions have been terrific. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He sent Thanksgiving cards instead. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really glad we did it,'' said LaMothe, whose company does
leasing for Mid-West Terminal Warehouse Co. ``It was a
break-away-from-the-pack kind of thing.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LaMothe, along with a growing number of business owners and
operators, sees Thanksgiving as a better time to express
greetings. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``At Christmas, you get lost in the volume, but I've already had
two or three people who called to thank me for the Thanksgiving
card,'' LaMothe said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kathi Mishek, Hallmark Cards spokeswoman, said the company made
about 15 Thanksgiving cards specifically aimed at the
business-to-business market. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Three years ago, the business was zero,'' Mishek said. ``Now
it's one of our fastest-growing business units.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hallmark won't have precise sales numbers until January, but
Mishek said early market research indicated that business operators
like Thanksgiving cards for more than just stand-out-from-the-pack
reasons. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a time thing,'' Mishek said. ``People are saying they
don't have enough time around Christmas. There's a small but
growing group that's calling our 1-800 number to thank us for
having these Thanksgiving options.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Having more time at Thanksgiving to personalize her messages is
important to Connie Swartz. Her company, Creative Courseware Inc.,
has sent Thanksgiving cards for three years. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a no-brainer almost,'' she said. ``Thanksgiving is a time
to give thanks. Plus, the holiday has a nonreligious slant. It's a
cleaner message.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Swartz also likes being in the Thanksgiving vanguard because no
card expectations are attached. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``If you send one, you're OK. If you don't, you're fine, too,
because no one expected one,'' she said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Right Management Consultants in Overland Park has sent
turkey-time cards since 1990. The office, which does career
counseling and outplacement work for executives and employees let
go by their employers, took advantage of an option to customize the
card's message. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The suggested words in the Hallmark catalog _ ``As we celebrate
all the reasons to be thankful this special time of year, we
remember you and our pleasant association'' _ was edited slightly
to eliminate the last four words and replace them with a statement
of best wishes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Vince Sabia, vice president of client services, said the company
customized the message to ``do businesses the way we want to be
known, to show that we understand people and care about them.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Thanksgiving card LaMothe sent from Industrial Park Realty
was created by Masterpiece Studios Inc., a card manufacturer in
Mankato, Minn., which sells the line exclusively through the
wholesale trade. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   John Kind, president of Masterpiece, said the company began
marketing Thanksgiving cards to businesses nearly 20 years ago. The
niche represents a small part of Masterpiece's overall card
business (about a dozen Thanksgiving cards compared with more than
300 Christmas cards), but its percentage growth has been ``nice''
in the last four or five years, Kind said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Neither buyers nor manufacturers said diversity concerns were
driving conversions to Thanksgiving instead of Christmas greetings.
Most companies already had moved to more generic ``season's
greetings'' in deference to those who might celebrate Hanukkah,
Kwanzaa or other holidays instead of Christmas. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Both buyers and card makers agreed, though, that Thanksgiving
was a logical time to tell business contacts they're appreciated.
And, at least so far, the message isn't getting lost in a
competitive deluge. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Current senders hope it stays that way. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't want to have to move to Valentine's Day,''
Swartz said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
