<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIVING IN THIS COUNTRY IS SOMETHING FOR WHICH WE SHOULD BE
THANKFUL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   What is there to be thankful for this Thanksgiving? Let us count
the reasons: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --The price of gasoline is going down, rather than up. Remember
Thanksgiving 25 years ago? It was a time of gas lines; predictions
of ever higher oil prices; and disciples of Thomas Malthus
forecasting doom, gloom and the end of prosperity fueled by dynamic
postwar growth. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --The price of most everything else, meanwhile, is rising only
slowly. During that gloomy Thanksgiving season a quarter-century
past, the Consumer Price Index was rising at a 9 percent rate and
headed for a 12 percent jump the next year. Since last
Thanksgiving, the index is up about 1.5 percent. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --The exception to this disinflationary trend, however, is the
price of stocks. The market has again begun to go up instead of
down. As summer was giving way to autumn, the Dow Jones industrial
average was almost a couple of thousand points below July's record
high. Many market mavens had embraced the notion that the bull
market had run out of gas. On Monday, both the Dow and the
broader-based Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index vaulted to new closing
highs. Monday's Dow close, incidentally, was about 1,000 percent
higher than where the average stood about this time 25 years ago. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The cost of money is going down, rather than up. Last
Thanksgiving, the prime rate that banks charge their most
creditworthy borrowers was 8.5 percent. This Thanksgiving, it's
7.75 percent. On Thanksgiving '73, the prime was 9.75 percent. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --Japan didn't take over America. Remember 10 or so
Thanksgivings ago? The joke was that Japan had lost the war but won
the peace. Many Americans feared America Inc. was on its way to
becoming a colony of Japan's growing economic empire. The Japanese
could do no wrong, and the key, liberal economists claimed, was
Japan's cooperative alliance between big government and big
business. Japan's stock market has lost more than 60 percent of its
value during the '90s, the economy is mired in recession, and its
financial system is beset by problems that may take another
generation to resolve. Meanwhile, the long-suffering average
Japanese consumer-taxpayer suffers much economic abuse at the hands
of both big business and big government. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --You live in America, rather than Russia, Indonesia, Thailand,
Malaysia, North Korea, Cuba, China, the place once known as
Yugoslavia, and just about anywhere else on the planet anyone would
care to name. The United States certainly has its problems, but
it's No. 1 in every way. Ask anyone who's traveled extensively
abroad. Too many Americans, unfortunately, don't appreciate the
blessings that naturally accrue to anyone lucky enough to be here
because they have allowed their way of looking at things to become
too provincial. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Don't wait until New Year's to make a resolution. Make one
today. Resolve to spend at least some time this Thanksgiving
thinking of all the reasons you have to be thankful. Whether you're
with loved ones or alone, at work or play, in good health or bad,
rich or not so, sad or happy, young or old, you always have
something to give thanks for. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's just a matter of creating for yourself a few moments of
quiet time at this special time of year to think about them. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
