<HEADER>
A0036 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-REDSOX-BOS &LR;      11-25 0984
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLIAMS STAYS PUT; VAUGHN AN ANGEL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a crushing reversal of fortune that has depressingly familiar
precedents, the Red Sox learned Wednesday night that instead of
signing free agent center fielder Bernie Williams, they were swept
away by a last-minute bid from the New York Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   With a seven-year deal for a guaranteed $87.5 million, the
defending champion Yankees retained the American League batting
champion and Gold Glove outfielder while maintaining their record
of one-upping their archrivals in acquiring elite talent. There's
also an option for an eighth year, reportedly with a $4 million
buyout, that makes the guaranteed value of the deal $91.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement of Williams's agreement with the Yankees came
within an hour of notification that Mo Vaughn had made his
departure from the Red Sox official, agreeing to a six-year, $80
million deal with the Anaheim Angels. The timing of Vaughn's
announcement only reinforced the image of the huge void in the
Boston lineup that general manager Dan Duquette had hoped Williams
would fill.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels also hold a club option on a seventh year for $14
million, with a $2 million buyout.
</P>
<P>
   Compounding the failure to land Williams _ Duquette had been
poised Wednesday night to receive a phone call from Williams's
agent, Scott Boras, to accept the Sox' seven-year offer _ was the
GM's assertion that the Red Sox were no longer interested in free
agent slugger Albert Belle.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox had courted Belle immediately after breaking off talks
with Vaughn, but Belle gradually slipped off the radar screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that's going to work for us,'' Duquette said of
signing Belle, who under a provision in his contract with the White
Sox has until next Wednesday to sign as a free agent with another
club, or return to Chicago with a deal to pay him $33 million in
the next three years. ``I'm sure Albert will play somewhere next
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Duquette would not elaborate on why the Red Sox bowed out of the
Belle bidding, though there were hints Wednesday night that the Sox
had become sufficiently concerned about character issues involving
the controversial slugger, who has a history of antisocial
behavior. Efforts to reach Belle's brother, Terry, his agent, Arn
Tellem, and Red Sox CEO John Harrington were unsuccessful as of
mid-evening.
</P>
<P>
   Belle was talking to the Baltimore Orioles, another Boston rival
in the AL East, and was expected to either sign with them or return
to the White Sox.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where do we go?'' a subdued Duquette said by phone Wednesday
night, echoing a question that comes in the wake of what may be a
worse lineup upheaval than the one caused by Roger Clemens's
departure two winters ago. ``We'll have to take a look. We'll
probably take a look at pitching.''
</P>
<P>
   That does not mean, however, that the Red Sox will be a late
entrant in the bidding for either Kevin Brown or Randy Johnson, the
top two pitching prizes on the market. The Sox had interest in
Johnson, but as Duquette said Wednesday night, ``Both pitchers have
said they'd like to play for a team in a different geographic
location.''
</P>
<P>
   Duquette also sounded unenthusiastic about renewing talks with
Rafael Palmeiro, the 34-year-old first baseman who reportedly has
received a five-year offer from his incumbent team, the Orioles.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's still available,'' Duquette said. ``We've always liked
him as a player. But it looks like it's up to five years.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox have also contacted Robin Ventura, a third baseman who
can play first, and reportedly have shown interest in Gregg
Jefferies, but neither of those players can approach the power
numbers (40 home runs, 115 RBI) that Vaughn posted in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   There are several trade options the Sox could explore. They've
talked to the Expos about outfielder Rondell White, but according
to a source, the Sox don't have the talent to make that deal work.
Also available in trade is Gary Sheffield, the Dodgers' slugger
whose career began in Milwaukee when Duquette was with the Brewers,
but he has had injury problems and his production has fallen short
of what a team would expect from a $10 million-a-year player.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees had consistently refused to offer Williams more than
a five-year deal, and owner George Steinbrenner publicly mocked
Boras's assertion that the agent had at least one seven-year offer
in hand. It wasn't until the Red Sox met for two days with Williams
in Atlanta, and put their seven-year deal on the table, that the
Yankees summoned Williams and Boras for a meeting Tuesday night in
Tampa.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Red Sox jumping in like they did certainly sped the
process up to get us a lot higher than we were before,'' said
Yankees GM Brian Cashman.
</P>
<P>
   Boras had spoken in glowing terms about his meeting with the Red
Sox, and as late as Wednesday afternoon, one of Williams's closest
associates believed that Williams would sign with the Red Sox. The
deal to which Williams agreed was very close to the seven-year,
$100 million contract Boras had vowed his client would receive last
spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was hard for me to go somewhere else,'' said Williams in a
conference call from Puerto Rico. ``It came down to I wanted to be
a Yankee and remain a Yankee for my whole career.''
</P>
<P>
   Duquette was asked if he felt used by either the agent or the
Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made good offers on a couple of fronts,'' he said. ``That's
just the way the market works.''
</P>
<P>
   Told that Williams had come away enthusiastic about his meetings
with the Sox, Duquette replied, with a hint of sarcasm, ``We
impressed him? That's nice to hear.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams's deal guarantees him $91.5 million, or a half-million
more than the seven-year, $91 million deal Mike Piazza had signed
with the Mets, the industry's previous benchmark.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-25-98 2137EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
