<SLUG> BC-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WELL, WHAT HAVE WE HERE? NOT MUCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is not a Mo Vaughn story. Promise. Well, I almost promise.
For now we will try to stay away from the betrayal-and-trust theme
in which the Red Sox and Mo had entangled themselves the past few
years. It is a theme with so much psychosis that the syrupy Dr.
Laura could devote an entire radio show to it. Until she got bored.
And she would become bored.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is that Dan Duquette and John Harrington could
probably tell us some startling things about Vaughn. And Vaughn
could probably dish us some devious, inside management stories.
They might tell us that Mo snores. Mo might tell us that they wear
wingtips and knee-high dress socks to the beach. That's fine. We
can let those three stand in a semicircle and singe each other with
verbal grenades. But this is what I truly want to know:
</P>
<P>
   Who has the Dom Perignon on ice so we can all celebrate the Jose
Offerman Era?
</P>
<P>
   That's what Sox fans were left with Wednesday. Vaughn finally
became an Anaheim Angel, agreeing to a contract that is worth $80
million; Bernie Williams thanked the Sox for their kind words and
stayed with the Yankees (did anyone really think the Sox were going
to outbid the pinstriped vault known as George Steinbrenner?); and
Albert Belle, who had grown cool to the Sox a few days ago, further
receded to either the Baltimore or Chicago horizon.
</P>
<P>
   Now, pretend for a moment that you are an objective baseball
fan, viewing the transaction wire from a city such as Anchorage or
Tuscaloosa. You see that shortly after saying goodbye to Vaughn,
the Sox sign Offerman to a deal averaging more than $6 million a
season, even though they already have enough second basemen to fit
any style you want to play. You hear Offerman say that he struggled
so much in Los Angeles because there was too much pressure. Yep.
Too much pressure. In LA. You see that Offerman dominated in Kansas
City, a Triple A team that finished about 700 games out of first
place in the AL Central for about the 30th consecutive season.
</P>
<P>
   You continue to read, although you are frightened by these
people. You watch the Bostonians pursue a true jazz head in center
fielder Williams. You watch them chase after the Angriest Brother
In The Business in Belle, a man who _ true story _ once flinched
when he thought a reporter said, ``You suck'' to him when the
reporter actually said, ``What's up?'' You begin to frown when you
see that the Indians signed Roberto Alomar to a contract worth $30
million-$32 million, only $6 million more than Offerman's.
</P>
<P>
   I am sure the Sox have a vision. I am not sure I want to know
what it is. I am not sure I want to visit them too often next
season. Remember the good days of October, when the Sox were only a
few players away from being a very good team? They are now about
six players away. Maybe even six years away. Not only did they lose
Vaughn, they also lost a very good setup man in Greg Swindell. They
have to hope the Bret Saberhagen Miracle continues and that
Offerman can be a great leadoff man in front of ... in front of ...
whom?
</P>
<P>
   We know John Valentin can hit second and Nomar Garciaparra can
hit third or fourth. But who else is there? The Sox were exposed in
the postseason because they needed another above-average bat to
complement Vaughn and Garciaparra. So they lose their top home run
man, add a guy who popped seven homers, and still have not added a
starter who can pitch between Pedro Martinez and Tim
Wakefield/Saberhagen. Worse, look at all the major signings. Many
of them are in the American League. Randy Johnson looks like he'll
sign with the Rangers. Mo is in Anaheim. Williams is in New York.
The Indians have a Fantasy League All-Star lineup and the strongest
bullpen in the league. And the Sox have Offerman and a bunch of
nice rejection letters reading, ``You're a sweet guy who is going
to make someone happy one day. It just won't be me ...''
</P>
<P>
   Despite all the local chatter about Duquette as a heartless
cyborg, I actually like the man. He is a lover of literature and
Bruce Springsteen. But if he continues to let things like this
happen with his team, he will have plenty of time to theorize on
the musical Boss after being pushed aside in the AL East by the
Yankee Boss.
</P>
<P>
   If you thought the Yankees were dominant last season, they could
win 135 games if they manage to trade for the most underrated
player in baseball, Montreal's Rondell White. Duquette? Well, his
famous poolside interview with Bob Lobel will become his personal
Buckner. He won't be able to watch himself say that you cannot let
potential free agents walk away and get nothing for them.
</P>
<P>
   He had to know Mo was leaving, right? Everyone knew. They hoped
he would stay, but even the children from his Blue Hill Avenue
youth center knew he was going to be out. Why didn't The Duke know
and react to it? He knew Vaughn was going to leave as soon as he
stood in front of the Green Monster (another Buckner moment) and
did not mention Vaughn as a potential All-Star in 1999. I am afraid
to ask where the Sox will be at the '99 All-Star break. I am afraid
to ask what kind of numbers Vaughn will be dropping on the rest of
the AL by then, too.
</P>
<P>
   But more than anything, I am afraid of the people who are
running the Red Sox. Yo, Duke. If you are not acting alone, please
speak up. Tell us if Harrington is putting you up to this. If this
is all your work, you might find yourself chilling in the
Berkshires at the All-Star break and beyond the All-Star break.
</P>
<P>
   Happy Thanksgiving, Sox fans. Be thankful. The Red Sox have
brought you Offerman.
</P>
<P>
   (Michael Holley is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
