<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER LOSING FOCUS, WATTS BACK ON TRACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ For a while, Quincy Watts' life was set as nicely
as a Thanksgiving table. After winning two gold medals at the 1992
Summer Olympics in Barcelona, Watts had fame, fortune and friends
at his fingertips. It was a sumptuous feast and Watts freely
indulged.
</P>
<P>
   His gnawing hunger quickly was sated but Watts didn't stop.
People kept loading his plate with seconds and thirds and fourths,
shoving appearance money and first-class plane tickets and lavish
party invitations in front of his nose.
</P>
<P>
   The former Taft High track standout was too obeisant. That much
is so obvious to him now but the truth escaped him back then, when
he was seated at the head of the quartermiler's table eating
everything up, ignoring the internal voice that was screaming for
him to stop.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with becoming fixated on everything on your plate,
as Watts would come to see, is you tend to ignore the people who
are preaching moderation, who can't bear to watch you overindulge,
who try to coax you from the table.
</P>
<P>
   Watts had to gain weight and lose his lofty world ranking before
he realized it's not the opulence of the spread that matters, it's
the family fanned out around you at the table.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I've been through has made me appreciate my family,''
Watts said. ``They are what I'll be giving thanks for because
they've never stopped supporting me.''
</P>
<P>
   It's funny how time has a way of re-directing our gratitude. In
1988 gymnast Kristie Phillips, a seeming shoo-in for Olympic
stardom, could do no better than second alternate on the U.S. team
and didn't get to compete in Seoul. Ten years later she told Sports
Illustrated that not having a chance to shine on the world's
grandest stage did her a world of good because if she ``had gotten
everything, I wouldn't know what it takes to make it in the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   Her words drew nods and murmurs from Watts, who had gotten
everything so easily in 1992 that it made navigating the next few
years doubly difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never had had to deal with losing,'' he said. ``I never had
had to battle myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Never mind his gold medals, the real triumph of the human spirit
is revealed in Watts being back on the track and back on track.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Phillips, Watts was a long shot for Olympic stardom who
delivered in stunning fashion, finishing five meters ahead of his
nearest competitor in the 400 and setting an Olympic record that
would weather Michael Johnson's challenge in Atlanta four years
later.
</P>
<P>
   He added a second gold medal in the 4 X 400 relay and in the
European kingdom, where track athletes are royalty, was immediately
anointed a knight. Overnight he found he could earn more money
simply for showing up for a race than his father netted in a year
as a postal employee.
</P>
<P>
   The wind(fall) remained at Watts' back through 1993. He became a
cult figure in Europe after starring in a commercial every bit as
popular as today's stateside standby, ``Got Milk?''
</P>
<P>
   In the commercial a Viking king offered Watts his hefty wife in
exchange for a pair of the runner's generously cushioned sneakers.
Watts took one look at the woman and ran the other way as she gave
chase and cried, ``Quin-cy!''
</P>
<P>
   It was hard to imagine the lean times that lay ahead, in those
days when a continent was screaming his name. Watts gained a few
pounds on the post-Olympics banquet circuit but managed to run
fourth in the 400 at the 1993 World Championships.
</P>
<P>
   After that he became increasingly harder to track as injuries _
to his legs, back and, worst of all his psyche _ slowed him to a
virtual stop. Indeed, the rumors of his demise traveled faster than
did Watts in 1996 when he finished seventh in the 400 at the U.S.
trials, assuring the perpetuation of the 400's Olympic streak of
no-repeat gold medalists.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was living in the fast lane,'' said Watts, who had the
personalized license plate (2XGOLDQ) on his late-model luxury sedan
to prove it. ``I had everything I wanted. I thought it would never
end. I started getting distracted. I was missing practices. I was
doing everything not to be successful and I always had an excuse
for everything. A lot of the things I blamed people for, I can now
see I brought those things on myself.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1994 Watts was ranked seventh in the world in his specialty.
He hasn't seen the top-10 since. For the past two years he has been
the phantom of the 400. He really was invisible to many of the
friends and business acquaintances who had ingratiated themselves
to him in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the lessons Watts had to learn, the hardest was there
were people who used him as though he were an ATM. Thankfully, his
grandmother Olivia and father Rufus remained steadfastly in his
corner. With their support, Watts finally resurfaced in September.
</P>
<P>
   He returned to the track after a right ankle sprain ended a
whimsical free-agent tryout with the San Diego Chargers.
</P>
<P>
   Football had been an itch Watts didn't dare scratch since he
played for the USC scout team in 1990. He had wondered ever since
how far he might have gone in the sport if he had concentrated on
it instead of track.
</P>
<P>
   He finally decided to devote one year to finding out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to get the what-ifs out of my mind,'' Watts said the
other day, soaking up the sun after sweating through a weight
workout at UCLA. ``If it worked out, great, and if it didn't I
could always go back to track.''
</P>
<P>
   So it is that he resumed his love affair with running. The
surprise is that he has been able to look at the track's same old
curves in an entirely new light.
</P>
<P>
   ``Football turned my whole perspective around,'' Watts said.
``Running now gives me so much pleasure. I have a whole new respect
for it that I should have never lost.''
</P>
<P>
   Odd, isn't it, to think he had to work like a dog in one sport
to rediscover the joy of being a greyhound in another.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realized I have a God-given talent to run track,'' Watts
said. ``Through my own faults I've let this talent kind of go into
hibernation. I'm not going to let that happen. I'm not going to
waste my talents.''
</P>
<P>
   Watts will be 30 in 2000. That's the same age another Angeleno,
Michael Larrabee, was in 1964 when his comeback in the quarter mile
ended in Olympic gold. If Watts gets to Sydney, great. But he
doesn't need to accomplish anything more to be grateful. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
