<SLUG> BC-FBN-GIANTS-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRAHAM RECALLS A THANKSGIVING BLOWOUT AND BLUE FEET 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ On Thanksgiving Day six years ago, Kent
Graham was a 24-year-old Giants rookie about to start his first
National Football League game on national television in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Graham did not approach the situation with cold feet.
</P>
<P>
   They were blue.
</P>
<P>
   Someone had dyed Graham's feet blue in practice that week,
putting a colorless powder in his socks and shoes that turned blue
when combined with any kind of moisture, like perspiration. The dye
took about a week to wear off.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was raining that day in practice and my feet really got
soaked,'' Graham said Wednesday at Giants Stadium. ``Apparently,
there was blue stuff seeping out of my shoes.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham was forced into the lineup that week of the 1992 season
because of injuries to the Giants' two top quarterbacks, Phil Simms
and Jeff Hostetler.
</P>
<P>
   ``Phil and Hoss were just looking at my feet and laughing,''
Graham said. ``I didn't get it, and I didn't even notice until
after practice when I took my shoes off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was like, `What's this?'''
</P>
<P>
   Graham suspects that the wide receivers coach, George Sefcik,
put the blue dye in his socks.
</P>
<P>
   If it's a trick that Graham found offensive, it's one he has
learned from.
</P>
<P>
   This year at the Giants' training camp, the rookie quarterback
Ben Anderson showed up one day with a case of blue feet.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone pointed the finger at Graham.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, with a wide grin, Graham said, ``I don't know how his
feet turned blue.''
</P>
<P>
   Blue feet or not, Graham's NFL debut did not go well. Dallas was
on the verge of its first Super Bowl season under coach Jimmy
Johnson. On Thanksgiving Day, the Cowboys blitzed Graham _ and his
eventual replacement, Dave Brown, _ all day in a 30-3 rout. Graham
completed 12 of 28 passes for 151 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a long time ago,'' Graham said when asked what he
remembered about the day _ besides having blue feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember being nervous. I remember that I almost threw up in
the tunnel before the game. It was a dream come true, starting on
Thanksgiving on national TV.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham gets another shot on national television as the Giants'
starting quarterback Monday night in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a lot more comfortable about it than I was six years
ago,'' said Graham, who has since started 18 other NFL games for
the Giants and Arizona Cardinals. ``But I'm just as excited to have
an opportunity on national television. I'm going to go out there
and attack the defense, and I'm going to have fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Just the same, he may check carefully this week before putting
on his socks.
</P>
<P>
   Barely a Ripple
</P>
<P>
   Both San Francisco coach Steve Mariucci and 49ers quarterback
Steve Young made little of the controversy spawned by Jerry Rice's
complaints last weekend that he wasn't getting enough passes thrown
his way.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a situation where he was venting,'' Mariucci said of
Rice, who is leading the National Football Conference in receptions
with 61. ``He's got such high standards. But it's not an issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking with reporters on a conference call, Young said: ``I
respect Jerry because his work ethic is so unbelievable. He works
for the ball, he deserves the ball. It's not that hard to throw the
ball to Jerry Rice. We've always had trouble having enough balls in
this offense. It's very difficult to get it around to enough people
when you only have one ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Young was asked if he had sent Rice flowers this week as he is
depicted doing in a popular television commercial.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, that was a one-shot deal,'' Young answered.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton Apologizes
</P>
<P>
   Giants defensive tackle Keith Hamilton had little comment on his
arrest Monday on a charge of marijuana possession.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to apologize to the Giants' organization and to my
family and to the fans,'' said Hamilton, who was stopped early
Monday morning for speeding on the George Washington Bridge, which
links New Jersey and Manhattan. Police said they found less than an
ounce of marijuana and a pipe on Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton was also charged with driving an uninsured car and
driving under the influence of a controlled dangerous substance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been in the league seven years and nothing like this has
happened before,'' Hamilton said. ``We'll see how it ends up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
