</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOYS-BURNED-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLASSROOM EXPERIMENT GOES AWRY, BURNS TEENS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY PATRICIA FARRELL AIDEM, LISA VAN PROYEN AND LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Two high school seniors were burned Wednesday _
one suffering life-threatening injuries _ when a homemade cannon
crafted for a physics experiment exploded as about 30 horrified
classmates watched.
</P>
<P>
   Chris James was listed in critical condition and Nolan LaMar in
serious condition at the Grossman Burn Center at Sherman Oaks
Hospital, where they were airlifted after the explosion. Their
physics teacher and friends kept vigil with the families of the
17-year-old boys.
</P>
<P>
   A third student, Jesse Honea, also 17, was released from a
Valencia hospital after treatment for respiratory difficulty
resulting from the blast, which occurred on the football field of
the Hart High School campus, about 25 miles northwest of Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very fortunate,'' Honea said. ``I had my back turned and I
didn't see what happened. I felt the flames go straight past me. I
felt the intense heat. It sounded frightening. A lot of people were
crying.''
</P>
<P>
   Schoolmate Mike Baker was in the health office when LaMar was
brought in after the 8:25 a.m. accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's devastating. He was bleeding, his face was so burned,''
he said. ``There are a lot of people standing around. They're
crying, everybody is worried.''
</P>
<P>
   The physics class was gathered on the football field for a
supervised experiment designed to calculate velocity, said Bob Lee,
superintendent of the William S. Hart Union High School District in
the Santa Clarita Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Empty fruit-juice cans were opened, then taped together to
create a cylinder that was closed at one end.
</P>
<P>
   A capful of methanol _ a fuel more volatile than gasoline _ was
added to the ``launcher,'' a small hole poked near the bottom and a
tennis ball wedged in the top. Students were to light the fuel with
a match at the hole and hold the device at an angle as pressure
mounted to launch the tennis ball.
</P>
<P>
   But James and LaMar apparently saw no reaction. They were
looking into the launcher when the fuel flashed and exploded with
intense heat.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a danger when you use methanol,'' said Lt. Tom
Spencer of the Los Angeles County Sheriff Department's
arson/explosives detail. ``When it's lit, you can't tell it's
burning. You can't see a flame.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. A. Richard Grossman, medical director at the burn center,
said paramedics recognized that James was starting to suffocate
from the trauma and very likely saved the teen's life by inserting
a breathing tube as he lay on the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like super-heated air,'' Grossman said. ``At thousands of
degrees, it instantly cooks in a millisecond.''
</P>
<P>
   James, a member of Hart's varsity soccer squad, suffered
third-degree burns to his face, chest, shoulders and arms.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors told James' parents that the boy's most serious burns
were to his vocal cords and airway, life-threatening injuries
caused by inhaling the burning methanol. He was placed on a
respirator to keep his airway open.
</P>
<P>
   Grossman performed surgery on James' hands Wednesday morning to
prevent gangrene.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Grossman said, James will undergo ``the real
surgery'' when doctors take a look at the boy's lungs and ``strip''
his vocal cords. Surgeons also will place a tube through the boy's
abdomen into his stomach so they can feed him solid food for the
next few weeks, Grossman said. In the meantime, he will be fed
intravenously.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be critical to get him through the next few weeks,''
Grossman said, adding that James is ``going to have a severely
scarred face.''
</P>
<P>
   When James came to the hospital, he was alert and conscious and
responding to questions, said Larry Weinberg, a spokesman for the
burn center.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any third-degree burn is life-threatening. But he's young,
he's strong and he's in very good health. He has a very good chance
of fighting this,'' Weinberg said.
</P>
<P>
   About a dozen members of James' family, including his older
sister, Nancy, and his 16-year-old brother, went immediately to the
hospital, hugging one another, shedding tears and waiting for
updates.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's such a good kid, a very responsible kid, very reliable.
He is highly respectful to his parents and to other people,'' said
his grandmother, Joanne Webberley.
</P>
<P>
   James' aunt, Valerie Fought, said her nephew wants to be a
theatrical director and has made several videos for the family.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a real ham,'' she said. ``He hoped to get a sports
scholarship.''
</P>
<P>
   She said James' mother, Carolyn, had bought three large turkeys
for Thanksgiving and was planning to host a big family gathering.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know where we'll be spending Thanksgiving,'' she said,
referring to the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   LaMar, an aspiring firefighter who plays varsity baseball, was
transferred from Henry Mayo Newhall Memorial Hospital to the
Grossman facility, where he was in serious condition with
respiratory problems as well as burns to his face and chest.
</P>
<P>
   At Hart High, a crisis counseling center was set up in the
school library for teachers and students, said Eileen Foderaro,
secretary to Principal Gary Fuller.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the students went home early, Lee said.
</P>
<P>
   Physics instructor Chris McGee went to the Sherman Oaks
hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``The teacher was very troubled, very upset,'' said sheriff's
Deputy Scott Gibson, the liaison to Hart.
</P>
<P>
   Friends who went to the hospital to check on their classmates'
conditions said they were horrified.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone was shocked. It's just a freak accident that
happened,'' said James Shields, a junior.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
