<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-TICKETS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS RANGERS RAISE TICKET PRICES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Rangers increased ticket prices yesterday in anticipation of
having a 1999 payroll of somewhere between $75 million and $80
million.
</P>
<P>
   They just aren't sure if free-agent pitcher Randy Johnson will
be part of that increased payroll. Barry Meister, Johnson's agent,
said yesterday the Rangers are still one of four teams being
considered, refuting reports that the decision was down to either
the Anaheim Angels or the Arizona Diamondbacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are four clubs involved,'' Meister said. ``The
indisputable fact is the Texas Rangers are one of four clubs Randy
is considering pledging his services to for four years. It's a
four-horse race and none of the horses have been eliminated.''
</P>
<P>
   Meister said he would have notified owner Tom Hicks if the
Rangers had been eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a number of mutual business associates with Mr. Hicks
and I have too much respect for Mr. Hicks and his reputation to
hold him up one more minute than is necessary in giving him a
positive or negative answer,'' Meister said.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Dodgers are the fourth team involved. The
Diamondbacks again showed their determination to be competitive
when they signed pitcher Armando Reynoso to a two-year contract
yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels have reached an agreement with Mo Vaughn on an $80
million contract, and a source said yesterday the All-Star first
baseman has been lobbying Johnson to join him in Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   Meister said he is hoping Johnson will make a decision no later
than Monday.
</P>
<P>
   But the Rangers couldn't wait that long to announce their price
increases because season tickets and miniplans go on sale tomorrow.
Only adult tickets were affected. Prices were raised from $1 to $5,
depending on the category.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody likes to increase prices, we certainly don't,'' Rangers
president Tom Schieffer said. ``But what we had to face was the
payroll is going to go up substantially. The choice we had was to
increase ticket prices or decrease the payroll. We just needed the
revenue. We're sorry we needed to do it, but all the money is going
into the payroll and more.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers finished this season with a payroll of approximately
$62 million. Schieffer estimated the payroll will be between $75
million and $80 million next year. He said that will be the case
even if the Rangers don't sign Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a question of whether we're going to sign Randy
Johnson or not sign Randy Johnson,'' Schieffer said. ``We're still
going to have a big payroll. We'd like to have Randy Johnson and we
think we can have him on the team and players around him that will
help us win. But if we don't have Randy Johnson, we still think
we'll add a lot of players that will add up to Randy Johnson
numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers did not increase prices on children's tickets (13
years old and younger) in the bleachers and grandstands. They added
children's tickets in certain upper box areas. There are no
children's discounts in the lower seating bowl, upper reserved and
home run porches.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're sensitive to the fact that increasing ticket prices
makes it harder for families to come to The Ballpark,'' Schieffer
said. ``We're trying to do everything we can to soften that blow.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
