<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-LEBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERE'S A LESSON FOR TCU IN TULANE'S AMAZING SEASON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are four undefeated teams in major college football, and
every time I say the name of one of them it makes me want to cough
up my giblets.
</P>
<P>
   In a Thanksgiving, uh, classic, unbeaten Tulane (perform
Heimlich maneuver on me here) will face Louisiana Tech today for
the chance to elevate its record to a perfect 11-and-0.
</P>
<P>
   I know Tulane. I grew up not far from Tulane. I used to ride my
bike to Tulane and buy $1 tickets and sit in the end zone at old
Tulane Stadium, which was sort of the Taj Mahal of rust.
</P>
<P>
   And it was in that north end zone, after watching the Greenies
squander yet another fourth-quarter lead and lose to yet another
Vanderbilt or Rice or worse, that I came to the realization that a
life linked with Tulane would mean nothing but heartache.
</P>
<P>
   The coach of the Greenies in those years was Andy Pilney. In
eight seasons at the New Orleans school, Pilney won 25 games.
</P>
<P>
   When Tommy O'Boyle took over in 1962, he remarked how, while it
was tough to see Coach Andy go, ``No coach should ever put himself
in position to lose 62-0,'' a score by which Pilney's teams had
lost to rival Louisiana State not once, but twice.
</P>
<P>
   Four years later, LSU again beat Tulane by the surgically
precise score of 62-0. O'Boyle was canned the next day.
</P>
<P>
   As he returned to his office after being told the news, O'Boyle
saw secretary Lurlyn Fitzpatrick. ``Miss Fitz,'' a stunned O'Boyle
said, ``can you believe it? They fired me!''
</P>
<P>
   O'Boyle had won only six of his 40 games.
</P>
<P>
   So, I know Tulane. The problem is, I don't think Tulane knows
Tulane.
</P>
<P>
   There are people back home who actually think 10-0 Tulane should
hold out on the Liberty Bowl invitation it has received and wait to
see if the Greenies get a Bowl Championship Series berth.
</P>
<P>
   That's a good one.
</P>
<P>
   To his everlasting credit, one of them isn't Tulane coach Tommy
Bowden, who has said, ``We're right where we ought to be. I'm
ranked ahead of Michigan and behind Nebraska, and I don't have to
play either one.''
</P>
<P>
   With Davey O'Brien award finalist Shaun King at the controls,
the Green Wave soared through the Conference USA race. The Greenies
have humbled the likes of Navy and Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on which computer you use, Tulane has the nation's
104th toughest schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, here they are today, playing for 11-0 and an odds-on chance
to end up in the final Top 10.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, good grief.
</P>
<P>
   There isn't a team in the Top 20 that couldn't jackhammer Tulane
by three or four touchdowns. Yet, history beckons. The last time
that a Green Wave team did this well was 1931.
</P>
<P>
   One neighborhood's Chevy is another neighborhood's Cadillac. The
Greenies are beneficiaries of (A) Bowden's coaching, (B) King's
passing and (C) almost voodoo-like scheduling.
</P>
<P>
   TCU, are you following all this?
</P>
<P>
   The Horned Frogs _ like Tulane, a modest-sized private
institution with a somewhat tarnished recent football past _ have
seen two conferences slide out from under them in the past few
seasons. Fresh from a 6-5 campaign, TCU could emerge as the
preseason favorite to win next year's Western Athletic Conference.
</P>
<P>
   Don't laugh. The Frogs could be next season's Tulane.
</P>
<P>
   Is that good? You tell me. Tulane, even on its diet of C-USA
shrimps, has enjoyed the prominence of a high national ranking,
weekly mention on ESPN and a conference championship with
accompanying bowl bid.
</P>
<P>
   You tell me. Or should TCU set its future sights on a bigger
pond?
</P>
<P>
   Tulane fans _ which number in the dozens _ would rather ignore
the footnotes and revel in the success. Two years ago, admittedly,
they were losing football games to the same teams that they have
soundly thrashed this season.
</P>
<P>
   But Tulane is a myth. Their games in the 70,000-seat Superdome
have drawn an average of 21,000, even in this undefeated season.
Bowden has cried for New Orleans fans to support ``the hometown
team,'' but the Tulane student body now numbers less than 30
percent from the New Orleans area. Almost as large a percentage
come from the New York City area, New Jersey and the Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   Tulane doesn't have a school band anymore. It borrows bands from
the area high schools. Its alma mater is a taped recording.
</P>
<P>
   Rival LSU dropped Tulane from its schedule because it felt the
games weren't profitable.
</P>
<P>
   Their loss, alas, is Tulane's gain. The Greenies are this
season's quintessential big fish in the small green pond.
</P>
<P>
   Today they go for 11-0, and I think I'm going to throw up.
</P>
<P>
   Surely, TCU has higher sights than that.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-25-98 2346EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
