r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-COWBOYS-KISELAK-T     11-25 1654
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-KISELAK-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS' KISELAK IS A FEEL-GOOD STORY FOR TURKEY DAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN LYONS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Five Thanksgiving Days ago, he was going
door-to-door, selling whole- and term-life insurance to businesses
in San Antonio. To enjoy the holidays, he watched the way he spent
his paycheck, which at times was a $250 a week.
</P>
<P>
   Today, he is the starting center for the Cowboys. Making
$158,000 a year, he can buy all the turkey and dressing he wants.
</P>
<P>
   You want a feel-good story to go down with your after-dinner egg
nog?
</P>
<P>
   Meet Mike Kiselak.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm living a dream,'' Kiselak says. ``It took me a long time
to get here, and I'm not going to wake up in the middle of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Buoyed by his devout faith, he endured eight years and two
football leagues to finally make an NFL roster, which he did with
the Cowboys last summer.
</P>
<P>
   And so, at age 31, when most NFL players are facing the downside
of their careers, Kiselak is an NFL rookie.
</P>
<P>
   He is giving thanks today because his journey from the
University of Maryland to Valley Ranch did not end on some dusty,
sun-baked practice field in Missouri, or Texas, or New York, where
he was told three times that he was not good enough to block NFL
defensive linemen.
</P>
<P>
   He is giving thanks that he did not suffer a career-ending
injury while barnstorming for World League clubs in San Antonio and
Sacramento, Calif. He is giving thanks for the opportunity to play
in the Canadian Football League, and for the friend who sent his
game tapes to the Cowboys in the hopes they would offer him a
tryout.
</P>
<P>
   ``Isn't that what the American Dream is about?'' Cowboys coach
Chan Gailey said. ``Here is a guy who continued to persevere and
fight until he reached a goal.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is,'' Kiselak said, ``an amazing story if I go back and
think about it.''
Driving through tears Kiselak thought it was almost over before it
started.
</P>
<P>
   After moving from the defensive line his junior year at
Maryland, he started every game at right guard until graduating in
1990. He signed as a free agent with the Kansas City Chiefs. But
coach Marty Schottenheimer, who had selected center Tim Grunhard
and guard David Szott in that spring's NFL draft, cut Kiselak
before training camp ended.
</P>
<P>
   Kiselak gave Schottenheimer his Chiefs playbook. Then he packed
his 1985 Nissan with his belongings and drove the 23 1/2 hours in
the rain to his home in Pine Bush, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a major storm, but I drove anyway and I cried all the
way home because I thought my days of playing football were done,''
he said. ``I didn't know what I was going to do with the rest of my
life. I had no plans.''
</P>
<P>
   Kiselak, however, knew how to build things, having worked at
various construction jobs to pay his way through college. So he
helped his brother build an eight-room, 7,500-square-foot house.
Feeling better about himself, he was about to settle into his
career.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in early 1991, Kiselak heard about this new football
league being formed, the World League of American Football. A few
franchises were setting up in the United States. He dropped
everything to go to Orlando, Fla., for the league combine. That
spring, the San Antonio Riders selected him in the fourth round of
the first WLAF draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't even know where San Antonio was,'' he said. ``I'm
thinking Santa Barbara, Santa-something. Must be California. I
called my mom and told her I was going to California. She said,
`Mike, you are going to Texas.'''
</P>
<P>
   Kiselak played two years for the Riders. But the itch to play in
the NFL never subsided, and because the WLAF seasons ended in late
spring, it gave him a chance to try out for NFL teams during the
summer. In 1991, he went to the New York Giants camp. In 1992, he
went to the Houston Oilers camp. Both times he was waived.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Houston, I went out there and I just was not physically
ready,'' he said. ``The WLAF season had just ended and I was tired.
When I signed with the Giants, I'd worked out and thought I was
playing well. My strength was better. I just wasn't in their plans.
It happens like that sometimes.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, the WLAF folded. Needing work to support his family _
he got married
</P>
<P>
   in July _ Kiselak earned a license to sell insurance. It wasn't
a lot of money. But at least he and his wife Kimberly were eating
every night. ``I've got a lot of respect for those guys selling
insurance because you've got to love what you are doing.''
</P>
<P>
   The insurance gig did not last long. The Canadian Football
League announced plans to field teams in the United States. In
March 1993, he signed a free-agent contract with the CFL's
Sacramento Gold Miners. He started at center there for two years.
Kimberly, who stayed in San Antonio, was able to visit regularly
when she landed a job with Southwest Airlines. ``That saved our
marriage,'' Mike said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was frustrating not being able to see him,'' Kimberly said.
``I was going to go live in Cleveland with my family. But we came
through. Everything worked out just fine.''
</P>
<P>
   The Gold Miners moved to San Antonio in 1995. And just as
Kiselak was getting better as an offensive lineman _ he was a CFL
All-Star in 1995 _ the league announced it was no longer fielding
teams in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Kiselak thought his football career was over.
</P>
<P>
   Again.
</P>
<P>
   He thought about trying out for the NFL again. Or he could get
back into the insurance-selling business. And there was always a
construction job waiting for him.
</P>
<P>
   Then he received a phone call. The Saskatchewan Rough Riders
selected him in the CFL's dispersal draft. The prospect of playing
in Central Canada, with its cold winters and ``big mosquitoes''
wasn't appealing to Kiselak. He talked it over with Kimberly.
Maybe, they thought, he should just give up playing football.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was going to quit,'' he said. ``Then I got this phone call
from Toronto. It was from some of my coaches who'd transferred from
San Antonio. They said, `Hey, we're picking up Doug Flutie, and a
lot of other good players. We want you to be our center. I said
`sure.' They traded away one of their offensive linemen and maybe a
pack of cigarettes and I was there.''
</P>
<P>
   Snapping the ball to Flutie in Toronto, Kiselak was selected the
CFL's most outstanding offensive lineman two consecutive years. The
Argonauts won consecutive Grey Cup championships. Kiselak was
enjoying himself. But he still wanted to prove that he could block
people like Reggie White and Bruce Smith.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted,'' he said, ``to play in the NFL and continue to
play, not just make it and let my breath out.''
Attention at last By now, game tape showing Kiselak's talents was
floating all around the NFL. Cowboys scouting director Larry
Lacewell had a copy and liked what he saw. But he admits he didn't
get serious about Kiselak until a friend of Kiselak's, Mike
Krueger, kept sending Lacewell more tapes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He kept calling me, almost like he was his agent,'' Lacewell
said. ``There wasn't any doubt in my mind that he could pass
protect because all they did in the CFL was pass. But I had no idea
if he could run-block the way we have to in this league. It just
doesn't happen up there. I had no idea.''
</P>
<P>
   Lacewell talked to team owner Jerry Jones and vice president
Stephen Jones and told them ``we should take a chance because we'll
never know until we suit him up.''
</P>
<P>
   Krueger, it turns out, had been friends with Kiselak since his
days in San Antonio. When Mike and Kimberly Kiselak accepted Jesus
Christ into their lives, they started going to Krueger's house to
read the Bible. Krueger was not Kiselak's agent, but he and a
family minister advised him on many things, including his football
career.
</P>
<P>
   When the Cowboys offered Kiselak a contract after working him
out last winter, Kiselak waited.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Lord spoke to us and told us there'd be two teams that
would offer us a contract,'' Kiselak said. ``The first one is the
one the Lord put his hands on. The second team would offer more
money. Sure enough, Dallas offered me a chance to play. Then, about
a month later, Seattle offered more money. I told my agent that
we're going to Dallas.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he had to make the team. The Cowboys selected three
offensive linemen in last spring's draft and signed five others to
free-agent contracts during the summer.
</P>
<P>
   Kiselak knew he was a long shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody knew who I was,'' he said. ``And that was fine with me.
I didn't lose any sleep. I knew I had a job to do. I believed I'd
make the team. During training camp, my wife got a transfer from
San Antonio to Dallas. We got out of our house and bought a house
up here. And this was before the final cuts. So they could have cut
me. But that wasn't on my mind. I was here to make the team.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys waived five offensive linemen before the season.
</P>
<P>
   Kiselak, to the surprise of Gailey, was not one of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We kept thinking, `No way was he going to make it,''' Gailey
said. ``He wasn't fast enough, or strong enough. But the longer he
played, the better he got. He kept blocking the right guy and he
kept fighting. He won us over.''
</P>
<P>
   He continued his strong play during the regular season and
received his first extended action Oct. 4 against the Washington
Redskins when starting right guard Everett McIver sprained his
knee. He moved into the starting lineup Nov. 8 when center Clay
Shiver sprained a big toe. Kiselak has played so well that Gailey
has kept him in the starting lineup even though Shiver is healthy
again.
</P>
<P>
   And Kiselak plans to stay in the lineup for a long time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Through all those years, I knew I was getting older and
older,'' he said. ``But for some reason, the Lord kept opening
doors for me to continue playing. I'd play for nothing because I
loved the game. I've got a great opportunity here. And I don't want
to waste it.''
</P>
<P>
   He hasn't so far.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
