<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-11-25 23:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0275 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-NOTREDAME-LBPT     11-25 0933
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-NOTREDAME-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRISH LEAN ON BACKUP QUARTERBACKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE IRVINE  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Bob Davie, Notre Dame head football coach of the
present, learned everything he needed to know about Coley O'Brien
on Sunday from an Irish coaching legend of the past.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien, for the uneducated in the lore of Notre Dame football,
was a reserve quarterback who, because of a shoulder injury to
starter Terry Hanratty, stepped in to lead the Irish to the most
lopsided victory in the storied rivalry with USC. It was 32 years
ago today that O'Brien in his first start threw for 255 yards and
three touchdowns as the Irish blitzed the Trojans 51-0 to cap a
9-0-1 season and capture the national championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to Ara Parseghian and he talked about the 1966 (USC)
game,'' Davie said. ``He told me about Coley O'Brien taking over at
quarterback.''
</P>
<P>
   Davie then went out and put his history lesson to use.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told our football team, `Arnaz Battle is Coley and Eric
Chappell is O'Brien,''' Davie said.
</P>
<P>
   Arnaz Battle and Eric Chappell have spent Saturdays this fall
watching Jarious Jackson quarterback the Irish to nine wins in 10
outings. This Saturday, when the Irish come to the L.A. Coliseum
for their annual tussle with the Trojans, things will be much
different for Battle and Chappell, or Coley and O'Brien, if you
please.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest thing I have to deal with is just the whole idea
of playing in a game like this for the first time,'' said Chappell,
a 6-foot-4, 225-pound junior from Montgomery, Ala. ``It's different
because the other times I've been in there with the second and
third strings. So I have to get acclimated to playing with the ones
on our team against the quality of competition.''
</P>
<P>
   The majority of the quarterback work this season has been
handled by Jackson, who waited three seasons behind Ron Powlus for
the chance. The 6-foot, 220-pound flash from Mississippi completed
104 passes in 188 attempts for 1,740 yards with 13 touchdowns and
six interceptions and rushed for 441 yards on 113 carries with
three touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   But Jackson's regular season came to a close last Saturday in
South Bend on what was supposed to be the final play of a 39-36
victory over LSU. The Irish had the ball deep in their own
territory and the plan was for Jackson to run the final eight
seconds off the clock before taking a knee in the end zone. But LSU
linebacker Arnold Miller came untouched around the corner and hit
Jackson while the Notre Dame quarterback was trying to plant his
foot to escape.
</P>
<P>
   Battle was one of the first players off the bench to Jackson's
side as he was being treated by the trainers in the end zone for
what was later diagnosed as a regular-season ending partial
ligament tear in his right knee.
</P>
<P>
   ``After Jarious got hurt, he just told me and Eric to step up
and lead the offense,'' said Battle, a 6-1, 196-pound freshman from
Shreveport, La., who considers Jackson a mentor.
</P>
<P>
   So Davie and the Irish will hinge their hopes of playing in the
Rose Bowl or another BCS-affiliated bowl on a pair of quarterbacks
who, without a media guide, are unknown. Sounds good enough to the
guy who'll make sure they get the ball on every play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone has to make their first start at some point,'' said
Notre Dame center John Merandi, a graduate of Rim of the World in
Lake Arrowhead. ``Once the game starts, you just play.''
</P>
<P>
   Battle's last start came a year ago while playing for C.E. Byrd
High in Shreveport, where he threw for 527 yards and rushed for 677
yards as a senior. His Notre Dame playing time has consisted of a
10-play, 80-yard scoring drive late in the loss to Michigan State,
three snaps in a win over Stanford and eight plays in a victory
over Baylor. Battle left the Baylor game, which was Oct. 31, with a
shoulder sprain and hasn't played since.
</P>
<P>
   ``My shoulder is a nonfactor,'' said Battle, who beat out
Chappell for the backup spot before hurting his shoulder. ``I can
go out there and do anything I need to do. It's the least of my
worries.''
</P>
<P>
   Chappell, who is more of a passing threat than Battle, threw for
3,000 yards in his final two seasons at Carver High in Montgomery,
Ala., but only 700 came in his senior year. He didn't take a snap
in his first two years at Notre Dame but did see special-teams
action in the final five games of last season. This year he has
attempted one pass _ it was incomplete _ in two abbreviated
appearances.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eric has shown a lot of improvement lately,'' said quarterback
coach Mike Sanford, a USC graduate and former Trojans assistant.
``When Arnaz hurt his shoulder and (Eric) got more reps, he got
better in just about everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Davie might not decide who will start until Saturday morning,
but he said the game plan won't be drastically changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though that position is crucial and vital,'' Davie said,
``you're not going to make 10 other players uncomfortable by doing
something different.''
</P>
<P>
   The guys devising the other game plan _ Paul Hackett and his
staff _ are a little uncomfortable not knowing what to expect.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality is that until the game starts and until the game
begins to unfold, we're just not going to know exactly what we're
up against,'' Hackett said. ``There's no tape to study, so there's
no chance to get the nuances, the strengths and weaknesses of the
unknown quarterback. There's a history of teams making this change
and performing brilliantly.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently he's also heard all about Coley O'Brien.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
